<SLUG> BC-BBA-NEW-YORK-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWENTY YEARS LATER, ZIMMER CLEARLY REMEMBERS DENT'S PLAYOFF HOME
RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees celebrated the 20th anniversary of their
1978 World Series championship by having Bucky Dent, Chris
Chambliss and Willie Randolph, three stars from that team, throw
out the first pitches before Game 1 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dent thought Yankees coach Don Zimmer should participate in the
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dent asked me to catch him,'' Zimmer said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer declined, preferring not to dwell on the events of long
ago when Dent, now a coach with the Rangers, brought ruin to the
best team he ever managed. Tomorrow marks the 20th anniversary of
the day Dent hit his three-run home run off pitcher Mike Torrez and
helped the Yankees defeat the Boston Red Sox in their classic
one-game playoff at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like 20 years,'' Zimmer said last night,
recalling that spectacular autumn afternoon in Boston. ``I first
realized it a couple of weeks ago. We were in Boston and they
brought \RDennis\S Eckersley in to relieve and I started thinking,
that son of a ... it's been 20 years since Eckersley pitched for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, celebrating his 50th year in baseball, said he doesn't
think about that day unless somebody asks about it. But he
remembers it well, perhaps his most disappointing day in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful going into the clubhouse and seeing grown men
cry,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Did he cry?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' Zimmer said. ``There wasn't a whole lot to say. We
blew a 12- or 14 game-lead, the Yankees led us by 31/2 games, then
we came back. We won eight straight at the end of the season. I
told them I couldn't be more proud of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Guidry, a Cy Young Award winner that season, started for the
Yankees, but the Red Sox scored a couple runs early and led 2-0
into the seventh. Then the Yankees put a couple of runners on base
and Dent came to the plate. He lofted a high fly ball toward the
Green Monster, the 34-foot wall in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in Fenway Park, you know probably 95 percent of
the time when it's going out, when it's against the wall or in the
net,'' Zimmer said. ``It was 75 degrees that day, cool enough so
that the wind should be blowing in. But the wind was drifting out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hit the ball, I said, `Good that's an out.' I see
\RCarl Yastrzemski\S go back, then turn around and I said, `Well
that's not the worst, it's off the wall.' Then it was in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer insisted 20 years later that that wasn't the biggest play
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest one is the one nobody ever talks about,'' Zimmer
said. ``Guidry's pitching, we have a one or two-run lead and a
couple men on base with two outs. In Fenway, your outfielders give
the \Rfoul\S line and bunch in the gaps. Fred Lynn hits one down
the right-field line for extra bases. My first thought was don't
bounce in the seats, because I wanted both runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou Piniella caught the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Yankees came over to the Red Sox clubhouse to
shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Piniella, `How could you catch that ball,' '' Zimmer
said. ``How could you play a left-handed hitter to pull the ball
off Guidry? He said, `I'll tell you, I thought Guidry had lost a
lot of velocity, so I cheated three or four steps to my left.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tremendous answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer managed for 13 years in the majors and that was his best
team ever, even better than his two Rangers juggernauts in 1980-81.
The Red Sox won 99 games but, because of Dent, did not make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it anymore,'' Zimmer said. ``It was
painful the next day when I was driving home. But there's nothing I
would have done differently. If you're going to be in this game a
long time, you've got to take that kind of stuff because it's going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer later did get revenge. Dent was traded to the Rangers in
1983 and Zimmer had been hired by the Yankees as a coach. With no
place to live, he rented Dent's house in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk in that house and there's a picture of Dent hitting
that home run in every room,'' Zimmer said. ``Bathroom, living
room, it didn't matter, there was a picture of him hitting that
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The living room also had one of those nice white shag carpets.
You know, like a shaggy dog. So after a couple of months, I called
Dent up. I said, `I couldn't stand it anymore so I turned every one
of those pictures around and spit tobacco on your shag carpet.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
