<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-CREW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREW TOP METROSTARS, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Bora Milutinovic's success as coach in the
World Cup failed to rub off on the MetroStars in his first playoff
game in Major League Soccer tonight. Milutinovic's newest team
suffered a 5-3 loss to the Columbus Crew at Ohio Stadium to fall
behind in their first playoff series in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The two-of-three-game series will resume Saturday night at
Giants Stadium, and if a third game is necessary it will be played
here next Wednesday night. A third game will not be necessary,
however, if the MetroStars and Milutinovic do not find a formula to
mark tighter on defense.
</P>
<P>
   That aspect of the MetroStars' game was so loose on Wednesday
night that the Crew paraded at will inside the penalty area and
found ample room to operate once they got near Tony Meola, the
goalkeeper. He had little chance on any of the goals, which came in
rapid succession: two three minutes apart and two others five
minutes apart, all before the game was 38 minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little bit lackadaisical,'' said Mike Sorber, who
scored the second goal for the MetroStars. ``We just didn't have
the intensity and they came at us pretty good. Their transition
game was better, but we corrected some things and we did well in
the second half. We proved that we can score goals on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the MetroStars staged a good rally in the second half
after Milutinovic put Miles Joseph and Billy Walsh into the game in
place of Jim Rooney and Brian Kelly. The MetroStars got goals from
Eduardo Hurtado, Sorber on a penalty kick and Joseph. But they only
made the score more respectable after the Crew had jumped to a 4-0
lead by intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McBride scored the first two goals in the first 12 minutes
to stun the MetroStars. Rob Smith and Jason Farrell scored the next
two and Stern John got the fifth one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came very fast in the first half,'' Milutinovic said of
the Crew's forwards, who steadily got behind his defenders before
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you receive goals like that,'' Milutinovic said of
McBride's two early goals, ``it's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The two early goals by McBride, who scored the only goal for the
United States in the World Cup last summer, appeared to awaken the
MetroStars. They took control of the game for the next 20 minutes,
but came up empty despite some sloppy goalkeeping by Juergen
Sommer. Three consecutive shots from the MetroStars bounced off the
Crew's goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the MetroStars' failure to get at least one goal
during their 20-minute domination, the Crew regained the initiative
and capitalized on two chances that were created after mistakes by
MetroStar defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The four-goal burst set a league playoff record for goals in a
half. It also put the MetroStars in a hole that even a coach as
successful as Milutinovic could not get them out of. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
