<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS RESHUFFLE
</HEADLINE>
 (CORRECTS SPELLING OF HOFFMAN IN LEAD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ New Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone truly
likes Glenn Hoffman and his coaching staff. But he wasn't going to
put the future of the team in the hands of six guys he met just
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   So with his attention still focused on getting Montreal manager
Felipe Alou, Malone announced the reassignment of Hoffman and his
coaches Wednesday, giving Hoffman a spot on the major-league staff
and the rest a place in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance the coaching staff of Joe Amalfitano, Mike
Scioscia, Mickey Hatcher, Charlie Hough and John Shelby could
remain in some form with the Dodgers in Los Angeles. But Malone
wants the new manager to play a critical role in forming the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the organization needed to make a change, create a
new direction,'' Malone said. ``I just needed my guy, to get a guy
who is a proven manager who I trust will be on the same page with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he hopes to have a new manager in place by the
annual organization meetings, which will be held Oct. 28-Nov. 1 at
the Dodgers spring-training base in Vero Beach, Fla. Actually, he
would like it well before then, but several candidates remain under
contract with other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have contacted the Expos about Alou, who worked in
Montreal when Malone was general manager (1993-94). Alou, 63, has a
year left on his Expos contract, worth $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal president Claude Brochu said Monday he would not stand
in Alou's way of taking the Dodgers job, but so far has not granted
Malone permission.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos are expected to learn next Wednesday whether citizens
of Quebec will agree to fund a new stadium. If the measure fails,
which is likely, the club probably will be sold and leave Canada.
But since Alou is the most popular Expos figure since Gary Carter
in the early 1980s, Montreal does not want him to walk away just
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have interest in Felipe because he is a friend and an
excellent baseball mind,'' Malone said. ``We have not gotten
permission to talk so everything is hypothetical.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou would be a popular choice among the reassigned coaches. In
Montreal, Alou only has ties to first-base coach Luis Pujols.
Third-base coach Pete Mackanin and pitching coach Bobby Cuellar
were brought in by Expos general manager Jim Beattie. Mackanin has
indicated he would like to be considered for the manager's spot if
Alou leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he also is considering former New York Mets,
Cincinnati Reds and Baltimore Orioles manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate is Kevin Kennedy, the Taft High product who
lives in Tarzana. Kennedy previously managed in Texas and Boston
and was a minor-league manager in the Dodgers organization for many
years. He worked in the Montreal farm system under Malone and is
now a baseball analyst for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who lives with his wife and five children in Anaheim
Hills, left Wednesday for a two-week family vacation and was
unavailable for comment. He was 47-41 after taking over for
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Because positions will not be assigned until a new manager is in
place, Hoffman's actual spot on the new staff is uncertain. At
Triple-A Albuquerque, where he was manager before taking over June
22 from fired Bill Russell, Hoffman also was the third-base coach.
</P>
<P>
   Amalfitano has been the Dodgers third-base coach the past 16
years and Malone and Alou are fans.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, Hoffman's bench coach, was the longtime Dodgers
catcher who also played with Texas and San Diego at the end of his
career. He was a candidate last year for the manager's job with the
expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Hough and Hatcher were promoted from Class-A San Bernardino a
week after Hoffman was named manager.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hough was offered the pitching coach's job but
declined because of personal differences with Russell, his longtime
teammate. In June, he replaced Goose Gregson and got high marks
from most of the pitchers. Hoffman said players responded to
Hough's low-key approach and respected his 25 years as a
major-league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby, the center fielder on the Dodgers' 1988 World Series
championship team, made an unexpected rise to the major-league
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two seasons, Shelby was demoted as manager at
Double-A San Antonio and manager for Class-A Savannah, Ga. The
Dodgers eliminated the Savannah club and sent Shelby to coach at
Class-A Vero Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Dodgers' September minor-league callups said
Shelby was the best manager in the organization. He also was the
only African-American coach in the Dodgers farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't fired anyone,'' Malone said. ``Most organizations
would have fired the coaching staff. There is a lot of talent there
and I still want to use it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
