r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-NOTES-TEX     10-01 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT'S BAT SILENT, BUT HIS MOUTH KEEPS RUNNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Carl Everett's bat was quiet Tuesday, but his mouth
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 1, the Astros outfielder called Padres pitcher Kevin
Brown a ``nobody.'' That rip preceded Brown's 16-strikeout
domination of Houston and promoted terse retorts from the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes an ignorant person to say something like that,''
Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart said. ``Guys who say stuff like
that don't belong in the big leagues. I never knew Carl was that
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who said Brown ``was nobody until he's done
something,'' went 0-for-2 against Brown with a strikeout. Brown
said he was unaware of Everett's statement, but Stewart sure
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess (Brown's) done something now, huh?,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   While teammate Jeff Bagwell suggested that Everett ``let a
sleeping giant lay,'' the former Mets player did just the opposite
when asked about Thursday's starting pitcher, Andy Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown did his job,'' Everett said, ``but Andy hasn't done
anything yet until he goes out and proves it.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Padres owner John Moores is expected to attend Thursday's game
after missing Game 1 to be with his mother, who suffered a stroke
last week. Moores, a Houston philanthropist, has built athletic
facilities for his alma mater, the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playoff fever isn't exactly gripping Houston. After
approximately 4,000 seats were empty for Game 1, about 8,000
tickets remain for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday's victory was San Diego's first in the postseason in
almost 14 years, since Game 2 of the 1984 World Series. The Astros'
last playoff triumph came on Oct. 12, 1986 in Game 4 of the NLCS
against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moises Alou, who hit 38 home runs in the regular season, is
homerless in his past 104 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Padres have had fewer than 10 hits in their past 18 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
