<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' HELLING DISCOVERS NO ROOM FOR ERROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rick Helling discovered last night what Todd
Stottlemyre found out in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   There's no margin for error when the New York Yankees' pitchers
have your offense completely snuffed out. Helling held the Yankees
to three runs in six innings, but that's two more than the Rangers
scored, and Helling's first postseason start turned into a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I threw the ball good enough to win,'' Helling said
after the Rangers' 3-1 loss. ``But, the same as Todd, you have to
give the other pitcher credit. They outpitched us two days in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling's downfall was two home runs, a solo shot by Shane
Spencer in the second inning and two-run homer by Scott Brosius in
the fourth. Both came on fastballs, which was still Helling's best
pitch, producing nine strikeouts in six innings. But he conceded
that he relied on it too much, especially to Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it well to some good fastball hitters _ Derek Jeter,
Bernie Williams, Tino Martinez,'' Helling said. ``They either took
it or fouled it off. That told me it was moving good. When that
happens, I stick with it until they prove they can hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, a good fastball hitter, did just that. Helling worked
the count to 2-2, then came with one too many fastballs. Spencer
hit it high and deep over the left-center-field fence for a home
run and a 1-0 Yankees lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a mental mistake,'' Helling said. ``I've got to make
him hit a breaking ball. He's a good fastball hitter, that's what
the scouting reports say. But I felt so good with my fastball, I
thought I could hit my spot. But I missed it by a couple of inches,
and he hit it pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The fastball was also the culprit again in the fourth after
Spencer singled with one out. Helling tried to get a fastball down
with the first pitch but got it up instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed so bad with that pitch I'm surprised he hit it,''
Helling said. ``It was up in his eyes but I guess it came back over
the middle of the plate and he just tomahawked it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all the Yankees got but all they needed. Two mistakes
were too many considering what Andy Pettitte was doing to the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm disappointed, but I felt I threw pretty good,''
Helling said. ``Most nights I win that game, but we're not worried
about our offense. I'm sure Friday they'll come out swinging the
bats well. We just ran into some good pitching here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
