<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES, JOBS MAKE FOR VIOLATION IN WAITING
</HEADLINE>
 12 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When dealing with the various factions of the Big 12, achieving
a unanimous or lasting opinion on any subject is rare. This is the
only conference in America where produce items enjoy a longer shelf
life than the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet amid all the diverse viewpoints, football coaches have found
ironclad commonality. They agree on two things:
</P>
<P>
   None of their players is holding a part-time job despite an NCAA
rule enacted Aug. 1 permitting athletes to earn up to $2,000 above
the value of their scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring this new rule, which allows athletes to work for
school boosters, will trigger more headaches on college campuses
than the morning after a Metallica concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really playing with fire on this one ... and I'm quite
sure some people will get burned,'' Missouri coach Larry Smith
said. ``Putting boosters in contact with players more than raises
temptations. That turns temptation into opportunity for people who
want to cross the line. I think this will jump up there with
gambling in terms of being as big a concern as there is in college
athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   Because none of the Big 12 coaches has actually dealt with a
player holding a part-time job, it would be easy to dismiss such
bluster as premature. But not in this case.
</P>
<P>
   This rule, passed by the NCAA with the intent of allowing pocket
change for scholarship athletes, might work in non-revenue sports.
But it will never work in a sport that was overrun with infractions
cases detailing $100 handshakes and booster-financed slush funds
throughout the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the NCAA banned boosters from the recruiting process.
Allegations of improper payments to players did not disappear, but
the numbers have dwindled in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the NCAA has approved booster involvement with part-time
jobs. Iowa State coach Dan McCarney already knows what happens
next: Jim Bob Studmuffin, coveted recruit, wants to weigh one
school's job program against another before signing a letter of
intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what scares me the most,'' McCarney said. ``It becomes
a factor in recruiting. And there's no question that's a
disadvantage for us. We don't have a big job market in Ames,
Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum issued the same lament about College
Station. A similar case could be made in most Big 12 cities, where
Austin is the only one with a population in excess of 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the 1990s have been marked by the NCAA's 20-hour
rule, a mandate that limits practice time to preserve study time
for overburdened athletes. Suddenly, these athletes now have time
to study, play ``and'' work?
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so. Neither does Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the worst rule in the world,'' Dykes said.
``It's an absolute joke. After all we've heard about time
constraints, and they come up with this? Tell it to the Marines.
I'm not buying that.''
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative solution, Dykes suggests returning to the days
when athletes received a monthly spending stipend as part of their
scholarship. It happened in the 1960s and the cost fit nicely into
athletic department budgets before schools landed the largesse from
corporate sponsors, stadium suites and television contracts worth
multimillions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   If it could work then, it can work now. Devise a dollar figure,
draft the legislation and put it in place. It will certainly beat
the impending chaos NCAA administrators will soon experience from
their most recent tweaking of the rules.
QUICK HITS
TV DECISION DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives have exercised their right to wait until Sunday
before deciding whether to show Nebraska-Texas A&AMP;M or
Colorado-Kansas State as the network's 2:30 p.m. game Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The unselected contest, associate commissioner Tim Allen said,
will move to 6 p.m. and will be televised by Fox Sports Southwest
or FX. Also, the Texas Tech-Oklahoma State game will be a 6 p.m.
telecast on Fox Sports Southwest or FX.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-Oklahoma game will be televised at 11:30 a.m. by
KXTX/Ch. 39, giving the league a season-high four telecasts on Oct.
10. Alfred earns opportunity Because he drove the team to a
go-ahead touchdown in the fourth quarter of last week's 18-16 loss
to No. 15 Colorado, Baylor backup quarterback Jermaine Alfred will
receive more playing time in Saturday's game at Texas Tech, said
coach Dave Roberts. But Odell James, who has completed 16 of 37
passes (43.2 percent) with three interceptions and no touchdowns,
will remain the Bears' starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odell's our quarterback, but Jermaine may play a little more
this week than he has been,'' said Roberts, who watched Alfred
complete nine of 16 passes for 58 yards, including two third-down
connections on the fourth-quarter scoring drive. ``We've got to
improve our quarterback play.'' FRETS ABOUT FUMBLES
</P>
<P>
   The yards still come in bunches for Texas Tech tailback Ricky
Williams, who leads the nation in rushing with 192.5 yards per
game. But so have the fumbles. In the past two weeks, Williams has
lost the ball three times inside the opponent's 5-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe Ricky is trying too hard and we've got to
address that,'' Tech coach Spike Dykes said. ``Once it gets to be
habit-forming, you've got to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Williams' two fumbles in last week's 31-24 victory against
Iowa State, Dykes said both were the result of improper
ball-handling rather than jarring hits by Cyclones' defenders.
EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State officials will receive $1.3 million for moving
Saturday's home game against Nebraska from Stillwater, Okla., to
Kansas City, Mo., where most of the 70,000 at Arrowhead Stadium
figure to be Cornhuskers fans. Cowboys coach Bob Simmons said he
agrees with the decision to move the game and maximize the money.
Players say location shouldn't matter. ``Either place you play,
it's tough to beat Nebraska,'' linebacker Kenyatta Wright said.
``If you're not assignment perfect, you're going to lose.'' ...
Mike McGee, athletic director at South Carolina, has confirmed that
he has been contacted about the vacant Big 12 commissioner's job,
joining a list that includes Dan Beebe, Ohio Valley Conference
commissioner, and Karl Benson, Western Athletic Conference
commissioner. The Big 12 search committee is expected to meet with
candidates next week. ... Texas joins No. 1 Ohio State, No. 17
Oregon and Indiana on the short list of Division I-A teams ranked
among the nation's top 20 in the four major offensive categories:
rushing, passing, scoring and total offense. The Longhorns are 2-2.
The others are a combined 9-1. ... Baylor coach Dave Roberts,
explaining the evolution of an offensive line dotted with
junior-college transfers: ``Our first game, the offensive line hit
the wrong people. Last week against Colorado, they hit the right
people. They just didn't stay blocked. So we're making progress,
but we've got a long way to go.'' The Bears' average of 3.5 yards
per rush ranks 10th among Big 12 schools. ... Oklahoma coach John
Blake, on the influence of former Cowboys coach Barry Switzer, a
frequent visitor to Sooners practices: ``He gives me his opinions,
which I'd rather keep between him and I. But he knows we have
potential and thinks we're on the verge of making things happen.''
Blake said he is not concerned about an option-based offense that
produces 249 of its 330 yards each week on the ground, yet has more
passing touchdowns (4) than rushing touchdowns (3). ... Blake will
have Matt Reeves, a walk-on, handle kicking duties Saturday against
Colorado. Reeves, who hit two field goals in a 13-12 loss to
California Sept. 19, replaces Jeff Ferguson, who missed two
field-goal attempts and an extra-point attempt against the Golden
Bears.
</P>
</TEXT>
