<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE STRUGGLING? NOT AGAINST RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte's woeful September boiled down to major
failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had good stuff my last three or four times out,
but I wasn't able to stay out of the big innings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had good stuff last night at Yankee Stadium. The
Yankees' left-hander retired the first 12 Rangers he faced.
</P>
<P>
   But when Juan Gonzalez led off the fifth with a double down the
left-field line, one of those big innings loomed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pettitte escaped without major damage. Will Clark flied
out to deep center field to move Gonzalez to third, and Ivan
Rodriguez followed with a single to drive in the run. Pettitte then
got Todd Zeile to pop out to short and induced an inning-ending
groundout from Mike Simms.
</P>
<P>
   That inning, Pettitte said, was the key to beating the Rangers
in Game 2 of the American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big inning for me to hold them to one run,''
Pettitte said. ``When Gonzalez hit the double, I didn't give up two
or three runs. That was the big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the only damage the Rangers inflicted upon Pettitte in
seven innings, as he pitched his team to a 3-1 victory, giving the
Yankees a commanding 2-0 lead in the best-of-five series. He
allowed the one run on three hits, walked none and struck out
eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the old Andy,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The old Andy was the ace of the Yankees' staff. The new,
definitely not improved Andy struggled in the final couple of
months. He was 2-2 with a 5.71 earned-run average in August, and
1-3 with a 6.75 ERA in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having a lot of trouble with everything,'' he said.
``Mechanically, I was out of sync. Then I gave up hits, and my
confidence started to go.''
</P>
<P>
   There was even speculation Pettitte would be left off the
postseason roster. Torre, though, didn't consider it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never even entered my mind,'' he said. ``Andy has done so much
in the three years I've been here. Just because you get in a little
bit of a slump you don't lose faith in somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte rewarded that faith by being at the top of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get my changeup going, I was able to throw my
curveball for strikes and I had good control of my two-seam
fastball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That control might have been his best asset. He took advantage
of plate umpire Durwood Merrill's extra wide strike zone, spotting
his fastball off the plate and either getting called strikes or
forcing the Rangers to swing.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte didn't just dominate the Rangers, he shredded their
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Rangers to pull off the upset in this series was
to beat the left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the best laid plans of would-be giant killers.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, the first Yankees left-hander, pitched eight
shutout innings as New York won Game 1, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte almost matched him last night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
