<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-SPENCER-WRITETHRU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES FIND BONUS IN SPENCER 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shane Spencer quickly squashed a suggestion that he
is living out a fairy tale. After all, fairy tales end with
``happily ever after,'' and the Yankees outfielder isn't to that
point yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be a storybook until this is all over,'' Spencer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' when you play for the Yankees this season, refers to
the entire postseason, up to and including winning the World
Series. They are a long way from that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have eight or nine wins to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, they are one win away from dispatching the Rangers in
the first round, thanks largely to Spencer's magic wand.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer homered off Rick Helling in the second inning and
singled ahead of Scott Brosius' homer in the fourth as the Yankees
won, 3-1, to take a 2-0 lead in the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's saga might not be a fairy tale, but the story of the
late-blooming, 26-year-old phenom still reads like something off
the fiction shelves.
</P>
<P>
   He was a minor-league slugger seemingly destined to stay in the
bush leagues because of a lack of opportunity on the talent-rich
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer finally made the team this year because of injuries, but
didn't see much playing time. He spent the season bouncing back and
forth between Triple-A Columbus and the Yankees' bench.
</P>
<P>
   He finally got a chance in September and began swatting balls
over the fence at an amazing rate. Spencer batted .421 with a
team-leading eight homers and 21 runs batted in in the final month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it worked out it seems like this year I was ready, and
I'm glad I stayed with the Yankees so I can say I made it with the
best organization ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The afterthought for most of his career earned his first
postseason start yesterday, playing left field against the Rangers.
He made it a game to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get cheated,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``He knows what to do with that piece of wood, and it's not
cleaning his shoes. My only question is, where's he been all
year?''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was on the bench for Game 1 because Torre opted for the
better defense of Chad Curtis. With Joe Girardi replacing Jorge
Posada behind the plate for Game 2, Torre needed something else out
of his left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Spencer will be hard to put on the bench again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected the kid to do what he did,'' Torre said.
``It's going to be tough to get him out of there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3361 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-01 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART OF RANGERS' LINEUP ANEMIC DURING THIS POSTSEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is the first of October, Rangers fans. Do you know
where your ``Se$or Octubre'' is?
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, who put on one of the most awesome hitting
exhibitions in baseball postseason history two years ago, has
vanished, and he has taken the rest of the Rangers' offense with
him.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Rangers, dismal 3-1 losers to the Yankees last
night in Game 2 of the American League Division Series, face the
almost insurmountable task of winning three consecutive games in
order to advance to the AL Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Do not hold your breath waiting for this to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Missing persons reports have been filed with the New York City
police, and Rangers manager Johnny Oates has inquired about putting
the faces of Gonzalez, Will Clark, Rusty Greer and Pudge Rodriguez
on milk cartons.
</P>
<P>
   Posters will be available at convenience stores and post offices
sometime this afternoon as the Rangers take the day off to
contemplate how precarious their situation has become.
</P>
<P>
   Finding their heart again is first on their list of things to
do.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of their once powerful batting order, that is.
</P>
<P>
   When Oates predicted that starting pitching would be the key to
this best-of-five series against the Yankees, he didn't expect the
Rangers' vaunted offense, which carried this team to its second
division title in three years, to produce a total of one run and 10
hits in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the regular season, starting a left-hander against
Texas was like dropping a goldfish into a tank of piranhas. But
it's the Rangers who have gone into the tank against the Yankees'
David Wells and Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not collect a hit of any kind in the first three
innings of either game and have had just one single in the first
four innings of both games.
</P>
<P>
   And while the sudden hush from Rangers bats has been basically
universal, it is the Fading Four _ Greer, Gonzalez, Clark and
Rodriguez _ the group that produced 105 home runs and drove in 458
runs this season, whose disappearance is most critical.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, their performance has been abysmal, a combined
4-for-31, 1 run, 1 run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, they have been merely pathetic: Greer: 1-for-8;
Gonzalez, 1-for-8; Clark 1-for-8; Rodriguez, 1-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need,'' Oates said, ``is to swing the bats like we did
all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to do that when you're trying to swallow the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is no more to blame than anyone in the lineup, it's
just that much is expected of the man who drove in 157
regular-season runs and who will likely win his second American
League most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying the best I can, but I'm human,'' a depressed
Gonzalez said in the gloom of the Rangers' clubhouse. ``I go to
home plate and I try hard for my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez did produce the Rangers' only extra base hit of the
night, a double down the left-field line leading off the fifth. He
scored the Rangers' only run in two games here on Rodriguez's
two-out single to left.
</P>
<P>
   That, folks, was the Rangers' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez struck out leading off the seventh against Pettitte in
one of his most frustrating at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of pitches to hit, but I missed them,'' he
said, shaking his head. ``Our offense is one of the best in
baseball, and we scored one run here. That surprises everyone in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, has stepped forward to trigger the offense. Two
Octobers ago, Gonzalez was the Rangers' only hot hitter. In the
final two days of September 1998, they had none.
</P>
<P>
   There was a chance for redemption in the ninth. Tom Goodwin led
off with a pinch-single off Yankees closer Mariano Rivera. But
Greer, swinging at the first pitch, finished a futile 0-for-4 night
with a weak roller to second.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez had a chance to rekindle 1996 glory but bounced
harmlessly to third. And Clark, who cut his teeth on clutch
situations like this early in his career, struck out swinging on a
chin-high fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees fans danced into the streets, the Rangers trudged off to
their clubhouse and a flight home and September faded away.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first of October.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Se$or Octubre'' is going to make an appearance, it had had
better be soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
