</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE PITCHES YANKEES WITHIN GAME OF SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once again, the starting pitcher dominated. Once
again, the bottom of the order produced the runs. Once again, a
little was more than enough for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   New York put the Texas Rangers on life support Tuesday night,
taking a 2-0 lead in this best-of-five Division Series with a 3-1
victory before 57,360 fans at Yankee Stadium. The Yankees can
finish off the Rangers  &UR; tomorrow &LR;  night at The Ballpark in
Arlington, Texas, with David Cone going against the Pattonesque
Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   New York got a terrific outing from lefthander Andy Pettitte,
who allowed three baserunners and a gift run in seven innings. He
struck out eight, didn't walk a soul, and, like David Wells in a
2-0 win the night before, kept the big guns quiet. The Rangers came
into the postseason batting .316 against lefties, but they managed
only 8 hits in 53 at-bats (.151) against Wells and Pettitte while
scoring one run.
</P>
<P>
   New York, meanwhile, was again opportunistic at the plate. It
had no other choice. Rookie phenom Shane Spencer, a k a Joe Hardy,
rewarded manager Joe Torre for starting him by drilling a solo
homer in his first playoff at-bat in the second inning. In his
second at-bat, Spencer singled and came home on Scott Brosius's
first playoff dinger, making it 3-0 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be a storybook until it's over,'' said Spencer, who
is fast making left field his permanent domain. ``I'm happy just to
be out there. I'm riding it now, cherishing every moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Spencer to an already loaded Yankees team almost
seems like overkill, as if Bill Gates discovered he had been left a
huge inheritance by some unknown rich aunt. Spencer was sent back
to the minors three times this season, came up for good in
September, then hit .421 in the month, with eight homers (three
grand slams) and 21 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get cheated,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates said.
``He knows what that piece of wood is for, and it's not to clean
his shoes. My only question is, where has he been all year?''
</P>
<P>
   Torre started Spencer because Darryl Strawberry is ailing, the
manager wanted an extra bat in the lineup, and he felt gimpy-kneed
Tim Raines would have trouble with the slippery turf. Torre never
told Spencer; he simply posted the lineup. ``I started him
hopefully to do what he did,'' Torre said. ``But I never expected
him to come in and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's first at-bat was an amazing moment. He drilled a 2-2
Helling fastball over the 399-foot sign in left-center. He was
summoned out of the dugout for the obligatory curtain call and got
another big hand when he went back to the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Spencer singled to center with one out. On the
next pitch, Brosius drilled a line shot into the right-field seats.
That was it for the Yankees, who were hardly dominating. Their
first five hitters combined for one hit in 19 at-bats against
20-game winner Rick Helling, another Texas tough-luck loser, like
Todd Stottlemyre the night before. Batting champ Bernie Williams
and Derek Jeter are hitless in the first two games, and Tino
Martinez has one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte yielded a run in the fifth, but how he handled the
situation spoke volumes about the night. His one weakness this
season has been to allow the dreaded big inning. On this occasion,
Juan Gonzalez (1 for 8) hit a bullet down the third base line,
breaking up Pettitte's perfect game. He tried for a double, but
Spencer's throw was in time. Gonzalez, however, avoided the out by
kicking the ball out of second baseman Chuck Knoblauch's glove. He
scored two batters later, but Pettitte avoided further damage by
getting Todd Zeile (pop to shortstop) and Mike Simms (grounder to
third).
</P>
<P>
   ``That was key for me,'' Pettitte said. ``It was a big inning
for me because I was able to hold them to that one run.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not in danger again.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson got the first two outs of the eighth, and Mariano
Rivera came on to get his second straight save. For the second
straight game, the Rangers managed only five hits.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has to be wondering what is going on here. Prior to the
series, he said he liked his team's chances if his starting
pitchers performed well. They have. What he could not have
envisioned was his league-leading offense (.298) going south. In
two games, Yankee pitchers have yielded one walk and struck out 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can swing the bats better than we did here,'' Oates
said. ``Hopefully, when we get home, we can get the bats going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
