<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-PROBLEMS-H     10-01 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PROBLEMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has happened again and again over the course of baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   When you least expect it, somebody comes out of nowhere in the
postseason to make the big play, score the big run or deliver the
big hit. Or even have the big series.
</P>
<P>
   And it's usually somebody whom nobody would ever expect to make
such a huge impact in a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the local comedians would name Craig Biggio, Derek
Bell or Jeff Bagwell as those least likely to come up with the big
hit in the playoffs considering their efforts in last year's
first-round sweep by the Atlanta Braves and Tuesday's Game 1 of the
National League Division Series against the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   They have combined to go 2-for-47 in those four games, all
losses, but that's not what we're talking about here.
</P>
<P>
   No, we mean unheralded guys like Dusty Rhodes of the New York
Giants, who hit a game-winning three-run homer in the 10th inning
of Game 1 in the 1954 World Series, and then went on to hit another
homer to help lead the Giants over heavily favored Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times in the postseason there are guys, lesser
lights, who come along and become stars,'' said Astros manager
Larry Dierker. ``That can happen in this series, as it can in any
other series.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Astros are still searching for such a hero.
</P>
<P>
   While so much attention has been focused on the struggles
Biggio, Bagwell and Bell have endured, none of the other Astros
have really been able to come through with much offense at all.
</P>
<P>
   There has been nobody like New York's Brian Doyle, who came off
the Yankees' bench when Willie Randolph got hurt and batted .438 in
the 1978 World Series. Doyle, who helped the Yankees beat Los
Angeles in six games, didn't even make the roster the next spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the other Astros have been just as impotent as the big guns.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez, who hit .125 (1-for-8) against the Braves last
season, went 0-for-3, striking out all three times, against San
Diego on Tuesday. Bill Spiers was 0-for-11 against Atlanta in '97
but scratched out one of the Astros' four hits off Kevin Brown in
Game 1 against the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are still waiting, which is funny since this a team
that had several players emerge from the shadows of their more
high-profile teammates to make key plays. The Astros could not have
amassed 49 come-from-behind victories, including 27 on their last
at-bat, without contributions from everyone, not just the Killer
B's and Moises Alou.
</P>
<P>
   ``All season long, when someone was in a funk or something,
everybody picked one another up,'' Carl Everett said. ``It's been a
team game all season long. To me, there's no reason to shift the
focus on them (Bagwell, Biggio, Bell and Alou) now. Right now,
everybody just has to do their job individually, and it will become
a team game.''
</P>
<P>
   You would probably be safe in betting on either Sean Berry or
Everett to be the guy who does come through for the Astros. In many
of the Astros' come-from-behind victories, it was Everett who kept
things going with a big hit. And it was Berry who was the hero in
the Astros' last-at-bat victories, winning three with homers and
another with a bases-loaded single.
</P>
<P>
   With the offensive talent the Astros have from top to bottom of
their lineup, they probably don't need someone like Oakland's Gene
Tenace, who, after hitting just five home runs all season, hit four
homers in the 1972 World Series, helping the A's beat the favored
Cincinnati Reds in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   No, what they needed Tuesday was someone like Atlanta's
Francisco Cabrera, who came off the bench to deliver a two-out,
two-run single off Doug Drabek to beat Pittsburgh in the National
League Championship Series and send the Braves to their second
straight World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the character of this team,'' Spiers said.
``It's been that way all year. We've had people picking each other
up all year. The only thing we can do is keep doing what we've been
doing all summer. Things will take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros aren't about to panic. Instead, they will just keep
plugging along, the same way they piled up a franchise-record 102
victories this season. They way they see things, even with Brown's
overpowering performance, the Astros were right there at the end,
just one key hit away from either tying the game or winning.
</P>
<P>
   And they figure that sooner or later, someone, not necessarily
one of the Killer B's or Alou, is going to deliver that key hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to press,'' Berry said. ``If you press in this
game, especially in the playoffs you don't have time to do that
because before you know it you'll be going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's just one game. Everybody tried to make a big deal
out of who won or lost that game. Every game is so important in a
five-game series. (Today's) game is just as important as
(Tuesday's). We just have to go out and win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
