<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3367 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-01 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ON VERGE OF LEARNING HOW NASTY A WORD IS `SWEEP'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All is meek for the Rangers. Quietly, they fell again
last night, which meant there is now a confirmed date tomorrow with
the Grim Sweeper.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into Yankee Stadium to open the playoffs, the Rangers
counted heavily upon the huff-and-puff of a dangerous batting
order. And they prayed for pitching guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Score one for prayer. What has been received is the surprising
luxury of pitching _ winnable pitching _ for two games, only to
have the bats go to the devil.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, maybe David Wells really wasn't that good for
the Yankees in Game 1. Not after Andy Pettitte basically matched
him in Game 2 in everything except total shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte debuted last night in the 1998 postseason, having gone
2-5 with a massive ERA just under 7-point for his last seven
regular-season starts. It was questionable of manager Joe Torre
giving him this key assignment. But the Rangers took both Torre and
Pettitte off the hook, looking clueless at the plate in a 3-1 New
York victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sweep is such a nasty word in any postseason competition. Guess
who will be attempting to avoid ol' Nasty in Game 3 tomorrow night
at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is a Game 4, also blame the boredom of the Rangers'
bats for removing this series from the No. 1 prime-time slot on
Saturday. That would now be a noon start, due to a sudden network
shift last night after the Yankees went up two games to zip.
</P>
<P>
   This series, of course, is over, it's just a matter of when.
Winning three straight from the Yankees is as likely as a weekend
snowstorm in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   From the Dept. of You-Never-Know, the Rangers' pitching staff
allowed five runs in the two games at Yankees Stadium, and still
had L's hung on starters Rick Helling last night and Todd
Stottlemyre in Game 1. Coming in as long-odds underdogs, the
Rangers had to think they could have allowed five runs per game and
still had a shot at winning both. Being outscored, 5-1, over 18
innings eliminated that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Helling had to bulldog his way through six innings, throwing a
massive 119 pitches, but the right-hander kept a win available. His
downfall was a pair of home-run balls, one being a solo from
Yankees rookie monster Shane Spencer, and the other a two-run shot
by Scott Brosius, the bottom-of-the order bomber.
</P>
<P>
   But all Helling and the Rangers' bullpen lacked was run support,
the same as Stottlemyre the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the positive pitching, if these two losses didn't
qualify as a bitter disappointment, then...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bitter,'' disagreed manager Johnny Oates, strongly.
``This is baseball. We got outpitched. I'd like for us to swing the
bats better, to take better swings, to score runs. But what are you
gonna do? We have pitched well, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Pettitte, the Rangers' order appeared to have a bigger
problem last night with composure. Basically, the only noise coming
from the batter's box was verbal barking at the strike zone of
plate umpire Durwood Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   What's this _ some kind of sudden discovery that Merrill has a
wide strike zone? He's been umpiring the same way for 21 years.
When Durwood is behind the plate, you'd best be hacking. Instead,
the Rangers took called strike after called strike, making it easy
for Pettitte. Way too easy.
</P>
<P>
   Less mouth and more cuts might have served the Rangers better,
but instead, the frustration piled up.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, pitching coach Dick Bosman figured to be under the
same fire in this series as he was for most of the season. Instead,
Bosman dressed quietly again last night in the visitor's clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have responded to the challenge,'' he said of
Helling and Stottlemyre. ``Everyone knows this is a tough place to
pitch, and a tough club to get outs off of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helling didn't give them much to hit, despite the fact they
\Rthe Yankees\S made him work hard, fouling off all those pitches.
The two \Rhome runs\S were the only time he missed, and that's
great considering all the pitches he threw.''
</P>
<P>
   A questionable rotation for most of the season has certainly met
the September challenge, including the two games here and the five
divisional showdown contests with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of our guys,'' said Bosman. ``Pressure pitching is
what September and October are all about.''
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, is pressure hitting. But for the two games here,
the Rangers didn't qualify in that area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     10-01 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ACCORDING to America's leading baseball authorities, there's only
one way for the Astros to escape this postseason malaise of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   They must hit.
</P>
<P>
   Hit, hit, hit.
</P>
<P>
   Then hit some more.
</P>
<P>
   They must treat Andy Ashby today as though he were Andy
Griffith. They must tear into the baseballs that Andy Ashby will be
throwing as though they have Osama bin Laden's mug on them.
</P>
<P>
   In short, to finally whiff a little playoff success, they've got
to stop whiffing. Either the Astros' bats stand up and be counted,
or the walk back to the dugout is going to take them directly into
the Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way to break the ice,'' Craig Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   And to break Ashby's heart. I mean, this is a guy who hasn't
been able to get anybody out since about July. Of late, after a
rousing start to his season, Ashby has been more like Andy Griffith
than Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine, John Smoltz and Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Against that particular Fab Four, the Astros are 0-4 over two
Division Series, spanning the 1997-98 playoffs. They have managed a
mere 20 hits in 126 at-bats, which computes to a .159 average.
Their ``slugging'' percentage is all of .198, since only three of
those 20 hits have gone for extra bases, one of them an accidental
Chuckie Carr homer.
</P>
<P>
   They have scored six runs, Carr's dinger included. And they have
struck out 41 times, practically once in every three plate
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Appalling.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do? Gerry Hunsicker, the general manager, joked that
he was going to bring in a sports psychologist, or perhaps a
hypnotist.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Tom McCraw, who needs to try something by virtue
of his job description, said he was going to call a meeting after
Wednesday's optional workout. Mack's not ordinarily a fan of
group-therapy sessions, but these straits are beyond dire. It was
to be just Mack and his boys, circling their wagons.
</P>
<P>
   His message? In 25 words or less, relax and hit the &AMP;%! ball.
More specifically, drive it to all fields. Stop trying to yank
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might suspect the Astros are choking, and maybe they
are. Biggio, to his credit, accepted the mounting heat regarding
the Astros' offensive anemia as intrinsic to the lofty territory
they occupy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were winning anyway,'' he said, ``it wouldn't be a
story. But we're losing, so it's the story. We need to refocus and
change our results. In the playoffs, it's a different game. You
only face the other teams' horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's no debating the merits of the opposing arms
they've been up against, and Brown, in particular, was even better
than he's supposed to be. As Larry Dierker mused: ``As good as his
stuff is, I've never seen it as good as it was (Tuesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Brown struck out 16 Astros over eight innings, the most ever by
a pitcher in a Division Series. Along about the fifth, the Astros
were whipped, whimpering puppies. Hunsicker swears he could see
their early confidence literally drain, inch by painful inch, from
their peaked personages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were OK when the game started,'' he said, ``but as it wore
on and we saw what kind of stuff Brown had, we became afraid to go
deep into the count against him. By swinging at bad pitches early,
we expanded his strike zone, and he definitely didn't need the
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker suggested a drastic change in attitude is in order for
the Astros to resume being the club they're supposed to be, a club
worthy of its 102-60 regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take the next step beyond just winning the division
championship,'' he said, ``we've got to be able to handle the top
pitchers in the game. That's what the postseason is all about _
beating the great pitchers. Because you don't see many bad ones
this time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's doing it. Hey, the Braves don't go to the World
Series every year.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Florida went last season instead, propelled in part by the
big stick of soft-walking Moises Alou. Alou the Astro, alas, also
brought balsa with him to the Astrodome instead of hardwood against
Brown, although he did slap a ninth-inning infield single off
Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently buoyed by that small success, Alou exercised his
option Wednesday and passed on batting practice. But, present in
street clothes, he did convene with McCraw afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, for his part, was keeping his trap shut. What does an
old pitcher know about slump-busting, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball's not a sport where you can give supercharged pep
talks,'' he said. ``You're better off if you're not too fired up.
The key is staying patient. So I haven't said anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Biggio, designated leader of the so-called Killer B's,
whose production shortfall has been most conspicuous, he made a
simple suggestion before parting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be aggressive,'' he said. ``And remember to have
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Astros have failed spectacularly on both fronts.
Come October, which comes today, to hit is to live, and they're
dying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
