<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TEXACO-HNS &LR;      10-01 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TEXACO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The 1998 FedEx championship was decided two races ago when Alex
Zanardi clinched the PPG Cup and the $1 million bonus faster than
any driver in Championship Auto Racing Teams history.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might take a little luster off the inaugural Texaco Grand
Prix of Houston on Sunday and the other two races left on the
schedule, but it's still a race to the finish for a handful of
drivers who remain in contention for second place.
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up status might not sound like such a glamorous deal, but
$500,000 is on the line for the driver who can finish No. 2 in the
points standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say what it means to everybody else, but I can tell
you that second place is very important to us,'' said Scotland's
Dario Franchitti, who drives the Team Kool Green Reynard/Honda.
``We had such a slow start this year that we knew early on we were
out of the hunt for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to have the chance now to finish second really says a lot
about this team and what we've done in the second half. It would
mean a lot to get the money, but it would mean more to us just to
say we were No. 2 for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti ranks fourth in the CART standings with 122 points,
but he is only four points behind third-place Adrian Fernandez. The
man in the No. 2 spot is Jimmy Vasser, the 1996 champion. Vasser
has 136 points, but five drivers are within 30 points of Vasser _
Fernandez, Franchitti, Greg Moore (118), Michael Andretti (112) and
Scott Pruett (106).
</P>
<P>
   Pruett is the only one of those contenders who has not won at
least one race this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every race is critical the rest of the way,'' Vasser said. ``I
think we have the tools to put the Target car second, but there are
five other guys who have a legitimate shot at it. They're all good
drivers with good equipment, too, so there's a lot at stake in the
last three races. It should be fun for the fans to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   A maximum of 22 points is available at each race for the winner.
Finishing first is worth 20 points, but a driver can earn one bonus
point for being the top qualifier and one point for leading the
most laps.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top 12 finishers in the 28-car field receive points, so
it's not out of the question for any of the drivers who rank No. 2
through No. 7 to end &UR;  &LR; up as the runner-up to Zanardi this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if Vasser finished 13th on Sunday and Moore won the
event, Moore would have at least 138 points and Vasser would have
136. Another scenario could have Andretti winning the last three
events while Vasser finishes with two fourth-place finishes and one
fifth. Andretti would have at least 172 points, and Vasser would
have 170.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are endless for how the standings will shake
out in the last three events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with all the bad things that have happened to us, it's
amazing we still have a shot at finishing second in the points,''
said Andretti, who has finished second in four races this year.
``It's a lot of money to shoot for. Plus, there's a million bucks
waiting for the winner of the last race, and that's a nice
incentive as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The CART Championship Series 500 at California Speedway on Nov.
1 will have a record winner's purse of $1 million. It could be a
$2.5 million payday for Chip Ganassi's Target team that day if
Vasser wins the race and finishes second in the points
championship, because Zanardi has clinched the $1 million prize for
the title.
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi and Vasser have combined to win the past three
championships. If they end up first and second in the standings
this year, it would be the first time team members finished at the
top of the points chase since 1994, when Al Unser Jr. and Emerson
Fittipaldi were first and second, respectively, for Team Penske.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to do this for Chip,'' Vasser said. ``It would
say a lot about this organization if we are one and two this year
after winning the last three titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser believes Sunday's race will be the toughest test of the
remaining three events because the 1.68-mile, 10-turn course
downtown is an unknown for all the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A brand-new course makes things more difficult for us but not
insurmountable,'' Vasser said. ``We're all in the same boat, so
it's just a matter of which team can get its cars set up the best.
One of our goals is to have a good car coming off the trailer so we
can pick up the track a little more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti has done a good job of picking up the track nuances
at street and road courses this season. He won back-to-back at Road
America in Wisconsin on Aug. 16 and the Vancouver street race in
Canada on Sept. 6. But Franchitti also was on the pole at the
street race in Toronto on July 19 and led 76 of the first 79 laps
before his day ended with a spin caused by faulty brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confident of our chances on these type of courses,
so this should be a good place for us,'' Franchitti said. ``But you
never know for sure until you get out there. I do know that it's
going to be one heck of a fight between the guys battling for the
No. 2 spot in the championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
