<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3371 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HUNSICKER-TOWERS-     10-01 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HUNSICKER-TOWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
It was the offseason of 1995, and Gerry Hunsicker and Kevin Towers
were trying to secure their first jobs as major-league general
managers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As fate would have it, they were candidates for the same
position, only neither knew it. Towers, the Padres' assistant GM at
the time, even sat in on interviews while the franchise's brain
trust quizzed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Padres surprised everyone, including Towers, by
removing the ``assistant'' from his title. Hunsicker didn't get
that job, but a promising challenge awaited him in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Both men laugh about the irony of the situation now as their
teams battle for the right to advance to the National League
Championship Series. That alone is proof it could not have worked
out better for either of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I interviewed for the job, Kevin seemed to be
promoting me,'' Hunsicker said. ``I remember talking to him and
feeling like we could really work well together. He has a great
personality and great people skills. He's one of those guys that
everyone likes five minutes after they meet him. It's ironic how
our paths crossed. A week later I was being interviewed for (the
Astros) job and the Padres were deciding on Kevin.''
</P>
<P>
   They both took jobs that didn't allow the GM to be on equal
financial footing with most of their counterparts, and they both
excelled by getting the most out of their limited resources.
Hunsicker built a team that is competing in the playoffs for the
second year in a row; the Padres also have reached the postseason
twice during Towers' three-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute that their deep backgrounds in scouting
and player development have nothing to do with the shrewd decisions
that went into building their championship-caliber clubs.
Hunsicker, in particular, has developed a reputation for being on
the right side of lopsided deals.
</P>
<P>
   He acquired starting center fielder Carl Everett for John Hudek,
a reliever the team didn't think it had a place for on the roster.
Righthanded reliever Jay Powell came to the Astros for minor-league
catcher Ramon Castro, who most believe never would have reached
starter status.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are that Hunsicker got the best of Towers in
the Sean Bergman-for-James Mouton swap. Bergman won 12 games for
the Astros this season; Mouton struggled with the Padres and was
left off the playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember telling (Padres president) Larry (Lucchino) that he
couldn't go wrong with Gerry, and I really meant that,'' Towers
said. ``Gerry has done a really good job of putting this team
together. I don't think you could find many moves that he made this
year that worked out in a negative way. It's been all positive. I
can't say enough about the job he's done here. This is a very good
ballclub he's put together.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's the big deals that seem to define a GM, and both
pulled off at least one major coup for 1998. Towers traded for
Kevin Brown, who had 16 strikeouts and beat the Astros 2-1 in Game
1 of the Division Series; Hunsicker added star-quality players in
Moises Alou and Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us have shown that we're not afraid to pull he trigger
and make some big deals,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of acting in such a manner is high when you oversee a
small-market club without the financial resources to outspend
mistakes. But mistakes have been few and far between for Hunsicker
and Towers, and that's the main reason they are the leading
candidates for NL Executive of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't like talking about awards,'' said Hunsicker,
who shared Towers' opinion on the subject. ``I will say that it's
meaningful from the standpoint that your peers are doing the
voting, and everyone wants to be respected by their peers. But
that's really secondary to what the organization accomplishes. I
can assure you it will be a bigger disappointment if our ballclub
doesn't progress in the postseason than rather I get an award or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. has the Padres to thank for
selecting Towers over Hunsicker. Otherwise, Hunsicker would not
have been available when the Astros came calling. Although McLane
is partial to Hunsicker for obvious reasons, he believes both men
deserve consideration for the NL's top award for an executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them have done truly outstanding jobs,'' McLane said.
``Neither team is the Braves, the Mets, the Dodgers, the Orioles,
the Yankees or even the Rangers. Neither one of us has financial
resources like that. For every investment we make in salary, we
have to make it pay off or we won't be a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money doesn't buy success. There are a lot of teams that spend
more money, but never win. Spending a lot of money doesn't
guarantee a lot of success, and that's why I think you have to
respect what Gerry and Kevin have done. We're proud to have Gerry
as our general manager. He really got us some bargains with some of
these guys, and you have to have that on a club like ours. I think
both of them deserve a great deal of credit and recognition, but
particularly Gerry.''
</P>
<P>
   When the award winner is announced, we'll find out who GMs
around the league chose to receive the ultimate recognition.
Hunsicker or Towers? Towers or Hunsicker?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, they can't go wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0053EDT &QL; 
