<HEADER>
A3372 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      10-01 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Being down 0-1 in a five-game series doesn't exactly send up a red
flag for a team that claimed 49 come-from-behind victories and won
27 games in its last at-bat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Projections of gloom and doom quietly hovered over the Astros as
they went through an optional workout Wednesday at the Astrodome.
But not surprisingly, the whispers weren't coming from anyone
wearing an Astros uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else might be saying those things, but we're not,''
Astros right fielder Derek Bell said. ``I don't read the papers or
listen to you guys talk trash on TV. Do you guys want to pick up a
bat and try to hit Kevin Brown, John Smoltz, Greg Maddux or Tom
Glavine (the four pitchers against whom the Astros have lost their
last four playoff games)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our situation isn't dangerous. What's dangerous is when you
walk out in front of a semi truck on the interstate. That's
dangerous. Pressure is when you have to wake up in the morning
knowing you can't pay your bills. That's pressure. This isn't
pressure. If you win, you keep playing; if you lose, you go home.
It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's too early to start helping the Astros pack for an
early winter vacation, but a loss today would knock a little dust
off their suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   No National League team has won a Division Series after losing
the first two games. Randy Johnson led Seattle from an 0-2 deficit
for an improbable victory over the Yankees in a 1995 American
League Division Series, but that's obviously not the preferred way
of getting to the League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has been determined,'' Astros center fielder Carl
Everett said. ``The goal is to win three out of five games, and we
lost the first one. Now, we have to concentrate on winning three
out of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to have won the first game, but it's not
like we haven't won three out of four before. No one in this
clubhouse thinks it's over. The way this team is, we always think
we're capable of winning. That's the only way you win 102 games in
a season.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Everett is fond of pointing out, the regular season is
meaningless at this time of year. During the regular season, the
Astros had the most potent offense in the NL. But in Game 1, Padres
ace Kevin Brown ripped their bats to shreds with a 16-strikeout
performance that was the best in the four-year history of the
Division Series. Brown won a 2-1 pitchers' duel against Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Things don't figure to get any easier for the Astros today when
they try to even the best-of-five series against 17-game winner
Andy Ashby. Then again, it probably can't get much worse than in
Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we took their best shot,'' Astros shortstop Ricky
Gutierrez said. ``Ashby's a great pitcher, too. But it will be
tough for anyone to pitch as well as Brown did (Tuesday). It would
even be tough for Brown to come back and do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Now would be a good time for the Astros to break a funky pattern
that popped up more than a few times during the regular season.
There were nine times during the course of the season when the
Astros scored one run or none in a loss and also lost the following
game. On six of those occasions, they scored two or fewer runs in
the second game.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have shut down our offense before, but we usually don't
stay down for too long,'' Gutierrez said. ``This team has a lot of
offensive capabilities, and we're not going to let one game bother
us too much. We know we can score runs; it's just a matter of going
out there and doing it, and I think we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything is possible, but as for getting swept, the Astros'
regular-season performance suggests that's not likely. Their
longest losing streak this season was four games, and they lost
three in a row on only two other occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Righthander Shane Reynolds, who won 19 games during the regular
season, will try to stop the current losing streak at one when he
takes the mound for the Astros today. If the Astros go down 0-2 in
the series, they can get ready to be reminded of last year's
Division Series sweep at the hands of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can play with your mind if you let it,'' Astros third
baseman Bill Spiers said. ``But I don't think that's going to
happen with us. We all know what happened last year, but we've only
lost one game, so we're not making a big deal out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got dominated in Game 1, but we believe we have what it
takes to come back from that. That's just the character of this
team. We never say die. From what I can gather in the clubhouse, no
one is dwelling on what happened (Tuesday). The only thing we're
concerned about is trying to get a win (today). Right now, that's
the only thing that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Astros haven't won a playoff game since 1986,
securing one victory is a good place to start for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-ASHBY-HNS &LR;      10-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-ASHBY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until he arrived in San Diego, packing had come to mean more for
pitcher Andy Ashby than simply preparing for a road trip during the
baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   He had traveled some rather rocky roads that led to brief stops
in Philadelphia and Colorado. Speculation abounded over whether
Ashby might ever unpack his bags for an appreciable time in any one
major-league city.
</P>
<P>
   His talent was solid, but there was one big question about an
intangible that has kept more than a few would-be major-leaguers
from achieving their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers, sometimes it's hard to tell when they're going to
mature,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said Wednesday. ``And I think
Ashby is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, you hear how great a guy's arm is, how great
of stuff he has. But he just has trouble getting over the hump and
you don't know if he will or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (former Padres general manager) Randy Smith made a
great deal (in 1993 to get Ashby from Colorado). Then, Ashby comes
over to us and continues to develop. He started pitching with
confidence, and he's just come into his own now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, 31, will be on the mound at the Astrodome today when the
Padres try to take a 2-0 lead over the Astros in their best-of-five
National League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   While the 6-5 righthander is throwing with far more confidence
than earlier in his career, he's coming back from tendinitis in his
left hip that derailed a 1998 season that early on was filled with
victories and potential.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby became the National League's first 16-game winner Aug. 12.
He had earned his first appearance in the All-Star Game at
midseason and was in the midst of what would become his best season
in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   But the tendinitis began to surface over the second half of the
season. And Ashby's last seven starts resulted in a 1-3 record and
7.75 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   The tendinitis, said Bochy, ``was affecting his landing with the
left foot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that was causing him to elevate the ball a little
bit,'' he said. ``He's not the kind of guy to make excuses. He kept
trying to pitch through it. So we finally skipped him a start to
let that clear up. Once that cleared up, he's been pitching the way
he did the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of his first-half performance, Ashby finished
the regular season with career highs of 17 victories, 151
strikeouts, 226 innings pitched, 33 starts and five complete games.
</P>
<P>
   His 3.34 ERA was 11th-best in the National League. The Padres
were 23-10 in Ashby's 33 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was acquired from Colorado as the player to be named in a
July 1993 trade that sent righthanded pitcher Greg W. Harris and
lefthander Bruce Hurst to the Rockies in exchange for catcher Brad
Ausmus and pitcher Doug Boechter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were, at the time of the trade,'' said Bochy, ``making some
moves to unload some salaries and get some prospects, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ash had pitched in the big leagues, so you could consider him
more than a prospect. But with us being a smaller-market club,
(management) was going to let go of some salaries, go for some
prospects, start building. It was a very good move, because (Ashby)
is a good guy to start building a team with, along with Ausmus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ausmus, of course, would eventually wind up in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, meanwhile, dug roots deep into the soil around San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Kevin Brown, who beat the Astros 2-1 Tuesday, Ashby
makes for a Padres one-two punch that gave Astros manager Larry
Dierker cause for concern long before the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before the series started that the Padres pose a
particular problem for us in the sense that they have righthanded
power pitchers,'' he said. ``And those are the kind of pitchers
that match up best against our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby is optimistic about his turn on the mound today. The
tendinitis apparently is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine,'' he said. ``I threw on the sideline Monday for
about 20 minutes, and I think the big thing was the last two starts
that I had. Before the last two starts, I hadn't been able to do
any side work. So it was a big plus being able to throw without any
pain at all.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one more bit of pain Ashby would like to overcome. It
is one all of the Padres have felt since 1996, when they advanced
to the playoffs and were swept by St. Louis in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a different attitude this year,'' Ashby said. ``I
think everyone's got a little taste of (playoff experience), and we
know how disappointing it was in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played three games and went home. I know everyone in this
clubhouse, that's something we don't want to have happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
