<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3374 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-MURDERS-LADN     10-01 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-MURDERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER L.A. HOMICIDES MEAN MORE TIME TO WORK ON CASES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Los Angeles' homicide rate dropping to a
level not seen since 1970, detectives have lighter caseloads, are
solving more murders and getting more time to crack years-old
cases, police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Bernard Parks said this week that Los Angeles has
logged 307 homicides so far this year, putting the city on a record
pace toward fewer than 400 murders by the year's end, since more
occur in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, there were 1,077 homicides in Los Angeles and
detectives solved, or ``cleared'' in police terms, 60.8 percent of
the cases. By comparison, last year there were 569 homicides, and
the clearance rate was 70.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``With lower caseloads, detectives have more time to work on
cases so they should have a higher clearance rate,'' said Capt. Jim
Tatreau, commanding officer of the LAPD's Robbery-Homicide
Division, which handles many of the most complex and high-profile
homicides. ``We are seeing a higher clearance rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Parks issued a report that attributed the
decline in the rate of serious crimes to a variety of factors,
chiefly: the ``three strikes, you're out'' sentencing law; more
police on the streets; and demographics _ the decline in the number
of young males who, statistically, are most likely to be involved
in crime.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD officials are so encouraged by the trend that they have
ordered police divisions to audit unsolved cases going back five
years and to send promising cases to the Robbery-Homicide Division
for fresh looks.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles still does not have as high a clearance rate as
other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, which has twice the population and three times as
many officers, had 767 homicides last year with a clearance rate of
88.8 percent, said Lt. Stephen Biegel.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD officials also say that clearance rates must be viewed with
caution because they count all homicides solved in a year,
including crimes committed in previous years, against the number of
homicides committed that year. As a result, some divisions,
including the LAPD's West Valley Division, have had clearance rates
above 100 percent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the actual number of homicides solved can drop even with
higher clearance rates.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, LAPD officials say the drop in homicides this year has
given them a significant chance to spend more time on each case,
allowing for higher success rates in putting killers behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the city is that more apparent than in the South
Bureau, which has traditionally had the largest number of homicides
of any area of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau, which covers an area from the harbor to South
Central Los Angeles, had 428 homicides in 1993 _ nearly half of all
killings in the city _ which meant each detective handled 12 to 20
new cases that year, according to Lt. John Dunkin, who heads the
homicide unit in South Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with 106 homicides so far, detectives are handling
about five cases each, Dunkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The result: The clearance rate in South Bureau has risen from 55
percent in 1993 to 90 percent today, the lieutenant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, one of the significant factors is that detectives
have more time to work their cases, to chase down leads,'' Dunkin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police in the San Fernando Valley are also being freed up to
chase old cases and boost clearance rates.
</P>
<P>
   While some valley divisions are bettering the citywide clearance
rate, North Hollywood and others are not seeing dips in the number
of homicides and thus have had lower clearance rates.
</P>
<P>
   In North Hollywood, the clearance rate is 62 percent this year,
down from 70 percent last year and 94 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The valleywide rate so far this year is 68 percent, while in
1995, the earliest year available, the rate was 81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Nuys Division has a clearance rate of 87 percent this
year _ higher than the citywide rate.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 homicides this year, all but two have been cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the 15 homicides last year in Van Nuys Division
remains unsolved, Fisk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3375 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIERKER-BOCHY-HNS     10-01 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIERKER-BOCHY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Before they were managers, Larry Dierker made his living talking a
good game, and Bruce Bochy could call a good one.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dierker won 139 games during a 14-year major league pitching
career, 13 of those with the Astros. Bochy spent parts of nine
seasons as a catcher with San Diego, Houston and the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker never thought about a return to the playing field as a
manager. Bochy dreamed of the very notion.
</P>
<P>
   Once his playing days were completed, Dierker traded his jersey
and glove for a Hawaiian shirt, a cigar and a spot in the broadcast
booth. Bochy made three different stops as a minor-league manager,
winning three league championships and compiling a .507 winning
percentage in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Both have taken distinctly different routes to big-league
managerial positions, but the results have been similar.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, 52, is 186-138 with two National League Central titles
in two tries. Bochy, 43, is 335-295 in four seasons, guiding the
Padres to NL West crowns in two of the last three. Both are strong
candidates for NL Manager of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the wins and losses, both are also considered
players' coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to be doing something right,'' said San Diego
general manager Kevin Towers, a teammate of Bochy in the Padres'
farm system in 1988. ``It sounds like the players are responding to
(Dierker), as do our players with Bruce. I think to be a manager
these days you have to have the right personality, somebody that
can deal with the players of the 1990s. The game hasn't changed,
but the players have. It has to be somebody that is a good
communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Dierker was the right man for the job. The Astros
shocked the baseball world on Oct. 4, 1996, when they announced
Dierker would replace Terry Collins, who was fired after three
straight second-place finishes. With no previous coaching
experience, Dierker labeled his hiring as ``unconventional, risky
and adventuresome.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew his every decision _ pitching moves, strategies,
lineups, you name it _ would be under close scrutiny from critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we break out of the gate with a 10-game losing streak, I
might be worried about (doubters),'' Dierker said at the time of
the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   While some waited for Dierker to fail, it hasn't happened. Under
Dierker, the Astros have been below .500 for only 43 days during
the last two seasons. This season, the Astros moved into first
place in the NL Central April 29 and never relinquished the spot
for the remaining 135 games. They won a franchise-record 102 games
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because somebody hasn't managed doesn't mean he can't
manage,'' said Bill Virdon, the winningest manager in Astros
history with 544 victories from 1975-82. ``It's not common; there's
no question about that. It's happened. Jerry Coleman did it (going
from the broadcast booth to the dugout), but he wasn't successful
doing it. I think the critics have backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman served as the Padres' manager in 1980, when San Diego
finished last in the NL West at 73-89, before returning to his
broadcasting career.
</P>
<P>
   As Dierker looks back on the last two seasons, he is amazed at
how well things have gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done pretty well,'' Dierker said. ``I'm not the
most experienced manager. I don't think I'm as good as I can be,
but I think I have helped create an atmosphere that winning is an
expectation and not necessarily a pressure-packed, frenzied
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's philosophy has remained simple as he has strayed away
from long, drawn-out strategies. He has shown the ability to make
on-the-spot decisions, but for the most part he has assumed a
no-nonsense, laid-back approach to managing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the big impact he's had. He's let his older
players and every-day guys go out and do their jobs and didn't
really mess around with them,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said.
``At certain times he's going to intervene and do what he has to do
as a manger and make certain moves, but for the most part he leaves
us alone to do our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker still remains pitching-oriented. He holds five franchise
pitching records, and his 137 wins with the Astros are second only
to Joe Niekro's 144. When he hired his assistants, Dierker included
former hurler Vern Ruhle to head the pitching staff. Together,
despite losing 60 percent of the rotation from a year ago, they
have molded a 1998 staff that is second only to the Atlanta Braves
in ERA (3.50) and fewest runs allowed (620).
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us a chance to work out of jams that a lot other
managers might not give us a chance to work out of,'' lefthander
Mike Hampton said. ``I think it only makes us better. If we get
into some tight situations, we don't have to be looking over our
shoulder for some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy's ascension up the managerial ladder hasn't been as much
of a fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy began his playing career with the Astros in 1978 and spent
three seasons in Houston. He played one season for the Mets before
spending his final five seasons with the Padres. In his first
managerial position, Bochy won the Northwest League (Class A)
championship in 1989. He won two more titles during the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as San Diego's third-base coach from 1993-94
before being named the 15th manager in team history the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I always wanted to manage,'' Bochy said. ``As a
catcher, you sit and watch a lot of games. I knew when I was
getting toward the end (of my playing career) this is what I wanted
to do. When I went down to the minor leagues, I fell in love with
managing, worked my way through the minor leagues and got a great
opportunity. It couldn't have come at a better time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy replaced Jim Riggleman and in his first season went 70-74
in 1995, the best record for a first-year Padres manager since his
mentor, Jack McKeon (67-48), in 1988. In 1996, Bochy was named NL
Manager of the Year after guiding the Padres to their first
postseason berth since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In just four seasons, Bochy is three wins shy of becoming the
winningest manager in Padres history.
</P>
<P>
   And as is the case with Dierker, Bochy's success begins in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a terrific personality,'' Towers said. ``He has some
great one-liners to keep the guys loose. He's not afraid to kick
them in the rear end when they need to be jump-started sometimes.
He just has a great demeanor. He certainly knows the game. I think
he's one of the best in the game, but I'm biased since I'm with
him. I wouldn't want to say he's underrated, but I think he used to
be. People are starting to realize how good he really is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
