<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ They came tumbling out of the B train at 161st and
River, just as they have for generations, tawk-ing like diss and
singing the same reverberating verse over and over again: ``Let's
go, Yankees let's go, Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   They sang it loud, long and slow, as they have for generations,
enough to get the Yankees party rolling and more than enough to get
under the skin of anyone else. It's a Yankees tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, tradition means something. They expect the
remarkable and the perfect. Ruth and Gehrig. Mickey and Reggie.
</P>
<P>
   They want the unforgettable and the incomprehensible. They got
Shane Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday's memorable night at Yankee Stadium, the most
remarkable thing about these record-setting 1998 Yankees was that
their historic 114-win season came with everything but someone who
could capture the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Who cared if the guy would prove to be the real thing or not? Or
last even one day into next season? Yankees fans always reserve the
right to tear down a hero anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But this Yankees team and this season needed a budding hero, a
captivating figure, and got one in the 26-year-old Spencer, who
once was introduced to Mickey Mantle and swore he saw ``a glow
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Top to bottom, the Yanks' roster was one of very good players
having great seasons and making for a truly great year. Without
Spencer, the Yankees likely still would win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   How many teams can put such formidable sticks out there every
night as those belonging to Bernie Williams, Tino Martinez, Paul
O'Neill, Chuck Knoblauch, Derek Jeter and Scott Brosius?
</P>
<P>
   The word depth came to mind when talking about this great team.
But with Spencer, this team might now win it the traditional
Yankees way. Now, the name Shane is right there, staring at the
world with that freckled face.
</P>
<P>
   Into the Bronx jungle strode Spencer, a big, wide-eyed kid from
the Florida Keys, yessir-ing his way along, holding the keys to
57,360 hearts, and on the verge of becoming the latest
too-remarkable Yankees phenom to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in Yankee Stadium, I feel it,'' Spencer said of the
aura, expectations and demands of the tradition. ``It's always a
feeling of wow out there. There's a buzz in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was all his Wednesday night. And by the time Yankees
3, Rangers 1 was done, the final ingredient to this great team _
the nearly mythical hero _ was earning the ultimate honor from the
Yankees' fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane Spencer,'' they chanted as Spencer stepped to the plate
in his final at-bat. They continued the chant into the night and on
their way back onto the B train, marveling at the thick-legged kid
with a powerful swing who might just make October his.
</P>
<P>
   Already, September is going to be hard to top.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Spencer rocketed the towering center-field home run
that opened the scoring in the second inning, he already had been
drawing wild, mythical comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago when the general manager of Spencer's
minor-league team invited Mantle to meet the new kid, reportedly
saying, ``He's really got a chance to make it, Mick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in awe of meeting him,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the September call-up, a move Yanks skipper Joe
Torre made because the division pennant already was secured and
Torre was looking to the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we wanted to do was just take a look at him,'' Torre said.
``But what he did was pretty remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer walked among the greats, hammering eight home runs in
the month, knocking in 21 runs and batting .421. Three of his home
runs were grand slams, breaking the Yankees rookie record of two
set by Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 17 years to hit three grand slams,'' Torre said.
``This guy gets three in a couple of weeks. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre had no choice but to give the rookie a postseason start.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the heroic, mythical nature of it all when
Spencer stepped to the plate for the first time in the playoffs. He
took two strikes and shrugged, stepping out to take a few practice
swings. He then worked the count to 2-2 against Rangers 20-game
winner Rick Helling. He then hammered the next pitch to the deepest
part of the park.
</P>
<P>
   As the ball left his bat, Spencer's mouth dropped open as if to
say, ``Ohmigosh.'' He skipped down the line clenching one fist in
the air. And the booming shot landed in Monument Park behind the
center-field wall, literally bouncing off the plaque that honors
Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Too remarkable to believe. But it's what these Yankees fans
demanded. It was tradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
