<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REYNOLDS-H     10-01 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REYNOLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By JOSEPH DUARTE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
With the arrival of Randy Johnson, the title of ``ace'' _ and the
heavy burden it carries _ was lifted off the right shoulder of
Shane Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody forgot to tell Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Since the July 31 trade that brought Johnson to the Astros,
Reynolds is 7-1 with a 3.24 earned run average. The Astros won nine
of his final 11 starts over the last two months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it was good to pick the ace after the season
was over,'' said Reynolds, the Astros' starting pitcher today for
Game 2 of the National League Division Series against San Diego at
the Astrodome. ``He's the guy that you always look forward to
getting out there after a losing streak, the guy that maybe pitched
the most innings not so much had the most wins but pitched the
clutch games. That would be your ace.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Reynolds stacks up with some of the NL's No. 1
starters _ minusthe fanfare and headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Only one pitcher, Atlanta righthander Tom Glavine, won more
games than Reynolds, whose career-high 19 victories tied Chicago's
Kevin Tapani for second in the league. Reynolds' 209 strikeouts
ranked fourth, and his 233 innings pitched tied teammate Jose Lima
for sixth overall. Reynolds made 35 starts, tying for the league
high.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere, though, is Reynolds mentioned among NL Cy Young Award
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here, especially when Randy came over, he's gotten
overshadowed,'' said lefthander Mike Hampton, a teammate of
Reynolds for the past five seasons. ``Then you have the Kevin
Browns and the Braves' staff. He's one of the top pitchers in the
league and in the game, as far as I'm concerned. I've played with
him for five years now, and he keeps getting better and keeps
improving on his pitches and location. Eventually, he has a great
chance to win 20 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds had a shot at becoming just the fifth Astros pitcher _
and the first since Mike Scott in 1989 _ to reach the 20-win
plateau in his last start Sept. 26 vs. the Chicago Cubs. He allowed
one run and struck out 11 in seven innings but received a
no-decision in the Astros' 3-2 loss. It was the first time the
Astros lost in one of Reynolds' starts since Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros lacking a clear-cut No. 1 starter out of spring
training after the departure of free agent Darryl Kile, the burden
fell on Reynolds. Still trying to find consistency and control,
Reynolds struggled to a 1-2 record the first month. He won eight of
his next 11 decisions, including five straight from June 23 to July
14.
</P>
<P>
   How much of a boost was Johnson to the starting rotation?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we had that leader-type ace that we needed,''
said Reynolds, 30. ``He's a classic ace, a No. 1 guy that I think
we really needed and I think the statistics and stuff shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, hampered last season by injuries to his right knee
that required surgery, enters the playoffs with a 2-0 record and
2.53 ERA over the season's final month, a span in which he didn't
give up more than two earned runs in his last four outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people that play in Houston don't get much credit for
things that they do,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``I think
if you ask anybody around the league, they know Shane is a pretty
solid pitcher. That's all that matters to the pitchers, that your
peers respect your game. I think everybody respects the way Shane
Reynolds goes about pitching and winning ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the defining moments for Reynolds this season came in a
four-hit shutout of the Minnesota Twins. The night before the game,
Reynolds got a case of food poisoning that sent him to the hospital
and left his status for the game in doubt until two hours before
the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gamer; he's out there to win,'' Bagwell said. ``Every
year, he puts up great win-loss totals. Basically, he goes out and
wins. You can't ask for anything more from a pitcher, as a player,
than from a guy that goes out, keeps you in the game and wins. What
else would you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds finds himself in a familiar spot today _ down in the
playoffs with the Astros' hopes riding on his performance. Last
year against Atlanta, Reynolds pitched six strong innings, allowing
only two runs, but picked up the loss that eliminated the Astros
from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to make his second playoff start more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good. Everything feels good. The last start, I
thought I threw very well,'' Reynolds said. ``The postseason is
totally different. There's more out there. Not to say that the
regular season isn't a have-to-win situation, but you play 162
games. Here, you have a five-game series and whoever wins first,
the others have to go home. It's a different scenario and different
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-VAUGHN-HNS     10-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-VAUGHN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Diego's Greg Vaughn may appear on the surface to be the sort
of villain Astros fans can love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   He mashed an eighth-inning home run in Game 1 of the San
Diego-Houston National League Division Series on Tuesday, a shot
that ended up being the difference in the Padres' 2-1 victory. Six
of Vaughn's eight hits against the Astros during the regular season
were home runs. With his 50 homers and 119 RBIs this year, he would
have been a cinch to be named Most Valuable Player of his team if
not for the outrageous year closer Trevor Hoffman had.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much Astros backers may root against Vaughn,
it won't faze him. Not in the least. Padres fans, after all, sank
their teeth into him with far more disdain in the past than any
outsider could now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it got bad; it got real bad,'' Vaughn said Wednesday of
the treatment he received from San Diegans last season. ``But it
really doesn't matter. I really didn't care. It doesn't make a
difference if the guy behind the screen is screaming at me. He
doesn't have a big influence in my life. He has none. So I really
don't worry about that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy to say now. Vaughn had a huge season, and the cheers
returned for him. Now, he's at least partly responsible for the
Padres' 1-0 lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughn, getting the chance to contribute in the postseason
is even more exhilarating because of what he went through in his
first full season with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquired from Milwaukee in a trade on July 31, 1996. The
Padres went on to the playoffs that season, getting swept by St.
Louis. Vaughn got only three at-bats in that series as a pinch
hitter. That officially ended whatever honeymoon Vaughn may have
had with the fans in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was pure misery. He labored through a season in which
fans were unrelenting in their displeasure with his .216 batting
average and his 110 strikeouts, which far outnumbered his hits
(78). He was booed any time he failed to supply the pop for which
he was acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the low points came when he booted not one but two fly
balls into inside-the-park home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In Vaughn's defense, he was splitting time with Rickey Henderson
in left field, which didn't make things any easier for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a chance to play every day,'' Vaughn said. ``That
was it. All I asked was to get a chance to play every day. I would
play Monday and Friday and pinch hit. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got a chance to go at it every day. You can make a lot
of adjustments when you're out there every day. But there was
myself and Rickey Henderson. We had too many players for one
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Vaughn tried to stay as upbeat as possible. And
now, after a monstrous comeback season, Vaughn has regained his
confidence and the fans' faith. He also has made management look
good for the trade that brought him to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gets down to him being out there every day,'' Padres
manager Bruce Bochy said. ``It was a difficult situation the last
year and a half when he was here, because Rickey was here and we
had two or three other major-league players who were used to being
out there every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with that, though, I think he came into spring training
very determined. He came there in great shape. He had a personal
trainer, and it was obvious he put in a lot of work. He was
determined to show what kind of player he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled it very well. It was a tough situation; sure, there
were some fans who got down on Greg Vaughn. But in reality, it
takes someone to be mentally tough through that. And he was. It
takes a tough skin to get through what he did last year and to come
back and do what he's done for us. And I can't say enough about
what he's done and the way he's done it. I'd hate to think where
we'd be without him. And it says a lot about Greg Vaughn. He
handled the whole thing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Vaughn would be justified to view this season and this
playoff appearance as redemption, he doesn't necessarily look at it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out here to redeem myself,'' he said. ``I don't feel I
have to apologize for anything that happened. My numbers have
always spoken for themselves before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big to come back and have the chance to play. That's all
I've ever asked for. The whole bottom line is that everything
doesn't work out the way you want it to all the time. But if it
works out for the team, that's all that matters. It's a team game.
Of course everybody wants to hit .360 and hit 50 or 60 home runs
and 120 RBIs. But it doesn't always work out that way. You just do
whatever you can to help your team win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers came back. And that's how I approached it. If I
don't do anything one day, I'm still going to be playing the next
day. That makes all the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's home run off Randy Johnson on Tuesday was a majestic
shot that easily cleared the left-field wall. It was one of three
hits in four at-bats Vaughn had against Johnson. But it wasn't
because Johnson didn't have good stuff, Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always tough,'' Vaughn said of Johnson. ``It always looks
easy when you're not standing up there. He's throwing 97 miles an
hour with the slider breaking down and in on you. I didn't even get
a swing in my first at-bat. I just carried the bat back with me to
the dugout. I didn't want that to happen the rest of the day. I
just told myself to take a swing.''
</P>
<P>
   When he did, good things happened. But that has been the rule
this season for Vaughn, as he established career bests for average
(.272), hits (156), runs (112), slugging percentage (.597), RBIs
and homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sweet because we won the first game of the series,''
Vaughn said of his home run. ``But that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the series shifts to San Diego's Qualcomm Stadium after
Game 2 today at the Astrodome, Vaughn will return home as a beloved
Padre instead of the one who used to get all of the fans' angry
barbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
