<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NEAR ELIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once upon a time ...
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hit balls hard, scored runs often and instilled
consternation in those who stepped on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' rotation might not inspire fairy tales by the
Brothers Grimm, but another of its members _ this time left-hander
Andy Pettitte _ produced another grim evening for the Rangers in
this best-of-five American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte surrendered one run on three hits through seven
innings, pitching New York to a 3-1 victory in Game 2 last night at
Yankee Stadium. The victory gave the Yankees a 2-0 lead in this
series and placed the Rangers on the brink of elimination with Game
3 scheduled tomorrow night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the two most potent offensive teams in the American
League, and we've scored six runs in two ballgames,'' said Rangers
manager Johnny Oates, whose lineup produced only one of those runs.
``I don't think we've swung the bats very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Home runs from rookie Shane Spencer and Scott Brosius provided
all the Yankees' offense, and it was all they needed. Pettitte
retired the first 12 batters the Rangers sent to the plate en route
to his 94-pitch, nine-strikeout performance.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's counterpart, right-hander Rick Helling, provided the
Rangers a quality start in his first postseason appearance, but the
20-game winner fell victim to a lack of run support. Right-hander
Todd Stottlemyre suffered a similar fate during Tuesday's 2-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers collected 10 hits and drew only one walk throughout
their 18-inning stay in New York and departed without a victory
despite surrendering five runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have told you that you're crazy,'' Helling said of the
odds on that happening.
</P>
<P>
   Helling recorded nine strikeouts and issued only one walk during
his 119-pitch, six-inning appearance, but Brosius' fourth-inning
home run would be more than the Rangers' gone-fishing lineup could
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're not worried about,'' Helling said.
``Our bats have been there all year, and I'm sure they'll be there
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow?
</P>
<P>
   February?
</P>
<P>
   Brosius' two-run drive scored Spencer, who reached on a one-out
single, and gave the Yankees what proved to be an insurmountable,
three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Helling retired three of the first five Yankees batters on
strikes during the first two innings, but his two-out, 2-2 fastball
to Spencer caught too much of the plate. Spencer, the rookie cult
hero whose eight home runs and 21 runs batted in during September
led the Yankees, deposited the pitch above and beyond the 399-foot
sign in left-center field and produced the game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's tale did produce two happily-ever-after moments for
the Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   Their lineup advanced a runner beyond second base after 13 1/3
innings of this series. Right fielder Juan Gonzalez led off the
fifth inning with a double and advanced 90 feet on a deep fly ball
off the bat of first baseman Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers actually scored when Gonzalez crossed the plate with
their lone run in this series on catcher Ivan Rodriguez's single to
left field later in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Explanations?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flat-out plain and simple: Pitching,'' Clark said. ``Good
pitching beats good hitting most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, will hit again, said the first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it all year long,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers better or this story will conclude like this: The
End.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
