r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-01 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT MANAGER HAS WORK CUT OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's no truth to the rumor Glenn Hoffman was
sent to the Los Angeles Dodgers in June from Central Casting
because Kurt Russell wasn't available. The Dodgers, in need of
somebody to fill out the lineup card and spout cliches and act like
a big-league manager for just a few months, looked to Albuquerque,
not Hollywood, to fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Summoned from the franchise's Triple-A team to play the role of
consummate company man, Hoffman delivered a creditable performance.
He didn't botch any of his lines. Indeed, he played it straight
even when everyone around him seemed bent on turning the 1998
season into a farce.
</P>
<P>
   The former major-league shortstop deserved better than to be
hired in late June so he could be fired on the penultimate day of
September. But then, coaches Mark Cresse, Mike Scioscia, Manny
Mota, Joe Amalfitano, Charlie Hough, Mickey Hatcher, John Shelby
and Glenn Gregson also merited more than being treated like two-bit
extras in this ``Waterworld'' of a season.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman was relieved of his managerial duties Tuesday, after
being given all of 98 days to prove himself. That's called a
probationary period in the real world. Most bosses would have been
hard-pressed to quibble over Hoffman's results; the Dodgers went
47-41 under his direction to finish four games above the mediocrity
line at 83-79.
</P>
<P>
   But it says here his performance was largely beside the point.
Hoffman was hired to be a stand-in for his big-name successor. He
wasn't meant to be anything more than a warm body to occupy the hot
seat until the season ended and bigger names such as Felipe Alou
and Kevin Kennedy and Davey Johnson became available for the
pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been intriguing to see what the Dodgers would have
done had the team somehow rallied behind Hoffman and wrested the
wild-card berth from the Chicago Cubs. His reassignment would have
been considerably messier then, but we suspect no less unavoidable.
You don't, after all, hold on to Russell when a Will Smith or a
Leonardo DiCaprio or a Matt Damon is at your disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his nine-year playing stint in the majors,
Hoffman readily accepted his role as a backup. In signing on to
replace the deposed Bill Russell at midseason, the 40-year-old
Hoffman was being similarly pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got someone who would toe the party line in Hoffman,
and Hoffman got a ticket out of the minor leagues. He has been
offered a position on the new coaching staff, which is not a bad
place for someone who came to the majors with only two years of
managerial experience at the Triple-A level.
</P>
<P>
   So pity not Hoffman. Save your sympathy for his successor.
Regardless of who it is _ Montreal's Alou, former Boston and Texas
skipper Kennedy or ex-Orioles/Reds manager Johnson _ the task
facing him will be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers that Hoffman babysat were last in the league in
on-base percentage and finished well out of the top 10 in fielding
percentage, hitting, runs scored, slugging percentage, total bases
and walks.
</P>
<P>
   If you're general manager Kevin Malone, your first impulse is to
call the studios and see if the Cincinnati suburb of Washington
Court House can be re-created on a soundstage somewhere, the better
to make closer Jeff Shaw and his family feel at home in SoCal.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five of Shaw's 48 saves this season came after he was
traded to the Dodgers from the Reds. Because he had a multiyear
contract, Shaw can demand a trade. He isn't enamored of L.A., but
the Dodgers desperately need him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The simple act of keeping the Dodgers' core players will cost
roughly $75 million, which surpasses by $5 million the payroll of
Baltimore, the winner this year of the bulging bankroll and not
much else. And even at that, the Dodgers won't have a leader in the
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla? Puhleeze. He could have been a stabilizing
influence in the roiling seas but instead was the first to cast
about for excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield? Agreeing to move to left field would be a start.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi? A leader trapped in the body of a party animal.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, players have come and gone for a decade now
and the Dodgers haven't done diddly. Enough already with the
improvisational players. Malone's mandate is to assemble a
collaborative cast that's in it for the long haul and the curtain
calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
