<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BATTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTOM OF ORDER DELIVERS ONCE MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In taking a 2-0 lead in their division series with
the Texas Rangers, the New York Yankees seem to be using two
different batting orders: their top six are hitting only .125 (5
for 40) while the bottom three, notably Scott Brosius and the
rookie Shane Spencer, have a .529 average (9 for 17) with two
homers, all five runs batted in and all six runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a short series,'' said Chris Chambliss, the Yankees'
batting coach, ``you don't know who the heroes are going to be.
Sometimes the opposing pitcher is concentrating on the top of the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Yankees, that can be a dangerous mistake. Brosius,
whose two-run homer provided the margin in Wednesday night's 3-1
victory over the Rangers, has two singles as well as his homer in
six at-bats. He batted eighth on Wednesday night, after batting
ninth in Tuesday's opener when he had a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   In Spencer's post-season debut on Wednesday night as the No. 7
hitter, the rookie left fielder had a homer in his first at-bat and
a single, and scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of two pitches,'' Brosius said, alluding
to the homers he and Spencer hit off Rick Helling, a 20-game
winner. ``We know we have a balanced lineup. Sometimes it's the top
of the order, sometimes the middle, sometimes the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the Yankee batters worked deep into the count
against Helling, especially in the early innings, Spencer's single
and Brosius's homer in the fourth inning occurred back to back on
Helling's first pitch to each batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries to get Strike 1 on you,'' Brosius said. ``He's going
to throw a lot of fastballs. Sometimes that first pitch is the best
one you'll get.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the first four innings, the Yankee batters' patience forced
Helling to throw 91 pitches, including 33 in the second inning. In
those four innings, the Yankee batters fouled off 28 pitches.
Before Derek Jeter struck out in the third, he fouled off 8 of 12
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helling's got a good fastball and when he gets it up in the
zone, you get a lot of foul balls,'' Chambliss said.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, whose .374 average with runners in scoring position led
the American League, has now driven in 101 runs, including 98
during the regular season. ``Scott shortens his stride and puts the
bat on the ball,'' Chambliss said. ``He's the big reason there's no
rest through the bottom of the order.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, who doubled in each game, admired Spencer's
production. ``It's fun to see,'' he said. ``Especially somebody
who's paid his dues in the minor leagues. You need stories like
this in baseball. At this time of year, it doesn't matter how you
win or who does it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
