<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
 
Taylor plots waiver strategy &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The Kings and the NHL's 26 other teams will submit
lists to the league today of the 18 skaters and two goalies they
plan to protect in Monday's waiver draft.
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor said Wednesday night he'd just
about settled on his protected list, which he would not reveal. The
league will release the lists Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we weren't vulnerable,'' Taylor said. ``This year,
we're vulnerable. We'll have five or six players exposed. It just
means we're getting a little older and have a little more depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, player movement in the waiver draft has been
minimal. Last year, the Kings neither lost nor added players in the
waiver draft. The Kings will choose 17th Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the most difficult decision he faced in compiling
the list was whether or not to protect rookie defenseman Mark
Visheau, who has been a pleasant surprise in training camp but is
sidelined indefinitely with a dislocated left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   __ Talking but no action: The update is that there is no update
on unsigned defenseman Aki Berg, who is playing in Finland while
his agent and Taylor try to work out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he spoke Tuesday to agent Larry Kelly, who is
vacationing in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of progress to report, other than that both
sides reiterated their positions,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly earlier had said there was a clause in Berg's contract in
Finland that would prevent him from signing with the Kings after
Sept. 30, but Taylor said Kelly made no mention of the clause
during their conversation and negotiations will proceed up until
the start of the NHL season on Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   If Berg is not signed by then, he won't be because once the
regular season starts, he would have to clear waivers before
rejoining the Kings, and it is almost a certainty that he would be
claimed by another team.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have been granted an exclusion for Berg in the waiver
draft, meaning they don't have to protect him. However, if he signs
after the draft but before the season starts, the Kings would have
to waive one of the 18 skaters they plan to protect in the waiver
draft.
</P>
<P>
   __ Exhibition game: The Kings held a 3-2 lead Wednesday night
with 10 minutes remaining in their exhibition game against the
holdout-depleted Sharks at the San Jose Arena. Rookie Josh Green
had one goal and Glen Murray the other two for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Matteau and Bob Rouse had scored San Jose's goals in
the third period. Kings goalie Jamie Storr, in his first exhibition
appearance, had faced only eight shots in the game's first two
periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
