<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' BATS FALL SILENT FOR HELLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only a few folks outside of Texas and his hometown of
Fargo, N.D., could have matched Rick Helling's round face with his
feat this season. The Rangers' uncelebrated 20-game winner did not
have to be as dominant as Toronto's Roger Clemens or as fine as
Atlanta's Tom Glavine or even as dramatic as the Yankees' David
Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Helling joined the 20-victory club despite his 4.41 earned run
average for a reason: He always had the Rangers' offense there as a
safety net when his stuff went slightly awry. But as Todd
Stottlemyre discovered in Game 1 of the division series against the
Yankees, and as Helling found out in Game 2 on Wednesday night, a
fine performance is not enough when the glamorous bats of the
Rangers fail to hold up their end of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   What was true in the Yankees' 2-0 shutout of the Rangers in Game
1 on Tuesday night was also evident in the 3-1 loss Texas took in
Game 2. The Rangers' celebrity lineup _ including Juan Gonzalez,
Will Clark and Ivan Rodriguez _ has been put under hypnosis by the
Yankees' pitching staff, first David Wells and on Wednesday night
Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone would have said to me, this staff would give up
five runs in two games to the Yankees and still not have a win, I
would have said they were crazy,'' said Helling, who gave up three
runs, eight hits and struck out nine in six innings. ``I felt that,
like Todd, I pitched good enough to win on a normal night.''
</P>
<P>
   On a normal night, Gonzalez, Rodriguez and Clark would not go a
combined 1 for 11. In Games 1 and 2, that threesome has hit just 3
for 23. The Rangers' silence on offense has let the pitching staff
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've swung the bats very well,'' Manager Johnny
Oates said. ``We've got our backs to the wall. This year, we have
hit better in our own park. Hopefully we can get our bats going
against David Cone, but that's no walk in the park, either.'' Cone
will start for the Yankees against the Rangers' Aaron Sele on
Friday night at the Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Helling was not exactly going for a stroll around Yankee
Stadium. He worked and worked hard against the imposing Yankees
standing before him. They found a sweet spot on just enough of
Helling's pitches early on. This has been the rap on Helling: get
him before he settles in. After the seventh inning, he allowed
opposing batters to hit just .200 during the regular season. So the
Yankees seized their opportunity, starting in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Although Derek Jeter was one of many to foul off repeated
fastballs by Helling _ a fact that sent his pitch count to 91
before the fourth inning was over _ it was the bottom of the order
that hurt the Rangers' starter the most.
</P>
<P>
   It was the home run-happy Shane Spencer, who unleashed a homer
in the second inning to give the Yankees a 1-0 lead. In the fourth,
Spencer led off with a single and scored when the Yankees' No. 8
batter, Scott Brosius, hit a home run. Helling eventually found a
groove and set down six out of seven batters in the fifth and sixth
innings before leaving the game, but his pitch count was at 119,
and it was time to give way to a good relief effort from Tim
Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing strikes and staying aggressive,'' Helling said.
``I was ready for them. I didn't let the crowd get to me.''
</P>
<P>
   This was his first playoff experience at Yankee Stadium, an
unreal moment for a kid who grew up in the hometown of Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   This was also his chance to stand in the national spotlight and
let everyone know that he was one of just four pitchers to hit the
20-victory magic number this year. Helling did his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made two mistakes, and they hit two home runs,'' Helling
said. ``I'm not sure that Pettitte made any mistakes. I was out
there, still being aggressive, wanting to keep us in it until we
scored some runs. Usually, that's not something we've had to worry
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the end, with one out and a runner in scoring position,
the offense dissolved beneath the Yankee Stadium lights. Gonzalez
bounced out to third, and Clark struck out to end the game. This is
not what many, including the pitching staff, had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried,'' said Gonzalez, who came up with his first and only
hit of the series in the fifth, when he kicked loose a tag at
second for a double. ``I'm only human. I'm trying hard for my team.
It's hard. Our pitching's been good. It's just their pitching has
been impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling did not achieve 20 victories with the Rangers' failing
him at the plate. Before the season began, no one would have placed
Helling in the middle of the mayhem at Yankee Stadium last night.
He was a stubborn pitcher in love with the high fastball. For
several years he bounced up and down, from the minors to majors. As
he entered spring training, he was slated as the Rangers' No. 6
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be the first to tell you that if someone had told me I'd
be 20-7 at the end of the year, I'd have said they were crazy,''
Helling said. ``It just goes to show you that the team I play on
scores a lot of runs and the defense has played well behind me all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Those runs were not there for him last night. Stottlemyre could
sympathize. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
