<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. AND THE NFL: THE CIRCUS GOES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Later this month, just before Halloween, the groups interested
in acquiring the 32nd franchise in the National Football League
will be allowed to genuflect in front of the other 31 owners and
kiss the ring of commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   The media will not be allowed into the inner sanctum, but it
will have a good view if any smoke rises from Tagliabue's portable
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is no process in sports more twisted than the
NFL's fleecing of cities and millionaires. Cleveland, which once
had a franchise it dearly loved, was informed last month that the
cost of a new one would be $530 million.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, this was received as good news by Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is no less perverse. The New Coliseum project and
Michael Ovitz's Carson proposal, along with a group from another
disenfranchised city, Houston, will put on a show at the league
meetings in Kansas City in hopes that Tagliabue puts the winning
wafer in their mouth.
</P>
<P>
   This is pressure, unlike what you usually see in sports. A final
decision on Team 32 is likely a year away, but any group getting
sacked this October is looking at fourth and several years to go.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone responds to this pressure differently.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz group rolled out Shaquille O'Neal this week as a new
frontman. It certainly doesn't hurt having the Lakers' star on your
side, but frankly he doesn't help. Unless he commits to playing
tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the Ovitz group has been longer on style than details.
It says it has the money to back a package that might hit $1
billion in costs from building the stadium to franchise fee to
buying the land. But no one has seen anything in the form of game
plans or even a formal press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Carson has been told what it will cost to do
business with Ovitz and the NFL: $100 million, in the form of bond
sales. But it hasn't seen any bottom line financial details,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the bonds underwritten will not be a problem, says
Carson city councilman Daryl Sweeney. Bank of America, which has
extended Ovitz a line of credit large enough to buy the Ukraine, is
working with Carson and its consultants on this end. Sweeney also
said the NFL has bought off on any of the environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be until Oct. 20 before Carson's council gets a
chance to approve anything related to the bid, and the NFL meetings
begin Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received bits and pieces of information,'' said mayor
Peter Fajardo. ``What we haven't seen is what our revenue streams
will be, and what Ovitz and the NFL expects of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed, but we have to have something to show the
public that explains how we'll cover the debt service and how the
city will profit. We have concerns about parking, and what we can
tax, and what administrative costs there will be (police,
traffic).''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond giving Carson a clue, Ovitz needs to know the NFL has
little regard for gaps in proposals. When Carolina owner Jerry
Richardson, who runs the NFL's franchise committee, was in town
this summer, he said Houston was 95 percent of the way to having a
complete proposal in hand.
</P>
<P>
   That meant Houston had an answer and commitment for every
question. If Ovitz goes to K.C. without a land agreement in hand or
without Carson as a signed-and-sealed teammate, he could be asked
to run a down-and-out pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The New Coliseum project, spearheaded by Kings' owner Ed Roski,
has also been busy lately. Within the last month, it had to hire a
new architect (L.A.-based NBBJ, the architect for the new Staples
Center) to put together a new blueprint and model. Why? Because the
NFL had informed Coliseum backers that the existing model was too
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   It basically was the same model the league had seen for several
years, dating back to proposed Coliseum renovation for the Raiders.
It had too much baggage. The New Coliseum didn't need another hint.
A public unveiling of the newer Coliseum is expected before
everyone heads for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The New Coliseum group has also firmed up its financial package
with Merrill Lynch, has detailed all of its financial advantages in
relation to already-completed infrastructure around the Coliseum,
and rerouted redevelopment money as a way to fulfill the league's
requirement for public investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Coliseum will be more private than ever before,'' said
John Semcken, the groups' executive vice-president. ``But the
investment by the public is already in place, through the things
we've already done as far as parking and traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, of course, could care less that the New Coliseum can
bring its stadium in cheaper than Ovitz. It's trite but true: Show
Me the Money is the motto of all NFL owners.
</P>
<P>
   Semcken believes the New Coliseum offers the NFL one other
attractive thing: Franchise flexibility. Should Houston get Team
32, the New Coliseum project is willing to adapt its game plan and
offer itself as the new home to an existing NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners in Denver, Chicago, New England, Buffalo and Arizona
have expressed the need or desire for new stadiums. Voters in
Denver will go to the polls in November on a stadium referendum
issue. If Bob Kraft or Bill Bidwill can't get what they want from
Boston or Phoenix, the New Coliseum is willing to step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like a new team,'' said Semcken. ``But if someone cares
to relocate, Ed and the group would be willing to step back as a
minority owner, or as a local owner for someone else. We'd go that
way for any team.''
</P>
<P>
   Except one. The Raiders. Too much bad history, too much bad
blood, and too much litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have a suit pending against the league regarding its
territorial rights to Los Angeles. Legal types say Al Davis doesn't
have a case, but that doesn't mean the league wants to rush a team
into L.A. before the case is tossed. Only one man may believe he
owns the rights to L.A., but if that man happens to be Davis, the
league will tread lightly.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the bottom line. The league's in no rush to name No.
32, but pity the poor bidder who isn't ready for the October
summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
