<HEADLINE>
J.R. DOESN'T WORRY ABOUT HEISMAN SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Trophies have never been important to J.R.
Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing football at the age of 8 and it's always
been for pure fun,'' said Redmond. ``It was never for a big trophy
to put on my table at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, a junior at Arizona State, is now playing college
football. And there's no bigger trophy in college football than the
Heisman Trophy. Redmond knows exactly what it represents the best
player in college football, a free trip to New York City and the
opportunity to strike the pose.
</P>
<P>
   And, care about it or not, Redmond, who entered the season with
designs on playing full-time tailback and kick returner and
part-time defensive back, was a member of the relatively short
Heisman candidate list. Could he find a spot on his table now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Means nothing to me,'' Redmond insists. ``I never really think
about it until somebody brings it up. I went to a party (recently)
and all this one kid wanted to talk about was the Heisman. He kept
following me around talking about the Heisman. I had to make
something up to tell him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Redmond, a 1995 Carson High graduate, showed up at Arizona
State he carried a load of talent and plenty versatility. But he
didn't bring with him a preferred position.
</P>
<P>
   The sturdy 6-foot, 215-pounder with a time of 4.41 in the
40-yard dash was a tailback with the hands to play receiver. He
had, in fact, played both in high school while piling up 2,469
yards, 23 touchdowns and a 1993 L.A. City 4-A championship.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, he was a safety with the coverage skills of a
cornerback with experience at both. And he could break a game open
at any time on a kickoff or punt return.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put J.R. out there anywhere,'' Arizona State receiver
Lenzie Jackson said. ``You put him at running back, cornerback,
safety or receiver, he's going to go out there and make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State coach Bruce Snyder remembers the precise moment
Redmond became a tailback. It was about the time Redmond first
grabbed the football in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell a runner pretty fast and it was after one run I
said `He is going to stay there for awhile','' Snyder said. ``There
was some staff room bartering and negotiating going on about where
he should be. I said we were going to look at him at tailback and
it never changed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, with 2,431 all-purpose yards, 12 touchdowns and
only one start on his collegiate resume, Redmond, who added 10
pounds during the summer in the weight room and at the dinner
table, took the lead for a team expected to challenge for a Pac-10
title and possibly play at its home stadium in the Jan. 4 national
championship Fiesta Bowl game .
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a better (offensive) player in the conference than
J.R. Redmond,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   There are, as it turns out, better teams than the Sun Devils.
Arizona State opened the season with a heartbreaking, 42-38, loss
to visiting Washington and followed with an uninspired 26-6 setback
at BYU. Suddenly, the lofty dreams had turned into an 0-2
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a bit of a struggle,'' Snyder said. ``After the
BYU loss, which I hope is the low point for the season, we decided
as a staff to go back as it were training camp, rebuild the team,
and get them focused in on every game we were to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, who had been sensational against Washington (254
all-purpose yards) and shut down against BYU (62 yards all-purpose
yards), accepted the new approach as did his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living week by week for the games and day by day at
practice,'' said Redmond, whose only defensive duty thus far has
been two snaps against Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   The past two weeks haven't been perfect but they have been more
pleasant. The Sun Devils beat North Texas, 34-15, and knocked off
Oregon State, 24-3. Redmond had 201 yards on 19 touches against
North Texas and played through the pain of an injured toe to gain
168 all-purpose yards in the victory over the Beavers.
</P>
<P>
   The next weekly assignment comes on Saturday in the L.A.
Coliseum against Hackett's USC team and Redmond, being the
versatile guy he is, had to take on the role of ticket broker. He's
had to beg, borrow and purchase tickets for more than 30 family
members and friends so they can see him fulfill a lifetime dream of
playing in the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I would daydream about playing for the
Raiders in the Coliseum,'' said Redmond, who regularly has about 15
family members travel to Tempe for Sun Devil home games.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, who appears headed to the NFL when he chooses,
considered attending USC or UCLA. But he said the Bruins dropped
out of the running after he didn't obtain a qualifying score on the
SAT and USC stopped pursuing him after Redmond broke his clavicle
as a senior at Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona State is the only school which stuck with me,'' said
Redmond, who spent a semester at Long Beach City College before
reaching a qualifying score on the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Sun Devils are trying to get back on track and Snyder
doesn't mind riding his star tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a real special player and really a neat young
person,'' Snyder said. ``In a lot of ways, he exemplifies what we
want from work habits and carrying yourself as a person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
