<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON'S TALKS WITH TOBACCO QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 MICHAEL MURPHY AND CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorney General Grant Woods has asked the Justice Department to
investigate whether former Gov. Fife Symington got tobacco
companies to create a public relations fund in exchange for
opposing Arizona's $500 million tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Woods referred the question to U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
on Sept. 16, after he uncovered a gubernatorial aide's handwritten
notes from a 1996 meeting between Symington, his top aides and a
key tobacco attorney. The meeting occurred less than three weeks
after Woods sued the nation's top cigarettemakers, seeking
reimbursement of health care costs from smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Symington on Wednesday denied that any fund was established, or
that he sought any benefit from Big Tobacco in exchange for trying
to kill the lawsuit. He said his position was based on principle.
</P>
<P>
   The notes of the meeting suggest that Symington sought a written
commitment by the tobacco companies to provide him with a ``public
relations fund'' to help him battle any negative public opinion for
his opposition to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The notes also suggest that William Maledon, a Philip Morris
attorney who attended the Sept. 9, 1996, meeting, drafted a
Symington letter of Oct. 15, 1996, that ordered Woods to drop the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said Wednesday that the documents point to a possible
violation of the Hobbs Act, a federal law that prohibits
officeholders from receiving a benefit for the public actions they
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty clear what the facts are pertaining to the
meeting, but what happened prior or subsequent to that meeting, we
don't know,'' Woods said. ``We do know that Symington took the
action that was the subject of the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington lashed out at Woods, calling his actions a
``disgusting'' effort to criminalize his ``principled position''
against Arizona's tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just ridiculous,'' Symington said of the referral. ``I
would expect no less from Grant. I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington said he encouraged the tobacco companies to ``make a
public stand'' against state tobacco lawsuits. But he said they
never established a public relations fund on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that my position was going to be kind of an unpopular
position . . . a voice in the wilderness,'' Symington said. ``I
knew I was going to get beaten up, but I also felt it would be
great if the tobacco companies would stand and fight and launch
their own public counteroffensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with encouraging an industry to defend
itself when it's under attack for the wrong reasons,'' the former
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   While ``that obviously costs money,'' Symington added, that,
``as I remember, they really didn't do anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' office conducted a preliminary investigation of the
matter, interviewing Nancy Baehre, then Symington's assistant
legislative director, about the notes she took of the 1996 meeting
between Symington, his top aides and Maledon.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he decided to refer the matter because the Justice
Department already is pursuing similar allegations against the
tobacco industry from other states. He also feared a potential
conflict because Maledon is a key player in the tobacco industry's
counteroffensive against Arizona's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell said Arizona's
information will be turned over to the department's tobacco task
force, which is looking into whether the industry committed fraud,
perjury or other wrongdoing. The task force began its work after
tobacco executives swore to both the Food and Drug Administration
and Congress that nicotine was not addictive.
</P>
<P>
   Symington ordered Woods to drop the lawsuit, based on the
possibility that taxpayer money could be lost. At the time,
Symington said his decision had nothing to do with the tobacco
industry's opposition.
</P>
<P>
   While the Arizona Health Care Cost Containment System withdrew
from the state's lawsuit, Woods defied Symington and continued the
litigation. After Symington left office last year upon his
conviction on multiple felony bank- and wire-fraud counts, Gov.
Jane Hull ordered that AHCCCS be reinstated to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Woods uncovered the 1996 notes during discovery in the lawsuit,
which is scheduled to go to trial March 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In the notes, Baehre wrote that Symington asked Maledon about a
``public relations fund.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to do?'' about it, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Maledon answered that he will ``support Gov,'' she wrote, and
added, ``Gov wants to know in writing what they will do.''
</P>
<P>
   The next section of her notes reveals that Maledon was to draft
the letter ordering Woods to drop the lawsuit: ``Gov. _ take
highroad letter to A.G. outlining reasons for AHCCCS to be taken
off lawsuit _ Maledon to draft letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Baehre, through a governor's office spokeswoman, declined to
comment Wednesday, citing her involvement in a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   In a deposition, Baehre said she remembers little of the
meeting, but confirmed that the notes were hers.
</P>
<P>
   Maledon said he did not set up a public relations fund and has
never heard of such a fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never contributed anything to anything and I do not
know what that (Baehre's notation) refers to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maledon also said he did not draft Symington's letter to Woods,
and said no other tobacco attorney ``to his knowledge'' wrote it.
</P>
<P>
   But Symington's letter informing Woods that AHCCCS would be
dropped from the lawsuit closely follows a 12-page memo faxed
months earlier from Maledon's law office to the Governor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The memo offers arguments that Woods' suit is baseless, illegal,
and bad public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Symington argued in his letter that 66 percent of any settlement
would have to be paid to the federal government. John Kelly, then
the acting director of AHCCCS, made a similar point in a letter to
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Maledon's memo states that ``approximately 66 percent of any
monetary recovery . . . would go to the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, Symington argued that the tobacco
litigation would open up claims against ``beef growers, liquor
distillers, wineries, dairy farmers . . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The Maledon memo cites dangers to ``the beef industry, the oil
and gas industry, and alcoholic beverage manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Heiler, Symington's former chief of staff, said Wednesday
that there was no deal in which Big Tobacco would provide
advertising support to help Symington deal with public outcry over
his decision to nix the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he was going to take a pounding for it, which, of
course, he got. I think he was asking, `What are you all going to
be doing about standing up for your position?' '' Heiler, who
attended the 1996 meeting, recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fife Symington were a man looking for cover, he simply
never would have made the decision he made in the first place. The
easier cover was to not do what he did. He did what he did out of
the philosophical belief it was the right thing to do,'' Heiler
added.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Heiler said, asking Woods to withdraw from the
lawsuit was a mistake. He alleged that Maledon made a false
statement in the meeting when he reassured Symington that the
tobacco companies would not settle the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona evidence may bolster contentions that Big Tobacco
provided advertising protection for key senators in exchange for
their votes against U.S. Sen. John McCain's legislation to enforce
a national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials are probing those allegations after a July
referral from Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks to me like another quid pro quo just like the one
the tobacco industry offered up to kill the McCain bill,'' said
William Novelli, president of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids.
``This is pretty egregious if proved.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-tobacco group filed a complaint on June 29 with the
Federal Elections Commission alleging that the nation's tobacco
companies provided illegal campaign contributions, in the form of
millions of dollars in supportive television ads in their states,
to senators who opposed the tobacco-settlement bill.
</P>
<P>
   These ads, the group argued, were not legal ``issues'' ads but
illegal corporate-campaign contributions designed to provide cover
for favorably disposed senators.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle then took the information developed by the campaign and
referred it to Reno, alleging further violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies' actions reveal the desperate lengths to
which they were willing to go in order to kill teen smoking
legislation,'' Daschle said in a July 2 letter to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, Reno wrote back that the Justice Department's
criminal division is examining the case, and said, ``The allegation
that tobacco companies may have promised favorable political
advertising in exchange for a senator's vote on specific
legislation raises separate concerns under the bribery and gratuity
statutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Parriott, regional advocacy manager for the American Cancer
Society, said she wasn't surprised by the interest Big Tobacco
showed in the Arizona lawsuit. Tobacco has had a tight hold on
Arizona policymakers for years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a defendant in a lawsuit and getting to write your own
dismissal _ it's awfully sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known the tobacco industry has claimed these suits were
without merit. It now comes out that they were so desperate and
frightened by this suit that they felt the need to go to a totally
different branch of government to get it dismissed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
