</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-AZR </SLUG>
  
t AID TARGETS SOFTWARE SELLERS  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDI VILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, Microsoft officials received complaints about some
of its computer software being substandard.
</P>
<P>
   Then they found out that hundreds of units of its software and
end user license agreements were pirated and distributed
nationwide, and possibly worldwide, out of a Valley home-based
business.
</P>
<P>
   Now authorities think they've identified two key culprits _ a
Chandler woman, who happens to be a neighborhood Block Watch
captain, and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities raided Microzon Inc. on Wednesday and accused the
company of manufacturing and distributing counterfeit Microsoft
Windows 95 and Office 97 Professional software for at least the
past 14 months, selling them for ``pennies on the dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The labels looked identical to the ones that come with
legitimate Microsoft products,'' said Chandler police Sgt. Ken
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they suspect Aaron Duhon, 27, the president and
co-owner of the company, and his wife, Jennifer, the other owner,
also installed fake Windows 95 software into computers that they
then sold cheaply to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Duhons, whose home serves as their business headquarters,
are under investigation, although neither was arrested Wednesday,
Phillips said. Jennifer Duhon, 26, the company's vice president, is
a Block Watch captain in the couple's neighborhood in the 1200
block of West Boston Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know till this morning that they were actually
producing this,'' Phillips said. ``It was a little bit of a
surprise to us. We thought they were getting the product from Japan
or China or Los Angeles. Usually, they'll get the product from
somewhere else and set up these homes as the middleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Microzon caught the attention of authorities in July 1997 when a
customer sent 10 units of Windows 95 to Microsoft Corp., along with
a note inquiring if the products were counterfeit, according to a
police search warrant affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The product, which was bought for $69 a piece, was analyzed by
Microsoft and found to be fake.
</P>
<P>
   In August, another customer told Microsoft he purchased 600 End
User License Agreements from Microzon and suspected they were
counterfeit. He also bought 21 copies of Microsoft Office 97
Professional from the company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft analyzed the software and six copies of the
agreements, plus four ordered by its own investigator in September,
and determined that all were fake.
</P>
<P>
   Microzon was founded in 1990 as Computer Solutions, then changed
its name to Microzon Computer Co. in 1995. In February 1996, the
company incorporated in Arizona and changed its name again to
Microzon Inc. Its Web site bills the company as ``your premier
source for quality computer components on the Web'' and boasts that
the business sells ``top quality computer products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you had a license to do this,'' Jennifer Duhon
reportedly said to her husband when police arrived Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Duhons referred all questions to their attorney, Marc
Victor, who could not be reached for comment Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Piracy and counterfeiting have become rampant in the software
industry, costing $11.2 billion in lost revenue last year alone,
according to the Business Software Alliance. Worldwide, more than
40 percent of all software in use is illegally copied. This
translates into fewer jobs, less innovation and higher costs to
consumers, the alliance says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is apparent that counterfeiters now understand that the
value of software is in the license,'' Microsoft attorney Anne
Murphy said in a press release. ``We applaud the efforts of Arizona
and specifically the Chandler Police Department for protecting
intellectual property and ensuring a level playing field for honest
resellers.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said it's too early for police to determine the extent
of Microzon's business. Detectives also seized a bank account,
computer equipment and business records.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a man arrested last month in Troy, N.Y., for
selling 100 units of counterfeit Microsoft Office 97 Professional
software, implicated Microzon as his supplier. The man called
Microzon when he was confronted by police and was assured that the
software, bought at $22.50 each, was not pirated.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said that Microzon very likely bought floppy disks in
mass quantity, then copied the programs onto them, manufactured the
fake license agreements and sold the units en masse to other
distributors, who in turn passed them along to other consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Floppies for both software programs cost Microzon less than $1
to produce, Phillips said. Windows 95 has been replaced at local
computer stores by Windows 98, which sells for around $180. Office
97 Professional costs about $300 wholesale and nearly $600 retail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making almost 100 percent profit,'' Phillips said.
``The potential was limitless here.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Judi Villa can be reached at 444-7972 or at judi.villa &LR; pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
