A3469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-QUARTER     10-01 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-QUARTER-HORSES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS BRINGS AN ABLE STABLE OF HORSES TO LONE STAR PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ As stable hands hustled around Lone Star
Park's Barn 6 to finish chores, three white-faced horses were
traveling in circles outside while tethered to the walking wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The scene could have been from any barn. Those could have been
any horses. But they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   One was Falling In Loveagain, the top-earning quarter horse in
the country this year after her victory Labor Day in the
All-American Futurity. Next to her was Dashing Perfection, last
year's horse of the meeting at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie. The
third horse isn't as well-known. Four Six Dash hasn't lived up to
expectations, but he won the Retama Challenge Derby.
</P>
<P>
   All are trained by legendary Jack Brooks, whose stable looks
more powerful than ever for Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie's
second quarter-horse season. The Fall Meeting of Champions begins
at 6:35 p.m. Friday with 11 quarter-horse races each Wednesday,
Thursday, Friday and Saturday through Nov. 28 except for
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star's 33-day season features 24 stakes races, including
the Nov. 14 MBNA Challenge Championships, which have been compared
to thoroughbred racing's Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Brooks, who leads the nation in 1998
earnings, has a say in quite a few of the big events. Brooks'
runners have earned $2,022,424 this year, far ahead of runner-up
Rodney Reed's $845,024; even without the $1 million from the
All-American Futurity, he would be in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had good horses in the past, but I don't think I've ever
had as many big runners in one barn,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old native of Blanchard, Okla., started training
quarter horses in the 1950s, when the livestock company he was
working for closed his sheep department. Because he was unemployed,
he decided to try his luck at quarter horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a poor country boy, and everything has gone right
for me in this game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, that 40-year-long trend should continue this
fall. Brooks trains Dashin Is Easy, which has won three derbies
this year and is No. 1 in the latest American Quarter Horse
Association poll. Another of his stars is Heza Ramblin Man, also
among the top 10 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Dashing Perfection had a sensational four-race run last fall at
Lone Star but has only a dead-heat win in four starts. He won a
coin flip to qualify for the $300,000 MBNA America Challenge
Championship and probably will have a local race before that,
Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he could outrun a jet airplane last year,'' Brooks
said. ``But we had some problems with his feet, and he hasn't been
quite up to par this year. He seems to love Lone Star, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Dashing Is Easy, owned by Jim Pitts of Wichita Falls, is
expected to follow the same path Brooks took with Dashing
Perfection a year ago: the Dash For Cash Derby on Oct. 23 and Texas
Classic Derby on Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Heza Ramblin Man is stabled at Los Alamitos near Los Angeles and
is to be brought to Lone Star for the MBNA America Challenge
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The goals for Falling In Loveagain, Brooks said, are the Dash
For Cash Futurity on Oct. 24 and the Texas Classic Futurity on Nov.
28. The Dash For Cash Futurity and Texas Classic Derby and Futurity
are rated as Grade I stakes by the AQHA, as are the four major
Challenge Championship races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, everything looks good and you can't get any luck,''
Brooks said. ``But I was leading trainer at Ruidoso Downs \Rthis
summer\S, and it looks better now than it did then. I've got a
2-year-old that's probably going to be world champion, a 3-year-old
that's world champion, and an older horse that's got a shot at
being world champion. That's hard to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   It also defies belief that Falling In Loveagain gave Brooks his
seventh victory in Ruidoso Downs' All-American Futurity, a race
perhaps as tough to win as thoroughbred racing's Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream was to win one,'' he said. ``But the seventh was just
as exciting as any of them, maybe more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
