<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-FORECAST-SFCHRON &LR;      10-01 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-FORECAST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF WARNS OF SLOWING GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The International Monetary Fund predicted Wednesday
that world economic growth will be more than halved this year _
prompting a U.S. economic slowdown _ in a forecast filled with
unusually grim warnings that things might turn out much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing its ``World Economic Outlook'' at its annual meeting
now taking place in Washington, the IMF said world growth is
expected to drop from 4.1 percent last year to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The decrease in growth will cost the global economy $800 billion
in expected income, more than the annual output of the entire
Canadian economy.
</P>
<P>
   The decrease is concentrated in Asia and Russia, where severe
economic contractions have reduced millions of people to poverty
and now threaten to spread to South America.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF expects the U.S. economy to ``slow markedly'' but skirt
a recession as it absorbs spillover effects from the turmoil
abroad. The powerful U.S. expansion, now in its seventh year, has
generated the first federal budget surplus in three decades,
although a downturn could quickly reverse that progress.
</P>
<P>
   IMF chief economist Michael Mussa welcomed the Federal Reserve
Board's decision Tuesday to lower interest rates to help avert a
worldwide recession. However, the report warned that chances for
recovery next year have diminished, ``and the risks of a deeper,
wider and more prolonged downturn have escalated.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF said a global recession remains unlikely, but that
forecast rests on a series of uncertain assumptions:
</P>
<P>
   --Investor confidence will rebound in Asia's devastated
economies.
</P>
<P>
   --Japan will take ``decisive action'' to climb out of its worst
recession in 50 years and restore solvency to its banks, now
burdened with an estimated $1 trillion in bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   --Investor capital will return to Latin America and Central
Europe, avoiding new financial crises there.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and the United States will avoid recessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significantly worse outcome is clearly possible,'' the IMF
said, calling the world economy ``unusually fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   If global investors and banks continue to flee developing
countries, the IMF said, more financial crises could follow,
accompanied by disruptions in world trade, further stock market
plunges and deeper economic contractions.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is a 182-member nation agency designed to maintain the
global financial system. The IMF has assembled an unprecedented
$100 billion in emergency loans since last year for Thailand,
Indonesia, Korea and Russia. It stands ready to make heavy loans to
Brazil if conditions worsen there.
</P>
<P>
   Mussa said Russia's default in August sent shock waves through
all emerging markets, particularly in Latin America and Central
Europe, frightening investors who fled to a haven in U.S. Treasury
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, credit flows to emerging markets had begun to
recover from the initial stages of the Asian crisis, which broke
out in Thailand 14 months ago. U.S. and European stock markets were
even hitting all-time peaks, with the Dow Jones industrial average
topping 9,300 on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian devaluation ``triggered a kind of sea change in
world financial markets,'' Mussa said. Capital flows to developing
countries, which by July had recovered to $20 billion a month,
``fell to $2.5 billion, and since the middle of August they've
effectively been zero,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Mussa called such a reversal ``a millennial event,'' the kind of
thing that the odds say ``will happen once in a thousand years _
and it happened in the middle of August.''
</P>
<P>
   Net private capital flows to emerging markets peaked at a record
$215 billion in 1996; the IMF expects them to shrivel to just $57
billion this year, a drop of nearly 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As developing economies contract and their currencies devalue,
U.S. and European exports shrink and cheaper imports surge,
undermining corporate earnings and slowing the economy. U.S.
farmers have been especially hard hit by the drop-off in Asian
buying power.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF report said the strong U.S. economy has provided a vital
buffer to Asian economies by absorbing their exports. But the
result is a U.S. trade deficit that is expected to climb from $155
billion last year to $299 billion in 1999, a level the fund calls
unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
   If the crisis spreads to South America, which buys 20 percent of
U.S. exports, the U.S. economy will be hit even harder.
</P>
<P>
   There are bright spots, the report noted. South Korea and
Thailand have undertaken sweeping reforms to clean up their
debt-ridden corporations and banks. But they face a precarious
uphill climb unless Japan, the world's second-largest economy and
their biggest trading partner, recovers. The IMF said Japan ``bears
a particular responsibility to support recovery in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Mussa vehemently defended the IMF rescue packages for Asia,
which have come under fierce attack by critics who charge that the
fund blundered by forcing countries to raise interest rates at the
onset of their financial panics.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's goal was to prevent local currencies from collapsing.
If currencies had been allowed to go into free-fall, given the huge
short-term, dollar-denominated debts held by banks and businesses,
widespread bankruptcies, bank failures and even deeper economic
contractions could have resulted, the IMF maintains.
</P>
<P>
   But critics contend it was the interest rate increases that
plunged the economies into depressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those who argue that monetary policy should have been
eased rather than tightened in those economies are smoking
something that is not entirely legal,'' Mussa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impression seems to have developed that the fund staff has
nothing to recommend but tighter monetary and fiscal policies, the
tighter the better, everywhere, and always. This quite simply is
nonsense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 0337EDT &QL; 
