</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORM-FOSSILS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLION-YEAR-OLD WORM TRACKS FOUND IN INDIA, SCIENTISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team of fossil-hunting biologists say they have discovered
traces of worms that burrowed through the sands of an ancient
storm-tossed sea more than a billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If the scientists are right, their find could change the
scientific world's thinking about the earliest eons of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Until the startling and controversial claim was announced
Wednesday, virtually all scientists had held that the evolution of
life more complex than single-celled organisms really began during
the ``Cambrian Explosion.'' This occurred about 540 million years
ago, when a marvelously varied menagerie of creatures started
evolving to become the ancestors of us all _ from snakes and sharks
to puffins and people.
</P>
<P>
   During that explosive burst of evolution, animals began to
develop feet and fins, stomachs and lungs, hard shells for
protection and sharp teeth for predation _ all clearly preserved
today in the fossil record.
</P>
<P>
   But before that, all life, beginning nearly 4 billion years ago,
was merely single-celled and slimy: blue-green cyanobacteria,
protists, and the even more ancient archaea. None of them left
fossils to testify to their existence.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, comes a claim from Adolf Seilacher of Yale
University and Germany's University of Tubingen that draws a very
different picture:
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Wednesday and a report to be published Thursday in
the journal Science, Seilacher said he and his colleagues in
Germany and India have found ``trace fossils'' of long, sinuous
burrows that the worms dug in the wet sand of a shallow sea that
covered much of Central India more than a billion years ago _ twice
as long ago as the beginning of the Cambrian period.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the spineless creatures, Seilacher said, were too
soft to leave their own fossils. But their meandering wormy burrows
no thicker than a soda straw _ often branched and sometimes
suggesting that they could back away from dead ends _ show that
they must already have developed senses, nervous systems and
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists found the burrows in ancient sandstones along a
modern but poorly paved road that passes through the village of
Chorhat, about 10 miles south of the city of Allahabad in central
India, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The worms apparently lived beneath a thick mat of single-celled
organisms whose decaying bodies provided food while the mat itself
gave them oxygen, Seilacher said.
</P>
<P>
   And so the worms thrived with virtually no evolutionary change
for half a billion years before the Cambrian Explosion, Seilacher
said in a telephone interview from Germany, where he was attending
a conference.
</P>
<P>
   But how could evolution remain so stagnant during all that time?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there was no competition, no Darwinian fight for
survival,'' Seilacher replied. ``A billion years ago, the world was
a much more peaceful place because there were only the one-celled
organisms and the worms, and they were not eating each other. So in
such a peaceful world there was no need for creatures to develop
weapons to fight for survival, or hard armor to defend themselves.
And thus they left no fossils, and evolution could proceed very
slowly for millions of millions of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, however, several teams of molecular geneticists
developed what they called a genetic clock to calculate the
estimated rate of evolutionary change in animal life. They
concluded that multicelled animals might have arisen as long ago as
500 million years before the Cambrian Explosion, but they knew no
fossils existed.
</P>
<P>
   And still they remain unconvinced. At the University of
California at Davis, for example, evolutionary biologist Geerat J.
Vermeij was one of the clock-makers, and in an interview Wednesday
he said of Seilacher's claim:
</P>
<P>
   ``I would surely like to believe it, but it's all incredibly
early. It's quite consistent with theories, but it isn't
necessarily true, so I'm somewhat skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeij said he sees no problem with the idea that multicelled
animals evolved long before the Cambrian period, because they could
well have begun diversifying millions of years before the time when
skeletons and shells evolved to leave fossil evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But it would take more than a few eroded tracks that look like
the remains of burrows to convince him, Vermeij said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
