<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-CO     10-01 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Slow to change, but not a habitual offender
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Oct. 4, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man began the telephone conversation by giving his name,
which I failed to take note of. (Of which I failed to take note?
Hmm.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, he wanted to talk about my use in a column of the
indefinite article ``an'' before the word ``historic.'' He asked
why I used ``an.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught it somewhere along the line,'' I responded almost
sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where? What school? I want to know where you were taught
that!'' he demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a quiz?'' I asked my interrogator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am astonished that a journalist would use such horrible
English,'' he said. ``Goodbye!'' And he hung up.
</P>
<P>
   That was disturbing for several reasons. I don't like it when
people hang up on me. Second, was my usage of ``an'' really wrong?
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to understand about the English language is that
it is not like the Ten Commandments; there are no rules sent down
by a higher authority. Prescriptive rules of the English language
are based on usage. Dictionaries and language usage publications
are put together and constantly revised by juries of mortal men and
women. Often, the reference books and the jurors do not agree with
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously I am bothered about being scolded for writing ``an
historic'' instead of ``a historic,'' but is it such horrible
English as my caller contends? Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fowler's ``A Dictionary of Modern English Usage,''
I am not as guilty of using improper English as much as I am slow
to accept trends in our language.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler's, which is considered more British than American in its
orientation, says: ``A'' is used before all consonants except
silent ``h'' (a history, an hour); ``an'' was formerly usual before
an unaccented syllable beginning with ``h'' and is still often seen
and heard (an historian, an hotel, an hysterical scene, an
hereditary title, an habitual offender). But now that the ``h'' in
such words is pronounced, the distinction has become anomalous and
will no doubt disappear in time. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The book attaches no time limit. Therefore I must assume that no
matter how anomalous ``an historic'' might be, it is not yet
officially extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's English Grammar, an American effort, also leaves a gray
area. It gives the preferred use of ``a'' and ``an'' based on
consonants and vowels, but also leaves a caveat: ``There once was a
strict rule, still observed in England but generally disregarded in
the United States, to the effect that ``an'' should be used before
unaccented ``h,'' as ``an hotel'' and ``an historian.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally disregarded does not mean totally disregarded.
</P>
<P>
   American-produced Barron's ``Essentials of English'' also leaves
options open. ``In some instances,'' it says of the usage, ``when
there are different pronunciations of the same word, the
pronunciation used by the speaker or writer determines the form of
the article.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, I now shall cease to use anything but an ``a'' in
front of historic to avoid telephone calls such as the one I
received and to underscore the study programs of countless English
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   We all err in our language at times, but there is a question
about who (whom?) sets the official rules for linguistic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter on usage in the 1975 American Heritage Dictionary,
Morris Bishop _ professor emeritus of Romance languages at Cornell
University _ said of the distinguished 125-member usage panel
assembled by the American Heritage Publishing Co.: ``It is
significant that on specific questions, the usage panel disagreed
more than they agreed, revealing a fact often conveniently ignored
_ that among those best qualified to know, there is a very
considerable diversity of usage.''
</P>
<P>
   At times the most perfect English usage can be its most awkward.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a part of lore that when someone once challenged
Winston Churchill on the grammatical construction of one of his
sentences, he retorted: ``This is the sort of English up with which
I will not put.''
</P>
<P>
   A historic response, Winnie!
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
