<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX     10-01 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Contrast the bipartisanship of 1974
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disturbing partisanship of the House impeachment process so
far stands in dramatic contrast to Congress's sober management of
the impeachment inquiry into the Nixon presidency. The signs are
few that procedures even approximating bipartisanship are likely to
evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Political folk memory has been encouraged to misremember the
impeachment of Richard Nixon as the work of roughhouse Democrats
ganging up on the Republican president. The record is very
different.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the key decisions were made with overwhelming bipartisan
support, and even the few split votes drew substantial GOP support.
In the end, the decision for impeachment was unanimous on the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to create the Senate Watergate Committee was 77-0, and
the decision of the committee to subpoena Nixon's tape recordings
was unanimous, too. Ditto a House subcommittee finding a few weeks
later that the White House had misused the CIA in the Watergate
coverup.
</P>
<P>
   There were only four dissenting votes when the House gave its
Judiciary Committee power for a formal impeachment inquiry, and the
Senate's decision soon after to end its hearings was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee voted 33-3 to subpoena White House tapes,
and earlier in the week six GOP Senate leaders had warned Nixon
that if he didn't provide Watergate materials, he would be in
contempt of Congress and could be impeached on that charge alone.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief partisan split in Judiciary over whether to
accept White House transcripts of the tapes or to require the tapes
themselves, but within two weeks the committee was voting 37-1 to
subpoena additional tapes. Only four votes were cast against still
further subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   When push came to shove on the impeachment charges, Republicans
split, with 10 or more in opposition but, depending upon which
charge, six or seven concurring.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, the ``smoking gun'' tape was found, showing Nixon
had ordered the illegal coverup and subverted federal agencies for
it. All the Judiciary Republicans who had hung back announced they
would vote for impeachment. The committee's final report was
adopted by the House 412-3.
</P>
<P>
   This Congress's process opened with a hard partisan right to the
chops _ a straight party-line vote to violate grand-jury secrecy
and publicize the president's videotaped testimony. The following
flood of prosecutorial raw material compares poorly to the
carefully limited demands and screened releases of material by the
1974 committees.
</P>
<P>
   With crucial votes imminent on whether to conduct formal
impeachment hearings and if so how, Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde did make some procedural concessions to Democrats last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he was doing that, the politicizing of the process
was intensified by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott's declaration
that, forget the Constitution's criteria, ``bad behavior'' is
enough to warrant impeachment. ``Bad behavior,'' of course, is
whatever the opposition party says it is.
</P>
<P>
   An impeachment process should be advanced only by careful
bipartisan steps. This pony is off to a lurching and wobbly start.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
