<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV04-C     10-01 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: ACCESSING THE BIG PICTURE ON TV
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 4.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Now we add sight to sound,'' electronics pioneer
Robert Sarnoff said at the 1939 New York World's Fair as he
announced the advent of commercial television broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   TV sets can now be found in 99.7 percent of U.S. homes,
capturing over-the-air, cable and satellite signals. The images we
watch are sharper, usually in color and larger than they were six
decades ago. But basic transmission standards, which impose a limit
on overall quality, are the same as in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   That is about to change in November with the rollout of digital
television, or DTV. Were Sarnoff alive today, he might say: ``Now
we can look out the window and back at DTV sets without telling the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   DTV offers about five times more picture data than current sets
do. It also offers a wide-screen format and surround sound, as in
movie theaters. With DTV, you either get a breathtakingly clear
picture _ or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Industry tycoons are about to make multibillion-dollar bets that
DTV will catch on just like CD players and VCRs. The feds have
decreed that DTV must be available to every American household by
May 2002, and that the current-standard signals will be turned off
for good in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the public responds to the new big picture with a
big yawn? And what if people come down with a collective case of
sticker shock, thereby keeping set prices from coming down through
high-volume sales?
</P>
<P>
   Official Washington, you can be sure, will then get the message.
Deadlines will be allowed to slip, because politicians know that
you don't mess around with TV access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of the government is not to supply the business plan
for digital TV or to put artificial limits on the industry's
business plan,'' Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill
Kennard recently told a clutch of broadcasting honchos. ``The
transition to digital TV is inevitable, but the pace of the
transition will be set by the private sector,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for the best, 26 stations will begin to offer DTV next
month in Atlanta; Boston; Chicago; Dallas; Detroit; Los Angeles;
Manchester, N.H.; New York; Philadelphia; San Francisco, and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians will be watching: Manchester is a must stop for
virtually any White House hopeful. And Vice President Al Gore wants
the 2000 Democratic National Convention to be held in Philadelphia,
the city that inaugurated political telecasts in the summer of
1948.
</P>
<P>
   The next tier of DTV cities are also likely battlegrounds in the
next presidential race: Baltimore; Charlotte, N.C.; Cincinnati:
Cleveland: Denver: Hartford/New Haven, Conn.; Houston;
Indianapolis; Miami/Fort Lauderdale; Minneapolis/St. Paul;
Orlando/Daytona Beach; Phoenix; Pittsburgh; Portland, Ore.;
Raleigh/Durham, N.C.; Sacramento/Stockton; San Diego; Seattle; St.
Louis, and Tampa/St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   By the time TV stations in those cities go digital in November
1999, the main elements of the 2000 campaign should be coming into
DTV-like focus. Issues that Sarnoff could have hardly envisioned _
such as whether cable outlets should be made to carry DTV
broadcasts _ could well intrude into that contest.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
