<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPERLING02-COX     10-01 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPERLING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WASHINGTON INSTITUTION SERVES UP EGGS, MUFFINS AND NEWS
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    Cox photos to illustrate this story have been placed in the
National folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Set between the silverware and plates of eggs
benedict are tape recorders, which the diners dutifully punch into
action when the genial host, Godfrey ``Budge'' Sperling, announces
as always: ``The only ground rule here is that we're on the
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a national newsmaker will barely find time for a sip
of coffee while answering questions at a Sperling Breakfast _ a
Washington institution that celebrates its 3,000th session Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Cal Ripkin of breakfasts,'' observed Jim Perry, a
retired Wall Street Journal reporter, in a congratulatory note to
Sperling. The 83-year-old former Christian Science Monitor bureau
chief has presided over the gatherings since they began on Feb. 8,
1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first guest was Charles Percy, a Republican senator from
Illinois. He was a red-hot presidential prospect back then,''
recalled Sperling, who was nicknamed ``Budge'' in his boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I thought that would be the end of it,'' he said. ``I had
no idea we were going to do 3,000. I didn't come to Washington to
preside over breakfasts. This wasn't one of my ambitions in life,
but in many ways it's been one of the most fulfilling things I've
done in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is difficult to find a political figure of national
significance in the past three decades who has not sat down for
``breakfast with Budge.'' Presidents Ford, Carter, Reagan and Bush
all attended Sperling Breakfasts, and other guests have made major
news.
</P>
<P>
   It was at a Sperling Breakfast that House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., created ``cry baby'' headlines by complaining that President
Clinton had relegated him to the back of Air Force One on an
overseas flight.
</P>
<P>
   And it was here that Republican campaign strategist Ed Rollins
boasted that he had paid ``street money'' to African American
ministers to hold down the black vote when Christine Whitman was
elected governor of New Jersey in 1993. He later admitted that this
was a false boast intended to inflate his own importance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a Democratic presidential hopeful named Bill Clinton
brought his wife, Hillary, and both talked about having dealt with
difficulties in their marriage and having put those troubles behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a rehearsal for what they said later on '60
Minutes','' said Warren Rogers, a syndicated columnist and former
Washington bureau chief of Look magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast ``was set up originally to kind of size up these
public figures,'' said Sperling, describing how he began getting
together a politician and his journalistic colleagues from the
campaign trail. ``But it turned out to be a good place for news to
be generated.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the tense news conferences familiar to television
viewers, the breakfasts are marked by a relaxed tone of inquiry and
a dearth of attention beyond the Beltway. The reason is a rule
Sperling established at the beginning: no electronic media allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is all about civility,'' said Rogers, a regular
since the early 1970s. ``We don't have any TV cameras, so nobody is
trying to become a news media celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're full of good humor as a rule,'' said Sperling, who
always asks the first question and then calls on other reporters
who raise their hands like schoolchildren. ``I think guests are
more likely to be forthcoming when they're not being hammered on
the head. I think our questions are awfully good. We're just not
hostile about it. This is not adversary journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Washington press corps has changed dramatically since the
first Sperling guest was served up. Newspaper bureau chiefs and
columnists dominated the media then. Legendary journalists such as
Peter Lisagor of the Chicago Daily News and Washington Post
columnist Joseph Kraft were among the initial breakfast group.
(Actually, the first session was an off-the-record luncheon, but
the meal and rules were soon altered.)
</P>
<P>
   A changing capital has forced other adjustments as lines blurred
in a multimedia world. The faces of many regulars _ columnists and
commentators such as Bob Novak and David Broder _ are perhaps as
familiar to television viewers as to newspaper readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a group from the print media, although, as
time has gone on, some people in the group also do television,''
Sperling explained.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning promptly at 8 a.m., the symbiotic breakfasts bring
together political figures who want to be in the news and political
reporters who can put them there. It's ``lazy'' journalism,
conceded Rogers. ``Budge brings the guy to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past couple of decades, most of the breakfasts have been
served on china and crystal in the subdued splendor of private
dining rooms of the Sheraton Carlton Hotel, a few blocks from the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The tab per person has risen from about $1 to about $20 over
nearly 33 years. Although eggs and fried potatoes are always
available, recent decades have also found a buffet table with
fruit, bagels, juice and cereal for the cholesterol-conscious. The
number of journalists who attend usually ranges from 20 to 50,
depending on the prominence of the guest.
</P>
<P>
   Although the earliest breakfasts were attended only by men,
women have long had a place at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``My breakfast group has always mirrored the bureaus and what
was happening there,'' said Sperling. ``When the bureaus started
bringing in women, we started having them at breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories have always been the staple of the menu, of course, and
Sperling has a plateful to tell. Perhaps his most memorable
breakfast came in 1968 when the guest was Robert Kennedy, then a
Democratic senator from New York, and the nation was split over the
Vietnam War. Asked about his presidential aspirations, Kennedy at
first said it was ``inconceivable'' that he would enter the race.
But during the breakfast, news of the Tet offensive reached the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Before that breakfast was over, ``inconceivable'' had been
softened considerably, Sperling said, and the reporters left
convinced that Kennedy was running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as memorable but considerably less historic,
then-California Sen. S.I. Hayakawa asked for and ate a breakfast of
canned sardines on lettuce, Sperling recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The guest for the 3,000th gathering will be Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary Committee and a key player should
the House vote to impeach Clinton and set up a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Some former regulars who have since retired will attend. There
will likely be a few nostalgic words, but the event promises to be
more typical than climactic. Sperling is hardly ready to turn over
his coffee cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking each breakfast as it comes,'' he said, describing
how he rises at 5 a.m. on the two or three mornings a week that he
hosts breakfasts. He reads the morning papers and arrives at the
hotel early to check the room and menu. ``I have the energy for it
and I still enjoy doing it. I'm an early bird anyway, so I'll keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
