<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZHEIMERS02-COX     10-01 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas' First Lady to lead annual Memory Walk
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Before he began the rapid descent so common
among people suffering from Alzheimer's Disease, Laura Bush's
father would joke that he could see the dreaded disease coming,
although he wasn't sure what to call it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to say, 'I think I've got that old-timers
disease,''' said Bush, wife of Gov. George W. Bush. ``Everyone
fears it I because they know what a burden they will be to their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady's father, Midland developer Harold B. Welch, died
in 1995 after a two-year struggle with Alzheimer's. Watching her
mother shoulder the burden of caring for him took a toll on Bush,
one reason she has become involved with the local Alzheimer's
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of frustration with taking care of Alzheimer's
patients,'' Bush says. ``That's why it's so important for
caregivers to get support.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 50,000 people in the Austin area suffer from
Alzheimer's or care for someone who has the degenerative disease,
which attacks the brain and frequently causes memory loss,
disorientation and impaired behavior. Because of the aging of the
baby boom population, the association expects the number of
Alzheimer's patients locally to grow to more than 325,000 by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's patients often wander off or forget where they are,
have problems speaking and writing, and can need help with basic
activities such as bathing, dressing, eating and going to the
bathroom. The emotional and physical stress of caring for
Alzheimer's patients is difficult and damaging, and patients
frequently outlive their caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Alzheimer's progresses, it becomes impossible for one
family member to care for another family member,'' says Julie
Parker Johnson, executive director for Alzheimer's Association's
Greater Austin Chapter, which serves 11 counties in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration drives many caregivers to enlist the help of other
family members or to hand over care to nursing homes. Those who go
it alone can expect that care will cost more than $40,000 per year
and should seek out day care centers that can offer them a break
from having to give constant care, the association says.
</P>
<P>
   Welch, a World War II veteran who built houses and developed
subdivisions in Midland, was so ill by early 1995 that he did not
attend the governor's inauguration. Bush says her mother was lucky
to have the time and money to take care of him as his health
declined and ``50 years worth of friends in Midland'' to depend on
for help.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the Alzheimer's Association at
454-5476
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN02-COX     10-01 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   He sometimes goes by the name Shane Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   By Kirk Bohls
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The balance of this hotly contested National
League division series between Houston and San Diego _ two teams
that couldn't be any more evenly matched if they swapped dugouts
and very nearly did in that mega-12-player trade four years ago _
could rest on the squared-off shoulders of . . . uh . . . it'll
come to me . . . oh yeah, ol' whatzisname.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, Shane Reynolds will be referred to as savior if
he can somehow restore order to this best-of-five first round and
even the series at one win apiece. The bet here is he does. But
until then, the 30-year-old right-hander will largely be
remembered, so to speak, at least by casual fans, as the forgotten
man, even though he is widely respected inside the game. A case
could be made, in fact, that he is the best No. 2 pitcher in
baseball. That is, baseball west of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A quick quiz, however. How many playoff games has Reynolds won,
going back to his college days at tiny Faulkner University in
Alabama and the University of Texas? Answer: zero. How many has he
pitched in? One.
</P>
<P>
   He was a mediocre 12-10 in two years at Faulkner and, although
he was 7-0 in his lone season as a Longhorn, he had a 6.04 ERA and
was unceremoniously and deservingly left off Texas' College World
Series roster in 1989 even though the team was pitching-poor after
Kirk Dressendorfer and Brian Dare that season. This, after a fall
in which he was given Roger Clemens' No. 21 uniform. Of course,
Reynolds has always been chasing excessive expectations, whether
it's as the next Clemens or as the beneficiary of a three-year,
$10.5 million contract after 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clemens, Reynolds was a late bloomer who didn't mature
until after he left UT. Clemens never even made all-conference in
two Longhorns seasons. But Reynolds, with a cotton farmer's work
ethic, has since developed into one of the game's elite pitchers
and would now fit into an all-time UT starting rotation with
Clemens, Burt Hooton and Greg Swindell, if pro careers were
included.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has won 63 major-league games in just five full seasons
and, but for a knee injury that sidelined him for a month last
year, has steadily improved each season. Except for a final-game
start in which he had a no-decision despite a strong game against
the Cubs last Saturday, he would have joined Atlanta's Tom Glavine
as the only two 20-game winners in the National League and been one
of only five in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, few outsiders would place him in the company of Clemens,
Glavine or any of the other marquee pitchers, although Reynolds
undeniably should be on the list of the game's top 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most players who play in Houston don't get much credit,''
slugger Jeff Bagwell noted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly would apply to Reynolds, a control pitcher who
has a nasty, split-fingered pitch to go with an above-average
fastball and a curve and slider he now throws more often and
earlier in games to show hitters all his pitches. If he were
getting his due, certainly his name would be mentioned in the Cy
Young chase, a race that's been limited to San Diego's Trevor
Hoffman and Kevin Brown and Atlanta's Glavine and Greg Maddux. Even
teammate Randy Johnson received consideration, and he made only 11
NL starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other guys have more wins and lower ERAs,'' Astros Manager
Larry Dierker explained. ``But you could be the fifth or sixth-best
pitcher in the league and not get mentioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have forgotten that Reynolds has been Houston's opening day
pitcher the last two Aprils. He almost duplicated departed free
agent Darryl Kile's numbers from a year ago with an identical 19
wins and 233 innings, just 22 fewer than Kile's in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds does give up more hits than innings pitched but walks
few and gets as many ground balls as he does strikeouts. The
arrival of Johnson took much of the pressure off Reynolds and
helped him in another way because the Big Unit completed four of
his starts and kept the bullpen fresh for Reynolds, who finished
only three of his 35 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we had that leader-type ace guy that we
needed,'' Reynolds conceded. ``He's a classic ace.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a major surprise if Reynolds doesn't throw as well
today as he did in last year's playoff start against the Braves
(two runs in six innings) and an even bigger surprise if his
teammates fail to provide some of the offense that has been lacking
in the Astros' last four playoff games. Houston has eked out just
six runs over that span, including the three-game sweep by Atlanta
last season, but those four losses have come against Maddux,
Glavine, John Smoltz and Brown/Hoffman, pitchers who can claim
SEVEN Cy Youngs among them after this year.
</P>
<P>
   But look for Houston to score more against Andy Ashby, a strong
No. 2 pitcher himself but one with tendinitis in his hip and a poor
finish in which he won one of his last seven starts. In the event
it doesn't, Dierker is already making noises about coming back with
Johnson in game three on three days' rest, in which case No. 3
starter Mike Hampton adopts the role of forgotten man.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes sports commentary four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
