<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UT-WILLIAMS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offensive line making adjustment to UT power game
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky Williams is just ahead of schedule on his
quest to break Tony Dorsett's rushing record. And the University of
Texas' star tailback is already well beyond his rushing total at
this time last year, 736 to 519.
</P>
<P>
   What most people don't know is that the counter trey, which
historically had been Williams' most prolific play, has been
scrapped this season by a staff that is emphasizing power blocking
over finesse. And he's gaining all those yards running behind an
offensive line that has had an uneasy time this season making the
transition in blocking philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three years at UT, Williams was nearly unstoppable
running the counter trey, a finesse play that had a guard and a
tackle, together, pulling away from the line of scrimmage and
taking out a defensive lineman or a linebacker to give Williams a
massive, upfield block.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got a whole bunch of my yards on the counter trey, that and
the isolation play,'' Williams said. ''We talked about that before
the game. I know it's been really hard for the offensive linemen.
They played in one system for three years, and now they have to
learn another one. I know the tackles, especially, loved to pull.
For me, it's the best feeling in the world is coming around (the
line of scrimmage) with no one but the safety to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams still is beating safeties with his stiff-arm,
especially those who played Saturday for the Rice Owls. But he's
getting past the linemen and linebackers with a blocking scheme
that relies less on finesse and trickery.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't even know what finesse is,'' UT offensive line coach
Tim Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting more one-on-one individual blocks,'' right guard
Ben Adams said. ''Coach Nunez stresses the first two steps. . . .
You've also got to get a low pad level, to get under your man,
because whoever gets the lower body level leads.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Williams gained 318 yards, second-best single-game
total in UT history, mostly on off-tackle runs, sweeps and draws,
but with a sprinkling of misdirection. The offense also broke the
school record for total yards with 692. It's interesting that the
offense and Williams put up those numbers just a week after its
woeful performance against Kansas State. That's when Williams
gained only 43 yards and the team scored only seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the line said they got together before the Rice game
and had their own pre-game pep talk. The most vocal was center
Russell Gaskamp. However, the whole line, with three of its members
destined for the NFL next year, took the words to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came together before the game,'' Adams said. ''We decided
we had to play for ourselves. We couldn't play for Ricky or for the
fans or for our parents. We had to prove to people that we are the
ones who make things run in this offense.'' Jay Humphrey, a
three-year starter at right tackle, said he was stung by the
criticism that was generated by UT's performance in a 48-7 loss to
Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see how anybody could have said that the offensive
line has played badly,'' said Humphrey, who was listed in a mock
draft this week by CNN/Sports Illustrated as a late first-round NFL
pick. ''The offensive line didn't play horribly against Kansas
State, it was just one guy breaking down on any one play.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the Rice game, everybody talks about how well we played.
We went from the outhouse to the penthouse in a matter of a week.
It makes me go mad when people say we haven't been playing well. It
makes you want to go out and hit somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   What the line showed against Rice and what they didn't show
against Kansas State and at times UCLA and New Mexico State, was
that it had grasped the new power scheme employed by Nunez. In this
system, the offensive linemen worries most about overpowering the
defensive guy crouched directly in front of them rather than trying
to use technique to keep the defender off-balanced and off his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're getting better,'' Nunez said. ''I don't think we
were as good as we should have been against Kansas State. I thought
we were pretty good against Rice. When you don't win, you're pretty
hard on yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
