<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAGLER-CATS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henry Flagler Museum cats causing ruckus
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH _ The curator, the cat lady, the trapper and the good
lieutenant all agree on one thing: The insanity must be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how, they're not sure.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that a social crisis is nearing critical mass
here, and it involves wild cats.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the feral Pulitzers or Kennedys again. This time it's
the street felines at the Henry Flagler Museum.
</P>
<P>
   For three decades, a colony of cats has roamed the 8 acres
around the stately mansion, oblivious to the fact that the great
architect was a dog lover. They were given charming names _ Peanut
Butter, Champagne, Fluffy and Fluffy Jr., Zipper, Nutmeg, John
Wayne and Marmalade _ and led charming lives.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1995, John Blades took over as the museum's curator. He
wants the cats to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not belong here,'' he says. ``They have infested the
carpets with fleas. They have caused damage. They are a health and
safety nuisance.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, a security guard stepped on a cat and turned
his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a workers comp claim,'' Blades says. ``I'm hoping and
praying no visitor is injured or gets cat-scratch fever.''
</P>
<P>
   The new curator's position infuriates Catherine Bradley, known
throughout the island as the ``Cat Lady.'' Each day for the last 13
years, she has taken a wooden box full of food to the side gate at
the Flagler Museum to ensure that the cats have full bellies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know each of the cats at the museum,'' she says. ``I have a
photographic memory.''
</P>
<P>
   This comes in handy because Bradley admits to caring for 300 of
the island's feral cats, the names she has given them being too
numerous to recount here. In another life, Bradley used her
sophisticated, British bearing to strike real estate deals. She
sold John Lennon's mansion, among others. Now she runs her Palm
Beach Cat Rescue league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work 100 hours a week,'' she says. ``I'm weary. It's
laborious work. The cats are heavy. I don't need another battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what she got recently when Blades decided to
take bold action against his purring squatters. This brings us to
Robert Freeman, the trapper, owner of Grizzly's Wild Animal
Service. Blades hired him to trap the cats _ humanely, of course _
and remove them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love cats,'' Freeman says. ``I am an animal lover. When I'm
called in, there's already a problem. But that woman (Bradley) is
creating a monster. Someone will have to stop her. I'm just trying
to curb her form of insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Grizzly's has trapped five cats and taken them to shelters,
including the Palm Beach County Animal Care and Control Division.
Which is where Lt. Gina DiPace enforces the law _ or tries to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under our new ordinance, the person who is the feral cat
care-giver is responsible to see that they are all spayed,
tattooed, and gotten their microchip and their shots,'' DiPace
says.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``feral cat care-giver'' is new to the county's
lexicon. It was born in June when Bradley convinced Palm Beach
County commissioners that people should be allowed to look after
wild cat colonies, so long as the care-givers register with animal
control officers and follow their rules.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat unclear exactly what the rules are, however.
</P>
<P>
   As it now stands, Freeman traps the cats and takes them to a
shelter, where Bradley retrieves them, spends up to $200 in fees,
then returns them to the museum _ much to the horror of the
curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is outrageous and irresponsible,'' Blades says. ``I'm
tired of being cast as the bad guy. She is expecting to pursue her
obsession on people's private property.''
</P>
<P>
   The cat lady believes the conflict is mostly a human thing:
``It's become a personal thing. Some people aren't used to having
their authority challenged. He's always putting down my program.''
</P>
<P>
   Blades says the cats absolutely will not stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's taking them back there?'' asked an incredulous Lt.
DiPace. ``Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Freeman, the trapper: ``Help me. I'm losing my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
