<SLUG> BC-REDOING-TEXAS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Architects to showcase their vision for downtown
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At the beginning of the decade, the Warehouse
District was a forgotten part of Austin's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this area is one of downtown's most dramatic
redevelopment efforts. Dilapidated buildings and empty warehouses
are now restaurants, nightclubs, stores and offices. Soon, housing
will join the mix.
</P>
<P>
   To capture this dynamic atmosphere, a group of local architects
will unveil a display showing what is happening and what could
happen in the Warehouse District and nearby downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
   To date, most of the changes in the Warehouse District have
occurred in old buildings. That is about to change with a spate of
new construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're about to see now is a major change,'' said Sinclair
Black, an Austin architect who helped organize the exhibit. ``We're
going to get back to some fairly serious building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting because it's not all office space,'' Black
said. ``There is housing and retail mixed in, and there are smarter
strategies about parking.''
</P>
<P>
   Black is working with Page Southerland Page to design a $56
million apartment cluster at Second and Colorado streets. The
project, by Chicago-based AMLI Residential, will include
underground parking and rows of ground-floor shops to improve the
project's pedestrian accessibility. The City of Austin is
negotiating with AMLI to build a sister project on city-owned land
a block south.
</P>
<P>
   Black also designed the headquarters for the Schlotzsky's
sandwich chain at Fourth and Colorado streets, which has received
design awards from the International Interior Design Association,
the American Institute of Architects' Austin chapter and the
Associated General Contractors of America's Austin chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The display _ Urban by Design: Architecture in Downtown Austin _
is designed to give the public a better idea how architects
contribute to the urban environment, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   It also should stimulate public debate on such projects as the
decommissioned Seaholm Power Plant, which has been mentioned as a
future museum or aquarium, and the design of the Lamar Boulevard
pedestrian bridge over Town Lake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Six architectural firms and several civic organizations are
contributing plans, models and drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Participants include Susman Tisdale Gayle, Steinbomer &AMP;
Associates, architect Dick Clark, DMJM of Los Angeles, Page
Southerland Page and Sinclair Black &AMP; Andrew Vernooy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the buildings to be highlighted will be Mezzaluna, Bitter
End, GSD&AMP;M Idea City, Cedar Street and the Schlotzsky's
headquarters. Residential projects will include the AMLI project
and the Brown Building, a historic office building on Eighth and
Colorado streets that has been converted into lofts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
