</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-INDIANS-BURBA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burba becomes beacon of light in second playoff game
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND, Ohio _ Nearly an hour after the game, a crowd outside
the gates of Jacobs Field, far down the left field line, stood
chanting, ``Bur-ba, Bur-ba, Bur-ba.''
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, Dave Burba shouldn't have been anywhere near
Cleveland that afternoon. He should have been in a boat somewhere
in the Alaskan wilds baiting a hook.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, Burba shouldn't have been anywhere near the
pitching mound Wednesday at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   He should have been relaxing in the Cleveland Indians bullpen,
cracking jokes and spitting sunflower seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Burba was thrust into the spotlight by some bizarre
events and was the day's stand-in star as the Indians crushed the
Boston Red Sox, 9-5, in Game 2 of the American League Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Burba not only saved the day, maybe he saved the series for the
Tribe, which drew even at a game apiece with the Red Sox in the
best-of-five, with the next two games in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's starter was Doc Gooden, who became embroiled in
combat with plate umpire Joe Brinkman three pitches into the game.
Four hitters into the game, the Red Sox led, 2-0, and Gooden was
gone _ ejected by Brinkman.
</P>
<P>
   Burba, a 15-game winner as a starter this year, but pushed to
the bullpen because of his experience there, was summoned to quell
the Gooden-Brinkman mess.
</P>
<P>
   Burba retired the two batters he faced in the bottom of the
first with no further damage and went on to pitch 5 1/3 innings of
three-run, four-hit baseball and was the winner when the Indians
scored one in the first, five in the second and one in the third
off knuckleballer Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   In late March, Burba was scheduled to pitch Opening Day for the
Cincinnati Reds and during spring training he planned a postseason
fishing trip to Alaska because, after all, these were the
going-nowhere Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Burba, unhappy about the trade to Cleveland (for Sean Casey)
when it happened, recovered long enough to call his fishing friends
and say, ``Count me out, I'm going to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said Wednesday, ``Once the trade was made, I knew there
was a good chance to go to the postseason so I canceled the trip. .
.by the time we're through the water will be frozen over.''
</P>
<P>
   With Burba's help.
</P>
<P>
   The surreal stuff began on the Gooden's second and third pitches
to Boston leadoff hitter Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first pitch was a ball,'' Gooden said. ``I thought the
second and third pitches were strikes.'' Brinkman not only called
them both balls, he whipped off his mask and shouted at Gooden, who
backed off the mound with his palms up, as if to say, ``Hey, OK,
everything is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't. According to Gooden, Brinkman kept yelling at
him. So Gooden walked toward the plate, bringing out manager Mike
Hargrove. After soothing Gooden, Hargrove confronted Brinkman with
some direct verbiage and was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden walked Lewis, walked John Valentin on a 3-and-2 count,
then struck out Mo Vaughn. Nomar Garciaparra drove one near the top
of the 19-foot high left field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis scored, but replays showed Valentin, trying to score from
first, was out easily. Brinkman called him safe. When replays were
shown and the 45,229 fans reacted, so did Gooden. He tried to get
at Brinkman and was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw the play, and he was in position, and I was right
behind him,'' Gooden said. ``Obviously, he was out. For some reason
Brinkley (Brinkman) called him safe. I was shocked. I was standing
right behind Brinkley (Brinkman) and it was not even a bang-bang
play. He was out by plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba was thrust into the fray, but given all the time he needed
to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagined I was starting the game, that it was 0-0 (it was
2-0, Boston),'' Burba said. ``I had plenty of time to get my
pitches ready, to get loose, to see which pitches were working and
which ones weren't. I was intent upon not letting what had just
happened affect me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing up stretching (in the bullpen) when I saw the
umpire throw Doc out, so I knew it was me,'' Burba said.
</P>
<P>
   David Justice, who had two hits and drove in four runs,
including a three-run home run in the five-run second, started the
Tribe back in the right direction with a sacrifice fly in the
first.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alomar contributed run-scoring doubles in the second and
third and Kenny Lofton had two hits, scored two and drove in one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three guys (Justice, Alomar, Lofton) are the guys
everybody targeted as having off years for us this year,'' Hargrove
said. ``It's a little ironic that these guys have stepped up big.
It doesn't surprise me. They're winners, they're good players,
they're good hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba, savoring the moment, admitted he wasn't thrilled with his
assignment in the bullpen after winning 15 as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my competitive nature and I wanted to start,'' Burba
said. ``I felt I was the backbone of the rotation all year. But as
Hargrove explained it to me, he had two young guys in the rotation
(Jaret Wright, Bartolo Colon), Doc Gooden is a bona fide starter
and he had no experience in the bullpen. So he said to me, 'You fit
the mold for what I need out there.' I told him, 'If that's what is
best for you and the team, I don't make waves, I'm there.'''
</P>
<P>
   As he walked down a tunnel toward the clubhouse after the game,
Burba smiled and said, ``This ranks right up there at the top of my
thrill list, but not as high as that home run I hit against the
Reds this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
