<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUHN-CUBS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What happened to the Cubs?
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It would be tempting to say the Cubs were hung over
from their Monday wild card playoff victory over San Francisco,
were emotionally spent, were lambs being led to the butcher.
</P>
<P>
   But then you'd have to explain all those other postseason games
John Smoltz has pitched exactly like this.
</P>
<P>
   What was the excuse in those?
</P>
<P>
   What was the Pirates' excuse in 1991 when they scored three runs
off Smoltz in 15 innings? The Twins' excuse in '91 (two runs in
14)? The Cards' excuse in '96 (two runs in 15 innings)? The
Yankees' excuse in '96 (one earned run in 14 innings)? The Dodgers'
excuse in '96 or the Astros in '97 when each scored one run in nine
innings?
</P>
<P>
   No, the Cubs needed no excuses Wednesday when they bowed to the
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prepared hard and we did everything we could do,'' Cubs
manager Jim Riggleman said. ``Smoltz was just the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' postseason monster bit off another head Wednesday as
Atlanta stuffed Chicago in the Divisional Series opener, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was his 11th postseason victory, the most in baseball
history, one more than Whitey Ford and Dave Stewart. Yes, he has
had more opportunities, especially now that the playoffs are
three-tiered. But the fact is, his numbers are undeniable. Against
the best teams in the game, in 21 postseason starts, Smoltz is 11-3
with a 2.29 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is,'' he said in the clubhouse later, ``I never
thought I'd be here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the hardest season of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And the best.
</P>
<P>
   How those two live together, Smoltz still can't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``God must have done it,'' he says. ``Really, I have no other
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   He was on the disabled list at the start of the year after
offseason elbow surgery. He went back on the D.L. in late May and
stayed a month.
</P>
<P>
   It hurt so badly, he was certain his career was over.
</P>
<P>
   When he came back off the second time, his elbow still bothering
him, he woke up nearly every morning wondering if he'd be able to
throw a ball. ``There must have been eight starts that I didn't
think I could make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he made every one.
</P>
<P>
   Final record: 17-3, his best percentage ever; 2.90 earned-run
average, second best ever, and better than his Cy Young season of
1996 when he was 24-8 with a 2.94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it happened,'' he said again.
</P>
<P>
   The key at-bats Wednesday came in the top of the seventh after
Sammy Sosa whipped a double into the left-field corner to lead off.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were down 3-0, but their guns were up _ Mark Grace, Oh
Henry Rodriguez and Gary ``The Rat'' Gaetti.
</P>
<P>
   Grace swung at the first pitch and popped up, flinging away his
bat in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him afterward if he was trying to doublecross Smoltz
because Grace usually swings at first pitches once per lunar
eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Grace said. ``I swing at a lot of first
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was more honest. ``I threw him the fastball over the
plate because he almost always takes a pitch,'' Smoltz said. ``But
I didn't mean to have nothing on it. If I throw him that pitch
again, he'll get me more often than I get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz then struck out Rodriguez with a 3-2 changeup, and got
Gaetti to bounce to second to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as tough as ever,'' Gaetti said. ``He pitches me in,
then out and then I find myself jogging back to the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the universal postseason explanation when Smoltz pitches.
And with Tom Glavine going today and Greg Maddux in Game 3, the
Cubs likely won't see Smoltz again until next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
