<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-DAVIDNDEE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dee and David Show delights in Columbus
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Call them the Killer D's. D-Lite. D'structive.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you tag them, the threat is always times-two with Ohio
State's David Boston and Dee Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most dangerous wide receiver tandem in college
football, Boston and Miller delight each Saturday in putting on The
Dee and David Show. Last season, the duo combined for 131
receptions, 1,951 yards and 19 touchdowns. In three games this
year, they've hauled in 35 catches for 509 yards and four
touchdowns. ``When the ball's in the air, I put my money on our
receivers, any day, against anybody,'' OSU quarterback Joe Germaine
said.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming Oct. 3 game against No. 7 Penn State (3-0), Miller
and Boston will get a chance to repeat the high-flying performance
they had against the Nittany Lions last season in combining for 22
receptions, 302 yards and two touchdowns. It was a career best
performance for each player.
</P>
<P>
   Their accomplishments were soured by a 31-27 Buckeye defeat, a
fate they hope to avoid this week when the Nittany Lions come to
Ohio Stadium for a battle of the unbeatens.
</P>
<P>
   With the 6-3 Boston and 6-1 Miller, OSU has a significant height
advantage over the Penn State defensive backs who are 5-9 , 5-8,
5-7 and 5-11. Miller says at times the height mismatch could factor
into the Buckeyes' game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if Joe (Germaine) puts a little bit of air underneath
the football, it gives Dave and I a chance to just jump up and make
some plays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Making plays is their speciality, although it took Miller, a
fifth year senior from Springfield South High School, a little
longer to get the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, a junior from Humble, Tex., waltzed into a starting job
_ ahead of Miller _ midway through his freshman season after Buster
Tillman got hurt. His game-winning touchdown catch in the Rose Bowl
made him an instant star and secured his position as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miller anxiously waited his turn. A knee injury had
sidelined him in 1994 and he received little playing time the next
two years, thanks in large part to Boston's arrival. Miller says he
doesn't begrudge his teammate for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that he's received and all the attention is
well-deserved,'' Miller said. ``I'm not a jealous guy. I just
wanted to come in and show everybody what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   He got his chance last fall when he was named the Buckeyes'
starting flanker. His breakout game came Oct. 11 at Penn State when
he caught a career-high eight passes for 149 yards. Boston set a
school single-game record for receptions during that same game with
14 for 153 yards.
</P>
<P>
   After a season in which Miller was a non-factor, it was quickly
becoming clear to opponents that OSU now had a double threat at
wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go after Dave because Dee will burn you,'' Germaine
said. ``You go after Dee, Dave will dunk you, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Boston: ``The better Dee plays ... the better it is for me.
It's great to have a talented receiver across from you so no one
can focus on one player.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller recognizes that Boston, who, in 1997, set a school
single-season record for receptions (73) and led the Big Ten in
that category, is still viewed by many as the marquee receiver for
OSU. He's just glad to be receiving partial billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's still talking about Dave, but I think they're
starting to realize that we have another good receiver on the other
side, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
