<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINGERPRINT-ID02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer problem freezes fingerprint ID in Florida
 &HT;    By Monika Gonzalez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dozens of crimes in Palm Beach County could be going unsolved
because the sheriff's computers can't compare fingerprints found at
crime scenes with those of criminals arrested in other parts of the
state, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While fingerprint experts said the now-two-year-old computer
communication problem in Palm Beach County should be fixed by
January, the delays it continues to bring investigators could be
the difference in whether a burglary victim gets her jewelry back
or whether a case's filing deadline will pass before a suspect is
found.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has affected six of Florida's largest counties. The
speed of technology is to blame, fingerprint examiners said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the state, it's not the local, it's not the
(computer) company. It's a little bit of everybody,'' said Pinellas
County fingerprint examiner Bill Schade. ``We're breaking new
ground. It's a tremendous program that's long overdue. The need is
so great and the benefit is tremendous. It's just a nightmare as
far as logistics.''
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to a software compatibility problem that
actually stems from improvements to a network of state and local
fingerprint computers commonly known among police as AFIS _
Automated Fingerprint Identification System.
</P>
<P>
   AFIS allows police to check fingerprints found at a burglary
and, through recent advances, lets them see if the man they just
pulled in for stealing a car might be giving a different name from
the last time he was arrested, or is linked to another crime.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the system compares an unidentified fingerprint to
databases with fingerprints of those arrested in the county and the
state, returning several possible matches. A fingerprint examiner
then checks each manually.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office AFIS _ like its
statewide counterpart run by the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement _ was growing outdated, said Palm Beach County AFIS
supervisor Mark McDonald. Both agencies decided to upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's office completed its upgrade first in October 1996
_ knowing it wouldn't be compatible with Tallahassee's AFIS until
the state switched to the new system, McDonald said. During that
time, only searches of the county fingerprint database would be
possible. Everyone expected it to take about six months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time FDLE completed its improvements, the statewide
AFIS system upgrade surpassed the Palm Beach County system _ and
the two still were incompatible. The sheriff's office then chose to
get another upgrade that would also allow it to electronically add
fingerprints to the state database as inmates are booked into the
jail.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald hopes that will happen by January. In the meantime, on
major cases, detectives take fingerprints to a county that remains
in communication with Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Once the systems are linked, Palm Beach County fingerprint
examiners will run the hundreds of unidentified fingerprints
collected over the last two years against the statewide database.
It could mean suspects will be developed in a slew of cases.
</P>
<P>
   But solving crimes is often a race against time, Palm Beach
County fingerprint examiner Jay Mullins said. Getting victims'
belongings back often depends on police finding the suspect
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Running the unidentified fingerprints will probably take at
least a year because of staffing levels, McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any cases that the statute of limitations have run out will be
put at the end,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade, Broward, Collier, Lee and Pinellas counties all lost
their Tallahassee link for some time after the state upgraded.
Broward went six months without the ability to search the state
database, but now has a temporary, limited link to Tallahassee.
Dade County went on line with FDLE only Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County appears to have spent the most time without a
link to the state AFIS. The county has spent nearly $1 million over
the past 10 years on the system.
</P>
<P>
   Most county AFIS systems get the majority of their matches from
their own local databases, officials said. Prior to losing its link
to the statewide database, Palm Beach County sheriff's fingerprint
examiners were getting about two or three matches a month from the
state database. Miami-Dade police got about 20 hits last month from
the state database, officials there said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really significant in the big picture, but I'd like
to get those three or four,'' said Cpl. Joseph Barber, manager for
the Collier/Lee AFIS.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   KickerHed goes here
</P>
<P>
   QuickReadBecause of computer problems, the Palm Beach County
sheriff's office hasn't been able to compare fingerprints found
here with a state database of criminals. Here's how the system is
supposed to work:
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified fingerprint is scanned into a computer that
compares it to the fingerprints of nearly everyone arrested in Palm
Beach County in roughly the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The computer may find several possible matches or ``hits'' and a
fingerprint examiner checks each manually.
</P>
<P>
   If no true matches are found, the examiner then searches
another, larger database that includes everyone that has been
arrested in the state and is run by the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
