A3748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-MEGAN02-COX     10-01 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MEGAN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Megan's Law'' upheld by Ohio court
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ohio Supreme Court on Sept. 30 upheld the state's ``Megan's
Law,'' saying sexual predators must register with the county
sheriff even if they committed the crime before the law went into
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-0 decision reverses a ruling last year by the 3rd Ohio
District Court of Appeals in Lima that barred enforcement of the
law in Auglaize, Mercer and Shelby counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision means that every Ohioan can feel safer,''
said Ohio Attorney General Betty Montgomery. ``Now, in all 88
counties, before every judge in the state, sex offenders will be
required to register, and communities will have a right to know
when an offender is in their midst.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruling stems from the first challenge to the
law.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court in Lima ruled that community notification
violated the Ohio Constitution's ban on retroactive punishment. It
held that the law could not apply to anyone who committed an
offense before July 1, 1997, when the law took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, at least two other appellate courts have made
similar rulings, creating a situation where some communities were
notified of sex predators and others were not.
</P>
<P>
   In reversing the 3rd District ruling, the Supreme Court found
the sex offender law does not violate the retroactivity clauses of
either the state or United State constitutions since the
registration requirements were ``remedial'' and not punitive.
</P>
<P>
   The high court acknowledged that sex offenders may be ostracized
or harassed because of the public notification requirement.
</P>
<P>
   However, it found that these consequences aren't the direct
result of the law, ``but instead as a direct societal consequence
of (the offender's) past actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also found that the government's interest in
protecting the public from sex offenders outweighed a sex
offender's expectations of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Most states now have laws modeled after the 1994 New Jersey case
in which Megan Kanka was lured into the home of a two-time sex
offender. The 7-year-old girl was raped and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's law requires sheriffs to notify neighbors, area schools
and day-care centers when a sexual predator moves into a community.
</P>
<P>
   The law defines a sexual predator as someone who has been
convicted of a sex crime and who is likely to be a repeat offender,
and must register with the sheriff every 90 days for life.
</P>
<P>
   It defines two lesser categories:
</P>
<P>
   Habitual offender: A person convicted of more than one sex
offense who must register with the sheriff once a year for 20
years; a judge can decide if the community should be notified.
</P>
<P>
   Sexually oriented offender: Generally a first-time offender;
required to register with the sheriff once a year for 10 years;
neighbors will not be notified.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, 1,958 sex offenders have registered, according to
Montgomery's office. Of these, 136 are sexual predators; 84 are
habitual offenders (14 with notification, 70 without); and 1,738
are sexually oriented offenders.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from the Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
