<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTZ-DDN02-COX     10-01 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTZ-DDN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ants march two-by-two into the nation's theaters
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ DreamWorks' Antz , a computer-animated insect
adventure featuring the voices of Woody Allen, Sylvester Stallone
and Sharon Stone, tromps into theaters today. Disney's A Bug's Life
, a similarly styled film from the creators of Toy Story , follows
on its six heels on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   In a year of competing asteroid flicks ( Deep Impact and
Armageddon ), as well as two films about boys afflicted with
Morquio Syndrome ( Simon Birch and the forthcoming The Mighty ),
the warring ants will be the most closely watched race of all.
DreamWorks moved its film's release date up from spring 1999 when
partial subsidiary Pacific Digital Images delivered Antz ahead of
schedule, allowing the studio to get a seven-week jump on the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually didn't know there was another movie,'' DreamWorks
co-founder Jeffrey Katzenberg said, jokingly, at a news conference
prior to Antz 's Sept. 19 premiere at the Toronto International
Film Festival. Katzenberg was head of Disney motion-picture
production during A Bug's Life 's development, prompting industry
debate over Antz 's origins.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his casual attire, Katzenberg's presence among the media
at a panel discussion with Antz 's cast and directors did not go
unnoticed. The film's star power and rushed release date
demonstrate his studio's desire to be king of the ant hill.
</P>
<P>
   Antz 's voice cast also includes Gene Hackman, Anne Bancroft,
Christopher Walken, Jennifer Lopez, Danny Glover, Dan Aykroyd and
Jane Curtin. A Bug's Life features Kevin Spacey, Dave Foley and
Julia Louis-Dreyfus.
</P>
<P>
   Director Tim Johnson, who served as animation director of The
Simpsons ' 1995 Halloween special, Homer3 , admitted it was
intimidating to be going up against the makers of Toy Story .
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid that if people saw our film after their movie it
would be nothing but compared, and the film would never stand up on
its own,'' Johnson said. ``So to me, the greatest thing about being
into the theaters before them is people will judge this movie for
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Antz tells the story of Z-4195 (Allen), a worker ant who dreams
of a life beyond the unyielding caste system of his colony. When he
falls for the beautiful Princess Bala (Stone), Z swaps places with
his best friend, a soldier ant named Weaver (Stallone). Surviving a
fierce battle with termites, Z becomes an unlikely hero, and soon
finds himself leading a revolution against regimented conformity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, human beings always try to displace their own
emotions to understand themselves through animals,'' said Glover,
who plays Barbatus, a seasoned soldier who takes Z under his wing.
``The idea that we take this insignificant little being and try to
understand something about loving, ideas, dreams and all, is
intriguing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Antz took nearly three years to develop from traditional pencil
drawings to state-of-the-art digital animation. Much of that time
was spent creating the details and nuances that convey what the
character is thinking. ``It has a lot less to do with big broad
gestures than the very subtle things _ it might do with the brow or
the corner of the mouth,'' co-director Eric Darnell explained.
``And the animators work very hard on that. I think on average, a
good animator is lucky to do five seconds a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice actors recorded their dialogue individually, most in
two or three sessions lasting several hours each. Saturday Night
Live veterans Aykroyd and Curtin, who play a pair of snobbish wasps
named Chip and Muffy, recorded their banter in separate cities,
weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like doing radio,'' Curtin said. ``You're using your
wits, you're using your instrument and there's no facade, so you
can have a lot more fun with it, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No worry about weight loss or gain, either,'' Aykroyd added,
drawing laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, on the other hand, found it difficult to convey emotion
and sentiment using only her voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about doing a three-hour session, and at the end of
that you're truly exhausted,'' Darnell said, ``because they have to
put so much imagination, so much energy, into standing in this
empty room with just a microphone and to pull all of this stuff out
and get that into their performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast was videotaped as they recorded their voices, giving
the animators live-action reference for the gestures and movement
they put into their performances. While the arthropods don't
resemble the actors voicing them, their personalities are familiar
_ to everyone but the actors, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized everybody but me,'' said Walken, who plays Col.
Cutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got the length of my stinger too short,'' Aykroyd
quipped, again breaking up the room.
</P>
<P>
   Having such strongly identifiable voices can be a mixed
blessing, Johnson admitted. While there's a certain pleasure to
recognizing a famous voice, ``you really do want to lose yourself
in the characters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aykroyd used the example of Robin Williams as Aladdin 's Genie.
``We all knew it was Robin Williams, but he sold that character and
you didn't associate him, as the live actor, with the character
because it was just such a strong piece of animation, and marriage
of his ability with the animator's skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, whose character is introduced on a therapist's couch,
kvetching about being ``the middle child in a family of 5
million,'' signed on early in the process, allowing the directors
to fashion and mold the film to his character and his way of
working from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to know what our expectations were when we went in
to meet him,'' Johnson recalled. ``I guess I thought that as
somebody who is so accomplished as a director, that it might be
hard to have him see what we wanted in our vision for the film. But
the opposite was true. He looked at the script and he loved the
script and he said, `Guys, you tell me how to be successful for
your movie.'
</P>
<P>
   ``From that moment on, Eric and I would be sitting there in the
sound booth, Woody Allen would be reading our script and
improvising on it and changing words and making it much more
hysterical, and I would turn to Eric and say, `Here we are in the
middle of Manhattan and there all these people who just paid $75 to
see shows all over the city, and we've got the best show in town
right here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks certainly hopes that's the case.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-30-98 2013E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
