A3753 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREX02-COX     10-01 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREX02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State judge freezes assets of Austin Forex
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A state district judge recently froze assets
that Russell Erxleben may have received from his failed Austin
Forex International Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The move prevents him from moving money from investors into
other accounts or from selling items such as autos that are owned
by the company.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary injunction, granted by District Judge Pete Lowry,
was requested by attorneys representing investors.
</P>
<P>
   It lasts until a civil trial on charges against Erxleben and
several other defendants is held. A preliminary trial date was set
for May.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate court hearing, District Judge Suzanne Covington
allowed the State Securities Board to transfer $200,000 from a bank
account of a company affiliated with Austin Forex to the receiver
handling the case.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver is trying to find out what happened to an estimated
$40 million to $60 million invested with Austin Forex by 700
people.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 18, the State Securities Board took control of the
accounts and books at the foreign currency trading company and got
a state court to appoint a receiver to determine what has happened
to investors' money. The company closed Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Erxleben, a former football All-American kicker at the
University of Texas, has maintained that the money was lost in
trading losses and the actions of unidentified ``third parties.''
He was not in court on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys at the securities agency say it may be months before
the receiver can determine how much money may be left.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goldsmith, who requested the injunction, said that prior
to that action there wasn't sufficient protection to keep assets at
Austin Forex and its affiliate, International Foreign Exchange
Corp., from being moved.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Erxleben, Austin Forex and its affiliate, the injunction
includes any of the company's assets held in Bank of America or
Comerica Bank accounts, or by Michael Shapiro, a former Austin
Forex executive.
</P>
<P>
   The assets may include several high-dollar cars. Texas motor
vehicle registration records show that since July 1997, Austin
Forex has purchased a $48,459 1998 Lexus GS4, a $62,594 Mercedes, a
1995 Mercedes 420 and a $43,366 Chevy sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   John Stratton, Erxleben's attorney, said after losing the fight
over the temporary injunction that the court's action has ``no
impact whatsoever'' on Erxleben's personal assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that Mr. Erxleben has any of that
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, three investors testified that they separately
invested a total of more than $1 million with Erxleben's company
just weeks before it closed. Erxleben, they said, gave no
indication the company could be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   He also told them that a small percentage of the company's funds
were actually invested at any one time, they said. Mark Miller, an
Austin real estate appraiser, said he invested $240,000 with Austin
Forex between February and August.
</P>
<P>
   He said that during a meeting on Aug. 28, Erxleben told him that
Austin Forex was grossing between $1.6 million and $1.8 million a
month and he was personally earning $300,000 and $500,000 a month
from commissions.
</P>
<P>
   He said Erxleben told him that Austin Forex was then trading $40
million for investors.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Miller said Erxleben called him to invite him
to put in more money because ``the currency markets were moving
quite a bit and he had the opportunity to make quite a bit of money
for investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his solicitation, Miller said he had his last $50,000
investment wired to Austin Forex.
</P>
<P>
   Austin businessmen John Gilmore and James Wayne McMichael gave
similar testimony.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Stratton argued that each witnesses was a wealthy,
sophisticated investor who should have understood the contract they
were signing.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, who said he invested $650,000 with Austin Forex,
identified himself as a real estate investor who owns several dozen
properties worth at least $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael, who invested $60,000 in Austin Forex, said he has
managed and owned more than 100 properties worth $15 million to $20
million, and previously had oil and gas interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They admitted they knew the arrangement and didn't withdraw
their money,'' Stratton said.
</P>
<P>
   Erxleben, he said, ``was the agent merely as a trader,
authorized to trade'' and wasn't acting in a fiduciary role for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The State Securities Board has claimed that Austin Forex and
Erxleben violated state securities laws, in part, because of the
way the investors' funds were co-mingled.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lowry asked Stratton what chance investors had of getting
their money back. Stratton said it may be possible to recover from
third parties a substantial amount, ``even if they've been lost in
trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
