<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIGEONS-PBP02-COX     10-01 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGEONS-PBP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silly Pigeons is right on target
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Palm Beach Post-Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jaunty crime tales are at least as old as the 18th century and
The Beggar's Opera. But they were never standard fare. Late this
century, however, a dark comedy about your average serial killer is
as common as bloody murder itself. Wild and crazy mischief pays.
Examples are Elmore Leonard's novels and the Coen brothers' movies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the trend represents a kind of exorcism, like making fun
of the devil at Halloween. In any case, add rookie director David
Dobkin to the roster of movie-makers who combine low crime and
eccentric criminals with a police procedural that is both wacky and
intense.
</P>
<P>
   Dobkin's Clay Pigeons takes its cue from the Coens. There are no
Fargo wood chippers. But there is an offbeat killer and a schmo who
is ensnared in another man's crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The film isn't slick. The plot is a tad overstuffed, and the
score shrieks. A typically ``subtle'' joke occurs when a corpse is
pulled from a lake and we hear the theme from Deliverance. And can
you stand another Deputy Doofus in the Barney Fife mold? (Can't
anybody make a film these days without cutesy references to pop
culture?)
</P>
<P>
   But Dobkin, a music video director, gets good performances from
Vince Vaughn and Joaquin Phoenix. Even Janeane Garofolo's Medusa
mug has its charms. She plays an FBI agent who doesn't suffer
fools, and she has one fine bit when a crack appears in her deadpan
during a barroom pickup scene.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Pigeons is a movie created by youngish people for youngish
people. It's rambunctious and engaging, and wastes no time in
getting down to business.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is Clay Bidwell, a gas station attendant in a Montana
hick town. While shooting at beer bottles one afternoon, Clay is
suddenly accused by a buddy of sleeping with his wife (Georgina
Cates).
</P>
<P>
   This is true enough. But Clay is a decent lout. He doesn't
deserve to have his pal commit suicide in front of him, especially
when this pal has taken pains to make sure Clay is framed for the
``murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Frantic, Clay makes a mistake _ the first of many that will make
him chief suspect in a string of grisly murders. With every move he
makes, he digs a deeper hole for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to lend a shovel is Clay's new best bud Lester Long
(Vaughn). With his Stetson and fringy duds, Lester is a dime store
cowboy who suddenly appears in town and leeches onto Clay. His glib
patter and palsy manner _ not to mention a reflexive cackle _ make
him a dude to keep a wary eye on.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter Ed Healy gives us a fair number of twists, although
some wind up in too-neat circles. Vaughn (The Lost World) is a
chameleon of an actor, and brings a hypnotic touch of smiling
menace to his role. No pretty boy, Phoenix is convincing as an
average guy at loose ends, whose decent impulses and bad habits
combine to get him in plenty of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As a weary small town sheriff, veteran actor Scott Wilson holds
the moral center of a shifty universe in which the ordinary can
turn creepy. Cates is dislikable (and that's good) as a bored wife
who is loose in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   A story of a killer playing mind games with the innocent is
hardly new. And it doesn't get any fresher if you add a bouncy
sensibility. But despite its stylized moments, including an
unnecessarily prolonged stabbing scene, Clay Pigeons holds your
interest through good acting and, strange to say, silly humor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
