<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIGEONS-VAUGHN02-COX     10-01 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGEONS-VAUGHN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vaughn invented spine-tingling guffaw just for movie
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elvis Eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Vaughn's got them. But wait. He didn't have them in The
Lost World: Jurassic Park. Or did he? Maybe he wore them for his of
a wannabe Lothario in Swingers _ the breakthrough movie for the
28-year-old actor?
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn just cackles at the thought of Elvis. It's the eerie
laughter of his weirdo character in Clay Pigeons. He created that
guffaw for the film, and he doesn't mind using it as the answer to
questions during a recent phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   So who knows? Vaughn is proving himself such a crafty actor,
maybe he can make his eyes look different from movie to movie.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is an official Hollywood ``rising young star'' _ a phrase
that gets another Woody Woodpecker cackle from him. ``I just feel
like being in Los Angeles for 7 1/2 years, with a year and a half
without any work at all _ well, I am enjoying the chance to rise
for any job.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's kin were Midwestern farmers, but he largely grew up in
the Chicago suburbs. He went to Los Angeles at 18, after an
appearance in a Chevy commercial made him think he would cruise to
stardom. What followed was the long road of doing not much.
</P>
<P>
   The small-budget film Swingers led to a big-time phone call _
from Steven Spielberg. He wanted Vaughn to play the daring
documentary-maker in The Lost World. Spielberg said he was looking
for ``a new movie star _ an American icon to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Like slasher Norman Bates? That's Vaughn's upcoming role in the
remake of Psycho with director Gus Van Sant. He couldn't pass up
the challenge of reprising a classic.
</P>
<P>
   As for Van Sant, Vaughn said ``he's a great director who gives
you the opportunity to be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clay Pigeons, Vaughn makes another dubious character come
alive. He's slick and sinister. ``I figured this guy had a bad
experience of some kind. He didn't like his reality, so he created
his own. But I didn't want to make him a psycho-Frankenstein,''
Vaughn said. Cackle. Cackle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
