<HEADER>
A3789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOBBY-$ADV03-COX     10-01 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBY-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CIGARETTE COMPANIES LEAD SURGE IN LOBBYING COSTS
 &HT;    600&AMP;adds. With LOBBY-LIST for release Saturday, Oct.3.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Led by a British-owned cigarette maker, big
businesses and pressure groups are spending record amounts to
influence the federal government this year.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., a subsidiary of BAT Plc.,
spent an unprecedented $18.2 million on federal lobbying between
January and June, the latest available records show.
</P>
<P>
   That pace of $3 million a month is ``roughly double what anybody
spent lobbying last year,'' commented Larry Makinson, executive
director of the nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics, which
studies the role of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Another tobacco company, Philip Morris Cos. Inc., ranked second
with $14.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   A Cox Newspapers examination of lobbying disclosure reports
filed with the U.S. House of Representatives found that the next
highest spenders were Bell Atlantic, $9.6 million; the American
Medical Association (AMA), $8.3 million, and the Chamber of
Commerce of the United States, $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined the latest semi-annual reports of all
registrants who had reported spending more than $500,000 in the
first six months of 1997 or $1 million in that entire year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 97 organizations reported spending at least $1
million apiece between January and June. In the first half of last
year, only 89 spent that much.
</P>
<P>
   Total spending by the 100 biggest spenders in the first six
months of 1998 exceeded $264 million _ a 13 percent increase over
the approximately $235 million spent by the top 100 in the first
six months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think lobbying is getting more expensive in Washington,''
said Elaine Acevedo, president of the American League of Lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to have mostly generalists, but now you have people
specializing,'' she said. ``You hire your grass-roots coordinator
here, your independent-expenditure specialist there, your
focus-group specialist over there, and it all adds up.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, a lobbying blitz led by Philip Morris, the world's
largest tobacco company, and Brown &AMP; Williamson, the American
branch of the world's second largest, crushed a year-long attempt
in Congress to pass the National Tobacco Policy and Youth Smoking
Reduction Act.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, killed in the Senate by a Republican-led filibuster,
would have imposed high costs and tight rules on the industry and
its customers in return for federal protection from class-action
lawsuits under a plan drafted by the attorneys general of most
states.
</P>
<P>
   The battle could resume next year. So, tobacco companies have
continued to supplement their lobbying with political contributions
and with print, radio and TV ads that by the end of July had
already cost their sponsors more than $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most expensive and sustained issue advertising
campaign ever undertaken on a piece of pending legislation,''
according to Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School
of Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   At his Washington-based research center, Makinson said, ``The
tobacco companies are very smart and very rich, and they're not shy
about operating on a war-like basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for freedom of speech,'' said Mark Smith, a
spokesman at Brown &AMP; Williamson's headquarters in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We faced the largest possible tax increase and restrictions
that would have jeopardized many tobacco companies' actual
existence,'' he said. ``We had to do what the Constitution allows,
and lobby the U.S. Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional adds follow.)
</P>
<P>
   The companies ranked just below the two tobacco giants also have
a lot at stake in federal policies that affect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is one of the ``Baby Bell'' companies locked in a
fierce, multi-state battle with long-distance firms over how to
deregulate the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   The physicians in the AMA have stakes in battles between health
care providers, insurers and insured people over regulating managed
health care, cleaning up Medicaid fraud and restructuring the
financial incentives in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce is at the center of tax, trade,
minimum-wage and spending battles that affect bosses, workers and
shareholders in most communities in every state.
</P>
<P>
   Equally vital special interests are also at stake in this
Congress for the sixth through 10th biggest spenders on lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   They were the Edison Electric Institute (deregulation of
privately owned utilities), $5.5 million; American Council of Life
Insurance (entry into the insurance industry), $5.3 million;
General Motors Corp. (primarily trade, tax, environmental and
automotive policy), $4.9 million; Pfizer Inc. (primarily drug
licensing, health care and patent policy), $4.8 million, and Ford
Motor Co. (primarily automotive, trade, bankruptcy and
environmental policy) $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because registrants use different methods of calculating
lobbying costs, comparisons between companies are imprecise. But
spending is clearly up this year.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the top 10 reported spending more in the first half of
this year than in the first half of last year. So did 63 of the top
100.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the biggest spenders ... were defending the status
quo, because after all a lot of them are big guys who are doing
quite well right now,'' said Bill Hogan, director of research
projects at the Washington-based Center for Public Integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average citizen thinks Congress doesn't do much,'' Hogan
said. ``Well, they don't stop and think that there are a lot of
people spending a lot of money getting Congress not to do much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides that, a lot of lobbyists love multi-year fights,''
Hogan said. ``Telecommunications has been in play for more than a
decade, and it's an unbelievable gravy train for Washington
lobbyists on all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add that can stand alone as a
sidebar follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers examined the latest semi-annual reports filed
under the Lobby Disclosure Act with the clerk of the House and the
secretary of the Senate by organizations that use lobbyists. They
are supposed to provide ``best-faith estimates'' of how much they
spent, and list the lobbyists they employed or retained and the
laws or policies they sought to pass, block or modify.
</P>
<P>
   Reports for the first half of this year were due Aug. 15. The
public and press can examine them only after they are entered into
computers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the House reported that after 45 days of
processing the latest reports, ``virtually all'' of them had been
posted on the four computers the House lets the public use. In the
Senate, the estimate was 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cox contacted companies and associations directly when their
reports could not be found. All but two were willing to supply
copies of their reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like we ought to tighten that up,'' said Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz. ``Especially in a pre-election year, too long a
delay seems to restrict the public's right to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said, ``Maybe we ought to
handle lobby disclosure reports the way we do the reports on our
own personal finances.'' The Senate requires its clerk to let the
public see the annual reports of all senators and high-ranking
staff members on their personal finances 30 days after the filing
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist Acevedo said, ``It's better than it used to be, when
they were all in boxes and you had to leaf through them. But it
strikes me as odd in this day and age that you still can't look
them up on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Registrants can report only their direct costs of lobbying the
federal legislative and executive branches, as the tobacco
companies did. But most of them choose to report the figure they
already calculate for tax purposes, which includes all federal,
state and local lobbying, plus such indirect costs as recruiting,
training and motivating ``grass-roots'' volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of organizations ignore the methods specified on the
official reporting forms and make their own calculations. ``None of
the methods apply to us,'' said a spokeswoman for the Seniors
Coalition, a conservative direct-mail organization.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
