A3817 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIMALAYA-INDICTMENT02     10-01 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIMALAYA-INDICTMENT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DA going for murder in Himalaya case
 &HT;    By Bob Banta and Leah Quin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ It's a harrowing case. A 15-year-old girl is thrown off
a carnival ride and killed as her father watches. Accusations
surface that carnival owners, operators, inspectors and maintenance
workers knew the ride had problems and ignored them.
</P>
<P>
   But is it murder? ``I do not know all the facts of this case,
but it is a mystery to me how the district attorney plans to show
intent to murder,'' said Travis County District Judge Jon Wisser,
who presides over criminal cases, including murder trials.
</P>
<P>
   Wisser lowered the bail for all nine people, including the
owners of an Arizona carnival company, that a Travis County grand
jury indicted Tuesday for murder in the death of Leslie Lane. The
McNeil High School student was thrown from the Himalaya carnival
ride at the Austin-Travis County Livestock Show &AMP; Rodeo on March
19.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said murder charges in mechanical mishaps are
stunningly rare and that winning convictions will be tough, if not
impossible. ``The bail I set is more in line with a charge of
criminally negligent homicide, which most cases like this end up
being,'' Wisser said. He set bail for four of the defendants at
$10,000 and bail for the other five at $25,000 -- compared to the
$75,000 to $500,000 recommended by the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Murder is punishable by five to 99 years in prison. The
punishment for criminally negligent homicide is six months to two
years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The murder indictments shocked legal observers, who said it is
unusual for any criminal charges to be filed against company
executives in such cases, much less murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Ronnie Earle was out of the country and not
available for comment. Earle's chief assistant, Rosemary Lehmberg,
said it is possible the indictments against executives and
employees of B&AMP;B Amusements, owners of the ride, will be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not backing off the indictment,'' Lehmberg said. ``But
it is not unusual that, after interaction with the defense
attorneys, some fine-tuning could occur. However, it's premature to
be talking about that right now.'' Lehmberg declined Wednesday to
say whether district attorneys had asked the grand jury to return
murder indictments against the nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the grand jury thought that what they heard was
egregious enough that the individuals should stand charged with a
high degree of criminal responsibility,'' she said. Lehmberg said
if prosecutors see that other charges are more appropriate, the
indictments could be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury returned murder indictments against Robert Dale
Merten Sr., his wife Shara Merten, and their son, Robert Merten II,
owners of Arizona-based B&AMP;B Amusements, which owned the Himalaya.
The indictments also named B&AMP;B maintenance workers Ottis Frasure
and Jeff Campbell, and the two B&AMP;B workers operating the ride that
night, Daniel Tucker and Joshua Johnson. Robert Gill and Joe Culver
of Bob Gill &AMP; Associates, a Florida-based company that inspected
the Himalaya, also were indicted. John Yeager, attorney for the
Mertens, said the grand jury overreacted. ``Clearly, indicting the
Mertens as if they consciously desired to cause the death of Leslie
Lane is totally inappropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frasure's lawyer, David Wahlberg of Austin, said Frasure would
plead not guilty to murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is an attempt by the district attorney's
office to send a message to the amusement industry,'' Wahlberg
said. ``But using the grand jury process to send a message is an
abuse of that process.'' Lane's family attended the livestock show
every year, though her father said he had always been a little
concerned about the safety of the rides.
</P>
<P>
   On March 19, Lane, her 9-year-old brother and a 16-year-old
friend were in Car No. 19 of the Himalaya, a circular coaster on an
undulating track. As the car crested a rise, all three children
were flung to the platform. Lane, who struck a wall, died there,
the restraining bar beside her.
</P>
<P>
   Austin police said the lap bar intended to keep riders in place
broke away at all three points connecting it to the car. An
investigation by the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission found
Car No. 19 had a faulty lock and showed signs of wear at the bar's
base.
</P>
<P>
   Government and court records showed a history of accidents
involving the Himalaya, though none fatal. In a case similar to
Lane's, two California riders were injured because the pins
attaching the lap bar were not in place. Investigators in the Lane
case said cotter pins holding the lap bar to the car had sheared
off and that carnival workers told them the pins were sometimes
smaller than required.
</P>
<P>
   Most fatalities involving industrial mishaps are dealt with
through civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   If charges are filed, the vast majority are the equivalent of
criminally negligent homicide or manslaughter, which don't require
proof of intent to kill.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 20 years, the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, which protects workers, has referred no more than
about 130 cases to federal prosecutors, said Bill Wright, a
spokesman for the federal agency. Of those, most were not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most famous case of a company being criminally
charged in connection with deaths was one involving Ford Motor Co.,
which produced the Pinto wagon in the 1970s. A federal
investigation found the Pinto's gas tank could be easily punctured
in a rear-end collision, causing the car to catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   An internal memo disclosed Ford had conducted a cost-benefit
analysis that concluded it was cheaper to pay to settle civil
lawsuits filed by victims' families if deaths occurred than recall
all the Pintos and change the fuel systems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Ford became the first American corporation ever
indicted or prosecuted on criminal homicide charges. The company
was acquitted in 1980, although a jury hearing the civil lawsuit
awarded the victims $128.5 million. A judge later reduced the
judgment, the largest amount awarded at the time, to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Professors at the University of Texas Law School said the murder
charges were surprising and extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   To prove murder, prosecutors must show B&AMP;B officials knew their
actions _ and in this case, their machinery _ would kill someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very high burden to carry,'' said Michael Sharlot,
dean of the law school. ``To say they did this and knew it was
reasonably certain to cause death ... wow.''
</P>
<P>
   An example of such a case is a person who purposely drops a
large stone off a 20-story building, Sharlot said. The person may
not aim it at a particular victim, but a rock dropped from that
height is expected to kill someone.
</P>
<P>
   Charging company owners with murder is rare but not
unprecedented, according to veteran trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1986, a trial was held in San Antonio in a case in
which the president, vice president, nursing consultant, and other
executives of Autumn Hills Convalescent Centers Inc. were accused
of murder.
</P>
<P>
   An 87-year-old woman died in a Texas City nursing home owned by
the corporation. Police charged she died from neglect.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly seven months, a jury deadlocked over whether to
convict the company and its executives. A judge dismissed the jury
and the chief prosecutor, Galveston District Attorney Mike Guarino,
dropped the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We based our case on the position that the defendants
knowingly _ not intentionally _ but knowingly neglected these
fragile patients and deprived them of their needed care,'' Guarino
recalled. ``We were not successful. Juries don't identify
defendants like these with the usual criminal type that shoots a
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
