<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Oct. 1, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-WORMS (San Antonio) _ First there was drought. Then there
were floods. Now worms are munching their way across Texas, eating
pasture grass, lawns, oats ... and football fields. The fall
invasion of army worms common to the South and Southwest, was
revved into high gear by heavy late-summer rains. By ELIZABETH
ALLEN. (Photos available on Wieck database)
</P>
<P>
   HEART-DEFIB (Houston) _ The American Heart Association is
campaigning to encourage corporations to acquire automated external
defibrillators and train employees how to treat victims of heart
attacks. By LESLIE SOWERS.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-REPORTING (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Pete Wilson
has vetoed a bill that would create a system for reporting HIV
statistics, a move San Francisco activists and health officials say
is a blow to public health. California is one of nine states that
does not report HIV statistics into a databank used to track the
epidemic, which has killed 65,000 people in the state so far. By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SENATE (San Francisco) _ Republican state Treasurer Matt
Fong has unveiled the first TV ads of his campaign for U.S. Senate,
including spots aimed at Asian American and Latino voters. The
commercials, which air in Cantonese, Mandarin, Spanish and English,
address education issues. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   SF-CHINATOWN (San Francisco) _ Behind the facade of Chinatown's
red lanterns, roast ducks and herb shops is the real Chinatown _
the one where residents live with filth, squalor and constant
neglect. While landlords must take some of the blame, tenant
advocates say the city is just as much at fault for the situation.
By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT-WARNING (Floresville, Texas) _ A 4-foot concrete peanut
in the center of town declares this community the ``Peanut Capital
of Texas.'' A growing peanut allergy movement, however, has left
planners of the 54th annual Floresville Peanut Festival
shellshocked _ and worried about what it could do to business. By
JESSE CLEMENTS.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-SLAUGHTER (San Francisco) _ An agreement over the proper
way to slaughter live animals for sale in Chinatown has died over
the thorny question of how to kill a turtle humanely. By GREGORY
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-PAINTINGS (Undated) _ Jim Zintgraff, 72, will be going west
next week to a canyon along the Pecos River _ a journey to his own
past and that of a prehistoric people. In 1952, at the same site,
Zintgraff discovered a pictograph painted about 4,000 years ago.
After photographing the unique figure, named ``The White Shaman,''
he devoted his life to understanding and protecting the Pecos River
rock art. By CRISTINA MASUDA.
</P>
<P>
   EASYBAKE-CONTEST (Katy, Texas) _ When it comes to bake-offs,
winning is an old Morten family recipe. Natalie Morten, 10, is one
of five finalists in the first Easy-Bake Oven ``Baker of the Year''
contest. Her mother, Linda Morten, won $10,000 in the Pillsbury
Bake-Off two years ago. And big sis Jennifer Morten, 17, went home
with $2,000 in last year's Pillsbury Bake-Off. By MELISSA FLETCHER
STOELTJE.
</P>
<P>
   ART-MURALS (Houston) _ From classical-style paintings to scenics
that turn a space into a room with a view, murals are showing up on
the walls of homes as well as in public places such as restaurants
and sports bars. By MADELEINE HAMM.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-THIRDEYE (Undated) _ Third Eye Blind's breakthrough hit
was called ``Semi-Charmed Life.'' Given the double-platinum success
of the band's self-titled 1997 debut album, ``Totally Charmed''
might be more like it. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-ROBIN-WILLIAMS (Undated) _ Robin Williams dies in the
first few minutes of ``What Dreams May Come.'' But as the movie's
tag line proclaims, the end is just the beginning. For this is a
movie that proclaims that there is a life beyond death, and that
some great loves never die. By LOUIS PARKS.
</P>
