<P>
   ADOPT _ ATLANTA _ Beda Warrick grew up in a Jewish home, even
though she's a blueblood who now knows her ancestors came over the
Mayflower. The 46-year-old Atlanta woman spent years searching for
the birthparents who had surrendered her for adoption. Now she's
helping others in her situation by promoting RegDay (Saturday),
short for International Soundex Reunion Registry Day, which draws
attention to a free, mutual consent registry in Nevada that matches
up blood relatives who have been separated by adoption or divorce.
Locally, RegDay boosters will be promoting the event at stores, on
the radio, TV, etc. WITH PHOTO. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-CHARLESTON _ CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Gardening is simple if
you remember one thing, says Felder Rushing. ``This ain't England,
Texas or Kansas. It's the South,'' says the Mississippi Extension
agent in his down-home drawl. Yet Southern gardeners insist on
making a rewarding hobby a dreaded chore by trying to grow things
that will never make it in this climate. Rushing, the co-author of
the best-selling ``Passalong Plants,'' may be preaching to the
choir but he had a captive audience Thursday in Charleston, where
gardening is second only to history among residents. He's among the
featured speakers for the Southeast's largest fall gartdening
event, the Charleston Garden Festival, which continues through
Sunday. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NURTURE _ As a psychology grad student, Judith Harris was kicked
out of Harvard because her work wasn't considered ``original.''
This fall Harris published a book, ``The Nurture Assumption,'' that
was original enough to turn psychology on its head, essentially
declaring that parents have little to no impact on their children's
personalities, after their genetic contribution. All those
goodnight stories, flash cards, and educational toys: wasted.
Harris, the outsider who stormed the gates of psychology, doesn't
have a degree, doesn't even have a school and has no expensive
experimental data: she based all her work on published studies. She
could have based them on her own life. Her two daughters, one
biological, one adopted, turned out radically different from each
other, though both were raised in the same home. We travel to her
Middletown, N.J., house, where she must spend almost all her time
due to lupus, to profile her. (Emerson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NURTURE-HISTORY _ Thumbnail history of what parents have been
told about raising kids over the past 100 years. (Emerson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
