<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nashville book fest draws South's brightest
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Southern Festival of Books was launched 10 years ago in
Nashville, even some of the founders wondered about its future.
Nashville, after all, has always been more famous for country music
than literature.
</P>
<P>
   The festival not only has survived, though, it has flourished.
This year's event, scheduled Oct. 9-11 at Nashville's War Memorial
Plaza, features some of the best and brightest stars in the
literary field. Among the more than 200 authors participating are
Kaye Gibbons, Lee Smith, Terry Kay, Jay McInerney, Jill McCorkle,
Kinky Friedman, Tony Horwitz, Wendell Berry and Clyde Edgerton.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will feature panel discussions on mystery writing,
country music, poetry and the Civil War, as well as readings and
book signings. A variety of national and regional publishers and
book sellers will have exhibits set up on the plaza. In addition,
Brian Lamb's C-SPAN will televise live from the exhibit area Oct.
10-11.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is free and open to the public. Information:
615-320-7001 or at http://www.tn
</P>
<P>
   -humanities.org on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY MATTERS: Novels about women's friendships are as hot as
memoirs these days. Rebecca Wells' best-selling novel, ``Divine
Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood'' (HarperCollins, $14), the story
of a daughter's relationship with her mother and her mother's
friends (the Ya-Yas), has become a cult classic. Inspired by the
book, dozens of Ya-Ya groups have sprung up around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now Susan Kelly, a North Carolina native and former Atlantan,
mines some of the same territory in ``How Close We Come'' (Warner,
$20), a novel about the friendship between two women. The main
characters, Pril Henderson and Ruth Campbell, are neighbors who
share tools, recipes and secrets they don't even tell their
husbands. When Ruth leaves for a skiing vacation with her children
and never returns, Pril is angry that her friend did not tell her
of her plans. Later, when she is named as a witness in a custody
suit filed by Ruth's husband, she is faced with a decision to
testify against Ruth or to stand behind the friend who shattered
her own family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hung around women all my life,'' says Kelly, who grew up
with three sisters and attended an all-girls school. ``I talk to
them every day. The stories in the book are theirs as well as
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 44, who worked as a paralegal in Atlanta in the late
1970s, was a budding writer as a child, but she didn't begin
writing seriously until she was 35 and the mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   After writing two unpublished novels, Kelly entered ``How Close
We Come'' in a contest sponsored by Banks Channel Books in
Wilmington, N.C. The manuscript won first place and was published
by the small press. Warner Books noticed the good review in
Publishers Weekly and bought the option to reissue the novel to a
wider audience this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kelly has been contacted about a possible movie deal
and the University of North Carolina at Greensboro is using the
novel in a graduate course in women's studies. The author is happy
her book is being used, but she's just not sure about some of the
terminology being applied to her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women that I know don't fling around words like `patriarchal
structure,''' she says, laughing. ``They just know they're mad.''
</P>
<P>
   OFF THE ROAD: If Alice Walker meant what she said in a Ms.
magazine interview, next Monday's reading at Emory University may
be one of the last chances we will have to hear her. ``I'm not
going to do any more lectures or readings beyond the ones I've
already agreed to,'' says Walker. The Pulitzer Prize-winning author
of ``The Color Purple'' will be in town to read from her new novel,
``By the Light of My Father's Smile'' (Random House, $22.95).
Walker says the novel presents ``a celebration of sexuality, its
absolute usefulness in the accessing of one's mature spirituality,
and the father's role in assuring joy or sorrow in this arena for
his female children.'' The father in the novel finds his
15-year-old daughter Magdalena having sex with a loyal boy. He
beats her in a scene witnessed by her sister, Susannah, and while
both daughters are wounded by the beating, it is Magdalena who
remains scarred.
</P>
<P>
   Walker will read from her novel at 7 p.m. Monday at Glenn
Memorial Auditorium, 1652 North Decatur Road. General admission is
$20. Information: 404-727-8425.
</P>
<P>
   KING BOOKS: As part of its multimillion-dollar publishing deal
with the Martin Luther King Center, Warner Books will issue ``The
Autobiography of Martin Luther King Jr.'' in November. Edited by
King scholar Clayborne Carson, the book is compiled from a variety
of documents _ some never before available to scholars _ and is
written as if King is the narrator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
