<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PAPERBACKS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New hero emerges in Mosley stories
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Mosley, best known for his Easy Rawlins series, has
outdone himself with ``Always Outnumbered, Always Outgunned''
(Washington Square, $14). The connected stories introduce Socrates
Fortlow, who moves to Watts after serving 27 years in prison for
murder and rape. The book is ``ultimately the picture of a black
community struggling to take on the challenge of finding its own
better life,'' the Los Angeles Times said.
</P>
<P>
   For a lighter look at life, try ``Lightning Song'' by Lewis
Nordan (Algonquin, $10.95). Leroy Dearman, 12, lives on a llama
farm in the South, surrounded by eccentric family members. (Uncle
Harris sets up a bachelor pad in the attic.) Self magazine called
the novel ```Portnoy's Complaint' set ... in Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil War and baseball addicts should check out ``Play for a
Kingdom'' by Thomas Dyja (Harcourt Brace, $14). A Union and a
Confederate company meet for a series of baseball games played
during the Battle of Spotsylvania. The Christian Science Monitor
said Dyja ``realistically encompasses two pillars of American
history and culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers also praised ``The Wind-up Bird Chronicle'' by
Japanese novelist Haruki Murakami (Vintage, $14). In Tokyo, a young
man searches for his wife's missing cat and finds himself looking
for his wife, too. He encounters a bizarre cast of characters as he
looks. The New York Observer found the novel ``a stunning work of
art.''
</P>
<P>
   Another international work, ``Panther in the Basement'' by Amos
Oz (Harcourt Brace, $11), takes place in 1947 in Palestine. Proffi,
12, becomes the friend of a kindly British soldier, though his
father dreams of dying in battle for the creation of a Jewish
state. Our AJC reviewer called it ``a fetching meditation on
treachery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reader'' by Bernard Schlink (Vintage, $11), an
international best seller, was published in this country last year.
In postwar Germany, young Michael Berg is helped by a woman twice
his age, who in time becomes his lover.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund White concludes his trilogy that began with ``A Boy's Own
Story'' and ``The Beautiful Room Is Empty'' with ``The Farewell
Symphony'' (Vintage, $14). As the narrator mourns his lover's death
from AIDS, he leads the reader through 30 years of memories.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Owl Books has published two volumes of short stories by
Harold Brodkey. ``First Love and Other Sorrows'' ($14) originally
appeared in 1958, but this edition includes three
never-before-collected stories. ``The World Is the Home of Love and
Death'' ($15) is Brodkey's final volume, assembled in the weeks
before he died in 1996. The New York Times Book Review noted that
``Brodkey captured the inner poetry of consciousness, the outer
music of the spoken voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential reads
</P>
<P>
   ``Living Faith'' by former President Jimmy Carter (Times, $13)
was a New York Times best seller for good reason. As Publishers
Weekly noted, it's ``an enjoyable look into the life of a man
engaged in living out his faith in the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics are at the forefront in ``Abuse of Power: The New Nixon
Tapes'' edited by Stanley I. Kutler (Touchstone, $17), detailing
201 hours of Watergate-era recordings from June 1971 through July
1973. The Los Angeles Times said this is ``Nixon raw, in his own
words, a president unmasked.'' Just as revealing is ``Mutual
Contempt: Lyndon Johnson, Robert Kennedy and the Feud That Defined
a Decade'' by Jeff Shesol (Norton, $17.95). Shesol details the
historic clash that shaped federal policy and shattered the
Democratic Party in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
