<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUTURE-COX     10-01 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A grandmother attacks long-held beliefs about child rearing and
sets psychology on its ear
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, N.J._Rear your own children. Or let strangers do it
for you. The little creatures will grow up the same, either way.
</P>
<P>
   Or so says a new book that has set psychology on its ear. Pretty
much all your efforts to instill family values or make your kid
succeed in school are a waste of time, says ``The Nurture
Assumption: Why Children Turn Out the Way They Do'' (Free Press,
$26).
</P>
<P>
   Children, we are told, are shaped by biology and their peers.
``Parenting matters zilch,'' author Judith Rich Harris declares in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Published in September, Harris' pugnacious theory has landed
like a hand grenade in the foxhole of family-obsessed America. Now
she's watching with glee as parents and the parenting industry
scramble to throw it back.
</P>
<P>
   Though endorsed by powerful names in the field, including MIT
professor Steven Pinker, Harris' view has drawn protest from
professionals and soccer moms alike. Writing in The Boston Globe,
Harvard psychologist Jerome Kagan said Harris' book ignores
important facts and is, perhaps, a sop to a generation too
self-centered to care for its children.
</P>
<P>
   Her message surely will appeal to two-career yuppies with busy
social lives, the folks who invented the concept of ``quality
time.'' Harris states blandly that there is no appreciable
difference between children raised in day care and children with
24-hour-a-day moms.
</P>
<P>
   Portrayed by critics as a monster who has given us permission to
abandon our children, Judith Harris looks rather meek. She's a
graying, sparrow-sized 60-year-old grandmother, just shy of 5 feet
tall, about 98 pounds of wit, grit and oversized spectacles. On a
recent sunny morning Harris could be found padding around her tidy
home in the prosperous South Jersey hamlet of Middletown, petting
her sheltie-collie, Page, and brewing coffee for her late-sleeping
husband, Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   This is the semi-agricultural end of New Jersey, where horse
farms are being carved into subdivisions of million-dollar homes.
Suffering from poor health, Harris rarely ventures out of her
modest, aluminum-sided cottage, but phone calls and e-mail let her
know the ruckus she's raised.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, words like ``zilch'' get people excited, she concedes
with a smile. She admits to presenting an ``extreme case'' and, of
those who accuse her of being purposefully provocative, she says
``they may be right.'' But, she adds, ``I believe the case I'm
making is defensible.''
</P>
<P>
   After chatting for more than an hour in her kitchen, she excuses
herself to answer a few calls and returns flushed with good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston Globe is going to give me 1,000 words!'' she says,
gasping with excitement. This will give her a chance to defend her
theory against Kagan and others, in particular those who accuse her
of saying ``parents don't matter.'' Harris says heatedly that
children obviously wouldn't survive without parents and that
parents should treat their children well, regardless of the
outcome, simply out of common human decency.
</P>
<P>
   Though she cries that her theory has been misunderstood, she's
obviously tickled by the attention, even the negative attention.
``People always feel strongly when you threaten their cherished
beliefs,'' she says, sipping filtered water at her Formica-topped
kitchen table. Neither Galileo nor Darwin, she points out, was
received with shouts of joy.
</P>
<P>
   Galileo and Darwin _ that's fancy company to be keeping. But,
says Pinker, who wrote the seminal ``How the Mind Works,'' Harris
belongs among the revolutionaries. Her book, he writes in the
foreword, ``will be seen as a turning point in the history of
psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   If Harris' theory truly is a breakthrough, it could not have
come from a more curious source. Harris was kicked out of Harvard's
psychology graduate program in 1960 because, according to acting
Chairman George A. Miller, her work didn't look like it would
amount to much.
</P>
<P>
   Bedridden with a mysterious lupuslike disease while researching
her book, Harris left the house only to collect books from the
Middletown library. She wrote sitting in bed, with a pen and a
spiral notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Her work goes to the very core of how Westerners have come to
view children in the 20th century: She accepts the notion that both
genetics and life experiences (''nature and nurture'') shape
children's personality. But she attacks what she calls ``the
nurture assumption,'' which she traces to Sigmund Freud: the
accepted tenet that parents are the most important environmental
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Harris proposes that the most significant environmental
influence comes from outside the home, in the playgrounds and the
schoolrooms and the places where children teach each other how to
live. Her work ties together phenomena that argue against parental
influence _ evidence that twins reared together are no more alike
than those reared apart, for example, and that the children of
immigrants end up speaking the language of their peers, not their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Harris first presented her ``group socialization theory'' (her
term for the way peer groups shape most of our significant
personality traits) in a 1995 article published in the journal
Psychological Review. Two years later her paper won a prestigious
prize, the George A. Miller Award, named for the man who had kicked
her out of school.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the award, the response from academia was thundering
silence, she says. Because she was a nobody, with no university
affiliation, no experimental evidence, no Ph.D., she wasn't taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   That reaction prompted Harris to go over the heads of the
academics and write a book for a general readership.
</P>
<P>
   Her outsider status also made it possible for Harris to ignore
conventional psychological wisdom and hatch her theory in the first
place, she says. ``I was not required to perpetuate the status quo
by teaching the received gospel to a bunch of credulous college
students.''
</P>
<P>
   If she wanted evidence that parental influence is overrated, she
didn't have to look far. She is the mother of two daughters. Her
biological child, Nomi, excelled in her studies and was easy to get
along with. Elaine, adopted after Nomi was born, rebelled against
her parents, took up smoking, hung with a rough crowd and dropped
out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   Same family environment, different outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   The girls had different biological parents, but the girls' story
speaks to more than just the power of genetics. Today, both girls
are leading successful lives. Nomi earned a master's in computer
science at MIT, and the once-troubled Elaine is a happily married
mother, a practicing nurse and a CPR instructor.
</P>
<P>
   The tale is meant to reassure parents, says Harris. Don't worry
so much, because your children are beyond your control. The
pressure she put on Elaine to reform ``actually caused quite a bit
of ill feeling and it didn't do any good in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea even Harris has had a hard time accepting, as
Elaine confirms: She likes the offer from The Boston Globe because
it gives her a chance to state her theory in her own words. The
payment is not important.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean they pay you for that sort of thing?'' she asks,
ingenuously. ``I'm not interested in clothing or jewelry, I don't
smoke or drink, I can't travel. I'm perfectly happy with my life
the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   What she wants is to push psychology into new avenues. And to
give parents a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted parents to feel less guilty, less pressured, less
obsessed with the idea that they might make a mistake,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of her book, she writes, parents have been sold a
bill of goods, and they can accept neither the credit nor the blame
for the kind of adults their children turn into.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we can make our children turn out any way we
want is an illusion. Give it up. Children are not empty canvases on
which parents can paint their dreams,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not yours to perfect or ruin: They belong to
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
