<SLUG> BC-BURKINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confronting obstacles to Africa's renewal
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he visited Africa in April, President Clinton spoke of an
``African renaissance.'' Yet economic hardship, famine and war
still afflict the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Blaise Compaore, the president of Burkina Faso and
chairman of the Organization of African Unity, visited Atlanta to
brief former President Jimmy Carter on a range of African issues.
The next day, he sat down with Cox writer Don Melvin. Here are
excerpts of that conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Earlier this year, President Clinton made a high-profile
visit to Africa, and there were questions raised as to whether it
heralded a new era in U.S. policy toward Africa or was merely a
grand photo opportunity. What does the evidence suggest so far?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is no doubt that, through discussions President Clinton
had with African heads of state and through the message he
delivered, we are experiencing a new era in the relations between
the U.S. and Africa. The United States is prepared to assist Africa
in terms of infrastructure development. Another element is that the
United States is prepared to open its markets to African products.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are a number of places in Africa where the per capita
income is less than it was 20 or 30 years ago. What is the primary
cause of that, and what are the main remedies?
</P>
<P>
   A: Essentially this is due to bad organization of international
trade, which has not always been in favor of African countries,
which have been selling primary products. There has been a fall in
the prices of primary products as compared with the soaring prices
of manufactured goods that those African countries imported.
</P>
<P>
   The second element which could explain this is the bad
governance, which did not help economic development.
</P>
<P>
   We need a stable political environment, which encourages private
investment. Regarding the international community, what is needed
most is the opening of developed markets to African products.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently returned from a trip to report on the famine in
southern Sudan. The aid workers said the international community
cannot maintain its level of effort indefinitely, and that without
some resolution of the civil war in Sudan, these problems will
occur again and again. Are there steps that the international
community can take to press the parties in Sudan to reach a
permanent political solution?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is true that without peace, we will still be watching the
tragedy of famine and death in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is in a position to exert pressure on both
parties so that they engage in a dialogue towards a political
solution to the crisis. Such political solution should be based on
the need to recognize full citizenship to all the Sudanese people,
to work towards greater participation of all Sudanese regions in
the management of public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you favor an independent investigation into the nature of
the factory that was bombed in Khartoum by the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: We are small countries, and the United States is a powerful
country with bombs and fighter planes and a whole military arsenal.
Our concern is that one day we might be bombed without knowing the
reason why. The victims of the bombing have a right to know why the
bombing took place. This will not only be in the interest of
America; it will also be in the interest of African countries. If
Sudan is proved to be producing chemical weapons, this will not be
a matter of insecurity for the United States alone. It will be for
us, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you favor lifting of the sanctions against Libya? Do you
disagree with the U.S. contention that Libya has been a sponsor of
terrorism?
</P>
<P>
   A: Now we are referring to a given case: This is the Lockerbie
bombing. We are in full agreement with the United States when they
want to find those who are behind such bombings so that they face
international sanctions. But this should be done through a balanced
and transparent trial which will clearly establish who is
responsible for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have (U.N.) Resolution 1192, which provides for a trial
in the Netherlands, and we think that this will lead the
international community to understand that there are avenues to
combat international terrorism on the basis of the rule of law. The
terrorists act outside the law; those who want to enforce the law
should not follow the same course as the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And therefore sanctions should be lifted in advance of the
trial?
</P>
<P>
   A: We requested that there should be no sanctions before the
trial actually takes place, and this is based on simple logic. Let
us imagine that the trial takes place and the Libyans are found not
to be guilty. How will we offset the consequences of the sanctions?
If there is no trial there should be no sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the likelihood that the situation in Congo could
involve a war outside the borders of Congo?
</P>
<P>
   A: The war already involves Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola. If the
war is protracted, there are possibilities that the war might spill
over on the basis of political interests or ethnic interests.
That's why we feel that the international community should do its
utmost to bring the various parties to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a significant Nigerian community in Atlanta. How
great is your confidence that Gen. Abubakar will hold free and fair
elections in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   A: President Abubakar inherited a very difficult political
situation. But from what I know of him, I'm convinced that he has a
firm will to lead Nigeria to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
