<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $9 million effort to wipe out Guinea worm
 &HT;    By Keith Graham and Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Carter Center in Atlanta is making a final assault on Guinea
worm disease with some hefty fiscal backing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the center announced that a record-breaking
total of more than $9 million was committed for the Guinea worm
eradication program in the 1998 fiscal year. Among key donors are
the World Bank, American Home Products Corp. and governments of
Japan, Norway, the United Kingdom and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their generosity and a lot of hard work by people in
remote villages, we hope that Guinea worm will be eliminated
everywhere in the world outside of Sudan by the end of 2000,''
former President Carter said in a statement. ``Then we will focus
on Sudan and making Guinea worm only the second disease in history
to be eradicated.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, when the Carter Center became involved in the
eradication effort, more than 3.2 million cases of Guinea worm
disease were reported and more than 100 million people were at
risk, mostly in 16 African countries, Yemen and India. Today _
thanks largely to the Carter Center's leadership of a global
eradication coalition _ most of the 150,000 cases remaining are in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Voice of a Georgian
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia State University professor, Dr. Nack An, has begun a
weekly stint fielding questions on American politics from around
the world during a live call-in show on the Voice of America radio
network. VOA broadcasts international, regional and U.S. news and
programming in 52 languages. The show in which An participates
transmits in the Korean language Wednesday mornings and generates
calls from Korea, China and Russia. The main topic on callers'
minds of late? The Clinton investigation. An, a professor in GSU's
Department of Political Science, says most callers want to know
about the likelihood of an impeachment and details on the process
of removing an American president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Latest developments
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Center will host a public forum on development in
South Asia from 6 to 8 p.m. Oct. 8 at Emory University(Ga.)'s Cox
Hall. The event follows a round-table discussion at the center,
where leaders of nongovernmental organizations will discuss shared
social challenges facing South Asia and the United States.
Participants in the public forum will include Ashok Row Kavi of the
Humsafar Trust of India, Abdul Hay Khan of the Grameen Bank of
Bangladesh, Noor-un-Nisa Ghanghro of the World Wildlife Fund
Pakistan, and Vinya Ariyaratne of the Sarvodaya Shramadana Movement
in Sri Lanka. The forum is free but registration is required. Call:
404-420-5188.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
