<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUTURE-HISTORY-COX     10-01 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTURE-HISTORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harris follows Spock, not Freud
 &HT;    By Eric Sundquist
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judith Rich Harris' message for parents, that they should stop
worrying so much about doing just the right thing, has a
back-to-the-future ring. A century ago there were no degreed
experts, aside from the family doctor or clergyman, to spell out
the ``right way'' to raise children.
</P>
<P>
   The modern view of child development begins with Sigmund Freud.
An Austrian who laid the groundwork for modern psychiatry in the
late 19th and early 20th centuries, Freud thought parents played a
central role in shaping kids' minds. When treating patients,
Freudian therapists traced mental illnesses to relationships with
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Later, American B.F. Skinner and other ``behaviorists'' argued
that children learn through rewards and punishments. If parents
reward a child for an action, the child would repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Such thought remained largely academic until after World War II,
when psychological theories began to be translated into parenting
manuals. The best of these, Dr. Benjamin Spock's ``The Common Sense
Book of Baby and Child Care,'' has sold 46 million copies since its
1948 debut.
</P>
<P>
   Before he died this year, Spock told USA Today that the advice
industry had grown too influential. Parents in the '90s, he said,
``buy more books, or go to more lectures, or read columns about
child-rearing, and are very easily intimidated by these things.
Half the articles I've written say don't be afraid of doing the
wrong thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris takes that message further. Parents shouldn't worry, she
says, because genes and peers outweigh whatever personality-shaping
they may try anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUTURE-THEORY-COX     10-01 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTURE-THEORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harris: Peers affect kids more than Mom or Dad
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judith Rich Harris' ``The Nurture Assumption'' carries a second
subtitle, ``Parents Matter Less Than You Think and Peers Matter
More.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, Harris intends to redirect the attention of
psychology from the grown-ups who birthed us to the peers who gave
us noogies on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   Harris points out that much research purporting to show the
impact of parenting on personality fails to filter out the effects
of genes. The research shows that parents who read to their
children raise children who love to read. But did the kids get
their verbal skills from cozy bedtime stories or from their DNA?
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from primate studies, anthropology, social psychology
and behavioral genetics, Harris presents a case for influences
outside the family.
</P>
<P>
   One assumes parents teach their children to speak, but the
evidence indicates otherwise. Many deaf parents have no verbal
signals to impart, yet their children grow up speaking normally.
They acquire language from their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Another example: The best predictor of teen smoking is whether
the teen's friends smoke, not whether the teen's parents smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Harris discusses the tendency of humans and other primates to
break into warring groups. It is through identification with the
group, not the family, that adult personality emerges, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Can parents have any impact? Some.
</P>
<P>
   First, says Harris, make sure you live in a nice neighborhood.
Children of single parents are no more likely to drop out of school
or get pregnant than the children of two-parent households, she
writes, as long as they stay in the same middle-class
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   A high-status position in a peer group can also be a boost, she
says. You can help your children make a good impression by making
them as ``normal'' as possible, buying them nice clothes,
orthodontia and even plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Group socialization'' knocks the parenting industry into a
cocked hat. Why should parents listen to Dr. Spock or Dr. Laura if
children aren't listening to parents? Accepting Harris' theory
means tossing out Zany Brainy's educational mobiles and Gov. Zell
Miller's classical music CDs. It means that sending children to day
care isn't a bad thing after all.
</P>
<P>
   Though the family-minded accuse her of throwing the parent out
with the bath water, even some critical psychologists credit Harris
with sparking a needed debate.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kindermann, developmental psychologist at Portland State
University in Oregon, thinks parents have more power than Harris
grants. But ``to focus the emphasis on peers is not a bad idea,''
he adds. ``They've been neglected across the last hundred years of
psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris says others have questioned the primacy of the family,
but they've been ignored. So her own book has an intentionally
strident tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have presented an extreme case to clarify the issues,'' she
says. ``Nobody pays attention to you if you're wishy-washy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
