<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3906 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-ADULTERY-NYTS     10-01 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-ADULTERY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW COMMON IS ADULTERY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    David Letterman put the issue lightly but bluntly: ''Come on,
haven't we all had sex with an employee young enough to be our
daughter and lied about it under oath?''
 &HT;    No.
 &HT;    The best studies on American adultery have been conducted by the
National Opinion Research Center (NORC) of the University of
Chicago. It asked this question: ''Have you ever had sexual
intercourse with someone other than your spouse when you were
married?''
 &HT;    The response: 2 percent of women and 5 percent of men said they
had committed adultery within the last year. The cumulative
adultery rate of those who had ever been married was only 12
percent for women and 21.5 percent for men.
 &HT;    I mentioned these numbers to Dr. Shirley Glass, a therapist in
Baltimore who has written extensively on adultery, and she
dismissed them. She cited a study she made 18 years ago of 300
adults interviewed at Baltimore and Washington airports which
revealed 26 percent of women and 44 percent of men had violated the
commandment, ''Thou shalt not commit adultery.''
 &HT;    She questioned the NORC's methodology: ''They interview people
in their homes. They were not alone. Other members of the family
were present. There was no anonymity. They asked them a few
questions, and then asked if they have had sex outside their
marriage.''
 &HT;    Not so, says Dr. Tom Smith of the National Opinion Research
Center.''These questions come at the end of a long survey, the
General Social Survey, that has nothing to do with adultery. At the
end of the interview, people are asked to fill out a
self-completion form in private and put it in a sealed envelope.
 &HT;    ``They are not asked out loud to reveal sexual behavior. This
method is shown to have to highest level of frank and honest
answers. The rationale is that these questions are asked to help
health officials deal with sexually transmitted diseases.''
 &HT;    Second, NORC's estimates are based on an average of polls taken
in 1991, 1993, 1994 and 1996 and one not yet released. No other
analysis is as current or comprehensive.
 &HT;    However, Smith acknowledges that ''even under these
circumstances, not all will admit to a behavior they think is
undesirable, so there is some under-reporting.''
 &HT;    But the faithful outnumber the cheaters by a wide margin.
 &HT;    Dr. Glass asked, ''If in any one year, only 2 percent have sex,
why not multiply that times 30 years of marriage?'' Smith responds:
Much adultery is chronic, the same cheaters year after year.
 &HT;    The percentage of Americans who believe adultery is ''always
wrong'' is very high -- 78 to 80 percent. And this number has grown
from 70-72 percent in the 1970s, according to Smith, due to AIDS.
 &HT;    The base number is high because adultery ''is on the short list
of `Thou shalt nots.' Many Americans first learn that adultery is
something you should not do in Sunday School at ages 4 or 5, before
they have any idea of what sex or adultery is,'' Smith said.
 &HT;    Why then are so many willing to forgive Bill Clinton? Americans
say divorce is wrong, but most also say that it is a matter between
the husband and wife. It is up to them to work it out. ''The public
also distinguishes between job performance vs. personal behavior or
morality,'' Smith said.
 &HT;    Certainly, among some men, infidelity is more common. Famous men
seem to attract the Monica Lewinskys -- politicians, movie stars,
sports figures. Others have more opportunities and temptations,
such as airline pilots.
 &HT;    I asked Dick Tennies, an American Airlines pilot, to describe
the situation. ''Twenty years ago, I determined that 50 to 70
percent of pilots were not on their first marriage, and their
second wife or girlfriend was an employee of the airline. Now, with
the AIDS scare, fewer are as promiscuous.''
 &HT;    His wife, Alice, is often asked, ''Are you a flight attendant?''
Her response is, ``No, I'm his first wife!''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
