<HEADER>
A3919 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PRIMER-$ADV04-     10-01 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRIMER-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A PRIMER ON THE YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO SITUATION
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV04.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOME KEY CITIES IN AND AROUND THE KOSOVO REGION (For map
purposes)
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   Pristina
</P>
<P>
   Dakodica
</P>
<P>
   Pec
</P>
<P>
   Titova
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia:
</P>
<P>
   Skopje
</P>
<P>
   Albania:
</P>
<P>
   Tirana
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Belgrade
</P>
<P>
   Population: 10.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 39,449 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Summary: The country now consists of Serbia and Montenegro, the
remnants of the former Yugoslav federation governed by Marshal Tito
until his death in 1980. At his death, the federation began to
dissolve, and by 1991 Croatia and Slovenia declared their
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Serbs supported by Serbia entered into an armed struggle
to seize territory in Croatia, and at one point the Serbs occupied
a third of the country. In Bosnia, ethnic Serbs fought a fierce
battle against the country's move toward independence. Serb forces
massacred thousands of Bosnian Muslims and engaged in ``ethnic
cleansing'' -- expelling non-Serbs from areas under Bosnian Serb
control, which extended over as much as 70 percent of the country.
After Serbian aggressions won world condemnation, the United
Nations in 1992 imposed sanctions on Yugoslavia and massive air
strikes on Bosnia Serb targets to end the bloodshed. In 1995, the
Dayton Peace Accord brought an end to the conflict and was signed
by leaders of Serbia, Bosnia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Yugoslavian officials say their campaign to eradicate
the armed separatist movement is justified because the country has
the right to put down an insurrection in its own borders. They
describe the situation as analogous to the British government's
long struggle against the Irish Republican Army, which sought to
end British rule over Northern Ireland. The officials say the
civilian casualties and accounts of atrocities have been
exaggerated by ethnic Albanians to gain the sympathy of the West.
They also assert that the number of refugees created by the
conflict has been inflated by humanitarian aid groups.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2 million
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Pristina
</P>
<P>
   Area: 4,203 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Situation: A province of Serbia. Kosovo's population is mostly
ethnic Albanian -- 90 percent according to most accounts but less
according to Yugoslavian officials. The Serb minority is the
remnant of the medieval Serb Empire centered in Kosovo, which
retains monasteries and Orthodox monuments. Christian Serbs see
mostly Muslim Kosovo as their spiritual heartland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1389, Turkish forces of the Ottoman Empire defeated the Serbs
at Kosovo Polje (''Field of the Blackbirds'') causing the collapse
of Serbia, a battle that is viewed with reverence by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Most ethnic Albanians favor some measure of independence from
Yugoslavia, and the struggle against Serb rule has persisted for
decades. The conflict has been marked by a cycle of repression by
Serb authorities followed by ethnic Albanian resistance and now
guerrilla -- some say, terrorist -- warfare. Over the past several
months, more than 300,000 people have left their homes to escape
the conflict between Serb security forces and the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA), the rebel group seeking independence.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 ethnic Albanians are thought to be permanently
homeless and face severe threats as the harsh winter approaches,
according to relief organizations. The United States has expressed
great concern about the plight of the refugees and is advocating
the use of military force, if necessary, to halt the fighting. The
Clinton Administration favors autonomy for Kosovo, but not
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Tirana
</P>
<P>
   Population: 3.3 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 11,100 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Situation: Formerly allied with the Soviet Union, the Communists
were rejected by voters in 1992. Since then, the country has
endured economic stagnation and political unrest amid periods of
near anarchy. In September, unidentified gunmen assassinated Azem
Hajdari, a leader and member of parliament from the opposition
Democratic Party. Two weeks of rioting ensued and on Monday, Prime
Minister Fatos Nano resigned after failing to form a stable
government from his shaky five-party coalition. Nano's arch-rival
and former president Sali Berisha blamed him for the killing. Nano,
a moderate on Kosovo, became prime minister last year after his
party -- made up largely of ex-Communists -- defeated Berisha's
Democrats in parliamentary elections. The ruling Socialist Party
has nominated its 30-year-old secretary, Pandeli Majko to replace
Nano.
</P>
<P>
   Nano did not favor independence for Kosovo, and the country has
been officially neutral.
</P>
<P>
   MACEDONIA
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Skopje
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 9,781 Square miles
</P>
<P>
   Situation: A former republic of Yugoslavia, the country declared
its independence in 1991 -- and in 1996, normalized relations with
Yugoslavia. With the presence of a large ethnic Albanian population
-- which represents about 23 percent of the Macedonian people --
diplomatic officials worry the conflict in Kosovo could spill over
the border and destabilize an already unsteady government.
Consequently, the United Nations has a security force in Macedonia
to attempt to maintain stability at least for the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Internally, the country is already strained by a conflict
between Slavic Macedonians, who represent about two-thirds of the
population, and ethnic Albanians. There are also concerns that the
Macedonian army, which is 25 percent Albanian, would hold together
in a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
