</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PLAYERS-$ADV04     10-01 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PLAYERS-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KEY PLAYERS IN THE YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO SITUATION
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV04.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY (KLA)
</P>
<P>
   Spearheading a seven-month insurgency against the Serb military.
The KLA has claimed to have 50,000 fighters but more generally
thought to number about 15,000. The modestly trained and armed
group has surprised political leaders by its success. In July, the
KLA claimed possession of about 40 percent of Kosovo, even though
the Yugoslavian government denies the organization's holdings were
ever so large. The leadership of the group is shadowy -- barely
known even among ethnic Albanians -- and consequently, the KLA has
been a challenge for United Nations and NATO negotiators who find
it difficult to meet with anyone in authority.
</P>
<P>
   SLOBODAN MILOSEVIC
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian president since 1987. He seized power by exhorting
Serbs to rise up against perceived past injustices and create a
Greater Serbia. He is seen by many in the West as the man most
responsible for the descent of the Balkans into years of warfare.
He is blamed for the attempt at ``ethnic cleansing'' of non-Serbs
in Croatia and Bosnia. Under his government, Serbia was the main
supplier of arms to ethnic Serb fighters in Bosnia and Herzegovina,
but Milosevic has denied any involvement in the atrocities that
were reported in those conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   IBRAHIM RUGOVA
</P>
<P>
   The most recognized leader of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
Rugova has supported proposals to keep Kosovo within Yugoslavia,
but as a self-governing region. Often viewed as a pacifist, he has
called for passive resistance to Serb authority. Even though he
remains popular with the masses and commands moral authority,
Rugova's leadership nevertheless has been rejected by militants in
the Kosovo Liberation Army. While the West tends to consult with
Rugova, diplomats are frustrated because he seems to have no
influence over the warring factions.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
