<SLUG> BC-PEANUT-WARNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEANUT CAPITAL' FEARS MARKET CRUNCH AS ALLERGY SCARE SPREADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JESSE CLEMENTS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORESVILLE, Texas _ A 4-foot concrete peanut in the center of
town declares this South Texas agricultural community the ``Peanut
Capital of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing peanut allergy movement, however, has left planners of
the 54th annual Floresville Peanut Festival shell-shocked _ and
worried about what it could do to business.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the U.S. Department of Transportation directed
airlines to set aside ``peanut-free buffer zones'' for passengers
who suffer from allergic reactions to peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   And schools in the Midwest and New York have told students to
leave that staple of school diets _ the peanut butter sandwich _ at
home. Some schools have removed peanut candy from vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this airlines deal is just the latest effort by those
yahoos in Congress to put all farmers out of business,'' said
Vaughn Yeager, whose family has been growing peanuts on the same
690-acre farm for three generations.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is viewed with alarm here and elsewhere in Texas
where the goobers _ as peanuts are called here _ are a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300,000 acres of peanuts are planted statewide, and they
account for about $200 million in annual income. Texas ranks second
nationally in the production of peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of those who are sensitive to peanuts has all but
overshadowed recent planning sessions for the Floresville Peanut
Festival, which runs Oct. 8-10 in this town of 5,000 people
southeast of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Estrada, who has been in the peanut business since 1946, and
is this year's festival parade marshal, said he thought the concern
about allergies had been blown all out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are some people somewhere who suffer from this
allergy, but I just think this is an overreaction,'' Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
   At several recent meetings of peanut growers, the allergy issue
has been widely discussed, Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Association President Gloria Martinez confirmed the
subject was a hot topic.
</P>
<P>
   The federal order requires airlines to set aside at least three
rows where no peanuts can be served, whenever they receive an
advance request from a passenger with a medically documented peanut
allergy.
</P>
<P>
   Some private schools in New York City have banned peanut butter,
or established ``peanut butter-free zones.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines has made peanuts almost a part of its
corporate identity, having dispensed them free to passengers since
it began flying in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, the airline handed out 87.4 million 1-ounce
packages, Southwest spokesman Ed Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   And at one time, the Dallas-based airline even featured its
no-frills meals in advertising campaigns promoting fares for
``peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Southwest never has recorded an in-flight reaction from an
allergy sufferer, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually started peanut-free flights about five years ago
when passengers would notify us in advance of their allergy. But
the Department of Transportation has now ordered peanut-free zones
be designated in each plane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said there is no way Southwest can do that on its
planes, since the airline has open seating. But Southwest will
continue its past practice of a peanut-free flight when a passenger
suffers from the allergy and notifies the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT directive is based on a 1996 Mayo Clinic study which
found that peanut allergens can waft through airline ventilation
systems after 5,000 hours of flight.
</P>
<P>
   Allergists say an allergy to peanuts can be serious, even
life-threatening.
</P>
</TEXT>
