<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-WORMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY WORMS LAUNCH PERENNIAL OFFENSIVE IN HAPLESS TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH ALLEN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ First there was drought. Then there were floods.
Now worms are munching their way across Texas, eating pasture
grass, lawns, oats ... and football fields.
</P>
<P>
   The fall invasion of army worms, common to the South and
Southwest, was revved into high gear by heavy late-summer rains and
may not quit until the weather turns cool.
</P>
<P>
   Many pastures just recovering from drought are being devoured by
army worms, which actually are caterpillars with green and yellow
stripes that earned their name by marching steadily toward new
forage en masse. The damages are difficult to calculate, but
producers say ranchers will be hardest hit as the caterpillars dine
on fall forage.
</P>
<P>
   East of San Antonio, rancher Steve Ehrig said the army worms
stripped 600 acres of pasture in a few days; and rancher Bodey
Langford said the caterpillars munched through 75 acres of young
oats.
</P>
<P>
   Langford saw a few army worms at the edge of his oat field one
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up at 7 o'clock the next morning and they had eaten 75
of my 90 acres,'' he said. ``I never saw anything move through a
field that quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Langford estimated his damages at about $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Army worms are doing the most damage in the Coastal Bend and
East Texas, although they are reported in most Central Texas
counties, agricultural extension agents said. The weather pattern _
drought followed by late summer rains _ is similar to 1996, the
year of another army worm invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Extension agents balked at putting a dollar figure on damage
caused by the army worms' advance, saying it varies, depending on
the crop and the level of infestation, which can be patchy and
doesn't always destroy an entire field.
</P>
<P>
   The insects are expected to continue reproducing until
temperatures fall to the 50s at night.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean a long standoff for the Luling School District.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, football field caretaker Eddie Moses thought he
noticed the ground moving under the chalk he was applying for an
upcoming game.
</P>
<P>
   On closer inspection, Moses said, ``I saw a whole bunch of them
on the west end-zone area. I started looking at the street, and
they were crossing the street'' from the adjacent farm.
</P>
<P>
   School officials, trying not to mix pesticides and players, are
limited in how they can fend off the caterpillars. Moses said he
applied a dose of pesticide to the field, later watering it down.
</P>
<P>
   The worms are a serious threat to young oats and other winter
crops that haven't developed a good root system, said David Bade,
an extension specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Producers can spray pesticides on their acreage, but it's pricey
at $6 to $9 per acre, said Gonzales County extension agent Travis
Franke.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get rid of the army worm is expensive,'' Franke said. ``If
they've got ample hay, I recommend that they don't spray.''
</P>
<P>
   Extension specialists advise inspecting two to three times
weekly for army worms, which don't do as much damage when they are
small, and treating for them if as many as three insects per square
foot are detected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
