<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2012 OLYMPICS: NO-WIN SCENARIO FOR SEATTLEITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Memo to Seattle City Council: You hadda be there.
</P>
<P>
   If you were, you wouldn't want it coming here.
</P>
<P>
   Enough time has passed in the nation of the World's Shortest
Attention Spans that the mess of the 1996 Summer Olympics in
Atlanta is largely forgotten. But now that the Seattle Bid
Committee is attempting to persuade the council that it should go
for the 2012 Olympics, the experience of Atlanta needs to be
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In a word: Bleah.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the competitions themselves weren't delightful and
fascinating. Nor were the facilities less than first class. And the
thousands of volunteers were earnest and helpful. But there's
nothing all those wonderful athletes and volunteers can do about
the indisputable facts:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Summer Olympics are a gargantuan enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   -- The International Olympic Committee makes herculean demands
of the host city, yet takes no financial responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   -- Modern security requirements turn venues into virtual
garrisons.
</P>
<P>
   -- Economic forecasts and the physical consequences are almost
never what promoters claim.
</P>
<P>
   I know the fine people on the Seattle committee took many notes
about what went wrong in Atlanta, and along with the IOC and U.S.
Olympic Committee, have vowed the mistakes will not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there is no avoiding the fact that for mid-sized
cities such as Atlanta and Seattle, the scale and complexity of a
Summer Games becomes an overwhelming energy suck that warps
virtually everything else on the civic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For many Puget Sounders desperately grasping onto what is left
of the compelling reasons they remained or settled here, the
boosterism that always beats down good judgment on the way to
hosting an Olympics is anathema.
</P>
<P>
   Please, gung-ho developer types, save your letters calling me a
tree-hugging retro dweeb. Long ago I made my peace with the
inevitability of growth and change, and the need for economic
stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   An Olympics isn't the way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Boosters always cite the new sports facilities as well as the
improved infrastructure that accompany the Games. But in Atlanta,
it's not as if the legacy screams out at the visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, it's as if (the Olympics) never occurred,'' Dick
Pound, an IOC vice president, said last year. ``That's the real
tragedy for the city of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   If your impression is different, that's because you saw the
Games through the skewed filter of NBC, whose huge rights fees paid
for much of the Games. The money also allows them to tell stories
as they want, not as they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta was very fortunate that Dick Ebersol (NBC Sports
president) threatened to fire anyone who pointed a camera outside
the arenas,'' said Pound, a Canadian lawyer. ``The rest of America
had no idea how bad it was.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC didn't cover the thousands of ticketless kids from around
the world who roamed downtown, looking to party. It didn't cover
the adventure of getting through the security maze, or the
breakdowns of transportation and technology.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, the network didn't cover the financial
consquences. When the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games
(ACOG) closed its books last summer, it claimed to have broken even
on its record $1.7 billion budget, less $10 million to clean up the
last of the lawsuits. But ACOG had to auction off every last
doorknob and coat button, as well as negotiate downward numerous
contracts with the USOC and others. And the final tally didn't
include $156 million of a budget surplus that was promised as part
of Atlanta's 1990 proposal to the IOC that won the Games bid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Also unnoticed was that in order to make way for new facilities
downtown, an estimated 15,000 homeowners, tenants and small
businesses were uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta proclaimed its Olympics were the first to be completely
funded privately (not counting money spent on highways, police,
public services, etc.). But that created a tawdry spectacle of
commercialism that scarred the Games and Atlanta's image, and
provoked IOC legislation forbidding a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the only alternative is governmental subsidies,
such as was done for February's Winter Games in Nagano, Japan, as
well as the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney. On the eve of the Winter
Games, the mayor of Nagano said the final bill was going to be 20
percent more than the estimate that won the bid.
</P>
<P>
   As disturbing as are the consequences, Seattle's decision to
push for the U.S. bid probably is already done. Our congressional
delegation wants it, the downtown power brokers want it, the
high-tech crowd wants it. Nobody ever stops them.
</P>
<P>
   Those folks will begin to persuade the rest of us with TV
commercials showing smiling kids trundling from Ballard to the UW
for Olympic track or gymnastics. A local athlete will win a gold
medal, Alex Rodriguez will light the Olympic torch and ohmigawd,
who can resist?
</P>
<P>
   Just remember that the parents of those kids probably work for
Coke, Visa, Kodak, NBC or the myriad other mega-corporate sponsors
who underwrite the Games.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't think you would be offered a big-event ticket, did
you?
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
