u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SMITH-SPI     10-01 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES DISCOVER A KEEPER IN SMITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On a windy, late-December afternoon in El Paso in
1995, Josh Smith knew. He knew it was time to end this madness, to
escape the life of a football player asked to do things he couldn't
do.
</P>
<P>
   He was 250 pounds, a big human, a small defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iowa linemen were coming up to the line,'' he recalls,
``and laughing at me.''
</P>
<P>
   When that turkey of a Sun Bowl ended with Washington's 38-18
loss, Smith, who had spent two years in the program, went in to ask
coach Jim Lambright for a release from his letter of intent. That
would allow him to transfer to Portland State and receive financial
aid.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have done some creative things to patch together a
football program doubled over with the loss of 20 scholarships in
two years. They tried to recruit selectively, they beckoned
walk-ons. They got lucky with transfer receivers like Jerome Pathon
and Dane Looker.
</P>
<P>
   With Smith, they did something even more unusual. They stood in
the doorway. Lambright told him he wouldn't release him from his
letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very grateful he didn't,'' Smith says today. ``Yeah, it
ticked me off. But I'm a strong believer that these days, education
is overpriced. No way I could work, and I didn't want my parents to
pay for school for a year or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd stick it out.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times when Smith, now a senior, would have reason to
question that decision. Times like February, when he had back
surgery, and a month later when, after lying in bed for a week, he
went in for an operation on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Times like the conditioning segment of Husky drills, when Smith,
hunched and looking a lot like a 65-year-old man, lags behind his
teammates, his back killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Times like Tuesday in practice, when the defense was getting
pushed around a little too much and he heard a couple of teammates
taking it too lightly on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-five bleepin' points!'' he roared, loud enough to be
heard on Upper Campus. ``Fifty-five bleepin' points!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a young team,'' Smith says. ``I don't think they
understand quite yet. We got our butts handed to us on national
television. I don't care who's coming at you, you don't give up 55
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be the appropriate way, but it's got to be
voiced.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five points, 55 bleepin' points, is what Nebraska scored
on Washington last week, and now 14th-ranked Arizona comes to town
Saturday night. If this is a game of the heart for the Huskies, a
game to test their resolve, they have no better representative than
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   He's their resident tough guy. Polite and well-spoken off the
field, he's a rube on it. He was the one who crossed the field last
week in Lincoln to make a fairly game run at DeAngelo Evans on his
60-yard sprint with an option pitch.
</P>
<P>
   He's the one who threw up at halftime at Arizona State, did it
again walking up the tunnel at game's end. Finally, they helped him
up onto a table and hurried five liters of fluid into his system.
He took on three liters last week at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough kid,'' said UW strength coach Rick Huegli. ``His motor
is wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   In Huegli's empire is a conditioning apparatus, like a
stairclimber squared. The players hate it, the coaches love it
because the players hate it. You climb vertically using hands and
feet, and your effort is computer-calculated against an estimated
ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Smith discovered that assistant coach Rick Mallory, the former
NFL lineman, took about 25 minutes in scaling 4,000 feet. He
mounted the machine, hell-bent to beat Mallory.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decent effort is about 32 minutes, 31,'' said Huegli. ``He
(Smith) did it in about 26 minutes. He didn't beat him, but he put
in an impressive effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's coach at Sehome High in Bellingham, Birger Solberg,
remembers the same sort of passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a playoff game against Rainier Beach,'' says
Solberg. ``They had tons of speed. He missed a play on the
quarterback, who scrambled away from him. He got him 30 yards
downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's family moved from Boston to Bellingham when he was in
seventh grade. He chose Washington over Washington State and has
appreciated the ride, however potholed.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies eventually moved him to defensive end, where he
wouldn't get road-graded. This year, he stepped into a starting
spot vacated by Chris Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the best thing I've learned since I've been here is,
the grass isn't greener on the other side,'' he says. ``You can
always go through life and think it's going to be so much fun down
at Portland State, but it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   When it's darkest, and his mood is lousiest, he finds a teammate
usually there to crack him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camaraderie makes it all worthwhile,'' Smith said. ``I
love the football team. I might hate it at times, but I still like
going out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't be doing that much longer. Smith already has a job
lined up next year in Chicago, managing health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody,'' he laughs, ``needs health care.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as anybody, he would know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
