<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4113 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-MCKNIGHT     10-01 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-MCKNIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
  
 TOUGH DAYS FOR HAWKS' McKNIGHT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ The expectations for wide receiver James McKnight
could not have been much higher.
</P>
<P>
   That will happen when you are coming off a career-best season,
your team signed you to a new contract in the offseason and then
passed on selecting Randy Moss in the first round of the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   But four games into his season of great expectations, McKnight
is struggling along with the rest of the Seahawks' offense. He has
dropped passes in each of the past three games, including one in
the end zone in the fourth quarter of Sunday's three-point loss at
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with McKnight, the big-play receiver from little
Liberty University? And what can his team do to help him emerge
from his slump?
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon supplied those answers during and after Wednesday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do is alienate a guy when he's
having some problems,'' the veteran quarterback said. ``If
anything, you want to feed him. You want to give him more
opportunities to come out of it. Like a shooter in basketball who's
in a slump, you keep shooting. If this guy's having problems
catching the ball, you keep throwing it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon did that in practice, going to McKnight early and often as
the Seahawks began preparing for Sunday night's nationally
televised game against the Chiefs in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't concerns about McKnight and the
offense, which ranks 20th in the league. The offensive meetings
that usually wrap up just before midnight on Tuesday lasted until
after 2 a.m. this week, and coach Dennis Erickson sat in on the
sessions where the game plan is formulated.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches reached the same conclusion as Moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our minds, James is a proven player who has made plays,''
offensive coordinator Bob Bratkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, McKnight averaged 18.7 yards on 34 catches. He also
caught six touchdown passes, averaging 38.5 yards on his scoring
plays. This after catching only eight passes in his first three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McKnight is concerned, but not overly. He calmly
points out that he also had drops last year, but they didn't seem
as significant because the Seahawks had the NFL's top-ranking
passing offense. This year, the passing game has slipped to 24th,
so everything is magnified as everyone searches for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows what I'm capable of doing. They know the plays
I'm capable of making,'' McKnight said. ``I haven't been playing
100 percent, but none of my coaches or teammates have said it's
from a lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know that despite the circumstances, your team
has not given up on you.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been the drops _ the one last week, as well as a pair
on third-down passes against Washington the week before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to be the fall guy. I'm not playing well. So all
the pressure is on me,'' McKnight said. ``That comes with
territory. I have to deal with it. I can't sit around and say,
`This ball was there.' Or, `This guy was holding me.' That's not
me. I don't make excuses. I have to remain disciplined and go out
and help my team win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drop a ball, nobody can get more mad at me than I get
at myself,'' he said. ``But I see it on the replay and it's gone.
If you allow it to affect you, you're not going to be any good to
yourself or your teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight also has made plays _ four of his six receptions have
produced the yardage needed for the first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the James McKnight we know. That's who James McKnight
is,'' Bratkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the James McKnight the Seahawks need against the Chiefs,
whose physical style of jamming receivers off the line and covering
them one-on-one plays to McKnight's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Two of McKnight's breakout games in his breakthrough season came
against the Chiefs. He caught a 54-yard touchdown pass in Kansas
City last year, then had a four-cacth, 66-yard game against the
Chiefs at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Moon reminded McKnight of that before they took the practice
field Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything wrong with James,'' Moon said.
``I think he understands what he has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And what the Seahawks need him to do. McKnight must make plays
to relieve some of the pressure of constant double-coverage from
Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   As Moon said, this is the first year McKnight has been counted
on to make plays. And make no mistake, Galloway needs a productive
McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' the Seahawks' leading receiver said. ``James is
as important to me as Warren Moon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
