<HEADER>
A4121 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-SPI &LR;      10-01 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-SPI </SLUG>
  
 McILVAINE: `SEASON COULD NOT HAPPEN AT ALL'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sonic center Jim McIlvaine is in Seattle and he is
depressed.
</P>
<P>
   But his funk has nothing to do with a fear of constant rainfall.
McIlvaine is a frontline player in the NBA's labor strife and he
senses where the stalemate is headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season could not happen at all. That's a real
possibility,'' McIlvaine said from his Eastside home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine, secretary-treasurer for the NBA Players Association,
has been involved in every players meeting and was a part of the
only negotiating session between the union and the NBA owners since
the owners, exercising a clause in the collective bargaining
agreement, locked out the players on July 1. Wednesday, both sides
confirmed that bargaining negotiations would resume a week from
today. Only one formal bargaining session was conducted during the
summer, and that meeting ended abruptly when the owners stormed
out.
</P>
<P>
   The major sticking point is the salary cap. The owners want an
absolute maximum on player payroll; the players want to keep the
loophole that allows teams to exceed it.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine, who came back here just in case the Sonics' training
camp opened as scheduled next Tuesday, called the situation ``a
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that popped out of nowhere,'' McIlvaine
said of the labor problems. ``I've only been in the league four
years and I could see this building up. If I were the average fan,
I'd be disgusted that this is happening. I'm sure we're going to
lose a lot of fans, if we haven't lost a lot of them already. ...
It's anyone's guess when (the lockout will end).''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McIlvaine keeps busy. Between player meetings in New
York, the Sonic center has worked on his game. He worked out
consistently at his alma mater, Marquette. Last month, McIlvaine
again participated in Pete Newell's Big Man Camp.
</P>
<P>
   He's had surgery on his left ankle to remove bone spurs, but
also has enjoyed life's pleasures, such as the growth of his first
child, Hansen (10 months), and the building of a new five-bedroom
home in Jamesville, Wis., close to where McIlvaine grew up.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout will end when one side appreciably budges from its
stance, but that does not figure to happen anytime soon. The league
sent the union a new proposal last week, which the union dismissed
as being nearly identical to the offer owners made in May.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: The owners want to put a ceiling on player salaries.
The players will not accept what amounts to a hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Today marks the fourth month of stalled negotiations. The
regular season is scheduled to begin Nov. 3, and at least three
weeks would be needed after an agreement is reached to sign
players, make trades and hold abbreviated training camps. The
league already has canceled 25 exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides await a ruling from arbitrator John Feerick on the
union's grievance over whether players with guaranteed contracts
should be paid during the lockout. Feerick's decision could come at
any time before Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the owners) have no reason not to wait,'' McIlvaine
said. ``And they have basically told us that regardless of the
ruling, they're going to continue this. If (Feerick) rules in our
favor, the owners have basically said they will appeal. It's a
waiting game. They're banking that they can sit this thing out
longer than we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the owners' strategy could be to see what happens when
players miss paychecks. Players are scheduled to receive their
first paychecks Nov. 15. McIlvaine, though, cautions the owners
that the players union is unified and prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union did a good job of telling the players to save their
money a long time ago. From what I've heard, a lot of players have
done that,'' McIlvaine said. ``Plus, anyone who looks like they
need help can contact us. So far we've had only 12-15 guys. I
thought it'd be a lot higher, but I'm sure it will get a lot higher
the longer this goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine agreed with teammate Gary Payton's prediction:
</P>
<P>
   ``You might see a lot of players going to Europe or Japan or
wherever,'' McIlvaine said. ``The players association realizes that
they can't keep conceding to the owners.''
</P>
<P>
   The league, contending that several teams are losing money, has
intimated that it will not play an abbreviated season. The league's
hard stance is partly backed by its new six-year television deal.
NBC and TNT paid the first and final years' installment on its
rights fee up front, with the league paying one year's worth back
at the end of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   That means if there ever was a time to play hardball, this is
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides are prepared to take a hard line,'' McIlvaine said.
``But fans need to understand that we didn't go on strike. The
owners locked us out. We offered to work under a
`no-strike/no-lockout' clause, but the owners said no. ... For a
long time I was optimistic about this, but now it's just
depressing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
