<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALASKA-HIGHWAYS-2ND &LR;  &UR;      10-01 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-HIGHWAYS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 COLD BAY, Alaska: ... federal lands.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the fight over the road through Izembek National Wildlife
Refuge is the most heated because the road would pass through seven
miles of wilderness, where, by law, ``man is a visitor'' and roads
are forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   People in Alaska, home to half of all federal wilderness, have
long chafed at land policies they regard as rigid. Murkowski said
Congress should ``occasionally make exceptions to allow access
across a wilderness for a legitimate purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Babbitt and conservation groups such as Defenders of
Wildlife and the National Audubon Society say that Izembek, 300,000
acres of rolling green and gold hills that provide some of the
richest coastal bird feeding areas in the country, is the perfect
place to make a stand against wilderness development.
</P>
<P>
   An entire sub-species of geese, the Pacific black brant, stop at
Izembek to build strength for their winter migration, feasting on
the beds of eelgrass piled like mounds of spinach along the shore.
Once they leave, the birds fly for 60 hours straight to Mexico,
losing a third of their body weight.
</P>
<P>
   A road, even if it is used only once an hour, could reduce the
birds' chances of surviving their migration, argues biologist
Michael Roy of the US Fish and Wildlife Service. ``If they are
flushed once an hour and take 10 minutes to settle down, the
effect'' on feeding ``could be substantial,'' Roy said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the hundreds of brown bears of Izembek, beasts that
grow up to 9 feet tall, could face increased hunting pressure from
King Cove-based guides who would gain easy access to the
wilderness. ``It becomes a day hunt all of a sudden for some of the
best brown bear hunting, arguably, in the world,'' said Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the road would pass directly through the wintering area
of a caribou herd that is only now beginning to recover from a
natural population crash in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a place you can defend against a road, it's
Izembek,'' said Roy. ``There's no need for habitat management or
restoration because it's all here. It hasn't been screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Road supporters scoff at the idea that a dirt road would harm
the wildlife, noting that the refuge already has roads that are
used by hunters and fishermen. It was decided, in fact, not have a
paved road in order to minimize the impact to the environment. Even
the wilderness section of the refuge still has a few miles of old
military roads, though they are not maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about the animals,'' said Jim Plowers, vice
mayor of Cold Bay. He said people carrying on about the wildlife
are the same people who, in the 1960s, said, ``Play guitar. End the
war. Sit around the campfire and sing `Kumbaya.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens's office, too, says environmentalists needlessly pumped
up the controversy, applying urban sensibilities to a wild place.
They note that, in exchange for 85 acres where the road would go,
an Aleut-run corporation would agree to turn over 664 acres to the
refuge under Murkowski's bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska is a very unique case,'' said a member of Stevens's
staff, both because of its enormity and an economy dependent on
natural resources. ``Policies that work well in ... small eastern
states may not work as well in Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Alaska is unique, the place where, more than anywhere
else in the United States, nature has not been tamed.
</P>
<P>
   Though Alaska is twice the size of Texas, its road system is the
size of Vermont's, due largely to impenetrable mountains, glaciers,
and other obstacles, as well as the lack of people to drive on
them. As a result, more than 150 villages across the state are
accessible only by plane or boat.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the communities in the Bush, as Alaska's vast rural
outback is known, enjoy their isolation. Residents of the fishing
village of Cordova have repeatedly voted down a road project that
would have connected them to the highway.
</P>
<P>
   But most residents of King Cove feel a little too isolated.
Since the late 1970s, various government agencies have touted a
road from King Cove to Cold Bay as a way to boost the area's
fishing economy. In 1995, Governor Tony Knowles renewed the call
for a road, saying it ``would allow the bountiful wild salmon
caught in the King Cove area to be delivered quickly ... anywhere
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in Congress have taken leadership on the road,
focusing relentlessly on the medical need for it. ``How many Aleuts
have to die'' before the road is built? asked Young.
</P>
<P>
   Backers recite a litany of victims, such as Tatiana Samuelson,
whose husband had to wait three days to get to a hospital after his
1989 heart attack because severe weather closed King Cove's
airstrip. The delay damaged his heart, ultimately requiring a
transplant, she said. Her husband died in 1992 at the age of 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely believe if we could have gotten him out of here
when he had his heart attack, he would still be alive today,'' said
Samuelson.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that, while the rural health problems are real,
a road costing $14 million to $29 million is not the solution when
bad weather will often make it impassible.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, a University of Alaska at Anchorage study found
that ``telemedicine'' could eliminate 49 percent of all medical
evacuations from rural areas by allowing doctors to treat patients
from afar. A video screen would bring doctor and patient face to
face, while the phone line would transmit information about the
patient's condition.
</P>
<P>
   For those who require hospitalization, road critics say a
helicopter emergency squad or a marine rescue team might work
better than a road, while allowing emergency crews to serve other
isolated communities who would not benefit from the road.
</P>
<P>
   But Marilyn Mack, chief of the King Cove rescue squad, said the
alternatives seem dreamed up by outsiders who do not know what it
is like to be so close to Alaska's third largest airport and not be
able to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes sense to be able to take a car and drive a
patient to the airport,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, some residents say that people who choose to live
hours from medical care have to accept that they are taking a
health risk. ``There are many sacrifices we make and risks we must
accept,'' said Terri L. Mach of Cold Bay. ``We have made this
choice, fully cognizant of the risks, just as a mountain climber
ascends a peak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALASKA-HIGHWAYS-2TAKE     10-01 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-HIGHWAYS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKAN ROAD PLAN PITS MEDICAL, ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLD BAY, Alaska _ It is hard to imagine a place further removed
from America's love affair with the car: a windswept cluster of
pre-fab houses and Quonset huts on the edge of the tundra, with no
roads connecting them to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the main road is dirt, and people share it with the huge
brown bears who sometimes wander in from the nearby wildlife
refuge. The only way out for the 82 residents _ the reason Cold Bay
exists at all _ is a World War II-era airstrip literally big enough
to land the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   But a proposal to build a one-lane dirt road connecting Cold Bay
to the even more isolated village of King Cove has made this ground
zero in the national debate over where America's highways should
end.
</P>
<P>
   Despite veto threats from the Clinton administration, Alaska's
senators were to launch their bid Thursday to win approval for a
27-mile road through a prized federal wilderness where birds and
caribou now roam largely free of people. The Alaskans say the road
will save lives by giving King Cove emergency access to an
all-weather airport.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists believe the road is a Trojan horse,
appealingly cast as a medical issue when the real goal is to weaken
protection for 15,000 square miles of wilderness from the
California desert to the Great Swamp of New Jersey. Since the
Wilderness Act passed in 1964, no permanent road has been built
through legally protected wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt calls the Cold Bay-King Cove
road ``the opening shots against the integrity of our nation's
parks, wilderness areas, and wildlife refuges.'' If the road is
built, Babbitt warned last summer, the ardently prodevelopment
Alaskan congressional delegation ``will have driven a stake through
the heart of wild places everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Once one road is built through wilderness, administration
officials say, the next will be harder to resist. And for what
follows, they point to the tourist-jammed roads to Yellowstone
National Park to Alaska itself, whose population growth followed
construction of a road to the ``Lower 48.''
</P>
<P>
   While the argument goes on in Washington, the people who live in
King Cove and Cold Bay are divided, too. Here, people debate
whether a road is the best solution to a health crisis common to
scores of communities in Alaska's roadless areas.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic in King Cove, a predominantly Aleut village of 770
near the Aleutian Islands, has no doctor, or even a technician who
who can read X-rays. Anyone who is seriously ill or injured has to
be airlifted to Anchorage, 750 miles away. The Aleuts are native
people who have lived in southwestern Alaska for thousands of
years.
</P>
<P>
   That is dicey in a region known as ``the birthplace of the
wind'' for its 80-mile-an-hour gusts and 300 days a year of
overcast weather. Only Cold Bay's airport, built to repel the
Japanese invasion of the Aleutian Islands, has the electronic
navigation aids to remain open in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Stories abound in King Cove of people forced to wait for vital
medical care because the village's dirt airstrip was closed, such
as the 5-year-old whose broken arm could not be set and the
fisherman who waited three days after a massive heart attack to see
a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, residents of King Cove overwhelmingly support
construction of the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had that darned road, I'd be home right now,'' said
Amidha Porter of King Cove, stranded in Cold Bay for the night on
her way home from gall bladder surgery in Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   Other residents, especially in Cold Bay, believe that
alternatives, such as tele-medicine, where doctors treat patients
through electronic communication, should be explored first. They
fear the road will cause as many problems as it solves, bringing
drunk driving, auto accidents, and other problems more common to
the Lower 48.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build a road, I'm buying a wrecker and I'll be busy on
Friday and Saturday nights,'' said John Waterhouse, manager of Cold
Bay's bar, grocery store, and motel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But Alaska's congressional delegation brook no talk of
alternatives, and are going all out to get the road. ``If anyone in
this Senate votes against me, this is one I will not forget,''
warned Senator Ted Stevens, an Alaska Republican, at a hearing last
June.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, observers expect a close vote in the Senate,
perhaps on party lines, as environmentally oriented Republicans
feel pressured to back senators Stevens and Frank Murkowski, both
of whom chair important committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough vote,'' said Nicholas Graham, spokesman for
Senator John Chafee, Republican of Rhode Island. He said Chafee,
usually closely tied to environmental groups, remains undecided on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists increasingly oppose new roads on public lands,
viewing them as the first step toward exploitation of remote
places. Earlier this year, they persuaded the US Forest Service to
freeze construction of logging roads in many national forests,
roads that first allow logging, but then permit much heavier
recreational use of formerly inaccessible areas.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful Alaska delegation on Capitol Hill represent perhaps
the major challenge to that view, often pushing for more
development of public land. Stevens is chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, while Representative Don Young and
Murkowski, respectively, chair the House and Senate environmental
committees.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the trio has pushed a variety of measures to open
undeveloped areas, including bills to permit a road across a major
waterfowl feeding area in Alaska's Chugach National Forest, to
study a new road in the park near Mount McKinley, and to allow
helicopter tourism throughout Alaskan federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
