<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS &LR;      10-01 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_OF GENES AND OBESITY: MORE CLUES TO A LINK  
 _PREDICTING FATAL RISKS OF A HEART SYNDROME  
 _LYMPH-NODE SURGERY: METHODS ARE DEBATED  
 _COUNTERING THE EFFECTS OF BRITTLE-BONE DISEASE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Of genes and obesity: More clues to a link
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Boston's Joslin Diabetes Center have discovered
another defective gene that can cause severe obesity, adding to
clues about the connection between genes and weight.
</P>
<P>
   The normal gene controls the formation of adipocytes, or
fat-storing cells. When it is mutated, the gene speeds the
development of fat cells, enhancing the body's fat storage,
according to a report in the current issue of the New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The mutant gene, called peroxisome-proliferator-activated
receptor gamma-2, was found in four of 121 very obese men and women
in a group of unrelated individuals in the North-Rhine-Westphalia
region of western Germany. Further study is under way to determine
if the mutant gene is similarly common in other populations, said
Dr. C. Ronald Kahn, director of the Joslin center, who authored the
report along with Dr. Michael Ristow.
</P>
<P>
   Neither this gene nor several others that have been uncovered
the past few years account for a significant amount of obesity,
Kahn said in an interview. ``But while rare, they are beginning to
help us understand something about the genetics of obesity,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Predicting fatal risks of a heart syndrome
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the estimated 25,000 to 50,000 Americans with a genetic
heart condition called long-QT syndrome are likely to die suddenly
in moments of stress, while others tend to have recurrent fainting
spells that are not fatal. Now, a genetic test can pick out those
at highest risk of sudden death and target them for treatments such
as implantible defibrillators, says a report in the current issue
of the New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Long-QT syndrome causes abnormal heart rhythms that can be fatal
in young athletes or other young people under physical or
psychological stress, said Dr. Arthur J. Moss of the University of
Rochester School of Medicine, an author of the article. In studying
541 people with the syndrome, the researchers found that one of
three different genetic mutations that can cause the syndrome is
associated with a higher risk of death than the other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means that by identifying a higher-risk group'' with a
gene test ``we can use drugs or put in a defibrillator'' that can
shock the abnormal heart rhythm back to normal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Lymph-node surgery: Methods are debated
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Removingall the under-arm lymph nodes in a woman with breast
cancer is the standard way of determining whether the cancer has
spread beyond the breast. But this surgery causes pain, swelling,
and other side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Removing just the ``sentinal node,'' the first gland that the
cancer would reach, is a new method that avoids extensive surgery.
But a study from the University of Vermont and other centers,
published in the New England Journal of Medicine, found varying
success rates among surgeons and patients, and said that in some
cases the sentinel node couldn't be identified.
</P>
<P>
   A group of specialists said in an accompanying editorial that a
number of questions need to be answered in ongoing trials. Until
then, said the specialists, led by Dr. Kelly M. McMasters of the
University of Louisville, the standard method shouldn't be
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Countering the effects of brittle-bone disease
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bone-building drug called pamindronate can increase bone mass,
reduce pain, and maintain growth in children with osteogenesis
imperfecta, a genetic disorder also known as ``brittle-bone
disease,'' scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 and possibly 50,000 people in the United States
have the disease, which has several forms and can cause patients to
have hundreds of fractures and be unusually short because their
vertebrae are fractured and compressed.
</P>
<P>
   No treatment has been very successful up to now, say the
scientists reporting in the New England Journal, led by Dr. Francis
H. Glorieux of the Shriners Hospital for Children in Montreal. But
pamindronate, which prevents bone cells from being reabsorbed by
the body, helped slow bone turnover in the trial involving 30
children, and enabled four of them to stop using wheelchairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
