<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-01 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOT-SO-HOT IMPERSONATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not content with being cute and popular, the Apple iMac on my
desk has lately begun doing an impersonation of a Windows PC. It's
better than my impersonation of Charles Bronson, but not a whole
lot better.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago I wrote about a couple of nice PC programs for
searching the Internet. I complained in passing that the programs
aren't also available for the Macintosh. I got the usual barrage of
responses from Mac users _ a few rude, but most of them useful.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, readers pointed out that the next upgrade to the
Mac operating system will include a feature called Sherlock, which
is similar to the PC search programs I wrote about. Industry rumor
has it that the Mac upgrade will appear in mid-October, though the
company has not confirmed this.
</P>
<P>
   But other readers declared that I needn't wait. I could run my
favorite Windows programs on the iMac, they said. All I needed was
emulation software _ a program that makes a Mac imitate a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Emulation software tries to solve an old problem in computing.
Traditional computer software is tightly bound to the hardware used
to run it. Operating systems like Windows and the Mac OS are
designed for specific processor chips. Windows was designed to run
on chips designed by Intel Corp., or on clones of Intel chips. Mac
OS works with the old 68000 series of chips from Motorola Inc., or
the newer Power PC chip from Motorola and IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Real people use the software that runs on top of the operating
system _ browsers, word processors, games. But these programs have
to be written especially for a given operating system, which in
turn is written for a particular chip. And that's why you can't
play the PC version of, say, Mechwarrior 2 on a Mac.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you could write a program that would make your
computer pretend to be a different kind of computer? Engineers have
done this for years. How do you think they design new chips? They
write a program that will work exactly like the new chip they're
designing. Then they load this program on a computer, and see what
happens when they run it. This way, they can fix bugs in the chip
design without having to burn any real silicon. In the same way,
you can make a Power PC-equipped Mac think it's a Pentium-based PC.
</P>
<P>
   Just one problem with this approach. You're using a piece of
software to make one piece of hardware pretend it's another piece
of hardware. Perhaps out of sheer confusion, the whole thing tends
to go rather slowly.
</P>
<P>
   So I've discovered while using SoftWindows 98, from Insignia
Solutions of Fremont, Calif. SoftWindows is one of the most popular
PC emulators for Mac users. The box cites a Chicago Tribune
reviewer's claim that a Mac with SoftWindows runs PC software as
well as a 266-megahertz Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Trib guy's Mac was specially modified by NASA. On my
straight-from-the-box iMac with 32 megs of RAM chips, SoftWindows
98 can't even match the old 120-megahertz Pentium I'm typing this
on.
</P>
<P>
   SoftWindows is adequate for standard business applications like
word processing. With some advice from Insignia executives, I got
it tuned to where Microsoft Word ran only a little slower than it
does on a real PC. But Web browsing in SoftWindows is distinctly
sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are games. There are far more available for PCs than
for Macs, and some of you may be tempted to buy SoftWindows just
for play. But SoftWindows has trouble with some popular PC games. I
tried a favorite shoot-'em-up, ActiVision's Mechwarrior 2, but it
was SoftWindows that crashed and burned. I did get Quake to run,
but it was more of a limp.
</P>
<P>
   Emulator programs are memory hogs, so the measly 32 megs in an
iMac are far too few for a proper test. I'll bet Mac users with
hotter boxes get much better performance. But a lot of iMac buyers
are computer newbies who may believe that buying SoftWindows will
turn their Mac into a crackerjack PC. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need a PC more than a third of the time, a separate PC
probably is worth it,'' an Insignia spokeswoman admitted. Good
point, especially when you consider SoftWindows 98 lists for $169.
Nowadays you can get a real PC for a few hundred more, instead of
turning your iMac into a not-so-hot PC impersonator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
