<SLUG> BC-HOME-CHENILLE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE'S TALKING ABOUT CHENILLE APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So plush. Warm. Cuddly. We're not talking teddy bears, we're
talking chenille. Some 60 years ago, that fuzzy yarn first cropped
up in this country in the form of bedspreads and bathrobes.
Fast-forward to the early '90s. Chenille transformed itself into
colorful sweaters that were all the rage. As the decade nears its
end, chenille furnishings have migrated back into millions of
homes.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its meaning in French _ hairy caterpillar _
chenille has seen its future as a butterfly. In the past five
years, this tufted velvety yarn has matured into beautifully
textured and patterned upholstery and slipcover fabrics and
luxurious furniture throws, pillows, tassels, and trims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chenille is especially appropriate for the New England climate
because it gives a warm, lush feeling to a room,'' says Susan
Shulman of Susan Shulman Interiors in West Newton, Mass. ``It's a
very soft and tactile fabric that seems to envelop you in a way
other fabrics don't. It's like wrapping yourself in a blanket. And
there's a natural tooth to it that keeps you in place, unlike
sitting on leather, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   In Shulman's opinion, chenille is a gender-neutral fabric. It
appeals to everyone and comes in a wide array of colors, textures,
and prices. The most popular colors are muted, neutral tones _ the
beiges and off-whites.
</P>
<P>
   Chenille, Shulman says, has also taken over the trim, tassel,
and fringe departments of furnishing stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love working with chenille because it's so lush and the
varieties are endless,'' says Shulman. ``Plus the prices vary
widely, as does the quality. It can fit into anyone's budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices depend upon fiber content, says Larry Isaacson,
upholstery buyer for Fabric Place in Framingham, Mass. He says the
most popular chenilles are the softest ones, which are usually made
from 100 percent cotton. Another top seller is a blend of 71
percent cotton and 29 percent polyester. Other blends include rayon
and olefin, man-made additions that allow the fabric to be
classified as ``double rubs'' and rated for heavy-duty use.
</P>
<P>
   David Webster of Webster &AMP; Company in the Boston Design Center
raves about his top-of-the-line chenilles. They are made from 100
percent viscose, a manmade fiber that is strong and luxurious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the viscose because it's more durable than other
chenilles and has a prettier look to it,'' says Webster. ``The
sheen is really beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   What everyone agrees on is that upholstery chenilles must come
with backing, whether knit or acrylic, to make them durable. The
softer or looser the chenille, the more fragile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important to know the fabric because many chenilles
must be backed with a stabilizing finish before they can be used,''
says Cheryl Chernack of A Second Opinion Design in Natick, Mass.
``They have a great deal of stretch and movement and without the
proper backing and preparation, the final product could stretch and
wrinkle. But if they are properly backed, they can take a lot of
wear and tear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chenille is a very interesting yarn because it is twisted and
can be woven in different ways,'' says Mike Zimman, owner of
Zimman's in Lynn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a technical, weaving point of view, you can do a lot more
with it than velvet. It's also a very textured and comfortable
fabric. It provides the nesting comfort that people are looking for
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Goldberg of PGG Interiors of Providence, R.I. sees a
trend toward using chenille in vacation homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it a lot in summer settings,'' she says. ``There's
nothing more comfortable than coming in from a round of golf or a
tennis game and sitting on a chenille sofa or chair with bare legs.
Besides that, I think chenille has such a calming influence on
people.''
</P>
<P>
   This may hark back to the days of tufted bedspreads and
bathrobes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a memory thing, almost Proustian,'' says Rick Garafolo of
the home-furnishings store Repertoire in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something very powerful about the message that
chenille brings up for our customers. It's a very positive memory.
And although chenille is a mainstream fabric and has been around
for a number of years, we have recently used it for drapes and
pillows and on club chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The story goes that at the turn of the century, a Georgia
teenager named Catherine Evans Whitener wanted to give her brother
a special gift for his wedding. So she made a bedspread decorated
with soft cotton turfs. Thus, chenille was born.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; By the '40s, spreads and bathrobes made from the fabric were
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But just in the past five years, chenille has become a fabric to
reckon with in the home-furnishings industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chenille has made an incredible resurgence in the past two
years,'' says Dan Gaudet, manager of the Lee Jofa showroom at the
Boston Design Center. ``It is an updated replacement for antique
velvets. There are so many new chenilles with various napes,
textures, and patterns. They just don't come in solids as in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Leni Joyce, president of Leni's Inc., a fabric mill in
Watertown, Mass., says she started hand weaving chenilles 18 years
ago. Then, no one wanted them. Today, she can't keep up with her
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chenilles are not just relegated to family rooms anymore,''
says Fabric Place's Isaacson. ``The solid chenilles still are
appropriate for dens because they are more casual. But the tapestry
chenilles can be used in more formal settings. And Italian and
Belgium mills have started using their chenille yarns in historic
prints that are hundreds of years old. They are beautiful. I
definitely think they are here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Patty Anjesky, design consultant for Choice Seating in
Cambridge, Mass., agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll ever go out of style,'' says Anjesky.
``It's a very rich look. It makes a statement along the lines of
velvet. It's a classic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
