</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAUGHTER'S GIFT OF UNDERSTANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My daughter Laura gave me a dress for my birthday. The material
is an Indonesian print sprinkled with a series of moons in their
various phases and it's so short I'm using it as a tunic over
tights. It's definitely a hippie-type dress designed for someone
much younger, but I'm wearing it anyway. I take Laura's gift as a
sign that I'm finally entering that stage of life when I no longer
have to worry about mortifying my children.
</P>
<P>
   It was very different back in the late '60s and early 70s. There
I was in my favorite costume, an anklet with bells and wide-legged
jeans I'd embroidered with dragons and mermaids, embarrassing my
kids every time I jingled. Before I went anywhere near their
schools, the kids insisted on dressing me in the most conservative
clothing they could find in my closet. When I talked to strangers
in elevators or in line at the movies, they cringed and pretended
they were with someone else. More than anything, they wanted me to
look and dress and act like a mother, a role they felt should be
filled by someone who was quiet, well-mannered, dignified, and, as
far as I could tell, nearly invisible.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to please them, but I couldn't imagine enjoying life if
I could no longer laugh with my head thrown back and my mouth open.
I doubted I could twist myself, like a pretzel, into someone who
takes up very little space and never calls attention to herself. I
didn't want to give up my leather mini-skirts, my pink aviator
glasses, or my yellow high-heeled clogs, but I certainly never
blamed my kids for trying to rein me in.
</P>
<P>
   I'd felt exactly the same way about my own mother.
</P>
<P>
   My mother painted in oils and made recordings for the blind. No
one else's mom did anything like that. Refusing to become a
housewife, she ignored the dishes in the sink and the mounting
piles of laundry. How could I invite anyone to our messy house?
Plus, she'd talk to anyone. Once, when we were driving past Fort
Devens, one of the guards whistled at our car. She turned around
and went back. ``Did you want something?'' she asked sweetly, as
the guy, realizing he'd whistled at a woman twice his age, turned
beet red. When you went somewhere with my mother, anything could
happen. I smile now, but at the time I sank back into the passenger
seat and wished I was anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   A funny thing happened on my way to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   I became proud of her.
</P>
<P>
   I came to see my mother as a woman who followed her own heart in
many ways. She chose to do things that made her feel creative and
useful. She ignored the conventions that would have confined her to
home and hearth, and though working was not really an option for
women in her position in the '40s and '50s, she filled her leisure
time with imagination and playfulness. She supported the same
traits in her children, giving generously of her time and energy as
long as we did things that interested her. This lady, whom I often
railed at for ``ruining'' my life, was actually a great model.
</P>
<P>
   Who would want to grow up if it meant putting yourself in a
straitjacket as envisioned by a 12-year-old?
</P>
<P>
   Like her, I didn't give in to my kids' importuning. I was afraid
that if I trimmed my sails and made myself into the very model of a
model mother, the day would come when my kids would look at me and
decide that they certainly didn't want to grow up to become this
same pale shadow of a whole person. I was convinced my kids would
view my self-abnegation as a diminishment of my real self. Besides,
I knew they'd never take the responsibility for having done this to
me. They were only children, after all. How could I blame them for
my decisions?
</P>
<P>
   And there I'd be, having suppressed everything that made my life
interesting and fun, for what?
</P>
<P>
   I'd have simply become another kind of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm taking Laura's gift as a signal that my daughters are
coming to terms with how I dress, at least. There's nothing more
liberating in the world than to reach the point where you
understand that the only person your mother can truly embarrass is
herself. I can only hope my daughters reach that point soon. Since
both of them are more conservative than I am, you'll never find
them looking like characters from a local production of ``Hair''
who've wandered offstage without removing their costumes.
</P>
<P>
   I can live with that.
</P>
<P>
   As long as they no longer mind if I do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
