u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-ROBIN-WILLIAM     10-01 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-ROBIN-WILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBIN WILLIAMS FINDS PARADISE IN PURGATORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robin Williams dies in the first few minutes of ``What Dreams
May Come.'' Fortunately, as the movie's tag line proclaims, the end
is just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows life beyond death and proclaims that a great
love can survive that journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe in that,'' Williams said. ``I believe love
is the one kind of unifying thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in keeping with a movie that deals, sometimes darkly,
with separation and loss, Williams seemed a bit subdued when he
called to talk about his new film, which opens Friday. Subdued, at
least, compared to his usual buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   But, as is almost always the case with Williams, there comes a
point in the conversation, usually sooner rather than later, when
the chat ceases to be an interview and starts to be a Robin
Williams performance.
</P>
<P>
   The longer you can keep from laughing (not long), the more
straight answers you can get. But once he senses your amusement, it
seems he can't help himself.
</P>
<P>
   So you enter uncharted territory when asking him a question
like, ``Do you believe in life after death?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams took an audible deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or, as the Buddhists say, life is a (drag) and then you die
and then you die and then you die? Don't squash that cockroach; it
might be Richard Nixon,'' Williams joked, then, switching to a
Nixon imitation: ``I'm over here. I never ate that chicken. I am
not a cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the interview, and Robin the comedian has
taken control, tossing in humorous lines so fast it's hard to keep
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to follow that act,'' said ``What Dreams May Come''
producer Barnet Bain. ``He's amazing; it's like interviewing a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Robin first read the script of `What Dreams May Come,' he
called up very excited and said, `I've got to play this part. I'll
play all the parts.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dreams May Come'' is a fantasy in which the initial story
feels familiar _ Williams' character, Chris Nielsen, dies, and his
spirit tries to find a way back to the living.
</P>
<P>
   Like many movie afterlife fantasies, this one is romantic. Chris
wants to contact his wife, Annie (Annabella Sciorra). But it cannot
be done, he's told.
</P>
<P>
   Williams believes such fantasies are popular because people are
fascinated with the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different books and accounts of people who
have had out-of-body experiences,'' he said. ``Or people in L.A.
with out-of-car experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked Annabella, `What do you think death is?' She said,
`I think you die, and then there's a lot of dirt.' That's the
nihilist view. Boom, that's it, thank you, check please.''
</P>
<P>
   But seldom has a romantic fantasy presented such dark twists and
turns for its characters to overcome. The movie deals seriously
with loss, guilt and sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``But also,'' Williams said, ``the idea of eternal love, a love
that goes beyond. It falls in the category of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   And never has a fantasy had such extensive special effects to
portray an alternative world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of the reason to do it,'' Williams said. ``To see
special effects used in such a unique way _ to create a world. And
not just any world. I mean, I've never seen this done before. I've
seen it to create animals and aliens and lots of explosions but, to
get the virtual van Gogh, that's quite different.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the movie takes place in heaven and hell. To show it on
screen convincingly meant a huge amount of imagination and
special-effects work. Creating two entire worlds also meant a
budget of about $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   The actors spent much of the movie pretending to react to seeing
wondrous or horrible things that would not be added to the movie
until post-production. For Williams the experience was both
familiar and different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it before,'' Williams said, ``but it's not like
`Jumangi,' where you're running from a Teamster carrying a sign.''
(That's a joke refering to ``Jumangi's'' union problems.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects (in `What Dreams May Come') have an emotional
resonance. When you see a tree, it has a lot of emotional
reverberations, and you have to find a way of dealing with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll show you a storyboard . . . and you try to work with
that. After that, it's up to your imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird thing,'' Williams said, ``because sometimes they
explain to you one thing, and then because of budget cuts or
whatever, it changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The special effects were a major reason the movie took so long
to get to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't the technology to show the visuals,'' said Bain,
whose partner, Stephen Simon, bought the rights to the Richard
Matheson novel 20 years ago. ``Even while we were making the movie,
we were inventing it as we went along.''
</P>
<P>
   Bain also believes the public was not ready for such a spiritual
movie in the past but that has changed because of what he calls
``millennium consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Previously, there was something in our culture that
(suspected) a lack of depth if you had a spiritual center or
thoughts that weren't empirical,'' Bain said. ``A deepening
appetite for issues spiritual and philosophical makes this
mainstream in a pleasing way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bain and Simon set up their film company, Metafilmics, which
made ``What Dreams May Come,'' to make movies that touch people in
a way more profound than action movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metafilmics' movies are about empowering people and showing
the decency of being human and the beauty of being a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   So while effects are essential to ``What Dreams May Come,'' it
is the story and the message that is important, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects can be astonishing, but if they're not following
the characters, they are kind of like a giant cat toy.'' He
laughed. ``A sparkly.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that emotional aspect that worried Williams about doing
the film. Playing such a charged role for four months would be
painful. Like the scene in which his character speaks at the
funeral of his two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's really hard,'' Williams said. ``Emotionally, it's
difficult. One day you have to (act out) a eulogy for your children
for 13 hours. It's not something you really want to do for five
minutes, having to inhabit that and do it time and time again. It's
not something you want to extrapolate if you have children.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams hopes ``What Dreams May Come'' will open the way
for Hollywood to find more imaginative and thoughtful uses of
special effects than dinosaurs and spaceships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the hands of the artist,'' he said. ``The amazing
thing now is effects can be used for anything. The possibilities
are almost infinite.''
</P>
<P>
   He would like to think that people will leave the theater having
serious conversations on the nature of life, death and
reincarnation. But being Robin Williams, he also can't help making
fun of it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is kind of strange to me is these people who do
past-life regressions. They always say they were amazing things,
like `I was Nefertiti's gynecologist.' `I was a princess.' `I was a
warrior god.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They never say, `I was a schlub named Murray,' you know?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
