<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
. 
ANTZ-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ ``Antz,'' the first of the season's two
computer-animated insect cartoons, features the voice of Woody
Allen as a worker ant who starts a class war in the name of love.
Other pests sound like Sharon Stone, Sylvester Stallone, Gene
Hackman and Jennifer Lopez. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
ANTZ-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ On all fronts _ graphic, thematic,
character _ ``Antz'' points to the vast potential computer
animation holds while setting admirably high standards of its own.
Heck, the acting's even better than in most live-action films you'd
care to mention. Starting with the voice work of Woody Allen. 3{
Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
DOCTOBER-FILM (Los Angeles) _ October is shaping up to be
documentary month around Los Angeles, starting Friday night in
Pasadena with the weeklong DOCtober exhibition at the historic
State Theatre. Also, UCLA's documentary series gets under way next
week. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
IMPOSTORS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ The toughest thing to do in movies
is make a successful farce. Stanley Tucci, who wrote and
co-directed the sleeper hit ``Big Night'' two years ago, gives it a
game try with his new film, ``The Impostors,'' and he triumphs over
the form for about an hour. After that, the wheels come off. 2{
Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
ROXBURY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``A Night at the Roxbury,'' a
big-screen version of that ``Saturday Night Live'' skit about the
two nerds who are always bopping their heads to the beat of
Haddaway's ``What is Love?'' barely sustains three minutes of
``SNL'' airtime every month or so. Though a slight 83 minutes, the
movie is still about 80 too long. 1{ Stars). By Bob Strauss. 
. 
DREAMS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``What Dreams May Come'' is a visual
feast of a movie that takes you on a provocative trip through
heaven and hell, all the while holding your hand with familiar film
conventions. 3 Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
ART-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ The Tony-winning drama ``Art'' in which
three friends violently disagree over a modern painting, is coming
to Hollywood for an eight-week run in early 1999. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
GOMEZ-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Gomez, five young musicians who
recorded their award-winning debut album on a shoestring in
bedrooms and garages over the space of a year, don't produce the
Brit-centric pop of fellow nominees like Pulp, Massive Attack and
the Verve. Instead, the British quintet is steeped in Americana. By
Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ Local singer-songwriter Rebekah Florence
proves subtle wit and country music can co-exist. On her second
self-produced album, ``Mexican Prozak,'' Florence sings of a trip
across the border to buy foreign-made pharmaceuticals and, in the
song ``Chris Douridas,'' of trying to attract the attention of the
former music director at influential public-radio station KCRW-FM
(89.9). By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ As the title suggests, Sheryl Crow's
self-produced ``The Globe Sessions'' has a raw, blow-by-blow feel
best realized on the disc's atmospheric finale, ``Crash and Burn.''
Those expecting the supremely catchy upbeat-ness of her previous
albums should plan to let this one sink in a bit. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
PRISONER-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ The mantra in any David Mamet script
is ``Don't trust people _ they're not always who they seem to be,''
and that's what keeps you guessing right up until the end in ``The
Spanish Prisoner.'' By Rob Lowman. 
. 

