<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHER TAKES A JOURNEY THROUGH TIME WITH ROCK ART 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRISTINA MASUDA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Zintgraff, a 72-year-old San Antonio photographer, has an
assignment scheduled next week. He will be going west to a canyon
along the Pecos River _ a journey to his own past and that of a
prehistoric people.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has made the same trip for 46 years, Zintgraff said
the area retains its magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel very impressed every time I visit that region,''
he said. ``I have a strong feeling being there.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1952, at the same site, Zintgraff discovered a
pictograph painted about 4,000 years ago. After recording the
unique figure, named ``The White Shaman,'' through his camera's
lens, he devoted his life to understanding and protecting the Pecos
River rock art.
</P>
<P>
   The art and mythology of Pecos River people are the main focus
of his work. The pictography, Zintgraff said, was the way the
indigenous artists expressed their conflicts and doubts. The
artists depicted the meaning of life, life after death and even
their food supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pictographs, people dramatized their religious and
political concerns,'' he said. ``And some of these questions remain
in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Through almost 100 slides, including ones with ``The White
Shaman,'' Zintgraff affirms the importance of preserving this
treasure, painted upon the limestone canvas of rock shelters and
canyons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man has destroyed important sites in the name of progress,''
he said, mentioning the man-made Amistad Reservoir, west of Del
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Zintgraff worked on a project to record prehistoric
pictographs before water covered the area. ``Going back to the site
when the water level was down, I saw (that the) drawings had been
washed (away) completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Zintgraff's interest in prehistoric art began in the 1950s with
an admiration for anthropologist Joseph Campbell's work.
</P>
<P>
   Zintgraff's love for photography began in his childhood. ``I
grew up with a camera in my hands,'' said Zintgraff, whose father
was a photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting involved with the pictographs, Zintgraff's career
was focused on advertising. The expedition to the Pecos River
region dramatically altered his professional life.
</P>
<P>
   Zintgraff has published two books with images of his journeys _
``Ancient Texas: Rock Art and Lifeways Along the Lower Pecos'' and
``Pecos River Rock Art: A Photographic Essay.'' San Antonio's Witte
Museum also has a permanent exhibition of his works.
</P>
<P>
   Zintgraff is a co-founder of the Rock Art Foundation, created in
1992 to promote the conservation and understanding of the Pecos
River legacy. The foundation also offers guided tours to the
region.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 713-467-0234.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
