<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SAFETY IS A HAZARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens when the Federal Reserve Bank orchestrates a $3.65
billion rescue of a failed hedge fund? What would have happened if
the Fed had not intervened in the meltdown of Long Term Capital
Management? What will happen as a result of the Fed's intervention?
These questions haunt financial markets today and raise a larger
issue that affects the culture of American politics. That issue is
known as moral hazard.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple concept. To quote The Wall Street Journal, moral
hazard is a ``term the financial community uses to describe the
distortions introduced by the prospect of not having to pay for
your sins, in this case financial ones. The prospect of government
bailouts leads to abandonment of credit standards and assessments.
As moral hazard grows, you get a market so skewed by the
expectations of bailouts that vital signs about genuine risk no
longer get through. Eventually, the danger turns into one of
systemic collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps appropriate that the collapse of Long Term Capital
Management was brought about by Russia's default on its financial
obligations last month. Long Term Capital had 8 percent (or as much
as $125 billion, depending on how you count the value of derivative
financial products) of its highly leveraged funds in Russia, not
because it thought Russia was a good investment, but rather because
it thought Russia too big to fail. Prior to the default, Russia was
literally printing money to meet its obligations. Cross-border
investors were reaping huge returns.
</P>
<P>
   Long Term Capital bet billions of dollars on a morally hazardous
certainty: that the United States and the International Monetary
Fund would always come to the rescue of an economically perilous
country with thousands of potentially ``loose'' nuclear warheads.
Russia's default made that certainty uncertain, and within days
margin calls came raining down on Long Term Capital's Greenwich,
Conn., headquarters. Long Term Capital sold what it could to meet
its obligations, but after selling the good stuff, it was left with
a ton of useless paper. No one would buy it, at any price. And the
game was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve did the right thing in jawboning Long Term
Capital's creditors into becoming a consortium of cash infusion.
Allowing Long Term Capital to collapse might have spelled disaster
for the world's financial system and completely undone the market
for derivative products. An orderly liquidation of the hedge funds
portfolio over three years allows the financial markets to regain
their balance.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that in so doing, the Fed has re-raised the issue
of moral hazard. In a recent post on the financial news Web site
thestreet.com, David Kansas wrote that Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin, prior to Long Term Capital's collapse, believed that moral
hazard had diminished as an issue, ``primarily because a lot of
those who invested in more speculative projects in places like
Russia and Asia have already suffered steep losses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' Rubin told Kansas, ``if you look at what
happened to investors and creditors and others over the past year.
Enormous losses have been sustained, so the moral hazard issue that
people have been concerned about is not nearly as potent as it used
to be because people have taken the kinds of losses that hopefully
will induce more careful investment and credit extension.'' Rubin
went on to say that moral hazard issues will not stand in the way
of the United States providing ``national assistance where it is
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing national assistance where it is needed makes sense,
especially in those cases where US national security interests are
involved. Organizing the rescue of a private hedge fund, the very
definition of a risky financial vehicle, is another matter
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, no public monies were involved. Yes, it is true that the
rescue scheme is better than watching $50 trillion of derivative
products chain react and come home to roost. And yes, it is true
that Long Term Capital Management's partners are forever disgraced
and face the real possibility of prosecution under the Federal Wire
Fraud Act.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, the signal sent by the Federal Reserve's
intervention says that the rules that apply to the rest of us do
not apply to certain elites. Any other hedge fund would have been
shut down by Goldman Sachs or Merrill Lynch in a three-minute phone
call. Long Term Capital gets a cash infusion of $3.65 billion and
is allowed to continue to charge a management fee that would make
Fidelity blush.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has been sending this signal for a long time, but
with heightened frequency of late. The most noxious recent example
of Washington moral hazard is, of course, the contention that
President Clinton should not be impeached for perjury, obstruction
of justice, and misuse of executive power because he has a high job
performance rating in public opinion polls. The effect of all this
on the body politic is toxic. It teaches people to believe that
they can never be too cynical.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
