<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-LADN     10-01 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROXBURY' ONE LONG COMEDY SKIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 1{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They'll just turn any ``Saturday Night Live'' skit
into a movie, won't they?
</P>
<P>
   If ``It's Pat'' was a one-joke premise, ``A Night at the
Roxbury'' has got to be a half-a-joke concept. It's a big-screen
version of that skit about the two nerds who dress themselves up in
slick suits, scare women at nightclubs and are always bopping their
heads to the beat of Haddaway's ``What is Love?''
</P>
<P>
   The gag barely sustains three minutes of ``SNL'' airtime every
month or so. Though a slight 83 minutes, the movie is still about
80 too long.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, time must be taken to tell you everything you don't
need to know about the Boppers _ and if you've seen ``Wayne's
World,'' you know this backstory anyway in, by comparison, more
Proustian depth.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, they're idiots, played like lobotomized Abbott and
Costello by Will Ferrell and Chris Kattan. They're also brothers;
Steve (the big, dense one) and Doug (the little annoying one)
Butabi. They work in their grumpy father Kamehl's (Dan Hedaya) silk
flower shop and live in his unaccountably grand, Beverly Hills
home. They drive Dad's luxury cars to all the hot Sunset Strip
clubs, which they're nonetheless too uncool to get into.
</P>
<P>
   The non-plot involves a traffic accident with Richard Grieco
(Richard Grieco!) that results in entree to the glamorous Roxbury.
A life goal achieved, the brothers have nowhere else to go but
toward a falling out. When a ruthlessly nesting-minded non-hottie
(``SNL'' cast mate Molly Shannon) seduces Steve into engagement, it
looks like the Butabi boys' partying days are finished.
</P>
<P>
   Laughless for, oh, about the first hour _ you know the wit
situation is dire when we're expected to be amused by the Butabis
struttin' down the street to ``Stayin' Alive'' for three minutes _
``Roxbury'' actually gets pretty humorous as the climactic,
inevitably catastrophic wedding approaches. Shannon is far and away
the film's funniest element; her desperate-yet-determined
bride-to-be may be an unflattering cliche, but at least she's not a
brain-dead cipher like every other character in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The director, John Fortenberry, makes his feature debut after
helming episodes of such better-than-average TV comedies as ``Just
Shoot Me,'' ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' and ``The Ben Stiler
Show.'' He also reportedly directed the pilot for a projected TV
series built around Toonses, the ``SNL'' cat who drives cars off
cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   If they had put a Toonses scene in ``Night at the Roxbury,'' the
whole thing would've added up to a one-joke concept.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-HEALTH-HNS &LR;      10-01 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAND STUDY FINDS AMERICANS LIVING NOT ONLY LONGER, BUT HEALTHIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The number of older Americans who can perform
simple tasks of daily living is on the rise, evidence that people
are living not only longer but healthier as well.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by two Rand Corporation researchers, published Thursday
in the American Journal of Public Health, showed that between 1984
and 1993, older Americans found it easier to read newspapers, carry
a 10-pound bag, and walk a quarter mile.
</P>
<P>
   The results varied according to age. Gains were modest among
50-to-64-year-olds. But they were more dramatic among those over
80.
</P>
<P>
   Rand, a social research think tank based in Santa Monica,
Calif., underwrote the study with support from the federal National
Institute on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initial reports of the decline in disability among older
Americans were met with enormous skepticism,'' said Richard Suzman,
associate director for behavioral and social research at the NIA.
``This study provides important new evidence of the strength of the
trend and moves us toward understanding what is behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   The study by Rand researchers Vicki Freedman and Linda Martin
marks a number of health improvements for all older-people age
brackets. The number of those with:
</P>
<P>
   _ Difficulty seeing newsprint dropped from 15.3 percent in 1984
to 11.6 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Problems lifting and carrying a 10-pound bag fell from 23.5
percent in 1984 to 18.9 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inability to climb a flight of stairs without resting declined
from 24.5 percent in 1984 to 22 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Difficulty walking a quarter mile, about three blocks, went
from 25.8 percent in 1982 to 22.3 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers chose these activities as markers because most
people do them regardless of their traditional gender roles in
households, how much money they have, and what kind of house they
live in.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies used activities such as bathing, shopping or
doing laundry, which can be affected by factors that have nothing
to do with health.
</P>
<P>
   A male respondent, for instance, may not give an accurate
response on the difficulty of shopping or doing the laundry because
his wife does both. And someone who reports greater difficulty
bathing may lack a walk-in shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we looked at were less susceptible to environmental
factors and socially defined roles,'' said Freedman. ``What we
found is that there actually are improvements in underlying health.
Socio-economic characteristics don't explain these changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The study team did not seek to determine why older Americans are
more healthy, but Freedman said the improvement probably reflects
greater health consciousness among them, as well as healthier
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the elderly today are better educated than 10 years
ago, and we know people with education are less likely to engage in
unhealthful behaviors, and are more likely to see doctors,''
Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   She and Martin based their research on data compiled by the
Census Bureau's Survey of Income and Program Participation. From
that data, they compiled the answers for 1984 and 1993, and
adjusted them for age, sex, marital status, race, income and
geographic region. The sample sizes were 13,277 in 1984 and 12,716
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements were most dramatic in the age 80-and-above
category. There, for instance, the number of people with problems
lifting a 10-pound bag declined 10.5 percentage points, from 51.5
percent in 1984 to 41.0 percent in 1993. By contrast, the number of
those in the 50-to-64 age bracket reporting similar problems fell
from 16.6 percent in 1984 to 13.5 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes at a time of national debate on shoring up
Medicare and Social Security, the two pillars of federal social
programs for the elderly. Both are under financial stress with the
massive baby-boom generation scheduled to start reaching retirement
age in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that the elderly have become healthier could be useful
ammunition, for instance, for those arguing that the age at which
people start receiving Medicare should rise from 65 to 67.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan passed the Senate last year during debate over the
balanced budget agreement. But it lost in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The study also supports other evidence that for many seniors,
the ``golden years'' are more enjoyable than ever. A poll of 1,300
Americans over age 60 found that 61 percent of men and 37 percent
of women engage in sexual activity at least once a month. Also, 79
percent of men and 66 percent of women said an active sex life was
an important aspect of their relationship with their partner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
