   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Democrats try to figure out what
their alternative proposal might be; and have a few alternatives,
including censure plus, an inquiry with a strict timeline, or an
inquiry with strict subject limits. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ An inside, close-to-the-ground look
at how the Lewinsky charges are affecting the strategies and the
campaigning of candidates in two competitive House districts; and
how the matter is playing nationwide. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LOWELL (Washington) _ A profile ofAbbe Lowell, the chief
Democratic staffer on the Judiciary Committee's Clinton inquiry. In
making their choice, Democrats took a blatantly opposite path from
Republicans. While Republicans chose an outsider, a streetsmart
lawyer from Chicago who shies from the limelight, Democrats opted
for a savvy Washington insider who relishes his role and enjoys the
klieglights. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMO (Washington) _ More HMO's drop out of Medicare
citing government refusal to let them raise premiums or cut costly
prescription drug benefits. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Four different abortion proposals
are holding up four different appropriations bills. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JONBENET-MURDER (Denver) _ More infighting over the JonBenet
Ramsey murder case in Boulder, with one police officer quitting in
protest of what he sees as harassment of the parents and the
parents coming out swinging against the police. Meanwhile, a grand
jury investigates. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   VA-COMA (Manassas, Va.) _ A judge early Thursday rejected the
state's last-minute attempt to halt relatives of a comatose man
from removing the feeding tube that has kept him alive for 3{
years. The ruling left no obstacles for the family of Hugh Finn,
44, to take the step that would lead to his death. The family said
it will not announce when that happens. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hedge Fund Bailout &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-REGULATE (Washington) _ Fed Chairman Greenspan says in
testimony before the House Banking Committee that the Fed's
brokering of the rescue of Long-Term Capital was a one-time event
that did not signal a new policy by the central bank to protect
investors in hedge funds. The New York Fed's McDonough also
testifies. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT (Undated) _ Developments: Sumitomo Bank of
Japan says it has $100 million invested in Long-Term Capital;
Italy's Foreign Exchange Office says it invested $100 million in
Long-Term Capital and lent another $150 million to the hedge fund;
and Dresdner Bank of Germany says that it has ``a position at
risk'' of 240 million marks, or $144 million, with Long-Term
Capital and that earnings in the third quarter were hurt by the
turmoil in emerging markets. By Peter Truell and Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-MERIWETHER (Undated) _ Profiling John Meriwether, the
man behind Long-Term Capital. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the industrial average was
down 139 points, the Nasdaq index was off 58 points. Elsewhere,
prices fell 1.6 percent in Tokyo, while Hong Kong was closed for a
holiday. They declined 8 percent in Frankfurt, 2.7 percent in
London, 4.9 percent in Brazil and 4.3 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 1 3/32 point at midday,
with the yield at 4.91 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
