<SLUG> BC-ART-MURALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURALS ADD AN EXTRA TOUCH OF CLASS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  with art 
 
By MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For the newly renovated lobby of The Rice apartments,
it was that extra touch of class.
</P>
<P>
   For the media room of a Houston-area mansion, it was a permanent
party mood.
</P>
<P>
   For a Lake Conroe resort restaurant, it was the illusion of
being transported to an exotic place.
</P>
<P>
   More than decoration or even works of art, murals can create a
distinct ambiance in a private room or public arena. Paintings once
planned to fill a blank wall or even provide an imaginary view now
often set the desired tone in a space.
</P>
<P>
   Although artists have been painting fanciful designs, scenes,
angels, animals and people on walls and ceilings for centuries, in
recent years it seems to be the thing to do. Relatively plain
spaces acquire instant atmosphere with walls painted to look like
ancient ruins or a tropical rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   During long, intense days in late summer, native Houstonian
Russell Erwin put his classical art training to the test while atop
a 30-foot scaffolding in the rotunda of The Rice. As various
craftsmen refurbished the elegant lobby of the historical Houston
hotel, now converted to residential lofts, Erwin and his assistants
painted six murals into the curves where columns meet the vaulted
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring in delays and other aspects of the project, each mural
was completed in an average of two days. Erwin says the
``classical'' paintings were inspired by imagery used by painters
Lord Frederic Leighton, C.A. Lenoir and J.W. Waterhouse.  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The first stage of Erwin's Rice project involved the creation of
two murals for the ballroom. While the rotunda murals were sketched
and painted on the walls, the ballroom murals were painted on
canvas, then mounted on opposite walls high above the room.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin said the project started with ``one unsigned and
irreparably damaged original mural from the Rice Hotel.'' He said
the 6-foot-by-36-foot canvas, found in the basement, could possibly
be 100 years old and had obviously been exposed to high heat and
humidity for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old mural was full of holes and parts of the canvas were
completely rotten. Worst of all, (it) had never been varnished, and
the oil paint was rapidly disintegrating,'' Erwin said.
</P>
<P>
   After restoration was ruled out, the choice was a new mural
based on the canvas, expanded by about a third. Erwin says the
original mural appears to have been painted by a theatrical or
scenic artist using a decorous Neoclassical, Victorian style.
</P>
<P>
   To create the new mural for the west wall above the stage, as
well as one for the opposite wall, Erwin altered and adapted other
works in the style of the original. When finished, the new murals
received an umber glaze, simulating an antique patina.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the upper floors of The Rice, artist Jeff De Lude
turned the long hallway in a two-bedroom loft into a view of a
Tuscan landscape, seen beyond a columned archway. The mural, which
is 12 feet wide and almost 9 feet high, visually opens up the
space, giving an illusion of depth.
</P>
<P>
   The mural is painted directly on the Sheetrock. De Lude painted
the surrounding walls to look like aging plaster. The subdued
colors in the mural, plus a few spots where it appears that the
paint has flaked off, give the effect of an antique painting.
</P>
<P>
   Interior designer Sandy Lucas of Lucas/Eilers Design Associates
finds murals a good way to deal with large spaces, especially in
residences. When Lucas was doing the interiors for a new residence
in the Memorial area, she and her client were inspired by the
murals in Joey's, one of the Vallone family's restaurants, during a
trip to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we wanted something playful and fun for the walls in
the wine room. It's a small space with high ceilings,'' Lucas said.
``We hired artist Janice Parsons, who has done the murals for
several of Tony Vallone's (restaurants), decided on a
Toulouse-Lautrec Moulin Rouge-type theme, and went from there. It
was the perfect solution because a mural allows you to keep the
scale of the art large enough to be seen high on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   A mural also proved the answer for the media room. ``We needed
something to set the tone for the room, to complement the purpose
as well as balance the big screen, but not be too serious,'' Lucas
said. ``My client thought it would be fun to make it look like a
party, with their favorite celebrities and friends.'' Erwin was
commissioned to paint the family and other favorite people on the
walls, making it a very special space.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Cynthia Stone decided she needed more than paint or
wallpaper to liven up the exercise room of Mountain Canyon, a
residential high rise in Phoenix, Ariz. ``We needed something to
counterbalance the coldness of those exercise machines,'' she said.
The Houston interior designer turned to Houston artist Suzanne
Kitrell to create a ``cheery and fun'' mural of energetic
exercisers with a Southwestern desert-type landscape.
</P>
<P>
   A desert southwest setting also was painted onto the walls and
ceiling of a Lake Conroe restaurant, giving the remodeled space the
look of a quaint village nestled at the base of an ancient cliff
dwelling. Designer Sharon Staley worked with Richard Aiple, resort
manager of Del Lago Golf Resort and Conference Center, to develop
his ideas for transforming &UR;  &LR; the dated garden-theme restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The concept for the new restaurant, renamed Kiva, was a logical
extension of the exterior Spanish-Mediterranean architecture of the
hotel complex. Airbrush artist Rick Fitzpatrick worked from
photographs of Santa Fe, N.M., and Phoenix to paint the intense
scenes that envelop the dining areas.
</P>
<P>
   Denice Hockett worked with Staley on the design of Grand Slam,
the Del Lago sports bar, and Fitzpatrick painted the multisport
murals that wrap around the space. Sports fans will recognize
famous football broadcasters, such as Frank Gifford, in the press
box above the bleachers. Other sections of the nostalgic murals
represent baseball, basketball, even water-skiing. Staley said the
resort reports a strong increase in business because of the lively
atmosphere. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
