<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ASIA-EFFECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPPLES OF ASIAN CRISIS SPREADING IN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes job-loss text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For more than a year Massachusetts has watched warily
as Asia's economic downturn has forced one sector of the state's
economy, semiconductors, to lay off more than 3,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Gillette Co. preparing to issue pink slips to 4,700
employees worldwide _ and the number in Massachusetts still
undisclosed _ the state now is on notice that Asia's problems may
take a wider toll here in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The next industry to be hit, economists said Wednesday, could be
financial services _ a sector that includes mutual funds, banks and
insurance companies, and which had 166,000 employees in the state
at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of anecdotal evidence that there is a hold on
hiring'' in financial services, said Rachael Chiono, a regional
economist at DRI/McGraw Hill in Lexington, since US stock markets
began plummeting in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already hearing of layoffs on Wall Street,'' added Wayne
Ayers, chief economist at BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also warned that, even if the impact of global
financial problems on Massachusetts can be limited, almost every
economic reversal has a ``ripple effect.'' This includes ``everyone
from the people who supply the copy paper to the pizza shop,'' said
Ayers.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's problems as a worldwide seller of consumer goods are
singular in Massachusetts, which has few large firms that sell
consumer goods and fewer that sell globally, said David A.
Tibbetts, the state's commissioner of economic development.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, repeating the views of others, a broader mix of
industries than during previous recessions is expected to help the
state better withstand any recession in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   But Gillette's announcement was a warning, Tibbetts said, that a
recession could have impacts far beyond the specialized
semiconductor industry that depends heavily on Asia for sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a concern? Yes,'' said Tibbetts. ``Is it time to
panic? Certainly not.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiono said DRI economists now believe there is a 50-50 chance
of a recession in the United States that could reverse years of job
growth in Massachusetts. But even if a recession can be averted,
she said, the fact Massachusetts exports a higher fraction of its
industrial output to Asia than other states will limit job growth
here to about 1 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ongoing layoffs, the state's job growth rate this year
is running about 2.9 percent, said Chiono.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Mark Zandi of Regional Financial Associates of West
Chester, Pa., agreed with these projections, but only if the global
economy ``expands at a better rate next year than it has this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``if the world economy goes flat next year
and the stock market falls another 25 percent,'' Zandi said, the
shocks will be substantial almost everywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Tibbetts said Gillette chairman Alfred M. Zeien refused to tell
him the company's plans for its Massachusetts plants and offices,
but left him believing there will be little if any impact at the
largest of those plants, in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `We've just spent $400 million upgrading this
plant, and it is running seven days a week, 24 hours a day _ you
can read between the lines,''' Tibbetts said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
