<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE: TURN OVER A NEW LEAF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Twenty-one games have come and gone since
the last time Drew Bledsoe set foot in the Superdome in New
Orleans. The game, you may recall, was the most important of
Bledsoe's career _ a 35-21 Super Bowl loss to the Green Bay Packers
Jan. 26, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bledose returns to the scene of the frustrating loss, though he
knows Sunday's game against the Saints won't be quite the same. He
knows it will be louder _ and more hostile _ because the partisan
crowd will be behind the 3-0 hometown Saints. He goes into the game
older and wiser. The Patriots are 13-8 since the Super Bowl,
including playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of facing Danny Wuerffel, New Orleans's second-year
quarterback, led Bledsoe to reflect on what it's like to be a young
quarterback in the NFL, specifically about the struggles of rookies
Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf, who already has had run-ins with the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Ryan a little bit,'' said Bledsoe, who attended
Washington State five years before Leaf. ``He's going through some
tough things right now. He's a volatile guy, always has been, and
probably always will be. If he goes through the emotional swings
like he seems to be going through now his whole career, he's going
to have a heart attack. I haven't talked to him, but I left him a
message after the Kansas City game,'' when Leaf was 1 for 15 with
two interceptions in a 23-7 San Diego loss, ``and told him to keep
his head up.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf has lashed out at reporters and had to issue a statement of
apology this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at times people forget how hard the job that we do
is,'' said Bledsoe. ``And to come in as a rookie and try to be a
starter in the NFL at quarterback, it might be the toughest task in
sports. The guys are struggling a little bit. Ryan is struggling a
little bit with the media off the field. I know Ryan a little bit
and he loves to play football, but he's probably a little bit like
me in that he loves the game but the off-the-field stuff he could
let slide a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get caught up in the emotional swings where you get
real high after a win or real low after a loss, that can be hard on
you. You have to maintain a certain level each week _ win or
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bledsoe was a rookie, his coach, Bill Parcells, deflected a
lot of the media attention. The Colts' Manning, despite a horrible
start, seems more mature than Leaf and better able to cope with
failure, probably thanks to his father, Archie, an NFL veteran who
surely told Manning there would be some tough times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be the determining factor with Ryan and Peyton
_ how they're dealing with the adversity they're going through,''
said Bledsoe. ``They can go at it one of two ways. Either they can
bounce back from it, be a little patient, gain some confidence,
move on, and be successful, or they can let it get to them and go
down that road and then bounce around from team to team. Sometimes
they'll have to deal with (adversity) for two or three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who has a calmer demeanor than Leaf, credits agent
Leigh Steinberg with helping him deal with the media. Leaf also is
a Steinberg client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leigh Steinberg gave me a lot of direction in how to deal with
the media and also I tried to pay close attention to guys who were
perceived well and guys who were perceived negatively by the
media,'' Bledsoe said. ``You watch some of the guys who are some of
the real classy guys in the NFL and watch the way they conduct
themselves. Everything is always positive and they're upbeat
regardless. They take as much responsibility as they can. You learn
by watching. You don't want to be like the guys who point fingers
at somebody else or make excuses. Ultimately that comes back to
haunt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he learned from watching veterans such as Troy
Aikman, Warren Moon, and John Elway who are ``respected on and off
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   His message to Manning and Leaf: There will be tough times, but
it's better to roll with the punches than throw them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to Buffalo my first game and seeing Bruce
Smith walk onto the field and that was an intimidating thing for a
21-year-old,'' Bledsoe said. ``It was just a blur looking back on
it. I remember some of the positives. I had an excellent tight end
who was just coming into his own in Ben (Coates). At the time I had
a center who was extremely smart in Bill Lewis. When I'd come up to
the line and if they were giving me a certain look, he'd turn
around and say `Check 58.' So I'd call out `Check 58.' I had some
guys who helped me out a little bit. I was never 1-for, but I had
some bad ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has not been intercepted once this year. But he's
certainly not taking New Orleans for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very aggressive up-field defense,'' said Bledsoe.
``They led the league in sacks last year. They're showing why this
year. Probably more now than in other weeks, there's a real matchup
up front for our guys. If they can give me a little time to throw
and a little room to run, we'll be all right. If they don't, it
could be a real ugly game offensively. That's the overriding theme.
Teams look ugly when they play against them. We have to execute and
make a couple of plays in the game to put some points on the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he figures the Saints will get into the pocket and
try to make him throw on the run. He said the Saints will do
everything they can to stop Robert Edwards. And he's ready for the
dome noise.
</P>
<P>
   He has wrist bands that have some of the longer plays written on
them so he can expedite play calling. And backup quarterback Scott
Zolak will be equipped with a headset wired to quarterback coach
Jack Reilly, so if Bledsoe can't hear the play call from Reilly in
the transmitter in his helmet, he can turn to Zolak for help.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe realizes the fact that he hasn't thrown an interception
yet won't help him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a week-to-week battle. If I go out and turn the ball over
a lot in this game, we won't have a chance of winning the ballgame.
The most important statistic other than the final score is the
turnover ratio. We have a gaudy record (24-2 since 1994) when we
have a positive turnover ratio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
