<HEADLINE>
EGANS OF EMC FAME MOVE INTO VENTURE INVESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decade that saw the undoing of such giants as Digital
Equipment Corp. and Wang Laboratories, no company or family better
epitomized the continuing vitality of Massachusetts' technology
story than EMC Corp. and its founding family, the Egans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of the 1990s, the Hopkinton computer storage
company has seen its revenues explode to nearly $4 billion from
$132 million and profits mushroom to more than $500 million from
the red-ink days of the 1980s. The Egans, and any investor smart or
lucky enough to stick with them, got rich: The stock rose from
about 27 cents a share at the start of the decade to about $57 a
share today.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe, in its annual ranking of companies, this year
named EMC the ``Company of the Decade.'' The company itself touts
its success as ``The EMC Effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a core of young tech start-ups are hitching their futures to
``The Egan Effect'' _ a bet that the family's magic and money can
make them something special, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the Egans wind down their involvement with the company they
built from scratch, the family is increasingly focusing its energy
_ and its money _ on a new generation of New England technology
companies. Investors, too, might want to note where the Egans are
placing their bets.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month John R. Egan, EMC's heir apparent and the son
of cofounder Richard J. Egan, said he was leaving the company to
run Egan-Managed Capital, a venture firm built on the family
fortune. John Egan, 40, cited a desire to spend more time with his
family and his passion for venture investing as the reasons behind
his departure from EMC.
</P>
<P>
   In a venture capital world flooded with money, this is a modest
beginning. The firm was started with $32.8 million in Egan family
money, a sum dwarfed by any number of other firms aimed at
early-stage companies. Another larger fund, which will include
money from outside investors, is planned for early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But more than money _ in some ways the easiest part of the
venture game these days _ the firm is pushing the Egan name and all
that it represents. In the venture business today, success or
failure is determined by who can persuade the best and brightest
entrepreneurs that you are the venture partner for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is different about us is John Egan. We lead with that,''
admits Michael Shanahan, one of Egan's two partners and a former
partner at Eastech Management Co., a Boston venture firm.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's other partner is Francis J. Hughes, a longtime partner
and president of American Research &AMP; Development Co., the storied
Boston venture firm that originally bankrolled a young Ken Olsen
and his fledgling Digital Equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Egan says he is focusing on New England technology companies
because New England is where he is and technology is what he knows.
The firm has so far invested anywhere from $1 million to $2 million
in six small companies and plans to make as many as 16 investments
before the current pool is spent. Says Egan: ``If it is a passive
investment, we're not interested. If it is more active, we're more
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the money, Egan says the family contacts can provide his
start-ups an entry to potential customers at some of the biggest
companies in the world and be helpful in recruiting talent. He
thinks Egan-Capital knows technology and how technology companies
work.
</P>
<P>
   And, he says, there is less pressure for the kind of quick
``trophy'' public offering other venture firms want. ``Our family
doesn't have that cadence. We can be patient,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Like most venture firms that specialize in start-ups, the Egan
portfolio is littered with no-name firms: Eprise Corp. in
Framingham, Terascape Software in Needham, VXI Corp. in
Rollinsford, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   EPiCON Corp., a 40-person software development firm in Waltham,
says it went to Egan-Capital for a reason: ``There is an Egan
Effect,'' says Jack Sweeney, EPiCON's chief executive. ``The Egans
have a lot of credibility in the market. I wanted John on the board
to help bring that credibility to EPiCON.''
</P>
<P>
   BlazeNet Inc., which plans to make network switches, has just 35
people, no revenues and won't even ship its first product until
next year. Egan ran the search that found the company's chief
executive, Bruce Cohen, a cofounder of Chipcom. Says Cohen: ``The
venture capital community always talks about high risk, high
reward. This definitely is high risk. We think it is going to be
high reward _ that is to be determined.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups are calling for the head of Massachusetts
insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt. Who would be insurance
commissioner if Attorney General Scott Harshbarger were to beat
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci in November?
</P>
<P>
   The smart money is on Joanna Connolly, Harshbarger's assistant
attorney general who handles most of the office's insurance issues.
Connolly has been a low-profile presence on a lot of high-profile
issues over the last few years, including sales practice cases
against Prudential Insurance and John Hancock Mutual Life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
