<HEADLINE>
ACCORD OVER CHINATOWN ANIMAL SALES COLLAPSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The agreement between Chinatown merchants and
animal-rights proponents on the proper way to slaughter animals
collapsed Wednesday, threatening to prolong a cross-cultural
dispute in the ethnically vibrant section of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel frustrated, angry and betrayed,'' said Richard
Avanzino, president of the San Francisco Society for the Prevention
of Cruelty to Animals. ``We unfortunately are getting into an
adversarial and combative mode.''
</P>
<P>
   An agreement brokered in April by the SPCA and the Chinese
Consolidated Benevolent Association, a group with a 150-year
history in Chinatown, fell apart over the humane and proper ways to
kill hard- and soft-shell turtles, and how to store frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Avanzino said he and others would ask the state Fish and Game
Board to take action against Chinatown merchants who sell live
animals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, they will contend that frogs and turtles
are nonindigenous species being sold illegally and released into
wilderness areas and public ponds and lakes, threatening the
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wartelle, an attorney representing the merchants, countered
Wednesday that a court ruling in July had already vindicated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stores don't treat animals inhumanely at all. ... We don't
have to do any of this,'' Wartelle said. ``The courts say our
methods are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over selling live turtles, frogs and other animals
for food in Chinatown has raged for more than two years. In a 1997
lawsuit, animal-rights activists accused the merchants of storing
and killing animals in a cruel fashion by keeping them in cramped,
dirty conditions, denying food and water, and tearing shells off
live turtles.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Superior Court judge said in a tentative opinion
in July that the merchants were not violating health or penal
codes, a charge leveled by the activists. He denied the activists'
request for an injunction on the sale of live seafood and poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the court ruling, attempts to reach a compromise
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines included a ban against selling injured or
diseased animals, storing animals in cramped conditions, and
removing feathers, skin or shell while the animal is alive.
</P>
<P>
   Wartelle said in an interview Wednesday that the negotiations
began to break down after the merchants hired Dr. Joy Mench,
director of the Center for Animal Welfare at the University of
California at Davis, to analyze the handling of animals and to
recommend how it could be improved. Mench made a few
recommendations but said the animals already were being treated
humanely.
</P>
<P>
   The merchants took Mench's recommendations to SPCA
representatives, who disagreed. Wartelle said the disagreements
were insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Because the agreement fell apart, Avanzino said, the SPCA will
seek or has discussed seeking a ban on the sale of turtles and
frogs, advocating a boycott of Chinatown, sponsoring a statewide
initiative banning live animal sales and seeking criminal charges
against the market operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was avoidable,'' Avanzino said. ``Now, we're in an
all-out confrontation ... that's created a dynamic that hurts
everybody. It leads to divisiveness that's sad and unfortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
