<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS FEELS THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ There are many young players who are
benefitting from the fact that four free agents have not yet come
to terms with the Bruins, especially the forwards. With Jason
Allison, Anson Carter, Ted Donato, and Kyle McLaren on the
sidelines, that has meant a lot more ice time for players such as
Antti Laaksonen, Peter Nordstrom, Peter Ferraro, and Chris Taylor.
While the Bruins are thin at forward, they've got goaltenders
aplenty. Wednesday's exhibition against the Pittsburgh Penguins at
the Centrum was Rob Tallas's chance to make a case for staying in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jim Carey and Byron Dafoe have had their full games. Tallas
was next in the rotation. One factor that complicates Tallas's
situation is that the Bruins have to play Carey in about a dozen
games in order to be able to expose him in next June's expansion
draft. Tallas said he knows there are other considerations when
putting the roster together besides how well he plays, and that
puts more pressure on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's there,'' said Tallas, 25. ``It's obvious and it's out
there. It's something you think about. I'm just trying to make this
club. I think last year I wasn't just a backup in the league, I was
the best backup in the league, and that means something to me. I
took a lot of pride in that. I want to get back into that rhythm. I
know it's a new season, I can't look back at last season, it's
done, it's behind me. I just have to look at what's up for me in
the future here and what's going to happen. That's something that
is always on your mind. It just seems like every year I've been the
odd man out and it is tiring and it is hard. It's mentally hard
through training camp knowing that you are kind of still the odd
man out all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas took the Bruins to arbitration this past summer believing
he deserved a one-way contract after posting a record of 6-3-3 in
14 games in Boston last year with a 1.83 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is one thing but I've never been one that worried
about money,'' said Tallas. ``I don't think I need to be rich to
have a good life. I just really enjoy being in the NHL. There are
nights I sit on the bench and I'm in awe that I'm still here and
excited that I'm here. It's never been about money. Going into the
arbitration case, we never had a figure we were sticking by, we
were just arguing for a one-way (contract). That's all I really
cared about and being up here. I really enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas is trying to relax and remain focused as he, Dafoe and,
Carey battle for two jobs. Dafoe came into camp as the No. 1
netminder and has done nothing that would alter that perception,
which leaves Carey and Tallas fighting for the backup job. As long
as the free agents remain out, goals will be hard to come by and
the goaltenders' roles will become more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes goalies tend to think we can stop anything,'' said
Tallas. ``Even on great goals, we look back and think, `I could've
had that.' Some games you might have had it. But you have to worry
about what you're doing out there. You can take the worst offensive
team in the league and put in Dominik Hasek and I guarantee you
they'd win some games. It all comes down to goaltending and guys
rally around that. Last year, we were kind of looking at it the way
we're looking at it now. Who do we have really? But guys shined
through and really stepped up. Hopefully it will happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, the only thing the Bruins and Allison were
agreeing on is that they disagree. Assistant general manager Mike
O'Connell spoke to Bob Gerow, Allison's representative, before
Gerow and Allison left Boston Wednesday and they were no closer to
working out their differences than they had been before Allison and
Gerow came to town for a meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically asked them if they were comfortable with the
decision they've made,'' said O'Connell. ``He wants a two-year deal
and we just can't come to an agreement. Of course we hope something
will get done but if it can't be done, we've got to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the Bruins won't trade Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even thinking about it,'' he said. ``It doesn't make
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   On a more optimistic note, O'Connell spoke to Doug Messier, the
agent for defenseman McLaren, and is hopeful there will be a
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good discussion,'' said O'Connell. ``We're getting
closer, it appears to me.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said there was no news on Carter or Donato.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center Dmitri Khristich's shoulder strain could keep him
sidelined through the start of the season Oct. 10 ... Center Joe
Thornton (bruised shoulder) skated on his own Wednesday and said he
planned to skate with the team Thursday. He said he is hoping he
will be able to play in the club's final two exhibition games this
weekend but there appears only an outside chance that will happen
... Defenseman Don Sweeney, who underwent two surgical procedures
to repair his broken shoulder blade, made his exhibition debut
Wednesday night ... The Bruins wrap up the exhibition season with
back-to-back games against the New York Rangers at the FleetCenter
Saturday and in Hartford Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
