<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Oct. 2, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ANTS (Undated) _ DreamWorks Pictures' first animated
feature, ``Antz'' is certainly no ``Bambi,'' but it is a visually
engaging and moderately entertaining fantasy that makes another
eye-popping showcase for the fast-evolving art of computer
animation.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DREAMS (Undated) _ Any movie set almost entirely in the
afterlife seems doomed to a certain kind of failure from the start.
``When Dreams May Come'' is so grounded in Hollywood imperatives,
and so intent on being acceptable to all denominations and points
of view, that _ despite its undeniably striking visuals _ the film
comes off as being weak and unconvincing on one hand, and shrill
and fundamentalist on the other.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-IMPOSTERS (Undated) _ There's not much to say about a
comedy that falls as flat as Stanley Tucci's ``The Impostors.'' As
hilarious as it may have seemed on paper, the
writer-producer-director-star fails to bring off even a single
scene. Sitting through it is a grueling experience.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ROXBURY (Undated) _ Things move in waves at the movies, and
disco currently is the craze. ``A Night at the Roxbury,'' which is
a whole lot more fun and memorable than the current box office dud
``54,'' is the surprise in a less-than-memorable pack.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LOLITA (Undated) At first glance, Stanley Kubrick's
``Lolita'' would seem to be the rare movie classic that could stand
a remake. After all, in the movie climate of 1962, Kubrick had to
dance all around the subject of a 37-year-old man's lust for a
14-year-old ``nymphette.'' But the new ``Lolita'' has fared badly.
As good as the film is in many respects, the concept of a more
``serious'' treatment of Nabokov's novel has proven to be less
appealing on celluloid than it did on paper. The story seems to
demand a heavy sense of irony, even comedy. Without it, the film is
a long 137 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ST.PETERSBURG (St. Petersubrg, Russia) _ Often called
``The Venice of the North'' for its architecture, beauty and
setting by water, St. Petersburg is one of the world's great
cities. With a little advance preparation, a visit can be a pure
delight.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``t'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
