<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories in sight at this hour from The New York
Times News Service for Friday, Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VAN-GOGH-EXHIBIT (Washington) _ The van Gogh exhibition opening
at the National Gallery in Washington on Sunday is a beautiful
retrospective of 70 paintings from the Van Gogh Museum in
Amsterdam, which is now closed for renovation. By Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   TITANIC-BACKSTATGE (New York) _ Audiences generally know a
production by its stars, story, music. Rarely do they get a glimpse
behind the scenes, where the set and costume changes can be as
intricately choreographed as the dancing, where the relationships
may be easily as intense as those the actors portray on stage, and
where the unexpected crises can be even more suspenseful than the
plot. ``Titanic'' offers a particularly compelling example of the
magnitude and the minutiae of this backstage drama. By Robin
Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MERCER-HOTEL (New York) _ Our writer Bruce Weber gets a
different perspective on his old neighborhood by staying at the
Mercer Hotel, the upscale hostelry at the corner of Prince and
Mercer in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTZ-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Antz'': Eric Darnell, Larry
Guterman, Tim Johnson, directors. Animated, with the voices of
Woody Allen, Sharon Stone, Gene Hackman, Anne Bancroft, Christopher
Walken, Jane Curtin, Jennifer Lopez, John Mahoney, Paul Mazurzky,
Danny Glover, Sylvester Stallone. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   HIT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Hit Me'': Steven Shainberg,
