<HEADLINE>
`ART' OF THE MATTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's ``Art'' all right, but is it art? That's a
question critics and audiences on two continents have answered
mostly positively about Yasmina Reza's play ``Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Now L.A. audiences can have their own say. Alan Alda, Victor
Garber and Alfred Molina will re-create their original Broadway
roles in an exclusive eight-week engagement of the play, Jan. 15
through March 14, at the UCLA/James A. Doolittle Theatre, 1615 N.
Vine St., Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 Tony Award-winning drama, the relationships among
three friends are turned upside down when one of them buys a piece
of modern art _ an all-white painting.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are available only as part of Center Theatre Group's
Blockbusters Series, a package that also includes ``Fosse: A
Celebration in Song and Dance,'' the musical ``Titanic'' and
Matthew Bourne's ``Cinderella,'' and to current Center Theatre
Group subscribers at the Ahmanson Theatre and the Mark Taper Forum.
For more information, call CTG Audience Services at (213) 628-2772.
Tickets for ``Art'' will go on sale to the general public in
November and will be available through TeleCharge at (800)
447-7400.
</P>
<P>
   OUTSTANDING OVATIONS: ``The Cider House Rules,'' the Mark Taper
Forum's marathon adaptation of John Irving's novel set in and
around a Maine orphanage, squeezed out 13 nominations for the 1998
Theatre LA Ovation Awards, which were announced at a Sept. 28
cocktail reception at the Hotel Inter-Continental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cider House,'' which received nods for best play, lead actor
(Josh Hamilton), lead actress (Jillian Armenante) and director of a
play (Tom Hulce and Jane Jones) was followed by ``Chicago'' with 10
nominations and Circle X Theater Company's ``Great Men of Science
Nos. 21 &AMP; 22'' with seven nominations. Four productions received
six nominations each: ``Blame It on the Movies'' and ``The Old
Settler,'' both at the Pasadena Playhouse; Actors Alley's ``Room
Service''; and East West Players' ``Pacific Overtures.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 26 categories in all, with separate awards for larger
and smaller theaters in most categories. Voting season covered the
period Sept. 1, 1997, to Aug. 31, 1998. A total of 281 productions
were eligible to compete, of which 105 were world premiere plays or
musicals and 21 were new translations or adaptations. The voting
body consists of professionals from Theatre LA member companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovation Awards are administered by Theatre LA, the nonprofit
association of more than 150 theaters and producers that represents
and promotes theater in the Greater Los Angeles area. Its programs
include the Theatre LA half-price ticket outlet at Jerry's Famous
Deli in West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be presented at a gala ceremony at 7:30 p.m.
Nov. 16 at the Shubert Theatre in Century City. Nathan Lane will
host. The awards are open to the public; tickets may be purchased
by calling TeleCharge at (800) 447-7400 for $15, $35 and $125. For
groups of 15 or more buying $35 seats, a 10 percent discount is
available by calling Jeanne Kowalski at (714) 994-6150.
</P>
<P>
   THIS YEAR'S MODEL: Seventeen years since she scored a surprise
British pop hit with ``O Superman,'' Laurie Anderson is still
wearing purple suits and a punk-Tinkerbell haircut.
</P>
<P>
   She's still delivering her stream-of-portentousness commentaries
in a unique tone of voice _ husky, insinuating, seductive,
conspiratorial _ that makes her sound like the mischievous twin
sister of HAL the computer in ``2001: A Space Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   And she's still painting in the same aural palette of monstrous
electronic squawks, sotto voce growls, synthetic banshee wails and
digitally processed yodels that occasionally seems as dated as
Michael Jackson's hiccups and shrieks on the ``Thriller'' album.
</P>
<P>
   Call it an '80s thing.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``The Speed of Darkness,'' Anderson's ``stripped-down''
solo performance Sept. 25 at UCLA's Royce Hall, had a slightly
retrograde feel to it, the 80-minute show also reaffirmed
Anderson's reputation as an artist of unquenchable curiosity and
astuteness. She tackles subjects that mainstream theater hardly
seems to know exist.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Anderson's subject is the dual-edged blade of
technology, specifically the creeping (and creepy) globalization of
world culture via computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do with something really big and really powerful
that you don't understand?'' she intones. ``You worship it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowing before the high-tech godhead, Anderson sees us as a
culture of information hunter-gatherers, a theme she interweaves
with soothing-menacing anecdotes about Cree Indian rituals,
cybersex, the Unabomber, Dolly Parton's ``Dollywood'' theme park
and sheep cloning. Culled from her own frequent-flier existence,
these impressionistic verbal e-mails have the ring of confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Her point? Humans are engaged in a ``personal arm's race,''
obsessively stockpiling arsenals of dubious info-bytes while
converting their souls and bodies into click-on icons. Hardly a
novel idea, plus the show's ostensible focus on a theater, a mental
hospital and a control room never gets very well developed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Anderson is able to fuse her mostly shrewd cultural
insights, cryptic stories and ominous soundscapes into a kind of
post-apocalyptic memory play, as if she were looking back on a
century's long, slow slide into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, whose next project is an adaptation of ``Moby Dick,''
is the Ishmael of performance artists, a sly survivor whose
prophetic musings look more prescient with each passing year. She's
an artistic Cassandra whose voice is still far too wise and funny
to be taken lightly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
