<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN     10-01 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GLOBE SESSIONS' SOMETHING TO CROW ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
SHERYL CROW/``The Globe Sessions'' (A&AMP;M)
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the title suggests, Crow's self-produced third effort has a
raw, blow-by-blow feel best realized on the disc's atmospheric
finale, ``Crash and Burn.'' Those expecting the supremely catchy
upbeat-ness of her previous albums should plan to let this one sink
in a bit. Crow is in a moody mood on many of these tracks, but the
material grows on you. Standouts include ``My Favorite Mistake,''
the lost Bob Dylan gem ``Mississippi,'' ``There Goes the
Neighborhood'' and the poetic ``Riverwide.'' Stones fans will
recognize Bobby Keys on sax, while Tom Petty hand Benmont Tench
tinkles the piano and Lisa Germano adds violin. In case you're
wondering, ``Anything But Down'' is not the first song ever written
about an elevator. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ELVIS COSTELLO With Burt Bacharach/``Painted From Memory''
(Mercury)
</P>
<P>
   This concept may have been better in theory than practice. The
pairing of Costello and Bacharach already had produced one winning
track _ the 1996 ``Grace of My Heart'' soundtrack tune ``God Give
Me Strength'' _ when the two pop geniuses decided to stretch the
collaboration out for an entire album. Bacharach immediately
channels his late '60s glory days by bringing in the female backup
chorus, the oodles of sweet strings and sharp acoustic piano, but
Costello is pushing himself beyond all reason. His singing often
sounds studied and forced, as if the tunes were beyond his comfort
range. Despite the clever arrangements and fine musicianship,
there's a surprising lack of memorable melodies here. 2 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOOTIE &AMP; THE BLOWFISH:/``Musical Chairs'' (Atlantic)
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to dredge up anything to hate about old Hootie. On the
other hand, it's difficult to drum up much excitement about the
band either. On the band's third major label release, the South
Carolina quartet puts forth confidence and muscle even while
churning out a pretty convincing bluegrass cut. The star of the
show, as usual, is r&AMP;b-tinged crooner Darius Rucker, whose soulful
approach helps sell so-so material like ``Michele Post,'' ``Las
Vegas Nights'' and radio-ready album-opener ``I Will Wait.'' 2
Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEE ANN WOMACK/``Some Things I Know'' (Decca)
</P>
<P>
   If you long for the days before country went Canadian, check out
the sophomore effort from chanteuse Womack, whose instinctive grasp
of phrasing connects with the listener. She's at her best on such
heartbreak ballads as ``A Little Past Little Rock,'' ``The Man Who
Made My Mama Cry'' and ``I Keep Forgetting,'' but best of all is
the dark and dreamy ``The Preacher Won't Have to Lie.'' A
supporting cast of Nashville's best and brightest adds to the fun.
3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHRIS ISAAK/``Speak of the Devil'' (Reprise)
</P>
<P>
   This velvet-throated king of lonely hearts knows what side his
bread is buttered on. And don't think for one minute he's going to
start playing in major keys just because he collaborated with
top-40 mainstay Diane Warren on one cut. For the just-released
``Speak of the Devil,'' Isaak and band Silvertone remain firmly in
that familiar post-Orbison downcast groove. The Warren-Isaak cut,
``Breaking Apart,'' might win some new fans, but the soul of this
record is in such material as ``Walk Slow,'' ``Black Flowers'' and
the strong title track. 2 { Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JUDE/``No One Is Really Beautiful'' (Maverick)
</P>
<P>
   The glossy well-produced sheen on this much-talked-about debut
from 28-year-old Michael Jude Christodal doesn't detract from the
generally despondent tone of this collection of witty originals.
Owner of a distinctive vocal sound and taste for high-wire
wordplay, Jude delivers intimacies on ``I'm Sorry Now'' as well the
super-freaky on the straight-to-radio ``Rick James.'' Strong backup
work from L.A. session mafia. Think Elliott Smith, except with
tunes. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOHN WILLIAMS/``The Guitarist'' (Sony Classical)
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the overly familiar classical or romantic guitar
repertoire, virtuoso Williams instead blends the textures and
harmonies of Eastern Mediterranean music with the rhythm and
character of music from the medieval era. Even the classical pieces
here are unusual _ arrangements for guitar and chamber orchestra
and solo transcriptions of piano pieces by French composer Satie _
plus originals and works by Greek composer Mikis Theodorakis are a
delight. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRANK SINATRA/``Songs for Young Lovers/Swing Easy,'' ``Songs for
Swingin' Lovers,'' ``A Swingin' Affair'' and ``Come Fly With Me''
(Capitol)
</P>
<P>
   Want to know what all the hub-bub about Frank Sinatra is about?
The four latest Sinatra reissues from Capitol wouldn't be a bad
place to start. The albums, recorded from 1953 to 1958, represent
the singer at his expressive best and continue the wonderful
remastering work Capitol and Reprise have performed on his
wide-ranging catalog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs For Young Lovers/Swing Easy'' (4 Stars) were Sinatra's
first albums with Nelson Riddle, the masterful arranger who helped
the Chairman redefine his sound after losing his way, not to
mention his recording contract. These two eight-song sets,
collected together on one CD, set the template for Sinatra's
Capitol years with their exquisite mixtures of swing, jazz and
ballads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs For Swingin' Lovers'' (4 Stars) is probably the best
album Sinatra ever recorded, although that's like saying blue is
the most beautiful color God created. (How do you choose?) But
``Swingin' Lovers,'' made in 1956, perfectly captures the
sophisticated swing Sinatra and Riddle had been honing on previous
records. It's a work that really is too marvelous for words.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Swingin' Affair,'' (4 Stars) which followed ``Songs for
Swingin' Lovers'' by a year, is a perfect sequel, another 15 love
songs about the joys and sorrows of love, this time including more
of a psychological bent. His straightforward rendition of Duke
Ellington's ``I Got It Bad and That Ain't Good'' is pure
confessional heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Fly With Me'' (4 Stars) has Sinatra joining forces this
time with arranger Billy May in a loose, boisterous album that
takes them around the world for classics like ``Moonlight in
Vermont'' and the title track. The album bounces between beautiful
ballads (``Vermont,'' ``April in Paris'') and rollicking numbers
(``On the Road to Mandalay''), a perfect synthesis of Sinatra's
genius.
</P>
<P>
   We can't wait for the next round of reissues.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
