<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DREAMS' IS ITS OWN HELL TO ENDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Here's what's wrong with giant movie screens: You can
fill them with extreme close-ups of Robin Williams' face.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can imply that this is what heaven's like: spending
eternity looking at giant close-ups of Robin Williams' face as he
weeps and moans and emotes in such a soppy fashion that he could
make a chorus of angels want to fwo up. (CQ)
</P>
<P>
   The last time Williams ventured from his safe ground of comedy
into metaphysical histrionics, he made the worst film of his
career, ``Being Human.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, with ``What Dreams May Come,'' he only makes the
second worst.
</P>
<P>
   Williams plays Chris, whose entire life is dispensed with in the
opening credits, when he is whisked from being a young man who
meets cute Annie (Annabella Sciorra), marries her, has a successful
career and two kids, has them die, then dies himself.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now the movie can begin, as Chris is led on a tour of the
afterlife by an angelic guide (Cuba Gooding Jr.).
</P>
<P>
   Chris' heaven is a place where you can create anything you can
dream up. So, what do people dream up? In this heaven, they float
upside down a lot, dress up like rich people from Victorian
England, ride old-fashioned bicycles and walk around holding tennis
rackets.
</P>
<P>
   But not Chris. He can't stop mourning for the soulmate he left
behind. When Annie commits suicide, she goes to a hell she can't
escape from because ``suicides don't realize they're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't stop Chris, who determines to rescue her from hell,
even though other ex-people tell him that can't be done, even
though they also tell him there are no rules.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe no one can make a really good metaphysical film about
heaven and hell. Certainly, director Vincent Ward can't.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who made the wonderfully poetic ``Map of the Human
Heart,'' slips into maudlin melodrama with this vision of the
afterlife as something created in negotiations between Peter Pan
and Dante.
</P>
<P>
   Ward is aided in his visions by screenwriter Ron Bass, one of
the best writers in Hollywood. Or maybe it was some other Ron Bass
who wrote ``Rain Man,'' ``Waiting to Exhale,'' ``Dangerous Minds''
and ``My Best Friend's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say which Bass and Ward got worse: the attempts at
cute romantic repartee to establish the deep love between Chris and
Annie (he likes to buy her meatball subs and thanks her for all the
arguments they've had together) or the deep philosophical
ruminations (``God is somewhere up there shouting that he loves us
and wodering why we don't hear him?'').
</P>
<P>
   You may cringe with embarrassment for creative people who are
incapable of cringing with embarrassment for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The first rule for dealing with metaphysics without looking
stupid should be: Don't put Robin Williams in your movie. He
appears to be made of spun sugar and sludge. Who can buy into a
deep romance where Sciorra (``Cop Land'') is glumly serious, while
Williams is walking smarm?
</P>
<P>
   Ward's visions of the afterlife provide the film's sole
redemption, ranging from Monetlike impressionistic gardens to
something that looks like the Bronx on a bad hereafter day. Some
people will be relieved to know that old dogs go to heaven, but
spiders go to hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dreams May Come'' is so incessantly treacly and morose
that it's strictly for people who felt that there just weren't
enough violins in ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dreams May Come'' is misrated at PG-13. It contains
enough profanity and flashes of nudity to have earned an R. 2
stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
