<SLUG> BC-DOCTOBER-FILMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTOBER IS MONTH FOR DOCUMENTARIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For those who couldn't pass up the critically
acclaimed documentary ``The Farmer's Wife'' last month on KCET,
there is more of that gritty, emotional realism ahead this month in
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of luckless Nebraska farmers, substitute
down-on-their-luck clowns on a pathetic road trip in ``Circus
Redickuless'' _ without a doubt the most curious documentary
subject of DOCtober, starting tonight at the State Theatre in
Pasadena. In all, 13 films are included in this second annual
weeklong event sponsored by the International Documentary
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Other intriguing topics include the women of the Black Panthers,
a widow's return to Vietnam to heal her emotional loss and a look
at the making of ``Kundun.''
</P>
<P>
   DOCtober originated in 1997 so the viewing public could see the
latest efforts by reality-based filmmakers. Three films from last
year's festival were nominated for Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Glau's film, ``Circus Redickuless,'' about a ragtag
circus of losers headed by a man named Chicken John, has been
recommended for Oscar consideration by IDA. Chicken John invites 17
friends and acquaintances with nothing better to do to join his
traveling show, which takes them all on a miserable journey of
canceled shows, broken-down vans, Dumpster diving and abysmal
hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Revolutionaries,'' by Sienna McLean, listens to two
women who participated in the '60s struggle for change waged by the
Black Panthers. In ``Regret to Inform,'' director Barbara Sonneborn
realized she has never gotten over her husband's death in the war,
so she contacts other widows to recount their experiences and loss.
``In Search of Kundun'' is Martin Scorsese's encounter with the
Tibetan people and the Dalai Lama during the making of the film
``Kundun.'' Directed by Michael Henry Wilson, the documentary
raises questions about spirituality in the modern world and how to
pursue it.
</P>
<P>
   The themes of brutality and violence are taken up in several
submissions, starting with ``The Last Days,'' directed by James
Moll and presented by Steven Spielberg. It follows five Hungarian
Holocaust survivors of the brutal Nazi occupation of their
homeland. In a germane tangent, ``Human Remains'' looks at the
personal lives of men who _ for worse _ changed the course of
20th-century history. ``Thug Life in D.C.'' is a collection of
stories told by prison inmates that sum up the bleak experiences
and futures for young African-American men.
</P>
<P>
   All films will be screened daily at the historic State Theatre,
770 E. Colorado Blvd. Call (626) 792-3540 for program information.
Tickets cost $6 per film or $20 for a festival pass. Tickets may be
purchased through Ticketmaster by calling (213) 480-3232 or (805)
583-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Laemmle's Grande 4-Plex in downtown Los Angeles
continues its ``Documentary Days'' series tonight with a weeklong
screening of ``Biker Dreams.'' This examination of the
Harley-Davidson subculture is ``a memorable portrait of people who
have found community, independence and the road to their dreams
straddling a motorcycle.'' It takes place at the annual Black Hills
Motorcycle Classic that draws 25,000 bikers from all strata of
society _ from bankers to outlaws _ to Sturges, S.D., to share
their mutual passion for bikes.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is at 345 S. Figueroa St. Tickets cost $6.50, and
validated parking is available across the street at the World Trade
Center. Call (213) 617-0268 for information.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the UCLA campus, the annual showcase of feature-length
and short documentaries gets under way Tuesday night at the James
Bridges Theatre on the UCLA campus. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   An 8-year-old guitar prodigy, Julian Lage, is the compelling
subject of ``Jules at Eight,'' screening at 7:30 p.m. Spike Lee's
Oscar-nominated ``4 Little Girls'' about a Birmingham, Ala., church
bombing in 1963 that claimed four girls' lives and had
ramifications for the city and nation as well.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 Contemporary Documentary Series runs through March
and is presented by the Academy Foundation of the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences and UCLA Film and Television Archive.
Call (310) 206-3456 for future screenings.
</P>
<P>
   The series picks up Oct. 13 with gay-themed ``Paul Monette: The
Brink of Summer's End'' and ``Stolen Moments.'' The former film
looks at the writer who chronicled the effects of AIDS, including
his own illness, at the end of his life. ``Stolen Moments''
spotlights lesbianism in Europe and North America and points to the
sense of community lesbians have established at various points and
places.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, the International Documentary Congress at the
academy in Beverly Hills opens with ``Docs Rocks,'' a collection of
some of the most memorable nonfiction films about rock 'n' roll
performers and their music. The three-day assembly of
documentarians convenes Oct. 28-30 and includes a screening of
``Docs That Shook the World'' and a screening of ``Everest'' at the
IMAX Theatre at the California Science Center at Exposition Park.
Registration is open to the public; call (310) 247-3000, Ext. 176,
for information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
