<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POKING FUN AT BORDER RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Local singer-songwriter Rebekah Florence proves
subtle wit and country music can co-exist.
</P>
<P>
   On her second self-produced album, ``Mexican Prozak''
(UnderStress Records), Florence sings of a trip across the border
to buy foreign-made pharmaceuticals and, in the song ``Chris
Douridas,'' of trying to attract the attention of the former music
director at influential public-radio station KCRW-FM (89.9).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people thought `Mexican Prozak' was an attempt to make
fun of country music but it was really a tribute to country music
and some of my favorite artists, like Lucinda Williams and Emmylou
Harris,'' the Santa Monica-based Florence said.
</P>
<P>
   Florence, who has opened for Harris, next appears Oct. 27 at
Genghis Cohen in West Hollywood with multi-instrumentalist Jinsoo,
who plays on the album.
</P>
<P>
   The song ``Chris Douridas'' was written when the ex-DJ was slow
to include Florence's first disc, ``Please Yourself,'' on KCRW's
popular ``Morning Becomes Eclectic'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a political ax to grind with Chris, only a
personal one,'' said Florence, who is in her early 30s. ``It was
making fun of myself for making someone so important. That's what
the song is about. It's like being a spurned lover except I was
spurned by this DJ.''
</P>
<P>
   The track includes such rhymes as: ``I'd ride to London on the
back of a cheetah/Wearing a pair of high-top Adidas/ Promise not to
use the word elitist/If I could just get a little attention from
Chris Douridas.''
</P>
<P>
   Douridas left KCRW earlier this year to take a job at DreamWorks
Records and was replaced by Nic Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks before Chris left, I did begin to get
airplay at the station,'' Florence said.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP TRICK: &UR;  &LR; In one of the oddest touring concepts yet, '70s
and '80s hitmakers Cheap Trick will revive entire albums in
sequence tonight and Saturday at the House of Blues.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago pop-rockers tonight perform the 1977 disc ``In
Color,'' which included the studio version of the group's first top
10 hit, ``I Want You to Want Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the West Hollywood club, the band will reprise its
``Heaven Tonight'' album, which featured the hit ``Surrender'' and
a cover version of the Move's ``California Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the recent repackaging of the band's first three
albums, Cheap Trick's drummer, Bun E. Carlos, declared the music
somehow timely.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what was recorded by other groups in 1978 doesn't
hold up this well,'' he crowed. ``Nothing was so trendy that it
sounds dated.''
</P>
<P>
   `SGT. PEPPER' FAVE: The Beatles' ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts
Club Band'' topped Web site Wall of Sound's top 100 albums poll
this week. The survey asked users to vote for their 10 favorite
albums from each of the last four decades. The results were
combined to create the final list. More than 25,000 users
responded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4291 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISONER-VIDEO-LADN     10-01 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONER-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST NO ONE IN `THE SPANISH PRISONER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Leave it to David Mamet to make a game of it _ a
confidence game, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright/screen writer/director takes pleasure in setting
his stories in the world of con men and high-price scams. His
latest film, ``The Spanish Prisoner'' (Columbia TriStar), which is
out on video this week, is reminiscent of his first film, ``House
of Games'' (1987) with its complex psychological twists, surprising
plot turns and sharp dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The mantra in any Mamet script is ``Don't trust people _ they're
not always who they seem to be,'' and that's what keeps you
guessing right up until the end in ``Prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's title comes from an age-old con. A man tells a
wealthy man whom he has befriended that his beautiful sister is
being held prisoner back in his home country. He produces pictures
and other documents to prove he's not lying, and then asks for a
loan to pay her ransom. In return, he says, he will bring his
sister back to marry the wealthy man. There is no sister, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Prisoner'' the con revolves around a formula that Joe Ross
(Campbell Scott) has discovered that is supposed to make his
company, headed by Klein (Ben Gazzara), a lot of money. Don't worry
about what the formula is because it's a McGuffin _ Hitchcock's
term for a plot device that gets the action in motion. On a
business trip to the Caribbean, Ross meets a mysterious
businessman, Jimmy Dell (Steve Martin), who asks him to deliver a
package to his sister in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   After some comments by a company assistant (Rebecca Pidgeon)
along for the trip, Ross begins to doubt that Dell is who he says.
His colleague (actor/sleight-of-hand artist Ricky Jay) tells him
that ``worry is like interest paid in advance on a debt that never
comes due'' _ an example of clever Mamet dialogue. But it soon
becomes evident that Ross should be worried as the scam unfolds.
The question is who's involved.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet makes his moves like a chess master as the story reveals
itself. But if it was all sleight-of-hand, then Mamet (the author
of ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' ``American Buffalo'') would be minor
leaguer. What ratchets up his dramas are the ever-shifting roles
his characters play, and ultimately that's what the stories are
about. For in Mamet's world, people's characters are the illusions,
and what we think we know about someone is as apt to disappear as
quickly as a coin from a magician's hand.
</P>
<P>
   After a while it all seems like tricks, and we're left with the
questions: What's real? How much do we really know? But in the
meantime, like any good magician, Mamet is diverting your
attention. This time with an enjoyable film.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE ADULTS: There are a few other new videos worth checking
out. Vanessa Redgrave gives a masterful performance in ``Mrs.
Dalloway'' (BMG) that, it is hoped, will be remembered at Oscar
time. The adaptation of the Virginia Woolf novel about Clarissa
(Redgrave), a London society matron, who reflects on the choices
and missed opportunities of her life is quite elegant, though a bit
stifling. Directed by Marleen Gorris (``Antonia's Line,'' the 1995
Oscar-winning foreign language film) it also stars Natascha
McElhone as the young Clarissa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Girls and a Guy'' (Fox) is one of those claustrophobic
productions that has you yearning for the wide open spaces by the
end. Starring Robert Downey Jr. as a two-timing actor who finds
himself surprised one day at his New York City apartment (where all
the action takes place) by the two women he's dating, Heather
Graham and Natasha Gregson Wagner. Although director James Toback's
script has its moments and Downey and Graham give terrific
performances, this menage a trois lacks heat. Still, it probably
plays better on video than it did in the theaters. By the way,
there is also an NC-17 version available, but you'll have to find
out how much hotter it is.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE KIDS: If you're looking for a fun family film that
adults can sit through, try ``Paulie'' (DreamWorks). It's the story
of a sharp-tongued parrot who is the pet and friend of a little
girl who stutters. When Paulie is banished by her family, who don't
know the bird talks, he ends up across the country where he begin
his odyssey back home. Told with good humor and warmth, ``Paulie''
is a winner for families.
</P>
<P>
   `X-FILES' UPDATE: According to Fox, the video of the ``The
X-Files'' movie (Oct. 13) will include new footage that will answer
one of the long-standing questions of the series (you'll have to
watch to find out what). The video also features exclusive
interviews with producer/creator Chris Carter and actress Gillian
Anderson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1501EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHROEDER-DIFFERENT-G     10-01 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHROEDER-DIFFERENT-GERMANY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY ELECTS A DIFFERENT KIND OF CHANCELLOR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week beginning
October 3, 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gerhard Schroeder is an ordinary man and, by electing him
chancellor, Germany has shown itself to be an ordinary country. A
banality? In other countries, ordinariness is not usually an issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany, so traumatized by history, has never before dared
to behave quite like other countries, and has always chosen leaders
who see the future through the prism of the awful past.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder will be different, and so will Germany be.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first German chancellor to carry no guilt-inducing
memory of World War II. He will be the first postwar chancellor to
hold office in Berlin, presiding over a Germany that will look
almost as much to Central Europe as it has, till recently, cast its
approval-seeking gaze across the Rhine to France.
</P>
<P>
   He is a business-friendly, barely left-leaning Protestant from
Hanover, in northern Germany, whose instincts draw him not just to
Paris and Rome but also to London, even to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He has a beautiful fourth wife, once a journalist on a tabloid
newspaper, and he seems unabashed about his three divorces.
</P>
<P>
   For making Germans feel relaxed enough to elect such a
thoroughly modern fellow, give thanks to Helmut Kohl, Schroeder's
ejected predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has been a great, generous and generally good man to have
at the head of Europe's biggest, and the world's third-biggest,
economic power for 16 years. His sincerity as peace-maker and
democrat is undoubted. His courageous leadership saw NATO's
missiles deployed, in the teeth of Soviet and much western
opposition, in West Germany in the last great confrontation of the
cold war. It enabled a nervous nation to seize the chance to unify
itself in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He had the determination -- wise or foolish, time will tell --
to drag an unwilling people into a single European currency to
further his desire to integrate a continent more tightly in the
interest, as he saw it, of peace.
</P>
<P>
   He was not infallible. He concentrated too much on European
designs. German unification proved expensive. Unemployment rose to
dreadful levels.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Kohl failed to modernize a corpulent economy when the
going was good. But, tired and passe as he had become, he finished
the task that his predecessors had started, of making Germany a
normal country. He paved the way for Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Many doubts attend the new chancellor. What does he really stand
for?
</P>
<P>
   After presenting himself at the start of the campaign as a
modernizer wedded to a ``new center,'' he edged leftward to curry
favor with blue-collar workers, pensioners, the unemployed and the
aggrieved of the ex-communist east. He said he would roll back some
of the outgoing government's tepid but sensible reforms to shave
welfare, ease hiring and firing, and cut taxes. But mostly he
remained vague.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been tactically wise. He did not want to upset too
many voters, calculating correctly that he could win by coming
across as youthful (at 54), flexible and above all fresh.
</P>
<P>
   But it has left onlookers uncertain as to what he believes in,
and how he will now act.
</P>
<P>
   First, he must set up a coherent and plausible team of
ministers. He has attractive, lively-looking candidates for some
posts -- a computer entrepreneur, Jost Stollmann, to take charge of
the economy, Walter Riester, a forward-looking trade unionist, to
deal with labor, Michael Naumann, a civilized publisher, for the
arts. But his hand is not wholly free.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he is obliged to give the Greens, his chosen
partners in coalition, some important jobs. The Greens' leader,
Joschka Fischer, is serious and mostly sensible. But, egged on by
their woollier elements, the Greens have some pretty silly ideas --
for instance, for tripling gasoline prices -- that they have only
recently and reluctantly shelved.
</P>
<P>
   Many Greens remain hostile to NATO, not to mention the idea that
Germany should play a bigger part in peace-keeping abroad. The
leadership has moderated its stance, but a Green foreign minister,
as has been suggested, would give some cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, there is Oskar Lafontaine. The doyen of the
party's socialist old guard, Lafontaine is much less of a
modernizer than Schroeder, and is far less keen to reform Germany's
increasingly unaffordable social-security system. Yet he commands
great support within his party and will plainly exercise much
influence, perhaps as finance minister. Schroeder will have a hard
job preventing him from tearing the heart out of any radical labor
and welfare reforms that the chancellor seeks to make.
</P>
<P>
   The hope must be that, now that his electoral victory is won,
Schroeder will become bolder -- if need be, beating back the more
foolish ideas of the reds and Greens with threats of seeking help
from the Christian and Free Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   As yet there is no reason for other countries to fear a
Schroeder administration, even if its assessment of Germany's
national interests may be more jarring to its neighbors than Kohl's
used to be. That, after all, will be evidence of normality.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder will not apologize for putting Germany first. In the
European Union, he may fight Germany's corner more obviously than
Kohl did. He might also make a bigger effort to strengthen
Germany's links beyond its special friendship with France -- to the
east, to Britain, even to America.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, would bespeak a new German attitude to the world. It
should not be feared. It is welcome. Long may Germany be boring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
