<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4304 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMITATORS-PRESIDENTIA     10-01 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMITATORS-PRESIDENTIAL-COMEDY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL THE REAL PRESIDENT (CLINTON, BUSH, REAGAN, KENNEDY ...) PLEASE
STEP FORWARD? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   You have to squint a little bit and get kind of a gravelly roll
in your throat, as if you're on the verge of a cold.
</P>
<P>
   Your voice should be soft but clear. Then you twang it up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can work on the hand gesture. It's almost as if you're
holding an imaginary remote control, your thumb poised to click at
any moment _ but you work your arm up and down, as if you're a
priest dispensing incense.
</P>
<P>
   But you're no priest. You're Billy Clinton!
</P>
<P>
   You too can imitate the president. Go ahead and give it a try,
using the directions outlined above.
</P>
<P>
   Not sure what to say? Come on, you know all the familiar
catchprases:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building a bridge to the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel your pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I want you to listen to me. I did not have sex with that
woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Very good! Welcome to the club. You're now one of the 50 million
people in the United States who has attempted a Bill Clinton
impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   With his distinctive voice, his undeniable charisma, his easily
lampooned sexual appetites and his ubiquitous presence on TV,
President Clinton is a dream chief executive for every professional
and amateur comedian who looks to the White House as a source for
humor. He is probably the most imitated human being in history.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody on the radio imitates Clinton; on any given morning,
there must be at least 500 heavyset guys in satin jackets who are
doing Clinton in a skit featuring the newsman as Ken Starr and the
perky sidekick as Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Even Howard Stern, who rarely bothers to attempt more than a
half-hearted attempt to duplicate a celebrity's vocal mannerisms
(his O.J. just sounds like Amos and Andy), has developed a dead-on
Clinton imitation in recent months. It's brilliant, and you can
tell Howard is surprised and thrilled with his impersonation every
time he trots it out.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern is not the King of All Clinton Imitators. That title
belongs to Darrell Hammond, who is sort of the heir to Phil Hartman
_ a bland-looking white guy who can slip into dozens of characters
with smooth comedic finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Hammond's triumph is that he sort of looks like Clinton.
Unlike other presidential imitators on ``SNL'' who had to be
heavily made up to resemble their target, Hammond needs only to put
on a suit and he's good to go.
</P>
<P>
   The key, of course, is the voice _ and Hammond more than any
other comic has captured the deceptively complicated vocal patterns
of the president. A rudimentary impersonation of Clinton is rather
easily attained, but Hammond has spent a lot of time studying the
subtle nuances of Clinton's speech, as well as the almost
evangelical way in which the president romances the camera.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it could be argued that Hammond's Clinton is the best
presidential imitation since Rich Little's take on Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure some vaudevillian did a killer take on Woodrow Wilson,
and no doubt there were radio comics who lampooned FDR's fireside
chats, but as far as I'm concerned the modern era of presidential
impersonations began with JFK duplicate Vaughn Meader.
</P>
<P>
   Meader's 1962 album, ``The First Family,'' reached No. 1 on the
charts and won the Grammy for Album of the Year. Meader's brief
moment in the spotlight happened before my time, but I have heard a
few snippets of ``The First Family.'' He did a pretty good job with
the president's famous voice, but the humor was mild and
affectionate _ downright corny by today's standards. They say
Meader's career died the day the president was assassinated _ but
how much of a career was the guy going to have if he just had the
one trick in his bag?
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Johnson, with a voice as big as Texas and a personality
to match, would seem to have been a perfect subject for
impressionists, but there wasn't any one comic who made a big
splash with an LBJ routine.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but Nixon! With his dark scowl, his habit of shooting his
arms to the sky in a double V salute, his baritone voice and
phrases such as ``Let me make one thing perfectly clear'' and ``I
am not a crook,'' the adult Nixon was juicy fodder for comedians
such as David Frye and Rich Little.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, after Nixon was out of office, Dan Aykroyd
skewered him on ``Saturday Night Live,'' most memorably in a skit
in which he told ``Henry Kissinger'' to get down on his knees and
pray. ``Saturday Night Live'' was also the home of Chevy Chase's
imitation of Gerald Ford, which wasn't really an imitation at all.
The mussy-haired, then-skinny Chase didn't even try to look like
the stocky, bald and much older Mr. Ford - he just fell down
beautifully, in ``tribute'' to Ford's occasional public stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Aykroyd and a number of other comics tried to duplicate Jimmy
Carter's blinding smile and his soft Georgia drawl, but there
wasn't much more to work with. Carter was dull, and so were his
mimics.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, the first actor-president, was a goldmine. Reagan
was in office for eight years, and he had a unique speaking style
as well as a TelePrompTer filled with memorable sayings, from
``There you go again'' to ``Make my day.'' He was imitated by
dozens of comedians, from Joe Piscopo to Harry Shearer to Randy
Quaid to Phil Hartman. Surprisingly, though, no single comic
emerged as the definitive Reagan imitator of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with George Bush. Dana Carvey owned George Bush. (For
that matter, Carvey also owned Ross Perot _ but oddly enough,
Carvey failed miserably when he attempted to make the transition to
a Clinton imitation.)
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us up to the Clinton era, and the legions of
funnymen and wannabe-comics who just can't resist trotting out
their presidential imitations. Politics aside, when Clinton leaves
he will be missed by those who have duplicated his voice over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   On the presidential horizon: Al Gore, or maybe George W. Bush
(the president's eldest son), or possibly Bill Bradley. Wooden,
boring and tall, in that order. Enjoy the Clinton era while it
lasts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
