<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4313 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-CYBERTIMES-ED     10-01 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-CYBERTIMES-EDUCATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST PREPARATION COMPANY OFFERS VIRTUAL LAW DEGREE 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to the Internet, a company best known for its courses to
prepare students for college admissions exams now plans to offer
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But a big question faces Kaplan Educational Center's new Concord
University School of Law, a four-year juris doctorate program
offered entirely online: Can virtual classes provide the kind of
education that trains students to think like well-spoken lawyers?
</P>
<P>
   Concord and Kaplan officials are convinced the answer is
``yes,'' but others are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to launch October 6, Concord University plans to
charge $4,200 a year for its four-year program -- a fraction of the
$6,500 to $26,000 charged yearly by ``bricks and mortar'' schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan is targeting working professionals and others who cannot
make it to a classroom regularly, but desire a legal education and
are willing to get it from an unaccredited school. Jack R. Goetz,
dean of the school, which is based in Los Angeles, said Kaplan has
received about 2,000 inquiries from potential students and
``dozens'' of applications since the venture was announced last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a wide array of people, working professionals and
others, who just want legal education,'' he said. ``There are tons
of people who just can't put down everything at 5 p.m., quit their
jobs and make it to evening class to begin legal education.''
</P>
<P>
   Goetz believes that technology can replace what goes on in a
conventional classroom. The Concord program will rely on
video-streamed lectures from law professors, supplemented with
standard textbook readings and discussions that will take place via
e-mail, by phone or in virtual chat rooms. ``We are able to offer a
quality legal education at less than the cost of fixed facility
schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Carl C. Monk, executive director of the Association of
American Law Schools, is among those who question whether ``cyber''
can adequately substitute for ``real'' when it comes to
jurisprudence. ``I am very skeptical of a degree offered totally
through online instruction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Monk pointed out, law schools are increasingly
offering students the opportunity to work under supervision with
real or simulated clients -- an experience that demands
face-to-face interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, Monk and others say, is that an
essential task of law school is training students to think and
respond quickly. Although not as favored today as it was in the
past, the Socratic teaching method, in which a professor asks
students probing questions to elicit well-thought out responses, is
still common in legal education.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a courtroom, if you are asked a question by a judge, you
can't say 'I need a day or so to look that up on the Web,''' said
James L. Hoover, associate dean and professor of law at Columbia
University's School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Goetz responds that students can learn clear thinking through
Concord's writing and research requirements. In addition, he
questions how often law students really get to exchange ideas with
their professors. ``Mostly today you have 110 people stuffed in a
lecture room and one professor engaged in a Socratic dialogue with
one student,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, one thing is clear: Concord officials do not
expect to get the blessing of the American Bar Association, the
main national accrediting body for law schools. Students who
graduate from one of the 182 ABA-approved schools in the United
States may take the bar examination, a licensing requirement, in
any state.
</P>
<P>
   Concord graduates, on the other hand, will face certain
obstacles if they want to practice law. They will be able to sit
for the California bar examination, the prerequisite for a license
to practice in that state, if they first pass the state's ``baby
bar,'' an exam given to students at unaccredited law schools after
their first year, according to Goetz.
</P>
<P>
   If they wish to practice elsewhere, they may be eligible to take
the bar in 10 to 15 other states -- but only after practicing in
California for three to 10 years, Goetz said.
</P>
<P>
   Concord officials have not applied for ABA accreditation
because, among other things, the organization's guidelines
currently call for at least 1,120 hours of ``in residence'' study.
``We recognize that an online law school doesn't fit into these
guidelines,'' Goetz said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is that the American Bar Association does not look
kindly on correspondence courses. Kurt S. Snyder, assistant
consultant on legal education to the American Bar Association, said
a big question if Concord were to apply would be whether its course
of study amounted to a correspondence course or to something
different, such as an online forum that provided for meaningful
professor-to-student and student-to-student exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Goetz believes that chat rooms, e-mail discussions, phone
conversations and electronic feedback on tests are good
substitutes. And Jonathan Grayer, Kaplan's chief executive officer,
hopes one day to apply for bar association recognition and make the
case.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Goetz is convinced that Concord will attract
what he believes is a large body of potential lawyers and students
who do not necessarily want to practice law, among them scholars
who want to deepen their knowledge of jurisprudence and business
people who think knowing the law will help them in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not competing with ABA law schools, the Harvards and
the Yales of the world,'' he said. ``We are competing for people
for whom law school is otherwise inaccessible.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Concord University School of Law: concord.kaplan.edu/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Pamela Mendels, a Manhattan-based writer, covers education,
government, censorship and civil rights issues for CyberTimes.)
</P>
