r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATEWAY-CYBERTIMES-TR     10-01 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATEWAY-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATEWAY'S SOLO 2500LS PACKS IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm always amazed at what Gateway charges for its computers. The
company seems to bundle everything but the kitchen sink with their
systems and still charge rock-bottom prices.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the Gateway Solo 2500LS. The unit I reviewed
was a 233-Megahertz Pentium II with MMX technology. It has a 12.1
inch SVGA, TFT active matrix display, an enhanced TouchPad (more on
that later), a 4GB hard drive, 2Mb of video RAM, a CD-ROM, a floppy
disk drive, two USB ports, an NTSC external video connector (for
displaying the output of TVs, VCRs and camcorders,) a 56K modem,
Windows 98, Microsoft Office Small Business Edition and a quite
nice carrying case. I upgraded the memory from 32 to 64 Megabytes
of RAM (an additional $100). All of this was priced at $2,349.
</P>
<P>
   Price alone makes this an attractive laptop, but it also stands
out on its own merits as well. The 2500LS beats a couple of systems
I've reviewed that cost a whole lot more. I threw everything at it
and it more than held its own. I loaded it with all my standard
stuff -- three Web browsers, two e-mail packages, software for the
Palm Pilot, some proprietary software for connecting to The Times'
Atex system, Adobe PhotoShop, Gizmos98 (a real system hog,) and my
current crop of system-intensive games.
</P>
<P>
   The system didn't even seem to breathe hard. It even survived a
heart-stopping, totally unplanned drop test. Some rowdy school kids
bumped into me and the unit slipped off my shoulder and bounced
onto the concrete platform of the Times Square subway station. The
bag obviously provided some protection, but I know of a couple of
units that would not have survived the fall. The 2500LS booted
right up with no sign of any problem with the unit.
</P>
<P>
   The 2500LS is an all-in-one laptop. An all-in-one unit is one
that contains a built-in CD-ROM and floppy disk drive and often a
network connection. These units are heavier, but you don't need to
carry any external devices like a CD-ROM or a floppy disk drive.
Those two devices add a couple of pounds to a laptop. A light 4-lb.
unit goes up to 6-plus lbs. with the added external equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But if you need to run an application that requires a CD or want
to save information to a floppy, you have to carry them and their
cables and connectors with you. The weight ends up being the same
but with lots of extra stuff that is not necessary when the laptop
has everything integrated. The Solo 2500LS weighs 7.1 lbs. It's one
ounce over my 7 lb. limit for laptops, but in this case, I'll make
an exception.
</P>
<P>
   I have made no secret that I'm not a big fan of TouchPads. But
the new enhanced TouchPad that comes with the 2500LS is turning me
around. It may be that the documentation for how to use the
TouchPad is so good. This is the first time that I've had a
detailed explanation on how to use a TouchPad effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The enhanced TouchPad has new features that make it more
user-friendly. I'm a right mouse button user. I find the shortcuts
available through the right mouse button options increase my
productivity. Tapping with 3-fingers on the TouchPad brings up the
right mouse button options.
</P>
<P>
   The enhanced TouchPad also has a scrolling option along the
right side of the unit. Scrolling through Web pages or long
documents is a breeze with the TouchPad. I can't say enough about
the documentation provided with the 2500LS. The text is in English
and the graphics are clear and helpful.
</P>
<P>
   I can't let the 2500LS off with an entirely clean bill of
health. The tiny LCD screen that tells you of the system's status
battery life, hard drive/CD-ROM activity and whether you're using
AC -- is unreadable in low light conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Picky, Picky.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Gateway: gateway.com/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen C. Miller is assistant to the technology editor at The
New York Times.)
</P>
