<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4326 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTZ-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      10-01 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTZ-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANTZ' CRAWLING WITH DETAIL, HUMOR WOODY ALLEN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Woody Allen has always been a funny little guy _ but
not this little.
</P>
<P>
   Woody turns up picnic-crumb size in the first of the season's
two animated bug movies, ``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   You remember Woody's early movies, when his sole goal was to
make us laugh at the tribulations of his neurotic life? Movies like
``Bananas,'' ``Take the Money and Run,'' ``Play It Again Sam''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz'' is a throwback to those comedies, which means it's
likely to be funnier for adults than young kids.
</P>
<P>
   Allen provides the voice for Z, a common worker ant with an
uncommon problem: He's afraid of crowds, which he blames on the
fact that he was the middle child in a family of 5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of verbal humor Woody dishes out as the computer
animation wizards create the life of an ant colony, wonderfully
imagined and amusingly realized. ``Antz,'' coming to us from Steven
Spielberg's DreamWorks Studio, proves conclusively that Disney
doesn't own all the artistic talent in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   As Z struggles to find himself, he becomes the accidental hero
in a war against the termites, kidnaps the princess (Sharon Stone),
and inspires a revolution when his best friend (Sylvester Stallone)
realizes that the worker ants ``control the means of production.''
</P>
<P>
   While Z and the princess dare the dangers of the outside world
searching for an insect paradise, the colony is threatened by a
general who wants to breed a race of superants.
</P>
<P>
   As in all animated films, it's the attention to detail that
makes the experience special. ``Antz'' is full of visual novelties
and clever humor that give us a telling bug's-eye view of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The film's writers have conceived Woody Allen shtick that only
occasionally rises to the best of the master's work but is
consistently amusing to see coming out of the mouth of a bug.
</P>
<P>
   It's also fun playing match-the-ant-to-the-voice, as the cast
includes Dan Aykroyd, Anne Bancroft, Jane Curtin, Danny Glover,
Gene Hackman, Jennifer Lopez and Christopher Walken (all right, the
Walken ant you can't miss).
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz'' provides one other Hollywood first: Where else but in
an animated film would Woody Allen get to romance Sharon Stone?
</P>
<P>
   As the first of the two animated ant movies to reach theaters,
``Antz'' stakes out the territory and sets a high standard for
Disney's ``A Bug's Life'' to match or surpass when it's released
this November. But ``Antz'' does leave room if ``A Bug's Life'' is
geared more for younger kids than the sophisticated comedy of
``Antz.'
</P>
<P>
   Smart kids 10 and older should enjoy most of the verbal humor in
``Antz'' while finding the visual creations highly entertaining.
But younger children may be confused by Woody's patter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz'' is rated PG, rather than the G that nearly all animated
films receive. Why the more cautionary rating? ``Antz'' contains a
couple of mild profanities that some parents may find
objectionable. Also, the battle between ants and termites is
unsettling in its devastation, creating an anti-war message that
calls for peace among insects.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe right after we achieve peace among primates. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WILD-BOS &LR;      10-01 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WILD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOVE INTEREST HERE IS A CONTINENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FIONA LUIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RULES OF THE WILD 
By Francesca Marciano 
Pantheon, 292 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is decidedly over, and more's the pity. Francesca
Marciano's first novel would have made a fitting companion during a
day at the beach. At its strongest, ``Rules of the Wild'' strives
to capture the expatriate's sense of dislocation and estrangement
amid the sweep of Africa. Stripped of this expansive canvas, it's a
simple love story struggling to find its footing.
</P>
<P>
   Set in contemporary Kenya, ``Rules of the Wild'' tracks the
pilgrimage of its Italian heroine, Esme, as she is cast adrift in
an emotional desert after her beloved father, a Neapolitan poet,
dies of a brain tumor. Numbed by her state of mourning, Esme
travels to east Africa, oblivious to her surroundings until the
close of the trip, when geography stakes its claim on her:
</P>
<P>
   ``On day seven we moved to the middle of the Masai Mara, to a
luxury tented camp surrounded by more ferocious American tourists.
... I remember smelling the rain. I could see dark clouds heading
our way, thick lead against blue sky. That incredible sky, which I
was seeing at last, took my breath away. ... In the stillness
before the storm, the plains opened before my eyes. The gentle
shape of the acacias, the herds of zebra and wildebeest and buffalo
dotting the yellowing grass in the distance: it all came alive and
whatever had been dead inside of me slowly started to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   At the genesis of this nascent overseas life, the figure who
helps pull Esme out of the darkness is Adam, a handily named
Kenyan-born safari leader. The somewhat pat touch with names
continues when Esme's renewal through romance is complicated by
Hunter Reed, a stereotypic portrait of the enigmatic, driven
foreign correspondent who documents strife wherever it takes him _
Rwanda, Somalia, or Afghanistan. So even as she explores her newly
adopted Garden of Eden, she stumbles and becomes Hunted.
</P>
<P>
   The telling of this love story, this tortured triangle, never
quite transcends its geometric convenience. What does, however, is
Marciano's love for, and rendering of, the consuming geography of
East Africa. Perhaps the protagonist of ``Rules of the Wild''
should have been the continent rather than a heroine who, at her
worst, is allowed to verge on the vapid. In the throes of her
affair with Hunter Reed, witness the quote of a friend who notices
she is spending time with him: ``You two are both so cerebral.''
That's just lame, and Marciano should have been saved by an editor
from lines like it. Clearly, the allure of Africa moves the author
to write her better lines, to paint her most stunning portraits.
Next to that sensory richness, the foibles and frettings of a white
expatriate community register as utterly secondary.
</P>
<P>
   When Marciano turns a critical gaze squarely onto the culturally
dislocated, she manages more of a triumph:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, everyone does try to have a go at history here. ... Our
prestige depends on the assumption that this is the last outpost of
wilderness and we are the last batch of Romantic heroes. Most of us
have built our careers around this assumption, and now entire
families depend on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of the Wild'' is a vexing book, engulfed with
contradictions: a palpable promise of depth battles with waves of
insipid romance, a tidal sweep of geographic grandeur and cultural
discord fights to overcome ripples of nonchalance. Yet there is
enough of a current here, a heat that draws me close, and I found I
was not willing to set the book aside.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian documentary filmmaker who splits her time between
Rome and Kenya, Marciano writes with consuming, abiding passion
about her second home. And it is all the more remarkable that she
gives voice to her story in English, which is not her native
tongue. It is this deft straddling of two worlds, and the respect
she accords this precarious dislocation, that allows her to sing
her song of Africa with grace. It's certainly not an easy universe
to inhabit _ the outsider's pitfalls of condescension and
imperiousness loom large _ but she navigates it commandingly.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, the love story of Esme, Adam, and Hunter and the
supporting story line of hacks and artists become secondary. What
is lasting is the sense that one woman embarks on a safari of the
heart, and pursues her solitary redemption amid the engulfing
soulscape of Africa. Let not the occasional stretch of banal
dialogue stall you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
