<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAND-BREAKUP-AZR &LR;      10-01 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAND-BREAKUP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL OVER FOR THE REFRESHMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - One of Tempe's most popular bands has come to an
unfortunate end, as the Refreshments called it quits due to a storm
of personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Gin Blossoms, the Refreshments helped define the
Tempe music scene on a national scale. Perhaps best-known as the
guys behind the theme song to TV's ``King of the Hill,'' the group
announced its breakup through a carefully worded news release
Wednesday that pointed out some of the turmoil that the Mill Avenue
Band has weathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in a working band requires that everyone be in the best
of health and spirit,'' the statement reads. ``We regret that
(guitarist) Brian Blush has had troubles with addiction, and on
several occasions we've reached out in an effort to help him
overcome his struggles. In an attempt to force the issue, after
much contemplation and with heavy hearts, Brian Blush has been
dismissed from the Refreshments.''
</P>
<P>
   Blush was unaware of the release until it was read to him. He
didn't disagree with the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I had been expecting,'' Blush said. ``I'm in no
way, shape or form bitter. I think my dismissal is warranted.
That's not to say it doesn't completely break my heart. I live to
play in that band.''
</P>
<P>
   The Refreshments enjoyed a brief but impressive run in the
national music scene. The group's three albums collectively sold
more than half a million copies, establishing their picaresque
songs with music fans across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The group rose to rare heights for a local band. Formed in late
1993, the band hit the Mill Avenue scene the following year with an
irreverent sense of humor and colorful lyrics with a Southwestern
slant.
</P>
<P>
   The group's debut album, ``Wheelie,'' came out on local label
Epiphany later that year. The mammoth PolyGram organization took
notice of the band, signing them to a contract. The group's 1996
effort, ``Fizzy,'' ``Fuzzy, Big &AMP; Buzzy,'' sold more than 400,000
copies and produced a pair of radio hits in ``Banditos'' and ``Down
Together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the group's slide began with the second PolyGram release,
1997's ``The Bottle &AMP; Fresh Horses.'' Sales were disappointing.
After the ironically titled ``Good Year'' failed to click with
audiences, a secondsingle never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel a heavy responsibility for that effort failing,''
Blush said. ``I was the author of ``Good Year.'' It shouldn't have
been a single. The label chose it as a single, and the band never
wanted it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was dropped by the label after finishing a tour in
support of the album. Following a Cinco de Mayo concert earlier
this year, bassist Buddy Edwards chose to leave the band. Breakup
rumors began to swirl soon after.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pretty much 8,000 different reasons why I chose to
leave,'' Edwards said Wednesday. ``I guess it seems like it was
time. We made two (major label) records and had quite a run.
Everything in my life pointed me toward something more civilized,
more toward living like a civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   He left in June with plans to go back to school and work on a
novel _ ``It's not about rock and roll,'' he says. His departure
made the breakup nearly inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support Buddy's decision to leave the band and wish him the
very best, and success with future endeavors,'' the statement
reads.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my favorite things about a Refreshments show was
watching Buddy,'' Blush said. ``It wasn't about guitar virtuosity;
it was about style. I hated to see him go. If I told him that he
could drag me for four miles behind his pickup truck on my bare
belly to make him stay, I would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Blush's problems, he says he was called into a meeting by
two other band members, drummer P.H. Naffah and lead
singer/guitarist Roger Clyne. He was given an ultimatum about his
personal problems three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He admits his addictions but declines to discuss specifics. He
says he plans to enter a treatment facility Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that I can say is that I never missed a
Refreshments gig,'' he said. ``I played with all of my soul. If
they had to excavate me and step me up on stage, I probably still
could pull off the riffs and put on a decent show.''
</P>
<P>
   He sounded a bit bewildered about the band issuing a statement
to the press without consulting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're human beings,'' he said. ``They've been to my house,
and they've discussed these issues with me, but I don't know. . . .
Maybe they think they've run out of options, which I can
understand. But . . . these are guys that stood up at my wedding _
I'd rather not be told through the newspaper that I'm out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Refreshments' manager, Michael Lustig, who still handles
Clyne and Naffah, said the two will continue in the music industry.
Neither was available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   From the band's statement: ``The Refreshments was a unique
collaboration between four musicians. . . . Without all four
original members, the special collaboration that made up the band
would be inarguably different; therefore, we shall no longer use
the moniker `The Refreshments.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Blush agrees with those words, though he still sounds
shellshocked by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bitter,'' he said. ``It would have taken death to get
me to leave that band. I hadn't planned on these circumstances. I
love the fans, and I'm grateful for the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the phone rang right now and they said that we had a
gig tonight, my stuff would be in the back of the truck, and I'd be
there. That's clearly not reality. . . . Reality is something I've
had to learn to take healthy doses of these days.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
