<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN AD CAMPAIGN COURTS HISPANIC, ASIAN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Republican candidate for Senate has begun
airing a series of television commercials designed to chip away at
incumbent Barbara Boxer's turf, the Asian-American and Hispanic
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are the first for the campaign of State
Treasurer Matt Fong, and the ads will air in Cantonese, Mandarin,
Spanish and English, stressing issues such as education and family.
</P>
<P>
   Fong campaign manager Sal Russo said the ads would air all over
the state, including the politically liberal San Francisco area, a
stronghold for Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce Herschensohn never advertised in the Bay area,'' Russo
said of Boxer's 1992 Republican opponent, a conservative
commentator who lost in a close race. ``He conceded a big chunk of
territory. We're not conceding any territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boxer campaign Wednesday announced the start of an Internet
advertising campaign. The campaign is putting banner ads on news
Web sites with links to the Boxer campaign Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very inexpensive way to reach people,'' said Boxer
campaign manager Rose Kapolczynski. The ads will cost several
thousand dollars, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Russo would not disclose how much the Fong campaign would spend
on the commercials. The first Spanish-language ads began airing
Tuesday in Sacramento, and the Chinese-language ads were to begin
in the San Francisco area on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some have questioned whether Fong could raise enough money to
compete on with Boxer on television, who aired her first commercial
on Sept. 11. This week, her campaign launched commercials attacking
Fong for not supporting new bans on assault weapons and so-called
``Saturday Night Specials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If she had poured $4 million or $5 million into ads in June,
we couldn't have matched that,'' Russo said. ``Now that we're in
October, we have money to wage an effective campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials highlight some of Fong's positions on education,
including his support for mandatory testing of students, merit pay
for good teachers and the removal of violent and disruptive
students from classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish- and Chinese-language ads open with the line, ``Matt
Fong's highest priority is family.'' Russo said he expected the
spot to play well in Hispanic and Chinese-American communities,
which place a strong emphasis on family.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities were the key swing vote for Boxer in 1992. But Fong
appears to be making inroads, especially with Asian voters. An exit
poll taken during the June primary by San Francisco political
consultant Tom Hsieh Jr. showed that while more than 80 percent of
Asian-American voters in San Francisco voted for a Democrat for
governor, 76 percent voted for Fong. Only 20 percent supported
Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Kapolczynski said she expected little if any defection of
Asian-American Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Boxer has been very active on issues of great concern
to the Asian-American community, like public education and
Asian-American appointments ...'' Kapolczynski said. ``I think when
they compare the two candidates, Asian-American Democrats will
stick with Senator Boxer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
