<SLUG> BC-SHREDDER-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING CON BAIT INTO CONFETTI  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA HELSER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Diane Rose doesn't care to share.
</P>
<P>
   So instead she shreds.
</P>
<P>
   Canceled checks, credit card statements, outdated documents &UR; and
any other piece of paper containing her name and account numbers
that might prove profitable in unscrupulous hands.
</P>
<P>
   With an electrical gadget Rose keeps on her kitchen counter, the
Scottsdale housewife merrily makes mincemeat out of her private
papers before throwing them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love doing this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The object of Rose's affection is her new home-style paper
shredder, a convenience that's fast becoming almost as popular in
Arizona households as bread machines and espresso makers.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech shredding has been a rapidly growing security measure
for businesses disposing of sensitive information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of commercial shredding companies has doubled in
the last seven years,'' said Robert Johnson, executive director of
the National Association for Information Destruction, a
Phoenix-based trade association for commercial shredders.
</P>
<P>
   And now it is an equally vital practice for private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my work I know people go through garbage and steal
credit card numbers,'' said Catherine Hughes, a Phoenix attorney.
``That's why I bought one for my personal use.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller and more affordable than commercial versions, the new
home models that both Rose and Hughes invested in sell for as
little as $25 at office supply outlets and are not much bigger than
a lunch box.
</P>
<P>
   More sophisticated home models range upward to $200 and include
crosscut shredders that turn paper into confetti for as little
$100. Heavier-duty motors account for higher prices, which in
general have decreased 15 to 20 percent for comparable models in
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; David Jordan, manager of a Phoenix Staples, said that customer
interest in home shredders is definitely on the upswing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just keeps rising and rising,'' he said. ``We're selling
three times as many now as we did 1{ years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ditto at the OfficeMax in Tempe, Ariz., according to
manager George Parker. ``Seems like it's people past their 40s who
are buying most of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parker assumes that older shoppers are perhaps more aware of the
consequences of stolen papers because of a bad experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can get stung really badly once someone commits
fraud with your information and it takes a lifetime to sort out,''
he said. ``It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Local law enforcement officials could hardly disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Vernon Busby of the Phoenix Police Department said that his
document-crime detail is besieged with mail-theft horror stories
and that victims' losses are rising dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losses used to range from $25 to $30,'' he said, ``but now
it's starting to be in six figures.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Busby said it's difficult to estimate how many of his fraud
cases relate to the misuse of personal information retrieved from
dumpsters because of the manner in which they are tabulated.
</P>
<P>
   But since a common scenario is to wash away ink on canceled
checks acquired through ``dumpster diving'' and then rewrite them
for large amounts, shredding of checks can only help to protect
potential victims.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-approved credit card application and home mortgage loans
also are worthy of thorough shredding.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is sign it, put in a change of address and
mail it back,'' said Karie Dozer, spokeswoman for the Attorney
General's Office and confirmed shredder. ``And crooks don't even
have to go sift through the coffee grounds to get them,'' she said,
referring to items in recycling bins.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't just checks and pre-approved credit applications
that crooks are after when they dumpster-dive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``They call them identity-takeover thefts, and it's one of the
fastest-growing crimes of the '90s,'' said Leo Nolan, inspector for
the U.S. Postal Service. ``Thieves get your name, address, phone
number, driver's license number, Social Security number, mortgage
account numbers, credit card number and line of credit, and then
they go to town with all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But shredding may be only a temporary protection.
</P>
<P>
   With so much personal information now available on the Internet
and even more expected in the future, ``five or 10 years from now
shredding won't do any good,'' Busby said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rose will be hard-put to abandon the practice for a more
current deterrent to crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recycle the shredded paper on my ceramics because it's great
for when you're firing in the kiln,'' she said. ``It burns into the
finish, giving the pottery a Southwestern or Asian form.''
</P>
<P>
   And she also uses the shredding for packing gifts such as
delicate glassware and other breakables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds crazy, but I've always wanted this
shredder,'' she sighed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Linda Helser can be reached at linda.helser(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
