</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TATTOO-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVING TATTOOS IS COSTLY, TIME-CONSUM ING AND IFFY  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG CARROLL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Somewhere along the way, well past flared polyester
slacks but shortly after yuppie guys with earrings, we became
Tattoo Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make this easy: Raise your hand if you (begin ital) don't
(end ital) have a tattoo, if you're (begin ital) not (end ital)
walking around with a Chinese dragon breathing fire down your
forearm or a barbed-wire motif guarding your ankle or a butterfly
flitting about your . . . well, ma'am, you know where that insect
is, and thank you for not sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Tattoos, once the province of sailors, soldiers and elements of
society that could charitably be described as ``fringe,'' are fully
mainstream now. And in American pop culture, you know what that
means: Sooner or later _ probably sooner than the freshly tattooed
can imagine _ they'll become passe.
</P>
<P>
   ``How '90s,'' people will say, perhaps in the disdainful tone
they now reserve for most things '70s.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike other fads that have come and gone, a tattoo
can't be dropped off at the church clothing drive or chopped off at
the hair salon. When it gets under your skin, that's where it stays
unless extraordinary measures are taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so ridiculously mesmerized by the whole fashion thing,''
says Dr. Jeff Ptak, a Phoenix plastic surgeon who removes tattoos
by laser treatment. ``Most of fashion is here today and gone
tomorrow, but this is one that's here today and here tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, it may become a widespread concern, and not just for
the gaudily decorated Dennis Rodmans among us. Tattoo removal has a
big downside: It's costly, time-consuming and not always completely
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Rosenberg, a dermatologist who also uses laser to
remove tattoos, insists that the trend hasn't peaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got back from Telluride, (Colo.), and I've never seen
so many people with new tattoos,'' Rosenberg says. ``People don't
see the big picture. They don't see that it might not be to their
advantage in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg refers to his office in north Phoenix as the ``Room of
Regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People live for the moment _ especially the young,'' he says.
``The mind-set is the permanence of it. They think they're
immortal, and then something happens to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like youthful feelings of indestructibility, body art is hardly
new. The word ``tattoo'' comes from the Tahitian ``tatu,'' meaning
``to mark something,'' and Egyptians used tattoos to indicate
social ranking as early as 2000 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese once used tattoos to mark convicted criminals, but
that changed around A.D. 1700, when only members of Japan's royal
family were permitted to wear embroidered clothing. Outsiders began
getting tattoos to adorn themselves without breaking that law.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the first electric tattoo machine was patented in
1891, tattooing began to catch on in the United States. In the late
1950s, it was outlawed for a time in New York City when a boy
contracted blood poisoning from being tattooed with an unsterilized
needle. A hepatitis outbreak in 1961 also resulted in a ban on
tattooing in parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona passed a law in 1996 requiring the presence of a parent
or guardian for those younger than age 18 wishing to be tattooed.
Even so, underage teens are getting tattoos, often from
less-than-reputable sources.
</P>
<P>
   Gang members make up a sizable percentage of this group, and
Ptak is involved in a Phoenix program designed to help them lose
the tattoos and find a positive direction in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a survival aspect to this (for gang members),'' Ptak
says. ``If you're branded, you're a target from now on. There's a
lot of indiscriminate violence because of tattoos.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, there are two options for altering a tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   The first is to have it covered over by another design. This
accounts for a fair amount of business at tattoo parlors,
particularly among lovelorn customers. (John has split up with
Nancy, but there's one big problem: He's still wearing her name _
and in a very private place.)
</P>
<P>
   The other option is to have the tattoo lasered off. Dr. Mark
Meyers, who works with Rosenberg at the Dermatology, Vein &AMP; Laser
Institute, says a tattoo of 4 square inches that cost $100 may cost
10 times that to remove.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of lasering is that it leaves little or no
scarring, unlike surgical excision (cutting the tattoo out),
dermabrasion (scrubbing the skin away), salabrasion (using salt to
abrade the tattoo) or chemical peels (using acid to burn away
layers of skin). Although not painless, there is considerably less
discomfort with lasering than with the other methods.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the process works: The laser emits a short pulse of
intense light, which passes through the top layers of skin, where
it is selectively absorbed by the tattoo ink. This breaks up the
ink into smaller pieces, which can be more easily excreted by the
immune system. Normally, the tattoo fades.
</P>
<P>
   Darker-skinned people may have a slight ``halo'' where the
tattoo was, although normal pigmentation usually returns, Meyers
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laser is the state of the art _ there is nothing better,'' he
says. ``The '90s lasers are really fine-tuned for the target.
They're very precise. The skin is spared as far as the technology
will allow.''
</P>
<P>
   Most tattoos require six to 10 treatments to remove, Meyers
says, and several weeks must be allowed between treatments for the
skin to heal and for the body to remove the maximum amount of ink.
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Workman _ tattooed from shoulder to wrist on both arms
and from knee to ankle on both legs _ has been going to Meyers for
treatment for five years and is far from finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say a tattoo is fine if it's in a place you can
readily cover in a social situation,'' Meyers says. ``But if it's
not, often you can't go anywhere in your career. I've had guys
working for major corporations who have been told, `You've got to
get that off, or you won't be promoted.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen tattoos everywhere _ and I mean everywhere _ on
people's bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tattooed makeup is very difficult to remove, and eyeliner is
impossible because of the dangers involved in working so close to
the eye with the laser.
</P>
<P>
   All of which seems to be of little consequence to the customers
seen by Dick Goldman, proprietor of three Blue Dragon tattoo
parlors in the Phoenix area and Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   If tattoos are an acquired taste, most have acquired it well
before they become marked men and women, Goldman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people made up their mind a long time ago and are
prepared for it,'' he says. ``Most people who aren't prepared don't
get one.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is that everybody should have at least one tattoo,
and preferably more.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Doug Carroll can be reached at doug.carroll(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
