<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSIES-RUSSIA-$ADV     10-01 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSIES-RUSSIA-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRIAL AND ERROR: HOW TO BUILD A BETTER EMBASSY, THE HARD WAY
 &HT;    With EMBASSIES-FUTURE-$ADV04.
 &HT;    With photo placed in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ One of America's newest embassy buildings has been
three decades in the making and tens of millions of dollars
over-budget.
</P>
<P>
   But don't blame simple government inefficiency, at least not
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The main culprit was Cold War spying.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-story chancery building rising above the U.S. embassy
complex in downtown Moscow is cloaked in white tarpaulins to mask
the work inside from prying eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The tarps also are a reminder of one of the biggest blunders in
the history of international espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1979 using Soviet workers and materials, construction
of the building proceeded apace until 1985. As the work was winding
down, mortified U.S. officials discovered the entire structure had
been laced with microscopic listening devices -- thousands of them.
</P>
<P>
   The red brick building was dubbed ``The Great Transmitter'' and
remained empty until work resumed several years ago with a target
completion date of late 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction uses materials and construction workers are
imported from America and carefully screened by U.S. security.
Construction workers are not allowed to talk about their work or
even acknowledge the reason they are in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Workers have lopped off the top two floors of what was an
eight-story building and are rebuilding four new floors on top.
They were unable to extract all the bugs from the lower floors, but
stripped much of what they could.
</P>
<P>
   The building, originally projected in 1979 to cost $72 million,
will cost U.S. taxpayers $240 million or more. An early proposal to
raze the building and start over was rejected as too costly.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 300 construction workers are housed in temporary
shelters on the site. It is not open to tours for the press or
public. Most embassy employees have never been inside either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unique for a working embassy. We have a construction
site in the middle of our complex that we can say very little
about,'' said embassy spokesman Michael Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the secrecy is to mask the components of a
building that will house America's spies. The Cold War may be over
but their work goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The new upper floors will be occupied by embassy staff
conducting classified business -- presumably the CIA, defense and
political analysts and the ambassador and other diplomats. The
lower six levels, which still may have listening devices embedded
in the concrete foundations, will be used by staff conducting
non-sensitive work.
</P>
<P>
   The delay had one positive effect. The new building will include
modern anti-terrorism security features -- including reinforced
walls, doors and windows -- that did not exist when it was
conceived.
</P>
<P>
   It also will have air-conditioning, which the current main
building at the complex does not. The original brick will be
replaced with a white limestone and glass facade.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy compound covers a city block near the Russian White
House and includes offices, living quarters for some diplomats and
their families and facilities for expatriate Americans, including a
day-care center, school and swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
