<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-TROOPS-$ADV03-     10-01 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-TROOPS-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPLACEMENT TROOPS ARRIVE IN BOSNIA FROM FORT HOOD
 &HT;    With TROOPS-BOX-$ADV03.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of locator map, Camp McGovern is directly
south of Brcko, which is on the Croatian border, west of the
Serbian/Croatian border.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Oct. 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP MCGOVERN, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ For U.S. Army Pvt. John
Wilbur, the difference between Fort Hood, Texas and his new station
here is simple. In Bosnia, he has to sleep on a cot.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect this 17-year-old Albany, Ga. native, who's been
in the Army all of six months, to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sleep anywhere,'' Wilbur says in a Southern drawl, while
downing a pizza at the Rose Garden Cafe near the center of this
camp. ``I'm in the Army ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur is one of about 5,000 soldiers from the U.S. Army 1st
Cavalry Division at Fort Hood deployed in Bosnia-Herzegovina last
month to relieve peacekeeping troops from a several U.S. bases in
Germany -- the majority of a total force of 6,900.
</P>
<P>
   While canvas folding cots may be the first thing Wilbur noticed
about his new assignment, bombed-out buildings and boredom may be
what he remembers most from his tour in this war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
   If he's lucky, he may get a break from radio duty once in a
while to go out on patrols of the area. The patrols roam villages
and towns along the Zone of Separation (ZOS), a narrow
three-mile-wide strip of land that winds through Bosnia and
separates the former combatants. Armed with M-16 and .50-caliber
machine guns mounted on Humvees, the patrols cover a 9,000-square
mile area about the size of Maine to reassure the masses that NATO
will not let a war start again here.
</P>
<P>
   Around Camp McGovern, there are reminders of the suffering that
was a way of life here when war gripped this country for years.
Entire neighborhoods in the ZOS still lie in ruins. And even
several miles away, in Brcko (pronounced ``Burch-Ko''), the nearest
city, the once thriving downtown is riddled with blown-out
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. soldiers are among 33,000 NATO peacekeeping troops in
Bosnia enforcing the military provisions of the Dayton Peace
Accords which, in 1995, ended the four-year ethnic war caused by
the break-up of Yugoslavia. Immediately following the U.S.-brokered
cease-fire in December 1995, the International Stabilization Force,
or SFOR, disarmed the three combatants -- the Bosniak Muslims,
Croat Catholics and Serbian Orthodox Christians -- and began
working to rebuild the war-torn country and re-establish peace in
the once multi-ethnic society.
</P>
<P>
   That job may have been made all the more difficult by the
elections in mid-September that resulted in anti-Western candidates
making significant gains in the Serbian state that surrounds the
40-acre Camp McGovern -- one of six in Bosnia-Herzegovina -- on
three sides.
</P>
<P>
   But if Wilbur doesn't get on a patrol now and then, he may spend
the next six months inside the camp, never even getting a peek at
the local politics or the fall-out from the elections.
</P>
<P>
   He, and his comrades from Fort Hood, also may not get a chance
to see how the locals feel about the presence of U.S. soldiers
here.
</P>
<P>
   The one group that seems to make the biggest impression on the
soldiers are the children. And like so many of the soldiers from
Fort Hood, Staff Sgt. Lonnie Radabaugh worries about the children
he sees when he's out on patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the children all wave to us,'' he said during a
recent patrol. ``You wonder what they've gone through, how they'll
grow up in all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Few soldiers here who've been on patrol are not stunned by the
level of devastation. At the same time, however, they are just as
heartened by the efforts to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really interesting to see how hard these people are
working to get their lives back together,'' Pfc. John Brumley,
originally of Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, said during a break on a recent
patrol. ``Every day when we go out on patrol, that's all they're
doing, working to rebuild their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   While some in the U.S. Congress argue about how long American
forces should stay in Bosnia, U.S. soldiers who have been living in
tents here since 1995 began to build wood huts a few months ago in
camps like McGovern. By the end of the year, Army officials here
expect to have the approximately 1,000 soldiers at McGovern living
indoors, just in time for the worst of the usually wet Yugoslavian
winter. (The remaining 4,000 Fort Hood troops are also expected to
move into wood huts.)
</P>
<P>
   The new officer in charge of the camp sees his mission as a
long-term one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just pull out, then general war starts again; and if
that happens and it starts spreading to other countries in Europe,
then we've got to come back in at great risk of loss of life,''
said Lt. Col. Mike Ryan, of New York City. ``It takes awhile. It's
not just cut and dried, 'OK, the war's over, now let's all get back
together.' It takes a long-term commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern isn't the only camp to get better accommodations for
soldiers in the past few months. Once President Clinton decided in
June to extend the troops' mission, the Army started improving
facilities all over Bosnia. A permanent dining facility is being
built at Camp Comanche, about 37 miles south of Camp McGovern, and
a larger and more permanent hospital facility at Eagle Base, the
main U.S. installation in Bosnia -- located in Tuzla, south of
Brcko.
</P>
<P>
   With the extension, Army officials said they're working hard to
keep the soldiers from getting too bored, or too homesick.
McGovern, for example, has a cafe, pool hall and gym. Soldiers,
also can take college courses and participate in basketball
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   There's no alcohol on the base, or at any of the U.S.
installations in Bosnia, however, so the soldiers have to settle
for the Army's idea of good clean fun. They can call home for 15
minutes every week for free and Ryan is having a computer room set
up so they can e-mail friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of young kids, separated from wives for first
time,'' said First Sgt. Kevin Kenneally, of Killeen, Texas, a
23-year Army veteran. ``Those are the ones you have to be careful
with. They will get bored if they don't do something.
</P>
<P>
   I've told my company, all staff sergeants and below will be
involved in correspondence courses,'' he said. ``It soaks up a lot
of their time, and it's good for their career advancement.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the limitations, most of the soldiers from Fort Hood
were surprised at how well they live at McGovern, compared to the
conditions for which they were trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as bad as what we thought it would be,'' said Pfc.
Ernest Curtis, of Austin, Texas. He said the extra pay he gets for
being in a hazardous area, and the experience of serving in a
peacekeeping mission are probably the best aspects of being
stationed in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no bad things,'' he said, pausing to think for a
moment. ``Well, there are no dance floors, no country bars and no
beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he plans to offer Curtis and the rest of the Fort Hood
soldiers a taste of home in the next few days by raising the Texas
flag under Old Glory.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
