<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOMEZ-MUSIC-LADN     10-01 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOMEZ-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A SHOESTRING
</HEADLINE>
 CORRECTION: Correcting the slug 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The announcement of the prestigious Mercury Music
Prize two weeks ago in London was a shock to everyone _ especially
the members of Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   The five young musicians, who recorded their award-winning debut
album on a shoestring in bedrooms and garages over the space of a
year, don't produce the Brit-centric pop of fellow nominees like
Pulp, Massive Attack and the Verve.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gomez is steeped in Americana, proudly pointing to such
landmark acts as Little Feat, the Band, Dr. John and Captain
Beefheart as signposts on the way to developing a unique sound.
</P>
<P>
   Tunes from Gomez's hard-to-pigeonhole album, ``Bring It On''
(Virgin), include ``Tijuana Lady,'' which could be an Eagles
outtake, and ``Free to Run,'' which late Little Feat leader Lowell
George would've been happy to call his own. The surreal-sounding
first single, ``78 Stone Wobble,'' recalls Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very American feel to the record,'' admits Gomez
singer-keyboardist Tom Gray. ``It's almost exclusively American
music we listen to. But bands coming along and experimenting with
American music because they love it is a constant theme in British
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez _ the name was borrowed from the last name of a friend _
appears Saturday with Eagle-Eye Cherry at the El Rey Theatre in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were five guys bored with the contemporary music scene in
Britain,'' Gray said this week. ``And that's not a good thing for
five people who are in love with music. We couldn't find what we
wanted, so we went out and did it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The British rock weekly New Musical Express dubbed ``Bring It
On'' one of the most ``assured, poised, hilarious, out-there ...
enjoyable albums in living memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The five guys in Gomez, none of whom is older than 21, came
together two years ago, but at least two members have been friends
since their childhood in Southport, near Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   Holed up in a cold garage, huddled over their amps and tape
console, the group cut ``Bring It On'' before ever performing
onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened very naturally,'' Gray said. ``When we play
together, that's the sound that comes out. The recording was five
friends having fun. It was recorded in bedrooms, garages _ all over
the shop. We had a little old 4-track tape machine that was
half-broken and you had to balance a book on the power supply to
make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gomez signed to Virgin, the tapes were taken to a
full-service studio, where the roughest parts were re-recorded. But
the slightly murky lo-fi quality adds to the disc's warm, bluesy
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs have always been the basis of Gomez,'' Gray said. ``We
love songs. I mean, we like to play with the structures, but I
think the most important medium in music is the song. Five years
ago, when the dance scene was at its height, people were saying
songs don't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today, even dance music has gotten very song-oriented.
That's because the song is too strong culturally. It means too much
to too many people. There's nothing better than a great song.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody picked ``Bring It On'' to bag the Mercury Prize. Among
the 12 competing albums were acclaimed efforts from such
top-selling acts as the Verve, Massive Attack, Portishead, Robbie
Williams, Asian Dub Foundation and Cornershop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt fantastic,'' Gray recalled. ``We weren't
expecting it. A lot of the people who work around us were willing
us to win, but certainly it came as a huge shock. It's difficult to
quantify what an award means to anyone. But it sure felt nice. This
was an album we made in our spare time for the love of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
