A4417 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ANTZ-SPI &LR;      10-01 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANTZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY DAZZLES IN DREAMWORKS' `ANTZ' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DreamWorks Pictures' first animated feature, ``Antz'' is
certainly no ``Bambi,'' but it is a visually engaging and
moderately entertaining fantasy that makes another eye-popping
showcase for the fast-evolving art of computer animation.
</P>
<P>
   The first of two big-budget, computer-animated features about
humanoid insects on Hollywood's fall release schedule (the other is
Disney's ``A Bug's Life,'' due Nov. 25), it's short on heart, but
dazzling to the eye and filled to the brim with familiar movie-star
voices.
</P>
<P>
   Its rather flippant storyline is about an angst-ridden worker
ant (voice of Woody Allen), who can't quite get into the narrow
regimentation of colony life, and dreams of individuality and a
more meaningful and fulfilling existence.
</P>
<P>
   One evening at an ant dance hall, he meets the colony's slumming
princess (Sharon Stone), and falls in love with her. Desperate to
see her again, he illegally trades places with a soldier-ant pal
(Sylvester Stallone) so he can pass before the royals in a parade
of troops.
</P>
<P>
   For his trouble, he's thrown into an epic battle with a
neighboring termite, and a series of circumstances that finally
propel him and his princess out of the colony and into
``Insectopia'' _ the enticing-if-perilous upper world of New York's
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its benign PG-rating, ``Antz'' is not the greatest film
for small children. Its termite battle scenes are as explicit as
``Starship Troopers,'' the storyline is no Aesop's Fable and it
simply doesn't deliver the kind of cuddly characters that will make
a tot warm up to its rather cold vision of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Directors Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson and their team of writers
also go for a tongue-in-cheek, hip humor that seems aimed at an
older audience, or designed to show off the special talents of
Woody Allen and a star-heavy supporting vocal cast that includes
Gene Hackman, Christopher Walken, Jennifer Lopez, Anne Bancroft,
Danny Glover, Jane Curtin and Dan Aykroyd.
</P>
<P>
   But it's impossible not to be impressed with the technology that
has gone into this sumptuous computer-generated vision of insect
life _ which already seems to have advanced a generation or two
since 1995's ``Toy Story.'' In every way, the CG-imagery appears
amazingly fluid, less mechanical and more life-like than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vast ant crowd scenes _ with seemingly hundreds of
thousands of individual figures, each doing a different thing in
the frame _ literally take your breath away. Whatever else you say
about ``Antz,'' it creates its own epic world, and it makes us
eager to see what the same studio will do with its even more
expensive, more ballyhooed, animated-Moses story, ``Prince of
Egypt,'' come Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Antz. Directed by Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson. Screenplay by
Todd Alcott, Chris Weitz and Paul Weitz. Voices: Woody Allen,
Sharon Stone, Gene Hackman, Sylvester Stallone, Christopher Walken,
Jennifer Lopez. DreamWorks Pictures. 77 minutes. Rated PG for
insect violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4418 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DREAMS-SPI &LR;      10-01 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DREAMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SOME EMOTIONAL IMPACT, `WHEN DREAMS MAY COME' DISAPPOINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any movie set almost entirely in the afterlife seems doomed to a
certain kind of failure from the start. There's simply no way to
deal seriously with the subject without wandering into the realm of
theology _ and making a quasi-religious statement.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Ward's ``When Dreams May Come'' might have had better
luck had it tried to be a more gentle, transcendental, even New Age
vision of the sweet hereafter _ or an audacious and original vision
like ``The Rapture,'' which left itself open to a variety of
interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Bass's script is so grounded in Hollywood imperatives,
and so intent on being acceptable to all denominations and points
of view, that _ despite its undeniably striking visuals _ the film
comes off as being weak and unconvincing on one hand, and shrill
and fundamentalist on the other.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of a New York doctor (Robin Williams) who, after
his two children have been killed in an automobile accident, has
painstakingly rebuilt his life and his relationship with his
grieving wife (Annabella Sciorra), an artist and art historian.
</P>
<P>
   When he is killed in a second car accident, he finds himself in
a pleasant if disorienting and wildly inconsistent heaven, where he
learns the ropes from his long deceased medical mentor (Cuba
Gooding Jr.), and gradually is reunited with his dead children.
</P>
<P>
   He soon learns, however, that, in her grief over losing her
entire family, his wife has committed suicide, thereby dooming
herself to an everlasting hell more gruesome than anything in the
Book of Revelations. From here, the hero's quest is to rescue his
wife's soul and fully reunite the family.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Ward, the New Zealander director of ``Vigil'' and ``The
Navigator,'' has a special penchant for the metaphysical in his
films, and a strong visual sense that has expressed itself here in
a succession of stunning images, many of them conjured from
medieval paintings.
</P>
<P>
   And based on the number of people weeping around me in the
film's Seattle preview last week, ``Dreams'' definitely will have
an emotional impact and inspirational effect on many _ especially
those who recently may have lost a loved one, or those who embrace
a traditional religious point-of-view.
</P>
<P>
   But it never really connects as the quest-adventure it sets out
to be. Since we never quite ``know'' the rules of this afterlife,
we never get caught up in the hero's efforts to beat the system;
and the inevitable Hollywood happy ending comes as something of a
non sequitur.
</P>
<P>
   The film also is rather flat as a romance. The doctor's love for
his wife is developed in an overly slick title sequence and then
frequently stated, but never quite felt. The script makes the case
that they're timeless ``soulmates,'' but it's hard to fully
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the filmmakers risk critical damnation by setting
their last act in an Old Testament Vision of Hell-with-a-capital-H
_ fire, brimstone, millions of shipwrecked souls, a God of
Punishment. It steers the movie right out of the New Age and right
into the domain of Oral Roberts and Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   What Dreams May Come. Directed by Vincent Ward. Screenplay by
Ron Bass. Cast: Robin Williams, Cuba Gooding, Jr., Annabella
Sciorra, Max Von Sydow. Polygram. 113 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
mature themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4419 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-IMPOSTERS-SPI &LR;      10-01 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IMPOSTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IMPOSTERS' DUE REPRIMAND FOR IMPERSONATING A MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's not much to say about a comedy that falls as flat as
Stanley Tucci's ``The Impostors.'' As hilarious as it may have
seemed on paper, the writer-producer-director-star fails to bring
off even a single scene. Sitting through it is a grueling
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci's idea, apparently, was to pay tribute to Billy Wilder's
``Some Like It Hot'' with a '30s period farce about two failed New
York actors (Tucci and Oliver Platt) who have to go on the run
after they inadvertently assault a famous Shakespearean actor
(Alfred Molina) in a barroom brawl.
</P>
<P>
   When they hide aboard a ship bound for Paris (which, by the way,
Stanley, is not on the ocean), it turns out the offended famous
actor is also on board. So, to avoid detection, the guys must
disguise themselves all through the voyage as stewards, buxom
women, etc.
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of his ``Big Night'' success, Tucci has managed
to assemble an impressive cast of American Indie stars to join him
out on this long, perilous limb: Campbell Scott, Isabella
Rossellini, Steve Buscemi, Lili Taylor, Elizabeth Bracco, Hope
Davis, Tony Shalhoub, Billy Connolly, even Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   All will live to regret it. No one comes off well: The humor is
so tortuously hammy and slapsticky it makes even the best of them
look inept. The very concept makes no sense: Who would go on the
run for offending a second-rate actor? And why would anyone rip off
``Some Like it Hot'' and leave out the Marilyn Monroe character?
</P>
<P>
   The one thing you can say about ``The Impostors'' is that it's
easy to know where to put the blame for its failure. Tucci not only
writes and directs abysmally, he also delivers the film's most
thoroughly unappealing performance. And he can't keep the camera
off his face. He clearly thinks he's just adorable.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's real casualty could be Oliver Platt. Arguably
Hollywood's top character actor of the late '90s, he's so smothered
in Tucci's ego and mugging guest stars here that even he looks like
an amateur. As the current front-runner for the 1998
supporting-actor Oscar (``Bulworth'' ``Simon Birch''), this misfire
could cost him dearly.
</P>
<P>
   The Impostors. Directed and written by Stanley Tucci. Produced
by Tucci and Beth Alexander. Cast: Tucci, Oliver Platt, Alfred
Molina, Lili Taylor, Steve Buscemi, Campbell Scott. Fox
Searchlight. 102 minutes. Rated R for no obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
