<HEADLINE>
`NIGHT AT THE ROXBURY' IS HARMLESS FLUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things move in waves at the movies, and disco currently is the
craze. Whit Stillman's ``The Last Days Of Disco,'' was first out of
the gate. All those flaring white bell bottoms and wide-lapel suits
came back into style and one could almost hear the ghost of Donna
Summer wailing, ``Love to love you baby,'' again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Night at the Roxbury,'' which is a whole lot more fun and
memorable than the current box office dud ``54,'' a ``tell-all''
about New York's drug-addled, elite celebrity haunt, is the
surprise in a less-than-memorable pack.
</P>
<P>
   And that's high praise for a film that has very little going on
other than to feel the beat and heat of two bumbling, badly
coiffed, gold-chained brothers, Steve and Doug Butabi (Will Ferrell
and Chris Kattan), who want to score big with the babes in L.A.'s
finest club, The Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a ``Saturday Night Live'' skit, the siblings, played by
SNL regulars Ferrell and Kattan, follow in a long line of big
screen schlubs pulled from the ailing, long-running late-night
show. Steve and Doug silently bump and grind against every
available female on the dance floor in hopes they might actually
persuade one of them to engage in a one-nighter (not that either
brother would know what to do with a ``willing babe''). So far
they're batting zero.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another red flag that keeps the Butabi boys from
reaching the nirvana of being admitted to The Roxbury: ``No one
gets in unless you're on the list,'' barks the formidable bouncer.
It's been a bumpy ride fraught with rejection, but where there's a
will, there's a way.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrell and Kattan, who embody Steve and Doug Butabi with a
vengeance and goofiness fringing on embarrassment, have broadened
the borders of their reptilian low-life skit by adding parents
(played by a spitting, shouting Dan Hedaya and a somnambulistic
Loni Anderson), as well as a dream; they want to open their own
nightclub _ one that will rival the allure and glamour of The
Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Night at the Roxbury'' is a terrible movie for the first
half hour, but then surprisingly, it finds its heartbeat, pulse and
pace and blossoms into an engaging, silly delight.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of working in daddy's Beverly Hills silk flower store and
even more exhausted over the endless rebuffs they've received while
trying to gain entrance into their dream disco, Steve and Doug
finally hit gold; they're rear-ended by ``21 Jump Street'' star
Richard Grieco, a regular at The Roxbury, who promises the boys
entree into eden to avoid a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Butabi's are thrilled. Who cares about daddy's crunched car?
Once inside the club they discover the new world. They catch the
eye of two ripe babes who mistakenly take the guys for rich
entrepreneurs because they've fumbled their way into the attentions
of the club's wealthy owner, Mr. Zedir (Chazz Palminteri).
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys ultimately gain a potential business partner. Only
dad stands in the way. How can they make their plan come to life?
Well, there's some psychology 101 to wade through. But in the long
run, this is pretty funny cotton candy tinged with Freudian
dysfunction. It has the depravity to humorously touch on brotherly
incest and the conflict between parents and siblings and how
expectations tear a aprat family _ even one as goofy as this.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can't take any of it too seriously. In the end ``A
Night at the Roxbury'' is just that _ a night out that fades into a
light, pleasant memory in the morning. And there's no hangover.
</P>
<P>
   A Night at the Roxbury. Directed by John Fortenberry. Written by
Steve Koren, Will Ferrell, Chris Kattan. Cast: Will Ferrell, Chris
Kattan, Dan Hedaya, Loni Anderson, Richard Grieco, Chazz
Palminteri. Paramount Pictures. 87 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
