<HEADLINE>
`LOLITA' ON SCREEN WAS BETTER THE FIRST TIME AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, Stanley Kubrick's ``Lolita'' would seem to be
the rare movie classic that could stand a remake. After all, in the
movie climate of 1962, Kubrick had to dance all around the subject
of a 37-year-old man's lust for a 14-year-old ``nymphette.''
</P>
<P>
   And devotees of the book's author, Vladimir Nabokov, never have
completely forgiven Kubrick for so playing up the book's humor that
he turned the story into a farce. Surely the time has come for a
more serious treatment of a serious novel.
</P>
<P>
   But the new ``Lolita'' has fared badly. First of all, the
filmmakers badly underestimated what an inflammatory,
hysteria-inducing subject pedophilia is in late-'90s American
society. Truly, it is our last taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, after the film was completed last year, the major
distributors refused to touch it. It finally made its debut on
cable earlier this year (after months in movie never-never land),
and even now it's getting only a modest, art-house theatrical
release.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, as good as the film is in many respects, the concept
of a more ``serious'' treatment of Nabokov's novel has proven to be
less appealing on celluloid than it did on paper. The story seems
to demand a heavy sense of irony, even comedy. Without it, the film
is a long 137 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious difference between the ``Lolitas'' is, of
course, the explicitness of the love scenes. Where the relationship
was mostly suggested in 1962, here we see the two mismatched lovers
in more than a few moments of steamy passion.
</P>
<P>
   But the more profound difference between the two versions may be
in the way they treat the central character of Humbert Humbert _
the refined, if sexually warped, European professor who marries an
annoying New England woman so he can be close to her 14 year-old
daughter, Lolita (who is, by the way, only 12 in Nabokov's novel).
</P>
<P>
   James Mason played him in the original as a fairly contemptible
lecher _ a classic dirty old man. But Jeremy Irons makes us believe
Humbert is profoundly in love, and Stephen Schiff's adaptation
gives him a compelling, even sympathetic, psychological motivation
for his stunted romantic tastes in females ``between the ages of
nine and 14.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Lolita'' is also a period piece: set in 1947, largely
on the road as HH and Lo tour the country. As always with the films
of Adrian Lyne (``Flashdance'') the film is a visual feast. Indeed,
his vision of backroads America _ motels, gas stations,
greasy-spoon diners, nostalgic road signs _ deserves an exhibition
in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   The script, however, is considerably less authentic. Lolita
talks about ``zits'' and even has a ``See you later alligator/After
while crocodile'' exchange with a friend _ a full decade before
Bill Haley and his Comets popularized the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   The performances could hardly be better. Irons is agonizingly
believable as a man lost in a hopeless and destructive love affair;
and 15 year-old newcomer Dominque Swain is just as credible as the
selfish, shallow object of his affection. As a portrait of tragic
sexual obsession, the new ``Lolita'' recalls ``Of Human Bondage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film somehow pales in comparison with Kubrick's
sassier, less sexually explicit rendition. As misguided and
self-indulgent as he may have become in his later career, Kubrick's
filmmaking instincts were dead right in 1962: to fly as a film, a
grotesque subject like the love affair of ``Lolita'' requires a
sense of the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Lolita. Directed by Adrian Lyne. Screenplay by Stephen Schiff.
Cast: Jeremy Irons, Dominque Swain, Melanie Griffith, Frank
Langella. Goldwyn. 137 minutes. Rated R for sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
