<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ST.PETERSBURG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARATIONS CAN MAKE A VISIT TO ST. PETERSBURG A TRUE DELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ As the guide marched us into a prized
temporary exhibit at The Hermitage in St. Petersburg, perhaps the
world's greatest art museum, she barked out a classic Russian tour
order: ``Ten minutes for the Cezanne. Ten minutes!''
</P>
<P>
   We begged 15 minutes and later negotiated a half-hour for the
incredible collection of French Impressionist paintings, much of it
confiscated from Czarist businessmen by Bolshevik authorities after
the 1917 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   There are no gains without pains, however. We were given less
than 10 minutes for the Dutch and Flemish masters, including the
museum's 25 Rembrandts. And we were made to march without stopping
through the Egyptian collection.
</P>
<P>
   Often called ``The Venice of the North'' for its architecture,
beauty and setting by water, St. Petersburg was founded in 1703 by
Peter the Great, who created out of a swamp the most northerly of
the world's great cities. The headstrong czar laid the foundation
after his victory over the Swedes in the Great Northern War.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 300 years later, in touring the city, Americans will feel
almost on a military timetable while visiting such famous
attractions as the Hermitage and the Peter and Paul Fortress.
</P>
<P>
   Dawdle to photograph reflections in the Neva River, or buy a Red
Army flask at a kiosk, and the guide will upbraid you in tones
reminiscent of those Marshal Georgi Zhukov upbraiding subordinates
while he was directing the defense that turned back Nazi armies at
the gates of the city in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   We spent about a week touring St. Petersburg and its environs in
mid-August, just as Russia's currency crisis began. Even in its
elegance, in the midst of baroque palaces and great neoclassical
buildings, visiting Russia's ``Window on Europe'' had the feel of
third-world travel.
</P>
<P>
   The international airport was dingy. Beaten-up cabs waited to
transport visitors at a fare to be negotiated. The streets seem to
have last been resurfaced when Stalin was in power. Hookers
inhabited lobbies of the few swank hotels. Beggars waited outside
the gate of Tikhvin Cemetery, where famed composers
Rimsky-Korsakov, Mussorgsky, Borodin and Tchaikovsky are buried.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we found the city enchanting. So will anybody who
remembers a quartet of informal guidelines used by adventure-minded
Americans to navigate in the globe's disorganized places.
</P>
<P>
   Advance preparation: Before you go anywhere near St. Petersburg,
invest in enough time to learn about the place. The Baedeker guide
is excellent for basic sightseeing. Harrison Salisbury's ``The 900
Days'' (Da Capo, 635 pages, $18.95) is indispensable for treatment
of the World War II siege of the city _ then called Leningrad _ in
which 1.1 million people died.
</P>
<P>
   Although out of print, Suzanne Massie's ``Pavlovsk'' should be
hunted up at the library. It tells the history of a great czarist
summer palace, its destruction at the hands of German occupiers,
and its painstaking 25-year restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Why do such work? Because you will know the origins of a faded
blue sign on Nevsky Prospect: ``Danger from enemy artillery.'' Or,
touring the Peter and Paul Fortress, you will come upon _ and have
some understanding of _ Mikhail Shemyakin's controversial
avant-garde statue of Peter the Great, with its tiny head, massive
body and spindly fingers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Russian Museum, you'll know where to find striking
paintings by Kandinsky, as well as paens to Stalin in the style
authorities dubbed ``Socialist Realism.''
</P>
<P>
   The get acquainted tour: Even if it means a forced march, take
an official tour to get a fix on what's located where. Once you
find out how not to get lost in The Hermitage, then you can return
on your own timetable and lose yourself in The Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   A bus ride will identify wonderful walks. Just in back of the
Russian Museum, for instance, is the Church of the Resurrection _
commonly known as the Church on the Spilled Blood. It was built by
Czar Alexander III on the spot where his father, the reformist Czar
Alexander II, was assassinated in 1881. (During a visit to the
city, President Clinton took an unplanned walk here, much to the
consternation of his Secret Service detail.)
</P>
<P>
   After inspecting mosaics of this church, you can stroll down
Canal Griboedova to the neoclassical Kazan Cathedral, used during
Soviet times as a museum to celebrate atheism. Another block's walk
will take you to the vastness of Palace Square and a pose for
pictures at the foot of Alexander Column, built to commemorate the
victory over Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching out: Connections mean everything in Russia. Try to make
some even before your trip, or find ways to reach out once you are
there.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Washington state's prominent Democrats, ex-state chair
Karen Marchioro and Jeff Smith, learned the name of a superb guide
and were rewarded with not only a tour of the city but of nearby
czarist summer palaces and Lake Ladoga.
</P>
<P>
   (The guide was Olga Kornilova. Write to her at: Dolgoozernaya
13, A.P. 70, St. Petersburg, 197371, Russia.)
</P>
<P>
   Our group, from St. Augustine's-in-the-Woods Episcopal Church on
Whidbey Island, Wash., linked up with our sister parish, St.
Nicholas' Cathedral in Pavlovsk about 19 miles south of St.
Petersburg. Friendships were instantly made.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-year-old in our group, Jason Pierson, was taken in tow by
two 18-year-old girls and found himself at a town festival immersed
in conversation with English-speaking college students.
</P>
<P>
   The priest's daughter, Anna, took us to Catherine Palace in
Tasarkoe Selo, almost completely destroyed in 1944. Restoration of
such features as the Amber Room, looted by German occupiers, is
still under way.
</P>
<P>
   What if you go to St. Petersburg without contacts? Ask questions
and strike up conversations at places you visit. This can be more
rewarding in Russia than any place else in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Russia is difficult and unpredictable _ and, during the
Soviet era, filled with facade and pretense. Intense conversation
is a form of national relief. Such talk with foreigners used to be
frowned upon, with the KGB making every effort to listen in. But
nowadays, everyone seems to have a story to tell. We exhausted
translators, and somehow managed to communicate by smiles and
gestures when words gave out.
</P>
<P>
   From such outreach, we heard the war stories of an 85-year-old
veteran who lost three fingers fighting the Nazis, and accounts of
rebuilding the Great Palace at Pavlovsk from an architect who
worked on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Team travel: St. Petersburg has a bit of a crime problem, so
Americans are wise to travel in twos or threes. The cyrillic
alphabet must be roughly understood. The subway system _ the St.
Petersburg Metro _ is a cheap, easy way to get around.
</P>
<P>
   If you are photographing the Samson Fountain and Great Cascade
at the Peterhof palace, west of the city, somebody needs to keep
track of when the last hydrofoil leaves for The Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   The group is sure to come home with shared memories and
adventures. Inevitably, each person will commit a faux pas, about
which friends can rib him (or her) for years.
</P>
<P>
   Pierson has come up in the world for a boy from Aberdeen, Wash.
He graduated from Gonzaga University and had headed off to begin
graduate studies at Yale Divinity School. Pierson will, however,
need time to live down a Tikhvin Cemetery visit in which he
strolled up to Dostoevski's grave, decorated with a bust of the
great writer, and asked: ``Who is this dude?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
