<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following auto features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AUTOMOBILES-BLOOM (Undated) _ The lower price discounts
and continued cost-cutting helped profitability for all three major
automakers. Still, Detroit automakers' earnings are increasingly
threatened by economic problems that are damping demand in Latin
America and Asia. By John Lippert.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-DEALS-LADN (Los Angeles) _ Consumers shopping for a new car
this fall are in for a dose of sticker shock. But it won't be
painful; indeed, they should leave the dealerships smiling and
maybe with some cash in their pocket. They will be reaping the
benefits of a rare autumn buyers' market as automakers offer
lucrative incentives on the last of the 1998 models and, on
numerous lots, are slashing prices on new 1999 models just hitting
showroom floors. By Gregory Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CAR-BUYING (Undated) _ A look at a new car buying service on
the Internet. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-INSURE-LAWSUIT-NYT (Washington) _ When Mark Covington
drives his 1992 Chevy Cavalier at night, the beam of the left
headlight wobbles across the road, and in daylight, the red paint
on the hood shows an odd ridge on the left side. He blames his
insurance company: After his wife crashed the car into the back of
a pickup in April, he said, he took the car to one of the best body
shops in Laurel, Miss., but the shop had to use generic parts.
``State Farm just absolutely refused to put GM parts on it,''
Covington said. Lawyers are seeking to add him to a large
class-action suit against State Farm. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-CAR-SHOW-BLOOM (Paris) _ More than a dozen cars will make
their debuts at the Paris auto show next week, which includes
displays by 50 companies. The show runs Oct. 1 to Oct. 11 at the
Porte de Versailles. By Brian Lysaght.
</P>
<P>
   BATTERY-VEHICLES-HNS (San Francisco) _ While the world's auto
companies struggle to create a viable electric vehicle, a small
swarm of electric bicycles and scooters are humming off the
assembly lines at Zap Power Systems, a company trying hard to seize
the tiny but growing U.S. market for electrified transportation. By
Matt Beer.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES-OUTLOOK-BLOOM (Detroit) _ U.S. vehicle sales rose
about 7 percent in September on a surge in light trucks at Chrysler
Corp. and Toyota Motor Co., as well as General Motors Corp.'s
recovery from this summer's strikes. By Paul Gargaro.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-OLDSMOBILE-NYT (Undated) _ Oldsmobile is hoping that
the newest member in its lineup, the entry-level Alero, a compact
sedan and coupe just hitting the market, will generate up to
150,000 sales a year. It's a tall order for this small car. After
test-driving two versions of the Alero, I concluded that it has
many pluses, but wondered if they would be enough to take on the
world's heavyweights. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-COLUMN-AZR (Undated) _ Model year 1999 is an evolutionary
one for the world's automakers, with a tuck here, a tweak there,
and a couple of face lifts. Only a few models are brand new for
'99, plus the re-entries of a couple of old names, as the
manufacturers gear up for the new millennium. Corvette adds a
model, Oldsmobile adds a compact, Toyota adds a coupe, Buick loses
a coupe, and Infiniti resurrects its entry-level car. As usual,
trucks are huge. By Bob Golfen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
