<P>
   &UR; PLACES AND DESTINATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT-KATAHDIN-HNS (Mount Katahdin, Maine) _ Indians called this
Katahdin, the ``highest mountain.'' Today, the mountain spirits _
one, a nasty creature with a terrible beak and claws; another, a
gigantic human form with stony eyebrows and cheekbones _ are quiet.
These mythical creatures do not throw storms of rain, snow or
sleet. They do not shroud the mountain with chilling fog or
blinding clouds. And they do not wrap the high peaks in a killer
hurricane. Instead, this day, Katahdin is but a whisper. Katahdin
is as calm as the two black ravens pecking about on nearby slopes.
On days like these, a hiker on the Knife Edge can talk downslope
with another some 2,000 feet below. By Fred Stetson.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PEI-COX (Victoria, Prince Edward Island) _ Chasing down a
memory is always a risk. Revisiting a favorite seaside raises
questions: Will how it looks today erase your dreamy images of the
way it used to be? Can any coastal town escape the transforming
tides of ``progress'' and development? Happily, the tiny southern
seaport of Victoria, where I spent the summer of '64, has managed
to dodge both. By Eileen M. Drennen.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOVASCOTIA-COX (Off Digby Neck, Nova Scotia) _ Nova
Scotia is wonderful territory for anyone interested in an active
outdoor vacation, offering great cycling, hiking, birding,
beachcombing and whale watching. In one week, we pedaled through
remote areas on the Digby Neck, visited quiet fishing villages and
experienced hundreds of years of history in Annapolis Royal,
Canada's oldest European settlement. By Denise Prodigo-Herrmann.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ROME-NYT (Rome) _ Rome primps for the millennium, but
will the city be ready in time? By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DISNEY-CRUISE-NYT (Undated) _ The mouse that sailed:
charms for all ages on the Disney Magic. By Jody Alesandro.
</P>
<P>
   FOLIAGE-TOURISM-HNS (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's a buck to be made
in the changing of the leaves, and states are catching on. New
Hampshire and Maine doubled their advertising budget for fall
tourism this year. In response, Vermont took out television
commercials for their own well-known fall foliage. By Alan
Wechsler.
</P>
<P>
   BAHAMAS-NASSAU-COX (Nassau, Bahamas) _ This colonial port city
moves to a soundtrack. I always listen to the rhythms of the
island, and in one weekend I heard Junkanoo, reggae, rap, rock and
sexy soca. By Grace Blackerby.
</P>
<P>
   BAHAMAS-PARADISE-COX (Paradise Island) _ The huge Atlantis
resort on Paradise Island will soon be even more enormous. The
1,200-room, 17-story Royal Towers hotel, which dominates the
island's skyline, will open Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-CRUISE-TEX-HNS (Port Canaveral) _ Forget the nit-picking.
Disney, having conquered the theme park, movie, cable TV and toy
industries, became the big fish in the cruise business the moment
Disney Magic's foghorn blasted out the first notes of ``When You
Wish Upon a Star'' and the ship's 83,000-ton bulk moved away from
the Port Canaveral pier in late July en route to the Bahamas. By
Jeff Guinn.
</P>
<P>
   LUNTS-MUSEUM-NYT (Genesee Depot, Wis.) _ Arts in America: In the
rolling farmland of southeast Wisconsin, Ten Chimneys, the
legendary and utterly peculiar summer retreat of Alfred Lunt and
Lynn Fontanne, for years the reigning couple of the American
theater, is to be come a museum. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-QUABBIN-BOS (Belchertown, Mass.) _ Sixty-five miles from
Boston, the Quabbin Reservoir is the watery heart of Massachusetts.
By William A. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CHINA-NYT (Undated) _ Ancient Pingyao, China's last
walled city. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-VALLEY-COX (Death Valley, Calif.) _ Click. Click. The
sounds of clicking shutters herald dawn as amateur and
not-so-amateur photographers try to capture the brilliant gold-dust
morning of Death Valley. Despite its reputation as a desert
wasteland, Death Valley actually boasts diverse habitats and
experiences for visitors. By Syd Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-VALLEY-SIDER-COX (Amargosa Valley, Nev.) _ Ash Meadows
National Wildlife Refuge, located about 40 minutes from Death
Valley, is a 22,117-acre wetland and upland desert oasis with the
greatest concentration of endemic species in the nation. While
threatened birds are known to haunt this refuge, the endangered
wildlife star here is the pupfish. By Syd Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-VALLEY-LOCATION-COX (Undated) _ Where to go, fees and
accommodations at Death Valley National Park. Compiled by Syd
Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMER NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISE-TREND-NYT (Undated) _ Vows by the bow, teen discos
and pizza parties prove popular on board. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT (Undated) _ Priceline, the Internet auction
service that lets travelers bid for flights, is planning to expand
into hotels; Swiss World Airways, a new carrier, has begun flying
between Newark and Geneva; a new train links Copenhagen
International Airport and downtown; other items. By Janet Piorko.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS-REGULAR FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ You could cruise or fly around the
world to celebrate the millennium. Or you could walk or bike.
Almost any type celebration you can imagine can be arranged _ for
the right price. By Harry Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ There's no city like New York
City. And in fall, it's a great place to visit. By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS (Undated) _ ``New York City'' can bring visions
of hundred-dollar bills floating away, but a trip to the Apple
doesn't have to be expensive. By Richard Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS (Waterloo, Belgium) _ Waterloo. That one word
has said it all for ambition and its demolition over the last 183
years. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS-NYT (Undated) _ Riviera off season; Japan
packages; Southern hemisphere cruises; Fall in Williamsburg. By
Janet Piorko.
</P>
