   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ Democrats on the House Judiciary
Committee huddle with Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri to
develop an alternative to Republican plans for a Watergate-style
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton. Among the options they
are pushing for is a firm timetable to wrap up the investigation,
or some form of punishment short of impeachment. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-HEALTH (Washington) _ The number of older Americans who
can perform simple tasks of daily living _ such as reading
newspapers, carrying a 10-pound bag and walking three blocks _ is
rising, evidence that people are living not only longer but
healthier as well, according to a new study. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICANS (Washington) _ Asian-American children are more
likely to be raised in families with two parents present than are
children in other ethnic and racial groups, according to a Census
Bureau report released Thursday. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CART-MARKETING (Houston) _ Some impressive autos have roared
into Houston for the Texaco Grand Prix, and they're burning plenty
of high-octane marketing fuel. Corporate sponsors are shelling out
$400 million to finance racing teams and adorn them with names like
Marlboro Team Penske, the Miller Lite Ford and the Nicoderm
CQ-Nicorette Champ Car. By GREG HASSELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's not true that all voters think
about is presidential philandering. A Maryland pol who suggested
that owners leash their cats created a public furor and quickly
learned that what people really care about is their pets. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Marianne Means will be away for the next two
weeks. Her column will resume on Monday, Oct. 19.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-SPENCER (New York) _ Shane Spencer has the callouses
on his hands as proof of the dues he paid on all those hot
afternoons in a batting cage. The only thing that came naturally to
Spencer was the stubbornness to not go away until he had worn down
the New York Yankees' resistance to let him show what he can do. By
STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ With one victory under their belts, the
San Diego Padres take on the Houston Astros in Game 2 of series. By
CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN and BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   CAR-CART (Houston) _ Drivers racing in Sunday's Texaco Grand
Prix are getting ready for a new course that they have never been
on before. By TERRY BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, Oct. 4:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BASE-BUILDING (Washington) _ President Clinton is going
back to basics to combat the impeachment threat. He's busy raising
millions of campaign dollars for hard-pressed Democrats seeking
seats in the House and Senate _ and collecting political I-O-Us
along the way. He's wooing traditional Democratic allies such as
labor activists, women, African Americans and Jews _ political
constituencies that have been the backbone of his support. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
