<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VAN-GOGH-EXHIBIT-2TAK     10-01 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAN-GOGH-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY AND THE BLOCKBUSTER ON VAN GOGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Dear Theo,
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday I received your letter in which you say my pictures
make the rooms of your apartment in Paris look so gay. You
embarrass and hearten me. However, I must tell you about the most
incredible night that followed. I dreamed that I was coming to
visit you and Jo, but on your doorstep a terrible beast, a
Cerberus, barred my way. He called himself the Ticketmaster and he
said I must pay a toll or he would not let me pass _ and to see my
own paintings!
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's so ridiculous, I know. I had a fit after waking but
then fell into yet another terrible strange delusion in which my
unfortunate paintings had now been assembled in some vast marble
mausoleum. Thousands of people swarmed and shoved and jostled each
other before them. I want my pictures to touch people, but I never
conceived they would cause so many people to touch each other! They
must have been devil worshipers because I clearly heard the devil
speaking in strange tongues through horns clasped to their heads.
Can you imagine? I need rest.
</P>
<P>
   I hear there's a nice place at Saint-Remy.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The van Gogh exhibition opening at the National Gallery in
Washington on Sunday is a beautiful retrospective of 70 paintings
from the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam, which is now closed for
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   There really isn't much to say about the show conceptually
speaking. It doesn't pretend to tell us anything new about him.
People will complain about the lack of the usual great hits and the
number of minor works, as if all van Gogh retrospectives should
look exactly alike. Actually, to the degree that the show stresses
less familiar pictures, even some bad ones, it makes his evolution
unfold freshly.
</P>
<P>
   A few random notes apropos of the show:
</P>
<P>
   We think of van Gogh as somebody whose art changed radically.
Critics love the cliche of the ham-fisted yokel turned genius, but
we see here how in important ways he really didn't change much at
all.
</P>
<P>
   His roots remained in the Netherlands. In Paris, for instance,
he painted a gem in the manner of early Netherlandish portraiture
(Memling and so on); it's a crisp self-portrait as boulevardier in
blue-trimmed jacket and big bow tie.
</P>
<P>
   In Arles, he gravitated to flat, patchwork fields that he
associated with Dutch landscapes by Ruisdael and to places like the
shore at Les Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer, with its multicolored
fishing boats, which recalled Dutch seascapes.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote from Arles to his brother, Theo: ``I keep thinking of
Holland, and across the twofold remoteness of distance and of time
these memories have a kind of heartbreak in them.'' What he learned
in Paris, he said, was ``leaving'' him: ``I am returning to the
ideas I had in the country before I knew the Impressionists.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, ``The Harvest,'' an orderly Dutchlike scene of ocher
cornfields receding in ranks beneath a cobalt sky, and ``The Yellow
House,'' which echoes an early Dutch picture by him, ``The Vicarage
at Neunen.'' The house and vicarage are both silent, heraldic
places, the discrepancy of palette (muted gray versus peppermint
green and pink) making remarkably little difference in effect.
</P>
<P>
   It's curious how amusing some of van Gogh's pictures are. He
could be funny, though we don't ever think of him that way. An
early work, ``Flying Fox,'' with the animal backlighted, its
translucent wings extended, is clearly a macabre joke, paired here
with ``Skull of a Skeleton With Burning Cigarette,'' an even
funnier picture, and like the fox, lusciously painted in a way that
somehow reanimates the dead subject. It's an image straight out of
Gothic literature.
</P>
<P>
   We know van Gogh read Poe. He was a voracious reader. His
``Still Life With Books,'' painted on an oval Japanese tea tray,
reveals his literary taste. Having done muddy landscapes and figure
studies in the Netherlands, he moved to Paris to recast himself as
a modernist of high-key palette and Japanese style. The still life
is a little declaration of the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He takes pains to indicate the books' titles, including Zola's
``Au Bonheur des Dames,'' the story of a certain Denise Baudu, a
virginal heroine fresh from the provinces who comes to Paris and is
corrupted by life in the metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh was the kind of reader who identified a bit too much
with the subjects of the books he admired, Zola's especially. Maybe
he intended to tell us something here: that, like Denise, he had
also become jaded about, and corrupted by, the modern world.
</P>
<P>
   He was savvier than most people think, after all. The catalog of
the show includes a chronology with a few useful reminders in it:
for instance, that he was the one who decided not to sell any
pictures until he had compiled a large enough group of what he
considered to be world-class paintings with which to announce
himself to the public; that in 1889, when he exhibited with the
Societe des Artistes Independants, he was well reviewed, and in
1890 Albert Aurier's article about him was published _ not bad for
a young painter who had been at it only a few years.
</P>
<P>
   He was clearly no madman when it came to his art. By now it's
trite to say this. He was, however, a visionary, which is a very
different matter. One of his visionary pictures is ``Almond
Blossom,'' painted at Saint-Remy in 1890, a gnarled scramble of
branches and buds against an azure backdrop, nearly abstract. Sky
fills the spaces between bits of unpainted canvas, the spaces, as
if in ghostly recession, becoming branches of the tree.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an amazingly flat and complex pattern of lines and
shapes recalling Japanese art but pointing ahead to Mondrian. It's
the essence of mature van Gogh: reality, painstakingly observed,
filtered through his peculiar style of drawing to produce an image
distinctly unreal.
</P>
<P>
   In his final letter, van Gogh wrote to his brother that his
paintings, ``even in the cataclysm retain their quietude.'' This is
true. ``Landscape at Twilight,'' one of the last works, is a prime
example.
</P>
<P>
   All the elements in the picture _ bottle-green pear trees, heavy
grass, citrine sunlight, blue chateau, clay road _ are broken down
into wet dashes that recombine in a swirl. The surface roils and
vibrates, but at its core the image stays remarkably calm.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, van Gogh's work is never as simple as it first
appears, and somehow it constantly looks new each time. That is the
thing about great art: no matter how often it is reproduced or how
trivialized it is by biographers and promoters, it manages to
retain its strange power.
</P>
<P>
   The most familiar works here, when you actually stand before
them, still have an immediacy, an implacable aura, which is so
arresting that, temporarily, it even silences the noise about
blockbusters and pandering to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, despite the hype, the work is the only
thing you'll care about _ that is, if you can manage to see it
through the milling backs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``Van Gogh's Van Goghs: Masterpieces From the Van Gogh
Museum, Amsterdam,'' opens on Sunday at the National Gallery of
Art, Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue N.W., Washington, and
runs through Jan. 3, 1999. It will travel to the Los Angeles County
Museum of Art (Jan. 17 to April 4, 1999). All advance passes for
the National Gallery of Art have been distributed. Beginning on
Sunday, a limited number of free same-day passes will be available
in the rotunda of the gallery. There is a limit of six passes per
person.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
