<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSEMBLYLINEARTIST-20     10-01 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSEMBLYLINEARTIST-2000-2Takes-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTER PRODUCES MASSES OF ART FOR THE MASSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ What do you want from art?
</P>
<P>
   If you're like most people, you want art of something you can
recognize, in colors that please the eye.
</P>
<P>
   You want an affordable original, handmade by someone who is
sincere about his work.
</P>
<P>
   And you probably don't care if the art world doesn't like what
you like.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you could get the art you liked and could afford and
that any number of artists, curators and critics also admire and
collect?
</P>
<P>
   Then come on down to Rice University, where Stephen Keene has
turned an ordinarily austere art gallery into Art-O-Rama.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MAN, ONE ASSEMBLY LINE: Keene, 41, mass-produces highly
decorative paintings and sells them to anyone and everyone _ from
people who never visit galleries to the director of the
Philadelphia Museum of Art. Most of his pictures measure about 2
feet square and sell for $2. At the expensive end _ $15 _ he makes
paintings that are 4 feet square.
</P>
<P>
   He sells them for less than the price of most coffee drinks
because he works like a one-man assembly line. He sets up 20 or so
pieces of plywood on a long rack, then goes down the line, painting
the same stroke again and again, dipping his brush in another color
and painting another stroke again and again ... until he has
finished 20 vivid pictures that might be adapted from a cereal box
or a textbook or, um, just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   This unconventional technique, Keene's frequent combination of
words and pictures, his habit of painting on wood _ all that and
the initial influence of Georgia folk artist Howard Finster _ might
make him sound like an outsider to an art world centered on
precious objects and elite patronage. But Keene is by no means
naive, self-educated, insane or any of the other labels attached to
many artists working outside the mainstream. He us totally a
product of the complex, market-oriented art system that has evolved
over the past 25 to 30 years in America.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be why Keene, his art and his means of producing and
selling it can arouse suspicion, even fear and anger.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Keene showed last December at the gallery at
Philadelphia's Moore College of Art and Design, several people
protested his activities there as ``mean-spirited and cynical,''
according to one ``Time'' magazine report.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being told they bought a piece of art, and they
haven't, which is condescending,'' one outraged academic said.
``It's a bad joke'' that ``has no merit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elsa Longhauser, who organized the show, paints a highly
positive picture of Keene. She calls him ``the Johnny Appleseed of
art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure people question his motives,'' she says. ``But
Stephen is a tremendously generous and skilled artist, and a very
aware conceptual and performance artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a conscious decision to work in multiples and make his
art accessible for almost no money. And, at Moore, he made his art
in public. People watched him go down a row, painting
stroke-by-stroke, which is beautiful and almost meditative to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, says Longhauser, Keene empowers people who are
otherwise disenfranchised from the art system, allowing to critique
the relative qualities of artworks, touch them, combine pictures as
they wish and then buy them.
</P>
<P>
   Keene, who is working 12- to 14-hour days at Rice, denies any
malice or cynicism. ``It wasn't like I had a career strategy, like
I was calculating all that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intended my artwork to go this direction, either. But
over the years, it's gotten such a positive response that it has
become what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Keene's public production, display and sale of art has the
quality of a happening or a performance _ activities that are
sincere and serious, but also fun. Keene likens the artworks people
buy to souvenirs that can be kept, traded or given as gifts.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disciplined physically. I know what I'm going to do and
how, what brushes and what colors,'' he says. ``But, obviously, a
$30 painting for over the sofa is not Tintoretto.''
</P>
<P>
   ART AS WORK: Keene has worked in this vein for about seven
years. He mostly shows and sells in nightclubs. Moore was the first
art institution in which he had shown; Rice is the second.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, his story resembled those of untold other artists.
</P>
<P>
   Like almost half the artists in the United States, Keene holds a
degree in fine art. His masters degree in fine arts is from Yale
University, which gives him an edge over countless colleagues. But
Keene says that he, like most artists, ``was always
middle-of-the-road with what I did. I was never bold enough to go
straight to New York after graduate school.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent his first three or four years after school in Richmond,
Va. He painted representational scenes in a painstakingly bland
style, showed in some decent galleries and occasionally sold
something.
</P>
<P>
   He sent out packets of slides, with updated resumes, to curators
and dealers. He went to museums and galleries and read art
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   By 1991, however, Keene knew he needed to break with art-world
protocol. He had some sign-painter-style things he wanted to do,
which he knew the art world wouldn't like. But he also knew he had
absolutely nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Keene and his wife, architect Star Keene, moved
to New York. Keene rented a studio in Brooklyn and set to work on
his production line. His art first started generating a buzz in
downtown Manhattan, home of New York's independent rock music
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Keene had worked as a DJ in college, had a lot of musician
friends and found it only natural to show in clubs and make art for
CD covers. Between doing well with one-night sales and getting
terrific word-of-mouth, he sold about 13,000 paintings between 1993
and mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   He sold a couple of thousand more paintings in Philadelphia and
some 1,200 on his first day at Rice.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain his inventory _ and to contribute to his household's
income _ Keene turns out maybe 90 small paintings in 12 to 14
hours. In theory, he spends perhaps eight minutes on each picture.
</P>
<P>
   His nose-to-the-grindstone process leaves Keene little time to
speculate on where his path will lead. In any case, he adds, much
of the project's integrity requires that he stay focused on the
task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for me to make the best art I can at any time
and not think ahead,'' Keene says. ``The harder I work, the more it
means to me and other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Keene's deliberate myopia doesn't mean he is insincere. And his
reactionary stance, vis-a-vis the system, doesn't mean he's mocking
it or other artists.
</P>
<P>
   His art is not about irony but about being ``out in the world,''
Keene says.
</P>
<P>
   THE KIDS LOVED IT: Keene has been at Rice since early September
and, from the start, his enterprise has caused a sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew just from hearing about it that Steve's work was right
for us,'' says Rice gallery director Kim Davenport, who learned
about Keene from a member of the gallery's advisory board. ``Our
mission is to primarily show site-specific installations _ and what
Steve does is to make an installation out of painting.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first day of sales, Keene blanketed the walls with
pictures, hung in layers from floor to ceiling. He had stacked so
many painted constructions and pieces of painted furniture on the
floor that people had to squeeze their way between things.
</P>
<P>
   There were landscapes _ from desert vistas to snowy mountains.
Flowers were everywhere, like daisies in May. Also scenes of
Houston _ from the downtown skyline to pictures from Bayou Bend _
Bible scenes, cutouts of the Alamo and cutouts of cute little
burros. And cutouts of Michael Jordan. The panels of a huge folding
screen at the front of the gallery feature a detail from Thomas
Cole's ``The Hunter's Return,'' from the collection of the Amon
Carter Museum.
</P>
<P>
   From his experience at Moore, Keene knew it would be tough
maintaining such a sense of flea-market density. So he planned not
only to produce on a daily basis; he also brought an initial supply
of 2,000 pictures with him from Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, come closing time the first Sunday of sales, the place
was decimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wild, but in an organized way,'' gallery manager Jaye
Anderton says. ``We had more than 1,000 people come through between
noon and 5 p.m. People were smiling and having a good time, but
they were calm and very focused on what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part was the kids. There were a lot of children with
big smiles on their faces, picking out a piece of art for their
very own.''
</P>
<P>
   NEXT STOP: GERMANY: First Moore, then Rice. Now the Museum
Ludwig in Cologne has decided to include Keene in a group show this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean the art world wants to rehabilitate its mildly
prodigal son?
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, it needs Keene. Like the retail and entertainment
industries, the art world is always starved for fresh talent and
new products. And, anymore, almost anything can be considered
important contemporary art _ even paintings some might compare to
velvet Elvis paintings and other forms of parking-lot art.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such potential, Longhauser muses, ``Can Stephen
Keene remain Stephen Keene?''
</P>
<P>
   Longhauser may speculate. But Keene, looking to his own
integrity and not wanting to leave anyone empty-handed, is too busy
painting to answer that question.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
