<HEADER>
A4532 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDA-BYDISNEY-2000(2T     10-01 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-BY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDI MEETS ELTON JOHN IN OPERA A LA DISNEY
</HEADLINE>
 DISNEY-2000(2Takes)-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of the people in the polite audience at the
Alliance Theatre were oblivious to the presence of one of the most
famous entertainers in the world sitting in the back row.
</P>
<P>
   Elton John, 51, sat quietly, practically underdressed in a red
warm-up jacket.
</P>
<P>
   John (Sir Elton, if you wish; he was knighted last year), was in
Atlanta for a performance of ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of
Aida,'' a new Disney musical he has written songs for, with a plot
frankly lifted, borrowed, stolen and inspired by Verdi's opera
``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney hopes to take the show to Broadway once it finishes
preview performances Nov. 8 in Atlanta, although there is no
guarantee and no announced date. If ``Elaborate Lives'' makes itto
Broadway, it will follow Disney stage hits ``The Lion King'' and
``Beauty and the Beast.'' ``The Lion King,'' which won six Tony
Awards, continues to be the biggest draw on Broadway, selling
nearly $1 million in tickets every week, according to Playbill. The
4-year-old ``Beauty and the Beast'' continues to sell more than
$500,000 worth of tickets every week.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Elaborate Lives'' is different: It's Disney's first
attempt to produce a live show not based on an animated movie. The
target audience, apparently, is middle-aged boomers with a newly
acquired taste for theater and a long-established fondness for '70s
rock.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics for the show are by Tim Rice, who earned his place in
the history of music and theater with the arrestingly sacrilegious
take on the Holy Scriptures that he provided for composer Andrew
Lloyd Webber in ``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat''
and ``Jesus Christ Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``Elaborate Lives'' came straight from the top of
the Disney organization: Michael Eisner wanted to make an animated
feature based on ``Aida'' even before ``The Lion King,'' and even
approached John, who liked the idea. However, ``The Lion King,''
which also has songs by John and lyrics by Rice, moved ahead of
``Aida'' on the Disney development track.
</P>
<P>
   Stealing a traditional opera plot for a Broadway show is not
unheard of; Gershwin's ``Porgy and Bess'' and Bizet's ``Carmen''
have both appeared in trimmed-down musical versions. Jonathan
Larson used plot and characters from Puccini's ``La Boheme'' with
great success in ``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that can work _ as it did in ``Rent,'' with a
script that deals with homelessness, AIDS, generational alienation
and drug abuse in a meaningful manner. But, at least in previews,
``Elaborate Lives'' proves that not just any old opera plot can
work in a musical.
</P>
<P>
   COMPARISONS TO VERDI: Until now, Elton John has focused on
writing music for himself. ``Elaborate Lives'' is the second major
chunk of music, after ``The Lion King,'' that he has written for
others to perform. It's also his second collaboration with Rice, an
indication that a new long-term partnership may be developing.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who attended last month's Sunday matinee with John, seemed
almost overdressed in a suit and four-in-hand tie. He frankly
admitted that he wrote the lyrics for ``Elaborate Lives'' before
seeing Verdi's ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it for the first time in London about three months
ago,'' he said. ``It was in Italian, so I didn't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Elton, however, was slightly miffed when asked if he knows
the Verdi opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he said. ``That's what makes this project scary.
Everyone will compare it to Verdi.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Verdi had his strong points, and John has his. Verdi churned out
30 operas, four of which _ ``Aida,'' ``Rigoletto,'' ``La Traviata''
and ``Il Trovatore'' _ are universally renowned.
</P>
<P>
   John has written hundreds of songs and could convincingly set a
laundry list to music _ although even some critics say he has been
``overproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Verdi, like John, enjoyed an immense international following and
lived comfortably most of his life after a tough start. Verdi
occasionally got tangled in a repetitive bass pattern, just like
John.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Verdi and John share that unexplainable,
unteachable ability to capture mood and character in music.
</P>
<P>
   `AIDA,' ROUGHLY TRANSLATED: Although it is inspired by one of
the most famous operas of all time, ``Elaborate Lives'' is not,
except in the broadest definition, an opera. But it is not an
old-fashioned musical comedy, either, since the end is tragic.
</P>
<P>
   What is it, then?
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDA-BYDISNEY-2ndTake     10-01 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-BYDISNEY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
ATLANTA: is it, then?
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's basically a pageant, an excuse for some Elton John songs,
with a little more plot than an overproduced rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   And, although it's continually engaging, it's not really
effective as drama. In true Disney fashion, Linda Woolverton, who
co-wrote the screenplay of ``The Lion King'' and co-wrote the
``book,'' or basic plot line, of ``Elaborate Lives,'' has reduced
this lofty tale of ancient Egypt to a domestic soap opera _ in this
case, a teen romance.
</P>
<P>
   Amneris, the daughter of Pharaoh, comes across more as a prom
queen than a princess, and Ramades is more like the captain of a
football team than a mighty warrior. Aida, the Nubian slave who is,
unbeknownst to her captors, the daughter of the king of Nubia,
emerges as a streetwise girl from the wrong side of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Act I, Ramades, Amneris and Aida are pretty much
Archie, Veronica and Betty, complete with a scene at the beach,
except in ancient Egyptian costumes.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental problem is how to draw this trivialized plot to
a close when Verdi's version calls for Aida and Ramades to be
locked in a tomb and starved to death. (Nothing like this happened
to Archie and Veronica.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Elaborate Lives'' preserves the tragic ending, but even with
fancy lighting and an attempt at spiritual apotheosis, the ending
clashes with the trivial spirit of the rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rice and John very nearly redeem it. Rice provides his
delightful limping couplets and cliches, and John responds with his
encyclopedic range of pop styles.
</P>
<P>
   True, there's nothing here that couldn't have been written in
1975; although one is tempted to classify ``Elaborate Lives'' as
just another musical in the Lloyd Webber idiom, remember that Lloyd
Webber's style originated in the 1970s rock of John and fellow
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The cast at the preview performances made the most of the
appealing lyrics and music. Princess Amneris, played by Sherie
Scott, is the central character and gets the best songs; and she
looks great in the pseudo-Egyptian costumes, unlike anyone else in
the cast. She also has lungs like Ethel Merman, only more refined.
</P>
<P>
   Her rollicking number ``Dress Has Always Been My Strongest
Suit,'' presents a fashion addict celebrating her wardrobe, in a
Motown style complete with two female backup singers. Her moment of
salvation arrives in ``I Know the Truth,'' a confessional aria in
the vein of Sondheim's ``Send in the Clowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Headly, Nala in the Broadway production of ``The Lion
King,'' plays Aida as a Whoopi Goldberg type who gets by on her
wits, guilelessly winning the prince's love with her brains while
guilefully gaining Amneris' confidence through her insight from
being a princess herself.
</P>
<P>
   She gets the not-particularly-relevant title song, which will
probably show up three or four tracks into an Elton John CD
someday, but has a great vocal moment in the gospel-style chorus
``The Gods Love Nubia.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Ramades, played by Hank Stratton, is a pretty standard
Disney prince, transforming early on from a mindless jock to a
sort-of-sensitive guy. He knows all the subtleties of the
Eltonesque vocal style, and nearly saves the role, in spite of a
costume that looks like drag.
</P>
<P>
   High priest Zoser (based on Verdi's Ramfis), who is also
Ramades' father in the Disney version, is a new incarnation of
Herod from ``Jesus Christ, Superstar.'' The duet ``Like Father,
Like Son'' that he shares with Ramades nearly duplicates John's hit
``Philadelphia Freedom'' _ but, after all, it is John's material to
begin with, and it works.
</P>
<P>
   One major additional character not in Verdi's version is the
Nubian urchin Nekhen, played winningly by 14-year-old Scott
Irby-Ranniar (who played the Young Simba in the Broadway version of
``The Lion King).''
</P>
<P>
   Director Robert Jess Roth and choreographer Matt West have not
come up with anything for the chorus and dancers to do except for
neo-Egyptian disco and some stiff poses a la tomb paintings.
</P>
<P>
   A large, movable pyramid that opens up to turn into a rolling
platform, or a set of stairs, is the central item of scenery; it
broke down in last Sunday's matinee. Phallic obelisks and smaller
pyramids and triangles rise from the stage floor or drop from the
ceiling, amid amulets and symbols vaguely suggestive of swastikas
and other fascist emblems; maybe the show could be called
``Elaborate Sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's an aesthetic flop as a piece of theater, that's no
guarantee of failure in today's market. The music should make a
great cast album. With some more polishing, ``Elaborate Lives'' may
even make a halfway successful tourist attraction on Broadway, and
later on the road. The audience cheered sincerely at all three
performances I saw, and there was audible sniffing and quiet
sobbing every time at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, don't worry about Verdi turning over in his grave.
Verdi won't even remotely care about this one.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida''
</P>
<P>
   Through Nov. 8: 8 p.m. Tuesday-Saturday, 2:30 and 7:30 p.m.
Sunday at the Alliance Theatre of the Woodruff Arts Center, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $20-$36
</P>
<P>
   Information: (404) 733-5000
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
