<HEADER>
A4590 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBADOS-BOX-$ADV03-C     10-01 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBADOS-BOX-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARBADOS: IF YOU GO. ..
 &HT;    With BARBADOS-TRAVEL-$ADV03.
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International and Travel folders on
the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories
for use Saturday, Oct. 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEN TO GO:
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is a year-round destination, although most rainfall
occurs from June to October. Many hotels offer free accommodations
for children between mid-May and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO TRAVEL:
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines flies daily non-stop to Barbados from Miami
and New York. Round-trip fares (currently) start at about $328.
Taxis are plentiful and rates are generally fixed. Hourly rates are
about $16 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT:
</P>
<P>
   The Waterfront Cafe near Trafalgar Square is a popular spot with
good food, live music, and people watching. Brown Sugar, on Bay
Street, offers excellent local cuisine and has a big buffet lunch
for about $17.50 a person. According to locals, the Cliff
restaurant ``is THE place to go.'' The high prices are worth it for
the well-prepared meals and a look at the elegant decor.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY:
</P>
<P>
   There are scores of hotels in Barbados ranging from basic to
deluxe. The island has more than 5,500 hotel rooms. Most are
clustered along the west coast and the south coast. The island's
top-rated hotel is Sandy Lane on the west coast, where rooms go for
several hundred dollars a night. However, the hotel is undergoing a
renovation and will be closed until October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO:
</P>
<P>
   Windsurfing and water-skiing are popular along the west and
south coasts. There's excellent snorkeling around the reefs and
coves at the beach at Folkestone, close to Holetown on the west
coast. Equipment can be rented on the beach. Catamaran tours go
along the west coast, providing food, liquor, and chances to
snorkel and visit deserted beaches. To get out of the sun, visit
caves and castles, restored homes and old forts. The Barbados
Museum, housed in a former British military prison in Bridgetown,
traces the island's history from pre-Columbus times.
</P>
<P>
   TO GET MORE INFORMATION:
</P>
<P>
   Call the Barbados Tourism Authority at 1-800-221-9831. Or check
out Barbados on the internet at www.barbados.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
