<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBADOS-TRAVEL-$ADV0     10-01 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBADOS-TRAVEL-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAVES, CASTLES, FORTS, MUSEUMS MAKE BARBADOS MORE THAN JUST FUN
'N SUN
 &HT;    With BARBADOS-BOX-$ADV03.
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International and Travel folders on
the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories
for use Saturday, Oct. 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados _ When travelers think Caribbean, they
think swaying palm trees, pina coladas under a glazing sun, and a
warm sea that's as clear as gin.
</P>
<P>
   The island of Barbados is all that, but it's also much more than
just a perfect spot to get a tan.
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is the furthest east of the West Indies, which arc from
South America to North America.
</P>
<P>
   The island is rich in history, with a variety of sites dating
back to early in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   It's also rich in shopping, watersports, and tasty cuisine, with
a wide array of good restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   With names like Brighton Beach, Hastings, Worthing, and Dover,
this former British colony has the feel of a foreign country, but
it is not so exotic as to throw you off-center.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this capital city -- though not much to look
at -- boasts some of the best nightlife in the region, much of it
centered in the one-room rumshops at Baxters(CQ) Road.
</P>
<P>
   Since most people live comfortably, what Barbados does not have
is a lot of the irksome hassle from street hawkers, or the poverty
that's so visible in shantytowns and rural areas in other parts of
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's the beaches you want, then beaches you can get,
particularly along the island's sheltered west coast, where
tame-as-a-kitten waves lap the smooth sands of some of the finest
beaches in the Caribbean, especially around Speightstown.
</P>
<P>
   Then for those who shun the beach, there's the rugged shoreline
on the Atlantic side, with its enticing caves, powerful waves,
jagged rock ridges, and an undertow that's so beastly there are
scads of signs to warn one against taking a dip.
</P>
<P>
   Though not frequented by swimmers, this side is quite popular
with surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is also a pleasant family destination. Children will
enjoy pirate ships, working mills and sugar plantations, as well as
tram rides past the stalagmites and stalactites of Harrison's Cave.
</P>
<P>
   The first Europeans to discover the island were the Portuguese,
who dubbed it Barbados, or bearded ones, after the Bearded Fig
trees that grew along the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   But English settlers came soon after and Barbados was a British
colony from 1627 to 1966, when it gained independence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the British influence is felt everywhere you go.
</P>
<P>
   Residents drive on the left side of the road. They speak English
with a lovely lilt. Cricket is the national sport.
</P>
<P>
   Many hotels are British-owned, offering afternoon tea served on
rattan-furnished patios alongside buttered scones.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgetown even comes to life around a Trafalgar Square, which
has a statue of Lord Nelson, sculpted by Sir Richard Westmacott and
predating its London equivalent by 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   The monarchy in England remains the head of state, while the
justice system and parliamentary style of government are both
borrowed from the United Kingdom. As an island steeped in
democratic tradition, the House of Assembly here is the third
oldest parliament in the hemisphere, celebrating its 350th
anniversary in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Today the 166-square-mile island supports a population of
266,000 people, many of whom are descendants of Africans brought
here as slaves to toil on vast sugar plantations.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders call themselves Bajans (pronounced ``Bah-jonz''). They
are polite, friendly, and highly educated. The literacy rate of
nearly 98 percent is the highest in the English-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   Like a small town, everyone here seems to know everyone else,
and drivers wave to one another as a matter of course. Bajans are
very religious, and the island has more churches than days in the
year. Surprisingly, they are also nutty about their horoscopes,
consuming them in their daily newspaper faster than the front-page
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the island's historical ties with Britain, children are
becoming increasingly influenced by American culture, with most
aspiring to be Michael Jordan when they grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Bajans are a people who appreciate their past.
</P>
<P>
   There's a strong preservation movement here and a dynamic
National Trust that has salvaged not only the forts, churches, and
plantation estates -- called ``great houses'' here -- of the
colonials, but the heritage of black national heroes as well.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Charles on Needham Point, which now forms part of the
gardens surrounding the Hilton Hotel, was the largest of the many
forts that guarded the island's south and west coastlines.
</P>
<P>
   St. Nicholas Abbey, dating from about 1650, is one of the oldest
domestic structures in the region, and one of only three surviving
examples of Jacobean architecture in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   There are two great houses near Six Cross Roads, where the
Easter Rebellion of 1816 took place.
</P>
<P>
   The Easter Rebellion was an uprising by slaves who mistakenly
thought that a bill had been introduced in the English parliament
granting them their freedom. The slaves destroyed many acres of
cane fields when they thought plantation owners were denying them
that freedom. Although no owners or their families were killed,
several hundred slaves were killed in a battle that quickly crushed
the rebellion, while other slaves were hanged afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   One great house in the area is Sunbury Plantation, some 300
years old. The house is elegantly decorated in Georgian style, and
most furnishings are mahogany. The other great house is Oughterson
Plantation, near the Barbados Zoo Park.
</P>
<P>
   The island boasts several impressive castles, notorious Sam
Lord's being among the most popular. This castle, built in 1820 and
since restored, was a hideout for the infamous pirate who,
according to legend, assembled a fortune by plundering boats that
became shipwrecked after he lured them onto Cobbler's Reef.
</P>
<P>
   Near Trafalgar Square, you can easily walk to St. Michael's
Cathedral, built in the 18th century. You can then stop by the
Synagogue, an early 19th-century building on the site of a
17th-century one, one of the two earliest in the hemisphere. You
can see the Gothic-style Parliament Building, built in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   About three miles away is the much-visited statue of a freed
slave that celebrates Barbadians' full emancipation from slavery
160 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But if you grow tired of all the statues and architectural
treasures, you can veer away from Trafalgar Square toward Broad
Street, where duty-free goods ranging from clothes to cameras are
sold.
</P>
<P>
   You can also savor mouth-watering cuisine and some of the best
fresh fish around.
</P>
<P>
   Flying fish come two or three to a plate, usually fried. Dolphin
-- the fish and not the beloved mammal -- is good and served at
most restaurants. Cou-cou (pronounced ``Koo-koo'') is a starchy
dish usually made with tree-grown breadfruit. Pumpkin is a staple,
served as everything from pumpkin soup to pumpkin fritters.
</P>
<P>
   So if you come to Barbados, it might be easy to stay at the
beach, sipping rum punch and soaking up the sun. But you'd be
missing a lot. When it comes to the Caribbean, Barbados is one
island where there's plenty to do, none of which has anything to do
with sand and surf.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
