<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKESS-SPENCER-H     10-01 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKESS-SPENCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERNIGHT SENSATION TAKES THE YANKEES (AND TEXAS) BY STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is The Unnatural, an overnight sensation nearly
nine years in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer has the callouses on his hands as proof of the
dues he paid on all those hot afternoons in a batting cage. The
only thing that came naturally to Spencer was the stubbornness to
not go away until he had worn down the New York Yankees' resistance
to let him show what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer arrived at the Bronx by way of Tampa, Oneonta,
Greensboro, Norwich and Columbus. He had more than 2,800 at-bats at
those minor-league stops before he got his first invitation to
Yankee Stadium. He is 26, and he is playing as if he cannot endure
the thought of one more bumpy bus ride to a bumpier field to play
another game under dim lights.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre did himself the favor Wednesday of
finding a place in the lineup for somebody who ended the regular
season by hitting seven home runs in nine games. Less than an hour
and a half before Spencer took his place in left field for Game 2
of the American League Division Series, somebody asked what his
best baseball moment had been before reaching the big leagues.
Spencer didn't know what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just every day, getting a chance to play,'' Spencer said. ``I
don't think I've had one yet. I haven't said, `OK, that's a great
moment.' I'm think I'm still waiting for one.''
</P>
<P>
   If Spencer keeps creating moments and memories the way he did
Wednesday night at the expense of the Texas Rangers, then
Cooperstown is going to have to clear some space for him. Mark
McGwire will refer to him as ``The Man.'' Hollywood will scramble
to the rights to tell his life story.
</P>
<P>
   Citizen Shane?
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 57,360 summoned Spencer from the dugout after his
first trip to the plate against Rangers right-hander Rick Helling
in the second inning. That's what happens when a rookie hits a home
run in the first playoff at-bat of his career to send the Yankees
on their way to a 3-1 victory. Spencer singled two innings later,
starting a two-run rally that turned out to be all the offense the
Yankees needed to move to within one victory of closing out the
best-of-5 series. One inning after that, Spencer rifled a throw
that arrived in time to nail Juan Gonzalez trying for a double, but
Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch dropped the ball trying to
make the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, it was just another day in the life of a former
28th-round draft choice. Three at-bats. Two hits. Another home run.
Add that to his regular-season totals, and Spencer has homered 11
times and driven in 28 runs in 70 at-bats. Before long, Torre is
going to expect this kind of thing to happen every time he writes
Spencer's name on the lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope it does,'' Torre said. ``The thought of `Damn
Yankees' and Joe Hardy come to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Damn Yankees is right, as far as the Rangers are concerned. The
Yankees were the best team in baseball before adding a cross
between McGwire and Roy Hobbs to the mix. Spencer's slugging
average during the regular season was .910. McGwire needed 70 home
runs to slug .752. And McGwire didn't hit three grand slams in nine
games, the way Spencer did to finish the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit three grand slams in 17 years,'' said Torre, a nine-time
All-Star who had 252 career home runs. No wonder teammates have
taken to calling Spencer ``The Wonder Boy.'' Lately, they've
teasingly scolded Spencer for making the game look ridiculously
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you one thing: He doesn't get cheated,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``He knows what that piece of wood is
for, and it isn't to clean off his cleats. My only question is:
Where has he been all year?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spencer started the season, as he always does, in the minors.
The Yankees had their reasons for not being in a hurry to take
notice of him. His home run totals in his first five minor-league
seasons: 0, 0, 3, 12 and 8. Spencer didn't get to Double-A until
'96, hitting 29 homers for Norwich. A .241 average with 30 homers
the next year at Triple-A didn't have the Yankees figuring out ways
to make room for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the minor leagues, I thought, `If I was with
another team, I would have a shot and can prove myself,''' Spencer
said. ``The way it worked out, this year I was ready. I'm glad I
made it with the Yankees. I made it with the best organization
ever, instead of a team that's going to be a .500 club.''
</P>
<P>
   An injury to Chili Davis earned Spencer his first call to the
majors _ finally _ on April 7. Spencer had four hitless at-bats
before getting sent down to Columbus on April 19. The Yankees
called up Spencer again in June, giving him two at-bats in 20 days
before sending him back to Triple-A. He replaced Dale Sveum on the
25-man roster on July 27 and got his first big-league hit the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after that, Spencer had a 5-for-5, two-homer game
against Kansas City. Ten days after that, the Yankees sent Spencer
to Columbus again to make room for Davis. The Yankees brought him
back on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden,'' Torre said, ``he kind of blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   He slugged home run after home run, until Torre had to see if
the magic could continue in the playoffs. On Spencer's first at-bat
Wednesday, Helling froze him with a 1-2 fastball that home-plate
umpire Durwood Merrill deemed to be just off the inside corner.
Spencer took advantage of the reprieve on the next pitch. He
walloped a belt-high fastball down the middle just left of the
399-foot sign in left-center. The fans would not calm down until
Spencer came out for a curtain call. As Spencer left the field at
the end of the game, the fans chanted his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than getting out there and not doing good,''
Spencer said, ``and having them boo you off the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
