<P>
   HOUSTON _ What do you want from art? If you're like most people,
you want art of something you can recognize, in colors that please
the eye. You want an affordable original, handmade by someone who
is sincere about his work. And you probably don't care if the art
world doesn't like what you like. But what if you could get the art
you liked and could afford and that any number of artists, curators
and critics also admire and collect? Then come on down to Rice
University, where Stephen Keene has turned an ordinarily austere
art gallery into Art-O-Rama. By JANET TYSON. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIDA-BY DISNEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of the people in the polite audience at the
Alliance Theatre were oblivious to the presence of one of the most
famous entertainers in the world sitting in the back row. Elton
John, 51, sat quietly, practically underdressed in a red warm-up
jacket. John (Sir Elton, if you wish; he was knighted last year),
was in Atlanta for a performance of ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend
of Aida,'' a new Disney musical he has written songs for, with a
plot frankly lifted, borrowed, stolen and inspired by Verdi's opera
``Aida.'' By WAYNE LEE GAY. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
