<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BASE-BUILDING     10-01 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BASE-BUILDING-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BRACES FOR IMPEACHMENT FIGHT BY NURTURING POLITICAL BASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is going back to basics to combat
the impeachment threat.
</P>
<P>
   He's busy raising millions of campaign dollars for Democrats
seeking seats in the House and Senate _ and collecting political
I-O-Us along the way from legislators who will decide the fate of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He's wooing traditional Democratic allies such as labor
activists, women, African Americans and Jews _ political
constituencies that have been the backbone of his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's classic Democratic politics,'' says Larry Sabato, a
political scientist at the University of Virginia in
Charlottesville, Va. ``The White House calculates that as long as
the Democrats' basic interest groups stay will Bill Clinton, there
is zero chance of impeachment and conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato adds: ``The strategy may not be enough to win favorable
treatment in the history books _ but it's enough to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   William Schneider, a political scientist at the American
Enterprise Institute in Washington, says Clinton is trying to avoid
becoming the lightning rod in the political campaigns leading up to
the Nov. 3 mid-term congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wants to motivate the Democratic base without
making the big splashy displays out on the campaign trail that will
stir up the anti-Clinton backlash,'' says Schneider. ``He's got to
get Democrats voted into Congress to help protect him against
impeachment without getting more Republicans elected in the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic gains _ or fewer Democrat losses than expected _ will
be seen ``as a mandate against impeachment,'' Schneider said. On
the other hand, ``Republican gains will be taken as a mandate for
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   After congressional Democrats complained, the White House
squelched a plan by People for the American Way last week to launch
a multimillion dollar nationwide advertising campaign on behalf of
Clinton. The campaign would have accused Republicans of
partisanship for pressing the scandal at the expense of progress on
national issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to imagine how a national media campaign
would help individual candidates district by district,'' said White
House Press Secretary Mike McCurry. ``The president is most
concerned about helping Democratic candidates who are on the
ballot. Our focus is how can we elect Democrats on Nov. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has helped to raise almost $45 million for Democrats so
far this year at events in more than a dozen states. He traveled to
Cleveland and Philadelphia on Friday to help raise campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 44 fund-raising events so far this year, 25 have taken
place in private homes beyond the reach of protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has abandoned _ at least for now _ the long
standing practice of scheduling public ``message events'' for the
president to tout his political agenda in cities where he also
holds private fund raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's final road trip before the Nov. 3 mid-term elections
is scheduled to be a West Coast trip that ends Oct. 21, leaving him
at the White House for the final two weeks of the campaign. Aides
said Clinton will probably take part in fund raisers in the
nation's capital during that period.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign money raised by Clinton is being used to benefit
Democrats seeking election or re-election to the House and Senate _
the two institutions that will decide his fate in the months to
come.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee is expected to vote Monday on
whether to seek House authorization for an impeachment inquiry
stemming from allegations of coverup, perjury and obstruction of
justice in the White House sex scandal. The House is expected to
vote Friday on the committee's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   If the committee later completes an impeachment inquiry that
recommends impeachment, the full House then would vote on whether
to impeach. If that occurs, the Senate would conduct the trial of
the president. If convicted by a two-thirds Senate vote, Clinton
would be automatically removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who carried 59 percent of union voters in 1996, dodged
a hot union issue last month by opting not to lobbying for ``fast
track'' trade negotiating authority. The AFL-CIO has opposed that
authority because it erases congressional powers to make changes in
trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also has pressed _ so far, without success _ for
congressional action to boost the $5.15 minimum wage to $6.15 by
2000. This is a another key goal of organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly spotlighted issues that appeal to women,
hoping to sustain the female support he got in the 1996 when women
voters went for him over GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole, 54
percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The president has equally courted African Americans and
Hispanics. Clinton carried 84 percent of the black vote and 72
percent of the Hispanic vote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He told the annual dinner of the 38-member Congressional Black
Caucus last month: ``I want to thank you for standing up for me and
understanding the true meaning of repentance and atonement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif, chairwoman of the black caucus,
hailed Clinton's leadership. ``We support Bill Clinton at this
critical moment in his career,'' Waters said, adding that the
Congressional Black Caucus ``will be the fairness cops'' in the
fight over impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   At the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute fund-raising
dinner recently. the president thanked the Hispanic caucus for
``being my friend, for standing with me on sunny days and in strong
winds.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has taken fresh steps to address the concerns of
many Jewish voters, a politically powerful constituency that cast
78 percent of its vote for Clinton in 1996, according to exit
polls.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the 25th anniversary of the Yom Kippur War in
1973, Clinton invited Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian Authority leader Yassir Arafat to the White House last
week where he won their agreement to attend an October negotiating
marathon designed to break an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a statement last week marking Yom Kippur, said that
the Hebrew religion's annual Day of Atonement was an opportunity
for ``Americans of all faiths to live our lives according to our
beliefs, to have faith in God's mercy and to have the humility and
strength of spirit to begin again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
