<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     10-01 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BELOVED' FROM DEMME  
 NO `DREAMGIRLS' MOVIE  
 SHARON STONE, MOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Jonathan Demme said he should be nervous, even a bit
panicky, about the opening of his new film, ``Beloved.'' But he's
surprisingly calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have zero nervousness,'' said the Academy Award-winning
director of ``Silence of the Lambs.'' ``My life has been `Beloved'
in the last two years, and I sort of feel satiated.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, an adaptation of the Pulitzer Prize-winning novel by
Toni Morrison about the shattering impact of slavery, runs nearly
three hours and opens Oct. 16. For Demme, making the movie was a
deeply personal journey that began after he made his last film,
``Philadelphia,'' in which Tom Hanks won an Academy Award for
playing a lawyer struggling with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Philadelphia' was such an emotionally draining experience,
and I wanted to do a comedy,'' Demme said. As one of only a few
A-list filmmakers, Demme, 54, is besieged with projects and can
more or less pick and choose. But this time the filmmaker found
that even his clout was limited.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Philadelphia,'' he spent about 18 months developing
``The Stopwatch Gang,'' a screenplay by the playwright Beth Henley
about a real group of Canadians who robbed banks in the United
States in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful, hard-to-characterize movie, not exactly a
comedy, not exactly a thriller,'' Demme said of that film. ``And it
proved to be the kind of movie no one wanted to finance. We had
Bono; we had Kate Winslet pre-`Titanic.' We had all the locations.
And the studios wouldn't make it without a giant star.'' He said,
with a bit of a laugh, ``My producers and I were humbled.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, which was two years ago, Demme was sent the
script for ``Beloved'' by Harpo Films, a division of the company
owned by Oprah Winfrey. Ms. Winfrey is also the star of the movie,
and its producer; she bought the rights to the novel and nurtured
the film project for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such top-quality material in every single way,'' Demme
said. ``I found it irresistible. To have a piece with so many
riches; it was a dream you never thought would come true.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Winfrey, Demme said: ``She made it clear from the
very beginning that she didn't want to be thought of as the
producer or the star. She considered herself an actress in the
film. And bringing the part to life would be a full-time job for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The making of it was such a collective high,'' he added. ``We
all felt so privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Demme said executives at Walt Disney Co., which made the film,
never objected to its unflinching depiction of the characters'
lives. The film is somewhat uncharacteristic for mainstream Disney.
(It helps, of course, to have Ms. Winfrey as producer and star.)
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Studios chairman Joe Roth recalled Demme's first
meeting with Ms. Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a list of directors, and the first person on the list
was Jonathan Demme,'' he said. ``I said to Oprah, `You never get
the first person on the list, and Demme only works every five years
or so.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``A week later Oprah called me and said Jonathan Demme had read
the material and wanted to meet her,'' Roth said. ``I said: `Oprah,
you're not used to this, but you're auditioning for him, he's not
auditioning for you. So don't mess this up.' She laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   No `Dreamgirls'
</P>
<P>
   Joel Schumacher had only two words to say about the sudden
cancellation of ``Dreamgirls,'' the movie version of the 1981
Broadway musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm devastated,'' said Schumacher, the director of ``A Time to
Kill'' and ``Batman.''
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation, or postponement, as studio executives call it,
of the high-profile film is in some ways a case study of the
jittery way Hollywood operates today. A Warner Brothers project to
be produced by David Geffen, it was to cost about $35 million. The
film, based on the show directed and choreographed by Michael
Bennett, was about a singing group similar to the Supremes, who
rose from the Detroit projects to national fame in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   For years, between work on other films, Schumacher had been
shaping ``Dreamgirls'' with a production designer, costume designer
and choreographer. He had discussed roles in the film with Don
Cheadle and Andre Braugher as well as the fast-rising singer Lauryn
Hill, who was to play Deena Jones, the Diana Ross-like lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Warners, a studio that seemed to dominate Hollywood in the
1980s and early '90s, has been in a slump the last two years, with
some expensive mishaps like ``Father's Day'' and ``The Postman.''
This summer, ``The Avengers'' proved disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Known in the past for its lavish spending and deals, Warners has
backed off in recent months from some planned projects, including
an Arnold Schwarzenegger action film and Tim Burton's version of
``Superman'' with Nicolas Cage. (``Superman'' may fly again, but at
a lower price.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as with baseball teams, every studio in town falls on
hard times and eventually recovers.
</P>
<P>
   And Warners is banking on the success of several projects to be
released in the next few months, including Nora Ephron's ``You've
Got Mail,'' with Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan, and Luis Mandoki's
``Message in a Bottle,'' with Kevin Costner, Paul Newman and Robin
Wright Penn. By the time Warners recovers, another studio will
probably fall into the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   What led to the cancellation of ``Dreamgirls'' was the poor box
office showing this summer of ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love.'' That
film was about the brief meteoric career and tangled romantic life
of singer Frankie Lymon, who died of a drug overdose in 1968 at 25,
at which point three women claimed to be his wife. The movie,
released in late August, has grossed only $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   A Warner Brothers executive called the failure of the film, for
which the studio had high hopes, a ``painful experience.'' The
experience led Warners to take a second look at ``Dreamgirls.''
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the Frankie Lymon film and ``Dreamgirls''
have little in common. Yet both films deal with three black women
in the 1960s. And both are driven by a strong musical score of that
era. It is also common wisdom in Hollywood that films with minority
casts often fail at the box office overseas. All those factors left
the studio frightened about going ahead with the project.
</P>
<P>
   Would any other studio make ``Dreamgirls''? Unlikely. Many
Hollywood studios refuse to give up the rights to projects, even
after deciding not to make them. That is to avoid the embarrassment
of seeing a rival turns a cast-off project into a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers learned its bitter lesson in the late 1980s when
it put a project in ``turnaround,'' and 20th Century Fox picked it
up. It was ``Home Alone,'' one of the biggest moneymakers of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Stone, Mom
</P>
<P>
   More than any other actress today, Sharon Stone is the archetype
of the classic Hollywood star who flourished in the heyday of the
studio system. But Ms. Stone does not hide her dissatisfaction that
today's studios fail to offer the kinds of roles that gave career
longevity to stars as varied as Bette Davis, Katharine Hepburn and
Lana Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only play the kinds of parts you're offered, and I'm
usually offered femme fatales,'' Ms. Stone (above) said. ``Frankly,
at my age I should do stunt pay for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old actress is now, quite happily, not playing a
femme fatale in an unusual (for her) role in a new film, ``The
Mighty.'' In the movie, she plays the strong-willed mother of a
smart handicapped boy (Kieran Culkin) who befriends a towering
youth who is slow in school and cannot find his way. Both outcasts,
the boys fearlessly live their own fantasies. The film, released by
Miramax, and directed by Peter Chelsom, will arrive in theaters
Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stone initially signed on as producer of the film after she
read the script. Then she asked Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of
Miramax, to cast her in the unglamorous mother role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blown away by the script: I thought it deserved to be
made, and then I spoke to Harvey about possibly playing the
mother,'' she said. ``I needed to play a normal person. I needed a
break from the lunatic pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stone tends to get what she wants. She is also appearing in
``Antz,'' a computer-animated film from Dreamworks that opens
Friday. She plays a somewhat spoiled ant princess in Central Park
who is charmed by a neurotic ant played by Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about the film and I got very brave,'' she said. ``I
started chasing Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg. I started
hounding them. I was obsessed with it. The idea was so funny and
charming. I had to do it!''
</P>
<P>
   How could Spielberg and Katzenberg refuse Sharon Stone?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
