<HEADLINE>
CENSUS FINDS MORE ASIAN-AMERICAN KIDS IN TWO-PARENT FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Asian-American children are more likely to be
raised in families with two parents present than are children in
other racial and ethnic groups, according to a Census Bureau report
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new Census Bureau statistics also reinforced the connection
between education and wealth. Asian Americans have the highest
median family income of all major census groups _ $49,100 a year _
and they are most likely to have college degrees, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that 84 percent of Asian-American children live
in households in which both parents are present. That compares with
77 percent of non-Hispanic white children, 67.4 percent of Hispanic
children and 32.8 percent of African-American children.
</P>
<P>
   About 42 percent of Asian Americans age 25 and older have at
least a bachelors degree, making them the best educated of any
census group, according to the report. By comparison, 26 percent of
non-Hispanic whites have such degrees, while 14 percent of African
Americans and 10 percent of Hispanic Americans do, according to the
data.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Waters, a Harvard University sociologist, said one reason
for the high income is that single-parent households tend to be
poorer than married couple households. With more Asian-American
families intact, it follows that their median family incomes would
be higher.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Lee, associate professor of sociology at Portland State
University in Portland, Ore., said another reason Asian-American
families have relatively high family income is that there are more
family members employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian-Pacific households tend to be bigger and they tend to
have more people working,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new statistics show that 38.8 percent of Asian-American
families have two earners and 12 percent have three earners,
compared with 35.6 percent and 6.7 percent, respectively, for
non-Hispanic white families.
</P>
<P>
   Waters attributed the high rate of intact families in part to
the traditional family-oriented culture from which many
Asian-American families come.
</P>
<P>
   That culture places a strong emphasis on keeping the family
together even through trying times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much greater disapproval of divorce and single
parenthood,'' said Lee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the family is viewed as a economic tool. ``There is
great emphasis on the family being the primary basis of support,''
said Lee. ``So if you are a family member, you are supposed to be
contributing and helping the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Klineberg, a sociologist at Rice University in Houston,
said Asian-American immigrants often arrive with higher educational
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume that all immigrants come to America and start at the
bottom and, by virtue of hard work and family values, work their
way up,'' Klineberg said. ``But many Asians came from educational
and economic backgrounds that are far superior to those of the
average American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are scientists, doctors and engineers from some of the
poorest countries in the world, the children of the elite in those
countries, who come over here already with college degrees and
advanced degrees,'' Klineberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have immigrants come from those sorts of
backgrounds in such numbers,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Better educational backgrounds have allowed Asian immigrants to
obtain well-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Andris Skreija, an anthropologist at the University of Nebraska
at Omaha, suspects there is a generational dimension to the high
rate of intact families in the Asian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   The more recent the immigrant, the more likely he or she is to
subscribe to the traditional family-oriented culture, according to
Skreija. As younger generations become more Americanized and as
older generations die off, the younger generations undergo a
transformation: They suffer a higher divorce rate and lower
performance in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would predict that in another 20 years, the number of intact
Asian American families will go down as a result,'' Skreija said.
</P>
<P>
   Waters cautioned against over-generalizations about affluent
Asian Americans, noting that many people who trace their heritage
to Cambodia and Laos have some of the highest poverty rates in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian-American census category includes Americans who trace
their ancestry to China, the Philippines, Japan, Korea, Vietnam,
India, Thailand, Pakistan, Laos, Cambodia and Pacific island
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The new data are based on a March 1997 current population
survey.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Asian Americans number about 10 million, or about 4
percent of the U.S. population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
