<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIRD-HALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD AMONG SEVEN TO BE INDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ Yes, there actually are some others who
will join Larry Bird as Hall of Fame inductees Friday night. A
couple even have Celtic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Bird will be one of seven inductees, gaining entrance in his
first year of eligibility. Each inductee must choose a member of
the Hall of Fame to ``present'' him for enshrinement. Bird's
choice: Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has been a good friend,'' Bird said. ``I had so much fun
playing with him because all he cared about was winning. I had
always admired him as a player and it was fun to be around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird's immediate family _ his wife and their two children _ will
be in attendance. But he said he was disappointed that his mother,
who died before Bird was elected, could not be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad, because she couldn't wait until this happened,''
he said. ``She was more excited about this than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird chose former Celtics head coach Bill Fitch to be the second
of his two presenters. Bird has always credited Fitch with helping
him adjust to the NBA and developing his game.
</P>
<P>
   Bird bypassed Celtics majordomo Red Auerbach as a presenter.
Bird wanted a player and a coach, and said this past May that he
rarely communicates with Auerbach anymore. Auerbach will be there
anyway, however. Lenny Wilkens, being inducted for a second time,
has selected Auerbach to present him. Wilkens, already enshrined as
a player, is being honored as a coach. He broke Auerbach's record
for coaching wins two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another Celtic Hall of Famer, guard Sam Jones, will present
University of Texas women's coach Jody Conradt, who is being
honored as the all-time winningest coach in women's college
basketball history. Her 1986 Texas team went 34-0 to win the NCAA
title.
</P>
<P>
   The other inductees are coach Alex Hannum, Marques Haynes, Arnie
Risen, and Alexsandar Nikolic.
</P>
<P>
   Hannum coached two NBA title teams: the 1958 St. Louis Hawks and
the 1967 Philadelphia 76ers. Those are the only teams to defeat a
Bill Russell-led Celtics squad in the postseason. Hannum also
coached the 1969 ABA champion Oakland Oaks. His Hall of Fame
presenter will be Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes is being honored as the first Harlem Globetrotter and one
of the greatest ballhandlers of all time. In his stint with the
Globetrotters and later with the Harlem Magicians (a team he
founded), Haynes played in more than 12,000 games in 97 countries
while logging more than four million miles.
</P>
<P>
   Risen is the selection of the Veterans Committee. He was a
member of the 1957 Celtics title team and was one of the top
centers of the 1950s, though overshadowed by George Mikan. He also
won a title with Rochester in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolic is the international honoree. He is known as the father
of Yugoslavian basketball and was the first coach to lead
Yugoslavia to a medal in international competition. Among the
players from Yugoslavia who have played in the NBA are the late
Drazen Petrovic, Vlade Divac, Dino Radja, Stojko Vrankovic, and
Toni Kukoc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BIRD-COMMENTARY-B     10-01 1853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIRD-COMMENTARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD DESTINED FOR THE HALL FROM THE OUTSET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He wasn't Michael, OK?
</P>
<P>
   He did not take off from the foul line and dunk the basketball.
He did not blow by defenders with extraordinary quickness or
perform incomprehensible acrobatics in midair.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael wasn't Larry, either. You've never seen Michael
Jordan throw bounce passes between defenders' legs to a cutting
teammate for a layup. You've never seen Michael Jordan redirect
long rebounds to someone underneath for a dunk, thereby picking up
both a rebound and an assist in the same motion. You've never seen
Michael rack up triple-double after triple-double after
triple-double. And you've never seen Michael Jordan challenge an
entire state and live to tell the tale, the way Larry Bird did in
Ohio back in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing the pecking order of greats and greatests makes being a
sports fan fun. Most of these arguments are irresolvable. But there
are some absolutes, and when a man such as Larry Bird presents
himself to Hall of Fame voters for their perusal, there is no time
wasted on discussion. Larry Bird was a Hall of Fame player from his
first minute in a Celtics uniform, and Friday night, in
Springfield, it will be made official.
</P>
<P>
   Before there was Michael's Time, there was Larry's Time, and
what a time it was. From 1979 through 1987, Larry Bird played on
three championship teams and won three Most Valuable Player awards,
and in the 1987 exhibition season and the first six games of the
1987-88 regular season, he may have been at his all-time artistic
peak. But in the seventh game of that season, he wrenched both
ankles on a play against the Cleveland Cavaliers, and after that he
was never really the same physical being again. If it wasn't his
heels, it was his back. Or his elbow. In one memorable game against
Indiana in 1991, it was his head, Larry having used it as a point
of contact with the famed parquet in pursuit of a loose ball. It
was always something, and as disappointing as it was for the team
and the fans, imagine how frustrating it must have been for Larry
Bird himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was feeling good,'' he says, ``the game was easy. But
when injuries caught up with me, it was another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry was feeling just fine in the months of February, March,
April, May, and June of 1986. He was the focal point of the very
best of all Celtics teams. The back and elbow problems of the early
season were forgotten. In February, he went on a West Coast
rampage. In March, he put on the greatest 3-point shooting
exhibition ever seen, sinking 25 of 34 attempts in one stretch, and
this was from the original 3-point line, which was more challenging
than the one we have today. And in April, May, and June, there was
one great playoff performance after another, culminating in a
phenomenal demonstration of all-around basketball prowess in the
sixth and concluding game of the Finals against the Houston
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   He and his basketball soulmate, Magic Johnson, were the twin
terrors of the NBA. They were the standards of excellence, and no
one was more respectful of the pecking order than a young talent in
Chicago by the name of Michael Jordan. When Jordan threw in those
63 scintillating points in a losing double-overtime effort against
the Celtics in the second game of the 1986 playoffs, Bird declared,
``I think he's God disguised as Michael Jordan. He is the most
awesome player in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the many tributes strewn his way on that Sunday afternoon,
the young Michael Jordan was most taken by those words from Larry
Bird. As reported in the current issue of Vanity Fair magazine, in
which there is an excerpt from the forthcoming book ``For The Love
Of The Game,'' Jordan was absolutely dazzled to hear those words
coming from Bird's lips. (itals)I remember reading what Larry said
about the game. I really couldn't believe he would say something
like that. Here was a guy who had been in the league seven years
and who was in a class I was trying to enter ... Larry Bird's
comments gave me credibility.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   In this sound bite world we live in, memories are short. The
latest is all-too-often assumed to be the greatest. But, as Duke
Ellington would say, it ain't necessarily so. If you wanted to see
just exactly how basketball could, and perhaps even should, be
played, all you had to do was watch Bird in his physical prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal,'' he said on the occasion of his retirement, ``was
control. By control I mean a little bit of everything. Start at the
defensive end. Rebound. Dribble the ball up. Hit a three. Get back
on defense and help double-team somebody to make him throw the ball
away. Come back to the offensive end and make a great pass. Rebound
again. Throw a baseball pass for a score. Just do one thing after
the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is the greatest talent ever to play the game; no
question,'' admits Magic Johnson. ``Michael has more ability than
Larry and me put together. We played a different type of game. We
could not dominate a game the way Michael can, but he can't
dominate a game the way we could, either. If we all tried to
reverse roles, it wouldn't work. No one can score at will the way
Michael can. Larry and I dominated games with triple-doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry liked to score. Who, aside from Dennis Rodman, doesn't?
But the really great Bird games encompassed more than the mere act
of putting the basketball in the hoop. Passing was always his great
pleasure. As far back as high school, when his passes as a junior
helped make teammate Danny King into an all-state player, Larry
Bird recognized the therapeutic value of passing to a team.
</P>
<P>
   Passing, Bird understood, was contagious. What Bird did in
taking an otherwise mediocre Indiana State team to the 1979 NCAA
title game was nothing less than the greatest individual
achievement in the history of college basketball, and that team's
calling card was the pass. Players who, if left to their own
devices, would never even have thought about making an extra pass
made extra pass after extra pass for an entire season because they
had been inspired to do so by The Man himself. It was no different
at the next level. As long as Bird was in uniform, the Boston
Celtics were, by definition, a team of great passers.
</P>
<P>
   Bird was capable of doing something clearly beyond the reach of
the great Michael Jordan: On many occasions he dominated basketball
games at the offensive end without ever taking a shot. He could do
this because in addition to being the greatest passing forward
ever, he was a consummate individual offensive threat. The
possibility that he might shoot was sufficient to create passing
angles and lanes for him to exploit. Is there any wonder,
therefore, that he and Robert Parish were the best pick-and-roll
duo ever to play? No defender could ever outthink Larry, so no
matter what the man wearing the other uniform did, Bird was able to
figure out something to do _ and then go out and do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry understood that passing is all about timing and
angles,'' Magic explains. ``First of all, Larry anticipated better
than anybody. He knew when DJ was going back door. He knew just
when Kevin was ready to receive his entry pass. He knew when Robert
was going to take off. Most guys hit people when they're already
open. Larry had such a great feel for the game. He knew when a
teammate was about to get open.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird simply had no peer as a passing forward. He compiled 140
career double-figure assist games. But 140 is a number, and no
number can explain the truly great athlete. The how is always far
more interesting than the what. Bird really and truly did things we
have never seen before or since. Some of them took place in venues
such as Marshfield High School on a hot August night during rookie
camp, or Hellenic College during any one of a hundred selected
scrimmages with naught but a writer or two in attendance. His
teammates saw things the rest of you will never, ever see again.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious to everyone that Larry was a magician with the
basketball in his hands, but the prevailing folklore holds that he
was a liability when the other team had the ball. Not so. He was no
one-on-one stopper, but in the NBA team defensive scheme he was a
killer. On at least one occasion the illegal defense rule was
rewritten to curb Larry's roaming (call it the original Larry Bird
exception).
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael, Scottie, DJ, they were great individual defenders,''
says Magic. ``But there was no one better than Larry on team
defense. To win championships, you need a great team defense, and
Larry was the greatest team defensive player ever.''
</P>
<P>
   He shot, he passed, he rebounded, and he defended, but it never
stopped there. He was a leader in every way. As much as any player
in history, he understood what it took to win games and
championships in the world's greatest basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Bird taught Michael how to win,'' lauds Magic. ``He
taught him that just scoring 50 points wasn't going to beat the
Boston Celtics. He taught Michael how to include the other players
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was never just a technically brilliant player, and that
really was the fun of it all. Even if a future player somehow
approximated the physical package, there is not going to be a Larry
Bird II. Period. He's not going to have the peculiar Indiana and
peculiar personal background. He's not going to have the wit. He's
not going to have the sheer physical toughness. He's not going to
have the basketball prescience and foresight. He won't have the
capability and inexplicable inspiration to take, and make,
lefthanded shots when he really didn't have to (check out the
fourth quarters of both Detroit Game 7 in '87 and Atlanta Game 7 in
'88). And he is surely not going to have the connection with the
fans that made Larry Bird a one-of-a-kind basketball icon in this
city.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. We had our chance. If we didn't fully appreciate what we
had when we had Bird in our midst, the joke's on us. There was only
going to be that one chance.
</P>
<P>
   And now the time has come to confirm the completely obvious.
Does Larry Bird belong in the Basketball Hall of Fame? Well, duh.
Could Sinatra sing? Could Basie swing? When are we going to get to
the hard questions? Bird going into the Basketball Hall of Fame is
a Given's given, even if the man himself doesn't exactly know what
to make of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ever wanted to do was be the best player on my high
school team,'' he says. ``I've never really thought much about
going into the Hall of Fame. My feelings are the same as I had when
they had the night for me five years ago. I really don't know how
it will hit me until I get up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can tell you is that the NBA life was the greatest
thing in the world. I smelled the roses all along, and people
didn't know I was doing it. I remember all the feelings I had
before big games, right back to high school. I loved it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Basketball loves him right back, as he will find out Friday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
