u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BIRD-INDIANA-BOS &LR;      10-01 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIRD-INDIANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS AS A CELTIC, CHERISHED AS A DOWN-HOME BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Undeniably, he is now theirs. He may have made
his fame and fortune as a Celtic, but the Indiana Pacers now can
legitimately claim favorite son Larry Bird as their own.
</P>
<P>
   In one short year as the head coach and unmistakable public
persona for the Pacers, Bird may have pulled off the unthinkable.
He may well have supplanted high school basketball and Indiana
University basketball and made the Pacers the epicenter of Hoosier
hoops. This is a state that takes its basketball seriously and Bird
was the serious-man's player. He had the flawless fundamentals, the
proper respect for the Coach, the hoop heritage that can only be
developed in Indiana. It's a match made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``There absolutely is nobody better that you could have brought
into the state of Indiana to associate with this franchise than
Larry Bird,'' says Indiana president Donnie Walsh. ``We couldn't
have hired anyone better with the impact that Larry Bird has in the
state of Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Walsh reports to his office at Market Square Arena
and pinches himself to ensure that, yes, it is still thus. He is
one of many people in all parts of the United States who cannot
understand why the Celtics let Bird slip away. He provided Bird
with money, job flexibility, more money, and the rest, as they say,
is history.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night Bird will be enshrined in the Basketball Hall of
Fame for the deeds he accomplished as a Celtic. The entourage from
Boston, said to be more than 40, will dwarf that of the four-man
Pacer contingent. But while he will enter the Hall as a Celtic, he
will leave it as a Pacer, returning to Indiana (on a charter, of
course) to resume his duties as head basketball coach and
credibility shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Bird likes it in Indiana. The people leave him alone. He can
wash his car every day (which he does, weather permitting) and mow
his lawn every day (which he does, at least when the grass
threatens to grow), and no one gawks or whips out a poster to sign.
He can dine in peace if he chooses to eat out, with even more
tranquility and comfort if he's not picking up the check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never spent much time here,'' he said of Indianapolis.
``I'd come up with some buddies in the summer and play golf, but
that was about it. I had no idea how great a place it is. I really
enjoy it and my kids love it.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is mutual. The Pacers are his Pacers in much the
same way the Celtics are Rick Pitino's Celtics. Very few coaches
(Pat Riley would be another example) cast such a large and luminous
presence that make them bigger than the players they coach. In one
season, Bird did that and more.
</P>
<P>
   The more the season progressed, the more the Pacers realized
just what they had. Bird had always been an Indiana icon, ever
since the days when Logotee was the big game. What better person to
have on the front lines for the next millenium and the move into
what may be the best new arena in the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   The building will be called, simply, The Fieldhouse. It is now
sprouting from a downtown hole in the ground and it will have the
retro look and feel of Indiana basketball, complete with old-style
billboards, slat-back chairs, pull-out bleachers, and exposed steel
trusses that will create, deliberately, a few obstructed view
seats. It's a building with Indiana basketball in mind, the way
Indianans think of the sport, the way Bird thinks of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different here,'' Walsh says. ``It's what makes it
special here. People here grow up with organized basketball. Not
the schoolyard stuff. And Larry is a product of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The building will open in the fall of 1999. All the suites are
spoken for and the club seats will be sold out as well. ``It's
going to be unbelievable,'' Bird says. ``It's a building for
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Pacers bring in potential sponsors to watch a
seven-minute sales pitch film on the building, they can look around
the room to see exposed brick, a black-and-white photograph of a
game in the old Madison Square Garden, and a picture of Bird. It's
not there by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this going before he got here,'' says Pacers general
manager David Kahn. ``But with him here, everything is so much
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is reluctant to tap into Bird-as-pitchman. He hired him
strictly as coach, he says, although his nose looks a little longer
everytime he insists, unconvincingly, that he didn't have something
more in mind. Bird may hawk hamburgers and fries with his voice,
but his presence is all that's required for the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   In the promotional video, Walsh notes the bond between
basketball and Indiana and how everything will be just so in the
new building. ``The addition of Larry Bird will help, too,'' he
says matter-of-factly. In the package of information geared to
sponsors, only one individual associated with the Pacers has a page
all to himself. You guessed it. The page is headlined ``Larry
Legend'' and has two pictures of Bird, one as the coach of the
Pacers and the other as a player at Indiana State.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the sidelines, Bird's work ethic will have a decided
effect on his team, creating a game that will thrive in the
Fieldhouse,'' reads one sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, as you might expect, is acutely aware of how the selling
game goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is,'' he explains, ``they brought me in here, but
they didn't use me. I know with me being here, it's a lot easier. I
understand that. And I can listen to Donnie talk all day about me
not being involved, but I am to an extent and I knew that going in.
I knew that was part of the package. These people have watched me
my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   They are watching him in his second career now. He agreed to
coach for three years, but the deal is open-ended. At some point,
he'll move into Walsh's chair (probably when he senses a downturn)
and anoint his successor (Rick Carlisle?). One of the key
ingredients in his decision to move was a piece of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to it, Celtics fans, Larry Bird is here to stay.
Indiana lost him once and won't let it happen again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
