<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV0     10-01 2141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS WINTER APPROACHES, KOSOVO REFUGEES AWAIT ACTION BY WESTERN
POWERS
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-PRIMER-$ADV04; KOSOVO-PLAYERS-$ADV04.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The year's first snow soon will fall on Kosovo. Then
there will be no debate about the enemy: It will be starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months of fierce civil war have forced more than 250,000
civilians, mostly women and children, to flee their homes with what
they could carry on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer and early autumn, Serbian police and Yugoslavian
military forces engaged in a village-to-village struggle against
the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), a guerrilla force seeking
independence for the province of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   In its attack on the KLA, the heavily armed government forces
have been accused of burning farms and leveling towns suspected of
being sympathetic to the rebels. In some cases, civilians have been
jailed or summarily executed, diplomats and other officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the bodies of 18 women, children and elderly members
of one family were discovered near the town of Gornji Obrinje with
bullet wounds in their heads. Some had their throats cut, and
others were mutilated with their noses and ears slashed off, said
witnesses who viewed the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Horrified villagers said the attacks were carried out by masked
men wearing Serbian military uniforms. Within a few hours,
residents of the village of Golubova five miles to the south
reported that Serb forces surrounded a pocket of refugees and
killed 13 men. There has been no independent corroboration of these
attacks, and Yugoslavian officials denied their forces were
involved if they did occur.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the images of the bodies and shocked relatives pointing
mournfully at the familiar shoes and clothing of their loved ones
dominated television screens Wednesday ind Thursday, prompting a
fresh wave of revulsion. ``This was not an act of war,'' British
Foreign Minister Robin Cook said of the killings. ``It was plain
cold murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Such discoveries, which have been all too frequent in recent
months, fueled the already pronounced fears of ethnic Albanians,
who comprise as much as 90 percent of the population of Kosovo.
They worry that the Serbs, who for centuries have viewed Kosovo as
their spiritual homeland, may be moving to repeat the ``ethnic
cleansing'' campaigns of Bosnia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 100,000 have sought shelter in the mountains and
forests of Kosovo and neighboring Albania, their homes destroyed in
the fighting. Many are believed to be stranded out in the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Even as relief organizations prepare for their winter offensive,
the scale of the task of feeding and caring for so many vulnerable
people in such severe conditions makes it all but inevitable that
some, perhaps many, will die.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Paddy Ashdown, the leader of the British Liberal
Democratic Party, returned from a tour of Kosovo and expressed
alarm at what he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Outside one village, he said encountered 700 refugees seeking
shelter in the forest. ``They were so frightened, they would not
come out,'' Ashdown said. ``They wouldn't show themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're living off berries and what they could gather from the
woods. They said to me, 'We will die where we lie,' and they lie in
the most miserable conditions in the deep woods of Kosovo because
they're not prepared to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim here.)
</P>
<P>
   The themes of the struggle for Kosovo are as old as
civilization. The province, though now populated by mostly Muslim
ethnic Albanians, once was the heart of the medieval Orthodox
Serbian empire.
</P>
<P>
   In 1395, the Serbs lost a pivotal battle in Kosovo to the
Ottoman Turks, leading to the collapse of the Serb Empire.
Ironically, the defeat elevated Kosovo in the eyes of Serbs to the
status of a holy land. Their ancient monasteries and cathedrals dot
the countryside today.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yugoslavia of Marshal Tito began to come apart after
the dictator's death in 1980, Serbs led by Slobodan Milosevic, now
the Yugoslavian president, began to dream out loud of a Greater
Serbian homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Kosovo, then an autonomous region of Yugoslavia, was
the site of important moments in Milosevic's political ascendancy.
In a dispute between the Serbs and ethnic Albanians, Milosevic shed
the ostensible neutrality of a government official to side with the
Serb minority.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered the power of Serbian nationalism and has rode its
wave to power. In 1989, he brought Kosovo and the autonomous region
of Vojvodonia under direct Serb authority.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Milosevic has exercised strict, and arguably
repressive authority over the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim here.)
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the republics of Croatia and Slovenia
declared their independence from Yugoslavia. In Croatia, ethnic
Serbs supported by Serbia entered into a civil war involving
Croatian forces. Serbia also provided arms to ethnic Serb fighters
in Bosnia. More than 200,000 people werd killed in years of
fighting in both countries. Serb forces captured huge amounts of
territory in Bosnia and Croatia and began ``ethnic cleansing,'' the
term for the process displacing non-Serbs to make room for new
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   After Serbian aggressions won world condemnation, the United
Nations in 1992 imposed sanctions on Yugoslavia to end the
bloodshed. In 1995, the Dayton peace accord brought an end to the
conflict and was signed by leaders of Serbia, Bosnia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all Kosovo, where dissident ethnic Albanians were
lead by a pacifist leader opposed to full independence, remained
attached to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts were surprised when Kosovo didn't opt out of its
union with Serbia seven years ago. ``We all thought it was going to
explode then because the conditions were right,'' said Michael
Clarke, the executive director of the Centre for Defense Studies at
King's College, London. ``It has been a tinder box for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion was finally touched off in February when KLA
forces ambushed and killed four Serbian policemen. This provoked a
Serbian retaliation, which led to a KLA counter-offensive and a
continued escalation of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA proved surprisingly successful, and at one point during
the summer claimed control over 40 percent of Kosovo. The
Yugoslavian government denies the rebels captured so much of the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats began to fear the upstart KLA was contributing
to regional instability by its very success while provoking harsher
reprisals from the Serbs. Most unsettling, they could find almost
no identifiable chain of command within the group and consequently
no one with which to negotiate. ``The group has a very shadowy
leadership, that not even very many ethnic Albanians know much
about,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Rugova, the respected leader of the Kosovar Albanians,
has little influence with the guerrillas. A pacifist who supports
Kosovo's return to more autonomy but remaining part of Yugoslavia,
Rugova advocates passive resistance to Serbian authority.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Western officials have been unable to forge a
political solution because they could not offer to use their
influence to restrain the KLA. Without such a concession, the Serbs
were being asked to implement a unilateral cease-fire, which they
refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated that they could not get a handle on events in Kosovo,
Western diplomats began increasing their support for threatened
military action to force the Serbs to end their attacks on the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials depict the KLA as terrorists seeking to foment
rebellion. Therefore, an official at the Yugoslavian embassy in
London argued, the country has been well within its sovereign
rights to use whatever force it needed to suppress such an
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavians draw parallels between the KLA and Irish Republic
Army (IRA), the armed group that campaigned for years to end
British rule over Northern Ireland. Just as Britain has the right
to send soldiers into Belfast to confront rebels, Yugoslavia has
the right to stop the KLA, their argument goes.
</P>
<P>
   That argument underscores a fundamental problem for the West in
dealing with Kosovo. The conflict is taking place within
Yugoslavia's national borders and the legal arguments justifying
force are thornier than when a nation attacks another -- as when
Iraq attacked Kuwait sparking the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   It is also perilous for Western powers to pick sides in what
amounts to an internal rebellion, said Spyros Economides, a foreign
affairs expert at the London School of Economics. ``They're faced
with this major dilemma of not being able to support any kind of
independence group in Kosovo because they will never be able to
support changing borders by the use of force,'' he said. ``That's
something that is completely against the grain of what is happening
in terms of international relations today.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as complex as the problem is, Economides and other
political experts fault Western powers -- particularly the United
States -- for failing to come to terms with the situation in a
timely fashion, allowing months of misery and instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``One the one hand it is a completely complex problem,'' he
said. ``I don't think it's a lack of will that has prevented a
solution. It's an inability to deal with it, the inability to find
the right tool to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest concern is that the conflict could spill
over into neighboring Albania, already near anarchy, and Macedonia,
where the frail government probably wouldn't survive.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bob Dole, who visited Kosovo early last month,
reminded U.S. officials of this concern after his return. ``As
terrible as the war in Bosnia proved to be, the war that both the
Bush and Clinton administrations feared most was in Kosovo -- where
it seemed inevitable that conflict would spread easily into
neighboring countries, thus destabilizing the entire region,'' Dole
said in a speech to the International Republican Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said his visit convinced him that the Serbs were brutally
attacking civilians in Kosovo. ``Based on what I saw, there should
be no doubt that Serbia is engaged in major, systematic attacks on
the people and territory of Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that the fighting could spread if action by the
West isn't taken soon to stop Serbian attacks and find a solution
to the complex crisis. ``In the blink of an eye, violence could
spread into Macedonia and tear that fragile democracy in two,''
Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before winter, conditions for refugees were severe, aid
workers say. Diarrhea caused by contaminated drinking water and
resulting the dehydration is already causing deaths, especially of
children. In addition, health workers worried that conditions were
ripe for epidemics of respiratory illnesses and tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit. Dole reported seeing similar problems. ``The
children in particular are already showing signs of a vitamin
deficient diet, they have sores on their mouths and most have
scabies or other skin ailments resulting from a lack of sufficient
hygiene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 U.S. and European aid groups are distributing food,
medicine and other necessities to refugees. Each week, about 500
tons of food are distributed. That amount is expected to increase
eight-fold by the end of the month. Washington has approved $22
million in food aid, and the United Nations World Food Program has
issued an appeal for governments to provide an additional $16
million for food.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian officials say the extent of the need is being
exaggerated but nevertheless have pledged not to interfere with the
distribution of food.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Serbs said the uprising had been crushed and they
began withdrawing their tanks and armored personnel carriers for
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts believe the pause will allow the KLA to regroup and
prepare for a spring offensive buoyed by increased support from the
West. Yet, unless something in the political mix is altered, the
cycle of violence almost certainly would reignite.
</P>
<P>
   While the West, moved by the fresh scenes of bloodshed, seems
ready to act now to end the violence, concerns remain about whether
the action will be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to ask ourselves why we have got to the stage that
at the beginning of October 1998 we're now starting to consider the
refugees in Kosovo when this thing started blowing up in our faces
six months ago,'' Economides said. ``Have we really learned the
lessons of Bosnia?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
