u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING02-COX     10-01 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIAL STORY OF KING ASSASSINATION 'DIDN'T ADD UP,' SON SAYS
 &HT;    Cox photos to illustrate this story have been placed in the
National folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It just didn't add up,'' said Dexter Scott King,
explaining why he has rejected the official conclusion that his
father, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., was assassinated by James Earl
Ray, a racist gunman acting alone.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a forum Thursday on the Justice Department's recent
decision to reopen the investigation of the 1968 killing in
Memphis, the son of the slain civil rights leader said no specific
piece of evidence convinced him and his family that ``there was
something more to this than the official version.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a prison visit persuaded him that the ``trigger man''
was not Ray, a career criminal who confessed to the killing shortly
after his capture but then spent three decades claiming innocence
right up until his death this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's ``plea bargain'' to avoid the electric chair is
``different from a confession,'' King explained.
</P>
<P>
   King said his family ``felt a moral obligation to press on''
with the investigation even after 30 years. There is no statute of
limitations on murder, he said, or on the emotional loss of a
family.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the notion that there is some benefit for his
family in advancing the conspiracy theories that have sprung up
around the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in this for anything other than the truth,'' said
King.
</P>
<P>
   King said he accepts the promise of Attorney General Janet Reno
to follow the evidence where ever it leads in the renewed
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the panel expressed considerably less trust in the
government. Indeed, in a free-wheeling two-hour discussion, vague
connections were drawn between Ray and not only the CIA, the Mafia,
and the FBI, but also Jack Ruby, the Dallas nightclub owner who
killed Lee Harvey Oswald, the assassin of President John F.
Kennedy, and a mysterious agent named Raoul.
</P>
<P>
   Ray was a ``patsy'' who knew little about the powerful forces at
play with and around him, explained William P. Pepper, his attorney
and author of ``Orders to Kill,'' a book detailing this alleged
conspiracy to assassinate King. Pepper maintains there was even a
backup team of U.S. Army snipers in Memphis in case a hidden,
never-identified shooter missed King on a motel balcony.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first suspicions were that there was more to this than met
the eye,'' echoed the Rev. Walter Fauntroy, the former
congressional delegate from the District of Columbia who headed the
House assassination subcommittee that concluded in the 1970s that
Ray was the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Fauntroy said he had questioned Ray and came away convinced that
this ``small-time, ineffectual criminal'' was not smart enough to
have pulled off the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing skepticism from the other side was George Curry,
editor in chief of Emerge: Black America's Newsmagazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the ant at this picnic,'' he said, pointing to a
confession, fingerprints and other evidence tying Ray to the murder
scene and the likely murder weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Conceding that Ray may not have acted alone, Curry he is
dismayed by ``this orchestrated effort to absolve'' the admitted
assassin. ``There is an abundance of evidence to show he was a
racist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are enough lingering questions to justify a renewed
probe, there is not yet enough to establish the veracity of a
conspiracy, agreed Todd Lindberg, editorial page editor of the
Washington Times. Sometimes ``coincidence and incompetence'' can
``look like a conspiracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion was moderated by Kojo Nnamdi(cq), host of Public
Interest, a National Public Radio program.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
