<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-01 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE, KITTY, KITTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's not true that nasty partisan exchanges over
presidential philandering and the impeachment process evoke the
only political outrage in the Washington, D.C., area these days.
</P>
<P>
   Public anger in a Maryland suburb less than 10 miles from the
White House recently exploded over something more important that
really arouses Americans' emotions: their pets.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are famous for having their day, but not this time. We are
talking cats here.
</P>
<P>
   Not Socks, either. Ordinary cats owned by ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular pet in the country is the cat. According to a
Simmons Market Research Bureau poll last year, Americans owned a
record 68 million purring felines. Take that, bow-wows. There are
only 56 million of you.
</P>
<P>
   A Montgomery County, Md., official of little acquaintance with
cats or their doting caregivers recently pulled a classic boner
that reverberated through the region. He rashly proposed a law to
control the beasts by restricting them to their owners' property
unless they are on a leash, controlled by voice command or
otherwise restrained.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for this absurd notion is that cats spread disease
and are a menace to other small creatures, preying on birds, mice
and insects. This got into the political dialogue because it is
being pushed by the American Bird Conservancy, which has mounted a
``Cats Indoor'' campaign. The organization objects to the cat
position in the food chain, somewhere below dogs but above birds.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC is not similarly upset that some birds also eat other
smaller creatures, such as fish, mice and insects. Perhaps it
should also mount a ``Birds Indoor'' campaign to preserve fish
life.
</P>
<P>
   As for the leash question, the White House puts Socks on a long
leash, but that's a special case, and the circumstances of his
existence are as strange as that of his owners. The rest of the
world couldn't get a cat to walk on a tether if a million dollars
rode on the achievement.
</P>
<P>
   And voice control _ here, kitty, kitty _ is an impossible dream.
Just try to get a cat to come when you call if he isn't in the
mood.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to walk my cat once on a leash and found myself dragging
a limp body on its back down the sidewalk. The strategy was very
effective. I gave up before the neighbors could call me a cat
torturer.
</P>
<P>
   A leash is not a cat's way. Cats are not dogs, who can be
trained to obey certain commands, wag tails happily when a leash
appears and generally behave in human-approved slavish ways. Cats
are, well, cats.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott is fond of saying that trying
to coordinate his GOP charges is something like herding cats, who
stick their tails in the air and go off in all directions. He's
right about the cats, and probably about the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The hapless official involved here, County Executive Douglas
Duncan, a Democrat, obviously has a poor sense of history. Over the
years the question of restraining cats has risen periodically
across the country. Every single time, the idea has been swiftly
defeated and its sponsor figuratively clawed to bits.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is no exception. After the outcry, he promptly backed
away from his proposal to keep offended cat owners from tossing him
out of office in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   This reaction is so predictable that certain newspaper editors
have been known to invent a spurious cat-restraint movement in dull
seasons, certain that the ``letters to the editor'' space would
promptly overflow.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago Gov. Adlai Stevenson, vetoing an Illinois measure that
would have restricted feline freedom, wisely observed, ``It is in
the nature of cats to do a certain amount of unescorted roaming.''
Herblock, the cartoonist and social satirist, once wrote an ode to
the fact that cats owned him rather than the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Some community pet controls are of course useful. Mandatory
vaccinations and voluntary spaying and neutering make good sense.
So does encouraging dog walkers to clean their animal's poop from
public spaces, although anyone who walks on a city sidewalk knows
that is virtually impossible to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   And not all cats are range-rovers. Some comfortably grow up
indoors as house pets, content to sit on window sills and look at
birds from a distance. One third of households with a cat keep the
cat indoors.
</P>
<P>
   I have an indoor version myself. He prefers to be near his food
bowl, and it is not outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   But a cat likes to decide the indoor-outdoor issue himself. If
he is of a disposition to roam, the wise owner will let him have
his way. The cat will be happy and the community unharmed. And a
clever bird will fly away if the cat gets too close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
