<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALDER WORKS ON THE MOVE  
 HERMITAGE WEST  
 WELCOME, PLEASE STAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Colo., Calif.)   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Calder Foundation is the latest suitor to make a
play for 2 Columbus Circle in Manhattan, that white marble building
with the slender arches and round holes that Edward Durell Stone
designed to be the Gallery of Modern Art in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander S.C. Rower, a grandson of the artist Alexander Calder
and the director of the foundation, said he believed it was time to
move the operation from its headquarters in Woodstock, N.Y., to
Manhattan. He has spent the last six months looking at sites large
enough to house a Calder museum as well as the foundation's
archives and library.
</P>
<P>
   Though 2 Columbus Circle would be an ideal spot, the fate of the
city-owned building appears uncertain. In July 1996, the city asked
for sealed bids from interested buyers. But three months later,
after the deadline for bids, no selection was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting to see who would be selected to develop the
Coliseum site,'' said Charles Millard, president of New York City's
Economic Development Corp., referring to a building on the west
side of Columbus Circle. ``We wanted a selection that would be
compatible. The real estate market has changed and we're evaluating
the situation. None of the bidders have been rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Millard declined to name the bidders, the Dahesh Museum
has made public its interest in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a wonderful addition to the city to have a Calder
museum,'' said Randall Bourscheidt, president of the Alliance for
the Arts, an advocacy organization in Manhattan. ``Calder had a
strong identification with New York and quite a following here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rower said he had been working with Schuyler G. Chapin, the
city's cultural affairs commissioner, to find a city-owned building
that would be suitable for the Calder Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking everywhere from Battery Park City to
Chelsea, TriBeCa, the West Village and a few sites in midtown,'' he
said. He confirmed that 2 Columbus Circle was on his wish list,
even though the foundation began to consider it after the bidding
had been closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've asked to be able to put in a bid anyway, but the city
hasn't gotten back to us yet,'' Rower said. ``Schuyler Chapin
thought we should go for it.'' A spokeswoman in Chapin's office
said the commissioner declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has large holdings, with some works owned by
family members and others by foundation supporters. The art
includes about 300 sculptures, 55 monumental outdoor works and more
than 3,000 works on paper, many not publicly seen since 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was a large lender to the exhibition ``Alexander
Calder: 1898-1976,'' which opened in March at the National Gallery
of Art in Washington and is now at the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art. The foundation also has extensive archives, with
more &UR;  &LR; than 100,000 documents.
 &UR;  &LR; ``We've spent the last 11 years working on the artist's catalog
raisonne and have 16,000 works documented,'' Rower said. Though he
was not sure when the catalog would be published, he said it would
be about 35 volumes. ``It will be an encyclopedia,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The State Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, Russia, may be
short on cash, but not on vision. The latest of its many plans is
to transform a home for the elderly in Amsterdam into a satellite
of the Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   The building, the 17th-century Amstelhof Nursing Home on the
Amstel River, belongs to a church, which wants to sell it to a
buyer that would make it into a cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   Why not a Russian cultural center in Amsterdam, asked Dr.
Mikhail B. Piotrovsky, director of the Hermitage. ``It would have
permanent exhibition space to show two shows a year, one that would
be up for a year and the other for six months,'' Piotrovsky said.
``We would also like to exhibit works from other Russian museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides giving the Hermitage another site for showing its vast
collections, Piotrovsky said, an Amsterdam location would make it
easier for people to see the museum's treasures. It could also
become a good source of much-needed revenue. ``I'm very optimistic
about the project,'' he said. ``We're beginning to do feasibility
studies.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited Berger Collection of British art is opening at
the Denver Art Museum on Oct. 10. Originally the exhibition, which
includes more than 200 works by artists like Reynolds,
Gainsborough, Constable and Sir Alfred Munnings, was to have gone
on view in November, when the museum reopened its European and
American galleries after a seven-year facelift.
</P>
<P>
   But the collection was too big for the space. So now the museum
has stored part of its permanent collection to make room for the
British art.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in just three years by William M.B. Berger, founder of
the Denver-based Berger Group of mutual funds, the collection takes
up about 10,000 square feet, the entire seventh floor of the
museum. It will be on display for six months. The works span 600
years and, in addition to paintings, include the Bute Book of Hours
and a Nottingham alabaster altarpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the Berger Collection was assembled too quickly
to have the depth of the Yale Center for British Art or the
Huntington Library Art Collections and Botanical Gardens in San
Marino, Calif. But Berger defends his collection, saying that
``even the Tate can't boast of having 600 years of British art.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum hopes the collection will never leave. ``I think
whenever a museum is able to host a show like this, it hopes to get
the collection,'' said Lewis I. Sharp, director of the Denver Art
Museum. ``Our European holdings are small, so for this institution
it would be a great gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger isn't so sure: ``I tell the museum, you put up the
gallery first and then we'll see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
