<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noted for its successes in the so-called urban niches _ black,
Latino, gay and lesbian _ New Line Cinema obviously hasn't hurt its
reputation lately with ``Rush Hour,'' Brett Ratner's karate
kickfest of a movie that combines not one niche, but two, with the
black comedian Chris Tucker and Asian action star Jackie Chan. To
date, the film has earned almost $70 million at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   But for another measure of New Line's track record in the urban
genres, look for the video of a little movie called ``Friday.'' In
1995, Gary Gray's film, described by Caryn James in The New York
Times as a ``ruder, cruder version of the hip-hop movie `House
Party,''' had its theater run and moved on to video, where it has
spent 93 weeks on Video Business magazine's best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Only ``Braveheart,'' at 100 weeks, has been on the list longer.
Asked to explain the film's staying power, Michael Karaffa,
executive vice president of New Line Home Video, cited its two
stars, Ice Cube and Tucker (then on the ascendancy); a good story
that keeps its sense of humor amid guns, drugs and other realities
of the streets, and a score that features Dr. Dre and Cypress Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie delivers,'' he said. ``And the soundtrack was
unstoppable.'' Critics also generally liked the film. ``A
fascinating glimpse of the way street life enters pop culture,''
Ms. James wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``House Party'' (1990) is another New Line property, as are
``Menace II Society'' (1993), ``Hoop Dreams'' (1994) and ``Money
Talks'' (1997), also with Tucker. Better-known New Line films in
the gay and Latino niches include ``Love! Valour! Compassion!''
(1996) and Gregory Nava's acclaimed ``My Family: Mi Familia''
(1994).
</P>
<P>
   None of those have matched ``Friday's'' run on best-seller
lists. Along with its broad appeal, Karaffa said, the movie, owing
in no small measure to its soundtrack, possesses the one ingredient
required of all best sellers: repeatability.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Programs and Profits &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This week the television and movie producer-directors Marshall
Herskovitz and Ed Zwick completed a groundbreaking deal with ABC
and Fox to waive up-front fees for new series they develop in
return for a share of the shows' future profits. A day or two
later, Herskovitz talked about an old series of his and Zwick's and
the vagaries of whether shows like it get a future at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started off slowly and it needed to build an audience like
`Hill Street Blues' or `Seinfeld,''' he said. ``People had to get
used to what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was ``My So-Called Life,'' six episodes of which will
be released by BMG Video on Oct. 15. On ABC briefly in 1994, the
series was a heady brew of growing pains faced by a teen-age girl
(Claire Danes). After 19 episodes it disappeared. ``In 1994
teen-age girls as a constituency weren't visible to the networks,''
Herskovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Now he and Zwick, who produced ``Thirtysomething,'' are working
on their first project under the new agreement. But deal or no
deal, any show has to stand on its own. ``Sometimes it finds an
audience, sometimes it doesn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Perfect Murder
</P>
<P>
   When the choice comes down to love or money in Andrew Davis'
sleek, chilly update of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Dial M for Murder,''
it's strictly no contest. Caught in an affair with the young wife
(Gwyneth Paltrow, left) of a shady Wall Street bond salesman
(Michael Douglas), an artist and convicted con man (Viggo
Mortensen) accepts her husband's offer of $500,000 to kill her. But
then she survives a spectacularly botched murder attempt and
carries on with a story that overcomes strained dialogue and,
Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times, has ``enough twists and
tantalizing clues for its ingenious mechanics to remain engaging.''
1998. Warner. $104.16. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish Prisoner
</P>
<P>
   Befitting a David Mamet film, the situation seems somehow out of
whack. On a business trip in the Caribbean, an inventor named Joe
Ross (Campbell Scott) learns from his boss (Ben Gazzara) that he
isn't about to collect the pile of money he expected from an
invention called the Process. Enter Jimmy Dell (Steve Martin), a
mysterious stranger, who glides up to the resort in his seaplane
with vaguely defined intimations of better times for Joe, including
an introduction to his beautiful, tennis-playing sister. Brushing
off the advances of an oddly off-kilter secretary (coyly portrayed
by Rebecca Pidgeon), Joe falls for Jimmy's blandishments in Mamet's
``craftiest and most satisfying cinematic puzzle'' (Janet Maslin).
1997. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 112 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two Girls and a Guy
</P>
<P>
   Waiting outside the same apartment house to surprise their
boyfriends, Lou (Natasha Gregson Wagner) and Carla (Heather Graham)
are themselves surprised to discover that they are sharing the same
lover. ``The truth is, I meant everything I said to each of you at
the time I said it,'' says Blake (Robert Downey Jr.) after they've
all gotten acquainted with the awkward confluence. Gradually,
though, it doesn't matter so much since both women seem content to
carry on with the bristling, clever fellow, who is vastly more
formidable and interesting than his lovers ``as far as this agile,
three-character movie is concerned'' (Maslin). 1998. Fox. $100.96.
92 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Hush
</P>
<P>
   Say hello to Martha Baring (Jessica Lange), a neurotic widow who
runs a Kentucky horse farm. During a Christmas visit by her son
(Jonathan Schaech) and his girlfriend (Gwyneth Paltrow), Martha
sabotages the young woman's birth control as part of a plan to get
her impregnated, kill her and keep the baby. But instead of a
gloves-off psycho-killer romp, Jonathan Darby's film ``hasn't the
foggiest notion whether it's a soap opera or a horror film and
wanders around in a generic fog'' (Stephen Holden). 1998. Columbia
Tri-Star. $105.77. 96 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY TOGETHER and FALLEN ANGELS. Two releases by the popular
Hong Kong filmmaker Wong Kar-wai reflect his frenetic and vibrant
style. In ``Happy Together'' (1997, 98 minutes, Mandarin and
Spanish with English subtitles), which earned Wong the best
director prize at the Cannes International Film Festival, two
lovers (Tony Leung Chiu-Wai and Leslie Cheung) try to salvage their
relationship by transporting themselves to Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   The zanier ``Fallen Angels'' (1995, 97 minutes, Mandarin with
English subtitles), an offshoot of the director's ``Chungking
Express,'' tells two interwoven stories about a woman who books
assignments for her lover who is a hit man, and an ex-convict who,
interestingly enough, makes a living by opening stores that have
closed for the night and forcing people to buy the merchandise.
Kino. $79.95 each. Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   PEPPERMINT FRAPPE and DEPRISA, DEPRISA (``Fast, Fast''). In
``Peppermint Frappe'' (1967, 92 minutes), the first of two films by
the Spanish director Carlos Saura, a doctor and devout Catholic
obsessed with his friend's wife explores the conflict between
desire and his religious roots. A documentarylike study of Madrid
street life, ``Deprisa, Deprisa'' is the story of three young
thieves who team up with a sharpshooting waitress to commit a
robbery. No easy money here, however, just disaster. (Befitting the
cinema-verite milieu, the stars, who were nonprofessionals, were
arrested off the set for separate criminal offenses.) Home Vision.
$79.95 each. Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
