<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STAGE AND OFF: TECHNICAL TORTURE; NONPROFIT, BUT ...; FAMILY
BUSINESS; OH, GOSH!; ALONG THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo advisory)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any veteran of a theatrical load-in, the installation
of a production, will tell you the experience is commonly known as
``tech hell.'' But for two Broadway shows, the past week has been
especially abysmal.
</P>
<P>
   Producers for ``Footloose'' and ``Little Me'' both announced
this week that their first previews would be delayed for several
days because of ``technical difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Richard Rodgers Theater, a 40-member crew for
``Footloose'' was struggling to find space in the slim backstage
area for 16 tractor-trailers' worth of equipment shipped from the
musical's tryout at the Kennedy Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kennedy is literally 13 or 14 times as deep as this
theater,'' said Peter Fulbright, the show's technical supervisor.
``It's like putting a 10-pound show in a 5-pound box.''
</P>
<P>
   In the theater's occasionally leaky basement, computer equipment
had to be hoisted onto 8-inch-high platforms in case of sudden
flooding. Upstairs, workers are demolishing a backstage shower to
make room for the cast of 37 to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Things weren't much better at the Roundabout, where technicians
for ``Little Me'' hauled gear in the front door, up a pokey
escalator and into the theater's crammed main stage. ``This is
about two and a half times larger than anything we've ever done,''
said Ellen Richard, the Roundabout's general manager. ``We're
really pushing the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   The principal challenge was a balky 33-foot-wide turntable used
to shift scenes. ``We've managed to get it to jog right and left,
but it still isn't coordinated,'' said Michael Curry, the theater's
production manager.
</P>
<P>
   The official opening for ``Little Me'' has been delayed two
weeks, until Nov. 12. The producers for ``Footloose'' insisted they
would make their scheduled Oct. 22 opening. Each show could lose at
least $100,000 in sales for the canceled previews.
</P>
<P>
   Michael David, a ``Footloose'' producer, played down the delay,
which follows mediocre reviews in Washington and the recasting of a
central role: ``What some people call trouble is what we call doing
our work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit, but ...
</P>
<P>
   If Broadway is stumbling, off-Broadway is sprinting, with five
shows opening in the next week.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more surprising entries is ``Duet! A Romantic
Fable,'' opening on Tuesday at the Actor's Playhouse. The show, an
off-off-Broadway hit for the Adobe Theater Company last fall, has
been moved with the financial backing of a major Broadway player,
Dodger Endemol Productions, known for musicals like ``Titanic''
and, yes, ``Footloose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just really like these kids,'' David said of Adobe. (Maybe
it's the small set.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite a $190,000 budget, the production remains low-key, with
beer sold from a cooler before shows and after-show parties on the
set. But tickets for the 75-minute play now run $45, with Tuesday
night tickets discounted to $19.98.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the higher prices square with the Adobe's mission
statement, which derides ``prohibitively expensive'' theater, the
artistic director, Jeremy Dobrish, said: ``We don't see this as an
opportunity for a profit. We're just rewarding the people who made
this happen, like the actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Family Business
</P>
<P>
   Writers examining their families are nothing new, but in
``Hesh,'' a Naked Angels production that opened on Sunday at the
Intar Theater, the formula is being given an intriguing twist.
</P>
<P>
   The play, by Matthew Weiss, tells the story of two brothers and
their father, a wisecracking ne'er-do-well. The catch? Weiss, 33,
portrays the older sibling, while the younger brother is played by
his younger brother, 30-year-old Marcus Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   The play's plot also hews closely to the Weiss family history.
The character Hesh is based on Harvey Weiss, a concert promoter who
suffered from a bad leg and a drug problem. Also true to life is
the sons' separation from and attempted reconciliation with their
father, who is played by Ned Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The eldest Weiss never saw the play; he died of cancer in 1996.
But shortly before his death, the brothers read the script to him.
``He kept closing his eyes and shaking his head,'' said Matthew.
``He didn't like to remember some of the things. But he laughed a
lot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Gosh!
</P>
<P>
   In the ongoing hunt for the theme of the fall season, another
contender has emerged: spoofing the sacred. In addition to ``Corpus
Christi,'' two other productions involve sensitive religious
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The first, ``The Cardinal Detoxes,'' by Thomas M. Disch, a poet,
is a 35-minute monologue about an archbishop who has killed a woman
while driving drunk. In 1990, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New
York demanded that a production of the play stop performances at a
church-owned building in the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the play was remounted by the Worth Street Theater
Company at the TriBeCa Playhouse. Jeff Cohen, the director of both
productions, said the restaging was not a stunt to attract
attention. ``This really is political theater,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zwilling, the spokesman for the archdiocese, said his
office had received no calls about the show.
</P>
<P>
   On a less weighty note, there's ``The Most Fabulous Story Ever
Told,'' Paul Rudnick's new comedy about a gay couple in Eden _ Adam
and Steve _ due to begin performances at New York Theater Workshop
in November. Don Summa, a spokesman for the show, said the theater
had received no complaints. ``We're Old Testament,'' he said. ``We
figure we're safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ The Classic Stage Company's coming production of ``Waiting for
Godot,'' with John Turturro and Tony Shalhoub, just got quirkier.
Christopher Lloyd, perhaps best known as oddball Jim Ignatowski on
the television series ``Taxi,'' has been signed to play Pozzo, the
clown. The show opens Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Joseph Papp Public Theater has another opening to
announce: Joe's Pub, a bar and restaurant on the theater's ground
floor. The bar's inaugural act, on Oct. 12, will be Audra McDonald,
the three-time Tony winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
