<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENTAGON-VIAGRA02-COX     10-01 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-VIAGRA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PENTAGON BILL FOR VIAGRA: $50 MILLION
 &HT;    By RUSSELL CAROLLO and JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The Department of Defense will spend an estimated
$50 million this year to provide Viagra, the new drug for sexual
impotence, to soldiers, sailors, flyers, retirees and their
dependents.
</P>
<P>
   Defense health officials said an original cost estimate, based
on the number of requests for Viagra the department was receiving
at military clinics and hospitals, was $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The figure was pared to $50 million _ roughly equivalent to the
cost of three F-15 Air Force fighters or 15 Army Blackhawk
helicopters _ after the Defense Office of Health Affairs restricted
prescriptions to men who suffer from a diagnosed disorder, penile
erectile dysfunction, and ruled that no user could get more than
six pills a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of money,'' said Marianne Coates, a Pentagon
spokeswoman, adding that the actual cost ``could be higher. It
could be lower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are, in fact, people who suffer from clinical
dysfunction,'' she added, and people who want simply to have a
``good time'' will not get the drug.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, John Mazzuchi, deputy assistant
secretary of defense for health affairs, cited the anticipated
Viagra expense as an example of the problems involved in planning
health care costs for the military.
</P>
<P>
   When the Defense Department's budget for health costs was being
written last year, Viagra did not exist. It appeared on the market
this year and overnight became one of the largest-selling
prescription drugs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Army, Navy and Air Force hospitals and clinics provide medical
care for roughly 1.2 million troops and another 5.3 million active
duty dependents, retirees and their dependents.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons general of the Army, Air Force and Navy appeared
before a House subcommittee last week to say that the funds
originally were provided for the fiscal year that began Thursday
would be $600 million short of the cost of providing acceptable
medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Their budgets subsequently were increased by shifting funds from
other Department of Defense programs.
</P>
<P>
   A chief problem in preparing health program budgets, all three
surgeons general told the House National Security subcommittee on
personnel, is a budgeting policy that prohibits consideration of
``technology and intensity of treatment'' factors.
</P>
<P>
   This refers anticipated costs from new medical technologies and
drugs - such as Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance before the Senate Armed Services Committee
earlier this week, members of the Joint Chiefs of Staff said the
services are underfunded by billions of dollars and cited ``quality
of life'' issues, such as pay, housing and medical care, as the
most pressing problems they face.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
