<HEADLINE>
A KLEZMER INNOVATOR LISTENS FOR GRANDMA'S VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When David Krakauer was a clarinet student at the
High School of Music and Art, and later at the Juilliard School, he
envisioned a life of playing Brahms and Dvorak with chamber groups,
with perhaps some orchestral work and jazz improvisation to round
out his schedule. He has done all that, with considerable success,
and his versatility and brilliant technique have made him a
valuable player on the new-music scene as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the one kind of playing Krakauer never imagined doing _
klezmer, the Eastern European Jewish dance music that in its
current form has a strong undercurrent of American jazz _ has won
him his biggest audience.
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer's klezmer career has a split focus. He started out
playing this music at weddings, and he still does that, performing
classic klezmer pieces in a traditional, straightforward way. He
adheres to rhythmically vital traditional dance forms like the
terkisher, doina and hora, which all have their roots in Romanian
folk music, as well as the lively freylekh and the slower chosidl.
And the dominant influence on his lilting clarinet lines, with
their bent pitches, modal accents and dynamic subtleties, is
clearly Eastern European.
</P>
<P>
   But in concert and on his recordings, he is creating an updated
klezmer style of his own, drawing freely on his experience with a
variety of other forms, including avant-garde jazz, African
drumming, Latin dance rhythms and rock.
</P>
<P>
   His latest project is a nine-movement, 29-minute suite in which
he suggests a fantasy encounter between two of his heroes: Naftule
Brandwein, a klezmer clarinetist who flourished in the 1920s, and
Sidney Bechet, the jazz clarinetist. The work, ``A Klezmer Tribute
to Sidney Bechet,'' will be the centerpiece of Krakauer's concert
with his band, Klezmer Madness, at Symphony Space on Sunday
afternoon. The suite is also featured on Krakauer's newest CD,
``Klezmer, N.Y.,'' which is to be released this month on the Tzadik
label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bechet and Brandwein both came here in the late teens or early
'20s,'' Krakauer explained, ``Brandwein from Ukraine, Bechet from
New Orleans, and they shared the wild energy of 1920s New York.
There is something about the way they both approached the clarinet
_ the sound, the cry, the inner cry in the tone _ that intrigued
me. I thought, `They're really musical soul mates.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was also fascinated to read, in John Chilton's biography of
Bechet, that when Bechet lived in France, he included `A Yiddishe
Momme' in his repertoire. I thought, wow, that's pretty neat. So I
just imagined a musical meeting between them. There is no
documentation to suggest that they actually ever met. But I think
that if they had, they would have been very interested in each
other's styles of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for one traditional melody and a piece by Dave Tarras, a
klezmer clarinetist who wedded klezmer to swing in the 1920s,
Krakauer composed the suite, basing its movements on traditional
klezmer dance forms. But he also expanded the sound palette beyond
what one typically hears in a klezmer performance.
</P>
<P>
   Several movements depict Bechet telling Brandwein about musical
life in New Orleans, including references to the African drumming
in Congo Square as well as French opera. For the opera section,
Krakauer recorded brief samples of operatic singing, usually single
notes, and wove them into a wild, unpredictable blend of electronic
and acoustic textures.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bechet and Brandwein might have looked askance at some of
these pieces. In fact, traditionalists may find that Krakauer's
experimentation stretches klezmer's limits too far. For example, in
his concert sets, he sometimes improvises, in klezmer style, on
themes from ``The Twilight Zone,'' ``Car 54, Where Are You?'' and
``The Munsters.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Funky Dave,'' a track on ``Klezmer Madness,'' his band's
debut album, also on Tzadik, he supports a wailing clarinet line
with a slinky guitar and a tight bass and drum accompaniment,
transforming Tarras' ``Heimisher Sher'' into a summit meeting
between the jazz avant-gardist John Coltrane and the soul duo Sam
and Dave. ``Bogota Bulgar,'' on the same disk, combines a dance
from Brandwein's repertory with a percussion section enlivened by
Latin cross-rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that one came about by chance,'' Krakauer said of this
last piece. ``It was born at a wedding I played at, in which the
groom was Jewish, and the bride was Colombian. There were two
bands, actually, mine and Los Macondos de Colombia, a group of
wonderful vallenato musicians. And we were switching off until at
one point we played together. We did a huge klezmer and vallenato
dance medley, and when it was over, the groom's father came up to
me, completely flushed with this incredible dancing, and said he'd
never heard anything like that. People really felt as though the
two cultures had come together at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of his cross-cultural experiments doesn't bother
Krakauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that in doing klezmer music, I consider myself a
preserver of a traditional art form,'' he said. ``But I don't want
to keep it in a museum. Any music, to be healthy, has to keep
moving forward. And I'm sure that there were people a generation or
two before Tarras and Brandwein who kvetched about what THEY were
doing to klezmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come to my concerts get a full sense of what
klezmer is. I'll play a bunch of tunes exactly as I'd play them at
a wedding, pretty straight, and then I'll play something that
examines something more intense. I think people are ready for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer, who turned 42 last week, grew up in Manhattan and
began playing the clarinet when he was 10. His first teacher, Joel
Press, played both classical music and jazz and introduced him to
the highlights of both worlds. When he was 14, Krakauer began to
study with Leon Russianoff, who remained his teacher through his
time at Juilliard, where he completed his master's degree. He also
studied at Sarah Lawrence College and the Paris Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to New York from Paris, Krakauer became a
freelancer with an increasingly busy workload. He was the principal
clarinetist in the New Haven Symphony and for the Martha Graham
Ballet, and he played regularly with New York Philomusica and in
new-music concerts by Continuum, Speculum Musicae, the Da Capo
Chamber Players and, as he put it, ``probably every new-music group
in town.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Aspen Wind Quintet, which won the
Naumburg Competition in 1984. He taught at Vassar for 10 years, at
Bard for one (a course in jazz history) and has been on the faculty
at the Manhattan School, the Mannes College of Music and Queens
College since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to klezmer music kind of by accident,'' he told a
listener who wondered where klezmer fit into all this. ``I grew up
very assimilated. My grandparents spoke Yiddish, mainly when they
wanted to say things that they didn't want my parents to
understand. My parents spoke a smattering of Yiddish. But by the
time it filtered down to me, there wasn't much Yiddish culture left
in my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I was studying with Leon Russianoff, he gave me some
pieces by his teacher, Simeon Bellison, who had played Jewish music
in czarist Russia before he moved to the United States and became
the principal clarinetist of the New York Philharmonic. So that
gave me some early exposure to Jewish music.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was a series of coincidences. I had a chance
meeting with Alicia Svigals of the Klezmatics, and she said, `You
ought to play klezmer clarinet, there might be a demand for it.'
And then I ran into someone else who was looking for a klezmer
clarinetist and thought I could recommend a student. But I said,
`Oh, I want to do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very spontaneous decision, and it took some chutzpah.
When I started to play, though, I thought: `This sounds familiar.
This sounds like my grandmother speaking.' It felt so easy, so
natural.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, around 1987, Krakauer thought of klezmer as a
musical hobby, something outside his regular career, and a way of
exploring his Jewish roots. In 1989 he joined the Klezmatics, one
of several young American ensembles that have given the klezmer
revival much of its momentum. He appears on two of the group's
albums, ``Rhythm and Jews'' and ``Jews With Horns'' (both on the
Piranha label), and in the group's set on the first of Itzhak
Perlman's klezmer albums, ``In the Fiddler's House'' (on EMI).
</P>
<P>
   By the time Perlman made that recording, and its related
television special, in 1995, klezmer had become a veritable growth
industry, not only in the United States, but in Europe as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's no coincidence that this interest really took off
in the late 1980s, coinciding with the fall of the Berlin wall,''
said Krakauer, who has made five trips to Poland to perform and to
teach klezmer to mostly non-Jewish students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they began to wonder, `What WAS life like when there
was a Jewish culture thriving here?' This summer I was teaching
classes sponsored by the Borderland Foundation, which is a group
located in the northeastern corner of Poland, where the borders
between Poland, Belarus, Ukraine and Lithuania have shifted back
and forth over these many years. And the director of the
foundation, who is not Jewish, said they have the sensation of
living on the ruins of an old civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel a need to understand Jewish culture, and they
believe that the way to understand it is to live in it. So klezmer
is something they really want to get deeper into. It helps fill the
hole left by what was torn out in the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer left the Klezmatics in 1996 to pursue his own vision of
klezmer. But he has kept up his career in other corners of the
musical world.
</P>
<P>
   He performed and recorded with the downtown composer and
saxophonist John Zorn, who in 1995 started Tzadik as an outlet for
what he calls ``radical Jewish culture.'' With the Kronos Quartet,
Krakauer recorded Osvaldo Golijov's ``Dreams and Prayers of Isaac
the Blind'' (on Nonesuch), a vivid, richly hued work about a
13th-century Jewish mystic that is well suited to Krakauer's
flexible, expressive technique. And there has also been more
conventional work; recent collaborations include a Weber Quintet
with the Tokyo String Quartet, and performances of Brahms chamber
works with the Lark Quartet and the Eroica Trio.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, klezmer dates increasing fill Krakauer's calendar. In
December, he is starting a series of weekly Sunday afternoon
klezmer concerts at Tonic, a club on the site of the old Kedem
Kosher Winery on the Lower East Side. And with the second Klezmer
Madness album about to be released, he is sketching out ideas for
the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do now,'' he said, ``is look at the klezmer
forms and see where I can go with them. And the balance I walk is
to not go so far that it doesn't sound like klezmer anymore. It has
to have that Yiddish feeling in it, that way of phrasing a melody,
and ornamenting it. It has to have my grandmother's voice in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll stretch it and stretch it, to the point where I
have to ask, `Is it klezmer or isn't it?' Sometimes it isn't, and
when I've created something that doesn't work, I throw it out. But
I don't mind when there's some ambiguity. In fact, I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO HEAR IT
</P>
<P>
   David Krakauer and Klezmer Madness are playing Krakauer's
``Klezmer Tribute to Sidney Bechet'' and other works at Symphony
Space, 2537 Broadway, at 95th Street, (212) 864-5400, on Sunday at
3 p.m. Tickets: $20, $15 for students, the elderly and members of
Symphony Space.
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer, who has made a spectacular recording of Osvaldo
Golijov's ``Dreams and Prayers of Isaac the Blind,'' with the
Kronos Quartet, is giving the world premiere of Golijov's
``Fanfare'' at Merkin Concert Hall, 129 W. 67th St., Manhattan, as
part of the hall's 20th anniversary concert Nov. 19. The concert,
which also includes performances by the Mendelssohn String Quartet
and Alicia Svigals, the violinist of the Klezmatics, is by
invitation to contributors to the hall of $25 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Krakauer is also the curator of ``Klezmer Sundays in the Wine
Cellar,'' a series of klezmer concerts at Tonic, a club on the site
of the former Kedem Kosher Winery, 107 Norfolk St., between
Delancey and Rivington Streets, on the Lower East Side, (212)
358-7503. Klezmer Madness is inaugurating the series on Dec. 6 at
1:30 p.m. Tickets: $10.
</P>
