<HEADLINE>
MLB, NETWORKS LINE UP GAME ANNOUNCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, well, well. There will be a fourth, and possibly a fifth,
game between the Red Sox and Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   With the best-of-five American League Division Series tied at
1-1 going into Friday's 4 p.m. game at Fenway Park, Major League
Baseball and the three networks covering the playoffs released the
weekend schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Buck and Tim McCarver call the 4 p.m. game Saturday at
Fenway on Fox (Channel 25).
</P>
<P>
   If the New York Yankees close out the Texas Rangers tonight or
Saturday, and the Sox and Indians need a fifth game Sunday, that
deciding game will be shown on Fox at 7:30 p.m. There is a
possibility that Fox will show the Atlanta Braves-Chicago Cubs Game
4 at 7:30, but that is extremely unlikely for one reason. A Game 5
is always better than a Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees need a Game 5, it would be shown on Sunday at
7:30 on Fox. The Red Sox-Indians Game 5, if necessary, would be
shown at 1 p.m. on ESPN, directly against the CBS telecast of the
New England Patriots-New Orleans Saints game.
</P>
<P>
   Competitiveness of a series is one factor networks use to
determine game times. Major League Baseball makes the ultimate
decision, but the networks have considerable input, especially the
two prime-time carriers this year _ NBC and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and NBC chose to air the Yankees' games in prime time for
obvious reasons: The team set an American League record for
victories, and it's New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are clearly the Goliaths of this year's playoffs,
and whether they win or lose, their rise and fall is a definite
story. Add the undeniable fact that the Yankees have a national
folowing and it becomes apparent why networks eagerly lined up to
air those games in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The games shown on ESPN are a little different. Since the
Division Series began three years ago, ESPN has wanted a chance to
air playoff games to round out its array of exhibition and
regular-season games and baseball news and feature programming. The
network's contract with MLB calls for it to air the afternoon and
late-night first-round games.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has much more flexibility than Fox or NBC. The two
over-the-air carriers have to worry about preempting prime-time
scheduling and are almost precluded from interrupting daytime
programming. All-sports ESPN doesn't have that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Take NBC's decision to air Braves-Cubs Saturday at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   NBC spokesman Ed Markey said the network had to make a decision
last night and couldn't wait until the outcomes of Friday's games.
NBC officials predicted that the Yankees would more than likely win
tonight. If Texas wins, Game 4 of the Rangers-Yankees series will
be shown Saturday at 1 p.m on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Market size is always a factor but not a major one. ``It's
incidental,'' Markey said. ``If everything else is equal, then the
bigger market would be preferable. A 20 rating in New York is more
viewers than a 20 rating in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   More important factors are time zone differences, especially for
ESPN. The network doesn't want to air the games of a West Coast
team at 1 p.m. EST or the games of an East Coast team at 11 p.m.
EST.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we can tell the teams or the major leagues that
we want this game to start at 2 p.m. and another game to start at 6
p.m.,'' said ESPN spokeswoman Diane Lamb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
