<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-REISCHAUER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARU REISCHAUER, JOURNALIST WHO WROTE ABOUT LIFE IN JAPAN; AT 83 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Haru (Matsukata) Reischauer, an author and journalist who was
the widow of the former US ambassador to Japan, died Sept. 23 in La
Jolla, Calif. She was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reischauer's career bridged the cultures of her native
Japan and the United States. She reported on her homeland for the
Saturday Evening Post and the Christian Science Monitor and was the
wife of the late Edwin O. Reischauer, who was ambassador to Japan
from 1961 to 1966 and a longtime member of the Harvard University
faculty. The university's institute of Japanese studies is named
after him.
</P>
<P>
   She was the author of the memoir ``Samurai and Silk: a Japanese
and American Heritage,'' which was published in 1986, and had been
honorary chairwoman of Harvard's Policy Advisory Committee of the
program of US-Japan Relations since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reischauer's paternal grandfather, Prince Masayoshi
Matsukata, was prime minister of Japan in the late 19th century.
Her father graduated from Yale University and her mother, though
Japanese, was born in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reischauer's childhood in Tokyo was spent under the
supervision of a series of English governesses. She attended the
American School in Japan. She graduated from Principia College in
Illinois in 1937 and spent summers during her undergraduate years
with her maternal grandparents in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to Japan in 1937 to find her homeland embarking on
the period of war that led to its devastation eight years later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, she married Reischauer, who was a member of the faculty
at Harvard. They settled in Belmont, Mass..
</P>
<P>
   During her term as an ambassador's wife, Mrs. Reischauer was the
second most popular woman in Japan, after the crown princess,
according to a 1962 article in the Christian Science Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1966 Globe story, she said that being the ambassador's wife
meant ``associating with Japanese women, bridging the gap between
the countries, and talking with the wives of American servicemen
who were stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese women,'' she said, ``think that Americans are very
militaristic because of our tremendous military buildup and the
Vietnam War. And, at the same time, American women in Japan needed
to understand the Japanese woman and the Oriental mind. When
anti-Western riots would break out, I would visit the Army bases
surrounding Tokyo to help explain the reasons why. ''
</P>
<P>
   She said the aspects of the position she found most demanding
were learning to make public speeches, forfeiting the academic life
in which she had plenty of time to read, and moving into the realm
of the women's clubs. At one time she was a member of 14 women's
groups.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves a son, Robert D. of Bethesda, Md.; two daughters, Ann
Heinemann of La Jolla and Joan Simon of Larchmont, N.Y.; two
sisters, Naka Rawsthorne of Los Angeles and Mari Bruck of Studio
City, Calif.; nine grandchildren; and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
