A4921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST02-COX     10-01 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIOPSY IN ATLANTA WATCHED ON CLOSED CIRCUIT TELEVISION
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While about 100 people watched on closed-circuit
television in a House caucus room, a woman underwent a breast
biopsy in Marietta, Ga., to demonstrate a new, non-invasive
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel a thing,'' said 47-year-old Judith Degen,
chatting with surgeon Richard Fine at the end of the 25-minute
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Members of breast cancer advocacy groups, congressional staff
members and five female members of the House and Senate put aside
lunches of sandwiches and potato salad and watched a television
monitor as Dr. Fine pushed a swizzle stick-sized needle through a
small incision in the side of Degen's right breast and began
extracting tissue for examination.
</P>
<P>
   When the procedure was over, she sat chatting with Dr. Fine, and
willingly opened her hospital gown to reveal an inch-long bandage
placed over the incision in which the needle had been inserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel a thing,'' she said. ``I highly recommend it.''
</P>
<P>
   A mammography had shown that she the breast contains
``microcalcifications,'' Dr. Fine said before doing the biopsy. In
10 to 15 percent of cases, the tiny white dots on X-ray film
represent a very early stage of breast cancer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new procedure became available, Degen would have
faced an operation in which she would have been put to sleep and an
incision made into her breast.
</P>
<P>
   The biopsy was performed at The Breast Center in Marietta and
used by the technology's manufacturer, Ethicon Endo-Surgery Inc.,
and the National Alliance of Breast Cancer Organizations to promote
findings of a poll indicating that most women with positive
mammograms are not informed of the biopsy options available to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The poll and the lunch served at the Thursday meeting were paid
for by Ethicon Endo-Surgery, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
