<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HAVE A LOT IN COMMON WITH EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky and Nomar Garciaparra were both born on July 23,
1973, in California _ she in San Francisco, he in Whittier.
</P>
<P>
   There. You have more proof that there is a Red Sox connection
with everything that happens in life.
</P>
<P>
   You think I am kidding? I am not kidding. We don't need six
degrees of separation or Kevin Bacon to link the Red Sox with every
major person and event of the century. Just try me.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest two stories of America's summer of 1998? Easy.
Sexgate and the Great Home Run Chase. The Monica-Nomar connection
covers our top story, and naturally, the Sox have a link to the
Home Run Chase. Mark McGwire's 70th and final home run was hit off
Carl Pavano _ the onetime Sox prospect who was dealt for Pedro
Martinez. In 1961, when Roger Maris hit No. 61, the pitcher, of
course, was Red Sox rookie righthander Tracy Stallard.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, name the topic, I'll give you the Sox connection.
</P>
<P>
   --The Titanic _ Too easy. Fenway Park was dedicated the same
week that the White Star ship sank to the bottom of the North
Atlantic. Leo DiCaprio wore a Red Sox cap when he attended Game 6
of the NBA Finals last spring.
</P>
<P>
   --The Yalta Summit _ No problem. Franklin Delano Roosevelt was
the cleanup hitter at Yalta. FDR went to the same high school
(Groton School) as Peter Gammons.
</P>
<P>
   --The Kennedy-Nixon debates _ Way easy. John F. Kennedy's
grandfather, John ``Honey Fitz'' Fitzgerald, threw out the first
ball for the first game of the 1912 World Series. The Red Sox have
had three players named Nixon _ Russ, Otis, and Trot. The Sox also
had a shortstop named John E. Kennedy and a manager, Kevin Kennedy,
who had a Johnson (Tim) as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   --Michael Jordan _ Played with Nomar in the Fall Instructional
League in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   --Cal Ripken _ Drafted with a pick acquired from the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   --Marilyn Monroe _ Said to have preferred DiMaggio over
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   --Matt Damon _ Never mind all the Carlton Fisk stuff in ``Good
Will Hunting.'' Go see ``Rounders.'' Damon plays a New York City
law student with a penchant for poker. Damon's character gets
cleaned out of $30,000 in a high-stakes, underground game at the
beginning of the movie. When he returns to the site at the end of
the film _ intent on reversing his misfortune _ he says, ``I felt
like Buckner going back into Shea.''
</P>
<P>
   --The Cheers Bar _ Barkeep Sam Malone, played by Ted Danson, was
a pitcher for the Red Sox, a guy who gave up the long home runs.
His nickname was ``Mayday Malone.''
</P>
<P>
   --Hank Aaron's 715th _ Aaron was originally property of the
Boston Braves. His record-breaking homer was hit over the head of
Dodgers left fielder Bill Buckner and was caught by Tom House, who
was later traded to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   --Bill Clinton's Girlfriends _ In 1992, presidential candidate
Clinton visited the Houston Astros' spring training site in
Kissimmee, Fla. The Astros were playing the Red Sox that day, and
Clinton exchanged a few words with Wade Boggs. Nice photo op. Both
of their mistresses (Gennifer Flowers and Margo Adams) wound up in
Penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   --The O.J. Trial _ Kato Kaelin moved in with Charlie Sheen after
he left O.J. Simpson's digs. Sheen is the man who paid $93,500 for
the baseball that trickled through Buckner's legs on the final play
of Game 6 of the 1986 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   --The late Jackie Kennedy Onassis _ Attended Billy Rohr's
one-hitter during the first week of the 1967 season with son
John-John. Jackie O had Rohr sign a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   --The Pope _ In 1978, the College of Cardinals assembled at the
Vatican to elect a pope. Boston television journalist Clark Booth
covered the event and was mildly surprised when the late Humberto
Cardinal Medeiros sought him out to ask how the Red Sox had done
the previous day. Booth remembers, ``I was standing in a courtyard
next to St. Peter's. I was waiting for them to come out. Finally,
there was a recess and Medeiros came out and asked, `How are the
Red Sox doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   --``Psycho'' _ Two connections. Anthony Perkins, who played
Norman Bates, also played Sox outfielder Jimmy Piersall in ``Fear
Strikes Out.'' And then there's Steve Lyons, the latter-day Psycho.
</P>
<P>
   --Wilt Chamberlain _ Tussled under the basket with Red Sox
starting pitcher Gene Conley.
</P>
<P>
   --John Glenn _ Flew missions with Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   --``Field of Dreams'' _ A scene was filmed at Fenway. Remember
Moonlight Graham?
</P>
<P>
   --World War I _ Shortened the Sox' 1918 season and put them in
the World Series on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   --World War II _ Took Williams, Johnny Pesky, and Bobby Doerr
away.
</P>
<P>
   --Walking On The Moon _ Happened on July 20 _ the same date that
the Red Sox led the Yankees by 14 games in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   --The Who _ Wrote anthem for Sox fans: ``Won't Get Fooled
Again.'
</P>
<P>
   --Jackie Robinson _ Went through a sham of a tryout at Fenway in
1945.
</P>
<P>
   --``Ally McBeal'' _ Shot scenes from first 1998 episode at
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   --The Kennedy Assassination _ Debbie Clemens, then an infant in
her mother's arms, was in Dealy Plaza Nov. 22, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   --The Beatles _ Breakthrough album, ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely
Hearts Club Band,'' released in 1967, the year the Red Sox regained
the love of New Englanders.
</P>
<P>
   --Watergate _ Carl Yastrzemski gave his 1967 MVP trophy to
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   --Boston Globe _ Formerly owned by Taylor family, which built
Fenway Park and named team ``Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   --Woodstock _ The site was Max Yasgur's farm. Known here as
``Yaz-gur's'' farm.
</P>
<P>
   --Babe Ruth _ We won't insult your intelligence by going there.
</P>
<P>
   --Elvis _ Whoa. You kidding? Have you taken a good look at Mike
Benjamin?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
