<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MO-VAL-BOS &LR;      10-01 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MO-VAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RED SOX' DYNAMIC DUO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every once in a while, they'll have a flashback. Mo will look at
Val, or vice versa, and instead of being at Fenway Park or Yankee
Stadium, they'll be back in South Orange, N.J., or Pawtucket, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Val and I have been through a lot together,'' says Mo Vaughn.
``Sometimes I look over at him and I think about how we used to
wash out our own uniforms when we were in college, and then think
about the life we're leading now. The big league life is very
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps somewhere in major league baseball, there is a duo who
can match Mo Vaughn and John Valentin for shared experience, but I
doubt it. Consider the resumes: two years together at Seton Hall,
parts of two minor league seasons together at Pawtucket, and major
league teammates as far back as 1992 and straight through since
1993 with the Red Sox. That's a lot of 6-3s, 5-3s, and even 4-3s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen often,'' says Valentin. ``Two guys playing a
large part of their major league careers on the same team after
playing together in college. Believe me, there have been a lot of
times when we've sat down and laughed about the whole situation.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Vaughn arrived on the Seton Hall campus, Valentin
was the starting shortstop on a team that included future major
league All-Star Craig Biggio and future cup-of-coffee major league
pitcher Kevin Morton. ``It was a really good team,'' asserts
Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo had a little transition period. We had a fall season, and
he did struggle a little bit. But when the spring season came, it
was boom-bam. He hit something like 27 or 28 home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did it as a designated hitter. ``Mo didn't even play
first base right away,'' Valentin explains. ``We had a guy named
Martese Robinson playing first, and Mo had to DH.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo would eventually take over at first base and leave Seton Hall
as the all-time school leader in average (.417), home runs (57),
and runs batted in (218). He was a three-year All-American, the Big
East Player of the Decade, and one of two Red Sox first-round draft
picks (No. 23 overall) in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin was not exactly ticketed for athletic greatness. He
arrived at Seton Hall as an unheralded 150-pound shortstop, and he
batted ninth. No one could have projected him into a fifth-round
draft pick or a future major leaguer capable of routinely hitting
40-plus doubles annually while driving in as many as 102 runs in a
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was always willing to work, and he was always willing
to do things the right way,'' says Vaughn. ``He has overcome
tremendous odds to get where he is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin happens to be white and Vaughn happens to be black.
This, to them, is an irrelevancy. ``We were close right away,''
says Mo. ``When you go to war with somebody as often as we have,
there is a bond. It doesn't matter what color you are. I think our
friendship shows people that in life, a thing like that doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happens that he's black and I'm white,'' Valentin
maintains. ``To me, it's as much a fact that we're both East Coast
guys as anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is from Norwalk, Conn. Valenin is from Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin finds it a curiosity that each wound up being drafted
by the Red Sox. ``I've often thought about it,'' he says. ``I have
nothing to base this on, but I'm wondering if the fact that (Seton
Hall's) Rick Cerone was with the Red Sox at the time had anything
to do with us both being drafted by this organization. Did he put
in a good word for us? I do remember scouts coming up to me when I
was in A ball in 1988 and asking me what I thought of Mo as a
ballplayer. Kevin Morton, too.''
</P>
<P>
   They were first reunited as professionals in 1991 with the
Pawtucket Red Sox. Vaughn got a call-up that year, hitting four
home runs (one of which came very close to becoming only the second
ball ever to leave Baltimore's Memorial Stadium) while batting
.260. He split time between Boston and Pawtucket the following
season.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin got his first taste of big league action in 1992 (.276,
5, 25 in 175 at-bats spread over 58 games). He became a full-time
major leaguer the following year, save for a two-game injury rehab
stint in Pawtucket. He did not have a straight-line path to the
bigs, either. There had to be some questions about him when he hit
.218 at Double A New Britain in 1990. But he never lost faith in
himself. He got into the weight room and he paid attention to every
detail. He never stopped believing he was destined to be a major
leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn needed some humbling and some adjusting before he became
the marquee player he is today. He admits that the big home run in
Baltimore gave him the wrong idea about what to do at the plate,
and he rededicated himself to mastering the inside-out swing that
produced the vital three-run homer in Tuesday's big win over the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Each remains president of the other's fan club. ``What Mo has
done this year is tremendous,'' says Valentin. ``To be honest, I
see a lot of things in the clubhouse you'll never see. He was able
to fight through so much this year to put up those numbers. I just
don't understand why he isn't signed. I can't think of any player
of his stature who wouldn't already have been re-signed by his
team. I don't know who we could ever bring in here to do what he
does for us, and do it in Fenway Park and in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo returns the compliment. ``Val has conquered so much to get
here, and the reason is he wants to be the best and he has always
been willing to do it the right way. Here's a guy who can play
short, third, and even second, and who can hit with power.''
</P>
<P>
   This right way/wrong way thing is important to Mo. ``What I'm
proud of is that we both had a plan,'' Vaughn says. ``We didn't
just want to get to the big leagues and then sit back and have a
good time. We wanted to get there and make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin will bat second and play third base Friday in Game 3 of
the American League Division Series. Vaughn will play first and bat
third. They're in the playoffs. They make a difference. In more
ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
