<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMINISHING SALES FOR `BRILL'S CONTENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Brill is gone. That horrible pun may explain decreasing
newsstand sales of the new ``Brill's Content'' magazine of media
criticism. Buoyed by founder Steven Brill's brilliant marketing
campaign for its ``Pressgate'' story, which alleged an unholy
collaboration between independent counsel Kenneth Starr and the
Washington press corps, the debut August issue received massive
media attention and flew off the newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brill's estimates, he sold between 275,000 and
290,000 copies of the first issue with 120,000 copies coming off
the newsstand. The September issue (with Bill Gates on the cover),
sold about 215,000 copies with about 60,000 of that representing
newsstand sales. No numbers are in yet for the October issue with
its cover story on TV magazine shows.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Shull, divisional merchandise manager for periodicals at
Borders bookstores, said ``demand was crazy'' for the initial
issue. ``The second issue was still very good,'' he added, ``but
nothing like the first one.'' Fred Cohen, the general manager at
Harvard Square's Out of Town News, is more blunt. ``We've displayed
it prominently, but without that media exposure, (sales have)
really tapered off,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No media outlet has a more experimental bent than The Orange
County (Calif.) Register (364,000 circulation), which bills itself
``the biggest community newspaper in the country.'' The paper _
known for enrolling staffers in a community awareness curriculum
and for putting suggestion boxes in local Starbucks outlets _ is
embarking on a technological and journalistic revolution dubbed
``The Dynamic Publishing System,'' scheduled for completion on
Valentine's Day 2000. (The paper has a mind-boggling 130 newsroom
people sitting on committees brainstorming on this.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what's happened with a lot of newspapers is that
they've clung to the way that works and the way they're organized
... because of technology that's outdated,'' said executive editor
Ken Brusic. ``As a consequence, it really affects the way people
think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Register is not only replacing the computer system for the
news and advertising departments, it is rethinking the traditional
concept of the newsroom. The goal is to create a series of
alternative newsrooms distributed throughout the circulation area.
(Brusic doesn't like to use the term ``bureaus'' because it implies
a heirarchical beat system.)
</P>
<P>
   The Register's secret weapon? The plan _ which is being tried in
a pilot program _ calls for the staff to be dispersed out of the
newsroom, with each reporter equipped with a laptop computer and
cellphone, what Brusic calls ``a sort of 21st century version of
the notebook.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and staffers are worried about the fate of The Daily
Free Press _ the 28-year-old student-run Boston University
newspaper that's been a training ground for countless journalists _
after a jury awarded a former employee almost $163,000 earlier this
week. According to the Free Press, the employee, Karen Miranda,
alleged she'd been fired from her job as office manager in 1994
because she was suffering from cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the award stunned Free Press editor Gene Johnson,
who said the paper might be forced to declare bankruptcy and
reorganize. ``Regardless, we really have to start squeezing things
as much as we can,'' he said. One immediate casualty is the Free
Press's once-a-semester magazine, Ink, which will cease
publication.
</P>
<P>
   According to Johnson, the Free Press has $140,000 in its
treasury, and an annual operating budget of around $450,000. The
paper had authorized a settlement with Miranda of up to $70,000,
but was clearly unprepared for the size of the judgement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lawyers kept telling us it was going to be settled,''
Johnson said. As the Free Press ponders its next move, its lawyers
are headed back to court to seek a reduction of the judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of Rolling Stone magazine lately seems much more
interested in flesh than Phish. A brief review of some recent cover
shots finds Janet Jackson falling out of her bikini top, ``Dawson's
Creek'' sweetheart Katie Holmes in a come hither pose, ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' star Sarah Michelle Gellar flaunting an S&AMP;M
outfit, model Laetitia Casta posing nude, and singer Shania Twain
having a major problem keeping her top on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we have female flesh on the Rolling Stone cover,''
responds mildly annoyed magazine spokeswoman Cathy O'Brien,
insisting this pulchritude doesn't reflect a new attitude. ``The
(cover) decision always is who's the most newsworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, when the music industry isn't making big enough
headlines, Rolling Stone relies on more basic marketing appeals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Jurkowitz is media critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
