<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEBEC-ENGLISH-BOS &LR;      10-01 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBEC-ENGLISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOUCHARD ASSAILS STORES' PLANS TO USE ENGLISH SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A venerable downtown department store has become the
latest flashpoint in Quebec's escalating language wars.
</P>
<P>
   This city's substantial English-speaking minority has mounted an
aggressive campaign to convince the Eaton store _ a 102-year-old
fixture in the heart of Canada's second-largest city _ to post
signs in English as well as French.
</P>
<P>
   But Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard Thursday called executives of
four leading North American retail chains onto the carpet, warning
Eaton, Sears, Wal-Mart and The Bay that any move toward English,
even in stores serving mostly anglophone customers, would
``jeopardize linguistic peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to know that it is completely unacceptable,'' said
Bouchard.
</P>
<P>
   But infuriated anglophones, as English-speakers are called,
renewed threats to launch a national boycott of Eaton stores and
possibly other retail chains to force the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to send a message that English is not a social
disease,'' said William Johnson, head of Alliance Quebec, the
province's top English rights group. ``English is not pollution. We
should be proud of our language.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Canada has enshrined both English and French as the
nation's official languages, Quebec refuses to abide by the dual
language standard, insisting French must predominate everywhere in
the public life of the restive province, from government documents
to restaurant menus.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, it is legal to use English in public displays, but
only if accompanied by equivalent French words printed in
characters at least twice as large and in a bolder hue. In reality,
any use of posted English _ except in a few neighborhoods much
visited by American tourists _ is likely to result in harassment
from the province's hyper-vigilant language police as well as
broken windows and spray-painted graffiti by Quebec nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec is the the only Canadian province in which
French-speakers form the majority of the population, about 80
percent of 7.3 million people. Most of the province's 800,000
anglophones live in and around Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, Quebec's English-speakers have been a passive
bunch, opposed to the drive for independence led by Bouchard's
governing Parti Quebecois, but more or less resigned to
second-class linguistic status. Even the name ``Eaton'' indicates
the degree of acquiescence; the department store was ``Eaton's''
for more than 75 years _ and so it remains in the rest of Canada _
but the chain removed the offensive apostrophe ``s,'' not used in
French, as a sop to Quebec's language purists.
</P>
<P>
   Whether known as Eaton or Eaton's, the company is Canada's most
famous chain and the store on Montreal's Rue Ste-Catherine is a
national landmark. Once a bastion of English Montreal, today every
sign on the premises _ whether marking men's socks or cosmetics
counter _ is in French only,
</P>
<P>
   But anglophone activists are demanding that retail outlets
serving a heavily English-speaking clientele, as is the case with
Montreal's Eaton, use signs in their language, in addition to
French.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we are seeking is respect for our community,'' said
Johnson, a former newspaper columnist who has emerged as the most
vocal champion of anglophone rights in a province where English
hospitals and other essential services have been shuttered by the
separatist government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual protest, several hundred English-speaking
demonstrators gathered outside the downtown Eaton store last week
to vent displeasure with the ``French only'' sign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The anglophones were met by jeering, egg-hurling toughs from the
ultranationalist Mouvement de Liberation Nationale du Quebec, a
fringe group descended from bomb-planting terrorists of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians go home!'' the nationalists chanted. ``Quebec for
Quebecois!''
</P>
<P>
   Although English is seldom heard in most of Quebec, Montreal has
boasted a large, thriving community of British-Canadians, Jews and
other anglophones since the 1700s and the city retains a uniquely
bilingual character.
</P>
<P>
   Most Quebec separatists are resolutely peaceful and despise the
Liberation Nationale movement's tactics of intimidation. But
provincial leaders pointedly declared Thursday that the push for
English signs could cause a dangerous backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Bouchard warned retailers against bending to the wishes
of English Quebecers. ``This is a provocation to our society,'' he
said. ``People who would make such a decision would show a profound
ignorance of Quebec's social landscape and Quebec's history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
