<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COMMUNISTS _ BEIJING _ For anyone who thinks that the
Chinese Communist Party is about to wither away and usher in a new
era of Chinese capitalism and democracy, events of the last month
must come as a stunning disappointment. As China celebrates the
49th anniversary of the Communist takeover on Thursday, President
Jiang Zemin has launched a Mao-like propaganda campaign to
celebrate the ``glorious'' achievements of the Chinese Communist
Party and of its military wing, the People's Liberation Army. Talk
of economic reform abounds in this multi-media blitz, but no one is
mentioning politicial reforms that might pave the way for democracy
and dilute the party's power. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
ETA: Noon.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MCCURRY _ WASHINGTON _ Michael McCurry, the mild-mannered,
wisecracking White House press secretary who has stood at the front
lines of President Clinton's troubles over this year's sex and
deception scandal, left his high-profile post on Thursday, saying
''frankly, the president misled me too.'' McCurry, a 43-year-old
father of three young children, signed off after 539 White House
news briefings and some 250 others given on the road, saying he
plans to spend time with his children, play golf and ''make a
little money.'' (Deans, Cox News Service 350).
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FARMERS _ WASHINGTON _ A report issued Thursday by the
Agriculture Department's inspector general says the department's
civil rights division is in disarray, has ``no decisive
leadership'' and is making no progress in clearing up a backlog of
discrimination complaints by black farmers. (Moscoso, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ WASHINGTON _ A fundraising letter from a major GOPAC
contributor on behalf of the Southeastern Legal Foundation has
raised concerns among some Democrats that the foundation may have
abused its tax-exempt status. The foundation is challenging the
Clinton administration's plan to use statistical sampling in the
2000 census. A court has ruled sampling illegal in a separate
lawsuit filed by Speaker Newt Gingrich. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAPES _ WASHINGTON _ House Judiciary Committee is
expected to release some 5,000 pages of Starr evidence on Friday.
(Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV _ As Congress releases more files from the
Clinton-Lewinsky grand jury probe on Friday, TV will be there to
cover it. But is too much too much (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PEROT _ WASHINGTON _ Checking the reaction, both pro and
con, to Ross Perot's announcement that he is launching a nationwide
petition drive asking President Clinton to resign. (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-VIAGRA _ WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon expects to spend $50
million this year on the anti-impotence drug Viagra for military
personnel and veterans, a spokesman said Thursday. The expediture _
about half of what was requested _ comes at a time when military
chiefs are pressing Congress for more operational funds and when
the military health service is cutting back services for reasons of
economy. (Nesmith and Carollo, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KING _ WASHINGTON _ Dexter Scott King, son of the assassinated
civil rights leader, led a forum Thursday on why he believes James
Earl Ray was ``not the trigger man'' in the assassination of Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr., and why the nation needs to re-examine the
circumstances of the 1968 shooting in Memphis. (Dart, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Cox photos will move to illustrate this story.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST _ WASHINGTON _ To dramatize the need for early detection
of breast cancer, a women's health group presents a televised
needle biopsy of an Atlanta woman during a press conference here.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SPERLING _ WASHINGTON _ Set between the silverware and plates of
eggs benedict are tape recorders, which the diners dutifully punch
into action when the genial host, Godfrey ``Budge'' Sperling,
announces as always: ``The only ground rule here is that we're on
the record.'' Once again, a national newsmaker will barely find
time for a sip of coffee while answering questions at a Sperling
Breakfast _ a Washington institution that celebrates its 3,000th
session Friday. (Dart, Cox News Service 600&AMP;add).
</P>
