   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PEDESTRIAN-FATALITIES _ ATLANTA _ A two-day national conference
in Atlanta on preventing childhood pedestrian fatalities discussed
``traffic calming'' features _ such as speed humps, curb extentions
and refuge islands. But the most obvious pedestrian aid, which is
only now debuting in some suburban Atlanta neighborhoods, and is
still nonexistent in many others, is the sidewalk. ''We need
policies that say the sidewalk goes in as soon as the street gets
built,'' said Dan Burden, a Florida based pedestrian advocate and
traffic engineer. (Ledford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AEROSPACE _ Former Air Force secretary Hans Mark gives the
keytnote speech at the National Aerospace Conference at Wright
State. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News). 10.
</P>
<P>
   LA-NINA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Thanks to September's heavy rains,
grass is greener these days in Texas than it's been since April.
But it could turn brown again and stay that way until late spring,
if dueling areas of cold and warm water in the eastern equatorial
Pacific Ocean reach a cold conclusion. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WONG _ Profile of Al Wong, Georgia's first elected judge of
Asian descent, who will be honored with a dinner sponsored by the
National Association of Chinese-Americans on Friday. (Woo, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
