<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-INDEPENDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG ANNIVERSARY OVERSHADOWED BY WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ China celebrated 49 years as the communist People's
Republic Thursday with performances, fireworks and speeches, but
regional economic turmoil and devastating floods cast a shadow over
this year's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech in Beijing, Premier Zhu Rongji praised
socialism's ``superiority and vitality,'' but acknowledged the
``international financial market has brought difficulties and
pressure to bear on China's growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, the rich capitalist enclave that returned to
Chinese rule last July 1, the 15-month-old Asian crisis cast a
broader shadow over festivities than in mainland China, which has
been largely insulated from the economic storm.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's open markets have been severely rattled by the
crisis, with property values dropping around 50 percent and the
stock market down over one-half from last year. Unemployment is at
15-year-high of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   China, however, has been spared some of the crisis' damage
because of its closed capital markets. Zhu asserted that China is
expanding foreign trade and industrial production and will have a
strong harvest despite the floods.
</P>
<P>
   But many economists say the weakened economies and currencies of
China's neighbors, as well as the costly damages brought on by
flooding, will make it impossible for China to meet this year's
target growth rate of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The target is considered the baseline necessary to create enough
jobs for tens of millions of workers who are losing cradle-to-grave
benefits as state-owned enterprises restructure. Meanwhile, the
International Monetary Fund this week cut its growth forecast for
China to 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Outside analysts worry that Zhu, the strongest proponent of
swift and sometimes painful reforms, has recently backslid on
promises to privatize housing and trim the debt-ridden state
sector.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the flooding that swept south-central and
northeastern China this summer _ the worst since 1954 _ officially
claimed 3,004 lives and cost more than $36 billion in losses. The
government has said the disaster could shave between half and one
percent off gross domestic product projections.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, officials emphasized the positive Thursday,
praising soldiers involved in flood relief and launching lavish
celebrations in Tiananmen Square under the portrait of communist
China's founder Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Hong Kong's bad news compounded as car distributor
Dah Chong Hong and industrial group Chen Hsong Holdings announced
layoffs, as did Cathay Pacific and filmmaker Golden Harvest.
Retailer Dickson Concepts Ltd. announced its third pay cut this
year, affecting 1,600 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, several hundred workers organized by the Hong Kong
Federation of Trade Unions marked through downtown shouting angry
slogans urging the government to take action. The government has
already intervened in the stock market, using an estimated $18.7
billion of public money to buy blue-chip shares.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa used his National Day
speech not to answer critics, but to promote patriotism and
cooperation with leaders in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But some locals said they were more concerned with Hong Kong's
bottom line than with talk of brotherhood with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have Chinese blood, but honestly I have penetrated
Western culture,'' said Francis Yau, 36, a computer salesman who
was watching a patriotic show by PLA forces. ``Hong Kong people
still don't totally agree with everything China is doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
