</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKET FALL DOES SERIOUS DAMAGE TO NISSAN'S FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The destructive impact of Tokyo's tumbling stock market
on corporate Japan turned apparent Thursday when Nissan Motor Corp.
announced a severe decline in the value of its securities
portfolio, which will likely erase profits for the six months that
ended Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Japan's second-largest car maker, said it would
record a 76 billion yen paper loss, about $553 million at current
exchange rates, because the value of certain marketable securities
it holds had fallen below the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Before the announcement Thursday evening, Nissan's shares had
sunk to a 15-year low of 315 yen, or $2.33, on heavy volume. Rumors
that the troubled auto manufacturer, struggling to reduce some of
the 4 trillion yen in debt it will have at the end of this fiscal
year in March, would fail to post a profit contributed to the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In May, when the benchmark Nikkei 225 index stayed largely in
the 15,500-point range, the company predicted its profits in the
first six months of the fiscal year would roughly equal last year's
net income for the period of 38.5 billion yen. On Thursday the
Nikkei closed at 13,197.12, the latest in a series of 12-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   While Nissan was one of the first to report the extent of the
stock market's damage to its finances, Nissan's disclosure is only
the tip of the iceberg. Trading companies and steel companies, in
particular, have large portfolios, as do insurers.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Japanese companies have carried their securities
portfolios at book value, rather than at current market prices. But
in 2000, they will be required to adopt what's known as
mark-to-market accounting, which will better reflect the real value
of their holdings, and some corporations have moved to adopt the
standard ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of Japan's debt-laden financial institutions are
now haunting those companies. Many companies hold bank stocks as a
result of the keiretsu system, the system of cross-shareholding
that has created powerful clusters of businesses financed by a core
bank or banks. Bank stocks have collapsed, and with them, the
portfolios of a good part of corporate Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In Nissan's case, the market has punished the car company not
only for its own problems but that of its main bank, Fuji Bank,
regarded by analysts as one of the most troubled in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      10-01 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLY IN BONDS CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices surged again Thursday for the fourth
consecutive session and pushed yields down to levels not seen since
1967, reflecting a growing investor migration out of stocks and
into the safety of government securities.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in bonds was also helped by a monthly report from the
nation's factory purchasing executives that showed further weakness
in American manufacturing _ the fourth consecutive month of
decline. Bond investors regarded that report as fresh evidence that
economic turmoil abroad is slowing the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond rose 1 10/32 to a price of 109 26/32. Its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 4.88 percent
from the previous 31-year low of 4.97 percent set on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treasury securities continued on their moonshot,'' said Donald
Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management. Worldwide
alarm over falling stock prices, he said, means that ``demand for
Treasury securities is coming from all quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine said he believes the Federal Reserve's decision Tuesday to
lower interest rates by one-quarter point was merely the first step
in the easing process; another quarter-point reduction will likely
come at its policymaking committee's next meeting in November, he
said. Lower rates would increase the value of bonds already in
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market may also have derived some strength from
expectations that the September employment report, scheduled for
release Friday by the Labor Department, will show that job growth
slowed because of weakening demand for American exports, which
depressed manufacturing production and employment.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists have forecast that the economy added 195,000
jobs last month following a gain of 365,000 during August. They
also have predicted that the unemployment rate for September held
steady at 4.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
