A4986 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPT-COX     10-01 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Non-profit agency works to get seperated families together
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Beda Warrick decided to trace her roots about a year
ago, searching for the parents who had put her up for adoption as
an infant.
</P>
<P>
   She found her birth father in Maine, her birth mother in New
Jersey, and a passel of biological siblings in between. Now the
39-year-old Atlanta accountant is trying to help others who wish to
find a child or birth parents. She's organizing Georgia's version
of RegDay, an event that draws attention to the International
Soundex Reunion Registry, the world's oldest, largest and most
successful free mutual-consent registry.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone separated from a blood relative by adoption, divorce or
war can sign up. If the non-profit agency mets a match, it puts
both parties together. Since 1975, the Carson City, Nev.-based
group has matched up 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Like tens of thousands of adoptees and birth parents, Warrick
had to plow through official roadblocks designed to seal adoption
records permanently. She found her birth parents not through the
registry but her own hard work _ and a lot of luck. All but three
states _ Kansas, Tennessee and Alaska _ seal records, and adoptees
can get birth certificates bearing only their names and the names
of their adoptive parents. Birth parents can't get information,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Although Georgia's only RegDay site is at a Roswell Wal-Mart _
where volunteers will distribute registry forms and answer
questions _ anyone can register by phoning 702-882-7755.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of names are in the ISRR computers, and
more than 1,000 new registrations are processed monthly, says
Anthony Vilardi, its registrar.
</P>
<P>
   For most adoptees and birth parents, he said, curiosity begins
early and never ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I processed a woman this week who was adopted in 1904,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Motivations vary, from curiosity, to finding a way to deal with
guilt, to a driving need to know about family genetics, heritage
and history, said Dr. Richard Winer, a Roswell psychiatrist who
counts adoptees and birth parents among his clients
</P>
<P>
   ``I see more adoptees who are very curious than the other way
around,'' Winer said. ``It's an idea of wholeness.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick was adopted when she was four days old. She decided to
search for her roots, in part to know something about family
heritage and medical history. She found out her birth mother and
father had never married, and as was the custom of the day, her
birth mom had come South on a train to surrender her for adoption
in West Palm Beach, Fla. ``We all have the idea that our biological
parents didn't want us, and we want to know why,'' Warrick said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she said she's getting along well with her biological
parents, and says her search strengthened her relationship with her
adoptive mother.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
