<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ANTZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High hopes of `Antz' flawed by predictable script
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When our nebbishy hero, Z, frets to his shrink about being
``middle child in a family of 5 million,'' the voice is instantly
recognizable as Woody Allen's. The body isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting six legs, a set of antennae and a bulbous posterior, Z
looks exactly like his gazillion neighbors. But he's about to make
a very distinct impression, as he literally decides to walk (and
dance) to his own beat in ``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest visually remarkable, computer-animated feature
that, like ``Toy Story,'' finds witty human satire in the least
human places.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Z is a reluctant worker in a totalitarian culture, an ant
colony plastered with pointed banners (``Let's Work!'' ``Conquer
Idleness,'' etc.). While his fellow miner Azteca (Jennifer Lopez)
and soldier pal Weaver (Sylvester Stallone) are content with their
lives, Z isn't at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a Disney film, this would be the cue for the
someday-I'll-find-my-place-in-this-world song.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't a musical. And ``Antz'' is from DreamWorks, which
is getting a head-start on Disney's similarly themed computer epic,
``A Bug's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Z isn't the only ant dissatisfied with his life.
Princess Bala (Sharon Stone) also chafes at her royal duties. But
as the Queen (Anne Bancroft) reminds her, ``Everyone has their
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a thesis statement screaming to be disproved.
``Antz'' spins an elaborate ``be yourself'' theme by sending Z and
Bala outside the anthill, where they encounter vicious killer
termites, fatal magnifying glasses that shoot burning sun rays,
gummy human feet and a place of rotting food and spilled colas,
known to the ants as ``insectopia.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the script of ``Antz'' is sometimes as
predictable as its visuals are not. It's a one-joke movie.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's 30-year-old, neurotic-dweeb shtick only underscores the
sense that the flick is constructed of secondhand or recycled bits.
Lacking the moments of giddy joy, surprise and wit that made ``Toy
Story'' a marvelous blend of technology and storytelling, ``Antz''
can feel pre-programmed. It lacks the kind of individuality that
its hero is striving to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Woody Allen, Sharon Stone, Sylvester
Stallone. Directed by Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson. Rated PG. 1
hour, 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A visual picnic that's marred only by a so-so
script.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
