A4990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PIGEONS-COX     10-01 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PIGEONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This `Pigeon' more like a turkey
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's happening. Low-budget independent films are becoming as
generic and self-cannibalizing as some Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   First came a string of interchangeable big-city, coffeehouse,
should-I-leave-my-boyfriend gabfests among young professionals
(``Walking and Talking,'' ``Naked in New York,'' ``Celeste Calls
Up,'' etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Now come all the Quentin Tarantino/Coen Brothers clones,
throwing in serial killers, small-town crackers and general bad
taste. (Some examples looming on the horizon: ``Very Bad Things,''
and a bigger-budget exploration of the same territory, ``A Simple
Plan.'')
</P>
<P>
   The newest from this mold, ``Clay Pigeons,'' has the imprimatur
of three indie regulars, Vince Vaughn, Joaquin Phoenix and Janeane
Garofalo. They're the best things going in a movie that has both
too much and too little going on.
</P>
<P>
   The flick kicks off outside small-town Mercer, Mont. Enjoying an
afternoon of target practice, Earl (Gregory Sporleder) aims the gun
at his pal Clay (Joaquin Phoenix), accusing him of sleeping with
Earl's wife, Amanda (Georgina Cates).
</P>
<P>
   Instead of killing Clay, though, Earl shoots himself. That way,
he figures his death will be pinned on Clay.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I wouldn't give away a plot twist like this one. But
it's only the first in a series of implausibilities. If you buy
this revenge-by-suicide notion, you might enjoy ``Clay Pigeons.''
It mixes murder and rural eccentricity with little attention paid
to logic. By the time a serial killer shows up, you'll hardly
notice, since the town's entire population seems to be borderline
insane.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn plays Lester, a drifter with a good-ol'-boy enthusiasm
and a goofy laugh; it's a terrific performance that's squandered on
this material. Same goes for Garofalo, playing a federal agent
tracking the killer. She puts her reliable deadpan spin on
insignificant lines and perks up the action, but can't save the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clay Pigeons''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joaquin Phoenix, Vince Vaughn. Directed by David
Dobkin. Rated R for violence, sexuality, language. One hour, 44
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A ``Fargo'' clone too self-conscious for its own
good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
