A4991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ROXBURY-COX     10-01 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ROXBURY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprise! `SNL' skit works on the big screen
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Live'' has taken a lot of hits over the years,
none more persistent than this: So many of its skits just aren't
funny, people complain. And even the ones that are humorous, aren't
after going on for too long.
</P>
<P>
   So how much hope could there be for ``A Night at the Roxbury,''
the feature-film version of that already almost-stretched-too-thin
``SNL'' skit about a pair of clueless, head-bopping and
nightclubbing brothers? It's a one-note joke _ actually, it's the
first few notes of Haddaway's ``What Is Love?'' that always drown
out the TV brothers' lame pickup lines _ one that clearly seems
destined to play out as the next ``It's Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   Except it's not. Oh, ``A Night at the Roxbury'' is silly, all
right. It's so silly, it's downright embarrassing, but only because
you're laughing so hard at certain points, you're afraid they'll
send in the head usher to remove you from the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Which would be tragic, because then you'd miss the picaresque
tale of the Brothers Butabi, high school graduates (it only took
them seven years each) and reluctant employees of their nouveau
riche pop's Beverly Hills silk plant boutique.
</P>
<P>
   But only by day. By night, Steve (Will Ferrell) and Doug (Chris
Kattan) have a dream. At first, it's just to gain admittance to
L.A.'s coolest nightclubs, with the coolest of them all being the
Roxbury. If it weren't the coolest, why would former ``21 Jump
Street'' star Richard Grieco _ playing a slightly older, more
bloated version of himself _ be such a cherished guest there?
</P>
<P>
   But what the Butabi boys really want to do is create their own
cool club! Nothing can deter them _ not rude rejections from club
bouncers and bodacious babes, and not the constant attempts of
their father (Dan Hedaya) to squelch their dream and create a
retailing dynasty by marrying Steve off to the daughter (Molly
Shannon) of the lamp store owner next door.
</P>
<P>
   And not their own social ineptitude, which _ like the boys'
seemingly endless supply of shiny suits _ anyone can spot a mile
away. Anyone except Steve or Doug Butabi, that is.
</P>
<P>
   They strut confidently down the beach, blissfully unaware that
their black thong bathing suits are on backward. They're never at a
loss for words _ ``Just what I thought, `Made in Heaven,''' Steve
coos to a startled woman after checking out the label on the dress
she's wearing _ even when they really, really should be.
</P>
<P>
   If it's memorably goofy lines and the silly fun of the ``There's
Something About Mary'' variety you want, ``Roxbury'' has it all.
But there's also something sweetly innocent about the way the
brothers support each other and react with genuine surprise when a
couple of great-looking women seem to fall for them.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a fairly coherent story line that wraps everything up
in less than 90 minutes, and the result is a better-than-average
comedy _ from the minds of ``SNL'' writers or anyone else, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Doug Butabi would say when trying to re-create a pleasant
mood: ``Puppies and candy canes, all right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Night at the Roxbury''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Will Ferrell, Chris Kattan, Dan Hedaya, Molly Shannon.
Directed by John Fortenberry. Rated PG-13 for language and sexual
content. 1 hour, 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A night to laughingly remember.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
