<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN02-COX     10-01 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: So little left of Creola, storm can't do much
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A gentleman with the euphonious name of Pat Patrick called with
a timely question. ``Guess where the eye of the Hurricane Georges
is now!'' he directed.
</P>
<P>
   I was giving him a choice of Gulf Coast hurricane spots when he
cut me off. ``It's over Creola!'' he said triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   Aw, I thought, Creola, Ala., is too little and peaceful, even
insignificant, to attract the attention of a major hurricane. But
we used to count on them in years that had a six in them _ 1906,
1916, 1926 and 1936. As for an eye, we always met and recognized
that period of dead, ominous quiet that comes in the middle of a
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He has his sources down there, where I spent the happy years of
my childhood. Also at Buck's Crossing and Mount Vernon. Calvert and
maybe even Chunchula and Celeste. He stays informed because he,
too, grew up in South Alabama and still has kinfolks scattered
along the river.
</P>
<P>
   My own family wasn't able to show any concern about Creola, as
much as I extolled its charms all their lives. They clearly thought
that a spot so distant from Mobile would not warrant the attention
of a storm. By the old road, it was 18 miles north of Mobile; by
the new paved road, 15 miles. And since they have an expressway and
all kinds of signs, the distance may be even shorter now.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend a lot of midnight hours waxing anxious over the
approach of a hurricane to an old home place. I worried about
Mobile's old homes and century-plus oak trees, but I couldn't focus
on anything Georges would endanger in Creola. All that I loved is
already gone, wiped out by what some call progress.
</P>
<P>
   J. Paul Getty bought and destroyed the mills and the turpentine
still, the commissary and office, the house where we lived and all
the houses where our friends lived. His excuse was to make room to
explore for oil wells. I guess he found the fuel, because we saw on
our last visit months ago _ before I started crying and we left _ a
towerlike structure with flames leaping out of it.
</P>
<P>
   In Creola proper, three miles from the mill, the two-room
grammar school where I went is long gone, and so is Mays' store and
post office, by the gravel road where we would see salesmen passing
through and sell tickets to school plays and church box suppers.
</P>
<P>
   Out at the mill where my father's family operated a naval stores
business as far back as before the Civil War, the only thing that
remains is the millpond, which some fishers and hunters from Mobile
have acquired as a ``sportsman's club.'' This clear amber body of
water would placidly await the eye of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   So I didn't worry over Mr. Patrick's call. I guess I felt a
little homesick for all the hurricanes we lived through and the
calm with which we greeted them. My mother believed in having food
ready. (A fire in the wood range would have been hazardous.) She
almost always had a baked ham ready for sandwiches and a big
chocolate cake. Now people evacuate _ a word in hurricane
vocabulary. We stayed home, mainly, I suppose, because there was
not a plenitude of shelters and motels in our area.
</P>
<P>
   A friend sent me a little historical sketch of Creola by my
schoolmate Mildred Ellison Smith, and I was warmed and cheered to
learn that Creola is still served by freight and passenger trains
from the Southern Railway. Is the flag station still there, or did
some oil tycoon or maybe some hurricane get it?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
