<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-CHARLESTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plant what you know, gardening expert advises
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ If it weren't for the cackles, you could
almost hear the gasps Thursday as Felder Rushing urged
horticulturists and gardener wannabes alike to toss the rules about
planting into Charleston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't England, it's not Maine, and it's not Texas. We
waste a whole lot of time and money trying to grow things here that
aren't meant to be,'' the Mississippi extension agent and
best-selling author said.
</P>
<P>
   And, at least for locals attending the Charleston Garden
Festival seminar, set in a city steeped in rules and traditions,
that was a tough pill to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing said Southerners should concentrate on growing native
plants or at least tough ones that have adapted over the years to
extreme climate and soil conditions. That doesn't mean, however,
that gardeners shouldn't travel to see great gardens, borrow ideas
and experiment with new plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't appreciate what you are or where you live until you
get out and scratch and sniff,'' Rushing said.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh-generation gardener, Rushing lives in Jackson and
co-wrote 1993's best-selling gardening book, ``Passalong Plants''
(University of North Carolina Press, $16.95). He described four
types of gardeners: the ``wound-tight'' control freak who plays by
the rules, the cottage gardener who does what he likes, the
``mowers and blowers'' and the copiers/adapters.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing, who counts himself among the last, showed slides of his
own garden, complete with yard art _ old tires made into planters,
trees adorned with bottles and kitchen sinks converted into water
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago that no matter what you do, your
neighbors are going to talk about you anyhow, so what you do is
your own business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he appreciates good design, he learned a simple approach
to arranging plants. ``My rule of thumb is you always include
something roundy, something spiky and something frilly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But plants are his thing. He's a member of the American
Hemerocallis Society, but the only daylily he grows is the common
orange `Stella de Oro', found in ditch banks across the South. He
knows he will have no problem with it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, garden designer and writer Scott Ogden left
the audience with the same message. A nationally known expert on
garden bulbs, he urged the gardeners to refocus their efforts on
heirloom bulbs, such as crinum, that have flourished along Southern
roadsides for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Today's speakers include University of Georgia horticulture
professor Allan Armitage and Mike Shoup of Dahlonega, an expert on
heirloom roses.
</P>
<P>
   -- The festival, the Southeast's largest fall gardening event,
includes garden tours, a market and workshops through Sunday.
Information: 843-722-0661.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
