<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FUNK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Fakin'' needs a little more bakin'
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rodney King's famous 1992 muttering, ``Can we all (just) get
along,'' has somehow become a movie called ``Fakin' Da Funk.''
</P>
<P>
   The heavy-handed morality tale that would probably play better
shorter, and on television, works hard to be diversity training for
teenagers. But the depictions of stereotype after stereotype work
just as earnestly at stripping away its good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Fakin''' starts in Atlanta, when Joe (Ernie Hudson) and
Annabelle Lee (Pam Grier) end up with a Chinese baby after an
accidental switch at the adoption agency. (Notice their last name).
</P>
<P>
   The father, a preacher no less, demands that the agency ``find
us a black-looking baby. Take this child and bring out the right
order.'' And when his wife says she wants to keep the baby, he
shoots back: ``Can you make moo goo gai pan?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the couple keeps Julian (Dante Basco), who by
elementary school has picked up the cadences of his father, is
dismissing his white female classmates' glances (``Look, baby, this
ain't `Ebony &AMP; Ivory'. I don't like cream in my coffee'') and goes
on to be in the choir. Accepted as ``black'' all the while.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for some vague reason, when Joe dies, Annabelle decides to
pack up Julian and his younger black brother, Perry (Rashaan Nall),
and move them to South Central Los Angeles. Julian and Perry's
first scene as the new boys in the 'hood is on the predictable
proving ground for young black men: the basketball court. And once
Julian shows the neighborhood players that he's got game, they
quickly conclude that ``Korean Abdul Jabbar,'' is ``Fakin' Da
Funk'' _ or pretending to be something he's not.
</P>
<P>
   What follows isn't hard to figure out: The guys who called the
Lee brothers a ``21 Jump Street starter kit'' on the court end up
being their best buddies. And the added, funny, story of a Chinese
exchange student (Margaret Cho) mistakenly being placed with a host
family (John Witherspoon, Nell Carter) in South Central ends with
the whole block practicing tai chi.
</P>
<P>
   But what is a bit perplexing is why Grier chose this background
kind of role after her supposed ``big comeback'' in Quentin
Tarantino's ``Jackie Brown.'' Or why ``Fresh Prince of Bel-Air''
star Tatyana Ali (Julian's love interest) decided to make her
post-television movie bow in what should be on the tube.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, this is a good answer to a lot of ``Whatever
happened to's?'' Tichina Arnold (``Martin''), rapper Tone Loc
(``Wild Thing'') and first ``Vibe'' television host Chris Spencer
all help make ``Fakin' Da Funk'' watchable, if not always
digestible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fakin' Da Funk''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pam Grier, Tatyana Ali, Ernie Hudson and Margaret Cho.
Directed by Tim Chey. Rated R for language. 1 hour, 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An after-school special in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
