</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IMPOSTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Impostors' barely rocks the boat
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flawed as it is, ``The Impostors'' is impossible to dislike.
It's too full of talented, entertaining people such as Lili Taylor,
Campbell Scott, Dana Ivey and Hope Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Stanley Tucci's follow-up to his immensely popular
``Big Night'' is something of a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to replicate '30s screwball comedy, the movie lacks
the crucial spark to make it sparkle. The result is a film that's
often amusing but rarely flat-out uproarious.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci and Oliver Platt play a pair of down-and-out actors in the
1930s. After a front-page run-in with an imperious Broadway ham
(Alfred Molina) who catches Platt spoofing his overripe Hamlet, the
two stow away on a luxurious ocean liner.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Molina is aboard, too, and our heroes spend most
of the movie trying to elude him and the ship's head steward
(Scott), a tyrannical Teuton with a dueling scar.
</P>
<P>
   The madcap tone is set less by the pair's travails than by the
passengers and crew. There's the social director (Taylor), who,
when she isn't fending off Scott's stilted advances, is a
sympathetic ally; a penniless widow (Ivey) on the hunt for a
wealthy new husband; her hilariously glum daughter (Davis); an
alcoholic, suicidal lounge singer (Steve Buscemi); and a half-dozen
others (Isabella Rossellini, Billy Connolly, Tony Shalhoub, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Individual comic sequences are sometimes successful, sometimes
not. The larger problem is that the script lacks the intricate
cohesiveness essential to farce. Plot complications don't build on
one another; they're simply tacked on (a conniving couple of
seducers, a terrorist with a cabin full of explosives).
</P>
<P>
   Still, the assorted characters are awfully funny, to the point
that they upstage the leads. Imagine the Marx Brothers, whose
``Monkey Business'' and ``A Night at the Opera'' this movie
recalls, being the butt of their comic chaos instead of the
instigators and you'll have an idea of the problem. Tucci and Platt
look funny together. They've been funny in other films. But somehow
they're not all that funny together.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the supporting players steal everything that's not
nailed down. Special mention must go to Scott. Everything he does
is amusing, from his stiff Germanic bearing to his clumsy but
insistent wooing of the uninterested Taylor. Catching up to her
after yet another attempt to corner the stowaways, he says
insinuatingly, ``The danger of the chase has made you perspire. It
has also made me ... moist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Impostors''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stanley Tucci and Oliver Platt. Directed by Tucci.
Rated R for language and sexual situations. At metro theaters.1
hour, 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Slight silly fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
