</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-NIGHTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fellini, Masina shine in `Nights of Cabiria'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one else in movies has a face like Giuletta Masina. Part
kewpie doll, part waif, with those huge Keane-kid eyes and just a
touch of Bette Davis as Baby Jane.
</P>
<P>
   Her looks were as unique as her talent. ``Chaplin-esque'' is the
word critics typically use, but it's not quite accurate. Her
naivete seems almost a self-protective bubble, her scrappiness more
instinctive.
</P>
<P>
   I can't think of a better introduction _ or re-introduction _ to
Masina than ``Nights of Cabiria.'' Filmed by her husband, Federico
Fellini, in 1957, the movie is a series of vignettes _ some
poignant, some funny, some wistful, some satiric _ that show us a
few days (and nights, naturally) in the life of a Roman prostitute
named Cabiria (Masina). A winner at Cannes and the Academy Awards,
the picture later provided the basis for ``Sweet Charity,''
starring Gwen Verdon on Broadway and Shirley MacLaine on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Cabiria is the eternal hooker with a heart of you-know-what.
Wandering the streets in her ankle socks and ratty fur, she's
hardly streetwise _ though she fancies herself so. But she is a
survivor. Her encounters with a bum of a boyfriend, a bum of a
movie star, a bum of another boyfriend _ you get the idea _
invariably end badly. Yet her resilience is both comic and
admirable. And one scene, in which a stage hypnotist gets her to
reveal her innermost longings, is as ineffably touching as anything
ever put on film.
</P>
<P>
   This new print hasn't just been spruced up for a new generation
_ seven minutes have been restored. A sequence called ''the man in
the sack,'' about a good Samaritan who feeds the city's poor, was
supposedly cut because the Vatican thought it made the church look
bad. True or not, the added section is welcome simply because it
gives us more Masina, more Fellini. More of both, please.
</P>
<P>
   One note to Fellini fans: This is not the over-the-top
``Fellini-esque'' maestro of ``8 1/2'' or ``Satyricon.'' This is
early Fellini. Simple. Toned down. Lovely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nights of Cabiria''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Giuletta Masina. Directed by Federico Fellini.
Subtitles. Not rated, but the subject matter is sexual and adult. 1
hour, 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Another magical restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
