u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENS-TALK-COX     10-01 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-TALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC: Moms can get teens to use condoms
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Don't abandon the idea of parental guidance just yet.
Teens whose moms give them a heart-to-heart talk about condoms
before they become sexually active are much likelier to practice
safe sex, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Most sexually active teens, about 71 percent, say their moms
discuss condoms with them.
</P>
<P>
   But the key is for mothers to bring up the subject at an early
age, the CDC emphasizes. Teens who get the condom talk before they
have sex for the first time are three times more likely to use
condoms than teens who never discuss condoms with their mothers or
only after losing their virginity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised that parents made such a difference,'' said
CDC research sociologist Kim Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and other researchers interviewed 372 sexually active
teens, ages 14 to 17, and their mothers in Alabama, New York and
Puerto Rico. The study appears in Thursday's issue of the American
Journal of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not address the influence fathers may have on
teens' sexual behavior, because of the study's limited budget as
well as the absence of fathers in about half the families involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we know fathers are very important,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that teens who use a condom the first time
they have sex are 20 times more likely to subsequently use condoms.
The average age of first sexual experience in the study was about
14 years. The average age at which teens in the study discussed
condoms with their moms was 13.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC estimates that half of all new HIV infections in the
United States occur among young people under 25. Teens account for
3 million cases of other sexually transmitted diseases annually,
and 1 million teenage girls become pregnant each year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
