<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN is brushing up image with a new set
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN will unveil a new anchor set and newsroom Monday, the
biggest change in the cable news network's on-air look in more than
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers won't be able to miss the new look, which includes the
Atlanta skyline behind the anchors and a new curved, wooden desk
with a cherry finish that gives off a reddish glow. The $7.5
million project, which also includes extensive renovation of the
newsroom, has been under construction since March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't changed the look of CNN in years,'' said Richard
Kaplan, president of CNN/U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``A set will never raise your ratings or cover up substantive
problems,'' he added. ``But what a good set will do is make it
easier for a viewer to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The new look will be nowhere near as big a break with tradition
as CNN competitor MSNBC's set, an exposed brick loftlike room that
Jay Leno once joked looked like a cross between a Lenscrafters and
a Bennigan's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just needed to freshen it up, bring it into the '90s,'' Sid
Bedingfeld, newly promoted executive vice president of CNN/U.S.,
said of the CNN set.
</P>
<P>
   The new CNN look, scheduled to appear on the air at 7 a.m.
Monday, will have the new wooden anchor desk at the front of the
viewer's TV screen. Behind the anchors, about 200 CNN staffers will
be working in the main CNN newsroom, with several clocks showing
different time zones also visible. On a back wall and above the
newsroom is a ``sign band'' of 15 CNN logos, which are gray with
red tubing. And below the sign band will be a series of photos of
the Atlanta skyline called a Duratrans, which will turn to night
photos during the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The anchors will sit on a newly built slab that actually juts
out over the CNN Center atrium, five stories overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tight in here,'' said Chuck Burleson, project manager
for Turner Properties. ``In the CNN Center, we basically have 15
pounds in a 10-pound bag.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN tour groups are already getting a sneak peek at the new
newsroom and anchor desk from a glassed-in corridor that's elevated
out of camera range.
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   CNN on the road
</P>
<P>
   CNN correspondent Larry Woods is on the road, re-creating John
Steinbeck's journeys in his 1962 book ``Travels With Charley.''
Woods, winner of an Edward R. Murrow Brotherhood Award for human
interest reporting, will retrace Steinbeck's route around the
perimeter of the United States from Connecticut to California. His
first report, an interview with Steinbeck's widow, Elaine, airs on
``CNN Sunday Morning'' (8-10 a.m.), and subsequent reports will
also air Sunday mornings. Woods also will write a weekly column for
CNN's Web site, http://www.cnn.com.
</P>
<P>
   A new anchor
</P>
<P>
   Also new at CNN: Anchor Carol Lin starts Monday on ``Early
Edition,'' the 7-9 a.m. ET show with Leon Harris. Lin, who's been a
national correspondent for ``Good Morning America'' and ``World
News Tonight,'' replaces Donna Kelley, who's moving to New York to
get married. Kelley will do free-lancing for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
