<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUILT-ART-REVIEW-2NDT     10-01 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILT-ART-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: later productions. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her first story quilt was done in 1983. Titled ``Who's Afraid of
Aunt Jemima?'', it's a grid of comical, childlike portraits,
accompanied by the rambling success story _ in black dialogue _ of
``Aunt Jemima Blakey'' and her children, who made a fortune in the
restaurant business.
</P>
<P>
   It transforms the derogatory image of Aunt Jemima into that of a
beautiful, successful businesswoman in a chic hat, probably based
on Willi Posey. Having found her real metier, Ms. Ringgold began to
work exclusively in the narrative quilt form, a singular vehicle
for her complex musings about ancestry, the black-white world and
her relation to it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best of her early quilts are several that deal with
family life in Harlem, like the popular ``Tar Beach'' (1988), whose
title is the same as that of Ms. Ringgold's acclaimed children's
book, published in 1985. Set in the 1930s, the scene is a homey,
nighttime family picnic on a rooftop (the Tar Beach of summer
stay-at-homes), against the glamorously lighted backdrop of the
George Washington Bridge. As her siblings sleep on a blanket,
Cassie Lightfoot, the 8-year-old narrator, flies over the bridge,
claiming it as her own. The quilt is the first of a sprightly
series dealing with women and famous bridges, whose spans symbolize
fantastical pathways to woman's freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The American Collection,'' the narrator is now Marlena, the
daughter of Willia, and the powerfully stated issues ``are less
about art and more about America,'' Ms. Ringgold said. And in
truth, the American quilts _ without the customary narrative
borders _ are starker, harder hitting and more strikingly composed
than the French group. The first of them, ``We Came to America''
(1997), depicts New York Harbor aswarm with drowning blacks forced
overboard from a burning slave ship in the background. In front, a
black Statue of Liberty with dreadlocks holds in one arm a torch
and in the other a symbol of hope, an infant rescued from the
agonized horde behind her.
</P>
<P>
   But the set piece of the ``American'' group here is ``Born in a
Cotton Field'' (1997), a dramatically composed Nativity scene in
which a haloed black infant sits between doting parents in a field
of cotton. Behind them looms the Prince of Night, a huge black
figure with arms protectively outstretched. Shocked villagers,
their faces partly hidden by cotton bolls, witness the holy birth.
Based on a fairy tale composed by Marlena, the scene pays tribute
to a slave child in Africa who, if successfully hidden, will
eventually lead the other slaves to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   All praise to the vivid sense of history, the audacious
imagination and above all the irrepressible joie de vivre that have
produced this appealing show. It will be supplemented by a
selection of additional quilts from ``The American Collection,''
along with other works, on view at the ACA Galleries, 41 E. 57th
St., from Oct. 10 through Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at the Louvre: Faith Ringgold's French Collection and
Other Story Quilts'' remains at the New Museum of Contemporary Art,
583 Broadway, near Prince Street, through Jan. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
