A5031 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CART-MARKETING-2TAKES     10-01 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CART-MARKETING-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CART-MARKETING-2TAKES 
 
CORPORATE SPONSORS GET ON THE `CART' TO REACH THE MASSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG HASSELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Some impressive autos have roared into Houston for the
Texaco Grand Prix, and they're burning plenty of high-octane
marketing fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors are shelling out $400 million to finance
racing teams in the Cart FedEx Championship Series _ which includes
Sunday's race _ and adorn them with names like Marlboro Team
Penske, the Miller Lite Ford and the Nicoderm CQ-Nicorette Champ
Car.
</P>
<P>
   Logos are slapped high and low, covering the cars, the drivers
and a good number of the non-moving surfaces surrounding the
downtown course.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dominant symbols flashing around Houston will be
the Texaco star. In addition to the millions it pays to sponsor
drivers Michael Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi, Texaco is
spending more than $1 million to be the primary sponsor of the
Houston race. That gives the oil company the right to put its logo
at 60 ``key locations'' around the course. And that's not including
the starting point and the finish line, which will be branded with
the name of the race _ Texaco Grand Prix of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   As if that sort of exposure weren't enough, Texaco has paid for
a slew of television commercials and billboards touting its
connection to the big race.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco has jumped on the racing bandwagon with both feet
because, ``Racing is one of the two growth sports right now, the
other being golf,'' said Kevin Ilges, manager of sponsorships and
events at Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   The cars racing at a grand prix have some of the best engines,
the best components, the best fuels and the best drivers in the
world. That's the sort of company an auto-related sponsor loves to
keep.
</P>
<P>
   ``That speaks volumes about the performance capabilities of the
products that are involved,'' said Sixtus J. Oechsle III, executive
director of corporate identity at Shell Oil Co., which is
sponsoring a car in Houston's grand prix. ``It's key to having
consumers feel comfortable with putting these products in their own
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   While racing is a natural for companies selling auto parts,
motor oil and gasoline, it also attracts sponsorships from
retailers, beer makers and a long-distance telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a truly international sport that does great at the
gate and has a very high demographic profile, which is very
important to sponsors,'' said Bret Werner, spokesman for
Championship Auto Racing Teams, the sanctioning organization for
the FedEx Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   According to CART studies, spectators at grand prix races are
twice as likely as the average American to have graduated from
college. They have an above-average household income of $52,700.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing is hot, and its gaining in mainstream popularity,''
said Bob Dorfman, a vice president and sports analyst for the San
Francisco-based advertising agency Foote Cone &AMP; Belding.
</P>
<P>
   During the past seven years, total race attendance has jumped
from 112,000 per weekend to 147,000 per weekend. At the same time,
the number of races has grown as CART adds events in cities like
Houston. Total attendance at CART races has soared nearly 50
percent, from 1.7 million in 1990 to 2.5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   All reserved seats in Houton already are sold out. More than
200,000 people from around the world will attend the event,
including some of the pre-race practice runs. In addition, the race
will be televised live on ABC and rebroadcast by ESPN to 188
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Response to the inaugural Texaco Grand Prix of Houston has far
exceeded our expectations,'' said race general manager Jim Melvin.
``We were sure we would have a lot of interest from ticket buyers
all over the country, but the demand for tickets, paddock passes
and corporate hospitality has genuinely surprised all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   While it might surprise locals, the success of racing does not
come as a shock to some advertisers, who could see years ago that
it was emerging as a popular sport in America.
</P>
<P>
   Back around 1971, when Congress eliminated tobacco advertising
from television, the big cigarette makers started looking about for
other promotional venues.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious solution was billboards, which they latched onto in
a big way. A less obvious strategy was sponsoring sporting events.
Since 1971, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has sponsored several
catagories of racing, including the Winston Cup Auto Racing
Circuit, Winston Drag Racing, and the now defunct Camel GT Series
and the Camel Mud and Monster Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing is made for television. That's the key,'' said Dr. Alan
Blum, a Baylor College of Medicine physician who has tracked
tobacco companies' advertising practices for more than 30 years.
``There would be no tobacco advertising of racing were it not on
TV. This allows them to get around laws that prohibit them from TV
advertising. If I were a cigarette marketer, I would have done
exactly the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlboro alone spent $20 million on racing promotions in 1992.
Fifteen percent of Marlboro's ads sport racing themes, according to
company documents released during recent legal battles with the
federal government and sundry state agencies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
