<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CART-MARKETING-2NDTAK     10-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CART-MARKETING-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CART-MARKETING-2NDTAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  HOUSTON: state agencies. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry has a narrowed field of communication
channels to consumers now. That makes every channel that's left to
us _ like racing _ more valuable,'' said Bert Kramer, sponsorship
manager for Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., which sponsors Team
Kool Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing is a sport that is high tech, that's contemporary,
that's exciting,'' Kramer said. ``Those are attributes our
consumers tells us are important to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing fans also are more likely to be smokers than the general
public. According to studies cited by Brown &AMP; Williamson, 36
percent of CART spectators are smokers, compared to 22 percent of
the total U.S. public.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes racing a good vehicle for us,'' he said. ``This
gets our brand out to the adult population and the smoking
public.''
</P>
<P>
   According to those company documents released during the various
court cases, tobacco companies found that racing projects a
masculine, powerful and dangerous image. Fans see race car drivers,
like cowboys, as loners, adventurers and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies have found racing to be fertile ground, and
that has attracted the attention of SmithKline Beecham, which makes
products for those who want to kick the habit: Nicorette gum and
the NicoDerm CQ patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost 75 percent of smokers polled say they would like to
quit, so we are making our name visible at venues that cater to
smokers,'' said Steve Kapur, associate director of promotion at
SmithKline Beecham, which sponsors the Nicoderm CQ-Nicorette Champ
Car. ``Racing is a good venue to reach smokers.''
</P>
<P>
   To piggyback onto its race sponsorship, the company has
dispatched to Houston its NicoVan _ a 34-foot long motorhome that
provides free counseling and tips for stopping smoking. The van
made stops at several Houston area stores this week, plus it will
be parked at the track area this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart is another sponsor looking to get more bang for its
sponsoring buck by mingling with the general public. On Thursday,
drivers Michael Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi appeared at
separate Kmart stores in Houston. Kmart also has the rights to sell
Houston Grand Prix merchandise in its stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will drive our sales up, definitely,'' said Nicole Brown,
who directs Kmart's motorsports vendor relations.
</P>
<P>
   Not every big corporation is eager to write a multi-million
dollar check and become the next big sponsor of an auto racing
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very expensive thing,'' said Jim Carter, vice president
of marketing at Exxon Co., which is not a big racing sponsor.
``It's hard for us to justify. Exxon already is a well-known
company, and name recognition is the prime benefit of a
sponsorship. We try to deliver a message instead of just saying,
`We're Exxon.'''
</P>
<P>
   No sponsor will tell you that participating in racing is cheap,
but they will argue that it's cost-effective. One favorite bit of
evidence is a report by Financial World magazine and Julius &AMP;
Associates in 1992, which examined 1,100 sporting events and
concluded automobile races represented eight of the 10 best
corporate sports sponsorship values.
</P>
<P>
   According to a CART study, 46 percent of grand prix spectators
say they are more likely to try a brand for the first time if the
product sponsors a favorite team or driver. The norm for this
measure when applied to all types of sponsorships is closer to 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a loyal and knowledgable group,'' Shell`s Oechsle
said. ``They really care about engines and performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Locating this race in Houston allows CART sponsors to bring
their show into a whole new part of the country. There are no other
grand prix races in the Sunbelt or southern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a state we've never raced in,'' said Ron Richards,
vice president of communications at CART. ``This allows our
sponsors to reach into a whole new market for racing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the race is over and the drivers have headed off for their
next contest, the marketing effort will just be beginning for one
Houston company. Koch Materials Co., one of the largest asphalt
companies in the country and a division of Houston-based Koch
Industries, supplied the binding material that holds the course's
asphalt together.
</P>
<P>
   The streets constituting the grand prix course _ including
Austin, Crawford, Capitol and Clay streets _ were paved with
demanding quality specifications so they can withstand the pressure
of cars flying along at 200 miles per hour, heating their massive
tires up to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come up with a new product, something that hasn't been
used anywhere,'' said Jerry Brown, a sales representative for Koch
Materials. ``It is supposed to last anywhere from 15 to 20 years
under normal circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Standard asphalt lasts about 10 years before it needs
resurfacing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the course streets were repaved earlier this summer, city
engineers from Arizona, Florida and Kansas came to watch the
process and check out the quality of the new paving material. Those
engineers, potential clients for a company like Koch, can be
expected to come back for another look after the Texaco Grand Prix
of Houston has blazed past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for the race to demonstrate the superiority of
our product,'' Brown said. ``This will be the smoothest, most
durable two miles in Houston.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
