<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5040 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-EXPANSION-KAN     10-01 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-EXPANSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA APPROVES $2.6 BILLION EXPANSION OF ST. LOUIS AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Federal Aviation Administration on Wednesday
approved an expansion plan at Lambert-St. Louis International
Airport expected to give Trans World Airlines a financial boost and
reduce flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have promised lawsuits to delay the expansion, saying
the plan would increase noise and needlessly displace thousands of
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion plan would add a third runway at Lambert, one of
TWA's hubs. The $2.6 billion plan, which would also add terminal
space and improve roads, would be one of the largest airport
expansions ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to look back on this one day and realize it was a
pivotal moment for St. Louis' future,'' said Jeff Rainford, a
spokesman for Citizens for a Modern Airport, a coalition of civic
and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements would be completed in 2003 at the earliest. The
expansion would be St. Louis' largest public-works project ever.
Most civic and business leaders, including TWA, back the plan.
</P>
<P>
   TWA says delays cost it millions of dollars a year because poor
weather can leave Lambert with just one working runway. The airline
had been shaky financial ground in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the airport estimates that delays could cost
airlines $400 million annually by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would add a 9,000-foot-runway but would require the
removal of more than 2,000 homes in the adjacent city of Bridgeton.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, known as W-1W, would double parking and terminal space
and increase passenger gates by about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents question how much the plan would help. They say
W-1W would not reduce delays as much as promised. They have asked
the FAA to conduct a computer simulation of air traffic under the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has divided residents in the western suburbs since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents in Bridgeton, St. Charles and other neighboring
towns mobilized against Lambert's expansion from the start. This
week, dozens protested at the mayor's office. A vanload of
opponents even drove to Kansas City last spring to picket a speech
by the airport's director.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bridgeton residents formed a group called ``Let's Get on
With Our Lives'' and want the airport to buy their homes as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeton officials said they planned to sue St. Louis in state
court, saying the city has no right to unilaterally expand the
airport outside its boundaries. Other cities plan to sue in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was going to come,'' said Rowan Raftery of
Bridgeton Air Defense, an opposition group. ``What this does is it
gives us an opportunity to challenge the decision. Once this gets
into the courts, that will cast a lot of doubt, and they could tell
them to go back and start over.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Air Traffic Controllers Association and the Air
Line Pilots Association see the need to expand but oppose W-1W.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert is the second-fastest-growing airport in the world.
Airport officials project traffic to double in 20 years. The
airport has consistently ranked in the top five in delays among
major U.S. airports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
