<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PEROT02-COX     10-01 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PEROT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEROT LAUNCHES PETITION DRIVE AMID CATCALLS FROM CLINTON CAMP
 &HT;    340&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and its allies Thursday ridiculed
Ross Perot's call for a national petition drive to ask President
Clinton to resign because of his ``erratic'' behavior in the Monica
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ross the hoss is back _ bucking again,'' quipped sharp-tongued
loyalist James Carville.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas businessman and founder of the Reform Party, speaking
on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' Wednesday night, issued a call to
veterans, ministers, small business owners and others to circulate
petitions locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will show them that we care about morals and ethics,'' he
said. ``We'll show
</P>
<P>
   them that we care about duty, honor and country. And, more than
anything else, we'll show them that the man who sends our children
into combat, and a man who can press the nuclear button, has got to
be a stable person who tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential press secretary Michael McCurry brushed aside the
Perot challenge, saying, ``His comments in the past several days
confirm the good judgment of the American people who did not elect
him president.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond to Perot's promise on CNN that he would not run
for president again if Clinton resigns, McCurry joked, ``That's
admittedly the first compelling argument we've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party chairman Russell Verney said of the reaction from
the Clinton forces: ``We would expect nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the petition drive, conceived only 24 hours before
it was unveiled, would be led by Reform Party state leaders. Part
of their job, he said, would be to send volunteers to collect
signatures at polling places on Election Day, Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Verney said that an Internet site, whose address (www.perot.org)
Perot held up for viewers, has received more than 500,000 visits
since Wednesday's announcement. The Internet site includes petition
forms that ask Clinton to ``resign now for the good of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot envisions a convoy of trucks bringing the signed petitions
to Washington in early December.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Response from the political establishment has been low-key.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom Delay, R-Texas, might be a natural ally,
since he has called for Clinton to step down, but his response was
cautious. According to spokesman Michael Scanlon, Delay said,
``Perot's his own person. He has a following and we'll see how it
turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   Carville conceded that Perot might spur a big turnout in a
petition rally in the capital. ``What's he worth, about $8 billion?
With $8 billion he ought to be able to put any number of people on
the Mall,'' he said. But, Carville said, ``You got about 90 percent
of the people who think he's a nut.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot is not alone in trying to stir up public input in the
presidential scandal. Consumer activist Ralph Nader on Thursday
called for a national referendum on the president to be added to
the Nov. 3 ballots.
</P>
<P>
   And People for the American Way, a liberal group, is raising
funds to run advertising spots urging an end to the impeachment
effort against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way has gathered a coalition of
environmentalists, feminists, labor union members and others behind
their campaign. Its message is ``it's time to move on to the real
issues,'' identified as education, health care and the
international economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made a big mistake'' in having a sexual liaison
with a former White House intern, said Michael Lux, political
director for the organization. ``But he has apologized for it, and
we think the punishment does not fit the crime in terms of him
being taken out.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
