A5045 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      10-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T WAIT TO DEAL WITH HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: An organization that provides sexual-harassment
awareness training after it's sued for having a hostile work
environment is like the person who vows to floss at the moment the
dental drill bites into tooth enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Good intentions. Too late to prevent the problem at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Two U.S. Supreme Court decisions issued this summer put
employers on notice about their proactive duty to stop sexual
harassment. The penalties for not acting on that duty can be
costly.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said employers might be liable for on-the-job
sexual misconduct even if they didn't know it was happening and
even if there was no tangible, job-related action taken against the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions should strike fear in employers' pocketbooks.
But the decisions also give clear guidelines to avoid trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That explains the flurry of sexual harassment seminars popping
up in workplaces around Kansas City and the nation. Employers that
were ``too busy'' or ``too small'' to worry about such staff
training have changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what employers are doing to protect themselves:
</P>
<P>
   Providing mandatory seminars to employees _ especially managers
_ to define, recognize and avoid sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Putting zero-tolerance policies in place and making sure the
work force knows the consequences of violating them.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing complaint channels and assuring workers that they
can file complaints without job retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up in-house investigation systems that move quickly and
fairly to investigate claims.
</P>
<P>
   Making it clear that no one _ not even the chief executive _ is
exempt from the zero-tolerance policy.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decisions also put a specific burden on the
harassment victim: If there is a policy and complaint system in
place, the victim must use it to protect his or her rights.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions broadened the definition of harassment beyond
having a hostile work environment or quid pro quo harassment _
which, for example, would include promising a raise in return for
sexual favors.
</P>
<P>
   The new definition asks whether the harassment was severe or
pervasive enough to alter the working conditions of the victim's
job.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions also make a distinction between harassment
initiated by a supervisor or a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   If the harasser is a peer, courts will ask whether the employer
knew or should have known about the harassment and whether the
employer took immediate action to stop it once it was discovered.
If not, employer liability looms large.
</P>
<P>
   If the harasser is a supervisor, courts will ask whether
tangible employment actions (demotions, failure to promote, etc.)
were taken against the victim. If so, there is employer liability.
</P>
<P>
   Even without tangible employment actions against the victim,
employers will be held liable for supervisor-inflicted harassment
if the organizations can't prove they had effective anti-harassment
and complaint policies in place.
</P>
<P>
   If employers can prove they had well-publicized policies and
procedures but the victim failed to take advantage of them,
employers may escape liability or at least be forced to pay reduced
damages.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late for lagging workplaces to take proactive care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
