<HEADER>
A5048 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      10-01 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIMPSES OF A CYCLE COMPLETED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHELATNA LAKE, Alaska _ Everything now speaks of endings.
</P>
<P>
   Last night there came another snow. The mountains at daybreak
wore a fresh crown of white, and this time it may stay.
</P>
<P>
   The sockeye salmon, or reds, have finished their run. There
still are some late ones lingering in the creeks, and now and then
_ quite by accident _ one will be foul-hooked or will strike a lure
being cast for trout or coho.
</P>
<P>
   But it is meaningless. Since leaving the ocean and returning to
the freshwater streams of their origin to spawn and die, they have
eaten nothing. Their remaining life is measurable in days, or for
some only hours.
</P>
<P>
   They are fast deteriorating, their flesh no longer suitable for
the table.
</P>
<P>
   But if one happens to become attached to a fisherman's line,
then runs with the current or turns its crimson flank broadside in
the flow, the power of the doomed creature can be astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   In the lake itself, the shallows near the shore are full of
them, floating dead or holding feebly in the still water and
waiting for the end, the future of their kind guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The brown dog, Jesse, stands shoulder-deep at the edge, growling
and barking at the untidiness of so much death all around.
</P>
<P>
   Then someone comes with cart and pitchfork to cleanse the shore
and haul the whitening corpses away for disposal in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, with guide Wade Elg, we decided to try Otter Creek
again, a stream we'd fished before with only moderate success. Cold
nights have lessened the runoff from the higher elevations. The
creek has fallen, and today the silver salmon were there in good
numbers, along with the occasional spawned-out red.
</P>
<P>
   Wade had brought along a folding table and chairs so we might
take our last shore lunch in comfort and with a bit of style.
</P>
<P>
   When the lodge closes next week for the winter, he said, he and
his fellow guide, Adam, plan to turn their attention to bigger
game. They'll set up a camp and lead visiting hunters to moose.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall in one of the lodge buildings we'd seen two
photographs of Wade. In each of them he was peering over the
bristling back of a grizzly he had slain. Wade is a bit of a bear
himself, but those creatures were enormous. In the pictures, they
looked as large as city buses.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with bears, in his view, moose are more work than
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to pack the meat out. If you keep the antlers and
cape, a moose is seven loads over 100 pounds,'' he said. ``So
/{where/} you shoot him's important. You want it where you can get
to him with a boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Light clouds drifted across the deep blue of the coming-autumn
sky. The air, pungent with spruce, had a hint of an edge to it.
Sometimes, talking or just drinking in the freshness of the day, we
forgot to fish.
</P>
<P>
   In that easy manner the afternoon got away. We motored to the
rendezvous on the river, and Seth came with the yellow pontoon
plane, circled once and then landed to gather us up.
</P>
<P>
   By the supper hour a threatening bank of clouds had settled over
the lake. It just might happen that a storm would prevent our
flying back to Anchorage tomorrow, said our host, Duke Bertke. It
was unlikely, but at least possible.
</P>
<P>
   I walked a last time down to the shore, trying to hold that
hope, even if I knew it was nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   In the dark water I could see the shadows of great salmon, their
destiny fulfilled, adrift now in the long continuum of their
generations. And I was reminded that, like them, every creature has
its time.
</P>
<P>
   And this was ours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
