<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-TOWN-KAN &LR;      10-01 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-TOWN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN ISN'T WAITING TO DEAL WITH YEAR 2000 COMPUTER GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Neb. _ Combines are earnestly combing the cornfields
here to harvest a bin-busting crop that is bringing farmers a
trifling $1.70 per bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle producers and 1,200 former employees of BeefAmerica Inc.,
once the town's largest employer, are still smarting from the
plant's closing in July, which dried up a $20 million annual
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Country Kitchen restaurant, those who have time to
take a break complain about the 40-degree drop in temperature over
just two days.
</P>
<P>
   So who has time to worry about a glitch that could cause
computers to fail on Jan. 1, 2000?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, about 200 small-business leaders, homemakers,
police officers, plumbers, bank presidents and politicians who
gathered Wednesday for a Year 2000 town hall meeting at Northeast
Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in human history in our time that can equal
this,'' said City Administrator Mike Nolan, who organized the
meeting and has become the town crier on the challenges of the Year
2000 problem. . ``For some reason, this is not resonating with a
majority of our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the audience, though, the wheels were turning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I knew all there was to know about Y2K,'' Gene
Walker with Hy-Vee Foods said of the nickname for the programming
problem, which could prevent computers from operating properly if
they can't recognize the difference between 1900 and 2000. ``But
after 10 minutes here, I felt my heart rate begin to go up, and I
can feel it in this room.''
</P>
<P>
   In 200 stores in seven Midwestern states, Hy-Vee will spend $6
million for a new software system and replace 800 personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Others in this city of 22,000 are already in motion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Norfolk will spend $300,000 to fix the glitches in
its system. Patrick Roach of Faith Regional Health Systems is even
planning ways to get nurses to work in a Y2K emergency.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a good idea, said Fire Chief Shane Weidner, who
expects problems on Jan. 1, 2000. ``You're going to call 911 and
we're not going to be there immediately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weidner's warning seemed to take the audience aback. And this
wasn't a crowd that would be easily spooked.
</P>
<P>
   Located in the Nebraska plains, the city still has a gritty
self-reliance that seems far removed from even Omaha. At midday,
tractors rumble down the main street without drawing a second
glance.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's gathering was different from other Year 2000 town
hall meetings being held across the country in places like Lowell,
Mass.; Medford, Ore.; and Boulder, Colo. In those cities, the push
for preparation comes from residents' demanding answers from
reluctant city leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In Norfolk, the hometown of Johnny Carson and Thurl Ravenscroft
(the voice of Tony the Tiger), the city leaders are warning
residents about the impact the Y2K bug could have if power plants
go dark, phones die and fuel pumps stop.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses like the Battle Creek Coop, Volkman Plumbing &AMP;
Heating and the Norfolk Rescue Mission all got on board to sponsor
the meeting. Of the 5,000 invitations sent, 200 people showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not good enough,'' said Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   But one national expert Nolan brought in for the meeting was
impressed by the turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk could become a prototype for other communities that need
to prepare, said Douglass Carmichael, a Washington-based
psychoanalyst and information consultant who has worked for the
U.S. government, Philip Morris and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the country, politicians don't want to panic
constituents, Carmichael said. Employees don't want to panic their
bosses. Business leaders don't want to panic investors.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to hush the potential for problems are actually
making matters worse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making certain a higher degree of ultimate panic
weeks before the year 2000, when people feel helpless to do
anything,'' Carmichael said.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan wants Norfolk to be prepared. After all, northeast
Nebraska isn't exactly a warm part of the country in January if the
power does go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two groups of people who are really dangerous,'' he
said. ``Those who are the alarmists and those who are in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk's information systems manager, Jim McKenzie, worries
about banks, which play a key role in a rural economy dominated by
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency Management Coordinator Faythe Peterson holds
twice-a-month meetings with police, fire and utility officials. The
Norfolk City Outlook newsletter carries a Year 2000 article in each
edition and public service announcements are being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   A Y2K civil defense drill is being organized to simulate the day
the computers might crash. Local ministers have agreed to help get
the word out. And the police department will send a Y2K speaker to
any neighborhood association that will listen.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Nolan doesn't want to panic Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's non-productive to assume this thing is going to be
apocalyptic,'' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Nolan is planning to stock a two month's supply of
tuna and soup in his home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
