A5063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSSIL-COX     10-01 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whale of a fossil makes big scientific mark
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A very old creature discovered in Georgia 15 years ago
finally has a name and an important niche in science.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern University scientists have named the creature,
a whale that lived 40 million years ago, Georgiacetus vogtleensis.
Its remarkably well-preserved remains _ North America's oldest
fossil whale skeleton _ were discovered in 1983 about 30 feet in
the ground by workers building Georgia Power Co.'s Plant Vogtle
nuclear power plant near Baxley.
</P>
<P>
   The new moniker ``honors both the state in which it was found as
well as the name Vogtle,'' says Georgia Southern acting President
Harry Carter.
</P>
<P>
   When the fossil was removed from the construction site, most of
it was still encrusted in rock. It was kept in some back rooms of
the Georgia Southern Museum in Statesboro, where over the years
scientists tediously chipped away the rock and learned how to fit
the skeletal pieces together. Then they analyzed the skeleton and
debated over it for several more years to determine its role in the
evolution of whales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consulted with whale experts all over the world, and many
of them came here to study it,'' says Georgia Southern
paleontologist Richard Hulbert Jr. ``It is perhaps the best
preserved specimen of an early whale in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In their report in the September issue of the Journal of
Paleontology, the Georgia Southern researchers conclude that the
fossil represents not only a new species, but a new genus _ an
entire classification of animals.
</P>
<P>
   Hulbert says the fossil is especially important to science
because it might shed light on the time when whales were moving
from land to the sea about 40 million years ago. At that time,
South Georgia was covered mostly by a tropical sea. The shoreline
stretched along what is known today as the ``fall line,'' which
runs through Columbus, Macon and Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   When they began living in the sea, whales switched to
tail-propelled swimming; their hind legs were reduced and
eventually lost. Also, the connection between the backbone and the
pelvis was no longer needed for support on land and was lost to
increase flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The pelvis of the Georgia Southern fossil has lost the
connection with the backbone, but the hind legs were still used for
swimming even though the tail provided most of the power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fossil initiates a new chapter in the history of
mammals,'' says Del Presley, director of the Georgia Southern
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power donated the fossil to the museum after university
scientists helped extract the specimen from the construction site.
In observance of the naming of the whale, the skeleton will be on
public display Oct. 4-25 at the museum. After that, it will be
dismantled and its individual pieces stored for more scientific
study.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
