A5085 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-FARMERS02-COX     10-01 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FARMERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AG DEPARTMENT'S CIVIL RIGHTS DIVISION IN DISARRAY, INSPECTOR
FINDS
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Agriculture Department's civil rights division
is in disarray, has ``no decisive leadership'' and is making no
progress in clearing up a backlog of discrimination complaints, the
department's inspector general reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report provides fresh ammunition for black farmers, who have
long accused the department of ignoring their complaints that they
have been the victims of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really confirms everything I've said for the past year,''
said John Boyd, president of the National Black Farmers
Association. ``The system is so corrupt. ...The investigative
process isn't working.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent inspector general's report blasts the civil
rights division for a variety of offenses, including providing
false information to inspectors, a data base full of errors, and
allowing student interns to determine whether discrimination
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staff members with little training and less experience were
put to judging matters that carry serious legal and moral
implications,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said he was ``deeply
disappointed'' by the problems identified by the report. ``I am
ready to act on it today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said President Clinton has
seen the report, but was ``confident that Secretary Glickman is
addressing the issue vigorously and effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   The report says division employees did not provide accurate
information about the number of active and closed discrimination
cases, and that these inaccuracies were repeated at congressional
hearings and other public forums.
</P>
<P>
   It recommends establishing a complaint resolution task force
that is independent of the civil rights division to immediately
assume control of the backlog. It also recommends that the
department appoint an assistant secretary of civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said he would make a recommendation to Congress for the
new assistant secretary's post next year, but rejected the
recommendation for a completely independent task force.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, employees from within the civil rights office along
with other department employees will make up a task force, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said a task force from within the Agriculture Department is
not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the fox watching the henhouse,'' he said, adding
that he would prefer an advisory committee approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, black farmers and members of the
Congressional Black Caucus were angered by a Justice Department
decision to uphold a two-year statute of limitations on
discrimination complaints. The limit effectively bars hundreds of
complaining farmers from getting any cash compensation even if they
suffered discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the complaints are a result of a Reagan administration
decision in 1983 to dismantle the civil rights complaint office,
which resulted in thousands of complaints being ignored for years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the complaints, the Clinton administration faces
a $3 billion federal lawsuit filed by 600 of the farmers over the
long delays in settling cases. A trial date of Feb. 1 has been set
for the case but lawyers representing the farmers have said they
hope to settle before then.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
