<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-NAGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAGY HOPES FOR REPEAT PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The expectations _ at least in the taxicab that brought
him to the ballpark _ were low and the pressure on Charles Nagy was
about the same the last time the Indians righthander pitched in the
postseason at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy would like nothing better than to match the results of that
game when he takes on the Red Sox in Game 3 of their best-of-five
American League Division Series this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was Oct. 6, 1995, and the Indians had won the first two games
of the first-round series in Cleveland. Nagy, in his playoff debut,
faced Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the park, the cabbie was talking baseball and
offered an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was a lock,'' Nagy recalled her saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, she felt, were going to give the Red Sox one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like, `Great,''' Nagy said.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy pitched seven innings that night, giving up four hits and
one run, and when he left, it was 8-1, the Indians went on to
prevail, and it's still his only playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sweep. The Red Sox went three and out, and that was the game
that ran to 13 the postseason winless streak that lasted until
Tuesday afternoon in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It was no pressure, no sweat, Nagy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up, 2-0, and I was in a no-lose situation,'' he said.
``Even if we lost, they had to win three straight. Orel Hershiser
and Dennis Martinez won the first two games and took a lot of
pressure off me. I was able to go out relaxed and just throw the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He did that well. And that's what he generally does against the
Red Sox. Throws well. In short, he'd likely take a repeat of most
of his starts against the Red Sox as he tries to break a 1-1 series
tie.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the playoff win, Nagy is 6-1 with a 2.54 earned run
average in his career against Boston. In the regular season, he is
3-0 with a 1.29 ERA at Fenway. He threw eight shutout innings the
last time he pitched here in April in a duel with Pedro Martinez,
gave up a couple of runs in the ninth, and the Sox won it in the
10th.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy grew up a Yankees fan in Fairfield, Conn., and played at
the University of Connecticut _ which makes him a longtime rival of
Norwalk and Seton Hall's Mo Vaughn in Babe Ruth, Legion, college,
and now the majors _ and says he can't explain why he has such
success against the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   He claims he loved the Yankees, but that doesn't mean he hated
the Sox. There are no magic spells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, you really can't explain anything like that,'' Nagy
said. ``Why is it that one year you pitch well against a team and
the next year you can't even get out of the first inning? It's just
baseball and that's the way it goes. It's not that I feel more
comfortable pitching against them or pitching in Fenway.''
</P>
<P>
   Just looks that way.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a roller-coaster season for Nagy. He began 7-2,
then didn't win in eight starts (0-4, four no-decisions) through
June and well into July before breaking the streak with a 4-3 win
over the Sox in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   He was 5-1 in his last seven starts. But in his last one, as the
Indians battled for the home-field advantage _ and to avoid the
Yankees in the first round _ he was roughed up for seven hits and
four runs in just three innings against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he led the Indians in wins and innings pitched (210
1/3) for the fourth straight season but had a 5.22 ERA to go with a
15-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy said he had fallen into some bad pitching habits _ neither
he nor manager Mike Hargrove wanted to elaborate _ and was able to
straighten them out with the help of pitching coach Mark Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very good athlete and he has good stuff,'' Hargrove
said. ``He worked continuously to get out of those bad habits. It
took most of half a year to get it done. It takes a while to
identify the habits. Some are or were so subtle that we were down
to putting tapes side by side on a screen and comparing them frame
to frame to see the differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove is well aware of Nagy's success against the Sox, but he
doesn't have a reason for it, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I hope this holds true,'' he said. ``At least one more
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox _ and the area's cab drivers _ hope otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
