<SLUG> BC-BBA-SABERHAGEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN AT HOME IN THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rich Zawacki watched as Bret Saberhagen, twinkle in his
eye and smile on his face, enjoyed the moment before his Moment _
pitching once again in the playoffs Friday, his wife singing the
national anthem at Fenway Park, his arm once again strong. All
seemed as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never gets booed,'' Saberhagen quipped of his wife, Lynn.
``I always get booed. I'll probably be more nervous for her than
for myself. She started us well on Opening Day'' _ a Red Sox
comeback win over Seattle after Lynn Saberhagen sang that national
anthem. Just the right touch.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Saberhagen thanked those who had helped bring him back
from a useless right shoulder, from that agonizing playoff game
three years ago when he had taken the mound though ``my arm was
killing me'' and had given up six runs, five earned, in four
innings as Atlanta hammered him and the Colorado Rockies, the
Braves clinching the series with that game.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen thanked his wife, thanked Mets reliever John Franco,
thanked his doctors, and then thanked Zawacki, thanked them all for
not letting him give up.
</P>
<P>
   Zawacki, the Red Sox' physical therapist, took all this in and
thought back to one April evening in Anaheim. Not April of this
year when all seemed promising for Saberhagen and his comeback, but
back to April 1997 when nothing seemed sure about Saberhagen's
baseball future.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'd first met Bret, after the extensive surgery he'd had,
I knew it was going to be a long time before he came back,'' said
Zawacki. But that was not Saberhagen's impression, even 18 months
ago at the start of the 1997 season when no one expected him to
pitch that year.
</P>
<P>
   Except Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``His impression _ we're talking 1997 now _ was that he was
going to be one of the starting pitchers when we left spring
training,'' Zawacki recalled. ``That's 1997 ... and that obviously
was not going to happen. So what I had to do was keep Bret focused
that it was going to be a long, long road ahead for him.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the Red Sox opened the 1997 season in Anaheim.
Saberhagen did some throwing before one of those first games,
Zawacki watching every toss most carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I remember it was tough,'' Zawacki recalled of his
efforts to temper Saberhagen's expectations with reality. ``I knew
that he thought he should be pitching for us. But (pitching coach)
Joe Kerrigan and I had scheduled a side day for him on the mound in
the bullpen, and Bret wanted to show us that he was ready to pitch.
In his mind, he was thinking, `I've had the surgery. I'm feeling
pretty good. I can pitch.'''
</P>
<P>
   And?
</P>
<P>
   ``So he threw 20 pitches as hard as he could,'' said Zawacki.
``Then he walked off the mound, basically cussing me out because he
wasn't ready. Actually, that set him back about two weeks ...
because he couldn't pick up a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Zawacki's physical therapy was most important. But, as
Saberhagen said Thursday, there was also mental energizing needed.
Most of that came from himself, of course, but reminders also came
from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after those tosses and cusses in Anaheim, ``we sat
down again,'' Zawacki said. ``He had calmed down and we talked
about it. I told him, `You're not ready and you're not going to be
ready for a while. And if you expect to pitch now, you're never
going to be ready, so you might as well go home. You're just not
ready to pitch and it's going to take some time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, Zawacki recalled with a smile, ``eventually came
around'' to that line of thinking. ``He then did what he was
supposed to do _ we never had to remind him to do it _ and he just
hung in there. After that incident in Anaheim, he sort of calmed
down as to his expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   For the entire 1997 season, Saberhagen was around the Red Sox,
doing his work, building up his arm _ all for the big test that
would come in 1998. But there came a time in July 1997 ``when I
didn't think he was going to pitch at all,'' said Zawacki. ``Things
were not going well at all. He just wasn't ready to get up on the
mound and throw like he wanted to throw. I was having my doubts as
to whether it was going to work or not.''
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, though, ``he started complaining less about his
shoulder,'' said Zawacki. ``I'm not exactly sure what happened. We
changed a few things that he was doing, and then he was better.''
So much so that ``one day Joe Kerrigan came up to me _ I think it
was in Detroit _ and said he thought we could throw Bret in a
simulated game,'' said Zawacki. ``He wasn't ready to pitch last
year, but it was important for him to get on the mound at this
level and get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen went on a rehabilitation assignment, starting games
in Lowell, Trenton, Pawtucket, and eventually Boston _ 11 starts in
all. By then, Saberhagen had come to the realization, said Zawacki,
that ``he had to be patient, that he was in it for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Since no pitcher had undergone the type of surgery Saberhagen
had, the whole process ``was trial and error,'' said Zawacki.
``There were things I wanted him to do that he just couldn't do. We
eventually ended up with `what works' exercises that would work for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen started fast this season, but there was a lull after
the first month. The pitcher several times said his shoulder did
not feel totally right. ``Alarms didn't go off for me,'' said
Zawacki, ``but I think they went off for him. A couple of times, he
came in to me and said, `Man, I feel like my shoulder is going to
dislocate.' He had put so much effort into throwing those days that
it just didn't feel right for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Here Zawacki was soothing. ``I'd say, `Why don't you come in
tomorrow and see how you feel then?' And `Come in the next day and
see what it's like then.' In a situation like that, you have to get
him thinking positive, because if they start thinking negatively,
they start getting down on themselves. A guy can't pitch if he has
concern about his arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Through this entire two-year ordeal, Zawacki has kept as close
an eye on Saberhagen as anyone in the Boston locker room. Zawacki
eschews terms like ``medical miracle,'' saying that what he has
seen Saberhagen accomplish _ a 15-8 record and 3.96 ERA _ ``is an
extraordinary achievement. Every day he had to do something, and I
don't think many players would do what he did for himself. Most
players would have hung it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, said Zawacki, ``is as mentally a tough person as
I've seen. You can compare him to (Roger) Clemens for mental
toughness. Bret just made up his mind that he was going to come
back if it was at all possible.''
</P>
<P>
   There was admiration in Zawacki's voice as he said those words,
just as there was a twinkle in Saberhagen's eye as he talked of
once again pitching in the playoffs. Where he belongs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
