<HEADLINE>
HARVARD MEDICAL SCHOOL TOUTS AFFIRMATIVE ACTION ACHIEVMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were the first wave of black students in Harvard Medical
School's then-new affirmative action program, arriving at the
intimidating school and in racially torn Boston with doubts and
worries, but determined to make it through.
</P>
<P>
   And make it they did, the 15 blacks in the class that entered in
1970, despite academic struggles and discrimination including being
mistaken for janitors and orderlies when they first came on the
wards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some patients said they didn't want a student examining them
because he or she was black,'' recalls Dr. Alvin Poussaint, the
black psychiatrist who joined the medical school that year as an
associate dean to help smooth what many feared would be a rocky
introduction to diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The program was a success and went on to broaden its reach to
other underrepresented ethnic groups, notes Poussaint, one of the
speakers at a ceremony Friday celebrating 30 years of affirmative
action at the Harvard medical and dental schools. Together, the
schools have graduated more than 700 minority students who have
gone on to academic research and clinical practice.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Harvard Medical School had enrolled one or two
blacks a year previously, but the assassination of the Rev. Martin
Luther King in 1968 prompted a new commitment to expanding black
representation, said Dr. Leon Eisenberg, professor of social
medicine and one of nine faculty members who urged Harvard to start
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation was abysmal,'' said Eisenberg Thursday. ``Only
about 2 percent of medical students were black, and about 150 of
them went to Howard and Meharry (universities), the all-black
medical schools, and the other 50 were divided among the other 90
medical schools'' in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Following a faculty vote to expand the Harvard class to 140 and
to recruit 15 blacks (in addition to three for the dental school),
Harvard professors wrote to friends and acquaintances in search of
promising black undergraduates. By the next year, they had filled
the slots and launched an effort that has achieved a minority
representation of about 20 percent in recent classes, said
Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's observance, titled ``A Recommitment to Diversity,''
sends a message of support for affirmative action even as it is
being rolled back or attacked in several states, said medical
school dean Dr. Joseph B. Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I'm here, we will make every effort'' to recruit
and graduate minority students, Martin said in an interview, ``and
to see that they get sent off from here with the best likelihood of
being able to contribute and to serve some of their own people.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin added that he is concerned about ``the persistence of
inequality in the way we treat people of color'' in medical
institutions in Boston and elsewhere, despite medical school
courses designed to sensitize students to racial issues.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration is clouded by the threat of declining minority
applications to medical schools following the dismantling of
affirmative action programs in California and Texas: a measure
aimed at a similar reversal is on the ballot in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said that nationally minority medical school applications
dropped 11 percent from 1996 to 1997 after the two states ended
affirmative action and the actual number of minority students
entering medical school declined by 8.4 percent. ``And we're all
anxiously awaiting the numbers for 1998,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Poussaint, who is a clinical professor of psychiatry and faculty
associate dean for student affairs, said, ``the minority group
students get discouraged: they interpret (abolishing affirmative
action policies) as a message that they're not wanted any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, he said, has an advantage in recruiting minorities
because it attracts the top students, but officials worry that even
so, recruitment could become more difficult if the pool of minority
applicants shrinks significantly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
