<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONTIAC BUILDS EXCITEMENT WITH PAIR OF POLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Former Sprint Car champion Dave Blaney captured
his first career NASCAR Busch Grand National Series pole position
at Charlotte Motor Speedway yesterday, completing a sweep of the
No. 1 qualifying spots for the Pontiac Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Derrike Cope earned the first pole of his
NASCAR Winston Cup career with a hot lap at 181.690 mph during
qualifying for Sunday's UAW-GM Quality 500. Blaney posted his
breakthrough pole yesterday afternoon, touring the 1.5-mile trioval
at 177.247 mph during qualifying for tomorrow's All Pro Bumper to
Bumper 300.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts served as morale boosters for both drivers, and the
manufacturer that traditionally has taken a back seat to Ford and
Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're always surprised (by a front-row start),
because you have to put a perfect lap together,'' said Cope, driver
of the No. 30 Gumout Pontiac. ``When we were here testing, we
brought two new cars and tested very well, and there were a lot of
good cars here. (Points leader) Jeff Gordon was here (in a
Chevrolet), and I knew the laps we turned were very productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could come back and match that and be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Cope's time of 29.721 seconds was 0.077 seconds quicker than
that of No. 2 qualifier Mark Martin, who toured the track at
181.220 mph in the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus. The pole came in
Cope's 331st career start. His previous best start was second in
back-to-back races at Pocono International Raceway and Michigan
Speedway in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Cope, who suffered injuries to his ribs, sternum and shoulder
blade in a grinding crash at Atlanta Motor Speedway in early March,
is mired in 37th in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely been a year of uncharted territory for (team
owner) Chuck Rider and myself,'' said Cope, who gave Pontiac its
ninth Cup pole of the season, a modern-era record for the
manufacturer. ``Being hurt to the degree I was really limited us.''
</P>
<P>
   BGN rookie Blaney, meanwhile, continues to make the transition
from the open-wheeled, dirt-track World of Outlaws Sprinters to the
world of full-bodied, pavement NASCAR stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a brand new team we started up _ not just me, but the
whole team,'' said Blaney, who won the World of Outlaws
championship in 1995. ``It's taken a little while to get everybody
going, especially me and my confidence up. It's a huge weight off
me. We missed the race at Michigan and I was wondering if I was cut
out to do this. I've been a successful Sprint Car owner and driver
and know how difficult it is to keep morale up.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaney, driver of the No. 93 Amoco Pontiac owned by Bill Davis,
is the 22nd different pole winner this season _ a Busch series
record. The previous record of 21 was set in 1995. The pole came in
Blaney's 16th career BGN race.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kenseth, who trails BGN championship leader Dale Earnhardt
Jr. by 97 points, qualified No. 2 at 176.887 mph. Earnhardt, winner
of a series-high six races, will start fifth after a lap at 175.393
mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
