<HEADLINE>
OLDER AMERICANS HAVE BETTER LIFE, CENSUS DATA SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life is getting better for older Americans, judging from a drop
in the percentage of those who report difficulty in mundane but
all-important tasks such as reading a newspaper, climbing stairs,
and hefting a bag of groceries.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest gains, according to an analysis of Census Bureau
data published Friday, have occurred among the oldest individuals _
those over age 80. That bodes well for those approaching such
advanced years and for society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this means that more elderly should be able to work
and live independently,'' said Vicki A. Freedman of the Rand
Corporation, who did the study with her Rand colleague Linda G.
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The study is based on Census Bureau interviews in which about
13,000 individuals 50 and over were questioned about their
difficulty in doing four everyday tasks: reading a newspaper,
lifting and carrying a 10-pound weight, walking up a flight of
stairs without resting, and walking a quarter-mile, about three
city blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing results from 1984 and 1993 surveys, the researchers
found ``large improvements across all age groups _ from folks in
their 50s to the oldest old,'' Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion who said they had difficulty seeing newsprint
dropped during that period from 15.3 percent to 11.6 percent. Those
who reported difficulty lifting and carrying a 10-pound weight
declined from 23.5 percent to 18.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Difficulty climbing stairs without resting declined from 24.5
percent to 22 percent, while difficulty walking a quarter-mile
dropped from 25.8 percent to 22.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While these differences may appear modest, the researchers noted
that they occurred over a relatively short period of time.
Multiplied by the number of older Americans _ and projected forward
in time _ such differences are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The largest absolute declines in disability occurred among the
oldest old. For instance, 52 percent of those over 80 reported
difficulty lifting a 10-pound weight in 1984, but that declined to
41 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic minorities, less well-educated Americans, and those
without liquid financial assets had substantially higher disability
rates. But even these less-advantaged groups experienced declines
in disability during the nine-year period.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in disability does not mean that the absolute number
of disabled older Americans will shrink. In fact, because the 78
million baby boomers are just entering their 50s, the number of
disabled elders is sure to rise. But the recent studies suggest it
won't rise as steeply as feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you assumed that disability remains constant the number of
older disabled people would triple by 2020,'' Freedman said. ``If
disability continues to decline at about 1 percent per year...the
number of disabled people will `only' double. Compared to tripling,
that's good news, but we still will have a lot more disabled people
than we have today.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysis, which appears in this month's American Journal of
Public Health, is not the first to suggest that disability rates
are declining among older Americans. However, the new study may
help dispel skepticism about earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study provides important new evidence of the strength of
the trend and moves us toward understanding what is behind it,''
said Richard M. Suzman, associate director for behavioral and
social research at the National Institute on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Stallard of Duke University, who coauthored a widely
discussed 1987 report on declining disability among elders, said
the Rand study ``supports our analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These reports tell us that the future is improving,'' Stallard
said. ``They tell us we're not going to get a significant increase
in the period of disability'' as the US population ages _ something
many social planners had assumed.
</P>
<P>
   The implications touch on a wide range of issues, from the
fiscal soundness of Medicare and the cost of long-term care
insurance to cultural attitudes and expectations about the last
third of the lifespan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
