<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ELECT-ART-2NDT     10-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ELECT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RIO DE JANEIRO, BRAZIL: the miserable.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tambara stood in an aisle at Wal-Mart outside Sao Paulo, unable
to afford a $16 4-foot aluminum ladder. ``I need the ladder, but
I'll have to find a solution, maybe make one out of wood, or
improvise in some other way,'' he said as he and his wife, Maria
Luisa Takada, left empty-handed. ``If I buy this, I won't have
money for something else that I need.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of the Real Plan four years ago, named for the new
currency, pushed millions of Brazilians into the consumer economy.
In its first two years the sales of appliances, electronics and
cars exploded. It was not just that salaries held their value from
one month to the next, but also that a low inflation rate, about 3
percent this year, meant ready access to credit for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   After he had lived with 3,000-percent-a-year inflation, 120
percent did not seem usurious at first, said Cesar Fraga, 36, an
advertising executive who was having his shoes shined on the
Avenida Getulia Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then people realized their salaries were staying the same,''
Fraga said. There would be no more adjustments for inflation. Now,
Fraga said, he buys only with cash.
</P>
<P>
   An out-of-work receptionist in Sao Paulo, Augusta Pettinari,
said she felt as if she had lost her identity when her credit went
bad. Just before her wedding in April she wrote a check to a
pharmacy for lipstick, face powder and shampoo, and charged
groceries to her credit card. Then she lost her job and could not
pay. Her husband lost his job. Her name was blacklisted, and
alienation set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an economic life,'' Ms. Pettinari, 28, said. ``I
don't have a name. I feel like I'm not Brazilian anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On some days, she said, when every door she knocks on for work
knocks back with another rejection, she goes home feeling
everything about her is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been honest,'' Ms. Pettinari said. She looked off
in the distance, tears forming in the corners of her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because I can't pay a few checks that I stop being
honest,'' she said. ``It's what my mother always taught us: `Be
poor, but honest.'''
</P>
<P>
   Da Silva, luckless in his search for work, labors to maintain a
name that is creditworthy, with each month bringing an unrelenting
march of due dates on bills. He and his wife juggle payments and
excuses, developing an intricate knowledge of where each creditor's
truly final limit lies.
</P>
<P>
   The couple smartly avoided interest from the start by joining a
Brazilian-style buying club, a peculiarly Brazilian invention. The
clubs operate on diligence and luck, with members contributing to a
fund for a fixed period and drawing lots to determine who buys
when.
</P>
<P>
   The da Silvas are paying a car consortium $220 a month for five
years, with their chance to buy coming by 2002 at the latest. That
is also how long they would have to wait to receive back the cash
that they have already paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I going to do with the money in 2002?'' he asked. ``I
need it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, with unemployment in Sao Paulo, the industrial
heartland, running at 19 percent before the recent interest
increases, the qualifications for even menial work are growing more
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Though discrimination because of age is against the law, all the
jobs advertised on the street where da Silva and Ms. Pettinari
looked for work gave age ranges. For work as a messenger or a
cleaner of houses and offices, employers now require some high
school education, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say people who are 40 years old are discriminated against
in the market,'' da Silva, 33, said. ``But in my case it doesn't
look like I'll have to wait until 40 to be washed up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
