<HEADLINE>
US STOCK FUNDS LOST 15% IN THIRD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mutual funds got clobbered in the third quarter, the
worst for investors in eight years and a sign that the party, at
least for now, is over.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of funds invested in US stocks lost 15 percent in
the three months just ended, erasing this year's gains for many
investors, according to early data Thursday from Lipper Analytical
Services, the fund tracking firm. Not only was it just about
impossible to make any money in a stock fund in the last quarter _
many of the losses were in hefty double digits. Among broad,
diversified stock funds, the low-cost, unmanaged variety that
tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index offered the least pain,
declining only 10 percent. By contrast, small-capitalization funds,
which buy stocks in up-and-coming companies, and mid-cap funds lost
twice that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Growth funds, which generally hold big, blue-chip names with
prospects of growing earnings, declined 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There have been bumps in the Great Bull Market of this decade;
many stock funds stood still in the second quarter of 1998. But not
since the third quarter of 1990, when the US stock market was in a
recession, have stock funds _ and Wall Street, on whose fortunes
most mutual funds depend _ performed so badly.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are unpleasant for fund shareholders, who had seen
double-digit gains in recent years. Now market watchers are in
fierce debate over how soon Wall Street might recover _ and whether
stock fund investors will shift their attention to bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're perfectly willing to call this the bear market of
1998,'' said Al Kugel, senior investment trategist at Stein Roe &AMP;
Farnham's mutual fund division in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The brutal quarter wipes out gains so far this year for most
investors, except for those holding S&AMP;P 500 index funds, which are
up 5.6 percent for the year through September. By contrast, growth
funds, whose composition may not mirror that of the S&AMP;P 500, have
lost 0.25 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the more a portfolio manager scoured the globe for
promising bets last quarter, the more he stood to get burned. Funds
invested in Latin American stocks lost 29.4 percent, those in
individual European markets declined 17.3 percent, and emerging
markets funds fell 23.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Funds that buy Asian stocks provided a cushion, but still lost
anywhere from 6.7 to 9.4 percent. Global funds, which buy stocks in
many countries, rather than one in particular, were down 14.8
percent. Among international stock funds, only those devoted
exclusively to European shares are up for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Funds invested in gold-mining stocks, considered a defense in
times of turmoil, rose 4.3 percent in the third quarter, which
covers July through September. But they are still down 5.1 percent
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors holding US long-term Treasury paper also eked out some
gains last quarter. But that 1.3 percent rise becomes negative once
fund management expenses are factored in. Still, long-term bond
funds are up 5 percent so far this year, and have outperformed the
vast majority of stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sector equity funds, which focus on individual industries, also
had their share of third-quarter woes. The worst hit were financial
services funds (down 19 percent) and natural resource funds (down
16.1 percent). Funds invested in utilities stocks offered one of
the best buffers around, l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
