<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-TOOB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET TOOB MAKER SAYS MICROSOFT MEDIA PLAYER A THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tiny company in Salem, Mass. says that a piece of free
software from giant Microsoft Corp. poses a major threat to its &UR;  &LR; 
business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Executives of Digital Bitcasting Corp. say their company is
put at an unfair disadvantage because its Net Toob software is
automatically deactivated by Microsoft's popular Windows Media
Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes in and says `OK, I'm now in charge of
everything,''' Digital Bitcasting president Peter Dougherty said of
the Microsoft program.
</P>
<P>
   Net Toob is a $20 program that allows users to look at movie and
TV clips over the Internet. Dougherty said that about 8 million
people use Net Toob to view videos created using a format called
MPEG.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft's Windows Media Player runs MPEG and many
other types of Internet audio and video. Its versatility and that
it's free have combined to make the Microsoft product quite
popular.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's habit of giving away software is controversial.
The firm challenged rival Internet browser maker Netscape
Communications Corp. by offering a free browser to compete with
Netscape's product, which cost $29 to $79. Netscape was forced to
start giving away its browser as well, but the company still has
continued to lose ground to Microsoft. A pending federal antitrust
case against Microsoft cites the company's browser giveaway as
unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty doesn't mind Microsoft's media player giveaway. He's
annoyed because Media Player, when it is installed, automatically
disconnects Net Toob.
</P>
<P>
   Net Toob can be set to run automatically as a user is browsing
on the Internet. The user clicks on a link to an MPEG video, and
Net Toob begins to show the images.
</P>
<P>
   Windows Media Player does the same thing, but with a difference.
When a user installs the Microsoft program, it disconnects Net Toob
from the browser, without telling the user. Now when this user
clicks an MPEG video, the Microsoft program starts up instead of
Net Toob. To go back to using Net Toob, the user must reinstall the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty says this is unfair. He thinks Microsoft should offer
an option that would install the free media player without
disconnecting Net Toob.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Schare, Microsoft's lead product manager for Windows
media technologies, described the dispute as ``a transparent
attempt by some of our our opponents...to create a controversy
where none exists.'' Schare said that Microsoft has e-mail messages
from Digital Bitcasting stating that the firm has no complaint
against Microsoft &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; a claim that Dougherty disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Schare also said that Microsoft might add more flexible
installation options to future versions of the media player, to
prevent the deactivation of competing programs. But he said the
current design was intended to make installing the program easier
for consumers, not to harm rival firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
