</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PCB-CLEANUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA OK'S NEW BEDFORD DREDGING AIMED AT PCB POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years after naming PCB-contaminated New Bedford Harbor a
Superfund site, the US Environmental Protection Agency finally
decided Thursday how to clean it up: a huge dredging project that
will lock up PCB-tainted muck in shorefront mounds.
</P>
<P>
   The work, not expected to be completed until 2006 at the
soonest, will involve dredging the equivalent of over 25,000
truckloads of dirt from 170 acres of the harbor floor, then burying
it in four carefully monitored ``confined disposal facilities'' on
the shorefront.
</P>
<P>
   The project could still be snarled by expected battles over the
design of the four disposal mounds, which EPA hopes to turn into
parks, shipping facilities and warehouse lots. The EPA has on hand
barely half the $120 million the project requires.
</P>
<P>
   Coming coincidentally a week after EPA agreed to a $150
million-plus deal with General Electric to clean up its PCB mess in
Berkshire County's Housatonic River, Thursday's settlement marks
the first glimmer of hope in years for cleaning up what is widely
deemed the state's dirtiest harbor. Since 1977, PCB contamination
has led to a ban on eating fish from the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Bedford Harbor is on the verge of a renaissance as both a
working waterfront and tourism destination,'' Mayor Frederick M.
Kalisz Jr. said, adding that the decision will ``allow this process
to move along and the revitalization to accelerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Simmons of Hands Across the River, a local environmental
group, called the decision ``the beginning of the end of our
PCB-contaminated river and harbor'' and promised his group would
bring ``an open mind'' to negotiating design of the mounds.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA promised to coordinate the dredging of 450,000 cubic
yards of PCB-contaminated muck with efforts to deepen navigational
channels in New Bedford Harbor to bring more shipping business to
the economically struggling city.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning about eight years ago, five New Bedford manufacturers
who spewed polychlorinated biphenyl wastes into the Acushnet River
and New Bedford Harbor for decades paid $70 million to settle
Superfund lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   PCBs, used in insulating oils for electrical transformers and
other products for several decades before Congress banned them in
1977, cause cancer in animals and are deemed by EPA a probable
human carcinogen.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA will use the $70 million to start dredging in the spring
of 2001. After that New Bedford will have to compete with hundreds
of other Superfund sites for EPA cleanup funding for the other $50
million or more required to finish the cleanup _ which could delay
completion past the 2006 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the EPA dredged up 15,000 cubic yards of
so-called hotspots from five acres within the harbor. Some had the
highest concentrations of PCBs ever found in the world. It has
stored them in a 300,000-gallon fenced-in pool at the end of Sawyer
Street near many homes and a playground, and plans to pump out and
treat the water and ship the rest to an out-of-state landfill.
</P>
<P>
   The plans call for four containment mounds totaling 44 acres
that would each rise about eight feet above the high-water mark.
Each would be covered with clean fill and monitored to ensure
pollution does not trickle out.
</P>
<P>
   Once the worst 170 acres of contamination are removed by Army
Corps of Engineers contractors, said David Dickerson, the EPA
project manager, questions will remain about what if anything to do
with thousands of acres of low-level contamination in the outer
harbor south of the hurricane barrier. Dickerson said the $120
million project will solve ``the lion's share'' of harbor pollution
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to remedy the harbor mess have been stalled for years
because of initial concerns dredging could just make the problem
worse, and then by a firestorm of local opposition on
``environmental racism'' grounds to plans to incinerate the hotspot
muck in a low-income Portuguese-American neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
