<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-KIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT-OF-KIN REQUEST GIVES SOME PASSENGERS A SHIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Manuel Feldman, 75, adjusted his lucky hat and handed
his airplane ticket to Alice Brew at &UR;  &LR; the British Airways counter
at Logan International Airport. Brew examined Feldman's blue
American passport, then handed him a ``contact information'' card.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman eyed the carefully-worded card, which asked for the full
name of a ``contact person not on the flight,'' and cracked a
knowing grin. ``Que sera sera,'' he said, shrugging before he wrote
the name of his attorney in the blank. ``He handles my estate.
He'll know who to call.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman had just experienced US Transportation Department
regulation number 14 CFR 243.13, which went into effect Thursday
and requires American passengers on international flights to do the
disconcerting: provide the name of someone who can be contacted in
case their plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation was established because of difficulties finding
relatives of victims in recent airplane disasters, including
SwissAir Flight 111 that crashed off the Nova Scotia coast Sept.
2., killing 229. The rule is limited to international flights,
where the federal government has a legal duty to notify friends or
family of crash victims.
</P>
<P>
   When a plane crashes in the United States, the airline or
coroner is responsible for bringing the bad news to loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   While some passengers at Logan took comfort in the new
regulation _ like Cindy Friesen, 29, who was heading to Canada to
spend that nation's Thanksgiving with family _ many others were
downright disturbed by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they wait until you're at the counter to do this?''
asked Mary Baxter, an Irish national who was not required to fill
out such a form but who felt sorry for those on her flight who did.
``Why don't they do it when you call to make your reservation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me the willies,'' said Nancy Sears, a senior citizen
from New Hampshire heading to Austria with a group of friends.
``You don't like to think about the fact that your plane might ...
ditch, or whatever,'' she said, placing a hand over her heart.
``It's unnerving enough just to get on the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Salzman, 58 and heading to France, made light of the
situation. ``I already told my next of kin where the jewelry is,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Salzman, who wears a necklace made of colorful metal
airplanes every time she flies, said she was superstitious, and the
regulation forced her think about something she'd rather not
consider.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hodges, 35, said he hoped the new regulation was
voluntary. ``There aren't enough freedoms in America anymore,'' he
said, opening his eyes wide with rage. ``The government interferes
in everything. Now they're making me sign this because of my
mother's interests, not my own. When will it end?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many passengers said they were unfazed by the new
request, and others thought it was a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great idea,'' said Belle Liberman, one of Sears's pals
headed to Austria. ``They should have done it a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears listened to her friend, thought for moment, then nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you're right,'' she said. ``Still, it may be a good
idea, but psychologically, I don't care for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
