A5133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-PLUNGE-BOS &LR;      10-01 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-PLUNGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET TAKES SECOND 200-POINT-PLUS BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, the United States stock market
tumbled more than 200 points amid growing concern that the global
economic turmoil will spread to the US by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this week's Federal Reserve cut in short-term interest
rates, investors have not &UR;  &LR; shaken off fears that economic problems
in Asia, Russia and Latin America will drag down the US economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are simply very unsettled,'' said Larry Horwitz,
managing director of Primark Decision Economics in Boston. ``We're
in totally uncharted waters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average Thursday fell 210 points, or
2.7 percent, to 7632.53. It came within 100 points of its low for
the year, set Aug. 31, when it tumbled 512 points in a day. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index Thursday fell 30.62, or 3 percent, to
986.39. The technology-laden Nasdaq tumbled 81.51, or 4.8 percent,
to 1612.33.
</P>
<P>
   Since the market hit its peak on July 17, the Dow is off 18.3
percent, the S&AMP;P 500 is off 16.9 percent, and the Nasdaq is off
19.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While stocks were falling around the world Thursday, bond prices
were surging as investors raced to find safer havens for their
money. The yield on 30-year US Treasury bonds, which on Wednesday
was pushed below 5 percent for the first time in three decades,
sank 10 more basis points Thursday to 4.88 percent. Bond yields
move inversely to bond prices. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This week's drop in stock prices was triggered by a series of
negative reports from around the world, which economists said add
up to a pervasive sense of gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a key economic survey in Japan showed that business
leaders are more pessimistic than they have been in four years. US
manufacturing activity declined for the fourth month in a row, due
largely to slowing exports. And sales of new and existing homes
were down for the second month in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors are also worried about the potential
exposure of banks, investment firms and securities companies that
loaned money to high-risk hedge funds, following last week's
near-collapse of Long-Term Capital Management, a giant hedge fund
that needed a $3.6 billion bailout by Wall Street's major banks to
stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're putting a mosaic together, with all these
pieces,'' said Robert MacIntosh, vice president and portfolio
manager for Eaton Vance Management in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And the picture that's emerging, he said, is not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market is expecting a higher chance of recession
next year than might have been the case a month ago,'' said
MacIntosh. Although he still believes the chances of a US recession
are ``much less than 50-50,'' investor behavior during the past
week suggests the fear is real, MacIntosh said.
</P>
<P>
   David Wyss, chief economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in
Lexington, agreed that the wave of bad economic news is having a
snowball effect on US markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way recessions happen. Confidence is everything. At
some point, if confidence gets shaken, then people stop spending
money, investors stop investing and businesses stop spending on
capital improvements. Pretty soon,'' he said, ``your shiny boom
turns into a recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer and Internet companies, along with financial services
firms, were among the worst-hit stocks Thursday. Retail stocks also
fell, however, as fears of a US recession mount.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp., the giant software company, fell 6 to 104 1/16
and IBM Corp. lost 3 1/4 to 125 1/4. Cisco Systems Inc., the leader
in computer networking equipment, fell 4 9/16 to 57 1/4. Even Dell
Computer Corp., a darling of Wall Street, fell 4 3/16 to 61 9/16.
More than 42 million Dell shares were traded, making it the most
active US stock.
</P>
<P>
   Among bank stocks, American Express Co. fell 4 1/8 to 73 1/2,
Citicorp fell 4 3/4 to 88 1/4 and J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. lost 3 5/8 to
81. Among local issues, Bank Boston fell 1 3/8 to 31 5/8 and Fleet
dropped 2 5/8, to 70 13/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
