<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE SOFTWARE FIRMS CONTINUE TO GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' software industry continues to grow,
according to a new survey, with 215 more companies and nearly 9,000
more employees than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The data, due to be released today by the Massachusetts Software
Council, shows there are 2,751 software and interactive companies
in the state, an increase of 8.5 percent from 1997 and three times
as many as in 1989, when the software council first began keeping
the tally.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 402 are Internet-related companies, 43 percent more
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, most of the companies that make up the state's
software industry are young and relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 percent of the software companies were established
since 1990, while more than half of the Internet companies were
formed in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   About 73 percent of the software companies have 25 or fewer
employees, and 80 percent of the interactive companies have fewer
than 25 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the state's software industry had 131,508 employees,
up 7 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of companies in both categories had revenues
of under $5 million, but together, the state's software and
interactive industry generated $9.2 billion in revenues, an
increase of 15 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are considered conservative, a council spokeswoman
noted, because about 1,100 of the 2,751 companies surveyed did not
provide revenue information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these companies are below the radar screens of the
people who track the industry,'' said council president Joyce
Plotkin, ``but Massachusetts' strength has always been with small
companies. That's where the growth has always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin said, ``We continue to be a center for software,
business innovationm, and company creation. The growth has just
been phenomenal. There's no shortage of ideas and products and
companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
