<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON TINKERS WITH RACE-DAY SETUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Winston Cup points leader Jeff Gordon will start
26th, the spot he earned during first-round qualifying Wednesday
night, in Sunday's UAW-GM Quality 500 at Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Because the top 25 positions were locked in during that session,
26th was as good as it was going to get for Gordon this weekend, so
he elected not to requalify yesterday afternoon. But Gordon's hot
lap at 178.974 mph in the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevy
ended a streak of 20 consecutive top-10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed it a little bit in qualifying,'' said Gordon, who
has a 199-point lead over Mark Martin with six events remaining.
``We're trying a different combination here, hoping it's going to
be a little bit better in the race than what we've been in the
past. It's just a different car, different body, different
front-end suspension on it than what we normally run here.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we normally run here is good enough to sit on the pole or
something near the pole, but it's not good enough to win during the
day. We're definitely trying a different combination.'' &QL; 
IRL DATE SWITCH EXPECTED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Motor Speedway officials are expected to officially
announce movement of the track's Pep Boys Indy Racing League event
from late July to Saturday night, May 1, during a news conference
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL has run under the lights at CMS the past two summers.
But the switch to May will allow IRL teams to test their
superspeedway setups before the 83rd Indianapolis 500 on May 30.
The May 1 date makes sense because Mother's Day _ traditionally an
off-day from racing _ falls on May 9 next year. And CMS will play
host to NASCAR's The Winston all-star race on May 22 and the
Coca-Cola 600 on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the IRL awarded Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, a
sister facility to CMS, the 1999 season ender on Oct. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
