<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court rules against census sampling
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal court has sided with an Atlanta-based
public interest law firm in a challenge to the Clinton
administration's plan to use statistical sampling methods in the
2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   A special three-judge panel in the U.S. District Court in
Alexandria, Va., ruled unanimously Thursday that such sampling is
illegal. It is the second federal court to issue such a ruling in
as many months.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is proposing to use sampling to get a more
accurate count of minorities and other groups that have been
historically undercounted in the decennial census.
</P>
<P>
   The matter is headed to the U.S. Supreme Court, which will hear
arguments Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling came in a lawsuit filed by the conservative
Southeastern Legal Foundation. Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), the
foundation's former director, is one of the plaintiffs in the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The first ruling came in a suit filed by Speaker Newt Gingrich
and the House of Representatives, as part of a compromise last year
with President Clinton to seek a speedy court resolution of the
controversy. A three-judge panel in Washington, D.C., then ruled
unanimously against sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans generally oppose sampling, fearing that it would add
people in traditionally Democratic areas. Sampling's effect would
probably be the greatest in the reapportionment of congressional,
state legislative and municipal electoral districts that will occur
in state legislatures around the country in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dangerous and short-sighted political attack on our
republic, which has now been outlawed twice by the federal courts,
means that President Clinton...must stop spending public money on
illegal sampling, period,'' said Matthew Glavin, the foundation's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
