<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUGH CALL FOR NFL'S WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one-game suspension of Detroit Lion safety Mark Carrier for
his frightening helmet-to-helmet hit Monday night against Tampa
Bay's Brice Hunter was not an easy decision for the NFL's top cop,
Gene Washington.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Washington, the one-time Stanford quarterback who went
on to become a Pro Bowl receiver with the San Francisco 49ers, is a
1965 Poly High graduate who long has known Carrier, a 1987 Poly
High graduate who played at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've run into Mark several times over the years at games and
different functions,'' said Washington Thursday from his NFL office
in New York. ``He's a good guy, and I like him a lot. That made it
doubly tough for me to do what I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What Gene Washington has to do in his duties as the NFL's
director of football operations is to mete out punishment to
players he thinks have delivered illegal hits.
</P>
<P>
   And after watching film of Carrier's violent collision with
Hunter, Washington felt Carrier deserved to be sent to the
sidelines for one game. It's the first time a player has been
suspended in the NFL since 1992 when Green Bay's LeRoy Butler was
forced to sit for throwing a forearm to the head of Detroit
quarterback Andre Ware.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my position, you have to put all personal considerations
aside and just consider the hard evidence,'' said Washington.
``Mark was coming in like a torpedo with his helmet against Hunter,
and it was a clear violation. You just have to put blinders on when
making these decisions, or it'll come back to bite you.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mark's case, we felt the frequency in which he was leading
with his helmet had got out of hand. There was a game last year
against Green Bay in which three of his hits came under review. He
just received a fine in that game, but four hits within a 12-month
period that are considered dangerous is simply too many. I felt the
punishment was appropriate under the circumstances. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The word from a Very Reliable Source With Strong Golfing Ties is
the world's richest man, Bill Gates, recently was turned down in
his bid to become a member of the Augusta National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the notoriously stuffy members of this notoriously
stuffy organization that stages the Masters weren't impressed when
Gates listed his handicap at a mere 24.
</P>
<P>
   As I've always said, money can't buy everything, including
birdies on a golf course or membership into the world's most
arrogant country club. ..
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire spent two hours the other day at The Abbey in Seal
Beach, a restaurant he made nationally famous when he kept wearing
its baseball hat at his post-game press conferences. He graciously
kibitzed with customers and signed autographs.
</P>
<P>
   He flew to Southern California Sunday evening after striking his
epic 70th home run earlier in the day in St. Louis, and was picked
up at the airport by his pal, Rob Burdick, the famed bartender who
so fortuitously gave him The Abbey hat that has resulted in a
financial windfall for the new establishment.
</P>
<P>
   I hear sales of The Abbey hats have exceeded $400,000. ...
</P>
<P>
   If any regular-season NBA games are canceled because of the
labor dispute, I hear there are 13 hard-line owners who would want
to close down the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt that will happen, but I also never thought I'd see the
World Series canceled, either, as it was in the sport's dark days
of 1994. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated indeed got it right in the headline on the
cover of its current issue. This indeed has been the greatest
season in the history of baseball, and none of us will see even the
faintest likes of it again in our lifetimes. If someone told me
before this magical season that McGwire would hit 70 HRs, Sammy
Sosa would hit 66, the New York Yankees would win 114 games, and
Kerry Wood would strike out 20 batters, I would have told the
person he'd have a better chance of seeing Cal Ripken voluntarily
sit out a game, which Ripken finally chose to do in this memorable
season. ...
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that every single guy I know who has a cell phone and
beeper attached to his trousers is in debt and never gets a date?
</P>
<P>
   I hear the Dodger coaches including veterans ones like Manny
Mota and Joey Amalfitano were told of their dismissals over the
phone from Kevin Malone instead of face-to-face. A real class move
by the new Dodger general manager. ...
</P>
<P>
   I have the overwhelming feeling that it'll be years before the
Dodgers become a serious National League pennant contender again. I
don't know Kevin Malone from Karl Malone, but I do know the
Fox-owned Dodgers sanctioned the trading of Mike Piazza, the best
hitter in the team's Los Angeles history. How many more similarly
stumblebum decisions will be dispensed by the new Dodger caretakers
in the future?. ...
</P>
<P>
   If I were the GM of the San Diego Padres, I'd have fired the
Padres' manager, Bruce Bochy, on the spot the other day for
removing Kevin Brown after he had struck out 16 Houston Astros and
yielded only two hits in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most dominant playoff performance I've ever
witnessed, yet Bochy brought in his extraordinary reliever, Trevor
Hoffman, in the ninth to finish up for Brown, who wasn't tired and
had been toying with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman almost blew the game the Padres escaped with a 2-1 win
and Brown was seen blowing his top in the San Diego dugout, which
was quite understandable.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres might go on to the World Series, but I have to stick
Bruce Bochy on my Gene Mauch-Bobby Cox-Tony LaRussa list of lousy
managers that makes moves that defy sound reasoning. ...
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Malone sounds too ominously to me like a typically
unctuous, slick-schmoozing, self-absorbed, egotistical
administrative tyrant when he says he feels compelled to make
changes for changes' sake.
</P>
<P>
   How ghastly!
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if I understand it right in his rationale for
detaching Glenn Hoffman, Malone didn't feel comfortable with
Hoffman as the Dodger manager because he didn't hire him. If Kevin
Malone is such a genius, then why weren't his former employers, the
Baltimore Orioles, in the World Series the past few years?
</P>
<P>
   I've always found corporate types who come into a new positions
and decide to clean house at the expense of qualified people to be
insecure buffoons who inevitably fail and wind up getting fired
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What did Glenn Hoffman do to deserve getting demoted? The guy
had a 47-41 record during his tenure with a mediocre Dodger team
and earned at least a shot to come back for another season.
</P>
<P>
   His only failing, evidently, is that he wasn't hired by Hoffman,
a grievous offense if there ever was one.
</P>
<P>
   Oh please! Just because Fox finds itself in a desperate
situation with a team devastated by its own inane decision to get
rid of Mike Piazza and decides to hand total control over to
Malone, that doesn't mean Malone has to disrupt everyone's life in
the Dodger organization with his micro-managing style. Remember,
Malone, that hoariest of axioms what goes around comes around. ...
</P>
<P>
   I find Randy Hill's wickedly light-hearted NFL comments in our
Monday Snap page far more entertaining than the games themselves.
...
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more irritating than calling AT&AMP;T long
distance information, and then having to wait and listen to a taped
spiel about whether you want the number you're seeking dialed
automatically for an extra 50 cents?. ...
</P>
<P>
   If the Long Beach State women volleyballers beat UC Santa
Barbara tonight at the Event Center in Santa Barbara, Brian
Gimmillaro thinks the second-ranked 49ers should assume the top
spot in the coaches poll instead of Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're fortunate enough to beat Santa Barbara, that would
give us seven wins over teams that have been nationally ranked,''
says the 49ers' coach. ``Penn State has played one nationally
ranked team.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Brian Gimmillaro's logic is faultless. ...
</P>
<P>
   I echo Bud Selig's sentiments. I wish this baseball season would
go last into infinity. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
