<HEADER>
A5151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TV-COX     10-01 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cable networks reshape journalistic landscape
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Congress releases more files from the Clinton-Lewinsky grand
jury probe today as expected, TV will be there to cover it.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours, the once-secret documents will be everywhere at
once: picked over by reporters and massaged by pundits, subjected
to flash polls, dissected on nightly newscasts and still later,
debated by newsmakers and noisemakers on Sunday morning talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   John Moody, vice president of news for Fox News Channel says the
unblinking coverage of the Clinton crisis is just what viewers want
_ and need.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there were only three networks, the attitude was `eat
your spinach,''' Moody says. ``Now we're letting people have their
cake and eat it. They can eat as much as they want, when they want
to.''
</P>
<P>
   But how much is too much?
</P>
<P>
   Some media observers wonder if TV _ especially all news,
all-the-time, cable networks _ are committing journalistic overkill
on the White House scandal and other splashy stories that have
gotten similar ``wall-to-wall'' treatment in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real sense of chaos here,'' says Robert Thompson,
who runs the Center for the Study of Popular Television at Syracuse
University in upstate New York. ``The need to fill all this air
time has resulted in drive-by opinion delivery. Having 24-hour news
channels has taken the whole idea of social thought and turned it
into a spectator sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined viewership of news-heavy cable networks _ including
CNN, MSNBC, CNBC and Fox News Channel _ remains just a fraction of
their broadcast cousins, but they are reshaping the journalistic
landscape once dominated by ABC, CBS, and NBC, which once doled out
information in neatly packaged newscasts twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, MSNBC, Fox News, and CNBC are not only changing how
Americans get their news, but what kind of news they get and how
much.
</P>
<P>
   From Hurricane Georges to the White House sex scandal and from
the O.J. Simpson murder trial to the death of Princess Di, the
cable networks are giving viewers more choices. Even critics
concede that's a plus, but they're concerned the abundance of
coverage tends to exaggerate the importance of certain stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cable networks help push stories that would have been less
of a story if we still only had three networks,'' says Rich Noyes,
political studies director for the Center for Media and Public
Affair in Washington. ``The problem with cable is no matter what
the story is, they make it a huge deal even if it's just a big
deal. The story is hyped to get viewers, but sometimes the story
isn't that exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they must fill a gaping 24-hour news hole every day,
Noyes says, cable networks are often recycling and repackaging the
same story to make it seem fresh to viewers just tuning in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll keep rewording the headlines and every single movement
in the story is exaggerated as a huge trend even if the story
hasn't moved that much,'' Noyes says. ``Through repetition, they
create a false sense of momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sesno, CNN vice president and Washington bureau chief,
defends the network's Clinton coverage as intelligent, fair and
accurate. Still, he admits feeling pangs of ``scandal fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an echo effect that makes it seem to the
viewer that it's just too much,'' Sesno says. ``I don't think it's
particular to any one network, but now there are lots of networks,
and lots of talk shows and lots of Internet coverage, and at some
point people just say, `Go away and get a life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in
Journalism in Washington, says the economic demands of running a
24-hour network creates a dizzying blur of facts, ideas and images.
For viewers, it creates a warped reality where distinguishing
straightforward reporting from opinions is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cable networks have really gotten into the business of
commenting on the news, which is cheaper to do,'' Rosenstiel says.
``All you need is a booker, a host and some guests and you have a
half-hour of programming. It's not only cheaper (than a half-hour
newscast), it's easier to do intellectually.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody at Fox News disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rule at Fox that correspondents can't be on the air
at the same time as our spinmeisters,'' he says. ``The only thing
driving us is that Monica Lewinsky is the biggest story to hit
Washington since Watergate. I don't think we are letting anything
push this story beyond what we think is responsible journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says TV's current information overload may have a
numbing effect on viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What might happen is that the variety and loudness and
constancy of the voices might create so much babble that they just
cancel each other out,'' he says. ``It may get so noisy people just
throw up their arms. It's like when you walk into a bar and you're
overwhelmed by the smoke. But five minutes later, you can't smell
anything anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
