<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTION FIRM GROWS IN PHOENIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GONDERINGER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A major credit management company expects to hire
2,000 workers in the next few years as it expands its operation in
the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Midland Credit Management quietly set up shop in east Phoenix
earlier this year and already has 250 employees at its call center
near Broadway Road and 44th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutchinson, Kans.-based company hopes to double that by
December, and have 1,000 employees by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Once the present 51,000 square-foot office is filled, the
company will look for a second center in the far east or west
Phoenix area that would employ another 1,000 people, said Les
Gilbert, a local career opportunity manager with MCM.
</P>
<P>
   If the two offices are filled, the company would also
considering opening a satellite operation of about 200 workers in
Flagstaff, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning to grow dramatically,'' said Frank Chandler,
Midland's president. ``Arizona is where we want to focus that
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand employees would make Midland one of the largest
back office operations in the Valley, said John Lewis, a projects
manager in the office of business and work force development for
the Maricopa Community College District, who has studied the local
back office market.
</P>
<P>
   The company is planning its expansion as many other local
back-office operators are reporting struggles in finding and
keeping workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley has become known as a popular destination for call
centers, with its large, educated labor pool with neutral accents
and its lack of weather problems. But as the number of back office
operations has doubled to 120 in the past few years, competition
for workers has driven wages from $6 an hour to more than $8. Many
call center operators have been frustrated as workers continually
jumped ship for a few more cents an hour elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis said many of the companies who complain about the
labor pool drying up are not understanding the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you employ the three 'bs' _ bucks, benefits and
benevolence _ if you treat your workers right, you could open up a
huge call center in the busiest area in the Valley and fill your
staff,'' Lewis said. ``The ones that are having trouble finding and
keeping workers usually fall into two categories: low-ballers and
sweatshops.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert acknowledges that hiring has not gone as quickly as
Midland had hoped, but he said the company is confident it will be
able to fill its openings. He said MCM's offering of high wages,
attractive benefits packages and a friendly, family-like atmosphere
have helped.
</P>
<P>
   The company is launching a major advertising blitz to jump-start
its hiring. Midland offers base pay of $10.39 to $14.42 per hour,
plus commissions, bonuses, medical benefits and paid vacations. A
job hotline at 707-5506 offers more details.
</P>
<P>
   Midland Credit Management is one of the larger debt management
companies in the country. Chandler took it over in 1991, and
changed it from a floundering third-party collector to a purchaser
of unsecured, charged-off accounts _ mainly credit card balances
and student and consumer loans. Companies like Midland purchase the
debt for pennies on the dollar and make their profit from what they
can recover.
</P>
<P>
   MCM has grown from 28 employees in Kansas in 1991 to 78 there
now, plus its expanding Valley operations. The amount of debt it
purchased has increased from $650 million last year to close to $1
billion this year. It is positioning itself to go public down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're seen as one of the up and coming companies in the
industry,'' said Steven Frie, an analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's who
prepared a report on Midland. ``Once a company gets up into the
billions in the debt it services, it becomes a pretty major
player.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lisa Gonderinger can be reached at lisa.gonderinger(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
