<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      10-01 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODHAM CLINTON PRESSES HOUSE DEMOCRATS ON IMPEACHMENT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is vigorously
pressing House Democrats to oppose an impeachment inquiry of
President Clinton, arguing that the presidency and the country
could be irreparably harmed by a full-scale investigation of her
husband's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her personal pain over the president's illicit affair
with Monica S. Lewinsky, Mrs. Clinton has aggressively reached out
to numerous lawmakers in recent weeks in the hope of sparing the
president from a formal impeachment inquiry, several lawmakers and
congressional aides said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the cabin of an Air Force jet on Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton made
the case to a half-dozen House Democrats, including Representative
Patrick J. Kennedy of Rhode Island, during a flight from Washington
to Puerto Rico to survey the damage from Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defense strategy is focused in part on keeping
the 206 Democrats in the House as united as possible in opposing a
formal impeachment inquiry to make it appear as if Clinton is the
target of a partisan investigation motivated by election-year
interests.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Mrs. Clinton has fully embraced the White House
initiative, as the House Judiciary Committee prepares to vote early
next week on recommending the formal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard for anyone to see that she's certainly upset
with this whole process, especially the unfairness of it all,''
Kennedy said Thursday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy declined to discuss specifics of Mrs. Clinton's private
conversation over the Atlantic Ocean with the House Democrats.
Among them were Representatives Charles B. Rangel of New York, Jim
McDermott of Washington, George Miller of California, and Donald M.
Payne of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy attributed Mrs. Clinton's anger in part ``to the
prosecutorial misconduct of Ken Starr, his entrapping witnesses,
his conflicts of interests, his political bias.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Mrs. Clinton spoke pointedly to the House Democrats
about trying to focus the midterm election debate on the
differences in spending priorities between the two parties. But she
placed special emphasis on working to block the impachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is obviously concerned about the country and the fact that
this thing has been given such a green light by so many people
without somebody saying, `Stop, what in the world are you
thinking?''' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired in part by his conversation with Mrs. Clinton, Kennedy
delivered a speech on the House floor Thursday in which he accused
Starr, the independent counsel, of engaging in ``sexual
McCarthyism.'' He also asserted that House Republican leaders are
rushing to launch a formal impeachment inquiry of Clinton now
``because the majority could never vote to initiate an inquiry once
they really knew what they were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is a reckless, embarrassing personal act by the
president,'' Kennedy said in his House speech. ``It was wrong. He
was human. He tried to hide it. That too was wrong. None of this,
however, shows that the president was on a course that was
dangerous to the republic or justifies throwing this democracy into
a constitutional tailspin.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and her spokeswoman were traveling in Latin
American Thursday and were not available to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House picked up key support Thursday from
the House Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, who
has pledged to mobilize rank-and-file Democrats against a full
impeachment inquiry unless the investigation is limited to the
Lewinsky matter, according to House Democratic sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to pass a resolution early
next week that calls for a full impeachment inquiry with
Watergate-style rules that allow for a wideranging inquiry, give
both Democrats and Republicans access to subpoena power and allow
the president's lawyers to participate fully. Under a draft of the
resolution released Wednesday by the panel's chairman,
Representative Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, no deadline would be set
for the probe, and the committee would be permitted to expand the
investigation beyond the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, even some who had pressed Hyde to adopt the
Watergate-style rules, said the resolution was designed by
Republicans to prolong the investigation as far into the 2000
election season as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Thursday to Hyde, Representative John Conyers Jr. of
Michigan, the Judiciary Committee's ranking Democrat, said the
resolution could ``only mire the country into a protracted and
partisan inquiry which could last for years and drag down the
country in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gephardt huddled privately Thursday night with Democrats on
the Judiciary Committee, trying to draft an alternative to Hyde's
resolution, Republicans accused many Democrats of duplicity,
particularly for seeking a Watergate-style resolution, then
criticizing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of doublespeak going on,'' said
Representative Stephen E. Buyer, an Indiana Republican who serves
on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer described the opposition as ``a diversionary tactic to
confuse'' the public and blamed it on ``extreme, left-wing
Democrats'' on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Added Representative Charles T. Canady, a Florida Republican and
committee member: ``I have a growing suspicion that no matter what
we do, they will criticize us.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats privately acknowledged they face a dilemma. If all 16
Democrats on the Judiciary Committee oppose Hyde's resolution for a
formal inquiry, they run the risk of looking badly out of step with
the large number of Democrats who favor an impeachment review and
may support the Republican proposal on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   That would provide Republicans powerful ammunition to attack
committee Democrats as more partisan than their peers, and perhaps
substantially weaken their ability to mold committee proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   With about 50 rank-and-file Democrats already poised to support
the GOP resolution, according to Democratic sources, Gephardt and
the White House faced a dicey task in designing a resolution that
would prevent a wholesale desertion of Clinton by the Democratic
caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who is close to Gephardt, tried to rally his colleagues
against the Hyde resolution, saying on the House floor that
supporting the measure would set the House on ``a reckless course
that wil imperil and permanently damage the Constitution and the
definition of what is an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the House was headed down ``a maddening road'' toward
the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton, Gephardt and Kennedy were given little chance
of blocking the GOP move, particularly because Clinton's popularity
among congressional Democrats is considered to be at an all-time
low despite broad public support for his job performance.
</P>
<P>
   When the House voted last month on the resolution that
effectively started the impeachment process, the measure passed,
363-63, with support from more than 130 Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
