<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BIRD-BOSTON-BOS &LR;      10-01 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIRD-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD, BOSTON IRREVOCABLY TIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ This is a true story. It is not a re-creation. Names
have not been changed to protect the privacy of the characters. It
is dramatic; it is not a dramatization. This is the story of a man
who took his last NBA fadeaway jumper on May 17, 1992. We know: so
far, none of this is unusual. Many men have retired from pro
basketball, sidelined by unpredictable backs and sore feet that
shifted and turned and cut into sneakers far too many times over 13
seasons. Careers end. It happens. But how many players can say they
made a city and region stop for six years?
</P>
<P>
   Our main character has done that. It is as if Boston and New
England life is a compact disc, a disc that the man can rewind,
replay, and freeze any time he wants. The last time he gingerly put
on his No. 33 jersey in 1992, Chris Ford was his coach, his final
opponent's arena was literally in the middle of Ohio woods, his
president's name was George Bush, his governor's name was William
Weld, and, like everyone else, he did not think there was anything
peculiar about a young woman named Monica wearing a blue dress from
the Gap. So everything has changed. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   When you think of our main character, all 6 feet 9 inches of
him, do you think of the pensive man at the end of the Indiana
Pacers bench? Or do you think of No. 33 throwing a no-look pass to
a teammate cutting to the basket? He will be inducted into the
Basketball Hall of Fame tonight in Springfield. Once again, we
know: This is not unusual. We could have prepared the appropriate
busts and plaques in the early 1980s. But cliches tell us that life
goes on. Apparently it doesn't for him. Life is the same. The man
isn't just as popular as he was when he played for the Celtics. He
is more popular. This doesn't happen often. Magic Johnson, a son of
Los Angeles, coached and left the Lakers and had a late-night TV
show _ made in LA _ canceled. If there were a program called ``The
Larry Bird Hour'' filmed in New England, do you think it would be
dropped, no matter how poor the ratings and/or content? If you
answered yes, you must read on about this very fictional yet very
real man. You must read about this Larry Bird, a man who has made a
city and region stop for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Larry is always watching. This is not some Orwellian statement
(although Bird won the first of his three MVP awards in 1984 while
George Orwell's book about Big Brother always lurking is titled
``1984''), it's a fact.
</P>
<P>
   If you are hungry, you can go to the Coolidge Corner Clubhouse
in Brookline. You can check the menu and find a Larry Bird
sandwich, a ham and turkey creation on white rye with Russian
dressing, Swiss cheese, and cole slaw. Following your meal, you can
travel further into Brookline to see Bird's old home, where people
still tell you that, yes, Larry once lived here. You can go to
Quincy Market, where our character once got into a scuffle at a
place named Chelsea's. The bar is long gone, 13 years after Bird
allegedly threw a punch at a 200-plus-pound, former college
offensive lineman named Mike Harlow. But the stories are still
there. Larry is still here. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things you cannot do. You cannot call the
Registry of Motor Vehicles and request a license plate that says
something like ``33'' or ``Larry 33'' or ``Bird 33.'' They're all
taken. Ed Lavoie knows about that. He says he probably shouldn't
admit it, but the other day he saw a Connecticut plate with ``L.
Bird'' inscribed on it and, well, he was very intrigued by it. He
wanted it. Desperately. Not desperate enough to go up to the car
and take what did not belong to him. But still desperate. You get
that way sometimes when, every day, you stare at a poster in your
office of Bird diving out of bounds after a loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   Lavoie is box-office manager at the Worcester Centrum. He has to
be there tonight when Janet Jackson comes to town. He would rather
be in Springfield, honoring the player he began following at
Indiana State in the late 1970s. Since then, he has met Bird and
built his own Bird Hall of Fame in his basement. There are
lithographs, Wheaties boxes, Sports Illustrated covers (signed by
Bird), books, a ``33'' license plate (from Aruba), an authentic
game jersey that someone gave him as a gift, and several game
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is more popular now for the simple reason that the
NBA has gone down in quality,'' Lavoie said of Bird. ``You don't
have players now who played like Larry, Magic, and Michael. You'll
probably think I'm crazy for saying this, but the only guy who
plays as hard _ diving after loose balls and concentrating on
rebounds _ is (Dennis) Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you don't have players who lived like Bird, either. He
despised the NBA's humming PR machine. He was notorious for
hovering over his cash, as if it were a rare harvest he never would
see again. He spoke simply and dressed simply. His Indiana twang
never merged with the silent ``r'' of Boston and his ``a'' never
sounded like an ``ah.'' He was just Larry Bird. Could there be a
more fitting tribute to him than the bronzed sneakers near Faneuil
Hall? Lavoie hasn't seen the immortalized shoes yet but, ``I'll go
there on one of my off days.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll go and hear the stories of how Bird, Quinn Buckner, and a
friend scuffled all the way out to State Street one May night in
1985. If he listens closely, he may hear the whispers of the
ever-present Bird, who told a Worcester paper shortly after the
incident:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care about my image as far as grown-ups are
concerned. Most grown-ups are a pain anyway. But in my heart, I
feel bad about the kids. I regret all of this because kids should
be able to look up to athletes, and my mom took it pretty tough.
She said, `You know better than that. You shouldn't have been in a
place like that.' That bothered me a lot. I'm real sorry about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one good thing about all this is that maybe people finally
will understand that I'm human. I make mistakes; I've made a lot of
mistakes. I like to drink beer and go out and have a good time _
I'm human.''
</P>
<P>
   He is flawed. He makes mistakes. He is human. Yet, how can he be
in two and three places at once?
</P>
<P>
   Places like the one on a Cape Cod beachfront, amid trendy
restaurants and hotel chains. You make a few turns off Routes 6 and
28 and you see Larry there. He is watching over the home of Peter
Shankman, a 48-year-old Bird lover who refers to basketball as a
funk ballet. Shankman has a 40- by 30-foot basketball court set up
at his house. There have been times when people drove by his
Dennisport home and swore that they saw someone standing outside.
They did see someone. A huge mural of Bird.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the places in the middle of the city. Places
where beachfronts are miles away, where drivers clamor for parking
spaces and youngsters run to a Dorchester facility called The
Colonel Daniel Marr Boys and Girls Club. You walk inside, go to the
second floor and see the usual basketball sights. But in a far
corner, there is Bird again. An artist named Mike Lalone has drawn
an early Bird, moustachioed, dropping back to shoot among the
cosmos. There are wings and space. It is as if Bird were meeting
someone like Jonathan Livingston Seagull. Bird stepping back to
shoot over stellar constellations and the moons of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Earth, 24-year-old Byron Goss and 18-year-old John
Martins, from Roxbury and Dorchester, tell of how they have played
under Lalone's drawing of Bird for years. ``Back in the day, I
think he influenced a lot of playground players because everybody
wanted to shoot 3-pointers,'' Goss said.
</P>
<P>
   And, really, who could shoot 3s and simultaneously talk trash
like Bird?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be more like (Michael) Jordan when I was a kid,''
Martins said. ``But I'll always remember Bird for making the clutch
shot. He always made the clutch shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it seemed that way. There were many nights when Bird
shot 4 of 15 or 6 of 20. But he was everywhere on the court. For a
rebound, steal, or block. Something. And when he stopped doing it
on the court, he was there off it. Like he is now. In Dennisport
and Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I used to drive 80 miles to see him because I felt like
I might see something that's never been done before,'' Shankman
said. ``Think how lucky I am. I am old enough to remember seeing
(Bill) Russell, (John) Havlicek, (Satch) Sanders and all the great
Celtic teams. And I got to experience Larry Bird. It was such an
orgasm for me to watch him play. Just think: The alternative is
that I could have grown up in Sacramento or Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Shankman is not in California or Missouri. He is in New England,
where there are stories and footprints and likenesses of Bird
everywhere. It has been that way for years. There will be
additional words and a higher focus on Bird today. But this has
been his area since he first arrived. It still is. We will start
believing that life indeed goes on when Bird is no longer a
regional king.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
