A5176 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-TECH-SHORTAGE-AZ     10-01 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-SHORTAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME DOUBT SHORTAGE OF HIGH-TECH WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - With almost two decades of experience as a computer
programmer, Robert Sanchez still can't find a permanent job.
</P>
<P>
   He's sent out dozens of resumes and most go unnoticed. To make
ends meet he does contract work, bouncing from one job to the next.
Sanchez scoffs at any suggestion of a shortage of technology
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Guidi, corporate director for information technology
support for an East Coast Fortune 1,000 company, began job hunting
in Phoenix and other markets in May. His result in Phoenix: not one
interview.
</P>
<P>
   One executive recruiting firm told Guidi it wasn't certain if it
received his resume, but knew it had no openings for him.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies from software firms to semiconductor giants
have complained for years about a shortage of qualified workers to
fill specialized jobs. When candidates can't be found locally, some
companies look overseas for workers to fill the gap. Frequently the
workers are foreigners studying at colleges in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States issues 65,000 foreign temporary visas a year.
This year, that cap was reached in May as companies snapped up
foreign computer programmers, engineers and other specialists
eagerly sought by high-tech employers.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-month debate, the House of Representatives recently
approved legislation that would set aside 142,500 visas over the
next three years for the foreign workers. The Senate was expected
to take it up Thursday. (NOTE: Oct. 3)
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp., Motorola Inc., and other industry giants with major
Phoenix operations say the change is imperative to find the workers
needed to keep projects in the United States. Other companies, such
as JDA Software and AG Communication Systems would also benefit
from a change that increases the hiring pool.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some remain skeptical of those claims, including Norman
Matloff, of the department of computer science at the University of
California-Davis.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that there is no high-tech employment shortage and
America is shortchanging itself by embracing more foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only `shortage' is one of cheap labor, especially in the
form of foreign nationals, who make on average 15 to 30 percent
less than comparable natives,'' said Matloff, who testified before
a House committee.
</P>
<P>
   Matloff's view hit home for Sanchez, 43, while at a Phoenix area
job fair. A form asking for minority-status information included a
category for those ``over 30.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an old foggie,'' Sanchez recalled. ``If there's really a
big shortage of engineers why won't they hire anyone over 30?''
</P>
<P>
   Older people may need to go back to school to upgrade to the
latest skills, said Ed Denison, executive director of the Arizona
Software Association.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is no mirage, it's the leading problem among
software firms, Denison said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting more foreign workers won't be a panacea but will
alleviate some of the struggle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we can get some (additional workers) we're a lot better
off than if we can't,'' he added
</P>
<P>
   Businesses agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times where we just need to go outside the U.S. to
find the technical skills and resources to meet our technically
advanced products,'' said Maureen Tuskai, spokeswoman for
Phoenix-based JDA Software, which employs 1,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   JDA has more than 50 people on work visas, roughly 5 percent of
its workforce. The company makes every effort to recruit locally,
Tuskai said.
</P>
<P>
   Shankar Kalyanam, a technical services manager at JDA on a visa
from India, challenges the stereotypes surrounding foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   Kalyanam, a computer programmer specializing in Oracle
databases, says he earns within the industry average of $50,000 to
$80,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   And what about those long hours?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I see my (American) boss in before me and leaving
after me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kalyanam, 27, who came to Phoenix in 1993 to work for an
India-based company, expects he will remain until next year and
then plans to work for one of JDA's 22 overseas offices.
</P>
<P>
   The big semiconductor giants pushing for the visa measure
strongly contend the work shortage is real.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13,000 people Intel hired last year, about 350 needed
HB-1 visas, which are available only to those with at least a
bachelor's degree and are getting a job that requires that degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are qualified people out there, at any age, we would
be glad to hire them because it's more expensive to hire foreign
nationals,'' said Coeta Chambers, a human relations attorney for
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   It costs up to $12,000 to sponsor a person for a visa and to
help them get the necessary credentials, she said.
</P>
<P>
   AG Communication has sharply curtailed its overseas recruiting.
Instead, the company farms out some of its work to a 100-person
team in India, a trend that's gaining popularity among many
high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   India has vast pool of skilled workers, most of whom speak
English.
</P>
<P>
   It provides a nice alternative to filling out the mountains of
paperwork required to bring in a foreign worker.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the telecommunications company with 1,200 Valley workers,
has certain government projects that can't be worked on by certain
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really been a need and we've not been able to fill it
so we've looked at other ways,'' said Charlie Schultz, vice
president and chief technical officer for AG Communication. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing can be reached at rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
