<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKAMERICA-COX     10-01 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKAMERICA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NationsBank name change coming in '99
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia customers can expect to see the NationsBank
name well into next year, even though that old name is living on
borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, NationsBank, the holding company, became
BankAmerica as the $43.1 billion merger announced in April was
completed. The new operating name is Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Thursday, company Chairman Hugh L. McColl
Jr. said the transition to the new corporate name will continue
into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run, the important message to our customers is
that nothing will change _ their accounts, checks, their credit
cards,'' said James Lientz, president of BankAmerica's Mid-South
unit in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still have customers using predecessor checks all over
the country,'' Lientz added. ``If you have a big supply of
NationsBank's checks, you can continue to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The changeover will begin in the East. North and South Carolina
will be first, and the Eastern transition will conclude with
Florida, McColl said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia will ``come between the Carolinas and Florida, sometime
in 1999,'' Lientz said. ``As soon as we have a time line, we'll be
more specific. There'll be a lot of happy sign companies.''
</P>
<P>
   As a first fruit of the marriage, NationsBank and BankAmerica
customers can now use 14,000 combined ATM machines around the
country_ without fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if this merger allowed the bank to lower fees
for all its customers. But based on history, that's not going to
happen,'' said Robert Pregulman of the U. S. Public Interest
Research Group's Atlanta office.
</P>
<P>
   McColl was exuberant at the news conference. But when a San
Franciso-based reporter expressed doubt about McColl's promised
commitment to that city, McColl responded, ``As Southerners we take
that question as an insult. When we give our word , we keep it.''
He refused to discuss the issue further.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the new Bank of America foundation will announce
community programs, and thousands of bank employees will turn out
into communities Saturday in a volunteer campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lientz said the $350 billion designated for community
development has not been allocated yet by city, but that he
assumed, ``owing to its importance, that Atlanta would receive a
disproportionate amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America has 8,700 employees in Atlanta and 10,100 in
Georgia, up from 6,200 and 7,000, respectively, when it became
NationsBank in 1992. That's a 45 percent increase in Atlanta.
Lientz expects that trend to continue ``because it's a great market
for us and a great place to do things.''
</P>
<P>
   He expanded on his remarks earlier this week about Atlanta's
importance, pointing out three Atlantans will be on the new board
of directors, and major lines of business will remain headquartered
here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his duties as head of BankAmerica's
small-business effort, Lientz cited the technology and operations
side, headed by James D. Dixon, and the real estate lending area
run by Michael Buchanan. William Middlemass is responsible for
credit policy and asset policy in consumer and commercial banking.
</P>
<P>
   McColl reiterated that Bank of America will take a ``special
charge of $1.3 billion, it could be higher, in the third or fourth
quarter.'' That includes severance pay and reserves for signage.
</P>
<P>
   He said NationsBank had no hedge fund exposure but that the old
BankAmerica has a $1.1 billion line of credit to hedge funds, of
which $300 million was loaned out. The bank also has an investment
in the D. E. Shaw hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   That did not strike analysts as significant. The new
Charlotte-headquartered banking giant, the country's largest, has
assets of $572 billion, and in its 22 states reaches one-third of
U.S. households, representing 8 percent of U.S. bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   On its first day of trading, the new BankAmerica stock closed at
$53.68 3/4 per share, up 18 3/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
