<SLUG> BC-COXCOMMUNICATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox signs off on Vegas cable deal
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Communications has closed a $1.33 billion deal to
buy a controlling stake in the cable TV system that serves all of
metro Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the country's 10 largest single systems with
319,000 residential customers. It's also one of the fastest
growing.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Las Vegas makes Cox Communications the fifth
largest cable TV concern, with 3.8 million subscribers. The
Atlanta-based company, controlled by Cox Enterprises Inc., had been
sixth. Cox Enterprises also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is complex, involving cash, stock and the assumption of
debt. Cox Communications is buying an 80 percent stake in Prime
South Diversified, a cable and telecommunications concern that had
been owned by Prime Cable of Austin, Texas, and the Greenspun
family in Las Vegas. The family also owns the Las Vegas Sun, a
daily afternoon newspaper. The newspaper is not part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Prime South will become Cox Las Vegas and be folded into the
parent company. The Greenspun family will retain a 20 percent stake
consisting of $134 million in preferred stock. They also will
receive $59 million in cash. And the Greenspuns are also expected
to remain active in Cox Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of the Las Vegas system makes Cox Communications
the largest single cable operator in the Southwest. It serves 1.8
million subscribers across the region, including such markets as
San Diego, Orange County, Calif., and Phoenix and Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
