</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWDOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    October gloom settles in; Wall Street drops 210
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took only one day of trading for October to live up to its
reputation as a frightful month on Wall Street, as major indexes
plunged. The Nasdaq composite tumbled 4.81 percent, the Dow Jones
industrial average 2.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors continued to show disappointment with
the size of the Federal Reserve's short-term interest rate cut _
only a quarter percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   But the market was also worried U.S. banks are vulnerable to
global loan losses stemming from currency and other economic
troubles in Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are concerned about a credit squeeze, especially
among banks exposed to foreign markets,'' said Herb Williamson,
vice president of the Enterprise Group, an Atlanta-based mutual
fund organization.
</P>
<P>
   He said the recent Fed-induced bailout of the Long-Term Capital
Management hedge fund added to investor worries about potential
Asian defaults on U.S. bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our banking system is one of the soundest in the world, but we
will have to work our way through the credit squeeze,'' added
Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan didn't help the market much with his
testimony before the House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said failure of Long-Term Capital Management ``could have
potentially impaired the economies of many nations, including our
own.'' He also said the bailout should be a rare event.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, bank stocks led the market to one of the worst
one-day losses ever on Thursday, with the Dow recording its second
stright loss of more than 200 points.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bonds, meanwhile, continued to reap the benefit of Wall
Street panic as investors abandon stocks to put their money in
safer but lower-yielding fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury yield dropped below 5 percent for the first
time on Wednesday and fell again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the market's direction this quarter will be
determined in large part by third-quarter corporate profit reports,
which companies will release during the next three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts anticipate the profits of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
companies will show a year-over-year decline _ the first since
1991, when the economy was emerging from a recession.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's cut in the federal funds interest rate on Tuesday was
designed to prevent a recession in 1999, according to analysts who
think additional rate cuts will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside risk is not over unless the Fed steps in and
moves rates lower again,'' Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst Paul Cherney
said in an S&AMP;P Web report.
</P>
<P>
   As for October, it is the month notorious for stock market
crashes, including the Great Crash in 1929 and the market's biggest
crash, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Others also note the month has recorded some big gains over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
