<HEADER>
A5185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCENT-COX     10-01 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucent Technologies to let go 425 at Georgia plant
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lucent Technologies said it will cut up to 425 jobs at
its sprawling plant along Interstate 85 in Norcross, even as it
continues to expand production of fiber optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which currently employs about 3,000 people in
Norcross, will eliminate as many as 175 management jobs and 250
manufacturing jobs held by Communication Workers of America Local
3263 members. Many of the workers will leave by the end of the
year, but the cuts aren't expected to be completed until late
March, Lucent spokesman Roger Frizzell said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Workers will be offered a package of incentives to voluntarily
leave the company or take early retirement. They can also apply for
other Lucent positions in metro Atlanta and elsewhere in the
nation, Frizzell said. ``Our hopes are that we have very few
people, if any, leave our business involuntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it wants to make its operations more efficient and
base many of its sales and management people in offices throughout
the world that are closer to customers. The production jobs, which
involve the assembly of cable connecting equpment rather than the
manufacturing of cable, will be shifted to a Lucent plant in Omaha,
Neb., and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The company said some of the work may also end up at a Fi-Tel
plant in Carrollton, according to Leon Gusek, president of CWA
Local 3262. While the plant is part of a Lucent joint venture,
workers there are neither Lucent employees nor union members. Gusek
predicted that Norcross workers won't be offered jobs at the
Carrollton plant because of their union background. ``That work
should stay here,'' said Gusek.
</P>
<P>
   Gusek said Lucent officials told the union that labor costs were
too high to make those products profitably at the Norcross plant.
Manufacturing workers at the Norcross Lucent plant make about
$16.29 an hour, according to Gusek.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tucker, the president of the Gwinnett Chamber of
Commerce, said there are still many jobs available for skilled
workers in Gwinnett. ``There are between 500 and 700 high-tech and
high-tech related companies in the county,'' Tucker said. ``I
expect there won't be much problem for qualified workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norcross plant's main business focus _ making fiber optic
cable _ is unaffected by the job cuts. Lucent continues to run
three shifts a day to make the cable, and it is continuing with a
$350 million expansion of the plant's production capacity. That
work now is expected to add at least 50 manufacturing jobs at the
plant, Lucent's Frizzell said. Officials expect to complete the
expansion within two years, though further expansions are possible,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   To convince Lucent to make the expansion in Georgia the state
agreed to kick in $5 million for a special lab that will help
improve the technology. The state has said Lucent is also eligible
for tax credits for new jobs it creates.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's stock closed at $66.12 1/2, down $3.12 1/2 Thursday.
Edward Jones analyst David Powers tied the drop to investors'
negative view of the overall telecommunications industry. He said
he hadn't heard of the job cuts in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writers Mark Clothier and Peter Kent contributed to this
report
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
