<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCARPOLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cope on pole; Gordon slips
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Did Halloween come early to Charlotte Motor
Speedway Wednesday night?
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain that Derrike Cope won his first career pole,
for Sunday's UAW-GM Quality 500, after failing to qualify in four
other events? That Jeff Gordon didn't make the top 25? That Mark
Martin was bumped from the pole by Cope?
</P>
<P>
   Cope, the 41st driver on the 1.5-mile track, surprised all with
his pole-winning speed of 181.690 mph, just a tick faster than his
inside front row partner Martin's 181.220 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of adversity, a year of uncharted territory
that has limited us,'' said Cope, referring to the beating he took
in accidents at both Atlanta and Texas. ``To win the pole is
self-gratifying for me toward my crew. I knew we had a shot at it,
and I wanted it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cope broke his ribs, sternum and shoulder in Atlanta, then
aggravated the condition in Texas, where he hit a slick spot on the
track and crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's poor lap was one he expected, but not to the extent of
not qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we tested here we weren't going to be good in
qualilfying,'' Gordon said. ``I'm not real concerned because I know
we've got a good race car. We misjudged a little bit, and I got a
little bit looser than I was expecting to get for qualifying. I'm
disappointed we didn't go faster, but I'm thankful to get this out
of the way so we can get ready to race.''
</P>
<P>
   For Martin, Gordon's slip was no more than a blip on the screen,
even though the crowd stood and roared when his speed was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real good lap for us,'' Martin said of his second-place
lap. ``This is a moody old girl here, this track, especially when
it comes to sun and cloud cover and nighttime and everything else.
I expect Jeff got into a little bit of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Buckshot Racing team announced Wednesday that
two-time Busch Series champion Larry Pearson will drive the No. 00
Pontiac and with a new sponsor, Cheez-It Snack Cracker, for the
1999 Busch season. Kenneth Campbell, formerly with the Timber Wolf
team, will oversee the program from their headquarters in
Spartanburg. Buckshot Jones will move to the Winston Cup circuit in
'99, with headquarters in a new shop in Spartanburg. Ricky Pearson
will be crew chief of the Winston Cup team. ...Todd Bodine returns
to the Busch circuit in '99 with Team 34, reuniting with the Frank
Ciccio/Scott Welliver team where he enjoyed much success in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
