<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCURRY-LASTDAY-NYT </SLUG>
 
AS HE BIDS PRESS CORPS FAREWELL, McCURRY DEFENDS CLINTON  
 (bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mike McCurry drew warm applause and on-the-record
compliments from the White House press corps Thursday even as he
departed as President Clinton's spokesman with a final defense of
the long mendacious months of presidential denials in the Lewinsky
sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I was determined, when that story broke back in
January, was to never come here and do what some of my
predecessors, unfortunately, did, which was to lie to you and
mislead you,'' McCurry said in a parting defense of his signature
strategem of deliberately not asking the president about the
biggest story of the year, the one that has put Clinton at risk of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes not knowing the answer _ even though that puts you
in a tough position, too _ is better than consciously misleading
people,'' Curry said as he headed off to the lecture circuit after
three-and-half years of speaking for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   To the end, reporters questioned the wisdom of McCurry in his
never-ask policy on the Lewinsky affair even as many in his
skeptical audience offered some departing applause, as if for an
actor who has carried off some searing Ibsenesque role in a drama
of dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave with your honor intact,'' allowed one critic in an
aisle seat, Sam Donaldson of ABC News. But Bill Plante of CBS News
did not let McCurry go that easily, asking why he felt he could
ever ``afford to remain ignorant'' of something concerning the
president and, even more, ``Who does a press secretary work for?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   True to form, McCurry fielded the questions with a gentle ease,
contending that to have behaved otherwise and pressed the president
for details about the Lewinsky allegations would have made Clinton
a ``sitting duck'' for Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr by
breaching Clinton's attorney-client privilege by way of the press
office. ``I segmented out'' Monica Lewinsky questions from
``millions of pieces of information that I stuffed in this pathetic
brain of mine every day,'' he said, adding he has no regrets for
this.
</P>
<P>
   The press secretary works for the taxpayers, the president and
the press, McCurry said, describing his role as operating
``equidistant between two combatants,'' the media and the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I know that at times I came up short,'' McCurry
said, apologizing for not always offering the right information.
``Frankly, the president misled me too, so I came here and misled
you on occasion. And that was grievously wrong of him, but he's
acknowledged that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, allowing himself a rhetorical question, he asked a
jam-packed press room, ``Did I ever knowingly come here and send
you folks in the wrong direction? I did not. I'm confident of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wry and smooth to the last word, the spokesman, who once
described his job as ``telling the truth slowly,'' was asked
whether he had learned a lot about how the White House works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, quite a bit, but I'm going to go out and make people pay
to hear it,'' he said, relishing the five-figure speaking fees he
has lined up as his bridge to the 21st century. Even as they
laughed, some reporters privately judged McCurry too clever by half
for presenting his dedicated ignorance of the affair as a virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old press secretary, who has spent half his life
honing his skills in government and political press relations,
showed his strengths in his final performance. He minimized his
answers on the ``white noise'' of the impeachment struggle up on
Capitol Hill, while indulging at length questions about Kosovo and
the Serbs, brandishing a command of detail he mastered earlier as
the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, to the final minutes the questions necessarily
continued about the president and the intern. One reporter noted
that, in February, McCurry admitted in an off-guard moment that
there would likely be no ``simple, innocent explanation'' for the
president's predicament. ``I don't think so,'' he conceded then,
``Because I think we would have offered that up already.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters took that as a slip of the Oz-like media curtain that
modern White Houses labor to work behind in their spin endeavors.
But the spokesman parried to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clairvoyance!'' said a grinning McCurry of those comments,
which preceded by six months Clinton's turnabout admission that he
had misled the nation about Ms. Lewinsky even as his staff, notably
McCurry, was daily proclaiming his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   As he paused in the TV lamplight, the spokesman mused that he
might write a book, but nothing nasty and tell-all, something
``about the changes we're going through as a culture, as we try to
communicate about public policy in the Information Age.''
</P>
<P>
   He drew mock groans and shouted advice (``Sex! You've got to
have sex in the book!'') from the assemblage of doubters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've done a good job, Mike, under the circumstances,'' said
Helen Thomas, the long-serving dean of the press corps, twice
stressing ``under the circumstances'' as she moreor less dismissed
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, Sweets,'' McCurry shot back. As laughter grew the
president's spokesman did not hesitate to add, as if in parody of
the White House's rough year: ``Helen and I always had a thing for
each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
