<HEADLINE>
METAL DETECTORS IN PLACE AT MAGIC MOUNTAIN, HURRICANE HARBOR THEME
PARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY BROWN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Metal detectors are being installed at the two
Six Flags theme parks, the first time the security devices will be
used at a Southern California amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   Every visitor to Magic Mountain and Hurricane Harbor in suburban
Valencia will be required to go through the airport-style
detectors, which spokesman Andy Gallardo said are simply another
tool to complement an already polished security force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to add to the safety of our guests,'' Gallardo
said. ``Six Flags probably has one of the more comprehensive
security programs in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallardo said the detectors could not have averted an incident
in April, when a 15-year-old youth from suburban Fontana was
fatally shot in the parking lot of the 260-acre amusement complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing we could do to prevent that shooting,'' he
said. ``It happened in the parking lot so, unfortunately, even with
the detectors that couldn't have been prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   Local sheriff's officials have been quick to praise security at
the Six Flags California site. Lt. Carl Deeley of the Santa Clarita
Valley sheriff's station said the park is one of the safest around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do an excellent job,'' Deeley said after a May 30 melee
that park visitors said involved gang members.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for Disneyland and Knott's Berry Farm in
neighboring Orange County and Universal Studios in suburban
Universal City said metal detectors are not in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have them, and I can't say whether or not they are
being considered,'' said Disneyland spokeswoman Marge Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Gallardo said installation should be completed by January and
that the devices should only add to an already impressive security
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will always look to make our program better,'' he said,
``although we feel our security is very thorough already. We are
very happy with our program.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
