<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEDESTRIAN-FATALITIES     10-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEDESTRIAN-FATALITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speed humps aren't only way to calm traffic
 &HT;    By Joey Ledford
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, efforts to slow traffic in residential areas
have almost exclusively involved the controversial speed hump.
</P>
<P>
   But during a two-day conference in Atlanta this week on
preventing childhood pedestrian injuries, the speed hump was only
rarely mentioned as a traffic engineering solution.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers have found that, in addition to better pedestrian
training for children and better supervision for the very young,
changes in roadway design can slow drivers and help prevent
pedestrian deaths and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Cities like Seattle, Portland, Ore., and Cambridge, Mass., have
become more pedestrian friendly by introducing ``traffic calming''
features in neighborhoods. Speed humps are the most extreme and
obtrusive, yet least expensive, example of a traffic calming, or
speed limiting device.
</P>
<P>
   Others include curb extensions, which shorten pedestrians' walk
across a street, and traffic circles, or roundabouts, used at
intersections to make traffic circle slowly instead of being
controlled by traffic signals.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrians are also protected by refuge islands, which give
crossing walkers a safe haven halfway across a street, and
chicanes, a routing device that makes traffic in effect zigzag and
slow in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious pedestrian aid, which is only now debuting in
some suburban Atlanta neighborhoods, and is still nonexistent in
many others, is the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need policies that say the sidewalk goes in as soon as the
street gets built,'' said Dan Burden, a Florida-based pedestrian
advocate and traffic engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic calming devices don't have to be expensive, said Peter
Lagerway, an administrator for a pedestrian and bicycle program in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, by piggybacking on, it's very little money,''
he said. When a street is torn up by utility construction, repaving
or even repainting, traffic calming treatments can be inserted at
little additional cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it's a matter of just moving paint,'' he said,
noting that bike lanes can be added and wide streets narrowed on
existing pavement, resulting in slower speeds through
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, he said, neighborhoods that want such changes are
given them in stages just to make sure it's what they really want.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we put in a new treatment, first we will paint it in,''
Lagerway said. ``Then we put cones in. Then we say, if you don't
like it, in a year we will take it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Very few neighborhoods decide to return to the old speed-driven
ways, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason motorists tend to speed in residential areas,
said several speakers, is that many roads in neighborhoods appear
to be built for speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedestrian needs have been largely forgotten,'' said Charles
Zeeger, associate director for roadway study at the University of
North Carolina Highway Safety Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Putting crosswalks or crossing signals on multilane roads is
like ``trying to put a small bandage on a badly broken leg,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta, recently named as having the nation's
seventh-meanest streets by a pedestrian advocacy group, most
commonly uses pedestrian signals as its lone concession to walkers.
But a 1983 Federal Highway Administration study of 1,700 signalized
intersections showed they had no safety benefits compared to sites
without them.
</P>
<P>
   Without a will to change our neighborhoods, or at least start
building better ones, our children will remain captives in front of
the television, eating instead of playing outside and getting the
exercise they need, said Richard Killingsworth, a Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention specialist.
</P>
<P>
   One of every five children is overweight, he said, as is one of
every two adults.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason? ``Our communities continue to be developed in a
way where walking is nonexistent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
