u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-520&AMP;ADD-N     10-01 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL CONDEMNS ATROCITIES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-MASSACRE, KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(sw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council, prodded by Britain and
the United States, on Thursday condemned the recent atrocities
against civilians in Kosovo and demanded that those guilty be
caught and punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Council members expressed considerable alarm at reports that
fighting was continuing despite the demand for a cease-fire, and in
particular that thousands more civilians have been forced to leave
their homes because of the actions of government security forces,''
said Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's representative and this
month's council president, after Thursday's emergency meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The condemnation called for an immediate investigation by the
Yugoslav government, though government forces are among those
accused of taking part in the atrocities. In order to get unanimous
backing of all 15 council members, it did not take the formal shape
of a resolution or presidential statement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some hedged language over the role of the War Crimes
Tribunal and no explicit mention of force, the message was welcomed
by the American representative on the council, Peter Burleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council is sending a clear signal of its outrage that the
council shares with the secretary general with regard to these
latest atrocities in Kosovo,'' he said after the meeting on
Thursday evening. ``It's a very serious situation, a very grave
situation. The council is deeply concerned about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very clear, direct message to the government in
Belgrade that they have to be accountable and responsible for their
activities, the activities of their security forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a renewed condemnation of the Serbs by the
Security Council, the British and Americans want Secretary General
Kofi Annan to speed up a report on Yugoslavia's compliance with a
resolution passed on Sept. 23 that called for an end to attacks on
civilians. Annan's report had been expected to be turned over by
the middle of next week. It will now go to the council no later
than Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Annan warned of a human disaster in the making. ''I
utterly condemn the unwarranted killings and excesses by the Serb
security forces,'' he said, adding that violence on both sides must
stop and that the relief organizations must get access to the
refugees in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appeal to all concerned to cease the violence and give us
humanitarian space and access to do our work,'' Annan said. He also
asked the Serbs to ``allow the negotiators to do their work and get
people back to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading NATO nations appear to want the moral authority of the
secretary general behind the decision to take action against
President Slobodan Milosevic. An American official said that his
report can be interpreted by those who want to interpret it that
way as a trigger for action or a validation of the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   The nations that have been working together as a contact group
on Yugoslavia _ Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the
United States _ are planning to meet at the ministerial level on
Friday in London.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke with several
European leaders on Thursday in advance of the meeting. American
officials believe that the recent atrocities in Kosovo have
galvanized into action some countries that were hesitant to talk
about using force and that some nations once more insistent on
another specific U.N. resolution authorizing an attack may be less
so now.
</P>
<P>
   France, whose foreign minister told reporters last week that a
decision on the use of force was still in the future, now believes
that last week's Security Council resolution constitutes sufficient
legal grounds for NATO to take military action against Milosevic's
forces, French officials said on Thursday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that they no longer believe that another
resolution would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has argued that NATO had the authority to
attack even before the resolution last Wednesday, which was adopted
under a chapter of the U.N. Charter that makes the resolution
militarily enforceable.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China continue to hold out against any kind of
military intervention in Kosovo. Last week China could not be
persuaded even to join in condemnation of attacks against
civilians. Thursday in Moscow, Russian officials repeated their
opposition to force. Within NATO, the Greeks are also reported to
be opposed. At the Security Council, Russia's representative,
Sergey Lavrov, declined to comment on Thursday's condemnation
except to say that it had been arrived at by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, in transition between governments, remains something of
a question mark. The outgoing chancellor, Helmut Kohl, may be
reluctant to authorize an action whose results would be left to his
successor, Gerhard Schroeder, to deal with. A Western diplomat here
said, however, that Schroeder might welcome a situation in which a
decision to take part in military action would be laid on his
predecessor's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, a NATO official said that ambassadors to the
organization from member countries would study the legal grounds
for action in Kosovo before any attacks took place.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the organization still had to complete
planning on what kind of peacekeeping force might have to be sent
to Kosovo if bombing or the threat of bombing causes Milosevic to
back away from more attacks on civilians and the situation requires
a neutral presence on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, NATO officials say, the organization has to take formal
control of forces, aircraft and other equipment pledged for bombing
operations and to collect an attack force at designated bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
