<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER OFFERS A GUILTY PLEA IN UNION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan lawyer who represented Ron Carey in his
1996 re-election campaign for the teamsters' presidency pleaded
guilty Thursday to one count of conspiracy to make false statements
to a court-appointed election officer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Nathaniel Charny of the labor law firm of Cohen,
Weiss &AMP; Simon, pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
to lying about the legitimacy of several contributions to the Carey
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The election monitor, Barbara Zack Quindel, overturned Carey's
1996 victory over James P. Hoffa after concluding that more than
$700,000 in union money had been improperly funneled into the Carey
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Charny, 33, admitted he had lied to Ms. Quindel when he
testified that he had questioned several wealthy donors about the
propriety of their contributions to the campaign. He also
acknowledged concealing that two employers had sent his law firm
checks for the Carey campaign; employers are barred from
contributing money to candidates in union elections.
</P>
<P>
   Charny was in charge of vetting contributions to a special fund
set up to receive donations from wealthy people who did not belong
to the International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Charny, a Manhattan resident, faces a maximum penalty of five
years in prison and a fine of $250,000. He acknowledged in court
Thursday that he was cooperating with prosecutors in the office of
Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
