<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CENTRAL CELEBRATES REBIRTH AS A LUSTROUS TRAIN STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SUSAN SACHS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once threatened with demolition, gnawed by decades of
urban grime, obscured by ungainly advertising signs, corroded by
roof leaks and just plain unloved by the 500,000 people who sprint
through its cavernous halls each day on the way to somewhere else,
Grand Central Terminal celebrated its rebirth Thursday as a
lustrous train station that ranks as a destination in its own
right.
</P>
<P>
   In its restored grandeur, with sunlight pouring through
steel-ribbed skylights and twin marble staircases curling to a
platform on the east side of the Main Concourse, the 85-year-old
structure is once again so imposing that it dwarfed those who came
to praise it during a spirited rededication ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `grand' has truly been put back into the Grand Central
Terminal,'' declared E. Virgil Conway, chairman of the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, his voice so distorted by the echoing
marble walls that it was indistinguishable from those
simultaneously announcing track numbers for the next trains to
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Lavish praise also came from many of the hundreds of people who
came to the station to see _ and this time, to stop and take a good
look at _ what hundreds of technicians, craftsmen and designers had
wrought over the last two years from the sadly decaying edifice
that had gone without a major overhaul since its construction
before World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' said Teresa Delgado, an office worker at a nearby
Chase bank, as she gazed around at the cream-colored marble walls
and stairways, gleaming chandeliers and twinkling ceiling lights.
``I pass by it in a rush, normally, but this time I decided to take
a good look, and it's absolutely gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ceremony signified not only the official rededication
of the terminal but also the public opening of the set of marble
stairways on the east side of the Main Concourse and a restored
entrance at 42d Street and Vanderbilt Avenue, and the removal of a
low deck covering the east ramp to the Oyster Bar that since 1927
had blocked the view up to the skylights and down to the concourse.
</P>
<P>
   While the building itself was clearly the star of the event, the
MTA also enlisted some kinetic razzle-dazzle. High above the
assembled dignitaries, who included Gov. George Pataki, a trapeze
artist from the Big Apple Circus was hauled up 120 feet to the
vaulted ceiling, where, resplendent in a taxicab-yellow bodysuit,
he dangled and flipped on a lone swing. Turquoise lights danced
across the painted ceiling to the sounds of ``Rhapsody in Blue'' in
a laser light show.
</P>
<P>
   In a performance by the Westchester Philharmonic of an original
march commissioned for the event, six uniformed Metro-North
Commuter Railroad conductors solemnly accompanied the musicians on
whistles, bells and a box with a ratchet that simulates the sound
of train wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the train noises get going in the opening, it's like the
hustle and bustle of the station,'' said Bruce Saylor, the composer
of the march, titled ``Grand Central!''
</P>
<P>
   For railroad buffs, there were vintage railroad cars on view,
outfitted with all the trappings of luxury travel _ wood-paneled
dining cars, fluffy beds with raspberry-colored linens, padded
leather bars _ that largely disappeared from Grand Central as it
evolved from the ``gateway to the continent'' into a commuter train
and subway terminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could work in one of these instead of my subway
car,'' said Steve Fink, a New York City Transit driver on the No. 6
line, who stopped by on his way to work and found himself gazing
wistfully into an old New York Central train car that once served
as a home on the rails for Cornelius Vanderbilt, the shipping
magnate who purchased the 76-acre midtown site in 1864 to house his
expanding railroad empire.
</P>
<P>
   The building was a steam locomotive depot for 30 years, and when
Grand Central Terminal first opened in 1913, more than 150,000
people came to see the underground rail yards and expansive
separate passenger waiting rooms during the first 24 hours. In
1947, at the height of its glory, more than 65 million people took
trains that departed from, arrived at or transferred through Grand
Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But the station's days of grandeur faded as more and more
Americans began to forsake rail travel in the 1950s. Its once
pristine interior halls were rented out for billboards, and by
1968, developers were talking about surrounding the terminal with
high-rise buildings and demolishing the Main Concourse.
</P>
<P>
   It was saved, after a 10-year court battle, with the help of
preservationists who enlisted the high-profile help of Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis, who will be honored with a plaque to be installed
in the Main Concourse. John F. Kennedy Jr. unveiled the plaque
Thursday. The Grand Central Terminal cleanup and renovation, which
has cost $197 million and was financed by MTA funds and its sale of
$84 million in bonds, has been revealed to the public layer by
layer since the project began in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, commuters were first treated to the sight of the
newly scrubbed and modernized sky ceiling, a blue-green swath of
color punctuated with lighted stars and the outlines of
constellations. It is meant to represent the night sky, seen from
above, and has been improved by switching to a fiber-optic lighting
system from hundreds of workaday light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   State officials were so proud of the cleanup job that they had
workers leave one lone spot on the ceiling just as it was _ nearly
black with the accumulated smoke and dirt from years of cigarette
smoke, poor housekeeping and neglect _ for contrast. During the
ceremony, a spotlight was turned on the blemish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
