<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-VANDY-TEX     10-01 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VANDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSTACLES ARE THE NORM AT VANDERBILT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Discovered lurking on the Mississippi State coaching staff a few
years back, noted crusader Watson Brown offered a perfectly
plausible explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got tired of getting my tail whipped,'' he said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Almost universally regarded as one of the bright young faces on
the coaching scene, Brown had nevertheless just completed a stretch
at two schools where his teams compiled a sparkling 14-63 record.
</P>
<P>
   The schools in question were Rice and Vanderbilt _ two
small-enrollment private universities that, in the quaint parlance
of the '90s, are referred to as ``academic'' institutions.
</P>
<P>
   It is a line delivered without irony, as if describing a member
of the community suspected of tree worship.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt, which will face TCU tomorrow in Amon Carter Stadium,
is on its third coach since Brown left in 1990. Thus far, the
ledger for the decade _ including an 0-3 start this year _ reads
26-65.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent, Woody Widenhofer, arrived in '95 as defensive
coordinator and became the head coach last year. While Brown was a
genuine Vandy hero who once quarterbacked a famous upset of
Alabama, Widenhofer gained acclaim and four Super Bowl championship
rings coaching Pittsburgh's famed ``Steel Curtain'' defense in the
seventies.
</P>
<P>
   They do share one trait, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it starts,'' Widenhofer says, ``you become obsessed with
turning this thing around.''
</P>
<P>
   It requires, among other things, an energetic approach to
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he says, ``when I was coaching at Missouri (his alma
mater), we obviously got some kids in school that we couldn't get
in here, because of our entrance requirements. But also, you could
take Prop 48s back then (in the Big Eight).
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't recruit junior-college players, because most of them
are in junior college because of their high school academic
standing. On each year's Top 100 recruiting list, there are a lot
of players we have to automatically cross off.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are a lot of good students out there who are also
good football players _ you just have to find them. The payback is
that the type of kids we get, it's really a joy to coach them and
get to know them. They are very intelligent, committed to getting a
quality education, and they are not the kind of guys that you get
calls from the police about at 2 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of Houston Memorial High School, Clay Condrey figured
he had two choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably could have gone to school somewhere in Texas, with
a bunch of my friends, and really had a lot of fun,'' he says.
``Both my parents went to the University of Texas, so it would have
been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or, I figured I could go somewhere and get an education that
would be important and useful to me for the rest of my life. I've
always wanted to be an engineer, and that's why I'm here. That's
why everybody is here _ for a chance to be something besides just a
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a senior, Condrey (6-6, 270) has been a starting tackle for
two years. He took a recruiting visit to TCU, but recalls that
``they told me their engineering program was still a year away from
being accredited, so I came here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough school. I've cut my class load down to 12 hours
per semester so I can make my grades and continue to play football.
I'll be here an extra semester _ perhaps a year _ but in the end,
there will be an engineering degree. And that's what I came here
for.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Commodores' adventures on the field (3-8 last year),
Condrey says, ``We don't sit around worrying about who Tennessee is
recruiting _ we just love playing teams like that. But although
we've played them close (12-7, 14-7, 17-10) the three years I've
been here, we've lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win. In that respect, we're no different from the
players at any other school.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also a big point with Widenhofer. Although there are 37
players on the current squad with grade-point averages of 3.0 or
better, he is inclined to downplay the academic separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of excellent football players at all of the
big state schools,'' he says, ``who are also very good students.
They are the kind of students who could have gotten into
Vanderbilt, but they chose those other schools ... primarily
because of the football tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted a school where they could win a championship, go
to a bowl, play on TV. That's what we are fighting, really. We need
to get more of those kids to come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that, we win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
