<HEADLINE>
HBO GETS TO THE HEART OF THE BOSNIAN TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The HBO movie ``Shot Through the Heart'' is the story of Vlado
and Slavko, and part of the prospective audience is adrift already.
</P>
<P>
   Vlado and Slavko were in Sarajevo. Journalist John Falk, whose
1995 article in Details magazine led to the movie, knows about the
average American's interest in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with Americans,'' he said in a recent interview,
``is before you tell them who you're going to cheer for, they've
got to be able to find the place on the map. You know, if they
can't find Rhode Island, they're not going to be able to find
Bosnia, so adios to that.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO made ``Shot Through the Heart'' anyway. Pats on the back and
shiny medals to HBO. Not only did it make the movie, which
premieres Sunday, but it also approved a low-profile cast, because
these actors were right for the parts.
</P>
<P>
   However thick the politics and ethnic entanglements, the story
is stark and powerful. Also, true.
</P>
<P>
   Vlado Sarzinsky (Linus Roache, ``Wings of the Dove'') and Slavko
Simic (Vincent Perez, ``The Crow 2: City of Angels''), best friends
and colleagues on the Yugoslav national rifle shooting team, end up
on opposite sides when the Serbs lay siege to Sarajevo in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Simic joins the Serbian army and begins training snipers who'll
gun down men, women and children on the streets of Sarajevo.
Sarzinsky becomes an anti-sniper. Ultimately, in an incredibly
dramatic metaphor for the whole bloody mess, one will be in the
other's crosshairs.
</P>
<P>
   The story of best friends split by war is so pungent that at
times it threatens to overwhelm the bigger picture. But the
particular tragedy of Sarajevo does emerge. This was a proudly
cosmopolitan place, an Olympic city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Sarajevo, not Somalia,'' says a bewildered Vlado when
the roadblocks spring up around the Bosnian capital. ``We're
Europeans, for God's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Grim but determinedly humanistic, ``Shot Through the Heart'' is
directed by David Attwood (PBS' ``Moll Flanders'') and was filmed
mostly at former Russian army barracks in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   But the cemetery at the end, with the tombstones signifying
various ethnicities and foreshortened lives? Sadly, unmistakably
Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ ``Legalese'' (Sunday on the TNT cable channel) is a little
poison dart of a movie aimed at lawyers and tabloid journalists. It
turns out to be more of a local anesthetic than a poisonous comedy,
but it's a moderately entertaining watch.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Glenn Jordan, the film is about an actress (Gina
Gershon) accused of murder, whose famous defense attorney (James
Garner) disguises his involvement by using a novice attorney (Ed
Kerr) as his front man. Kathleen Turner contributes as a shrewd
tabloid TV reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is heavy company for TNT. But Mary-Louise Parker, as
the sexy, cynical Garner assistant who falls for Kerr, waltzes off
with the film. Miles to go before the next Emmys; someone make a
note.
</P>
<P>
   _ And _ this is important _ don't forget to call your cable
operator and demand The Learning Channel, because educational TV
turns you on.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, TLC (motto: ``Adventures for your mind'') asked us to
put our thinking caps on for ``Next to Nothing: A History of
Lingerie.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the curriculum features ``Secret World of
Supermodels,'' which promises to help you ``discover the naked
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't miss it. It's on immediately after ``Secret World of
Beauty Pageants.''
</P>
<P>
   A little knowledge really is a dangerous thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
