<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-INDIANS-SOX-ADVAN     10-01 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-SOX-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOUREK TO FOLLOW SABERHABEN IN SOX PLAYOFF ROTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The pitcher's wife will sing the national anthem. The
general manager's mother will sit with her son in his private box.
The first base coach will ride the Green Line to Kenmore Square,
and Boston's most famous Dominican will arrive proudly with his big
brother.
</P>
<P>
   The red, white, and blue bunting will be draped over box seat
railings almost as old as the Eck, Ted Williams's home run seat
will be freshly wiped, and Pesky's Pole should sparkle like gold in
the late-afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   October baseball returns this afternoon to Fenway Park with Game
3 of the American League Division Series. Bret Saberhagen will toe
the rubber, Lynn Saberhagen will take the mike, Mary Duquette will
beam at her son Dan, Dave Jauss will pocket his subway token, Pedro
Martinez will tip his cap to his brother Ramon, and the Red Sox
faithful, their worry lines for a change dwarfed by the upturned
curves of their smiles, will rise as one to celebrate that the Olde
Towne Team has a place in the playoffs for the first time since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians, a/k/a defending American League
champions, will be here, too, which is why, shortly after
Saberhagen's first pitch to Kenny Lofton, the euphoria of the
moment undoubtedly will give way to the anxiety that runs as deep
here as the Quabbin Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, now just outside the big city in Norwood, has
been here only two years, so he still can't fathom why, in a
best-of-five series tied at a game apiece, so many people are
already fretting about a worst-case scenario _ namely, that by the
time the twilight shadows fade to black, the Red Sox will be on the
brink of elimination and Williams will have no choice but to call
on Martinez to man the ramparts for Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose Friday against Connecticut's Charles Nagy, Williams
said, that will not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete Schourek's going to start the fourth game,'' said
Williams, who stood in line at the neighborhood McDonald's for a
double cheeseburger before appearing at an off-day press conference
at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to make sure no one misinterpreted his meaning, Williams
restated his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro's not going to pitch Saturday,'' Williams said. ``He's
not pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't pitched with three days' rest this season. If it was
your son out there and he'd thrown 3,000-plus pitches and averaged
115-plus pitches a game and his career is on the line and you
panicked and pitched him too soon and hurt him, I don't think you
would be too happy. I know I wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense to the scouts who have reported that Martinez has
pitched tired in the second half of the season. Makes sense to
Indians manager Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know their reasons,'' Hargrove said, ``but I do know
Jimy Williams is a good baseball man and knows his club very well.
For Jimy to say that, he's got a very, very good reason for it. He
knows his club better than any of the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense to Duquette, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy's looking forward to a great start from Saberhagen,''
Duquette said of the 34-year-old righthander who as a 21-year-old
in 1985 won the seventh game of the World Series the day after
celebrating the birth of his first son, Drew, and this season is
2-0 against the Indians, allowing just a run in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy's anticipating the team will be up, 2-1,'' Duquette said,
``and in a position to clinch the outcome on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, the lefthander who arrived almost as an afterthought
in August, when everybody else the Red Sox auditioned as a
bottom-of-the-rotation starter had flamed out, said he appreciated
Williams's show of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the confidence,'' said Schourek, who resembles
``Seinfeld's'' Kramer but for reasons he can't explain has been
called ``Yogi Bear'' by Martinez ever since he beat Tampa Bay 10
days ago for his first win with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he is thinking,'' Schourek said of
Williams's insistence that Martinez will not go again unless there
is a Game 5. ``Obviously, I'm not a No. 1, but I give us a chance
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of elbow problems that have plagued him the last three
years, Schourek no longer is a No. 1. But he was the ace of the
Reds in 1995 when they went to the National League playoffs, and he
faced much greater uncertainty before his first postseason start
that year than he does now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in LA to play the Dodgers, and on the eve of that
series, they were expecting a verdict in the first O.J. (Simpson)
trial,'' he said. ``They were going to cancel the game if it didn't
go the way it did, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to get any big crowds of people, obviously.
So I had that anxiety, on top of getting mentally prepared for my
first postseason game ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek was equal to the task. He beat the Dodgers, 7-2, then
went on to face the Braves in the NL Championship Series, giving up
a total of two runs in two no-decisions against Atlanta, where
Williams was third base coach at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it goes back to the way I pitched against the Braves,''
Schourek said. ``Maybe he saw what I did under pressure, that I
didn't rattle.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Williams just wishes people would put first things
first. And that means Saberhagen. Martinez may be Boston's
wealthiest player, but he's not the club's only money pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about Saberhagen,'' Williams said. ``We will go
as long with him as it takes for us to win that baseball game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
