<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5261 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      10-01 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS EMBRACE PLAN TO COUNTER REPUBLICAN WATERGATE-STYLE
IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After weeks of disunity, Democrats on the House
Judiciary Committee late Thursday embraced a plan to counter the
Republican proposal for a broad, Watergate-style impeachment
inquiry of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Officials familiar with a 3-hour closed door meeting between
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and Democratic committee members said
the alternative would limit the Republican-controlled committee's
inquiry to allegations against Clinton contained in the Starr
report and whether they amount to impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Kenneth Starr last month delivered to
Congress a report alleging that Clinton committed perjury,
obstructed justice, tampered with witnesses and abused the power of
his office by trying to cover up his affair with Monica Lewinsky
during the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit and, later, during
an eight-month grand jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal pushed by Gephardt, D-Mo., the Judiciary
Committee would have until Nov. 25 _ Thanksgiving eve _ to hold
hearings and determine whether the allegations rise to the level
the founding fathers intended when they gave Congress the power to
remove the president for ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   If the panel decides the allegations meet that standard, then a
full impeachment investigation could be launched, said the
officials who agreed to discuss the Democratic alternative only on
the condition they remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal, to be unveiled today, was drafted by
Reps. Jerrold Nadler, of New York, and Rick Boucher and Bobby
Scott, both of Virginia. They were recruited by Gephardt to come up
with a plan to quell dissension among Democratic committee members,
who had been unable to reach consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something the rank-and-file Democrats can support without
being accused by their re-election opponents that they ignored
Starr's evidence against the president,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Democrats propose, it faces almost certain
rejection next week when the Judiciary Committee considers whether
to ask the House to launch the first impeachment inquiry of a
president in 24 years. The investigation of the Watergate scandal
in 1974 led to President Nixon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is to vote Monday or Tuesday on a
resolution of inquiry that mirrors the one used to begin the
investigation of President Nixon. As proposed by committee Chairman
Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican, the resolution would allow a
broad, open-ended investigation while giving Democrats equal
authority to subpoena witnesses. If approved, the resolution faces
a vote by the full House on Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cannot be a never-ending fishing expedition,'' complained
Rep. John Conyers, the committee's top-ranking Democrat before the
meeting with Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers, D-Michigan, said that following the course proposed by
the Republicans ``would only mire the country into a protracted and
partisan inquiry which could last for years and drag down the
country in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want the committee to have the time and authority to
examine other scandals touching on Clinton and the White House,
including campaign finance abuses, the Whitewater land deal, FBI
file misuse and White House travel office controversies. Except for
campaign fund raising, these topics already have been investigated
by Starr, who did not include them in his Sept. 9 report to
Congress on the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be irresponsible for us to establish arbitrary limits
on the inquiry,'' said Rep. Charles Canady, a Florida Republican on
the committee. ``I have a growing suspicion that no matter what we
do ... (the Democrats) will criticize it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats hammered out their alternative to Republican plans
for a broad impeachment inquiry, the president was trying to shore
up support in Congress by promoting his plan to hire more teachers
and build more schools.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 Democrats, many of whom had been critical of Clinton's
personal behavior, showed up at the White House to throw their
support behind his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that Congress was spending too much time on possible
impeachment proceedings, Clinton urged lawmakers to focus on more
important subjects. ``No issue has suffered more from misplaced
priorities and partisan pursuits than America's public schools,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending the Rose Garden ceremony was Rep. Gene
Green, D-Texas. Green said that while he does not condone Clinton's
behavior in the Lewinsky affair, he would continue to back many of
the president's policies and goals, especially his call for more
funding to help improve schools and reduce class size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I vote with the White House about 75 or 80 percent of the
time. We have some differences, but I'll work with (the president)
on issues that are important to my area,'' Green said. ``But I'm
not going to defend the president's behavior. He can't defend it
himself, so why should I.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter Greg McDonald contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
