<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAVISTAR-COX     10-01 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVISTAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNION AND NAVISTAR OFFICIALS REACH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT
 &HT;    By Don Baker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD - After about 19 hours of non-stop negotiations that
stretched six
</P>
<P>
   hours past a strike deadline, union and Navistar officials
reached a tentative
</P>
<P>
   agreement Thursday morning for a new labor contract at the
company's
</P>
<P>
   Springfield truck processing center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the agreement,'' said Steve Shelton, United
Auto Workers
</P>
<P>
   International representative from the Dayton regional office.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Rosswurm, Navistar spokeswoman in Springfield, said the
company also
</P>
<P>
   was happy a tentative agreement was reached, but she declined to
discuss
</P>
<P>
   details of the five-year pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's the best agreement we could reach under the
circumstances,''
</P>
<P>
   said Charlie Bush, UAW Local 402 president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a ratification vote has been set for 9 a.m. Sunday to
allow the 140
</P>
<P>
   or so workers his local represents at the processing center to
decide on final
</P>
<P>
   acceptance of the agreement. Tim Marshall, UAW Local 658
president, said a
</P>
<P>
   ratification vote has not yet been set for the 10 workers his
local represents
</P>
<P>
   at the processing center.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the two UAW locals had given union leaders permission
to strike
</P>
<P>
   Navistar's truck sales processing center if contract talks
failed. A strike
</P>
<P>
   deadline was set for midnight Wednesday by the UAW Local 402 and
Local 658.
</P>
<P>
   Both contracts expired Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Local 658 represents the center's office workers and Local 402
represents the
</P>
<P>
   production and maintenance workers. The center's workers bargain
separately
</P>
<P>
   from the main workforce at the assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said formal negotiations begain in August and worked
through local
</P>
<P>
   grievance issues before moving the discussions to non-economic
issues on Sept.
</P>
<P>
   1. Those non-economic issues were agreed to before the two sides
began
</P>
<P>
   discussing the economic aspects of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we were hung up on for a while; we'd move a penny
one way and
</P>
<P>
   then a penny the other,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   After talks hung up on economic issues late Wednesday night, the
strike
</P>
<P>
   deadline came and passed. ``We extended talks until 6 a.m. and
we got an
</P>
<P>
   agreement at about five till six,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides remained at the bargaining table into the early
morning
</P>
<P>
   hours, third-shift workers at the processing center were on
alert to leave if
</P>
<P>
   talks broke down, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the company held firm on its positions
until beginning
</P>
<P>
   to show some flexibility late into the negotiations, helping an
agreement to
</P>
<P>
   be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the company was firm on their positions, they were also
helpful and
</P>
<P>
   moved to make the agreement possible,'' Shelton said. ``It's a
nice financial
</P>
<P>
   package with a lot of gains. In exchange, the company got some
work rule
</P>
<P>
   amendments.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the workers at the processing center are skilled
trade diesel
</P>
<P>
   mechanics, Shelton said. The deal struck early Thursday will
keep those
</P>
<P>
   workers the highest paid in their field in the area and with the
best
</P>
<P>
   benefits, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The truck sales processing center is located next to Navistar's
truck
</P>
<P>
   assembly plant on U.S. Route 68, but is a separate operation
from that plant.
</P>
<P>
   The center is used for the customizing of Navistar's trucks,
with workers
</P>
<P>
   adding special features requested by customers.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the processing center went on strike for nearly three
weeks in
</P>
<P>
   1985. During that time, the union claimed the company used
``union-busting''
</P>
<P>
   techniques by bringing in temporary employees to work at the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
