<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU'S WILLIAMS PROVING HIS WORTH AT FULLBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU fullback Lance Williams remembered the
hurt about midway through the third quarter of Saturday night's
game against Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   He also recalled his vow.
</P>
<P>
   After watching helplessly on the sidelines two weeks earlier as
the Horned Frogs faltered during the waning moments of a 10-9 loss
against Oklahoma, he promised to make a difference in a close
situation the next time the opportunity arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when we got to that third quarter and had fallen behind, I
was like `here we go again,'' he said. ``Something in me just
sparked and made me kind of come on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs were able to rally from an 11-point deficit and snag a
35-34 stunning victory largely behind Williams' effort on offense.
Time and again the 6-foot-1, 228-pound senior leveled penetrating
Air Force tacklers to spring tailback LaDainian Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   He even displayed his worth as a rusher, stumbling then rumbling
13 yards for a touchdown in the third quarter, which helped pull
the Frogs within 31-28 with 6 minutes, 5 seconds left in the
quarter. Williams, who in one game eclipsed his 18 rushing yards in
1997, finished with 49 yards on the ground and 15 knockdown blocks
on the day.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione deemed Williams the game's unsung
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really came through in a big way,'' said Franchione, whose
2-1 Frogs take on Vanderbilt tomorrow at Amon Carter Stadium.
``Lance made some big plays for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But before Saturday night, Williams wasn't even a starter in the
Frogs' backfield after splitting time at fullback the past two
seasons. Williams and fellow senior Lou Porch were demoted during
two-a-days in favor of the smaller Tomlinson, who was moved from
tailback.
</P>
<P>
   In Franchione's offense, the fullback blocks according to the
reads defenses give them. Williams and Porch had become accustomed
to the isolation blocks on the linebackers, which were required in
the old offense. As a result, both natural fullbacks sat as
Tomlinson attempted to grow into the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt me real bad coming into my last year,'' said Williams,
a former All-State fullback in Georgia. ``But I talked with my
parents and my older brother about it, and they helped me to
continue to just fight for my job.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing special teams in the season opener at Iowa State,
Williams was put in at fullback on four snaps against Oklahoma. He
proved to the coaching staff during that brief appearance he was
ready to reclaim his starting role. On one particular play, he
unleashed a block, which sprung tailback Basil Mitchell for what
would have been a long touchdown were it not for an out-of-bounds
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think those four snaps contributed to the fact
they made me the starting fullback,'' said Williams, who has gained
59 yards and one touchdown on 13 carries this season. ``I just
wanted to prove to the coaching staff that they could count on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione now says when he moved Tomlinson up and Williams and
Porch out, it was only done as a temporary fix. He said the plan
all along was to get Williams and Porch comfortable and put
Tomlinson back at his more natural tailback spot.
</P>
<P>
   The move appeared timely on Saturday, as the Frogs were able to
put a fresh tailback in the game once Mitchell wore down. The
result: A 99-yard, two-touchdown rushing day for Tomlinson and 256
team rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it did was keep two fresh tailbacks in the game,''
Franchione said. ``And that really strengthens our team and the
things we can do late in the game on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   For Williams it serves as a reprieve as he begins to distance
himself from his recent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, you feel like they should have believed in you from
the beginning,'' Williams said. ``But I kind of wanted to prove
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt all along I was the man for the job, but obviously I
hadn't shown that to the coaches. Now, I just have to make the best
of this opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
