<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSPAN DEFENDS ROLE OF FED TO SAVE HEDGE FUND
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, defended the
central bank's role in averting the collapse of Long-Term Capital
Management, saying it had acted out of concern for the stability of
the financial markets rather than a desire to assist the hedge
firm's owners.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the House Banking Committee, Greenspan said it was
the central bank's responsibility to play a role in addressing a
crisis whose effects could extend far beyond the fate of Long-Term
Capital's owners, investors and lenders.
</P>
<P>
   IMF IS RECEIVING HARSH CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   At the annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank begins, the harshest criticisms are being directed at
the monetary fund and the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN CALLS FOR FISCAL OPENNESS
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said the United States would
press for ``a new openness in international finance'' that would
require private financial institutions to disclose far more
information about their loans around the world and force investors
to pay their share of the cost of bailing out troubled nations.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE TO DEVELOP IMPOTENCE DRUG
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Icos rose $1.625, or 9.15 percent, to $19.375, after
the biotechnology company and Eli Lilly said they would form a
joint venture to develop and sell an impotence drug that some
evidence suggests could be superior to Pfizer's successful Viagra.
The two companies will share the marketing and sales of the drug in
North America and Europe and split the profits 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DECLINE SHARPLY IN EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   European stock markets plunged, as investors across the
Continent seemed to conclude that they are no longer insulated from
the economic crises rocking other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   BOND YIELDS DECLINE TO 4.88 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices surged, and the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond fell to 4.88 percent from the previous 31-year low of 4.97
percent set on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER SALES SOARED LAST MONTH
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Chrysler cars and trucks increased 18 percent in
September compared with a weak month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   EXPORTS SLUMPED IN SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing weakened in the United States in September for a
fourth consecutive month, as exports slumped, while prices paid by
industrial companies fell to the lowest level in almost half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs DROPPING BENEFICIARIES
</P>
<P>
   Health maintenance organizations said they would drop tens of
thousands of beneficiaries next year, in part because the
government has not let them raise premiums or cut prescription drug
coverage for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   GLOOM GAINS IN JAPANESE COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese central bank's quarterly survey of corporate
sentiment showed that morale had sunk to the lowest level in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND RECOVERS FROM ITS TROUBLES
</P>
<P>
   When Russia went into a tailspin earlier this year, Poland's
stock market crashed. Investors pulled $1 billion in short-term
capital out of the country and prepared for Poland to descend into
the maelstrom. But the panic has receded and Poland is moving
forward. Although the Poland stock market fell Thursday, it is up
4.8 percent over the last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
