r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     10-01 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN TEE-HEE AND HAR-HAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest issue of the laugh-packed Weight Watchers magazine
reports that 90 percent of the members of the Three Stooges Fan
Club are men.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, after studying 2,000 casual conversations at
shopping malls, cocktail parties and restaurants, researchers at
the University of Maryland determined that both men and women laugh
more when talking to men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have something to do with power relationships,'' said
psychologist  &UR; Robert Provine &LR; , ``or women's desire to ease social
tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VOTE TO BAN DANES MOVIES IN MANILA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After the publication of two interviews in which 19-year-old
 &UR; Claire Danes &LR;  said unkind things about Manila, the city council
voted 23-3 this week to ban her movies, ``Romeo and Juliet'' and
``The Rainmaker'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   Danes, who had spent some time in Manila shooting ``Brokedown
Palace,'' told Vogue that it was a ``ghastly and weird city'';
those remarks, published in April, caused no furor.
</P>
<P>
   An interview in the latest issue of Premiere, however, was more
controversial. Manila ``smelled like cockroaches,'' she said, and
the residents are ``people with, like, no arms, no legs, no eyes,
no teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot accept irresponsible sweeping statements from
irresponsible actresses,'' said council member  &UR; Kim Atienza &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``This resolution is in fact abridging her rights,'' said
opposing city council member  &UR; Julio &LR;   &UR; Logarta &LR; . ``Most of what she
said is true.'' Logarta doubted that the council has the authority
to enforce a ban.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Douglas &LR; ' publicist confirmed to the New York Post
that the actor was the date of columnist  &UR; Maureen Dowd &LR;  at a
wedding anniversary party for  &UR; Art Garfunkel &LR; . ``They're friends,
and that's that,'' said  &UR; Allen Burry &LR; . ``I don't think it's the
love affair of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Gymtonic,'' a new song by French disc jockey  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Sinclair &LR; , samples pieces of  &UR; Jane Fonda &LR; 's exercise video
instructions, &LR;  and sets them to a booming disco beat. When the song
was played in New York at a Webster Hall dance party, the revelers
did aerobics to it. Royalties go to the Jane Fonda Cancer
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Kate Brandt &LR;  and  &UR; Paula Lichtenberg &LR;  were captivated by the
pairing of bumperstickers that read ``Porn Star'' and ``Yes, Lord,
We Will Ride With You.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Ladies Home Journal has named  &UR; Princess Diana &LR;  one of the
100 Most Important Women of the 20th Century. Meanwhile,  &UR; Will &LR; 
 &UR; Carling &LR; , the now-divorced soccer star who has revealed himself to
have been another one of Diana's gentleman callers, said this week
that the princess had urged him to leave his wife. In remarks
quoted in the Detroit Free Press, he also said that Diana thought
 &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton &LR;  ``overambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL THE REAL REPORTERS PLEASE STAND UP? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Former ``60 Minutes'' producer  &UR; Barry Lando &LR;  criticizes the
program, in the latest issue of Brill's Content, complaining that
producers do all the work while correspondents feign having
reported the stories, including faking surprise at interview
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think that the show that prides itself on revealing
hypocrisy and cant, on uncovering deceptions, would be all for
truth in packaging when it comes to itself. It's not,'' writes
Lando.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer  &UR; Don Hewitt &LR;  says that producers are
well-credited, and adds details about how much he doesn't like
Lando.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even my publisher, Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, an independent
publisher, considered Old World and cultured _ which means they
don't pay much _ was bought by a big German firm. I asked the
president. I said, `I'm not saying anything, but did you check
whose side they were on in the war? I mean just check.' ... People,
particularly in books and magazines, work for four or five people,
and none of them are really the people you'd want to work for when
it got right down to it. And it's become more and more like that
.... practically every industry is that way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Calvin Trillin in the new magazine Madison.
</P>
</TEXT>
