<HEADLINE>
FAMILY AFFAIR FOR THE SABERHAGENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston's Game 3 starter Brett Saberhagen will share the
field at Fenway Park today with his wife, Lynn, who will sing the
national anthem before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be more nervous for her than for me,''
Saberhagen said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Mrs. Saberhagen might have had the better season.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never got booed,'' Saberhagen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will tap into their history for the rest of the
pregame ceremonies. The ceremonial opening pitches will be thrown
out by Boston hitting coach and former left-field star Jim Rice and
by former Red Sox third baseman Frank Malzone. &QL; 
DEJA VU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a postseason baseball game played at Fenway
Park since Oct. 6, 1995. That was Game 3 of one of that year's
American League Division Series, and the Red Sox opponents then,
like today, were the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The starter for the Indians that day was Charles Nagy, who goes
again for Cleveland this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians won that game, 8-2, driving Boston starter Tim
Wakefield from the mound in the sixth inning when Cleveland scored
five times, building its lead to 8-1. Nagy was solid, yielding just
one run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave Cleveland, which had won the first two games of
the series at home, a 3-0 sweep and a spot in the American League
Championship Series. The Indians defeated the Seattle Mariners in
the ALCS before losing to the Atlanta Braves in the World Series. &QL; 
SHADY DEALINGS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The starting time for Game 3 is just after 4 p.m., and a topic
of discussion yesterday was whether the shadows that move across
the area between home plate and the pitching mound in the late
afternoon would adversely affect batters' ability to see the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Some players and Red Sox manager Jimy Williams agreed a
light-to-shadow pitch could be hard to pick out because hitters
might not be able to distinguish the rotation of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday afternoon, however, the shadows across the field had
covered both the mound and plate by 4 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
