s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-LEXUS-TOYO     10-01 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-LEXUS-TOYOTA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 TOYOTA LAND CRUISER AND LEXUS 470: ONE READY FOR THE WOODS;
THE OTHER, THE COUNTRY CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did conspicuous consumption disappear with the 1980s? Not where
large, expensive sport utilities are concerned. It seems that the
bigger and more expensive the luxury sport utility, the better it
sells.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Lexus LX 470 and its virtually identical cousin,
the Toyota Land Cruiser. Both of these full-sized sport utilities,
priced from almost $47,000 to almost $59,000, were redesigned for
the 1998 model year and introduced in April. They are unchanged for
the 1999 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the pricier LX 470 have unexpectedly exceeded those of
the Land Cruiser in some months this year, but the Land Cruiser is
expected to close the year ahead of its cousin. Lexus is
constrained in the number of LX 470s it can build because of
limited availability of suspension components.
</P>
<P>
   This comes at a time of unprecedented choices for the seemingly
limited pool of consumers who can afford these vehicles. Still
leading the charge is the wildly successful Lincoln Navigator,
introduced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. has an even bigger sport utility in the
works. Cadillac will soon introduce the Escalade, based on the
Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon. Last spring GMC added an even more
luxurious version of its Yukon, the Denali. The Chevrolet and GMC
Suburban remains a perennial favorite and the Range Rover _ the
granddaddy of pricey utilities _ is holding its own.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the phenomenal growth of the North American sport
utility market shows no signs of slowing, and the subsegment of the
large, expensive, gas-guzzling types is demonstrating the most
rapid rise in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus introduced its first sport utility, the LX 450, in 1996 to
keep its car buyers from moving into Range Rovers, Jeep Grand
Cherokees and Suburbans. Based on the highly regarded Toyota Land
Cruiser, the LX 450 added a formal grille and Lexus badging
outside, butter-soft leather upholstery and rich wood trim inside,
some additional equipment and $7,000 to the price tag.
</P>
<P>
   The formula remains largely the same this time around. The LX
470 _ the name change from the 450 connotes the more powerful
4.7-liter V8 engine _ and the new Land Cruiser still share the same
basic architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The two are by no means the biggest sport utilities available;
those honors go to the Chevrolet and GMC Suburban. Even the
gargantuan Lincoln Navigator is a foot longer than the LX 470 and
Land Cruiser. The Toyota sport utilities also are shorter than the
Cadillac Escalade, though Toyota has managed to add a third-row
seat that Cadillac did not.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the Navigator and its bold, chrome-laden grille,
the styling of the LX 470 and the Land Cruiser is understated.
Their lines have been softened from those on the previous
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable distinctions between the two is the LX 470s
four-beam projector headlights, its side body cladding and running
boards that match the body color.
</P>
<P>
   Both have a high step into the cabin, but the LX 470 has an
adjustable height control that the Land Cruiser does not. The
system lowers the vehicle for easier entry, raises it for off-road
driving or levels it for highway cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, both the LX 470 and the Land Cruiser are roomy and
comfortable. The LX 470 comes standard with a third-row seat,
providing reasonably comfortable accommodations for up to eight
people. The third seat costs an extra $1,135 in the Land Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   It is removable in both vehicles, though it is a two-person job.
If you don't want to remove the seat but need extra room, the seat
splits and the halves fold sideways out of the way. The second-row
seats also fold and tilt forward for more cargo-carrying
capability.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in interior ambiance between the base Land
Cruiser and the LX 470 is like that between the Toyota Camry and
Lexus ES 300. Both have all the comfort and convenience you need
but one provides more luxurious flair.
</P>
<P>
   The LX 470 comes standard with creamy leather and elegant
touches of genuine walnut wood trim; leather in the Land Cruiser is
a $1,820 option. The Land Cruiser's instrument panel layout of
rotary knobs and buttons is typical of a Toyota. Controls are
logically placed, easy to operate and highly readable.
</P>
<P>
   The LX 470s instrument panel, equally functional, has the same
holographic feel as that of the flagship LS 400 luxury sedan and is
stunning at night.
</P>
<P>
   Both sport utilities are well-equipped with standard cruise
control, three power outlets, power windows and locks and reclining
second-row seats. The Land Cruiser is available with five major
options _ rear air-conditioner, locking rear differential, leather,
power moonroof and the third seat _ which, in total, add $5,000 to
the nearly $47,000 price tag.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The LX 470, at $56,400, comes with virtually every standard
feature imaginable, some of which are not available on the Land
Cruiser. The only options are the power moonroof at $1,270 and the
Nakamichi premium audio system at $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   The most innovative feature in the LX 470 is the in-dash compact
disk player that requires no CD changer. The player swallows up to
six CDs, fed one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features in the LX 470 but not in the Land
Cruiser include: power tilt and telescope memory steering column;
memory for driver's seat and mirrors; rear-seat automatic climate
control; Homelink garage and security gate opener, and self-dimming
inside and outside mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   As for safety features, both of the sport utilities come with
standard dual front air bags, anti-lock brakes, daytime running
lights and pretensioning seat belts. Neither vehicle is equipped
with side air bags.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change in the LX 470 and Land Cruiser from the
models they replace is under the hood. Their predecessors had been
accused of being overpriced and underpowered with their V6 engines.
</P>
<P>
   Both now are powered by a sophisticated and refined 4.7-liter
dual overhead-cam V8 engine, a derivative of the LS 400's engine.
It produces 230 horsepower and 320 foot-pounds of torque and is
mated to an electronic four-speed automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities don't take top honors in horsepower _ the 1999
Navigator packs a whopping 300. Still, the Toyota utilities run
strong, smooth and silent.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Land Cruiser and the LX 470, in particular, ride
and handle like significantly smaller vehicles than their domestic
competitors. But a test drive revealed a subtle difference in ride
and handling between the two. The LX 470 is outfitted with its own
suspension system, which is more sophisticated than that of the
Land Cruiser and provides a ride more in the vein of a luxury
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to northern Michigan, the tested LX 470 glided over
the state's notoriously rough pavement without notice. The pleasant
ride is reminiscent of the riding-on-a-cloud feeling of the LS 400
sedan. Even more impressive is the braking capability of the LX 470
and Land Cruiser. At more than 5,000 pounds, the two nearly match
the braking of many 3,500-pound domestic sedans in testing by
automotive enthusiast magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The two vehicles also meet California's stringent low-emission
standards, but both are gas hogs. Fuel economy _ an oxymoron in
this instance _ is about 13 miles a gallon in the city and 16 on
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Both the LX 470 and Land Cruiser, with its long history of
traversing the African deserts, are extremely capable off-road.
Each comes only with full-time four-wheel-drive; a low range is
engaged by shifting a lever next to the transmission shifter.
</P>
<P>
   The Land Cruiser, with its more adventurous buyers, is more
likely to explore off-road; still, the Lexus plowed through a foot
of snow on an unpaved road without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   The LX 470's extras come at a premium. While the Land Cruiser
carries a base price of $46,898 (easily climbing to nearly $52,000
with all of the goodies), the Lexus starts at $56,400 and climbs to
$58,870 fully loaded, making it the second-most-expensive sport
utility, behind the Range Rover at about $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   The added features, the ultra-refined suspension, the exclusive
Lexus nameplate and the pampering Lexus ownership experience are
worth an extra $6,000 or so, aren't they? If one is consuming, why
not do it conspicuously? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Very refined, very expensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
