<HEADLINE>
COMEBACKERS SABERHAGEN, NAGY FACE KEY TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bret Saberhagen and Charles Nagy, Game 3 starters in
the Boston-Cleveland American League Division Series, each have had
their share of setbacks over the course of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen's have been all physical. Nagy's, his critics
suggest, mostly mental.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both have displayed the grit necessary to mount comebacks.
Saberhagen overcame numerous injuries plus major surgery to his
right shoulder to post a 15-8 record for the Red Sox this season,
leading them to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy also won 15 games and was especially strong after the
All-Star Break. However, he had to overcome the stigma of being
bypassed as the Game 7 starter in last year's World Series, and
surrendering the hit that cost the Indians the world championship.
He also had an alarmingly poor first half this season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Saberhagen and Nagy have been given the responsibility of
starting a game that would give its winner a stranglehold on this
deadlocked division series, and the loser a noose. Statistically,
both appear equipped to do the job: Nagy is 6-1 in his career
against the Red Sox; Saberhagen was 2-0 against Cleveland this
season.
</P>
<P>
   For Saberhagen, who won two games in the World Series for Kansas
City in 1985, leading the Royals to the title, this year's return
to prominence represents the capper to his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to get back to what I once was,'' he said
yesterday, ``and to contribute in the postseason and get another
World Series ring. Nothing beats it.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, Boston manager Jimy Williams said, is ``a very
strong-hearted individual that went through a very difficult
operation to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen signed with the Red Sox as a minor-league free agent
in December 1996, after missing the entire season after shoulder
surgery in May when he was property of the Colorado Rockies. He
pitched briefly last year in the minors and with Boston, then came
to spring training this season as nothing more than a possible
fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really weren't sure what we were going to get,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Saberhagen said, he's not much different than
in his glory days with the Royals and, later, with the New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The control is (still) there,'' he said. ``I don't throw 95 or
96, but I throw 93-94. I am happy the quality is there and I am not
just an average pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagy was far less than average for much of his season. He was
winless from June 5 through July 17, going 0-4 with a 5.72
earned-run average. Even with his 3-1 September, he finished with a
5.22 ERA. His 34 home runs allowed ranked third worst in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of the year I fell into some bad habits,''
said Nagy, not elaborating. ``We went back and looked at some tapes
and saw some things that I wasn't doing in the previous year. I
just made the adjustments and it seems to have helped.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his trying World Series experience last year, Nagy said
it no longer bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time ago. I've put it behind me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a pivotal game before them, Saberhagen and Nagy know that
whoever writes the best comeback story today could be in the
American League Championship Series next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
