<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     10-01 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THIS DARRYL IS ALREADY A SURVIVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBA-STRAWBERRY-CANCER.) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ ``Hey, Skip.''
</P>
<P>
   This was behind the batting cage at noon on a Sunday in
Montreal, during the pennant race of September 1984, back when the
Mets were young, when Darryl Strawberry was going to hit 1,000 home
runs and help the Mets win 10 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry and Davey Johnson went off in a corner and had a
terse little conversation, and pretty soon Strawberry was out of
the lineup, not up to playing so soon after whatever he had been
doing on Saturday night. I remember one of the Mets' coaches
banging his fungo bat against the batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   That was a Darryl Strawberry who could not look anybody in the
eye, who offered a limp handshake, and very often a limp
explanation for things that had gone wrong. That was a Darryl
Strawberry who nearly wrecked his life and other lives, through
drugs and alcohol and other diversions, to avoid facing the world
and himself in any sober way.
</P>
<P>
   We never really know how anybody will react to misfortune, but
it is reasonable to assume this was not a man who could have faced
terrible news with clarity and discipline. Then again, that was not
the same Darryl Strawberry who found out Thursday that he must have
an operation for colon cancer, perhaps as soon as tomorrow. This
Darryl Strawberry is not only physically straight but also mentally
and spiritually straight.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, in another baseball season, Darryl
Strawberry is now a Yankee, a survivor. Thursday, Joe Torre
recalled two meetings in 1996: ``Darryl came to us after the
All-Star break and obviously he brought a lot of baggage, but I
judge people on what I see, and he said he'd do anything for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the playoff series with the Texas Rangers, I was trying
to decide whether to play him or Big Daddy,'' Torre said, referring
to Cecil Fielder. ``Darryl said: `I can handle sitting. Why don't
you play Big Daddy?'''
</P>
<P>
   This was not some furtive bailout by the troubled man of an
earlier time. This was the alert decision by a grown-up, a player
who wanted to take the pressure off his manager.
</P>
<P>
   At some time, in one of those treatment centers, Darryl
Strawberry accepted that he had come close to going to jail, that
perhaps his second marriage and his life itself would not survive,
unless he stayed sober day by day.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in New York, who felt personally let down by
Strawberry, as if he had cost them money, would make condescending
comments about him. They did not want to know of his renewal, which
was real and tangible, up close.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he was still the same Straw _ the vile odor of his furtive
cigarette stinking out a tiny corner of the clubhouse, the bulging
chaw inside his cheek (tobacco is indeed a potent addiction), the
salty talk, the street wisdom. But Darryl was clean now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have different personalities, but I'm as close to him as
anybody in the clubhouse,'' Bernie Williams said Thursday. ``He's a
guy you can relate to. He's so down to earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Homer Bush, the earnest rookie, Thursday recalled joining the
Yankees in 1997, the same day Strawberry returned from a brief
training stint in the minor leagues. ``He talked to me, he told me
he liked the way I played, he said I was going to have a good
career,'' Bush said. ``He gave me advice.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the advice he gave, Strawberry suppressed the lesson of
his childhood friend, Eric Davis, who underwent an operation for
colon cancer last year and came back to play for the Orioles in the
playoffs. Davis has been preaching regular checkups, but Strawberry
ignored the pain in his intestines.
</P>
<P>
   After all his tax troubles, he needs every paycheck, every next
bonus phase in his contract, so he waited for the pain to subside
until finally he had to consult a doctor this week. In their shock
Thursday, the Yankees said that they hoped he had sought treatment
in time.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees looked stricken as they trudged out to a spiritless
workout. Tears rimmed the eyes of players who gave interviews.
Torre said this was not something one would wish ``on your worst
enemy.'' Nobody tried to sugarcoat this dreadful blow to their
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a good person,'' said David Cone, Friday
night's starting pitcher, who knows Strawberry from the wild Met
days. ``He's made his mistakes, we all have, but he's turned it
around. He's a team leader. We're all optimistic he has the
strength to beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   This may not be much consolation, but this horrible thing has
happened to a man whose strength will be even more of a blessing
than he could have known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
