<HEADER>
A5354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERR     10-01 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY HAS COLON CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A dark cloud settled over the New York
Yankees Thursday, and it had nothing to do with the American League
playoffs. After arriving here, the Eastern Division champions
discovered that teammate Darryl Strawberry has colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Still numb from the news _ which was relayed from Strawberry in
New York to pitcher Andy Pettitte to manager Joe Torre and then to
the entire team _ Yankee players filed out of their clubhouse at
The Ballpark in Arlington with sad faces. Some shed tears.
</P>
<P>
   But they set aside their emotions for a show of solidarity. At
the start of Thursday night's first ESPN ``SportsCenter'' telecast,
they gathered as a team behind sportscaster Harold Reynolds and
collectively wished Strawberry the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping that Darryl was watching,'' veteran outfielder
Tim Raines said. ``We wanted him to know the whole team was behind
him. We had spoken to Darryl earlier and he didn't want to let
anybody think it was worse than it was. That's the Darryl that we
all know. He wants us to support him. And one of the ways we can do
that is go out and play well in these games.''
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing his second series of tests in as many days at
New York's Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center, Strawberry
received the diagnosis. A colonoscopy revealed a maglinant turmor
in his colon about the size of a walnut, and the 36-year-old
outfielder-DH will undergo surgery at Columbia perhaps as early as
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook is encouraging: ``Because of the location (of the
tumor) and his good health, prognosis for a full recovery is
excellent,'' said Yankees spokesman Rick Cerrone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was deep concern on the part of his colleagues, for
whom the news overshadowed any enjoyment they may have taken from
winning the first two games of this best-of-five Division Series in
New York, setting up a chance for a sweep tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something you fear when you know your're going in for
tests,'' said Torre. ``The only thing we can do is just pray and
realize that some of the things we think are really important are
sort of insignificant. We know what we have to do. This ball club
has been able to focus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never faced anything this dramatic, although a couple of
years ago, when David Cone went down with the aneurysm (in his
arm), there was a lot going on. But we came to realize we just had
to do something and deal with it. We have a job to do and we're
pulling for each other. I think everybody realizes this is what he
wants us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry had stayed home Wednesday when the Yankees beat the
Rangers, 3-1, because doctors had dsicovered a growth on his colon.
He had been playing with abdominal pain for the last month or so
but had told none of his teammates and had sought no treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But after a trip to Baltimore and a conversation with Eric Davis
_ his lifelong friend, who this year staged a successful comeback
from colon cancer _ Strawberry was jolted into action. Davis had
reminded him that his cancerous condition began with a similar
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's diagnosis ended what had been a triumphal season for
Strawberry, the onetime Mets sensation who had overcome years of
substance abuse, a tax conviction, marital problems, and injuries
to hit 24 homers for a Yankee team that won a league-record 114
games. Those achievements seemed hollow after the news spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it strikes this close to home,'' said Cone, ``it shakes
you up. Reality sets in. You realize what's more important. It's
amazing to me that Darryl was concerned about the team, the welfare
and mind-set of the team. He said he was proud of the team not
because we won 114 games but because of the type of people we have
on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt Darryl has had a lot of turmoil in his life.
But he really was on the right track. He turned it around and was
one of the team leaders, one of the most respected people in our
clubhouse. He has the strength to beat this. Eric Davis did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone added that he knew from personal experience that these can
be difficult times for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you hear about the kind of tests that are being done,
it's scary. These sort of life-and-death situations supersede
baseball in every way. When you look back and see what's happened
to Dan Quisenberry (Cone's ex-teammate with the Kansas City Royals,
who died of brain cancer Wednesday) and his family, it's tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went through my situation, I didn't understand what was
happening to me. I needed to be educated. I didn't know if it was
life-or-death. I didn't know if my career was over. I'm sure Darryl
has those kind of fears. He doesn't know what's going on. It can be
very confusing and very scary. Our hearts are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spoke with Strawberry Thursday morning. He was moved
enough to organize a nationwide press conference to reaffirm his
faith that such a diagnosis doesn't have to be catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encouraged Darryl to have faith in the Lord and to lean on
those who love him the most,'' said Davis. ``The one thing we
should learn from this is that this disease can strike any one of
us at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' reaction did not surprise Torre. He has worked hard
to create a club where everybody feels a part of the family.
Strawberry, a marquee star early in his career, was just one of th
guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of an extended family,'' Torre said. ``Darryl
spends more time with us than he does with his family. My voice
cracked a little when I told the team. There was complete silence,
some sobbing, and some very sad people. You really don't know what
the right thing is to do. It's sure not comfortable. Darryl just
said he was looking to get this over with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, meanwhile, must return their attention to the task
at hand _ tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is down right now,'' said Joe Girardi. ``But we all
understand he wouldn't want the team to wear their hearts on their
sleeves. We just go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Petitte, ``He wanted to let everybody know how proud he was
to be a part of this team. We truly respect each other. He said,
`Pray for me.' That's what we plan to do. He assured us that he
would be fine and get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone said he would wear Strawberry's number 39 on the back of
his cap tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's no cheap motivational (ploy),'' he said. ``It just
means I'm going to be ready. I can't say how I will go about it,
but I'll be ready.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
