<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5355 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-ASTROS-TEX     10-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS TIE SERIES WITH 5-4 VICTORY AGAINST PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Ricky Gutierrez may not be fast, just fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome was shocked and deflated after San Diego Padres
pinch hitter Jim Leyritz's two-out, two-strike, two-run homer tied
the score in the top of the ninth inning. But Gutierrez used his
sneaky speed to eventually score the winning run on Bill Spiers'
single in the Houston Astros' dramatic 5-4 victory yesterday that
knotted their National League Division Series at a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the fastest guy we have,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said of Gutierrez. ``But I guess he's fast enough, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   After closer Billy Wagner allowed Leyritz's homer, Gutierrez
started Houston's ninth by beating out a chopper to shortstop for
an infield single. Leyritz dropped Brad Ausmus' foul bunt on a
diving attempt _ ``I overdove,'' Leyritz said. Gutierrez, however,
moved to second as Ausmus got the sacrifice down. Then, after the
Padres brought in closer Trevor Hoffman, Gutierrez shocked San
Diego, Dierker and the entire Dome by stealing third on the first
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't plan it, but they weren't looking at me even a
little,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   The steal, which didn't even draw a throw, drastically changed
San Diego's strategy. Hoffman intentionally walked Craig Biggio,
attempting to set up an inning-ending double play against Spiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great play on Ricky's part,'' Padres manager Bruce
Bochy said. ``I think he surprised us all. It was disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``It was totally on his own. I'm not smart enough
to even consider something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After swinging feebly at two Hoffman pitches, Spiers poked a
low, 1-2 changeup into right field to plate Gutierrez and give the
Astros their first postseason victory in almost 12 years _ since
Oct. 12, 1986, in Game 4 of the NL Championship Series against the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   This best-of-five series shifts tomorrow to San Diego's Qualcomm
Stadium, where the Padres were 54-27 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get it to the outfield any way I could,''
said Spiers, who besides his game-winning single had two early
doubles to help Houston build a 3-0 lead. ``It wasn't pretty, but I
got enough of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting long-awaited life from its star-studded Killer B's, the
Astros struck early. After an 0-for-10 performance in Game 1
dropped the trio of Biggio-Derek Bell-Jeff Bagwell to 2-for-47 over
two playoffs, they responded yesterday with three hits, three runs
scored and four runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got two hits in eight innings off Kevin Brown in Game
1. They matched that total against Andy Ashby on six pitches.
Biggio started the game with a single up the middle, moved to third
on Spiers' double and scored on Bagwell's groundout to give Houston
its first lead in five playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Houston added two more in the third when Biggio walked, Spiers
again doubled him to third and Bagwell spanked a line-drive single
to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to come through in a pressure game,'' Biggio said.
``The Killer B's thing is nice when we're winning, but I was
thinking about changing my last name if we'd lost this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Shane Reynolds and his dipping splitter rolled
into the sixth inning allowing just one hit. Consecutive hits by
Quilvio Veras, Steve Finley and Tony Gwynn pulled the Padres within
3-2 before Bell's homer in the eighth gave Wagner a two-run
cushion.
</P>
<P>
   After sandwiching a Ken Caminiti infield single around two outs,
Wagner fed Leyritz a steady diet of 99-mph fastballs before his 3-2
offering was lined just inside the right-field fair pole into the
seats to make it 4-4 and set up Houston's league-leading 28th
victory in its last at-bat this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blew my mind that it stayed fair,'' said Wagner, who ended
the inning by striking out pinch hitter George Arias with two
runners on. ``But this team hasn't given up all year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
