<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs: Wood's problem is motion
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen and Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Kerry Wood the probable starter for Game 3
Saturday, the Cubs will stress form over pitch count.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said Wood's doctors, trainers and the
right-handed phenom himself have told him that ``it's not going to
be so much with Kerry a matter of how many pitches he throws, as
much as it's going to be the position of his arm when he's
throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood believes the tenderness in his sore elbow, which caused him
to miss all of September, was caused by a mechanical flaw. Wood
threw 51 pitches Monday in an instructional league game in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels when he throws out of a certain slot that it causes
some problems with him,'' Riggleman said. ``What happens is if you
get tired, you tend to drop your arms in that slot where you can
have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman said the only reason Wood would not start the first
Chicago home game Saturday would be if the Braves are swinging the
bat well against right-handers and he decides to go with Terry
Mulholland, a left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ``Kerry's repertoire is kind of exceptional from
just about everybody else, so that would weigh heavier in our
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Still working
</P>
<P>
   Rookies Marty Malloy, who toiled seven years in the system
before the Braves called him up Sept. 6, and Odalis Perez, who was
chosen instead of World Series veteran Norm Charlton, survived the
cut to the Braves' 25-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   Malloy will be insurance at second base for Keith Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long ride, and it's been a fun ride,'' Malloy
said. ``This is what dreams are made of and something I'll cherish.
Hopefully, I'll get an opportunity to do something to help this
team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, a 20-year-old left-hander who made his major-league debut
Sept. 1, has an 0-1 record and 4.22 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm capable,'' Perez said. ``I am not surprised. In
the 10 times I've been pitching here, I've had one bad outing. The
other nine times, I think I've been doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Special feelings for Atlanta Jeff Blauser, in his first
postseason with a team other than the Braves, said about playing
his former team, ``I don't know if I would call it special. I have
a feeling about playing (here), but they're still the opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortstop, who lives in Alpharetta, pinch-hit in the eighth
inning Wednesday and flew out to left. ``Oh, sure, I would have
liked to have started,'' said Blauser, who was on the DL Aug.
25-Sept. 9 with an elbow irritation, ``but I understand I haven't
started a whole lot over the last month, so it wasn't a surprise.
You still have an opportunity to do something big in the
postseason, come off the bench, like Matt Mieske did (against the
Giants).''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   What looked like a head-butt was really a congratulatory hug
gone awry as Chipper Jones greeted Ryan Klesko at the plate
following Klesko's grand slam. ``I wanted to give him a bear hug,
but he dropped his head and almost knocked out three of my teeth,''
Jones said. ``I'll be better prepared next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
