<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs a veritable bye in opening round
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Doomsday Scenario didn't hit. There will be no Big
Unit in Round 1, no Trevor Hoffman, either. Instead, the Braves get
a fragile opponent with a fried pitching staff. Bobby Cox's
protestations to the contrary, sometimes his team does get lucky.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so there was a bit of skill involved. The Braves swept the
Mets, thereby defusing the division series danger. San Diego
would've been rough, San Diego followed by Houston perhaps
undoable. This way is eminently doable. Now the Astros, the single
greatest threat, have the more perilous trek. Now the Braves can
sit and wait for the dust out West to settle.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs? The Cubs are a veritable bye. The Cubs made the
playoffs only after trying hard not to. They wasted a seven-run
lead in Game No. 158 and a two-run lead in No. 162. They nearly
lost a five-run lead against San Francisco on Monday. In that game
Chicago used three starting pitchers _ a fourth warmed up _ and the
gassed-out Rod Beck, who's now the softest-throwing closer since
Hoyt Wilhelm.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the Cub bullpen, the Braves' relievers look as
impregnable as Fort Knox. In how many postseason series has this
team held an edge there? The way to beat the Braves in the playoffs
is to have your starting pitchers keep it close and then let your
bullpen win it. The Cubs can manage neither.
</P>
<P>
   The heralded Kerry Wood might not work in the series, his prized
arm tired from the strain of so many strikeouts. That leaves the
likes of Kevin Tapani, Steve Trachsel, Mark Clark and Terry
Mulholland. This does not compare to Smoltz-Glavine-Maddux. The
Cubs cannot match pitches with the Braves. Their only hope is for
some wind-blowing-out atrocities in Wrigley, but even there the
Braves catch a break.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the better team has been forced to open on the
road. (Not that it much bothered the Braves, who are 6-0 away in
the division series.) There was always the possibility of immediate
trouble. No more. Baseball has righted that inequity. The Braves
should have two games in the bank by the time they see Chicago,
whereupon the Cubs will go quietly. They've already had their
wild-card party, not to mention the various celebrations involving
Sammy Sosa. Time now for this flawed bunch to go the way of all
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that the Braves are invincible. A strong and
determined opponent can take them. Houston seems such a team, but
Houston must first survive San Diego, which is no lock. And the
Padres, who might have upended the Braves in a best-of-five,
probably don't have the depth of starting pitching to do it in
best-of-seven.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how bleak everything seemed three weeks ago? The Braves
were unraveling, in need of a hoary clubhouse meeting, in danger of
losing the league's best record. Things have changed. The Braves
finished hot. They got a kind draw. It's possible they could reach
the World Series without seeing Houston. This is still not a great
assemblage by Braves standards, those 106 wins notwithstanding, but
it might be good enough. It is way too good to lose to the Cubs.
Braves sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley can be reached at markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
