<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strawberry leaves park before game
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darryl Strawberry left Yankee Stadium before
Wednesday's game and the Yankees are not sure when he is going to
be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said doctors had discovered something the size of ``a
pimple'' on his colon. More tests were planned for today, a travel
day for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   While he is on the active roster for this divisional series
against the Rangers, Strawberry continues to be bothered by
mysterious abdominal pains.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee manager Joe Torre did not disclose what Strawberry told
him about his medical condition. The Yankees did not detail his
condition, either. But Torre did say, ``Cancer always comes to
mind. It's something you're taught to fear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was feeling better,'' said Strawberry, 36. ``Anybody
would be a little concerned because the problem I am having is
inside my body. It's not like a baseball injury or anything. No one
really knows what it is.'' Strawberry played in 101 games this
season, used both as an outfielder and designated hitter and hit
.247 with 24 homers and 57 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   An awesome Wells
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's John Smoltz may be considered the game's most
productive postseason pitcher, but Yankees left-hander David Wells
is not far behind. After his win Tuesday night, Wells is now 5-0 in
the postseason and has a string of 15 consecutive scoreless
innings. Smoltz is 11-3 in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Bomber talk
</P>
<P>
   Yankees general manager Brian Cashman is awaiting the birth of
his first child, which could come any time. Will Cashman be able to
travel with the club this weekend to Texas? ``If the doctor says it
could happen this weekend, I will have to talk to the Boss (George
Steinbrenner),'' he said. ... Reportedly, Yankees manager Torre has
agreed to a two-year contract extension that would begin after the
1999 season. Torre is making $1 million a year. ... How big are the
Yankees in New York? Despite it being only a divisional playoff
game, they graced the front pages Wednesday of the Daily News, Post
and Newsday. It must have been a slow day in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ranger talk
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were upset that the Yankees had given them just 40
tickets for each of the games in New York. ``We have too much class
to do it, but we should give him (Steinbrenner) the same treatment
when we get back to Texas,'' a Ranger front office executive told
the New York Post. This issue goes back to the 1996 playoffs when
Steinbrenner thought the wives of Rangers players were cheering too
loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
