</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astros jet past Padres, head straight to San Diego
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was ugly as the wicked Texas heat outdoors, and
about as draining. But desperate for any post-season good, the
Astros gladly took the win and headed for San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of being down two games in the best-of-five NL
Division Series, the Astros pulled out a 5-4 win Thursday night
when Bill Spiers lofted Padre closer Trevor Hamilton's ninth-inning
change up into right field. The Padres tied it in dramatic fashion
earlier in the ninth on pinch-hitter Jim Leyritz' towering two-run
home inside the right field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't look good on the first two change ups he threw me,''
said Spiers, who went down in the strike zone to hit the 1-2 pitch.
''After that, I was just trying to get the bat on the ball and get
it to the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ''Looking at the replay, I was pretty lucky to get enough of the
bat on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than walk Spiers and load the bases with one-out, the
Padres elected to face him rather than Derek Bell and then
potentially cleanup hitter Jeff Bagwell. Bell had broken an
0-for-20 post-season slump with a homer in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It could prove to be a huge victory for the psyche of the
Astros, victims of a three-game sweep by the Braves last year and
Kevin Brown's 16-strikeout performance in Game 1 of this series.
Their hitters had come under scrutiny for putting up just six runs
in those four games.
</P>
<P>
   ''This takes an awful lot of pressure off,'' said manager Larry
Dierker. ''These things grow larger than they are.''
</P>
