<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad news, Killer B's: Ashby healthy again
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Andy Ashby swears he's healthy again, and that could
spell more bad news for the Astros' silent bats.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby (17-9) opposes Shane Reynolds (19-8) in a battle of
right-handers this afternoon in Game 2 of the National League
Division Series. Ashby has been troubled by tendinitis in his hip
late in the season, going winless in six starts before picking up a
victory in his final regular-season start against the Los Angeles
Dodgers. His ERA was 8.70 in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw (Monday) for about 20 minutes, and I think the big
thing is the way I threw in my last two starts,'' Ashby said.
``Before the last two starts, I hadn't been able to do any side
work because of the tendinitis. It's a big plus to throw on the
side and not have any pain at all.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not what the Astros want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Although leading the NL in runs scored this season _ thanks in
part to the additions of Moises Alou and Carl Everett _ Houston
hitters flailed aimlessly at Kevin Brown in Game 1. In the last
four postseason games, including last year's three-game sweep by
the Braves, the Astros have scored a total of six runs.
</P>
<P>
   In those four games, the Killer B's _ Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell
and Derek Bell _ are a staggering 2-for-47 with 15 strikeouts. Bell
is 0-for-17 in the postseason, fanning three times in Game 1
against Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure at all,'' Bell said after Wednesday's
voluntary workout. ``It's three games last year and one this year.
That's just four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give credit to the guys we faced. When you face (Greg) Maddux,
(John) Smoltz and Kevin Brown _ do you want to go up and hit
against them? Here's the bat; you go do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cy Young campaign
</P>
<P>
   While Braves left-hander Tom Glavine has his Cy Youngsupporters,
Padres reliever Trevor Hoffman seems to rank as the favorite in the
Houston clubhouse. Hoffman saved an NL-record 53 games in 54
chances and allowed just two home runs all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trevor is having a Cy Young year, and he should be the Cy
Young winner in our league without a doubt,'' said second baseman
Biggio, who himself is in the MVP chase.
</P>
<P>
   But Padres manager Bruce Bochy probably did the Astros a favor
in the ninth inning of Game 1 when he pulled Brown in favor of
Hoffman. Houston scratched out an unearned run before losing 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Rotation Shuffle
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern product Joey Hamilton has been skipped over in
favor of left-hander Sterling Hitchcock for the Game 3 start and
will work out of the bullpen this series. In making the move, Bochy
said it came down to Hitchcock (9-7) pitching better in the second
half than Hamilton (13-13).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
