<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tucker's HR provides little bit of redemption
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As soon as Michael Tucker saw Sammy Sosa looking up
Wednesday afternoon, his season started doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's two-run homer in the second inning of the Braves' 7-1
victory over the Cubs changed the right fielder's fortunes from
second-half slump to postseason productivity.
</P>
<P>
   With two out, Andruw Jones on second and pitcher John Smoltz on
deck, Tucker hit a 3-2 pitch from Mark Clark into the right-field
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit excited about it,'' Tucker said. ``I just
wanted to make sure (if it hit off the wall) that I was going to
get to second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked out and Sammy was turned around looking up. I said,
`OK, that's two runs. Now if we can get a couple more, and Smoltzie
holds them out, we can win the ballgame.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Big hits, even base hits, had been scarce for Tucker lately. He
had only one home run since Aug. 9, and was batting .186
(29-for-156) since the All-Star break. Before the break, he had 72
hits including 11 HRs and 36 RBIs, and was batting .277.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty depressing,'' Tucker said. ``You have a great
first half, 11 home runs, and you're looking forward to doing the
same thing the second half and things just went downhill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start looking at everything, you think you found the
answer, and things don't seem to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   He started to improve the last couple of weeks. And thanks to
his defensive play, including a highlights-tape catch of a ball he
almost misplayed in the third inning, Braves manager Bobby Cox
never yanked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has never given up and has been hitting the ball better
lately,'' Cox said. ``He hit a bullet today and the ball was really
crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark threw a split-finger fastball he was trying to get down
and away, like he'd done with the previous pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hung it, and got it over the plate,'' said Tucker, who was
1-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman didn't second-guess Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't execute the way he wanted to, but the thought was
right,'' Riggleman said. ``He threw a forkball and it didn't look
like a forkball and didn't act like one.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Tucker's home run in Game 5 of the NLCS was his only
hit in 10 at-bats against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him to have a big series, a big postseason,'' Chipper
Jones said. ``I don't think you really can comprehend the
importance of having somebody at the bottom of the lineup swinging
the bat well. It certainly takes a lot of the pressure off the guys
up top and in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully he'll go home and sleep easy tonight and bring some
confidence back to the park with him tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
