<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs' biggest foe is history, not Braves
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This really isn't fair. While the Atlanta Braves have
just a single foe to conquer during this portion of the National
League Division Series, the Chicago Cubs must battle a couple.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are the easiest of the two. So this is awful news for
the Cubs, especially since they spent Wednesday at Turner Field
watching the Braves roll to the easiest of 7-1 victories during the
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Braves overcame the apathy of the snoozing 45,598
reportedly in the stands to do everything right. When the Braves
weren't performing the big things, such as clobbering the Cubs
after a two-out error with a two-run homer from Michael Tucker and
Ryan Klesko's grand slam in the seventh, they were performing the
little things, such as pushing a runner from first to third on a
single and scoring on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, for the Cubs, the Braves never stopped playing defense,
never stopped pitching, never stopped looking as if they were way
too potent for their weary visitors. The Cubs had that extra game
to play Monday night in Chicago against the San Francisco Giants.
As a result, with the New York Mets gasping toward oblivion, the
Cubs became the best of the least down the stretch for a wild-card
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the Giants, the Mets, the Braves or anybody else
the Cubs are facing at the moment, the Cubs always have their
second and mightiest opponent in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Cubs history, and it's brutal. Just ask Greg Maddux,
baseball's pitching Picasso, who figures to save the Cubs from
extended misery by helping the Braves sweep their way to the NL
Championship Series on Saturday in Chicago. Well, this depends on
Braves pitcher Tom Glavine becoming his typically clutch self
tonight at the Ted, ... but so much for details.
</P>
<P>
   Let's return to Maddux, an expert who spent seven years in
Chicago through 1992. ``You heard about the past every day there,''
Maddux says. ``Even the music they played at the ballpark was from
the old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Those old days often begin with 1945, when some Chicago bar
owner said he was placing a hex on the Cubs for not allowing him to
parade his billy goat around the field before the last World Series
at Wrigley Field. That was the last World Series at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Cubs have suffered everything from last year's
0-14 start, to those awful seasons of rotating coaches as managers,
to former manager Lee Elia barking something like ``85 percent of
Chicago works and the rest boo the Cubs at Wrigley,'' to Leon
Durham becoming Bill Buckner before Bill Buckner during an NLCS, to
tons of June Swoons, to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Always 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Williams definitely remembers. ``So do Ron Santo (a Cubs
announcer) and Phil Regan (the Cubs' pitching coach),'' says
Williams, the Cubs' batting coach, mentioning those others who
joined him on that Cubs team that blew an 8 1/2-game lead against
the Mets in late August to finish 9 1/2 games behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In tough times for this team, we (Williams, Santo and Regan)
always get questions about what happened in 1969, but these guys
don't know anything about those days,'' Williams says. After all,
Williams recalls how the current Cubs won miracle games at Wrigley
this season that included balls getting stuck in the ivy and down a
drain.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the ghost of Harry Caray pushing the current Cubs,
but ghosts are no match for Smoltz, Glavine and Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore can be reached at tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
