<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SEEK BENEFITS OF SHUFFLED LINEUP, HOME FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ New York Yankees right-hander David Cone
expressed a degree of apprehension yesterday regarding his
scheduled start for Game 3 tonight of this American League Division
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a dangerous team right now,'' Cone said, ``and I
realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone chose a peculiar adjective to describe the AL West champion
Rangers, who, in losing the first two games at Yankee Stadium:
</P>
<P>
   Scored one run in 18 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hit .156 (10-for-64) and drew only one walk.
</P>
<P>
   Witnessed their Nos. 3-6 hitters _ left fielder Rusty Greer,
right fielder Juan Gonzalez, first baseman Will Clark and catcher
Ivan Rodriguez _ hit .129 (4-for-31) with one double and one run
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of scares me to tell you the truth,'' said Cone, one
of four major-league pitchers to win 20 games this season. ``I know
in a five-game series that the momentum can swing in the course of
one game or one play. They're back in their home park, and they
play well here. So, it's my job to not let them get any momentum
going their way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will advance to the AL Championship Series with a
victory tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense might benefit from the return of two
left-handed batters to their lineup, center fielder Tom Goodwin and
designated hitter Lee Stevens, against the right-handed Cone (20-7,
3.55 earned-run average).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only been two games, but it just so happens to be a
five-game series,'' said Goodwin, who did not start either of the
previous two games against left-handers David Wells and Andy
Pettitte. ``I really don't see us being in some prolonged slump. I
don't see anyone panicking around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two outstanding pitching performances, too. We showed
that we could match them pitch for pitch. We just need to get that
clutch hit here and there and maybe we can turn those close games
to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, one of the league's fastest players, will bat leadoff.
Goodwin's speed makes it easier for the Rangers to manufacture runs
through stolen bases and running from first to third on singles to
the outfield. He hit .324 in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also will regain the bat of Stevens, who hit .387
(12-for-31) with four home runs and seven RBI in his final 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also might benefit by returning home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' .304 batting average at The Ballpark represented
the highest mark at home by an AL team since the 1984 Red Sox hit
.305 at Fenway Park. The Rangers averaged 6.20 runs per game at The
Ballpark, compared to a .274 batting average and 5.41 runs per game
in road contests.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also need the heart of their order _ Greer,
Gonzalez, Clark and Rodriguez _ to produce, although that foursome
would not be the only players struggling at the plate in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' first five hitters _ second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch, shortstop Derek Jeter, right fielder Paul O'Neill,
center fielder Bernie Williams and first baseman Tino Martinez _
hit .121 (4-for-33) in the series' first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there were times this season when our No. 3, 4, 5 and
6 hitters haven't done anything, but we knew we had 85 games
remaining or whatever the case may have been,'' Greer said. ``Now,
we're in a five-game series _ and those 12 to 20 at-bats become
more magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first thing to remember is that we cannot win
three games tomorrow night,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said,
``and you cannot get three hits in one at-bat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
