<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-01 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISK A SWEEP OR A SOSA, BUT TAKE YOUR SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ At this bleak postseason point on the local
baseball front, it grieves both me and Tom Grieve to bring up Sammy
Sosa's name.
</P>
<P>
   It's nine long years since the worst trade in Rangers history,
but like with the Titanic, people still try to raise it _ this
season more than ever, for 66 obvious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The unfunny thing is, what has surfaced this week involves a
roundabout connection between the infamous 1989 trading of a young
Sammy, and the Rangers' current 0-2 skunking in the American League
Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   To get here, meaning the playoffs and a must-win Game 3 at The
Ballpark in Arlington tonight, general manager Doug Melvin had to
be a busy and successful dealer in late July. Incoming in his
trades were Todd Stottlemyre, Royce Clayton and Todd Zeile. Without
them, the Rangers would have been as broken as Will Clark's toe.
</P>
<P>
   But out-going in July were, among others, young third baseman
Fernando Tatis, who was in a bit deep at this stage of his career
because the Rangers had rushed him. Given time, however, and there
are many scouting eyes who predict Tatis can become another ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Sosa,'' said Melvin, rather calmly. ``I heard the Sosa
comparisons in meetings with our own baseball people, plus I lean
in that direction myself. That's why in July, with Tatis' name
coming up all the time from other clubs, I originally was very firm
in saying, ``no-no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, the former GM and now a Rangers TV voice, wishes he had
stuck to his ``nada'' back in '89. He didn't want to trade Sosa,
nor kid pitcher Wilson Alvarez, but acquiring designated hitter
Harold Baines from the White Sox appeared to be a swell idea at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve and manager Bobby Valentine thought Baines provided the
answer to the franchise's finally winning a divisional title.
Instead, Baines sulked silently though the second half, and the
Rangers were 16 games back when a mercy-kill came with the end of
the season. For Grieve, however, there's still no mercy from that
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, the general rule is if you make a Sosa-Alvarez
kind of trade, or a Tatis kind of trade, you had better win,''
Melvin said. ``I don't know how Tatis or a couple of other lower
minor-league kids we traded in July will eventually pan out. But
the object was to win the division, get in the playoffs, take your
chances. And this team accomplished that.''
</P>
<P>
   But for what? To go into Yankee Stadium this week, sink into a
run-less trance, waste good pitching, and come home in a hopeless,
miracle-seeking state?
</P>
<P>
   Why, let's see, you have to go all the way back to ... to ... to
1995 it was, for the last time a team with a 2-0 lead in the first
round gagged the series by blowing three straight. The Yankees did
that against Seattle. See, all the Yankees heritage isn't glorious.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, back to Melvin and his July trading spree. Voices of
displeasure were heard locally, using the theory that no matter
what the Rangers did, they'd draw the Yankees in the first round,
and be swept. So big deal, don't waste prospects or time. Forget
the AL West. Give it to the Angels. Start regrouping for '99.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the dumbest baseball thing I'd ever hear _ actually,
it was beyond the dumbest. But those voices were many, and now, as
wrong as they were, they can still claim to be right, certainly if
the Yankees sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong,'' said Melvin. ``First, we're not out of this series
yet. I obviously don't like our position, but if the bats suddenly
come around, who knows. Here in Arlington, we're a better team in
all areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I didn't understand was how anyone who has followed the
history of this franchise, think winning a division is not
important. I heard some people say it (in July), and I couldn't
believe it. Where had they been for 25 years?''
</P>
<P>
   As in the 25 years it took the Rangers to crack the postseason
with a divisional title. Now there have been two in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin: ``To start with, winning creates the right atmosphere
for our players, our fans who support us so well, and even for free
agents who are looking around every winter. We all know money
talks, but if things are close to equal, free agents want to be in
a good city and on a team that has a chance to win. We can provide
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``What winning the division this time does is help build on a
winning tradition. It's very important we create that. And if you
keep winning a division, sooner or later you will find a World
Series. The Denver Broncos did in football. We can, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin admits he will watch Tatis' career in St. Louis with much
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my biggest worry is Game 3,'' he said, smiling. ``And in
the future, we will all concern ourselves with being involved in a
lot more postseasons. I like it here in the playoffs, and whatever
it takes to get here, that's the one and only objective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
