<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      10-01 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SIGN TWO KEY PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Bruins were playing in Worcester against the
Penguins Wednesday night, assistant general manager Mike O'Connell
sat in the press box looking forlorn when he declared that he
didn't think center Jason Allison was anywhere near being signed.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours later, Allison, the Bruins' leading scorer,
was signed to a two-year deal and one of the team's other free
agents, Ted Donato, was also in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Allison and his agent, Bob Gerow, flew into town for a long
meeting with the Bruins' brass Tuesday. On Wednesday, they flew
back to Toronto, no closer than they had been when they arrived.
But over the course of the next day, the sides seemed to ponder
their positions and Thursday, Allison phoned the Bruins, set up a
conference call for the afternoon and the sides hammered out a
two-year deal in 3-4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we left Boston, it looked like a dead end on both
sides,'' said Allison, who expects to arrive back in town sometime
today. ``There really wasn't much hope at the time. They were stuck
pretty low and I had a number I wasn't going to go off of for a
base. So I wanted to try to make it up in bonuses. My agent and I
sat down and structured what we thought would be a fair base salary
with bonuses. It's more creative this way. I can reach it if I play
well and if I don't reach it, well, I don't deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison reportedly will receive a base salary of $2.25 million
this year and $2.5 million next year. If he reaches 100 points for
two years in a row, he'll make roughly $9 million. Allison's first
bonus reportedly kicks in at 70 points, when he'll pick up
$100,000. If he gets to 80 points, he'll earn $475,000 more. For 85
points, he'd get an additional $300,000, another $200,000 for 90
points and $300,000 more for 100. All those bonuses automatically
would be part of the second year's contract if he reaches them.
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he didn't mind an incentive-laden contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I had to do to do a deal here,'' he said. ``I
wasn't scared of sitting out. But I didn't want to do that, and
they didn't want me to. I think the base is fair. The key was to
have a base I could live with. My worry was that if I was in the
top 10 in scoring for the next two years, I didn't want to be stuck
at $2 million if everyone else was making $6 million. I'm
definitely relieved. I didn't want to think about sitting out all
year. But I would've done it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the team was thrilled to have finished the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started with that meeting in Boston. I think Jason
realized we were very serious,'' said O'Connell. ``I think he
understood it a little more and we had a better appreciation for
how he feels. It was that combination that made us able to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The signings of Allison and Donato leave Kyle McLaren and Anson
Carter as the two Bruins who have yet to come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Donato, 29, was in a different situation than Allison, McLaren,
and Carter. Rather than haggling over money, he was unhappy about
his playing time in the second half of last season and had asked to
be traded.
</P>
<P>
   With other teams grappling with their own free agent problems
and trying to figure out who would start the season on their own
rosters, no teams appeared interested in adding another contract to
their mix and the Bruins to this point had been unable to
accommodate Donato.
</P>
<P>
   Donato didn't want to be relegated to a spare part once the
other Boston free agents re-signed and believed he'd be better off
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns, on the other hand, felt Donato should come into
training camp and show the club that he deserved more ice time than
he was getting in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he made Donato no promises about a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing changed,'' said O'Connell. ``We were always wondering
why he wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato, who is expected to be at practice at the FleetCenter
this morning, has been a valuable member of the Bruins since
joining the club after the Olympics in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted has been a useful and versatile player for the Bruins for
many years and we look for that to continue,'' said
president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``He has assured us that he
will come in and give the hard effort he always has and we are
expecting a good contribution from him this season.''
</P>
<P>
   It's believed that Donato accepted the club's qualifying offer,
which will pay him $1.06 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns, dissatisfied by the performance of several young players,
sent forwards Landon Wilson, Cameron Mann, Andre Savage and Shawn
Bates to Providence Thursday and recalled Jay Henderson, Eric
Nickulas and Marquis Mathieu to play in the final two exhibition
games Saturday and Sunday against the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them every opportunity possible to show it and they
won't show it,'' said Burns. ``What do you want me to do? I'll find
12 of the best players if I have to and I'll play 12 guys. They've
got to get involved. We're giving players opportunities to show it
and they don't show it. Well, this is the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember, the Providence Bruins didn't have a
lot of success last year with the same players. We'll bring up
three more from there and give them an opportunity until we find
the right ones, that's all. Of course we're disappointed and I
think they are too but either they take it as a setback or as a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of many of the Bruins' key players in contract
disputes put coach and team largely back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is starting over again,'' said Burns. ``I won't just
dress guys for the reason of putting sweaters on their backs and
saying, `Go out there' because I have nobody else. I'll play with
12 guys, guys who are going to work hard and be proud of being
Boston Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Taylor's line will play on the power play, they'll kill
penalties and check. We'll make Ken Baumgartner a center if we have
to but we're not going to roll over and die because (some) guys
aren't happy, that I promise you. We're going to go to war with the
guys who want to go to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Burns didn't have any of what was last year's top
line. Sergei Samsonov was sidelined by the flu, Dmitri Khristich is
out with a shoulder injury, and Allison had yet to come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Thornton didn't skate with the team and will miss the
weekend games because of a minor shoulder injury. Burns said he
should be ready to go next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
