<HEADER>
A5400 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN     10-01 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEDIA S.A.T.: TEST YOUR SARCASTIC APTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Bristol University included a course in
critical interpretation of the modern sports media, maybe we
wouldn't have to go through this recruiting process every few
years.
</P>
<P>
   The sad point is sports media critics are vanishing from the
landscape faster than DirecTV can hand out free T-shirts and caps.
More and more assume the position of acting as a clearinghouse for
network press releases, regurgitating ratings information as if
it's the Holy Grail or failing to grasp the fact that rights fees
paid to professional and amateur sports will forever dilute the
objectivity of the presentations for the home viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Are we going too fast for you?
</P>
<P>
   A correspondence course in Sports Media Criticism 101 would be
nice, but nice isn't what we're offering. If you may have what it
takes to continue this art form that's gone the way of cave
paintings, we suggest you attempt the Sarcastic Aptitude Test (our
SAT continues to measure ``aptitude'' rather than ``achievement''
because, quite frankly, there's nothing achieved by being
sarcastic).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will help you express your crankiness in a more
creative manner.
</P>
<P>
   --MULTIPLE CHOICE--
</P>
<P>
   1. The World Series matchup that Fox executives would like to
see the most is:
</P>
<P>
   a) Yankees-Cubs, because it represents the No. 1 and No. 3 TV
markets in the country.
</P>
<P>
   b) Red Sox-Cubs, because it creates a matchup of lovable losers.
</P>
<P>
   c) Braves-vs.-anyone, because it'll make for great shots of Ted
Turner nodding off on Jane Fonda's shoulder in the owners box.
</P>
<P>
   2. NBC has recovered from the absence of NFL games by showing:
</P>
<P>
   a) New NASCAR events.
</P>
<P>
   b) More golf events.
</P>
<P>
   c) Nonstop advertisements for ``A Night at the Roxbury.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Those most fearful of an extended NBA lockout and possible
cancellation of the season are:
</P>
<P>
   a) Executives at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   b) Executives at TNT.
</P>
<P>
   c) Marge Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   4. Major League Soccer's championship game this year will be
carried on:
</P>
<P>
   a) ABC
</P>
<P>
   b) ESPN
</P>
<P>
   c) Have the playoffs started yet?
</P>
<P>
   5. The future of women's sports on television is dependent upon:
</P>
<P>
   a) The commitment by the Lifetime network.
</P>
<P>
   b) The establishment of an all women's-sports channel.
</P>
<P>
   c) The speed with which a Women's Ultimate Fighting Championship
can be sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   --COMPARE AND CONTRAST--
</P>
<P>
   6. Chris Berman is to baseball play-by-play as:
</P>
<P>
   a) Howie Mandell is to talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   b) George Clooney is to emergency-room doctor.
</P>
<P>
   c) Dennis Miller is to acting.
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   --HISTORY-
</P>
<P>
   7. The greatest innovation in sports television in the last 10
years is:
</P>
<P>
   a) The on-screen time-and-score box at the top left corner by
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   b) The glowing yellow first-down line by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   c) The mute button on the remote control.
</P>
<P>
   8. The worst innovation in sports television in the last 10
years is:
</P>
<P>
   a) The glowing hockey puck by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   b) The glowing yellow first-down line by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   c) The carcinogenic sports-desk anchors who decide they are
required to have a 3{-minute introduction to each 30-second
highlight package, complete with arcane references and semi-sweet
puns that prove the clip they're about to show is from a sparsely
attended game between two teams going nowhere that couldn't get so
much as the score flashed in a pile of graphics on another local
sports show.
</P>
<P>
   -- MATHEMATICS--
</P>
<P>
   9. Bob Costas' self-importance is greater than or equal to:!off!
</P>
<P>
   a) Mark McGwire's biceps.
</P>
<P>
   b) Chris Berman's waistline.
</P>
<P>
   c) The Cirque du Soleil at the Bellagio in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   10. Network A pays $17.6 billion for the rights to the NFC.
Network B pays $11.6 billion for the rights to the AFC. Network C
pays $12 billion for the rights to NFL games on Sunday and Monday
nights. If each network has the same opportunity to sell
advertisements to recoup the cost of these investments, and none of
the networks were blackmailed into making these bids, which stands
to benefit financially the most?
</P>
<P>
   If your answer is Network D, please move to the next question.
</P>
<P>
   If you have some magic formula that shows either Network A, B or
C will turn a profit, please remember: We suggest no illegal
substances be taken before this exam.
</P>
<P>
   -- FINAL ESSAY QUESTION--
</P>
<P>
   The Beer, Babes and Billiards Channel _ pros and cons.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES:
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe McDonnell, awaking from a journalistic slumber to smack
Vic ``A Few Stamps Short of a Mailman'' Jacobs back into reality
after the later was duped by some ``mad love funkadelia'' from Karl
Malone on his AM-1150 show Wednesday. The Utah Jazz star dropped
loud hints on Jacobs about wanting to play in L.A. Jacobs took it
brick, line and sinker. Then Malone was offered a job to host a
show on the station. McDonnell squashed all that nonsense
immediately and continued to do so, in milder tones, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   -- A rehabilitated Marv Albert says in the Oct. 5 People
magazine: ``There are no more surprises coming from me, I can tell
you that!'' The surprise to us is that ABC's Boomer Esiason _ and
not Albert _ is included in the cover story naming ``TV's 40 Most
Fascinating Stars of '98.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Current MSNBC newsguy and former ESPN ``SportsCenter'' icon
Keith Olbermann, in the ``Scorecard'' section of the Oct. 5 Sports
Illustrated, has a somewhat self-serving but accurate review of the
ABC series ``Sports Night.'' ``How much more of my life can these
people borrow before they have to pay me?'' Which now signals the
alarm for ESPN Magazine to snipe at something on CNN-SI.
</P>
<P>
   -- Todd Donoho as left the building.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- A revived-baseball-crazed work force in the greater Los
Angeles area asks a simple question: Where are the playoff games on
the radio? TV is confusing enough with ESPN, NBC and Fox grabbing
for the best game possible. But on the car patrol, a hit-and-miss
selection of the daily games via ESPN Radio's syndicated broadcasts
have bounced around on San Diego's XTRA-AM (690), Burbank's KXTA-AM
(1150) and/or the Antelope Valley's tiny but mighty KAVL-AM (610) _
or none at all. We're told it should last through this first round
of play, maybe even into the ALCS and NLCS. Sure, why interrupt
people talking about sports to carry the actual sport instead?
Because the radio stations fear breaking up the continuity.
</P>
<P>
   -- KCBS Channel 2 has changed its singular Sunday NFL offering
from the Ryan Leaf-Peyton Manning matchup of San Diego-Indianapolis
at 10 a.m. to the 1 p.m. yawner of Oakland-Arizona. A station
spokesperson says it has to do with the fact that game works better
for them ``for competitive reasons'' in the later time slot and
``the Raiders have been playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Penn State-Ohio State game is on pay-per-view?
</P>
<P>
   -- The second-lowest ``Monday Afternoon Football'' rating of all
time _ 11.9, with a 17 share nationally. Sure, the Tampa
Bay-Detroit thrilla went head-on with the Cubs-Giants wild-card
playoff game on ESPN this week. And beat it from a ratings
standpoint. But if ABC's slide for this once invincible prime-time
(on the East Coast) slot continues, it might find itself trailing
``Buddy Faro'' by midseason. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Daily News staff writer Tom Hoffarth can be reached at
sptmedia(at)aol.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
