<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/01/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NYACK, N.Y. -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- STYRON'S-DAUGHTER, 10-1
-- Susanna Styron has made a film of a short story by her father,
William Styron. ``It was a wonderful thing to share,'' Ms. Styron,
43, says at her turn-of-the-century Victorian house in Nyack this
week. ``But it wasn't like we were healing old wounds or
anything.'' (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- HEDGEFUND-REGULATE, 10-01
-- Alan Greenspan, left, the Federal Reserve chairman, and William
McDonough, president of the New York Federal Reserve Bank,
appearing before the House Banking Committee Thursday. ``Let's not
presume that the ideal outcome is more regulation,'' says
Greenspan. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- CLINTON-CAMMARATA, 10-01
-- ``I can't believe this is happening,'' Joseph Cammarata, one of
Paula Corbin Jones' original lawyers, says of one momentous chain
of events. ``I'm amazed how it started as a simple small lawsuit: a
young woman wants her day in court against the most powerful man in
the world, she winds up with a 9-to-nothing victory in the Supreme
Court, and here we all are.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) ARLINGTON, Texas -- Oct. 01, 1998 --
BBA-STRAWBERRY-CANCER-2, 10-01 -- David Cone talking with his
father, Ed, on Thursday after learning the news of his teammate's
illness. Darryl Strawberry, the 36-year-old Yankees outfielder, was
diagnosed with cancer of the colon Thursday. (Barton Silverman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) ARLINGTON, Texas -- Oct. 01, 1998 --
BBA-STRAWBERRY-CANCER-1, 10-01 -- After working out at the Ballpark
in Arlington on an off day Thursday, the Yankees gather to deliver
a team message to Darryl Strawberry, via ESPN. Strawberry, the
36-year-old Yankees outfielder, was diagnosed with cancer of the
colon Thursday. Doctors say his prognosis for recovery is
excellent, according to Charisse Strawberry, the player's wife.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) UNITED NATIONS -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- KOSOVO-U.N., 10-01 --
Sir Jeremy Greenstock of Britain, the Security Council's president,
after the meeting Thursday. ``Council members expressed
considerable alarm at reports that fighting was continuing despite
the demand for a cease-fire, and in particular that thousands more
civilians have been forced to leave their homes because of the
actions of government security forces,'' he says. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- WHALE-HUNTERS-2,
10-01 -- Eric Johnson is captain of the team of Makah Indians who
will hunt for whale in A 32-foot cedar canoe. Though no living
Makah has ever hunted a whale, the Indian nation here at the very
northwestern tip of the continental United States was once renowned
for its prowess, and it is the only Indian tribe specifically
guaranteed the right to hunt whales under an 1855 treaty with the
American government. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- WHALE-HUNTERS-1,
10-01 -- Makah Indians who will hunt for whale paddle into fog in
their 32-foot cedar canoe Thursday. Finding themselves caught
between the save-the-whales ethos represented by the protesters and
the respect for centuries-old Native American traditions that the
Makah say their whale hunt is all about, many leading environmental
groups have taken no position at all on the matter. (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 10-01 --
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arriving at Capitol Hill on
Wednesday to talk with senators about the situation in Kosovo
Province. The United States will have both the political
authorization from its NATO allies and the military forces in place
to use against Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic in two
weeks if he does not agree to remove his special police from the
province of Kosovo, senior U.S. officials said Thursday. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-2, 10-1 --
The view from the fifth floor of the refurbished Grand Central
Station on Thursday, when it was rededicated. Once threatened with
demolition and gnawed by decades of urban grime, the 85-year-old
structure shines once again. (Fred Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-1, 10-1 --
Grand Central Terminal during a spirited rededication ceremony on
Thursday. The terminal celebrated its rebirth as a lustrous train
station and as a destination in its own right. In its restored
grandeur, with sunlight pouring through steel-ribbed skylights and
twin marble staircases curling to a platform, the 85-year-old
structure is once again so imposing that it dwarfs those who come
to praise it. (James Estrin/New York Times photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- MCCURRY-LASTDAY, 10-01 --
At his final briefing for reporters, Michael McCurry, President
Clinton's press secretary, shares a laugh Thursday with other
members of the White House staff, including his successor, Joe
Lockhart, far left. 0f the Clinton/Lewinsky scandal, McCurry says
he was determined not ``to lie to you and mislead you.'' (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- IMF-CRISIS-2, 10-01 --
Michel Camdessus of the IMF at a Washington news conference
Thursday. The U.S. Treasury's relations with Camdessus have become
more strained as he plays the role of world diplomat, traveling the
globe and trying to coax along political leaders. (Robert
Grossman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
