BBA-STRAWBERRY-CANCER-2, 10-01 -- David Cone talking with his
father, Ed, on Thursday after learning the news of his teammate's
illness. Darryl Strawberry, the 36-year-old Yankees outfielder, was
diagnosed with cancer of the colon Thursday. (Barton Silverman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) ARLINGTON, Texas -- Oct. 01, 1998 --
BBA-STRAWBERRY-CANCER-1, 10-01 -- After working out at the Ballpark
in Arlington on an off day Thursday, the Yankees gather to deliver
a team message to Darryl Strawberry, via ESPN. Strawberry, the
36-year-old Yankees outfielder, was diagnosed with cancer of the
colon Thursday. Doctors say his prognosis for recovery is
excellent, according to Charisse Strawberry, the player's wife.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) UNITED NATIONS -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- KOSOVO-U.N., 10-01 --
Sir Jeremy Greenstock of Britain, the Security Council's president,
after the meeting Thursday. ``Council members expressed
considerable alarm at reports that fighting was continuing despite
the demand for a cease-fire, and in particular that thousands more
civilians have been forced to leave their homes because of the
actions of government security forces,'' he says. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- WHALE-HUNTERS-2,
10-01 -- Eric Johnson is captain of the team of Makah Indians who
will hunt for whale in A 32-foot cedar canoe. Though no living
Makah has ever hunted a whale, the Indian nation here at the very
northwestern tip of the continental United States was once renowned
for its prowess, and it is the only Indian tribe specifically
guaranteed the right to hunt whales under an 1855 treaty with the
American government. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- WHALE-HUNTERS-1,
10-01 -- Makah Indians who will hunt for whale paddle into fog in
their 32-foot cedar canoe Thursday. Finding themselves caught
between the save-the-whales ethos represented by the protesters and
the respect for centuries-old Native American traditions that the
Makah say their whale hunt is all about, many leading environmental
groups have taken no position at all on the matter. (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 10-01 --
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arriving at Capitol Hill on
Wednesday to talk with senators about the situation in Kosovo
Province. The United States will have both the political
authorization from its NATO allies and the military forces in place
to use against Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic in two
weeks if he does not agree to remove his special police from the
province of Kosovo, senior U.S. officials said Thursday. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-2, 10-1 --
The view from the fifth floor of the refurbished Grand Central
Station on Thursday, when it was rededicated. Once threatened with
demolition and gnawed by decades of urban grime, the 85-year-old
structure shines once again. (Fred Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-1, 10-1 --
Grand Central Terminal during a spirited rededication ceremony on
Thursday. The terminal celebrated its rebirth as a lustrous train
station and as a destination in its own right. In its restored
grandeur, with sunlight pouring through steel-ribbed skylights and
twin marble staircases curling to a platform, the 85-year-old
structure is once again so imposing that it dwarfs those who come
to praise it. (James Estrin/New York Times photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- MCCURRY-LASTDAY, 10-01 --
At his final briefing for reporters, Michael McCurry, President
Clinton's press secretary, shares a laugh Thursday with other
members of the White House staff, including his successor, Joe
Lockhart, far left. 0f the Clinton/Lewinsky scandal, McCurry says
he was determined not ``to lie to you and mislead you.'' (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- IMF-CRISIS-2, 10-01 --
Michel Camdessus of the IMF at a Washington news conference
Thursday. The U.S. Treasury's relations with Camdessus have become
more strained as he plays the role of world diplomat, traveling the
globe and trying to coax along political leaders. (Robert
Grossman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- IMF-CRISIS-1, 10-01 --
Members of the North African delegations to the IMF annual meeting
joking Thursday in front of the fund's main building in Washington.
Inside, the mood was often somber because of the growing criticism
over the fund's handling of economic crises. (Robert Grossman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- CLINTON-LOWELL, 10-01 --
Abbe Lowell, the lawyer for the Democrats on the House Judiciary
Committee, in the main lobby of the Rayburn Building in September
as the panel deliberates the release of the Starr-Clinton
videotape. ``I recognize that, without being excessively humble or
modest, I am a very small part of a very big place called the House
of Representatives that's dealing with this,'' he says. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) VRANIC, Yugoslavia -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- KOSOVO-MASSACRE,
10-01 -- An ethnic Albanian woman returning to her car, which had
been burned by the Serbian police earlier this week, in the Kosovo
village of Vranic. The recent execution-style murders in this
region of Kosovo, a province where guerrillas are fighting for
independence from Serbia, prompted calls from Western leaders for
war-crimes investigations by The Hague tribunal. (Wade Goddard/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) RIO DE JANIERO, Brazil -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- BRAZIL-ELECT,
10-01 -- Sidewalk vendors and cabdrivers waiting for business in
Rio de Janeiro. Many Brazilian adults live on minimum salaries of
$110 a month. (John Maier Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- CARS-COLLECTING-2, 10-01 --
The Dymaxion, built in 1933, is one of five theme cars at the third
annual Louis Vuitton Classic. The show begins Friday and continues
through Sunday, transforming Rockefeller Center into a showplace
for extraordinary automobiles. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- CARS-COLLECTING-1, 10-01 --
The Airphibian is the centerpiece of the Louis Vuitton Classic at
Rockefeller Center. In July 1952, Popular Science found that the
plane-car hybrid could fly at 110 miles an hour in the air, and
after removing the wings, drive 50 miles an hour on the ground.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- MIZRAHI-DEMISE, 10-01 --
Isaac Mizrahi on his office fire escape in Manhattan. Mizrahi, who
was once considered the designer most likely to inherit the mantle
of Donna Karan and Calvin Klein, announced Thursday that he will
close his business this week. The unexpected news startled the
fashion community. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 4 --
DISNEY-ANIMATORS-THEATER-2, 10-01 -- Heather Headley, center, as
the title character in ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,''
Disney's new stage musical. Peter Schneider, president, and Thomas
Schumacher, executive vice president of Walt Disney Theatrical
Productions, are employing a team drawn from the Disney world of
animation and theme parks to propell this rock-and-roll retelling
of the operatic Aida story. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BURBANK, Calif. -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
4 -- DISNEY-ANIMATORS-THEATER-1, 10-01 -- Thomas Schumacher, left,
and Peter Schneider of Walt Disney Theatrical Productions at the
Disney Animation building - their offices in Burbank. At rear, a
drawing from the 1940 film ``Pinocchio.'' The two men may be,
potentially, Broadway's most powerful concealed weapons. (Marissa
Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- SPERLING-COX, 10-1 --
``Budge'' Sperling, center, askes a question of Christian Coalition
head Randy Tate, left, during a 'Sperling Breakfast' Wednesday. The
breakfast is an institution that celebrates its 3,000th session
Friday. Sperling, the 83-year-old former Christian Science Monitor
bureau chief, has presided over the gatherings since they began on
Feb. 8, 1966. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WAYLAND, Mass. -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- EXPLOSIVE-CHILD-BOS,
10-01 -- Dr. Ross Greene talks with a child in his Wayland office.
Greene's approach to taming what he calls the ``explosive child''
(from his book of the same name) is a radical departure from the
standard strategies for dealing with disruptive children. ``There
are parents and teachers who say I'm going to spoil kids with my
approach,'' says Greene, a child psychologist. (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) COLD BAY, Alaska -- Oct. 01, 1998 --
ALASKA-HIGHWAYS-BOS, 10-01 -- Ken Van Dike prepares to head out on
his all terrain vehicle in Cold Bay, shotgun at the ready in case
of bear encounters; with him is his dog, Dixie. A proposed road
linking the communities of Cold Bay and King Cove would pass near
both this stretch of tundra (just outside of Cold Bay) and an
abutting wilderness area. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- HOME-CHENILLE-BOS, 10-01 --
A chenille-covered dining room chair. In the past five years,
chenille has matured into beautifully textured and patterned
upholstery and slipcover fabrics and luxurious furniture throws,
pillows, tassels, and trims. (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 4 --
SLAM-FILM, 10-1 -- The team from the movie ``Slam'' are from left,
Saul Williams, the writer Richard Stratton, Sonja Sohn, the
executive producer Henri Kessler, Bonz Malone and the
writer-director Marc Levin. ``Slam,'' which opens on Friday after
being shown at the New York Film Festival, is the story of a young
black performance poet, Raymond Joshua who is imprisoned on a petty
drug charge but who manages to establish his identity and his voice
within the maelstrom of a Washington jail. (Linda Rosier/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- TITANIC-BACKSTAGE-4, 9-30
-- Wigs worn by the character Kate Mullins in the play,
``Titanic.'' The upkeep of the show between performances is a
formidable undertaking. It includes the maintenance of 71 wigs, all
made of human hair; every one needs to be reset after each
performance, constantly brushed and occasionally shampooed. To
handle all of this, the production employs five hair and wig
dressers. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- TITANIC-BACKSTAGE-3, 9-30
-- Melissa Bell, Jennifer Piech, center, and Theresa McCarthy on
the moving set of the play, ``Titanic.'' The production is
technically elaborate, involving everything from smoking coal bins
to a sliding piano to a precarious crow's nest from which the
lookout spots the iceberg. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- TITANIC-BACKSTAGE-2, 9-30
-- Melissa Bell, left, and Theresa McCarthy in a dressing room
backstage at ``Titanic,'' which offers a particularly compelling
example of the magnitude and the minutiae of the little-seen drama
backstage. The show is a beast of a production: There are 44
actors: 21 men and 15 women in the cast, plus 8 understudies who
step into a variety of roles. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1998 -- TITANIC-BACKSTAGE-1, 9-30
-- By the time the cast of ``Titanic'' gathers for its final scene
on deck, many backstage scenes have unfolded. Audiences rarely get
a glimpse behind the scenes, where the set and costume changes can
be as intricately choreographed as the dancing, where the
relationships may be easily as intense as those the actors portray
on stage, and where the unexpected crises can be even more
suspenseful than the plot. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DEATH VALLEY NATIONAL PARK, Calif. -- Oct. 1, 1998 --
DEATH-VALLEY-HNS, 10-1 -- Crossing the sand dunes in Death Valley
National Park just after sunrise. Death Valley, which includes more
than 3.3 million acres in California and a small part of Nevada, is
becoming a year-round vacation spot. November through March are the
most comfortable months for visitors, with daytime temperatures
ranging from 65 to 80 degrees. Nighttime lows, accompanied by an
explosion of stars, hover in the low 40s. (Syd Kearney/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- IRMA-THEATER-REVIEW-2, 10-01
-- Everett Quinton as Lady Enid Hillcrest in a revival of ``The
Mystery of Irma Vep.'' The revival of the Ridiculous Theatrical
Company's 1984 hit, played with a consummate sense of timing is
just about all one could hope for in outrageous Gothic spoofing
that incorporates such dainty comic devices as leering Egyptian
mummies, blood-soaked oil portraits and bald men in bustles. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- IRMA-THEATER-REVIEW-1, 10-01
-- Stephen DeRosa, left, and Everett Quinton in a revival of ``The
Mystery of Irma Vep.'' You've never heard of projectile laughing?
It's a serious concern in watching this production, which is far
and away the funniest two hours unfolding anywhere today on a New
York stage. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- NY-ELDRIDGE-STREET, 10-01 --
The Jewish Daily Forward once occupied this building on East
Broadway, on the Lower East Side. It will soon be converted to
condominiums. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- AIDA-OPERA-REVIEW, 10-01 --
Maria Guleghina in the title role of ``Aida'' at the Metropolitan
Opera. Most strikingly, and very usefully in this opera, Ms.
Guleghina can rise from her gentle kind of delivery to be heard
over a stage full of chorus and principals, and can do so smoothly,
with no apparent exertion and no loss of tone. The effect is of a
zoom into a close-up in a crowd scene. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 01, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 10-01 --
Playwright and actor Matthew Weiss, left, Ned Eisenberg and Marcus
Weiss in ``Hesh,'' a Naked Angels production that opened on Sunday
at the Intar Theater. The play tells the story of two brothers and
their father, a wisecracking ne'er-do-well. The catch? Weiss, 33,
portrays the older sibling, while the younger brother is played by
his younger brother, 30-year-old Marcus. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHANDLER, Ariz. -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- DIM SUM-FOOD-AZR, 10-1
-- A selection of dim sum available at Cu-Fu Gourmet, a dim sum and
Chinese restaurant. Translated, dim sum means ``touch the heart.''
Actually, the name shows deference to master dim sum chefs called
``si fu'' - for wanting to please others by creating the delectable
morsels. (Tim Koors/Arizon Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CONGRESS, Ariz. -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- FROG ROCK-AZR, 10-1 --
Rose Mary Goodson is just one of the Congress locals who hauled
gallons of paint and a ladder up a rocky gorge to repaint The Frog,
a painted rock which has been a landmark in the community since the
late 1920's. It's not an easy task, painting a 60-ton frog. First,
there's the barbed-wire fence that has to be scaled while lugging
an extension ladder and several buckets of paint. Then it's a
rugged climb up to the creature, and at the top, there are few
places to anchor a ladder. (Sam Lowe/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SEATTLE -- Oct. 1, 1998 -- BOOKS-STEPHEN-KING-SPI, 10-1
-- Steven King surveys the room from a table at the Four Seasons.
With a 1.46 million copies in its first printing, King's new novel,
``Bag of Bones'' (Scribner, 529 pages, $28) is backed by a highly
focused $50,000 publicity campaign with stops in just five cities
and only a few interviews of the semi-reclusive author. (Paul
Joseph Brown/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
