<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SPECIAL TEAMS PICKING UP SLACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Troy Aikman's fractured collarbone figured to
make the running game the strength of the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   But the ground game has been more or less stuck in neutral
against the New York Giants and Oakland Raiders the past two weeks.
And Aikman's backup, Jason Garrett, struggled against the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   If only the Cowboys could run the kick return a little more.
</P>
<P>
   Punt returner Deion Sanders and first-year kickoff returner
Kevin Mathis each rank in the top five in the NFC. Sanders has
certainly taken his play to another level with three punt returns
of more than 39 yards the past two games, including a 60-yarder
Sunday that nearly turned around a 13-12 loss against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis was also effective against the Raiders with returns of 31
and 36 yards. He combined with Sanders to help give the Garrett-led
offense an average starting position of their 41-yard line against
the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Though exasperated his team failed to capitalize on the good
returns against the Raiders, coach Chan Gailey likes the Cowboys'
chances if given similar opportunities against the Washington
Redskins on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shortens the field for your offense, and if you look at the
scoring percentages, it's phenomenal how much it improves the
better your return is,'' said Gailey, who said he has never been on
a team ``this explosive'' on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   While new to Gailey, a solid return game has been the norm under
special-teams coach Joe Avezzano. Selected NFL special-teams coach
of the year twice since joining the Cowboys in 1990, Avezzano said
his success is no secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approach the kicking game the same way I approach the
offense and defense,'' Avezzano said. ``You have to be
fundamentally sound and put a group of players on the field that
believe what you are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Avezzano said he preaches to his return units the
importance of how a good return can aid the offense, he
acknowledged having quality returners goes a long way in helping
him get his point across.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the 11 guys out there on punt return, they understand the
importance and the possibilities because of our returner,'' said
Avezzano, who has had at least one of his return units ranked among
the top 10 in the league in each of the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guy is an exceptional guy. When we get an opportunity we
want to capitalize on it and everybody wants to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' thrilling efforts were expected. The multitalented
star, who doubles as a cornerback and receiver, is thought by many
to be the league's best returner. He ranks fourth in the NFL in
punt returns with an average of 17.6 yards per punt, and holds the
all-time league record for touchdown returns of any kind with 16.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, however, is somewhat of a surprise, considering one of
the Cowboys' biggest questions coming into this season was finding
someone to replace Herschel Walker.
</P>
<P>
   A second-year cornerback from Texas A&AMP;M-Commerce, Mathis
satisfied Gailey and Avezzano with his play during the preseason
and has continued to develop. His 26.5 yards per return average
ranks fourth in the NFC and is better than Walker's 23.3 average
from last season.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left for Mathis to do is break the long one. He could
get that opportunity against the Redskins, who rank last in the NFL
in kickoff coverage and have allowed three returns of more than 44
yards, including a 90-yard touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been close,'' Mathis said. ``I was just a move or two
away against the Raiders. But I'm just trying to do a good job to
set up the offense and carry on the tradition here under coach
Avezzano.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
