<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES TO JUICE OFFENSE COULD LET NHL EMULATE BASEBALL'S HOME-RUN
BINGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Joe Nieuwendyk witnessed the excitement baseball's
home-run derby generated and pondered the contention that a
``juiced'' ball helped create the Mark McGwire-Sammy Sosa
sweepstakes, he decided that the NHL could learn a lesson or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``So find a way to juice the puck then,'' the Stars' center
joked.
</P>
<P>
   They're trying, Joe, they're trying.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly, but the NHL would like nothing better than a
similar race chasing the single-season goal-scoring record of Wayne
Gretzky _ 92 set in 1981-82. With that goal _ and goals in general
_ in mind, the NHL has rewritten much of its rule book in hopes of
creating the attraction sports fans seem to find in big offensive
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take 20 fans in the stands on any given night, chances
are 10 of them will want to see me or Mike (Modano) or Nieuwie
score and the other 10 will want to see someone beat the heck out
of somebody else,'' said Brett Hull _ an ardent lobbyist for more
scoring. ``Does the league need more scoring? Of course it does.
That's what the people in the seats are paying to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL might finally be listening to Hull. League officials
have made significant changes to the markings on the ice surface,
perhaps the most significant in a single season since 1926. The
goal line was moved two feet farther from the end boards to 13
feet. The goal crease was shaved two feet on each side to eight
feet in width. The neutral zone was compressed four feet from 58
feet to 54, with two extra feet committed to each offensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there will be a leaguewide crackdown on the size of
goaltender equipment, with even the width of a jersey to be
measured. And the league also will experiment with two referees in
hopes of further reducing the amount of obstruction or holding away
from the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Each rule is aimed at getting more scoring into the game _ and
with good reason. Television ratings are at a relative standstill
and the league last season had its lowest scoring average (5.28
goals per game) since the 1955-56 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league was very serious about it, and they still are,''
Stars general manager Bob Gainey said. ``It's a difficult thing to
change. But the encouraging thing is you can see results of the
change.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a handful of players would like to see even more
results from the changes. Pittsburgh Penguins winger Jaromir Jagr
was the only player to break 100 points (102) last season, while
only four players _ Teemu Selanne, Peter Bondra, Pavel Bure and
John LeClair _ had 50 or more goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of talented players out there and there's no
reason we shouldn't have more scoring,'' Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   If the new rules work, then maybe Hull or Nieuwendyk or Jagr or
the Mighty Ducks' Paul Kariya will get 50 goals. If the changes
really work, maybe all four will, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   The league is not without its offensive talent. On the Stars
alone, three players have 50-goal seasons in their past _ Hull,
Nieuwendyk and Modano. In addition, Pat Verbeek has scored more
than 40 goals on four occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Around the league there is 50-goal potential from at least 10
players: Jagr, Kariya and Ducks teammate Selanne, the Capitals'
Bondra, the Islanders Ziggy Palffy, the Flyers' Eric Lindros and
LeClair, the Coyotes' Keith Tkachuk, the Maple Leafs' Mats Sundin
and the Canucks' Bure (if he returns from a contract holdout).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will help any player who has skill,'' said Craig
Button, the Stars' director of player personnel. ``You're adding
two feet of space to the offensive zone and that means the puck is
going to stay in the offensive zone longer and players are going to
have more offensive chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull hopes the rules changes do help, but even he's not sure.
The man who once scored 86 goals in a season and has three of the
top 14 goal-scoring seasons in league history said getting back to
the high-flying days of the 1980s is likely impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different game now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the offensive lobbyists aren't about to back down. So
it is a different game, and maybe there needs to be a more radical
look at how to change it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if these rule changes will help. Because while
they have opened up the opportunity for more one-on-one play around
the net, they probably won't create more speed through the neutral
zone,'' Verbeek said. ``This might sound crazy, but what they need
to do is outlaw the trap just like the NBA outlawed the zone
defense. If they do that, then maybe we can get some real scoring
back.''
</P>
<P>
   That does sound crazy. But right now, the scorers are desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, really,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``Can we look at some way to
juice the puck? They have to be able to do something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
