<HEADLINE>
1999 IRL SEASON FINALE SET FOR TEXAS MOTOR SPEEDWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A yearlong effort to make Texas Motor
Speedway the feature venue for the Indy Racing League outside of
Indianapolis has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   TMS general manager Eddie Gossage, with the aid of IRL driver
and Plano resident Greg Ray, announced yesterday that the speedway
will be host to the 1999 Pep Boys Indy Racing League season finale,
a race that could potentially crown the series champion. The Lone
Star 500K is scheduled for Sunday, Oct. 17, 1999, and again will be
the second of two IRL stops at the 1.5-mile superspeedway next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better place to decide a championship than at the Texas
Motor Speedway,'' said Fred Nation, vice president of corporate
communications and public relations for the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. ``Everything's big in Texas. We want the Pep Boys Indy
Racing League championship to be excited to be at the biggest place
we run on the planet outside of Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the interest IRL races have drawn at TMS, Gossage and
Ray have lobbied IRL officials to host the finale for almost a
year. The track was able to add a second date this season, but the
possible fireworks of a championship-crowning race is what the
speedway sought.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL's first stop at TMS next season will be June 12, the
first stop after the Indianapolis 500. TMS is the only speedway to
play host to two IRL races and has drawn crowds second only to the
Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic for the speedway and for the Indy Racing
League,'' Ray said. ``And being a hometown boy, it's fantastic for
me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Local fans have shown their desire to watch the 220-plus-mph
performances and side-by-side racing the IRL has brought to Texas.
Last month's race drew an estimated 81,000 fans and the night race
drew around 100,000. Both events were the top two draws outside the
Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw cars doing things that they simply aren't supposed to
do,'' Gossage said. ``We said this really has something going for
it, and we want to be the leader. We are the shining star on the
IRL schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Nation said IRL planned to release the season's full schedule
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to a Texas-sized celebration a year from
now,'' Nation said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
