<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERRY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES OUTFIELDER STRAWBERRY HAS COLON CANCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry
talked to his manager and teammates before Wednesday's evening
playoff game against the Rangers, and told them not to worry about
a few extra medical tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees knew better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see in his eyes that there was more than that,'' Tim
Raines said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 36, yesterday was diagnosed with colon cancer after
tests at Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center in New York. He is
scheduled to have surgery tomorrow to remove a walnut-sized tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Yankees were scheduled to start batting practice
here yesterday afternoon, Strawberry called the visiting clubhouse.
Andy Pettitte, who pitched the Yankees to a 2-0 lead in Game 2,
answered the phone. New York manager Joe Torre heard from a
teary-eyed Pettitte, then spoke with Strawberry before calling a
team meeting to inform the rest of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was complete silence, some sobbing, very sad people,''
Torre said. ``Hopefully, this is just another obstacle he will be
able to handle. There was no question he was trying to be upbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Strawberry's condition was a reality check for his
team, which could not celebrate a 3-1 victory Wednesday quite like
the Yankees wanted. The somber mood of Yankees players continued
after batting practice yesterday, which ended at about 6 p.m.
Yankees players gathered on the field at The Ballpark in Arlington.
With his teammates crowded around him, Raines spoke to Strawberry
on camera with ESPN analyst Harold Reynolds before the Yankees
retired to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a message in person, and we're hoping that Darryl was
watching,'' Raines said. ``We want to make sure Darryl knew we're
behind him and his family. We know how strong he is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the location of the tumor and Darryl's otherwise
excellent health, the prognosis for a full recovery is excellent,''
Yankees spokesman Rick Cerrone said.
</P>
<P>
   About 95,000 cases of colon cancer are detected each year,
according to the American Cancer Society. An estimated 46,000
people die of colon cancer annually. The five-year survival rate is
61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's boyhood friend and fellow ballplayer Eric Davis is
recovering from colon cancer. Davis, who grew up with Strawberry in
South Central Los Angeles, found out he had cancer last season. The
Baltimore Orioles' designated hitter bounced back this year to have
one of his best seasons, finishing fourth in the American League
batting race.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry spoke with Davis yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's upbeat about it and ready for the challenges that he's
going to have,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, once the toast of New York baseball as a young star
with the New York Mets, overcame his addiction to drugs and other
off-field problems to resurrect his career as a part-time player
with the Yankees. He capped his comeback by helping the Yankees win
the 1996 World Series. This season, he hit 24 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees teammates vowed to not let him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team was a little bit down today, but we all understand
Darryl would want us to go out, wear his heart and courage on our
sleeves and we will do that tomorrow,'' catcher Joe Giradi said.
``He doesn't want us to sit and worry about him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
