<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF STRAWBERRY'S ILLNESS RATTLES CONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JEFF SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Darryl Strawberry stunned his New York
Yankees teammates when he called the visiting clubhouse at The
Ballpark in Arlington yesterday to inform them he had been
diagnosed with a cancerous tumor in his colon. No one took the news
harder than tonight's starting pitcher, David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all very worried, very concerned, but we're also all
optimistic that he can beat this,'' said Cone, visibly shaken at a
news conference. ``Our hearts are really with him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cone, the news hit close to home.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, his former Kansas City Royals teammate, Dan
Quisenberry, died after a nine-month battle with brain cancer. Cone
himself missed four months of the 1996 season after undergoing
surgery to remove an aneurysm from his right arm.
</P>
<P>
   When put into perspective, it's understandable why baseball
games don't mean as much as they once did to Cone, long known as
one of the game's best big-game pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a rookie in Kansas City, Dan was a big influence on
my career,'' said Cone, who will put Strawberry's No. 39 on the
back of his hat tonight. ``When you look back at the past couple of
days and see what happened to him and his family, it shakes you up.
You kind of forget about hanging a slider or the magnitude of the
game and realize what's important when someone's health is on the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   As Strawberry's is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl and I have been close for a long time, and we've had
our ups and downs in New York,'' Cone said of his New York Mets
teammate from 1987-90 and his Yankees teammate since 1996. ``I'm
sure he's going through the same fears I was, and that he doesn't
know what's going on. He probably doesn't understand all the
medical jargon that's being thrown his way. It's an extremely
difficult situation and it can be very confusing and very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone said education is a key to helping cope when struck with
the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went through my situation, I didn't understand what was
happening to me. I needed to be educated,'' Cone said. ``I didn't
know if it was life or death or if my career was over but those
sort of life-and-death situations supersede baseball in every
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who was informed of his condition in May 1996, returned to
pitch in September. His baseball career, by far his secondary
career at that point, would not be over.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from his own medical nightmare, Cone has won a
World Series game, been a part of his second world championship
team and pitched in an All-Star Game. And Sunday, he won his 20th
game, becoming the first pitcher in major-league history to produce
20-win seasons 11 years apart.
</P>
<P>
   And, although his 1998 statistics (20-9 record, 3.55 ERA, 209
strikeouts) are not as impressive as his 1988 numbers (20-3, 2.22
ERA, 213 strikeouts) with the New York Mets, Cone is regarded as a
money pitcher come October.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remind yourself that you really weren't supposed
to get him back until probably May or June,'' Yankees manager Joe
Torre said. ``Once he settled in and started giving us the number
of innings that he gave us, that was incredible for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Rangers should expect the usual from Cone, a
fastball in the low 90s which will come from multiple release
points, one of baseball's best splitters, two curveballs that come
in at different speeds, and a few sliders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers are a dangerous team right now because they have
nothing to lose and it's my job not to let them get any momentum
going their way,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   However, no matter how dangerous Cone believes the Rangers might
be, he knows firsthand that nothing in baseball _ even a playoff
game _ means as much to him as what happened over the past two
days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
