</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INTERNET-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAIR TAXATION IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth in sales of goods over the Internet raises hard
questions about how states might fairly tax those transactions. The
same problem has existed for years in mail-order sales. Consumers
are technically liable for sales taxes on all purchases, including
out-of-state catalog purchases, but mail-order companies are
required to collect sales taxes only in states where they maintain
a physical presence. This loophole costs state and local
governments about $3.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The National Governors' Association and local government groups
are rightly worried that they will lose billions more a year from
Internet sales that would otherwise be taxable in a traditional
store. That loss _ estimated to reach $10 billion a year in the
next decade _ will have a disproportionate impact on states that
depend heavily on sales taxes, providing a tax break mostly for the
affluent who have access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Online service providers and electronic commerce lobbying
groups, of course, want to make cyberspace tax-free, arguing that
taxation would choke off Internet growth. Tax policy should not
discriminate against electronic sales. But neither should the
Internet be protected from taxes that apply in other realms of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should keep the principle of parity in mind as it works
through the proposed Internet Tax Freedom Act. The bill is intended
to give state and federal officials some breathing room to tackle
these issues in a coordinated fashion. The House version, approved
in June, would establish a three-year moratorium on any new
Internet sales taxes and taxes on access to online services. It
would also create a national advisory commission to examine ways to
improve tax collection on all remote sales, including possible
changes in Federal law to close the out-of-state-sales loophole.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, which debates the bill Friday, should resist
extending the moratorium to five years, as some senators want. A
long moratorium is unnecessary and would be hard to undo as
consumers and businesses become accustomed to a tax-free
cyberspace. In the meantime, the dozen states that have enacted
Internet access taxes should be allowed to keep those taxes in
place. Congress has no good reason to truncate state taxing
authority, particularly since Internet commerce is thriving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-McCAFFREY-NYT &LR;      10-01 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-McCAFFREY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MAYOR OWES THE DRUG WAR'S GENERAL A SALUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's enduring passions is
to demonize people as moral or social defectives when their only
sin is daring to disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   No question, a lot of New Yorkers admire that part of his
personality. Polls consistently show that many approve of the
pugnacious way he sets his agenda, even when they also describe him
as unlikable. It takes a tough guy to run a tough town, and all
that.
</P>
<P>
   But New Yorkers do not lack an appreciation for fair play.
</P>
<P>
   Just as many of them, if not more, are weary of being constantly
lectured about civility by someone who is cosmically uncivil to
those holding opinions different from his own. Time and again, the
mayor has taken a verbal blowtorch to people offering even mild
dissent, casting them as morally bankrupt, politically fossilized,
fiscally corrupt or, one of his favorite constructions,
intellectually dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani may have outdone himself in his recent jihad against
methadone programs for heroin addicts.
</P>
<P>
   He was not content simply to preach the virtues of abstinence
from all drugs while taking exception with Gen. Barry McCaffrey,
the White House drug czar, who proposes expanding methadone
treatment. Even though this is a complex matter crying out for
reasoned debate, the mayor, as usual, could not keep from picking
up the same flamethrower that he aims at the likes of Khallid Abdul
Muhammad. He cast the general as an enemy of decency.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give up the idea of a drug-free America is a disgrace,'' he
said. He also said, ``I think General McCaffrey is a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   That made James McDonough mad.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough is the director of strategy in McCaffrey's drug-policy
office. That makes him something less than a neutral observer. But
as a retired Army officer himself, he has known the general for 30
years. And to hear his colleague being vilified with words like
``disaster'' and ``disgrace'' was more than he could take.
</P>
<P>
   ``To characterize him as a disaster,'' McDonough said by phone
from Washington, ``is profoundly unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   And profoundly disrespectful, others would add. Agree or not
with McCaffrey's ideas on drugs, he has more than earned the right
to courteous treatment, especially from someone who never wore his
country's uniform, like Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   This ``disaster,'' now 56, was the youngest four-star general,
as well as the most highly decorated Army general on active duty,
when President Clinton appointed him to the drug post in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross, the United
States' second-highest medal for valor. ``If you get one, that's
incredible,'' McDonough said. ``If you get two, you're lucky to be
alive.'' Other McCaffrey medals include two Silver Stars, three
Bronze Stars and three Purple Hearts, for wounds received in the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you about that third Purple Heart,'' McDonough
said. ``He's commanding an infantry company, attacking a dug-in
North Vietnamese unit, when he takes a .50-caliber round in his
left arm. It almost completely severs the arm. Those rounds are
big. The fact that he doesn't die is a miracle. But he refuses to
be evacuated. Why? There he is, a young company commander who
doesn't want to leave his men.''
</P>
<P>
   His wounds were so severe that his wife, Jill, burned the
letters that he had written her, to help them erase the memory of
the war. Eventually, he regained use of the arm. Years later,
during the Persian Gulf war, McCaffrey led the 24th Infantry
Division on the ``left hook'' assault up the banks of the Euphrates
that wiped out dozens of Iraqi divisions.
</P>
<P>
   And where was Giuliani, who is about the same age, while Barry
McCaffrey was getting shot up in Vietnam? Attending law school and
clerking for a federal judge, who wrote to the draft board to
secure a deferment for his protege.
</P>
<P>
   That puts the mayor in the same category as other tough-talking
Republican men of the Vietnam generation who may have their eyes on
the White House: Dan Quayle, Newt Gingrich, Pat Buchanan, Jack
Kemp. One way or another, all managed to avoid regular Army service
when the bullets were flying.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, while he was being reviled as a disaster, McCaffrey
was asked what he thought of Giuliani. He called him ``a great
mayor,'' having learned at the cost of his own blood what it means
to be an officer and a gentleman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
