<DOCNO> NYT19981001.0510 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      10-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBI DENIES PLAYING POLITICS  
 FROM WEAPONS TO LECTURE TOURS  
 END OF A SOLO  
 UNFAMILIAR ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Those who expect politics _ or religion _ to exist in
a vacuum don't know New York.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting the Kol Nidre service Tuesday evening at Central
Synagogue's temporary sanctuary in the 7th Regiment Armory on Park
Avenue, RABBI PETER RUBINSTEIN asked the congregation to take note
of someone he said had been a special friend to the congregation in
the last few weeks, SENATOR ALFONSE D'AMATO.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation's 126-year-old landmark home was damaged in a
fire in August, and Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur services were held
at the armory using a backdrop created by the designer Robert
Isabell.
</P>
<P>
   The D'Amato introduction troubled some in the congregation.
``Whatever he did, mention it in the newsletter,'' said one person
who attended the service. ``I'd be equally outraged if it were
Chuck Schumer.'' Schumer is D'Amato's Democratic challenger.
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN KLEIN, the president of the synagogue, said that the
mention of D'Amato and other public officials was not meant to
inject politics into the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in any way, shape or form,'' he said. ``This is a
religious event, it was a spiritual evening and we did pay thanks
to a host of people who had been very helpful to us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he and Rubinstein had also mentioned Gov. George
Pataki, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, state Sen. Roy Goodman, and Jerome
Hauer, the director of the Mayor's Office of Emergency Management,
all of whom had attended the Rosh Hashana service.
</P>
<P>
   From Weapons to Lecture Tours
</P>
<P>
   SCOTT RITTER, who quit last month as the U.S. weapons inspector
in Iraq, has decided to try talking to nondiplomats for a while.
Ritter, 37, is heading to the lecture circuit. This week he signed
a deal with Greater Talent Network, a lecture-booking agency that
also represents RICHARD HOLBROOKE, President Clinton's choice for
representative at the United Nations; ADMIRAL WILLIAM CROWE JR.,
the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and New York GOV.
GEORGE PATAKI.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter was said to be traveling Thursday and not available to
discuss what he plans to lecture about. The head of Greater Talent,
DON EPSTEIN, would not say how much money Ritter would command as a
speaker, but did say that he was marketing Ritter to corporations
and colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``For colleges, he wants to get the word out, talk about Iraq,''
Epstein said. ``Corporate America sees him from a different point
of view: leadership, crisis management, strategic planning. He
relates to them, Wall Street, the banks, what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein also said that Ritter _ who charged the Clinton
administration with privately blocking efforts to uncover Iraq's
clandestine weapons programs while publicly expressing support _
was not interested in playing the Washington game of attack and
counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no ax,'' Epstein said of Ritter. ``He's a Boy Scout
kind of guy. You really have the sense that he really knows what's
going on here, but he doesn't want to make this personal and he
thinks that everybody else is making it personal.''
</P>
<P>
   End of a Solo
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Friday is the last day that the ``Today'' show host
is a single guy. MATT LAUER is scheduled to marry ANNETTE ROQUE on
Saturday in Water Mill. And Lauer's decorator, JENNIFER POST, has
been busy.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer hired Ms. Post to work on his East Side apartment before
he began dating Ms. Roque. But with Ms. Roque moving uptown from
her loft in TriBeCa, Ms. Post has made some changes. She removed
what she called ``some of the masculine touches,'' like sailing and
golfing prints. ``She's bringing her pictures, her art,'' Ms. Post
said, not to mention antiques. Lauer also agreed to give up a
golfing closet for wardrobe space, Ms. Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfamiliar Role
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ARNOT WALKER was not a household name except,
perhaps, in two high-profile realms, the Democratic party and ABC
News.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday PETER JENNINGS was the anchor for something quite
different from a newscast: a memorial service for Walker, who had
been his spokesman for eight years and who died on Monday. Before
he went to ABC News, Walker worked for BELLA ABZUG, GERALDINE
FERRARO, WALTER MONDALE, JOHN GLENN, FRANK LAUTENBERG and other
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings looked out at the crowd of 600 at the Brick Church, on
Park Avenue at 91st Street _ a crowd that included the chairman of
ABC News, ROONE ARLEDGE, and dozens of correspondents, producers
and executives _ and thanked them on behalf of Walker's ``most
intimate friends.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped, shook his head and tried again. ``We are all Arnot's
most intimate friends,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
