<SLUG> BC-TOXIC-WEED-ILLNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 N.J. TEENS HOSPITALIZED AFTER INGESTING TOXIC WEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.J. _ As four teen-agers lay in the hospital after
eating a toxic weed to try to get high, teachers at Howell Township
High School in this small flatlands town found themselves giving
unusual drug lectures on Thursday _ on the dangers of the wild and
plentiful plant, which grows within a block of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after one such talk, a 16-year-old boy went to the
nurse's office, complaining he was not feeling well after having
ingested the seeds of the plant, jimson weed, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The five cases underline what appears to be the growing
popularity of the weed among teen-agers in the area seeking a quick
high _ whether or not they know of its potentially deadly effects.
Howell Police Detective Eric Rice said bags of 100 seeds sell for
$5, and teen-agers chat about them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Three days ago, the four teen-age boys became critically ill
after eating the seeds. Three of them remained in critical
condition Thursday at the Jersey Shore Medical Center in nearby
Neptune, while the fourth was listed in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials refused to identify them or discuss their
cases. But Dr. Charles Dadzie, head of the pediatric unit, said all
were still suffering from hallucinations, rapid heartbeats,
periodic seizures and dryness of the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The boy who was stricken Thursday was also at the hospital, and
listed Thursday afternoon in satisfactory condition, with symptoms
less severe than the four earlier victims. They include a
13-year-old, two 15-year-olds and a 16-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Daniel Cosgrove of the New Jersey State Police said the
earlier victims were too incoherent from the effects of the weed to
tell police about how they came to ingest it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were totally out of it,'' he said. ``The next day, they
were still out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that we get the word out to other young people,
that they don't go out and try it,'' he said. ``It can have a fatal
effect on your system. You can slip into a coma.''
</P>
<P>
   Information on how many seeds the five ingested was not
available, but Dadzie said that one can get a poisonous reaction by
ingesting as few as 20 of the peppercorn-size seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have declined to discuss where the
five victims obtained the seeds or where they were when they ate
them. But the seeds are easily obtainable.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters found several of the three-foot-tall jimson weed
plants at the edge of a cornfield, growing among some wild
raspberries near from Howell High School.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the plants were common in open fields and
woodlands and along creek banks throughout Farmingdale and
surrounding Howell Township, including the meadows south of the
Howell police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Students said they did not believe that use among local students
was rampant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anyone who goes near them,'' said one high school
senior, Stefanie Negro. She said her classmates had a mixed
reaction to the five cases. ``I feel bad they're suffering,'' Ms.
Negro said as she started work this afternoon at an ice cream
parlor on Main Street. ``But don't go asking for trouble. If you do
something stupid you've got to expect problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But some officials fear that the recent spotlight on jimson weed
is prompting other teen-agers to try it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids hear that it's a hallucinogen, and they think it could be
a good high,'' said Dr. Steven Marcus, executive director of the
education program for the New Jersey Poison Control Center. ``But
it's extremely hard to control the dose and the side effects are
completely disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said there was no part of the plant that was safe. ``The
roots are toxic. The leaves are toxic. The pods are toxic,'' he
said. ``The stems are toxic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
