<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AMBULANCE-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBULANCE DRIVER ARRESTED AFTER CRASH KILLS THREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An ambulance driver was arrested on charges of
manslaughter Thursday after the police said she sped through a red
light on a nonemergency call and caused a crash that killed three
children Wednesday night in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The children _ aged 2, 5 and 7 _ died almost instantly when the
Nissan Sentra that their mother was driving was struck by the
private ambulance at 11:55 p.m., the police said. Their 9-year-old
sister was critically injured in the crash, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the ambulance, Anne Lamberson, 34, of Queens, was
arrested on three counts of manslaughter, said Detective Thomas
McGrath of the accident investigation squad.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said, ``It was not a legitimate
emergency, and she should not have been driving with her lights and
sirens on, and she should not have gone through a red light.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lamberson was driving east on Kings Highway at 50 to 70 mph
_ the limit there is 30 mph _ when she ran through a red light at
Bedford Avenue and struck the car, which was going south, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The car was being driven by Angela Igwe, 32, an immigrant from
Nigeria who was taking her four children home to Coney Island from
the Flatbush beauty parlor where she works. Horrified witnesses
described seeing Ms. Igwe crawling out of the car and begging for
help for her children, who were trapped inside the crumpled
wreckage. No one in the car had been wearing a seat belt, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was screaming that she was losing her children, that she
needed a telephone to call for help,'' said Sean Doyle, 22, who
heard the crash and saw neighbors rush to try to pull the children
from the car.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the police and ambulances arrived and took the
injured to hospitals. One of Ms. Igwe's sons, Akintonde Morak, 2,
was pronounced dead at Coney Island Hospital; her other son,
Olusegun Morak, 5, was pronounced dead at Community Hospital of
Brooklyn, and one of her daughters, Damilola Morak, 7, was
pronounced dead at Kings County Hospital Center, the police said.
Ms. Igwe and her eldest daughter, Ibornka Morak, 9, were taken to
Kings County Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday afternoon, Ms. Igwe was listed in serious but
stable condition; Ibornka was in critical condition, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   An uncle of the children, Isaac Muyibi, 38, visited the scene of
the crash Thursday and saw the crumpled Nissan, with the tiny
sneakers that belonged to his nephews and niece still lying by the
bloodstained back seat. ``When I saw the sneakers of those kids, it
touched me more than I can say,'' he said somberly Thursday when he
returned to Ms. Igwe's apartment. ``There was so much damage. I can
only imagine the pain that they had gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said the ambulance, which is operated by Transcare
Ambulance, a private company in Long Island City, Queens, was on
its way to pick up a patient on East 86th Street in Canarsie for a
``nonpriority'' medical call when it crashed into Ms. Igwe's car,
which had the right of way. He said skid marks indicated that the
ambulance driver tried to brake just before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances of the city's Emergency Medical Service, like police
and fire vehicles, are allowed to speed and run through red lights
in emergencies provided that they slow down before the light to
make sure that the intersection is clear.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Smith, a spokeswoman for the state's Department of
Health, which monitors private ambulance companies, said that only
in emergencies where there is the potential for loss of life or
limb should private ambulances use their lights and sirens or speed
and run red lights.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Transcare Ambulance were not returned Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
