<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE KILLING IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its European allies are rapidly
approaching a decision point on whether to take military action to
end Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's butchery in Kosovo. The
need for outside intervention is urgent. Recent days have brought
harrowing reports of massacres of women, children and the elderly
by Serbian forces. With winter coming, hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have been driven from their homes, many
having to hide without shelter or food in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Milosevic withdraws his special police, who are
responsible for the brutality in Kosovo, in a matter of days, NATO
warplanes and cruise missiles should strike Serbian airfields and
military installations in Kosovo and the rest of Serbia until he
does. As long as Serbian forces are present, the displaced in
Kosovo will remain in the hills, where they may starve or freeze to
death this winter. Kosovo's humanitarian organizations must be able
to move freely to provide assistance to these people and help them
return to and rebuild their destroyed villages.
</P>
<P>
   The objective of air strikes should be limited to getting
Milosevic to deliver on his repeatedly broken promise to withdraw
his security forces. This should be accompanied by an investigation
by the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia of
whether he should be indicted for the massacres.
</P>
<P>
   The use of military force is not the ideal way to handle the
conflict in Kosovo, especially because Washington and the
international community do not support the desire of Kosovo's
Albanians to create an independent state. Negotiation would have
been the best way to secure a restoration of the self-government
that Milosevic stripped from Kosovo in 1989, and perhaps even to
secure the granting of autonomous status for Kosovo equal to that
of Serbia or Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic's ethnic cleansing and attacks on innocents have
pushed the world to the brink of a military response. U.S.
officials said Thursday that Milosevic had about two weeks to stop
the attacks and remove his forces. The United Nations Security
Council should authorize the use of force. If it fails to do so
because of Russian opposition, which is likely, NATO should move
ahead anyway if military action proves necessary to save thousands
of lives.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, France and Italy have been reluctant to intervene
without a firm Security Council resolution. But all three have
edged toward approval of air strikes even without explicit Security
Council authorization in recent days because of public pressure at
home and disclosure of the massacres. NATO ambassadors are now
meeting nearly daily, and member nations have pledged fighter
planes for air strikes. NATO has not yet taken a final decision,
however. If all members of the alliance are not willing to
intervene, Washington, London and other partners they can muster
should be prepared to act on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has a history of using terror, then retreating under
threat of force, only to resume his attacks when the world turns to
other problems. In Kosovo, Serbian officials are already declaring
that their military campaign is over. If that is the case, there
may still be time for a negotiated settlement. But Washington must
be wary of Milosevic's feints, and be ready to take action if the
killing and intimidation continue. A lack of resolve will only
further embolden him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-98 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
