<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES COME FROM BEHIND TO TAKE 2-GAME LEAD OVER CUBS IN DIVISIONAL
PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the ninth inning, the Chicago Cubs were two outs
from victory. But when Thursday night's game ended, they were one
loss from elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a dramatic home run by Javy Lopez, a game-winning hit
by Chipper Jones, and critical mistakes by the Cubs, the Atlanta
Braves have grabbed a commanding 2-0 lead in this
three-of-five-game division series.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the bottom of the ninth inning, and the Braves
trailing, 1-0, Lopez hit a towering home run to left field that
sent the game into extra innings. Then in the bottom of the 10th, a
one-out single by Jones scored Walt Weiss from second base, giving
Atlanta a thrilling 2-1 victory at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional victory for the Braves, and a deflating loss
for the Cubs, who were on the verge of tying the series, riding a
masterly pitching performance by Kevin Tapani.
</P>
<P>
   But it all fell apart for the Cubs after Lopez hit a long drive
over the left-field fence that sent the Turner Field record crowd
of 51,713 into a frenzy. It tied the game, it ruined Tapani's
shutout, and it was the start of a disaster for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Things continued to go badly for the Cubs in their 10th when
they ran themselves out of an opportunity to take the lead. A walk
to Glenallen Hill, a sacrifice by Gary Gaetti, an intentional walk
to Mickey Morandini, and a steal of third base by Hill gave Chicago
runners at the corners with one out.
</P>
<P>
   But on a 3-2 count, Jeff Blauser struck out, and it turned into
an inning-ending double play when Lopez threw out Morandini who was
going on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Morandini threw down his helmet in disgust, as Hill looked on in
disbelief, stranded at third base. Then the Braves ended the game
against Terry Mulholland, who took over from Tapani (nine innings,
five hits, seven strikeouts, three walks). Weiss walked with one
out, then the Cubs made another mistake, when Tony Graffanino laid
down a sacrifice bunt, and Mulholland missed the bag covering first
base after taking a flip toss from Mark Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino was safe at first, putting runners on first and
second with one out. Jones hit the next pitch for a line drive to
left field that easily scored Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves ran onto the field in celebration. The Cubs walked
off the field dejectedly. They will try to keep their season alive
in Game 3, Saturday night at Wrigley Field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That the game evolved into a pitchers' duel between Tom Glavine
and Tapani was no surprise. Glavine was a 20-game winner during the
regular season, and he has won more games (179) than any other
left-hander over the last 11 years. Tapani fell just short of the
20-victory mark (19-6), and he defeated the Braves twice during the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine could not have pitched much better on Thursday night,
allowing just three hits, striking out seven, and walking one
through seven innings. But after five scoreless innings, Chicago
got its first hit of the game, its first run of the game, and its
first lead in the series in the top of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Morandini led off by grounding a single to right field. Scott
Servais followed with a flared single to right, putting runners on
first and second. After a nifty sacrifice bunt by Tapani moved the
runners up, the Braves kept the infield back, and Lance Johnson's
groundout to second base scored Morandini.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine retired the Cubs by striking out Manny Alexander on a
questionable call, but scoring the first run of the game was a big
psychological boost for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   With Glavine making the Cubs look so feeble at the plate, the
weight fell on Tapani to keep the Cubs in the game. And Tapani was
up to the task. He ended an Atlanta threat in the first inning by
striking out Ryan Klesko with two out and runners at the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the fifth inning, Tapani escaped more trouble by
cleaning up a mess he created. Tapani made his first mistake by
walking the eighth-place hitter, Michael Tucker. That allowed
Glavine to sacrifice Tucker to second base.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tapani made another mistake, when he was called for a balk
by the plate umpire, Bill Hohn, moving Tucker to third base with
one out.
</P>
<P>
   But at that point, Tapani did some of his best pitching. He
struck out Weiss swinging to keep Tucker at third, then ended the
inning by getting Keith Lockhart to fly out to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta threatened again in the seventh inning, but Tapani bore
down. After Tucker singled with two out, Manager Bobby Cox sent
Ozzie Guillen up to bat for Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tucker stole second base, giving Guillen a chance to drive
home a run. But Tapani got Guillen to ground softly back to the
mound, and Chicago took its 1-0 lead into the eighth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
