<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-01 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-DEBATES-NYT &LR;      10-01 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-DEBATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE ACCUSES PATAKI OF AVOIDING GUBERNATORIAL DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In strikingly harsh terms, Peter Vallone's
gubernatorial campaign Thursday accused Gov. George Pataki of
ducking debates with Vallone, echoing the charges that Pataki
leveled four years ago at Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, has tried to make it
impossible for Pataki to say no to debates by placing no conditions
on them. He has said that any time, place or format the governor
chooses will be fine with him, and he has left it to Pataki, a
Republican, to decide whether minor-party candidates will be
included.
</P>
<P>
   More than two weeks have passed since Vallone won the Democratic
primary and began calling, almost daily, for debates. But talks
over when, where and how the candidates should meet appear to have
broken down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just clear that they're not serious about debates,''
Kevin McCabe, Vallone's campaign manager, said in an interview
Thursday. ``It's a game. It's a silly, hypocritical, pathetic
little game they're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   McCabe and Pataki's campaign manager, Zenia Mucha, met Sept. 23
to discuss terms of possible debates. According to both of them,
McCabe said any terms were acceptable, leaving it to Ms. Mucha to
dictate them.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe said he had asked for another meeting as soon as possible
and that Ms. Mucha had not yet responded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mucha conceded that she had put off any more talks, and she
would not say when they would resume. She said she broke off
negotiations because Vallone had distorted the governor's record on
issues from abortion to college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's important that he be given some extra time to
educate himself about the issues that affect the state and to
acquaint himself with the governor's record,'' she said of Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he begins to demonstrate some knowledge of the issues and
some knowledge of the governor's record, we'll sit down and discuss
it. Until then, I don't see any need to continue negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was not stalling, trying to avoid debates or to
wait until so late in the campaign that they would have no effect.
``We intend to debate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Vallone, the matter is urgent, even desperate. With less
than five weeks to go in the campaign, he trails Pataki by a wide
margin in the polls and in the size of his campaign treasury, and
badly needs a dramatic stroke to spur his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's campaign said Thursday that the governor, who has
already spent $10 million in his re-election bid, had $9.2 million
on hand. Vallone's camp said the challenger had about $248,000 on
hand, after spending $4.4 million so far. The gubernatorial
candidates must file campaign disclosure statements Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Vallone tried to focus attention Thursday on debates and not
on campaign war chests.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional political wisdom is that a strong incumbent would
not want to debate because it would raise the opponent's stature
and risk the sort of televised blunder that could make a lead
quickly evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   But as debates become increasingly common in campaigns, voters
might take a dim view of a front-runner who openly shunned them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Pataki demanded debates with Cuomo, but they never took
place. He said of the incumbent, ``He lacks the guts to show up and
debate me one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   In this year's primaries, the Democratic candidates for
governor, state attorney general and the U.S. Senate all met in
debates.
</P>
<P>
   If Pataki agreed to debates, the most difficult question about
the terms would be whether to include minor-party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross, a Republican turned Democrat, is
the Liberal Party nominee, but neither Vallone's camp nor Pataki's
is inclined to include her in debates.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Party nominee B. Thomas Golisano, who drew 4
percent of the vote in the 1994 race, would be the most difficult
to ignore because he has spent so much money on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   After saying last month that he would spend $10 million of his
money on this race, Golisano raised the figure this week to $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   That would roughly match Pataki's spending but over a shorter
period of time, allowing Golisano in the final month of the race to
mount one of the most intensive media campaigns the state has seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
