<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LAWRENCE-NOBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOUNDING LAWRENCE NOBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   Congressional conference committees are supposed to be the forum
where lawmakers resolve differences between bills passed by the
House and Senate, not reverse key policy decisions on which both
chambers basically agree. Yet Republican congressional leaders have
badly abused the conference process to pursue their obsessive drive
to oust Lawrence Noble, the able general counsel of the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Noble's various investigations of Republican fund-raising
practices and his efforts to end soft-money abuses have not pleased
the GOP. But he has a record of evenhanded enforcement, and his
allies managed to thwart earlier attempts to get rid of him by
amending the Treasury spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana, the leader of the
anti-Noble forces, refuses to concede defeat, and this week his
stubbornness was rewarded. Over the objection of Democrats,
language designed to force Noble's removal was included in the
final bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., has vowed a filibuster. If Levin
succeeds, the Republicans would then be expected to attach the
Treasury bill _ and with it the objectionable anti-Noble provision
_ to an omnibus spending bill that will be sent to the White House.
President Clinton needs to make plain now that he will not sign any
bill that contains an attack on Noble and, more broadly, the FEC's
independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
