</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GRAND-CENTRAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GRAND CENTRAL, REBORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers, always on the lookout for interesting places to
rendezvous, can now add the Main Concourse of Grand Central
Terminal to the city's list of grand indoor spaces. The Beaux-Arts
structure, of course, remains a railroad station that must
accommodate nearly 500,000 people a day. But it is now full of
simple pleasures that can be had free and on foot, from the
sweeping new marble staircase at the east end to the celestial
beauty of the restored Sky Ceiling mural 120 feet above the
concourse floor. And what better place could there be to meet a
friend or arriving visitor than the four-sided brass clock in the
center of the concourse?
</P>
<P>
   The terminal was rededicated Thursday, an official act that will
not put an end to debates among preservationists and purists about
the esthetic choices the architects and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority made during the process of restoration.
There is already disappointment about some of these choices. But it
is important to remember that the mission was to restore a 1913
rail terminal, with all the commercial bustle that entails, not to
create a brand new space.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Central's new guardians, chiefly the MTA, now confront two
challenges. The most obvious is to ensure that the $200 million
that this project will ultimately cost will not be wasted by
subsequent neglect. The old terminal fell victim to the ravages of
deferred maintenance. That cannot be allowed to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Second, even though about 90 percent of the commercial space has
now been leased, there will inevitably be turnover. Responsible
officials must make sure that future tenants, and the design of the
spaces they occupy, are compatible with the overall majesty of the
space. This is, after all, one of the great gateways to the city,
and it would be a travesty if commuters and visitors found
themselves trekking through yet another deadening shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   These are not unreasonable fears. In June the MTA allowed a
115-foot-long banner promoting the movie ``Godzilla'' and a laptop
computer to cover three arched windows over the east balcony. This
was a temporary expedient, the authority says, but even so, it did
not inspire confidence. It made one wonder whether the authority
truly appreciates what the architects have wrought _ whether, in
other words, it understands that the light that streams through the
terminal's huge windows is just as important as the time and money
that has been spent on restoring them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
