<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXI AGENCY SAYS CABBIES TAMPERED WITH METERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tampering with taxi meters may no longer be as
prevalent as it once was, but the practice is not extinct, Taxi and
Limousine Commission inspectors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Eight cabbies had their licenses suspended Thursday after a
sting operation at John F. Kennedy International Airport turned up
three ``zappers'' _ devices attached to meters to make them run
faster _ and five other yellow cabs with evidence of
meter-tampering. The inspectors also temporarily suspended the
medallions of the cabs, blocking their owners from operating them.
</P>
<P>
   The taxi commission refused to release the names of the owners
and drivers, but said it would consider revoking the drivers'
licenses permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an egregious crime that we really view as stabbing
right into the heart of the integrity of the industry,'' said Allan
J. Fromberg, the agency's spokesman. ``Our intention is to see that
these people never have this kind of opportunity again.''
</P>
<P>
   The drivers and owners do not face criminal charges, Fromberg
said, because there is no criminal statute that covers tampering
with a taxi meter. Drivers would face administrative hearings
before their licenses could be revoked, and Fromberg said the
owners could be forced to sell their medallions.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors made the rounds of the cab holding areas at
Kennedy and La Guardia airports beginning at 4 a.m. and checked 300
cabs mostly at random, Fromberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the cabs that were checked were on a list of 175
vehicles that were the subject of overcharging complaints in recent
months. Of those seven, one was found to have a zapper.
</P>
<P>
   Fromberg said the zappers _ all found at Kennedy Airport _ were
wired into the meter to allow a driver to send an electronic pulse
to the meter, causing it to advance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
