<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-APOLLO-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCO SEEKS THE REMOVAL OF THE APOLLO THEATER BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The state attorney general's Office filed a lawsuit
late Thursday that seeks to remove Rep. Charles Rangel and several
other board members of the nonprofit foundation that runs the
Apollo Theater, contending that the board failed to manage the
theater's finances responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit represents the latest twist of fortune for a Harlem
landmark. In May, state officials announced that they would
withhold $750,000 in loans and grants from the foundation until
questions about its finances were answered.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the theater's stagehands went on strike in a squabble
that state officials said was related to the theater's finances.
The strike was settled earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, Dennis Vacco, the state attorney general, has been
investigating whether the nonprofit Apollo Theater Foundation,
which manages the state-owned theater, made deals that were
inordinately beneficial to Percy Sutton, the former Manhattan
borough president, who produced shows at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco contends that there were inappropriate business dealings
between Sutton _ a close friend of Rangel's _ and the board that
enabled Sutton's company, Inner City Broadcasting, to significantly
underpay the foundation for control of the television show, ``It's
Showtime at the Apollo.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Vacco has called for the removal of the entire
board in order to examine the foundation's finances, which Vacco's
office says are in utter disarray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' Vacco said in a statement, ``the Apollo
officers and directors generally abdicated through their conduct
and omissions, their legal responsibility to reasonably, prudently,
loyally, carefully and obediently, manage all of the affairs of the
foundation. As a consequence, they have caused financial harm to
one of Harlem's, and one of New York City's, greatest assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, a Harlem Democrat, said Thursday night that the
theater's finances are in good shape. He said that he had yet to
see the complaint, but he speculated that the lawsuit was rooted
more in Vacco's campaign for re-election than in any financial
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange that this is happening this close to the
election,'' Rangel, speaking by telephone from his office in
Washington, said. ``It makes so little sense that I don't even go
into combat with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton did not return a telephone call placed to his home
Thursday night, and a lawyer representing the Apollo Theater
Foundation also did not return a call.
</P>
<P>
   Under a five-year licensing agreement, Inner City Broadcasting
was to pay the foundation $2,000 for each taping of ``It's Showtime
at the Apollo,'' or 25 percent of the show's profits, whichever was
greater.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials at the Empire State Development Corp.,
the state agency that owns the Apollo, the foundation's executives
told its board that Sutton owed at least $3 million under the
agreement, but it received and accepted only $200,000 when it asked
for payment.
</P>
<P>
   This, Vacco contended, was insufficient for a nonprofit
organization. According to the lawsuit, the board failed to insure
that it obtained all of the compensation to which it was entitled,
and failed to obtain detailed financial reports from Inner City.
The board also did not ask to inspect Inner City's records.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's suit also focused on another aspect of
business dealings between the foundation and Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   After the original licensing agreement to produce ``It's
Showtime at the Apollo'' expired at the end of last year, the
foundation opened bidding on a new agreement. Two groups were in
the running _ Inner City Broadcasting, and the African Heritage
Network.
</P>
<P>
   Both submitted bids for $1.5 million. Sutton's company won the
bid, state officials said, by changing its bid to $1.6 million at
the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the lawsuit seeks to remove six people from the
foundation's board: Rangel, Arthur Hill, George Dalley, the Rev.
William James, Lloyd Williams and Richard Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The other four board members _ Ossie Davis, Marianne Spraggins,
Evelyn Cunningham and George Woody _ expressed concern about the
finances several months ago, Vacco's office said, and would be
expected to form the nucleus of a new board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
